DATA['2020'] = [{"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/81345.html", "year": "2020", "month": "03", "day": "08", "time": "11-34PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt7582657", "title": "Beware the 18th of March?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was checking my farmer’s almanac for good days to do various tasks in the garden when I noticed that the 18th of this month has Mars, Saturn, Jupiter, and Pluto all conjuncting the Moon in Capricorn.  That’s a whole lot of conjuncting going on! Some of them are conjuncting each other as well. Whoa! Forget the garden – what’s going on between the 18th and the 23rd  that us U.S. folks ought to be looking out for?\nAn earthquake? The end of the petro dollar? Or (hopefully so) people refusing to obey the pesky Daylight Time changes? Anything? Nothing particular, just BAU?\nI went scrounging on the ‘net and found dern-all about it. Altho’ one website said the last time there was a Saturn-Pluto conjunction in Capricorn was two months after 95 Theses were nailed to a door in Wittenberg. Are the heavens tolling a slow, solemn bell over our heads?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7583681", "title": "Re: Beware the 18th of March?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Mars-Jupiter conjunction in Capricorn will be a significant factor in this year's Aries ingress charts -- I've got three of those up on my Patreon and SubscribeStar accounts already, for the US, Britain, and India, and will have Japan and Australia posted as soon as I get them finished. The Mars-Saturn conjunction is further off -- it perfects on March 31 -- and Jupiter and Saturn don't perfect until December 21, which marks a major shift in political astrology. The Moon's just doing its usual thing, conjuncting every planet in a given sign within a couple of days. It'll be there again a month later.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7582913", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, thanks as always for doing these Q&As every week!\nIn the Irish pagan tradition, it's standard to invoke the elements of Land, Sky, and Sea instead of the familiar Water, Earth, Fire, and Air. Wondering if you know of a ritual--similar in focus to the Sphere of Protection--that could be adapted to make use of that three-element structure?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7583937", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of one. Four elements is pretty much a minimum -- the Sphere of Protection uses seven, including Spirit Below, Spirit Above, and Spirit Within. It's also challenging when you don't have a set of traditional directions to use. The Irish magical workings I'm familiar with, the system worked out by William Butler Yeats, uses the four directions and elements.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7595201", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may suggest, you could always assign Sky and Sea to the vertical axis of the SoP: Sky for Above and Sea for Below (As in the primal waters of the Underworld, The Well of Segais, etc). Then split Land into the 4 Directions and center (think the 5 provinces of Ireland, one at each quarter with Tara in the middle) and you have your 7 Directions. You could easily reconcile this with the 4 elements from Western Tradition, I would say...\nManuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7602369", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! In the immortal words of\nYoung Frankenstein\n, \"It...could...\nwork!\n\"", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7583169", "title": "Rings of Existence", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for hosting this as always, JMG. I’ve been fascinated by Iolo Morganwg’s concept of the rings of existence since I read about it in your Druidry Handbook a couple of years ago. I’m wondering: is there precedent for that idea elsewhere in occult philosophy, or is it original to Iolo? I can’t think of an analogous idea in the major world religions, but maybe I’m wrong? Was he the father of that sort of inverted neo-Platonism where existence is emanating from low to high?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7584449", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Iolo's system as a whole doesn't go from low to high -- that's just the path walked by individual souls in the course of their evolution. In Iolo's vision the creative impulse comes from the Divine at the highest level, in Ceugant, and creates souls at the lowest level, who then journey up through the circles of being toward their creator. That's a vision that goes way back in the more esoteric end of Christianity; think of Dryden's \"Song for St. Cecilia's Day\":\n\"When Nature underneath a heap\nOf jarring atoms lay,\nAnd could not heave her head,\nThe tuneful voice was heard from high,\nArise ye more than dead.\"\nCombine that with with the Platonic idea of the soul rising toward the gods through many lives -- see the Myth of Er in\nThe Republic\n-- and with the classical testimonies of the ancient Druids' belief in reincarnation, and you've got a pretty fair equivalent of Iolo's vision. Did he have other sources? Quite possibly, but nobody knows at this point.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7585217", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah ok, thanks very much for correcting my misunderstanding. So, fair to say then that he preserved that classic exitus-reditus schema? Is his eschatology still one of reunion, rather than a more Teilhard de Chardin-like evolution towards some more advanced state?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7586753", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Iolo himself doesn't follow the exitus-reditus scheme; what descends isn't souls but rather the divine Awen or spirit, and the souls rise out of Annwn in response to the descent of Awen rather than out of the divine Awen. Nor does he have a concept of divine union -- in fact, he specifically holds that only the Divine can dwell in the \"empty circle\" of Ceugant. He isn't that explicit about what happens to souls as they rise through Gwynfydd, the Luminous Life, but they don't become one with God.\nMind you, there are plenty of Druids who have spun things in other directions, either fitting Iolo's imagery into the exitus-reditus scheme or working it in other ways. Ours isn't a dogmatic faith, and such things are understood as raw materials for interesting speculation rather than points to get into fistfights over.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7588545", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That’s fascinating. Any suggestions for further reading on this topic? Thanks again, JMG!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7588801", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Barddas\nis currently in print in a hefty hardcover, and you can also read it online\nhere\n; that's the place to start.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-09 05:19 am (UTC)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7589313", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Also,\nHere's a downloadable PDF\nof the whole text of Barddas.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7594689", "title": "Re: Rings of Existence", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Wonderful, thank you again!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7583425", "title": "Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear jmg\nI recently got the book by peladan called “how to be a mage” and I’m intrigued by his suggestion that since each person is under the rule of a planetary energy then that planetary energy determines the process and form of success for that person, particularly in relation to spiritual attainment.\nDoes any other occultist talk about this?\nJ.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7584705", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's found in some of the older astrological literature, as I recall, but Peladan's discussion is the best one I've encountered. I'd encourage you to take it as a basis for meditation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7585473", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That sounds like a good idea.\nThe moment I read those words I agreed with them since it is something I suspected for a while, and completely fits with my personal experience of my life.\nOne thing I’m confused about though is that he says people are usually ruled by two or three planets.\nWhile I know you can find them out w astrology peladan seems to suggest you learn about this through personal observation of your life and personality.\nI find it hard to imagine someone doing this well with out a horoscope.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7587009", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you study the symbolism of the planets and the myths of the planetary gods, you can notice things going on in your thinking and acting, and say to yourself, \"Okay, there's some Mercury in there!\" I think that's what he has in mind.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7588289", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ok, that makes sense.\nHe also describes ways to defeat enemies and difficulties by infusing oneself w the energy of a planet that is the opposite of whatever planet governs your difficulties or enemies.\nDo you think that is sound advice as well? I can’t help but wonder about what would happen if you did that operation wrong.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7589057", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you do the operation wrong, why, you won't get the results you want, and then you can correct your mistake and try again. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7589569", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, of course.\nDo you know if any other of peladans works are going to be translated?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7602625", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Only if somebody gets off their duff and does the job. Have you considered getting a good working knowledge of French? There's a lot of good occult literature in that language that's never been put into English...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7637697", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maybe we could organize it here? It's a lot of work no doubt, so many might feel reluctant to start something already underway. I am interested but would prefer to work in a small team with a native French speaker as I'm only moderately conversant in modern French and haven't read older works of French literature in years.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7643841", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Let's throw it open.  Is anyone else interested?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7682241", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'd be interested in this even alone, so will ask next MM. Which work would you recommend starting with?", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7641025", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "open_space", "content": "I’ve been thinking about something you said a while ago. It was something along the lines of: everything from the rich wisdom of the past is right at this moment up for the grabs and that will determine what will survive for the next generations to come. I assume that is coming from one of the few good things of a hyper-connected world which is that knowledge is very accesible today like scans of old manuscripts and the ability to host forums like these.  Ever since I started taking spirituality seriously I knew that I wanted as much of my life dedicated to it and slowly I am doing the appropriate changes. For what I understand, western mysteries are the ones that took most of the beating in the transition to an industrial society  because of several reasons and conflicts in Europe. In your opinion, what are the areas that would need more of attention in order to survive? Translations to other languages, development and incorporation of missing parts like the western movement arts? I guess what I am asking is, for someone who is fairly young and new to this what would be your advise if one wanted to be part of helping enriching spirituality for the centuries to come?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7644097", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What I'd advise is that you follow your own passion in this. What is it that you, personally, think is important enough that you'd be willing to invest a thousand hours or so over the next few years to preserve, translate, or develop? That's a lot of work, and you're only going to be able to keep doing it if it's something you feel strongly about. Choose on that basis, and let the gods sort the rest of it out.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7596737", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Point of anecdata:\nWhen I was younger, even when I was getting into Occult Stuff, I didn't believe in astrology for a number of reasons (including the fact that my Libra-ness expresses itself in ways *very* different from the pop-culture \"starry-eyed romantic peacemaker\" stereotype* that was all I'd heard then). But I was always into wandering--both personally and as part of a family that moved every ten years and took a lot of road trips--and a big reader, and love and other indoor sports were always among my interests. When I ended up encountering patron gods, they turned out to be Hermes and Aphrodite.\n...and when I did my chart a couple years ago, it turned out my ruler is Mercury, and the *vast* majority of my planets are in Libra. Go figure. :P\n* Mars/Uranus/Neptune sextile and Saturn conjunction: I like what the polyam crowd calls \"new relationship energy\" but I'm not a huge fan of settling down, to put it mildly, and as for the classic Libra easygoing nature and desire to please...well, yes if I like you and VERY NO if I don't. Very Viking Saga combo, there, actually: people have flattered me by saying I'm a very loyal friend, and I *know* I'm a very bitter enemy.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7602881", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a lot of very lame astrological chitchat in the pop-culture circuit. It's done a lot of damage to the reputation of astrology!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7610305", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "So true! Anything that's printed in the same publication as What Shoes Are In This Summer is probably a fairly inaccurate representation of it, I've found.\nAmusingly, my entire family is slowly coming over to the astrology-belief camp, the exception being my dad, who says he's going to drink whenever we mention it. I'm planning to make his birthday present a type/brand of alcohol for every sign, because I'm a troll like that. :P", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7611841", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you worked out the zodiac of booze yet?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7640513", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "Well now I'm fascinated. Would the process of distillation alter the planetary correspondence of the mother liquor? Hard cider would be Venereal, beer Saturnine, wine solar? Lunar? Telluric? (Sorry, couldn't stop myself - must be the cider talking.)\nTequila strikes me as Martial. Whiskey maybe solar? Gin Mercurial? Anything that gets one laid would probably require a Jovial nod, at least. Have you worked this out already?? I need a fully-illustrated poster.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7644353", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't worked any of it out. Sounds like there's a need to fill some glasses for, er, meditation...  ;-)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7602113", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My take on this:\nStart with the planet that rules your Ascendant, then look for other prominent planets in your chart - which may not necessarily be the sun and moon.\nFor me, Capricorn rises, with its ruler Saturn in my 12th house, and I've noticed I seem considerably more saturnine than \"a Sagittarius\" should be - favoring durability over shininess, stability over novelty, etc.  But Neptune conjoins my ascendant, so it plays a prominent role (I'm prone to flights of creativity, I rely heavily on intuition and gut feeling, the spiritual is important to me), and there's a dash of Mars, too, the only planet (unless you count Pluto) in either rulership or exaltation (Scorpio, in this case), and angular), manifesting as a desire for independence and ability to make it on my own.  (Some of that may also be my Aries Moon.)\nBy contrast my Sun, in dignity by triplicity and in a loose (3.5 degree) trine with the Moon but nothing else, is kind of tepid.\nMy suggestion?  Without checking your natal chart, write down honest facts about yourself, your personality, and your preferences.  Then compare it to the natal chart.  Example: \"I'd like to travel, but I'd prefer to do it with a friend, and it seems like some problem always comes up whenever I do take a trip\" - I can clearly associate this with my 11th house Sun in Sagittarius, with Virgo on the cusp of a 9th house that contains the South Node and is ruled by a Mercury under the sunbeams.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7600065", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a copy of this in French. (To J.L.Mc12) Could you tell me which section it's in? Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7648705", "title": "Re: Peladan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It’s in chapter 1: neophyte, and in chapter 3 book 2: rapport or destiny.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7584193", "title": "Rosicrucians", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm looking to have a basic general reference on Rosicrucianism - I might explore the path in depth later but for right now I just want enough to understand what they are about and have a place to start if that path calls. I've found Fama Fraternitatis, Confessio Fraternitatis, The Chemical Wedding, and the Manual, but I'm wondering if JMG or the commentariat could recommend a book giving a Rosicrucian course of initiation for the solitary practitioner.\nAlso, can anyone vouch for the English translation of the Rosicrucian Trilogy by Joscelyn Godwin et al? The 'about the authors' section doesn't mention any of them actually being part of an Rosicrucian order, but Rosicrucians don't seem to worry too much about affiliation, so I don't know if the lack of affiliation with an order is actually a problem.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7584961", "title": "Re: Rosicrucians", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of any publicly available book that presents such a course, other than the Golden Dawn literature, and that's Rosicrucian only in a fairly specialized sense. You pretty much have to enroll in one of the orders. As for Godwin's translation, he's a first-rate scholar and his work is reliable -- I've looked at the originals of those texts, and never once found an error in his work.\nIf you can find a copy, by the way,\nThe D.O.M.A. Manuscript\nedited by Manly P. Hall is a very good addition to a Rosicrucian library.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7595969", "title": "Re: Rosicrucians", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Was afraid initiation was tied to the orders. I'll see what the internet can do as far as Hall's Manuscript. Thanks!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7591361", "title": "Re: Rosicrucians", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As a Druid inspired precisely by\nBarddas\nand the rest of the specifically Welsh tradition, I've tried to set down my own thinking here: https://ymgyrchiannwfn.wordpress.com/2020/01/22/the-wisdom-of-the-loom/ It may or may not be of interest, but feel free to leave a comment anyway.\nBogatyr", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7585729", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nYou mentioned \"initiation into the Golden Dawn Current\" above.  What benefit is there to initiation?  And, once initiated into Golden Dawn (or any other occult discipline), if one decides to look into something else, is it necessary to de-initiate, or would initiation into one discipline interfere with future efforts in another?\nMy thanks to you and all commenters!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7587265", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Initiation puts you into contact with specific sources of energy and guidance from higher planes. Once you've initiated yourself (or been initiated) into a current, you have access to  forces you'd have a hard time accessing otherwise, and you can also tune into your contacts on the inner for guidance. No, you don't have to de-initiate -- quite the contrary; I have a good dozen sets of initiatory contacts, and that's extremely helpful when working magic.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7585985", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are your correspondences for the Norse Cabbalistic Tree of Life? I've seen some pretty whacky ones online, but so far I think Kether is best represented by Odin, Chesed by Thor or Frey, Geburah by Tyr, Tiphareth by Baldr, Netzatch by Freya, Hod by Bragi, Malkuth by Jord... Ginnungagap is the Unmanifest.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7587777", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd have to go digging to find my notes -- I've been swamped with other projects for so long that I don't have the details handy. Sorry.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7594177", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Sven Eriksen)\nGot the notes right here. Starting from the top, and following the lightning flash on the way down: Odin, Thor, Freya, Frey, Tyr, Baldr, Saga, Loki, Heimdall, Idun.\njmg\n, glad to know I'm not the only one being swamped of late. Though I was starting to wonder if Fido might have devoured that last e-mail I sent you. Feel free to drop me a note when you are a little less busy ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7603137", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this! Yeah, \"busy\" is an understatement -- Llewellyn dumped a bunch of my titles with zero warning, and I had to scramble around getting them placed with a new publisher and doing necessary revisions, while other already-contracted projects such as the Weird of Hali RPG still had to get in on time! Fortunately that's mostly over with now.  I'll get a note heading your way as soon as Mercury turns around.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7622849", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Sven Eriksen)\nNo worries, JMG. I've been up to my eyeballs in work myself, ever since my return to academia, and thus quite happy to have our little project proceed at a leisurly pace. We'll talk more post retrograde... ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7639745", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! That makes a lot more sense to me than some of the ones I've seen online.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7586241", "title": "Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "I made a video of my own version of the hoodoo bath:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZtQMmZi72I&t=5s\nIt's another case of me being a visual learner and thinking others might benefit from seeing it presented bluntly and plainly.  Had there been anything out there that I could find that was similar to the no-frills presentation of this video, I would not have made it.  Though I enjoy watching videos, I'm not altogether keen on creating them.   Hope this helps someone.\nAlso, I posted another one of my Orphic hymns with free PDF sheet music in the description:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qmde1fh5vho\nAt Bandcamp:\nhttps://queeniemusic.bandcamp.com/track/orphic-hymn-to-jupiter", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7593665", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you Kimberly for your work with the Orphic hymns. They have really helped me with my new daily practice!\nRelated to both parts of your post, have you used Khernips in preparation for worship? It has a very similar effect to the hoodoo bath in my experience.\nGawain", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7610561", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Gawain, I was ignorant of Khernips until you posted this.  Thanks, obviously, no I have not used it.  I will certainly give it a try.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7612097", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If I may interject: khernips traditionally prepared ought to do an excellent job of purification, at least according to the groundrules of natural magic. Thank you for bringing this up!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7593921", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you very much for this. I stumbled onto this moments after you uploaded it, and performed the bath as per your instruction. First time I've been able to do it. Deeply appreciated, CP", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7597505", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kimberly,\nI really hope you will continue doing videos. I personally found the hoodoo bath one very informative and helpful.\nAV", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7615169", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath Video & New Orphic Hymn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you Kimberly, you are a generous soul.  --Sidney", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7586497", "title": "Prayers", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "To all of those who granted me permission to pray for them, including Maxine, Violet, LunarApprentice, and others, I've been doing it, often including those prayers in my nightly musical practice of the songs I wrote dedicated to Greek gods/Orphic hymns.  Thanks for the opportunity, and thanks JMG for this forum.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7590081", "title": "Re: Prayers", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you Kimberly,\nI will be happy to return the favor to you whenever you like.\nMaxine\nPS Your prayers must be working as all is very quiet here with no one waking me or bumping around in the night.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7598529", "title": "Re: Prayers", "user": "violetcabra", "content": "Many thanks Kimberly, that really means a lot to me!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7587521", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few questions today.\nSo I did a shield chart, a simple yes/no question, \"Will ___ share the secret if I tell them?\" The Judge was Carcer, a nice clear no after all Carcer is not only unfavorable but a figure of isolation. But I got to thinking, since Carcer is favorable in matters of security, does that mean Carcer should be taken as a yes instead?\nAnother, unrelated divination perplexed me, after spending a hour on it I had what I thought was a clever idea, a single figure reading asking if my interpretation was correct. Conjunctio was the answer and I immediately thought the answer was \"no\" as I remembered it was unfavorable in matters where clarification is needed and I was asking for clarification right?  But I'm not sure...\nKeeping with the trend, I was thinking of starting the Sphere of Protection, the version with the names of Jesus,but I'm having difficulty coming up with the appropriate imagery as I'm not exactly well read when it comes to the Bible. (But am nonetheless sure that's the version I should do.) Some are easy enough, others, which are more abstract, are leaving me baffled. I'm wondering what you would suggest?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7588033", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Depends on the other figures in the chart. A single figure by itself is almost impossible to interpret accurately.\n2) It really isn't that complex. If you get a favorable figure, the answer is yes; if an unfavorable figure, the answer is no. The temptation to overthink things is one of the obstacles to effective divination.\n3) Don't worry about the imagery for now. Simply use the names as given, and while you're at it, put the necessary time into Bible study so you can choose imagery that works for you!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7609793", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "mo_drui_mac_de", "content": "Regarding different Jesus imagery, in addition to Bible study, it might be useful to take a look at the Glorious/Joyful/Sorrowful/Luminous Mysteries associated with the Rosary, which center around potent events in the lives of Jesus and Mary. There scriptures associated with each, and each set provide a ready-made list to work from.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7590337", "title": "SOP versions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi there JMG\nI've begun studying the early chapters of the DMH whilst continuing my practice of the blog-version SOP. I'm thinking of following the DMH lessons in full. I noted your comment last week that the Elemental Cross is more suited to the DMH and Dolmen Arch than the other opening, so might I ask:\n1. is there anything else in the blog version SOP that ought be changed for me to follow the DMH, or is it just the opening?\n2. If possible I'd also be interested to know why the Elemental Cross is more suitable?\n3. Finally, I may try the more complex Closing at some point too. For both of these SOP changes I suppose I can just swap them in and carry on as normal (I would do so one at a time)?\nKind regards.\nMorfran.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7603393", "title": "Re: SOP versions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you can do the more complex closing, that would be helpful. I recommend it to anyone who can do it.\n2) Partly because you're tapping into the existing egregor, partly because the DMH system is very strongly focused on elemental work and so having that fourfold pattern right there at the beginning is helpful.\n3) Yes, exactly.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7619777", "title": "Re: SOP versions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Excellent, thank you.\nI don't know if I will be able to do the rotation SOP effectively, but my static SOP sometimes feels a little lacklustre. Even though it should be harder, I wonder if the challenge will help me invest the right level of energy/attention. I have so far made the most progress with the elemental callings; my openings and closings both need work.\nThanks,\nMorfran.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7652289", "title": "Re: SOP versions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Morfran,\nI would encourage you to try the Circulation of Light as part of your SOP.  It is really not that hard to do with a little practice.\nI find the Circulation of Light to be a really handy dehexer all on its own in emergencies.  I have lately taken to sending the ball of light to friends in hospital in another province and at the least, it does them no harm.  I suspect it does them good.\nMaxine Rogers", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7590593", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nDo you know why Hermetic Brotherhood of Luxor strictly rejected the idea of reincarnation? Is it because of their feud with Theosophical Society, or some other reason?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7603649", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Reincarnation was a huge hot-button issue in late 19th century occult circles, largely because of the very strong overlap between occultism and Spiritualism on the one hand, and between occultism and Christianity on the other -- both these had the notion of a paradise after death for the good people, of course. Also, bluntly, I get the impression that a lot of people in the late 19th century hated their lives and were horrified at the thought of having to return to this world; certainly the furious denunciations of reincarnation I've read in the occult press of that time gives that impression.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7604929", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "By about 1875 the world-wide Spiritualist movement had split right down the middle over the hot-button issue of what happened after death: reincarnation on earth vs. perpetual residence in the Summerland (the Spiritualists' equivalend of heaven).  The split lined up fairly well with the division between the English-speaking world and everyone else (especially in Latin America and Europe).  The first major pro-reincarnation writer was a Frenchman, namely \"Allan Karedec\" (Hippolyte L. D. Rivall).  His first Spiritualist book appeared in 1857.\nEventually the pro-reincarnation wing began to call themselves \"Spiritists\" (using Karedc's preferred term), while the anti-reincarnation wing kept on with \"Spiritualists.\"\nMadame Blavatsky, of course, was a Russian, so the form of Spiritualism that she practiced at the beginning of her occult career was naturally the pro-reincarnation form, and she held this position for the rest of her life.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7606977", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've seen Kardec referenced in glowing terms by Western believers in reincarnation as the man who revived belief in reincarnation in the West. That's a little too simplistic -- Thomas Taylor started the process, and Blavatsky probably did more to make it happen than anybody else -- but Kardek was certainly an important figure. (His pen name was the name he'd had in a previous life, when he'd been a Breton Druid!)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7611073", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "These are interesting points. I can imagine that reincarnation is seen by different people in a different light, depending on their expectations for future lives. What would you say to someone who fears that his next life will be even worse than the one he or she is in, because there are so many things which can go wrong in a human life?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7612353", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd say that there are just as many things that can go right in a human life. Karma is not an eye in the sky sitting there waiting for you to screw up so it can punish you; it's simply the sum of the impact your actions have on your character, and thus on your destiny. That is to say, you can shape your next life by the thoughts, words, and actions you choose today.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7629249", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why does \"karma\" wait for the next life for compensation? This doesn't sound as reasonable as the \"law of cause and effect\" which reacts immediately after an action. Plus, if we don't remember our actions in our previous lives, it sounds unjust to be held guilty of them. I think \"karma\" is a misinterpretation of the law of cause and effect, specially crafted by Brahmin cast to legitimize their hegemony over lower castes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7630273", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're certainly free to believe as you wish, but yas long as you think about karma in terms of being \"held guilty\" you don't understand it.  Your actions affect your character, and your character determines your destiny: that's karma. It very often has some influence in the current life, but the changes of circumstance that take place between one life and the next allow it much more freedom to act.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7630017", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Yes, I think that would be quite a helpful way to see reincarnation. I myself got the idea, that, maybe, if the majority of people don't seem to have messed-up lives or are debilitated, than the same thing would, statistically, be the case for different incarnations.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7635649", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Aside from the supporting evidence, the idea of reincarnation seems to fit well with two of the seven principles of Hermetic philosophy: 1) Cyclicity, 2) Analogy/correspondence. If matter is always recycled in nature (such as the cycles of oxygen, carbon, nitrogen etc.); then, by analogy, spirit must be recycled after physical death, too.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7636417", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good. Both of those principles have in fact been used to explain and defend the idea of reincarnation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7656385", "title": "Reincarnation and Akash", "user": "happypanda", "content": "If it helps anyone here's what Hinduism teaches about Reincarnation.\nPersonality/Persona doesn't re-incarnate. It's a one-shot deal and is one of the most limited things about you. What gets reborn is:\n1. Consequences to actions from prior lives when surrounding conditions are favorable for the consequences to express arise. One example of a consequence of prior actions is the creation of Vasanas (sanskrit) - what we in english call tendencies, proclivities or habitual-responses to certain kinds of stresses or events. The habitual stressing of certain parts of our thinking and emotions over others for example. Something as trivial as liking one flavor of beer and disliking another - if carried over multiple lifetimes creates a vasana for beer.\n2. Desires. This is what actually kickstarts the re-birthing process because a desire (from a Hindu standpoint that is) acts as as a magnet. There's nothing wrong with having desires but most people's desires are limited in the sense that the desire impels them to want the 'good' of whatever it is they want without realizing they'll also be getting any 'bad' part along with it if their vasana has created a blindspot to whatever they desire. Example: that guy or gal you know who always has a knack for falling head over heels in love with precisely the kind of person that's damaging to them in a relationship. And they repeat that proclivity over and over and over - sometimes lifetime after lifetime. You never just get one or the other of whatever you desire. It's always a whole.\nThat's why the Dharma religions often stress seeing your own life as one whole - letting go of judgements (ie prejudices/) and begin experiencing your own life and proclivities without blame, shame or judgement.\nIn Tantric terms when that begins to happen in one's own thought/emotional setup it means the Quintessence - Akash in the Tantric tradition - is beginning to increase in the mind & body. In Daoist terms it would be called transforming Jing to Chi (and thence Chi to Shen and Shen to the Unmanifest but that's getting way ahead - getting to Shen stage is very high level). The more Akash, the higher one's consciousness rises and quiets down. The higher one's consciousness rises the more unnecessary mental chatter transforms to pure awareness. Now you know one reason for the fame of the Shaolin Monks - pure awareness that can extend 360 degrees 10 feet out can become an amazing martial advantage when the local Chinese Long Descent Warlord and his band of Merry Thugs think your monastery has a lot of goodies they'd like to liberate.\nSorry, I digress. Hope that helps some folks though on the reincarnation question.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7590849", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Tolkienguy)\nSo...I think I may have had a TSW moment last week-or I may just be crazy. I'll let you decide since you know more about this stuff than me.\nAs I think I've mentioned on the other board, I work in a warehouse as a stockman, and when I get a new batch of clothes to stock, I have to scan them all in with a scanning gun, which then tells me where in the warehouse they go. Normally, upon scanning an item, the gun displays a \"processing\" message, then goes back to a blank screen so you can scan the next item. Last week though, the guns started glitching-on random items, usually every 3rd or 4th item, the gun, after processing the scan, would display an error message, then back out of its scanning function entirely (leaving me to spend several seconds going through three different menus to get back in, which was annoying). I asked my supervisor and he said it was just a network bug that he couldn't do anything about, so I decided to try something else.\nFrom what I've read about magic, I understand that one of the major components of it is visualization, which I understand to mean picturing an outcome that you want in your head, then focusing on it with as much concentration as possible. So, upon getting my next batch of items, I decided that, every time I scanned an item, I'd look at the scanning gun and imagine it processing the scan correctly and returning to the blank screen. I concentrated as hard as I possibly could on that image of the gun processing the scan correctly, and tried as hard as I could to make myself certain this was what was going to happen.\nThe batch I tried this on, the gun-which had been glitching 5-10 times on batches that size-only glitched twice. Seeing it scan item after item correctly, which it had previously refused to do that night, was almost surreal.\nIs this the sort of thing one can achieve by magic, or am I being delusional? I've done banishing rituals before, but this is the first time I've seen something had such an effect on the material world. I'll admit, for the next few days afterwards, my inner scientific materialist kept screaming that there's no such thing as mind powers and that letting myself think otherwise was a one-way ticket to insanity. But what do you think?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7603905", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Electronics can be influenced by the human organism. Every well-informed ham radio operator knows about \"hand capacitance\" -- the influence that the electric field around your hands can exert on electronic equipment -- and experienced hams use it to fine-tune their gear: hold the hand right here, and the static drops off. That's a simple example of something that can become a lot more complex. As for your inner scientific materialist, well, ask it this: is the mind part of the natural world? If it is, then it can influence other parts of the natural world. If it isn't, then your inner scientific materialist has just admitted the existence of supernatural realities.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7606209", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I didn't known about \"hand capacitance\": that explains a lot.  It seems to me that there's a mental component here as well.\nBack in the days when dinosaurs roamed the earth and one did one's personal computing by connecting to a \"virtual machine\" on a mainframe computer by way of a telephone line, a T-box, and a terminal, working connections were always hard to maintain.  Our T-box at home failed to connect far more often than it succeeded, and would often break off the connection not long after it was establishhed.  As the T-box tried to connect, a little green light would blink; when it succeeded, the green light would become steady, but when if failed, the green light would turn off.  Success was rare, and the connection often didn't last very long.\nBut eventually I discovered that if I fixed my attention on the blinking green light to the exclusion of everything else, and held a powerful mental image of it staying on to the exclusion of every other possibility, the connection would \"take\", and it would also last--against all odds.  TSW.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7606721", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted, there's certainly a mental component; I find that former scientific materialists tend to be rattled more effectively by having them look up hand capacitance, though. Sara and I have a radio in our apartment right now that's very sensitive to this -- I can make static on one station go away completely by putting my hand behind it, about an inch away from the box.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7631041", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can the \"placebo effect\" also be explained by mind power?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7633857", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a straightforward biological reason why the placebo effect works: the vagus nerve connects certain parts of the brain directly to the major organs and the adrenals, and so mental activity that stimulates those parts of the brain has an immediate effect on the health of the body. Look up \"psychoneuroimmunology\" sometime -- that's the field of research that explores these effects.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7668417", "title": "Poses to make the radio work better", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "From my experience, it's more than just \"hand capacitance\", because the next question is \"capacitive coupling with WHAT?\" Coupling into the currents induced by the \"human antenna\" is a possibility. One of the tricky things about radio is that stations which are too strong can make the radio noisily misbehave, whether or not the radio is tuned to the too strong station.  A conductive body (like yours) can resonate away some excess energy.  The wavelength at 100 MHz is 3 meters, so a half-wave resonator is 1.5 meters, not much different from a sitting human (depending on where the arms are held).\nLathechuck", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7608001", "title": "Hand Mind Capacitance", "user": "sothismedias", "content": "Good analogy about the hand capacitance!\nI'm going to tuck the question \"is the mind part of the natural world? If it is, then it can influence other parts of the natural world. If it isn't, then your inner scientific materialist has just admitted the existence of supernatural realities,\" into my back pocket for later use in conversation.\n73 de KE8COY", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7612609", "title": "Re: Hand Mind Capacitance", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have fun with it. I certainly have.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7591105", "title": "Musings", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "I'm not sure this is a question, but I want to explore a theme a bit out loud, and if it elicits feedback I'd be happy.\nFirst, thanks for the astrology advice a few Mondays ago for electing a date on which to leave my job. In the event, I felt way too green to follow them, so I engaged Chris Warnock, and he has provided me with a favourable date in about two weeks time.\nAnyway, the theme is: ways of playing around with the seven cantrevs in Dolmen Arch.\nOne way I found was to treat each \"set\" (EW, NS, AboveBelow) as a ray, crossing them to place the seventh at the centre. So far, so ordinary, a I've done is set them into their places in the SOP. But I did notice that my three rays gave seven \"directions\" (including centre), but also provide 12 right angles, if you consider the angles made by any two outgoing rays and the centre. What lies on these twelve angles I intend to meditate on a few times.\nBut, whether it had anything to do with the Tai Chi seminar I was at, I couldn't help seeing this as a dynamic system in which the centre is eternally here and now, the only possible place in which will can be effective. And, in the magical, or martial sense, a threat coming from any of the directions MUST arrive at the centre (here and now) from which a ready will can deflect it outward along another direction lying at right angles to the first, and allow it to continue on its way. If evil, its \"way\" will be outward to the ring-pass-not.\nAnyway, Monday, Will day, HereNow day, strikes me as Druid Day, and I think from henceforth I will do my groves on Mondays, and cultivate the and strengthen the centre. Thanks for the Dolmen Arch!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7604161", "title": "Re: Musings", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! Interesting. I could see that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7591617", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nThere's no real question this week, I just wanted to report that, according to my journal, last week marked the one year anniversary of my start on the DMH practices. I'm up to part where I'm waiting for the Ogham to give me the go-ahead to awaken the two currents.\nIt's difficult to quantify how much doing the daily practices have helped, but they definitely have. I still deal with deep set psychological issues which still flare up from time to time (a desire for approval, a tendency to be fearful) but generally I have a deeper sense of acceptance of all aspects of my current situation in life.\nMore specifically, the daily SOP clears my mood in the mornings and acts kind of as a psychological reset. I'm getting a better sense of when an element is strong or weak during the SOP, which sometimes correlates to the Ogham reading I do afterwards. I've sometimes been able to predict when a few will come up during my daily reading, albeit only occasionally - I'll get a sense that a few will come up, and it will.\nMeditation has been very useful, I've sorted through a number of things in the DMH with many useful insights, and I think I now need to start meditating a bit longer per day. That said, if I'm short on time in the mornings, then I usually drop or shorten meditation, according to my journal, I miss 1-2 meditations per week, so I need to work on that.\nThe Grove Ceremony, which I do roughly once a week, acts as an intensifier of the SOP, for a day or two afterwards it helps strengthen my ability to visualize. I've had useful results from both scrying and doing the transformative workings outlined in the DMH.\nAnyhow - just wanted to touch base about how things were going, I'm very happy that I picked up the DMH and started working with it! Thanks very much!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7604417", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome, and thank you for taking the work seriously and making it part of your life.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7591873", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Archdruid,\nIs there any equivalent of the \"three veils of negative existence\" in Druidry?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7604673", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on which Druid you ask. ;-)\nRemember that Druidry has been reinvented over the last 300 years or so out of a gallimaufry of raw materials, and it has no fixed dogma and no uniform theology or practice. That I know of, nobody's yet found the need to work with the three Veils in specifically Druid terms -- but then a lot of Druids over the last century have had at least some background in ceremonial magic, and anyone who needs to discuss that as a part of their experience of the cosmos can as well reference Dion Fortune.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7592129", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is more of an open question, how are people going with their Tentacular SoP and related worship? Any visits from the beings that live in the space between the spaces we know?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7617473", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Worshiping the Great Old Ones is substantially more impactful than using the raw elements. I can't compare the Tentacular SoP to one with 'real' gods because I haven't tried the later.\nThe Old Ones seem to have distinct personalities and resolving my personal conflicts with these entities seems to grant further access to the associated element to which I have assigned them. Lovecraftian deities, with the exception of Nyarlathotep, lack a friendly face, which makes them more difficult to relate to, but the added difficulty seems to be reflected in better magic when I actually manage to connect with them. I usually take a few moments after vibrating the name to check in, say hello, ask them for anything I need, and ask them for what they need when I'm feeling generous.\nSince starting the SoP, I've gotten contact from a certain Goddess who seemed to approve of the creation of new gods. Apparently, gods appreciate seeing new faces, even faceless ones. This makes me wonder if creating a god is more like putting out a 'help wanted' ad and then whatever divine force is aligned with the intention of your working puts on the listed identity like a set of work boots.\nI have noticed that Great Old Ones seem to not be as 'proactive' as 'real' gods. They show up when invoked and prayed to, and they seem to get work done when you're not looking, but I've never 'gotten a call' from one of them in the middle of the day, like I have working with established deities.\nIn my mind the only thing 'horrific' about the Great Old Ones is that they have goals of their own that have nothing to do with humans. Like other gods, you can offer them what they want and get for some of what you want in exchange. It's much like working with any other set of gods, which is much like working with a friendly set of people.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7592385", "title": "Views", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a budding interest in magick, druidry, occult practices, but am still somewhat reluctant to dive in based on lingering irritation with religion (strict-ish evangelical Christian upbringing which has since turned me off to organized religion and anything which smacks of the supernatural, and there is a lot of emotional baggage I'm still carrying around, as can probably be discerned from this message). My atheism of the last few years has been fed by Sam Harris and Richard Dawkins, making it hard for me tolerate anything which seems even remotely woo woo. But, as mentioned previously, I have an interest in the occult. I like the idea of an increased awareness of moon phases, of the sun, of nature.\nThis is a long set-up for the question, which is how do you see the stories, mythologies, etc. of the various practices you've engaged in (Golden Dawn, druidry, Freemasonry, etc.)? Given my upbringing and rejection of it, all religious stories and texts seem about as interesting as Aesop's Fables (teaching a simple moral for children).\nTangentially, if I heard you correctly on some podcast recently it sounded like you are working on a Norse version of the Golden Dawn. If so, do you have an expected publication date?\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7606465", "title": "Re: Views", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The classical philosopher Sallust outlined what is to my mind the best way to think about traditional stories in very straightforward terms: \"Myths are things that never happened but always are.\" They're not meant to be taken literally, but they're also not just simplistic moral fables. It's possible to communicate an immense amount of insight in narrative form, and to do so on many different levels. The next time you read a myth, ask yourself: what else could this mean?\nHere's an example. In Iolo Morganwg's Druid writings there's a legend about Einigan the Giant, the first of all created beings, and three rowan sticks on which he wrote down all the knowledge that ever was and ever will be. Later on, people worshiped the rowan sticks as gods instead of learning from what was written on them, and Einigan was so distressed by this that he burst apart and died. A long time later, Menw, the founder of what became the Druid tradition, found the skull of Einigan lying abandoned in a field, and the three rowan sticks had taken root and rose up through the eye-holes and mouth of the skull.\nDid any of these things actually happen? Of course not. In fact, the business about people worshiping the rowan sticks rather than learning from them is a warning against that kind of fundamentalism. But there's a lot more going on here than that. The skull of Einigan is also the dome of the sky, and the three rowan staves are the shadows cast by a standing stone at midsummer, spring/fall equinox, and midwinter sunrise -- the basis for the old solar astronomy practiced by the Druids. There's much more -- all of it woven into the imagery and events of the tale. Approach myth that way and you'll start to glimpse why it's actually important.\n2) That project's been on hiatus for a while, but it's going to be on the top of the stack shortly. I don't have a publication date yet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7613377", "title": "Re: Views", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for taking the time to answer.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7592641", "title": "Charm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A close relative found a charm on their kitchen counter three days ago made of a penny, cut counterclockwise along the edge so that it formed a sharp curled stem, with a flowerbed made with three short incisions on the uncut quarter of the edge. I immediately thought of hoodoo or something similar. It turns out He had recently separated from a lover hailing from the Delta region who was sad over the breakup.\nNot able to find any information about this charm so far, I had him bury it in his front yard and take a hoodoo bath.\nThree related questions, a) anyone familiar with this specific work, b) was my advice appropriate, c) is there an encyclopaedia of charms? Google nor Lucky Mojo weren't helpful. I'm a novice LRM student, finishing up today actually with self initiation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7607233", "title": "Re: Charm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's what I would have advised, though I'm not familiar with that specific charm and I don't think there's an encyclopedia of them -- it would not be in the interest of rootworkers to have all their secrets in one convenient place...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7592897", "title": "Central Ray and Ovate Temple", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThanks for being available for these questions.\nIs there a way that the Rite of the Central Ray fits into the Ovate temple or are they completely separate exercises?\nI felt like doing the Rite I’d the Central Ray as the meditation within the temple, is that ok? And if so, do I do the LRPB first or leave it as I have done LRPS in the opening of the temple?\nWhat would you recommend?\nMany thanks\nEdward", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7607745", "title": "Re: Central Ray and Ovate Temple", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can do the Exercise of the Central Ray in any magically prepared space; doing it following the LBRP is just the simplest option. Go ahead and do it right after you've finished opening the temple and before you sit and meditate, and leave off the LBRP.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7631809", "title": "Re: Central Ray and Ovate Temple", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7593153", "title": "On perfection and foxes", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Many thanks for answering all these questions every Monday, it's been splendidly helpful. I've got into the habit of reflecting over mine during the week, and this week I have one specific one on geomancy and a more general one about a  class of problems which I hope you have some insight on.\nThe geomantic question is about perfection by mutation. I cast a house chart earlier in the week and being rather distracted by the question could only see two aspects coming to the fore. I then realised the repeated figures were next to each other on the chart and that actually I was looking at perfection by mutation. So far, so obvious. However, thinking about it afterwards I realised that mutation could introduce up to two aspects; I'm not entirely sure if the minimum is one or zero.\n[It wouldn't be hard to write a program to find out if anyone was interested; there are only 16^4 charts, and 11 variations on each one, for questions involving  houses 2-12. That's around 721,000 distinct answers.]\nAnyway, the question was simply, if you find perfection by mutation - do you take any aspects into account or do they confuse matters in the same way that witnesses and judges can with a house chart?\nThe second question is about discouraging poor behaviour. I've recently cleared some land  for an outbuilding and a vegetable garden where there was a wood before. The wood contained foxes and in an entirely natural way they are now coming into the cleared space. I don't mind foxes; they are a nuisance  for farmers and livestock holders but I don't think they are inclined to menace my carrots. Also, there's a certain insouciance about them that's quite attractive. Sort of dog shaped cats in a way.\nUnfortunately, they do tend to leave byproducts behind that are really very smelly indeed. Not quite Skunk level but pungent and wet weather simply enhances the effect. I don't want to stop them coming round, and in any case that would be expensive and probably ineffective, but I would prefer them to handle the earthier aspects of fox life  in the woods. As bears do.\nA similar problem arises with my new neighbours who are hogging a shared resource - I'm afraid it's street parking - I'm not yet able to give up driving entirely. I'm new in the area and I haven't raised it in person with anyone yet as the chances of souring relations at such an early stage are quite high, there's also the practical problem that people are not often around, I've yet to meet some of them. On the other hand it would be nice to be able to park nearby occasionally, I'm often carrying heavy items.\nThe internet is full of banishing and binding spells, and noting your comments on malformed enchantments I suspect they range from the ineffective to the downright counterproductive. Even if I was able to make one of them work I don't actually want to banish or bind anyone. What I actually want is a slightly improved attitude to a shared resource\nBoth these situations share some commonalities, first of all they are utterly trivial and scarcely worth bothering with in the usual way of things, certainly not the sort of thing I'd bother a deity with, nor usually even an archdruid. Secondly they both require the communication of the basic concept 'please respect this space' where communication is difficult. I don't speak fox and my neighbours are not around much to chat with. Thirdly, I've developed the feeling that these are actually challenges that have been presented to me in order to push me in a particular direction. It means that I have to confront the ethical problem that since I've concluded TSW, I need to be sensitive about how I approach it.\nI've been brooding on this and concluded that - if possible - the only approach is to change myself rather than try to change the world. It neatly sidesteps the issue of consent, and modifying my own conscious is at least possibly within my grasp.\nSo (at last), the question becomes have I reached a reasonable conclusion? If I have - where do I start?\nAndy", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7608257", "title": "Re: On perfection and foxes", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I treat aspects as minor factors, commenting on the modes of perfection, but I do include them in a chart that perfects by mutation. If you have a chart that perfects via mutation, and there are some negative aspects (say, the mutating figure squares the significator of the querent), that tells you that the situation will work out but there will be some difficulty involved -- what kind of difficulty can be determined by the nature of the mutating figure and the house from which it squares the significator.\n2) You might consider invoking Mercury in both these cases, and asking for help resolving the situations.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7612865", "title": "Re: On perfection and foxes", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. That makes sense, and unfortunately rings all too true.\n2. I will consider it. As a matter of fact I have your translation of the Picatrix to hand, so I have a good starting point for research. I’d not read much of book 3, but I confess the description of Mercury sounds like the kind of personality that is very much up my street.\nThanks again for this.\nAndy", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7594433", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may ask, what the heck is going on with the Coronavirus scare? Do you think there’s some sort of magic at work here? I saw your link on the other blog about how the flu has already killed many Americans this winter, but I just saw that there is panic in the stock market now, too, though I guess that’s also because of the Saudi decision to pump more oil. It’s hard to know how to react: I find myself buying extra supplies every time I go grocery shopping, not because of the virus, but because I am not sure how other people are going to react. I’m basically getting dragged into this...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7608513", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Partly, the media loves panic because it's great clickbait, and since a lot of major media outlets are losing audience share at an astonishing rate, they're desperate. Partly, panic is a normal human response to sudden uncertainty. Partly, this epidemic is mostly a risk for old people, and so the Boomers are panicking -- and since they control so much of our national discourse, when they panic, that panic gets broadcast everywhere. The price war between the Saudis and the Russians has definitely added to the fun and games -- but we'll see how it all works out.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7594945", "title": "Dolmen arch", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Concerning the Seven Cantrefs... if you choose deities other than the examples you listed, does that change or affect the other attributes of the cantref? Sorry I don't have the book in front of me to be more specific...would you take into account the attributes of the cantref and more or less 'match' a name to it? Thanks for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7608769", "title": "Re: Dolmen arch", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you need to be fairly careful in assigning deities to the Cantrefs. I'd encourage you to consider using the original set for now, and bring in others after you've learned enough to be able to reassign the cantrefs on the basis of some degree of knowledge.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7595457", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To Bogatyr and 'Another Aussie', thank you both for your kind words last week.\nA parenI didn't see your comments til after cut-off time.\nHere with Mum now, (9.40pm) my sister is combing her hair to make her sleepy enough that we can get her to bed without too much fuss.\nRegards, Helen in Oz", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7595713", "title": "Gods and children", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My daughter is 7, almost 8, and was always very interested in religion. About 6 months ago I discovered that gods are real with help from Psyche. So a few months ago I told my daughter about it - I gave her a tame version of my experience, but she knows it's been pretty dramatic.\nThen she wanted to start praying too, so every night she prays the wording you suggested and that I first used: ‘I hope and believe there is a deity out there willing to work with me, please let me come into contact with that god or goddess.’ I did warn her that I did that for ages on and off until I got a response (at least one that I noticed), that we don’t know why gods do or don’t do things, but I think she inherited my lack of patience!\nI was raised Catholic but am in totally uncharted territory now. You suggested to other people to read myths from different pantheons to see which ones appeal. I’ve read her books of myths for children, but I don’t want to suggest that to her because she really, really wants to have a special god like I do, so she’d just pick anyone.\nI asked Psyche about it even though she doesn’t really talk to me, but afterwards before sleeping I was idly watching the white lights/astral static that I can always see in the dark and I asked again. I’m pretty sure they formed into an owl, twice. So I thought maybe Athena/Minerva was the answer. And when I read up on her, she sounds a bit like my daughter actually! But I did a divination next day to ask if that’s who she should pray to, and it gave me Colled. Right witness was Pobl and left witness was also Colled. On the other hand, divination hates me and the feeling is mutual…\nHow do deities relate to children? Should she pray to a whole pantheon, or wait for an answer from some specific god? And how would she choose a pantheon? Would it be ok for now if she just prayed to Psyche like me? I’m conscious that her path might be very different from mine and I don’t want to steer her the wrong way.\nDot.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7613121", "title": "Re: Gods and children", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on the deity, but Athena is one of the deities who traditionally was very close to girls -- she was served by young girls in some of her rituals, for example -- so she'd be a good choice. If you were an ancient Greek and saw the image of an owl take shape in the darkness, after asking that question, you'd accept as a matter of course that Athena was happy to accept your daughter's prayers. So I'd suggest you tell your daughter about what you saw, talk to her about Athena, and see if that works for her -- and if that does work out, your daughter's going to grow up to be even smarter and more self-possessed than she is already, which is not a bad thing...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7614401", "title": "Re: Gods and children", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Great thank you. She's going to be very excited about this!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7615937", "title": "Re: Gods and children", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I bet. You might consider -- if you haven't done so already! -- getting her a statue of Athena and helping her set up a little shrine where she can pray.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7622337", "title": "Re: Gods and children", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh yes, will get to work on that thanks. I see the Louvre have one of her with a cute little owl in her hand. She'd love a mini version of that if I can find one for sale...", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7596225", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nSince you are currently writing blogs on the history of American occultism, what do you think about \"The Secret Destiny of America\" book by Manly P. Hall?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7613633", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Like so many books of its kind, it's a magical working disguised as a prediction. Hall saw the potential for the United States to fill a very important role in the world, and created a potent mythic narrative to encourage the American people to rise to the challenge. Magic isn't foolproof, and he was shooting at a very exalted target; I'll leave it to you to decide to what degree his working succeeded.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7596481", "title": "planets/directions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG and all!\nA few magic mondays past, someone had\nasked about which planets would correlate\nwith which directions.\nyou posted this:\n'Sun is east, Mercury west, Mars south, Venus north, Saturn below, Jupiter above, and Moon within.'\nI have a couple of questions if I may:\n1. can these be used for the SoP? I presently just say the elements; and I\nwonder if I could use planets for my pantheon. I've been doing it for over 8 months and I am thinking I'd like to add more now.\nand if so, then:\n2. I am curious - why is mercury in the west?\nIn the SoP water is is the west, but wouldn't mercury be air?\nThis is why I wanted to know, because if it\ndoesn't fit for the SoP where west is water then I won't use it.\nThe other ones listed there make sense for it, it's just mercury I am a bit confused about.\nThankyou.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7613889", "title": "Re: planets/directions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can use these in the SoP -- that's what those attributions are there for.\n2) The element of water in Druid symbolism has meanings that aren't found in some other traditions. It's identified with growth and with learning, and with trees and tree lore -- that's why Esus the chief of tree-spirits is assigned to the west in the SoP. Mercury fits well with this, as the planet of learning, and also as the one planet whose corresponding metal (mercury) is liquid at room temperature.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7596993", "title": "Pittsburgh Magical Suggestions?", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Due to the coronavirus situation (Dad's really immunocompromised, and New York, where I changed buses, is now in a state of emergency), I'm staying with my sister in Pittsburgh for the foreseeable part of my trip instead of out in rural-er PA with my parents like we planned. So I figured I'd ask: does anyone have suggestions for bookstores/magical locations/herb shops/etc I should visit while I'm here? I might have some spare time between helping walk a post-surgery dog and distracting my nephew while his mom gets things done. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7610049", "title": "Re: Pittsburgh Magical Suggestions?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's been a while, but when I lived there, there was a neat little magic shop in Oakland called Hocus Pocus.\nFrick Park is, I believe, the second largest urban park on the east coast, after Central Park. It's worth visiting because it's beautiful. Also, I once had a spontaneous vision of the Green Man there.\nOn the other hand, I have encountered some creepy things in some of the other parks and urban woodlands (which are plentiful), Schenley Park included. So take that for what it's worth.\nAnd make sure to have a sandwich at Permanny's while you're there!\n-Steve T", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7618241", "title": "Re: Pittsburgh Magical Suggestions?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There's  a fun house show tonight in Hazelwood https://m.facebook.com/events/562367901289474 I won't be there, but some friends will. I would suggest going to Point State Park, the point of the rivers is potent. Bandi shaum in the south side is pretty cool too, you can walk up to a cliff through the woods that overlooks the city.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7597249", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good morning JMG and commentariat,\n1. In The Mystical Qabalah, Dion Fortune claims that Judaism is the predecessor of modern Western occultism. She makes repeated references to it as the “matrix of the European spiritual culture,” of the mystic tradition of Israel as being the basis of Western ceremonial magic, of Hebrew as the “sacred language of the West,” etc. Do you agree with this view? If you were to trace the genealogy of Western occultism, how would Judaism fit it with the line of descent that passes through Renaissance magic, Hermeticism, Platonism, and so on?\n2. Do you think that monotheism and polytheism can be reconciled at a deeper level, that while there are apparently many gods, they are all manifestations, servants or emanations of the one true god, the transcendent principle at the root of reality?\n3. What is the significance of moral virtue in magical work? Does being a good person, in the sense of having good karma or living up to the cardinal virtues of Christianity, matter for the purpose of being an effective magician, or is it all about technique, in the same way that someone can be a good musician while not being particularly virtuous?\n4. I’m interested in buying your book, the New Encyclopedia of the Occult (2003), from a source that will maximize the amount of money that goes to you, and that preferably isn’t Amazon. Could you point me in the right direction? A Canadian shipping option would be much appreciated.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7600577", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not JMG,\n2 - If you consider monotheistic God as a transcendent principle (like the Ineffable One/All/Good in Neoplatonism), and the polytheistic deities as archetypes on the mental plane, I think they can be reconciled.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7614657", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Dion Fortune was a Christian, if a somewhat eccentric one, and if you're Christian, yes, your spiritual roots are in Judaism -- after all, the god you worship was Jewish in his human incarnation. (I've always liked the joke that describes Jesus as a nice Jewish boy who went into his Father's business.) As I'm not Christian -- I've never even been baptized -- my relationship with Judaism isn't anything like so close. The Cabala is an important element of the Western esoteric tradition; it was originally Greek but came to the medieval Western world through Jewish channels, and picked up a lot of Jewish tradition and symbolism in the process -- but there are other aspects of Western esotericism, such as Neoplatonism, Hermeticism, and the Druid Revival, which have no connection to Judaism. So in the broader picture it's one ingredient in a large and diverse stew.\n2) Any two concepts can be reconciled given enough ingenuity, and working out various ways to fit monotheism and polytheism has been a booming industry for a good many centuries now. It's not something that interests me greatly, but if it turns your crank, by all means.\n3) Ethics are as important in magical practice as sanitation is in surgery, and for the same reason -- things tend to go septic otherwise. That said, a lot depends on your definition of moral virtue. It's essential not to use magic to try to harm or control other people, and a source of significant benefits to the practitioner to bless and empower other people; on the other hand, frantic sexual repression, which is what \"virtue\" means to too many people, benefits no one except your psychotherapist.\n4) I don't happen to know if Llewellyn.com has Canadian shipping options -- I'd be surprised if they don't -- but that's the best source for my Llewellyn books, in terms of my royalties. Thanks for asking!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7619265", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) I'm more interested in the moral/karmic background of an individual and how that affects their magical attainment, rather than the ethics of magical practice per se. Let's say you have two people of equal magical ability, A and B, who begin to practice at the same time, and for all intents and purposes, their practices are identical. Both A and B follow the guidelines of magical ethics and refrain from using it to harm or control other people. The only difference is that A is a convicted murderer, and B is karmically clean (for the sake of argument, assume they're a nun). Would there be any difference in their magical attainment, the degree of progress they can expect to see, and so on?\n4) Unfortunately, it looks like they don't ship to Canada at this time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7624129", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3) The moral background of the practitioner of magic is as irrelevant as it would be in the case of music or martial arts.\n4) In that case, you might see if any of the Canadian book chains have online ordering.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7630785", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "kulibali", "content": "Indigo (a Canadian bookstore chain) has a couple of copies:\nhttps://www.chapters.indigo.ca/en-ca/books/the-new-encyclopedia-of-the/9781567183368-item.html", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7597761", "title": "Viruses as sentient beings?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Myself and a couple of others I know are having really weird dreams about the novel Corona Virus.  In particular, that it is a sentient being and it wants something.  From an occult point of view, is this possible?  Could a virus be a god?  If it is a god, how would or should one safely interact with it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7614913", "title": "Re: Viruses as sentient beings?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Whether or not that's true literally -- and I have no idea one way or the other -- it can certainly be true symbolically. The next time you dream about it, try to remember to ask it what it wants.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7632065", "title": "Re: Viruses as sentient beings?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, smallpox appears to have been worshipped as a god, so there appears to be precedence for it. I also had a similar such dream, and it told me more or less that it wants to end our world. It didn't want to kill humanity, but it was determined that things needed to change.\nIf there was a deeper goal, or an end towards which it wanted to change things it wasn't saying though....", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7598017", "title": "Corona virus and the popularity of black magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you believe there is any connection between this corona virus and the rise in popularity of black magic, cursing and ddemonic magic that preceded it?  If so, what would be the best way to mitigate the spread of the virus and other plagues magically?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7615425", "title": "Re: Corona virus and the popularity of black magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If this is the blowback from the recent rise in black magic et al., it's a pretty tame blowback -- you might want to read\nthis article\nfrom the New England Journal of Medicine, which cuts through a lot of the hyperbole. (Sample passage: \"This suggests that the overall clinical consequences of Covid-19 may ultimately be more akin to those of a severe seasonal influenza (which has a case fatality rate of approximately 0.1%) or a pandemic influenza (similar to those in 1957 and 1968) rather than a disease similar to SARS or MERS, which have had case fatality rates of 9 to 10% and 36%, respectively.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7598273", "title": "astral and etheric", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,\nWhat's the difference between the Astral and etheric body, which one corresponds to our instict/emotional selves?\nAlso do you happen to know a good source for the magical properties of the black Walnut tree?\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7616193", "title": "Re: astral and etheric", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The astral body corresponds to the emotions, the etheric body corresponds to the instincts. The etheric body more generally is the body of prana/life force/voor, while the astral body is on a subtler plane, the plane of concrete consciousness which you access in imagination and dreaming.\n2) No, I wish I did.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7639233", "title": "Re: astral and etheric", "user": "syfen", "content": "1) Hmm, this begins to clear up some misconceptions. I didn't realize that the instincts were different from the imagination, but that actually makes sense. I'm still trying to wrap my head around the imagination and dreams as concrete consciousness, which is the reverse of how material science views the world.\n2) Well, I have a huge black walnut tree in my back yard, so I guess I'll go ask it.\nThanks for your help.\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7598785", "title": "Art of True Healing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recently picked up Regardie's Art of True Healing and have a couple questions about it.\n-Do you recommend switching from the solar plexus to the heart center for the middle pillar meditation, since that's the way I'm doing it with the CGD? Or do it the way he does it? Or experiment?\n-Is the middle pillar meditation safe to do in the presence of young children? At the moment I'm just at the stage of visualizing the centers filled with white light, and using th English phrases he suggests (I am, I see, I speak...etc)\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7616705", "title": "Re: Art of True Healing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you're working with the CGD system, stick with the heart center.\n2) You'll find that covered in the Magic Monday FAQ, which is linked in the Magic Monday post.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7599041", "title": "Putting  down the guitar mags and picking up the guitar...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I seen to remember you sharing a quote by M.P. Hall, the gist of which was that the day to start your spiritual practice is today, and the time to start is right now. I've had a terrible time with getting part the Watcher, and in starting to get angry. Right now it's a full moon and tomorrow it'll start to wane, and I have me idea what the planets are doing. But wit the above quote in mind, should I just say to Hades with to noon and just start already, if that's the way I feel?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7616961", "title": "Re: Putting  down the guitar mags and picking up the guitar...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. \"The place to start is where you are, and now is the acceptable time.\" My advice would be to get up from the computer right now -- at this very moment -- and begin your practices.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7599297", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nI've cast a number of shield charts now, mainly re my own path and issues.  This morning I tried something a bit different, admittedly motivated by some of the crowing I've been witnessing recently in the political press re Biden's ascendancy, presumed inevitability in light of the virus outbreak, and the \"reassertion of normalcy\" as he assembles his presumed governing team.  So I asked the question straight up: \"Will DJT win re-election this Nov?\"  I've not done an \"external\" question before, though I thought the answer in this case was quite clear:\n1  Amissio\n2  Albus\n3  Rubeus\n4  Caput Draconis\n5  Laetitia\n6  Fortuna Major\n7  Puer\n8  Tristitia\n9  Laetitia\n10 Fortuna Major\n11 Puella\n12 Fortuna Minor\nRW Puella\nLW Caput Draconis\nJ  Fortuna Minor\nJudge says \"yes.\"  LW suggests new beginnings?  Furthermore, rulership is 10th house, which is Fortuna Major, a strong \"yes.\"  So I get all that.\nMy questions are with respect to the ancillary aspects of the reading:\na) RW, representing the querent (me) is Puella.  What might this mean?\nb) Fortuna Major also shows up in the 6th house, relating to health and small animals (and service workers/staff?).  Is that relevant?  If so, how?  Might it refer to him \"winning\" the battle within the executive branch?  (But the Fortuna Minor in the judge perhaps suggesting that he's still dealing with a Democratic-held House?)\nc) Finally, following the via punctis, I go from Fortuna Minor in the judge to Puella in the RW to Laetitia in the first niece, to Amissio in the first mother.  This is the 1st house, representing the querent (again, me), and denotes loss.  How might this be understood?  Loss of image?  Loss of standing (with peers? community?)  Financial loss?\nd) Is there anything else in the chart that I'm missing?\nAny insights you could provide would be appreciated.\nThank you.\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7605185", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nI wanted to ask you to replace this question re an \"external\" reading with one much more pertinent to my path, but that comment didn't go through, so I'm guessing that I'm supposed to figure the answer out on my own.  (Which is mildly frustrating, as the resulting chart is far more ambiguous.)\nOh, well.\n--David BTL", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7617217", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, to begin with, don't try to read one chart as a shield chart or as a house chart. As a shield chart, this is a strong yes; as a house chart, it's a no. Which did you intend?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7618497", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I cast it as a shield chart.\n--David", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7624641", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In that case the answer is yes, and you don't worry about the houses of the house chart. In a chart for a big issue like this, one where you personally have very little involvement in the outcome, the querent isn't you as an individual, it's you as a representative of some broader class -- for example, the American people. The way of the points is therefore clear: Amissio as the first mother roots the result in the losses suffered by so many Americans as a result of neoliberal policies in the pre-Trump era; Laetitia as the first niece marks the arrival of better times; Puella as the right witness is an emblem of receptivity -- having seen the results of one term of Trumpismo, a lot of Americans are perfectly receptive to the idea of a second term. The electoral victory (Fortuna minor) follows, and the result is the beginning of a process of change (Caput Draconis).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7637441", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, that makes sense.  It is quite clear that I have a lot to learn, though, as I saw effectively none of that, aside from the judge.\n—David", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7599553", "title": "Amulet", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "jmg\n, thanks for doing this every Monday. I have two questions in relation to the amulet in the Frequently Asked Questions.\nI made three of the amulets at the last new moon, and gave one to a friend who is very sensitive and also very much in need of protection. She said she could feel the power of the amulet, but asked why the bag was red rather than, perhaps, green for protection or pink for unconditional love. Why is it red? Is there a reason?\nShe also asked about intention when the amulet was being made. How important is intention, and have you any advice on the intention to be followed when the amulet is being made?\nMany thanks\nM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7617729", "title": "Re: Amulet", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's red for life force. In most traditions of natural magic all over the world, red is the color of life and strength, which is what your protective amulet is meant to protect and defend.\n2) Natural magic is much less dependent on intention than other kinds of magic, but it's good to focus on the idea of protection and strength while you make this amulet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7627201", "title": "Re: Amulet", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks\nM", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7599809", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIn your experience, does performing the SOP outdoors improve/enhance its effects at all? And if random people see me performing the ritual, does this at all compromise it?\nYesterday was effectively the first warm day in my area this year. It was in the mid 50s and my first inclination was to go to the local park and try out the SOP there -- which I did. This park happens to have a lake in the middle of it. I stood in a position where the lake was due West of me, and directly to my North, a cluster of trees. It was sunny and windy out too. Seems like I had a nice assortment of \"real\" elements present as I did this, and performing the ritual felt quite nice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7617985", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It really depends on personal and local factors.\n2) Not unless having someone see you stresses you out.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7600321", "title": "Healing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My Dad and my wife don’t get along. They have both hurt each other and they both have trouble letting go.  They both also would like to get over it. What sort of thing could I do to help that healing along.  I am doing the Christian banishing ritual daily along with other devotions. I have also used the Anglican rosary, affirmations, and novennas effectively. Any suggestions\nThanks again\nWill Oberton", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7618753", "title": "Re: Healing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In your place I would pray to Haniel, the angel of Venus, to restore peace and good feeling between them. A green novena candle and rose incense would be appropriate. Do this every Friday in an hour of Venus --\nhere's a good online planetary hours calculator\n-- for at least seven weeks. You should see very positive results by then.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7620033", "title": "Re: Healing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you John Michael. This sounds like a good idea. I will do it. One question how do we know the names of the non scriptural angels and how they correspond to the planets?  Does that knowledge come from mystics?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7624897", "title": "Re: Healing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It comes from Jewish traditional lore, passed down to Christian occultists during the Renaissance. I suspect it's very ancient.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7600833", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What's your preferred translation of Parzival?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7619009", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The only one I've read is the fine old Mustard & Passage translation-- I still have my original Vintage paperback edition, copyright 1961.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7601089", "title": "The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John Michael, you know that I use muscle testing to communicate with my body about its health and needs, similar to the way that you use divination. That has produced consistently remarkable results, including my body telling me once that it had been bitten by a tick in the medial, posterior quadrant of my right calf. Lo and behold, I found a tiny larval-stage tick that I had to look at under a magnifying glass to make sure it wasn’t a grain of sand. Not much chance of contracting lyme disease from a larva, but muscle testing revealed that my body could only be sure of no infection after three days. Three days later my body gave the all clear (which I did have the lab coats confirm the next time I went in for a physical.)\nThat was just to provide a context for when I write that we all have far more contact and connection with our strangely intelligent and willful bodies and psyches than we tend to recognize. Our bodies are continually monitoring and adjusting our blood pressure, glandular secretions, chemical imbalances, temperature, immune responses, etc., etc., etc. Our bodies know so much that never comes into our conscious awareness, and, if we can figure out how to respect them enough to communicate with them as equals, they are happy to share that information. The body truly is a temple, complete with oracle. Our bodies’ goals like health and survival may be very different form our personalities’ goals like wealth and power, and they will certainly not share their truth with us if we try to control and manipulate them. They may well lie to us if we try, even to their own detriment. Never try to harness a wild thing; content yourself to travel beside it wherever it is going.\nI have often used muscle testing with friends to make medicinal teas for their various health concerns, but I had never tried to make a tea for myself until this coronavirus epidemic. I have to say, my body has pretty serious opinions about what herbs will and will not help with pneumonia, flu, and coronaviruses in general. Some herbs well noted for their immune support leave my body completely unimpressed, while it emphatically insists on others with no history I can find of use as a fever reducer, immune booster, lung supporter, decongestant, etc. As always, when I dare to ask the oracles, I respect their answers, whether or not I understand or agree with them.\nWith the multitude of disturbing effects from the coronavirus sweeping the globe, I am most puzzled by people’s fixation on protecting, isolating, quarantining themselves from this more-or-less frightening part of the natural world rather than learning from and working with the disease to increase their chances of survival. Death scares us; that I get. But the media I am reading, including many alternative sources, in multiple languages are ignoring any possibility of strengthening one’s self, one’s health, one’s immune system. This ensorcelled dependence on either fighting against nature or throwing oneself on the mercy of expert help should nature manage to sneak through our man-made defenses has been carefully built up through the continual cacomagic of advertising and political messaging. Many “consumers” no longer remember that they possess any ability to positively affect their own lives, other than by buying another hyped product. Given how natural a response it is to become as healthy as possible when anticipating a challenging trial, the cacomagicians must have worked extra disempowerments into their spells to prevent their victims from being able to recover their self-reliance in life-threatening circumstances.\nWhen this virus showed up in January, I started swimming for two hours a day both to strengthen my body and to increase my lung capacity. If drowning in my own lungs is the fate I would prefer to prevent as long as possible, improving my lungs’ efficiency at keeping me alive seems like a pretty good place to start. Fortunately, I just love swimming, so two hours of grueling workout feels like meditating to me. Prioritizing deep, restful sleep over the distractions that prevent it is a goal in which I still have lots of room for improvement. Yay, another worthwhile focus for my attention in stressful times!\nThe cacomagicians themselves have gotten caught in their own spells, and now appear to suffer the worst cases of ensorcellment. The mental cul-de-sac of isolating ourselves from whatever we find threatening, out of our control, or just generally yukky infests the dominant culture at every level, from gated communities to Russiagate to staging color revolutions. The state response to this viral outbreak so far has mainly consisted of ignoring it, misinforming anyone willing to listen, attempting futilely to isolate it, throwing experts at it while retreating, and blaming anyone who provides accurate information or takes effective action. How did we manage to double down so completely on our past-its-pull-date, Western, Humanist, Progressive vision of limitless human power and control? Our mythology appears to leave us far less equipped for dealing with serious shock than do the myths of the primitive barbarians we so love to look down on and pity. Is the barbarism of reflection the cause of our mental illness, or its eventual antidote, or both in their proper course?\nCan any of us really escape the incessant pull of the Western cultural myth of human control? Can we recover from the biblical myth of our dominion over nature, to develop an appreciation and respect for nature and the wild, willful things around us, including our bodies and psyches? Will choosing to strengthen ourselves deliver us from that crippling mythology or just redirect it towards the individual level — e.g. all we really control is ourselves? Is suffering from a less virulent form of the myth the best we can hope for while that myth continues to dominate the culture at large?\nChristophe", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7619521", "title": "Re: The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm just as baffled as you are by the flight into isolation. Especially for those who aren't at significant risk from this -- and if you're under sixty, don't have a serious health condition, don't smoke, and take reasonable care of your health, this means you -- it seems obvious to me that the best thing to do is get plenty of rest and moderate, healthy exercise, eat well, do whatever else you do to boost your immune system, and make sure you have appropriate remedies for a respiratory infection on hand, and then don't worry about it.  I expect to catch CoVID-19, if I haven't gotten it already, and I expect to be sick for a few days and then get over it, like the vast majority of people who've gotten it so far. That seems far healthier to me than flinging myself into a frantic and futile attempt to escape one of the ordinary realities of incarnate existence.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7623873", "title": "Re: The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On The Other Hand, if you live in an area with a very high percentage of seniors, lots of health care facilities, and are in a health care profession, please take the recommendations seriously; hand washing, don't touch your face in public, time your expeditions to stay away from the heaviest population exposures.  This is common sense, really.  I work in Hospice, and although I may not show symptoms, ever, of Coronavirus, or flu, or common cold, or whatever, I CAN be a vector.  Universal Precautions aren't extreme, and they are easily learned.  Bump them up with good affirmations and Hoodoo baths when you think it's necessary.  Washington State (where I live) has a major outbreak in King County in one health care facility, with the most fatalities as well.  Am I worried?  Not for myself.  In consideration for my elders, many of whom are compromised and in their 80's or 90's I will slow down my visits if the virus begins to show up in my vicinity.  --Sidney", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7625153", "title": "Re: The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, granted -- but that's not the same thing as locking yourself away for weeks.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7638465", "title": "Re: The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "syfen", "content": "What exactly is muscle testing?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7648961", "title": "Re: The bizzare faith in the cacomagic of self-isolation", "user": "open_space", "content": "I live in Seattle where a big chunk of the cacopanic is taking place and I have stopped telling people what I think about it because they are just too deep into it and I don’t like to be seen as a crazy person. The real damage to me is the panic, stress and delusion created by the media as you say. People at my work are absolutely losing their minds over it and I have clearly seen that people with most panic are people that spend their whole day with their faces shoved in a screen lustingly scrolling through the news live update of covid. On one of the groups at work someone asked. “How is it out there?” With and apocalyptic tone to it. The general agreement between the whole group is really not to get outside of their apt for as long as it lasts and I can tell how much their mental health is taking a toll which makes their immune systems so much weaker. Oh the irony!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7601345", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP\nEdit, that's a flower head, resembling a tulip or possibly a simple rose not flowerbed", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7601601", "title": "Boxing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just as I finished typing my first question I remembered a second question.\nI just started learning how to box.  This week I was working the heavy bag. I envisioned someone I do not care for and punched the bag really hard a couple of times right into their imaginary face. When I did that I thought that is probably a bad idea. Sending that emotion/action out through the astral realm.  So my question is am I correct that hitting the heavy bag like that is foolish.  Then if it is foolish should a person ever imagine an opponent of any kind during boxing/martial arts practice\nThanks a second time.\nWill Oberton", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7620289", "title": "Re: Boxing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, it's a bad idea. If you want to imagine an opponent, make it someone who doesn't actually exist, so you don't focus hostile energies on a real person.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7623361", "title": "Re: Boxing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What could happen to the other guy if you do this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7625409", "title": "Re: Boxing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're basically directing a curse at him. It's not that different from sticking pins in a voodoo doll.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7601857", "title": "Four Powers", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear John,\nI came across something in the writings of RJ Stewart which I haven't seen elsewhere. He enumerates 4 Powers that match the 4 Elements: Life (Air), Light (Fire), Love (Water) and Law (Earth). Are you aware of this set outside of Stewart's work? He doesn't seem to indicate whether he developed this himself or learnt it from WG Gray or someone else...\nThanks again for your time,\nManuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7620801", "title": "Re: Four Powers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's in Gray's work, notably the\nSangreal Sodality\nseries, so I'm pretty sure that's where Stewart got it. It may well be original to Gray.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7605441", "title": "Sending prayers to those who have passed on", "user": "jeffinwa", "content": "Hi John,\nMy wife of 50 years left her body behind the end of Jan. this year. I've been sending her light and love and \"happy trails to you\" daily since.\nFor whatever reason, the other day, I began to wonder just how to grok the entity I was praying for; she's not \"name\" any longer nor \"body\" but essence/spirit and as such unknowable to me now.\nAny advice as to how I can think of her as she is now while I pray or is this even an issue?\nThis question seems awkward as I write it but I want to do my best for her as she did for me while we shared this long strange trip we call life.\nBlessings", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7621313", "title": "Re: Sending prayers to those who have passed on", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, please accept my condolences. That's got to be difficult.\nSecond, according to the traditions I'm familiar with, the dead remember their former names and forms in the afterlife, and welcome prayers directed to them via those names and forms. So remember your wife as she was at the strongest and happiest time in her life, and use the form of her name or the nickname that you used for her while she was alive. That's the usual way it's done in those cultures that make prayers for the dead an important part of their spiritual lives, and it seems to work well.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7632833", "title": "Re: Sending prayers to those who have passed on", "user": "jeffinwa", "content": "Thank you; it is difficult but growing usually is.\nThank you, I feel better knowing that; your suggestions feel right and that's what I'll continue with.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7605697", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "The discussion last week about Christians accidentally practicing magic - the \"Angel boards\" and Christianized tarot cards, and whatnot - caught my eye. Mostly because I noticed something similar at my very Baptist/literal Creationist Dad's house over Christmas.\nHis wife was wearing a bracelet that had 7 different colored beads on a purple cord. Curiosity piqued, I asked her about it. She explained as she pointed that the black bead was for original sin (and I thought yes, Saturn, secrets, limitation), the red bead was for the blood shed on the cross (and I thought yep, Mars, blood, violence, courage), the blue bead was for baptism in water (and I thought, uh-huh, Moon, water, tides, cycles of renewal). I think you get where this is going!\nAnyway, I thought exactly the same thing you did. I didn't care what she was associating with each color, just found myself thrilled that she was engaging in that sort of symbolism.\nThanks as always for this forum!\nGrover", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7621569", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating! I'm delighted to hear this; the rebirth of the symbolic imagination in American Christianity could unconstipate a lot of minds.  ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7632577", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "That verb seems remarkably apropos...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7634113", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was chosen carefully!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7641281", "title": "Accidental Christian magic", "user": "ritaer", "content": "A couple of years ago my grandson joined the US Marine Corp. Now days each training platoon is assigned a Facebook page for family and close friends to communicate so that they can share travel plans to attend boot camp graduation, encouraging words, etc. Boot camp culminates in a three day field exercise called the Crucible which ends with the recruits climbing a hill to greet the rising sun and be awarded their Globe and Anchor insignia. I noted that many of the families (who from other things they posted were obviously Christian) were posting photos of good luck candles they were making for their recruit--some with names, birthdays, date of the Crucible, Bible verses, etc. written on a glass candle or on signs around the candle. I thought, \"do these good Christians realize they are doing magic?\" Meanwhile, I was, of course blessing a red candle with Mars oil and  Capricorn oil,  writing his name and birth date on the candle and set it up on a Mars sigil to light at the time the exercise was scheduled to begin. Was it a complete coincidence that the exercise began on the day and hour of Mars?? He did fine and assured us that it was no big deal.\nRita", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7641793", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Grover - In the past couple years I've seen jelly beans for sale around Easter with the exact same color symbolism explained on the package!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7605953", "title": "Magic & Cell Salts for... Hypertension?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nThe news reports show that hypertension and COVID-19 don't mix. I've had hypertension for several years now, something that seems to be hereditary. I treat it with medication but, so far, the news doesn't say whether there's any difference between treated and untreated hypertension in terms of mortality outcomes. I'm going to assume there aren't.\nI'm exercising and working on my diet and all of the conventional things I should do.\nAre there any magical or quasi-magical (or homeopathic) options I ought to include in my arsenal to rid myself of hypertension? I have a complete set of Hyland's cell salts. I don't use them regularly mostly because I can't figure out how I ought to be using them - there doesn't seem to be much consensus on how to employ them. Do you have any recommendations? Any books that might prove helpful in using the cell salts optimally? Websites seem to disagree and suggest different things - which has made me throw up my hands.\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7622081", "title": "Re: Magic & Cell Salts for... Hypertension?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay,\nthis\nis the book on cell salts I recommend. The thing you need to know in using cell salts is that which one you use doesn't depend on the label the doctors have slapped on the condition you have, it depends on the fine details of your symptom picture -- and not just the symptoms of the one condition, the whole galaxy of symptoms your body is displaying. You go to the repertory of symptoms in the back of the book I've recommended -- or any other book on cell salts -- and look over the symptoms, noting down which cell salts are recommended for the specific symptoms you have. You'll find that they tend to cluster around one or two salts, and those are the ones you need to take.\nBTW, Ferrum phos and Natrum sulph, 4 pills each under the tongue 4 times daily, is the traditional treatment for flu-like illnesses. Don't take them until you first notice symptoms. Just saying...  ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7607489", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was driving kids around, and got to thinking on that some natural fiber fabrics are insulating magically and some are not, and we have the Old Testament prohibition of fabrics of mixed fibers, which could be a cultural set aside marker or it could be a practical magic thing.  From there my mind wandered to head coverings, both hats and otherwise, and as a hat wearing lady, whether those might have magical effects is of interest--my particular favorite is an antique of real beaver felt trimmed with mink, and dates to WWII.  Of course traditionally there were sex differences in who covered their heads and how, but it's very common in older cultures.  I'd say it's just a pre-central-heating and air conditioning thing, but might there be other reasons?\nI know I feel almost naked when I have to take my hat off for Eastern Star, and I have no religious convictions attached, just a dislike of skin cancer and preference for comfort!\nAny thoughts on the subject?  Any of you with better aura seeing abilities than mine (which is to say, everyone, probably) have any insight?\nBoysMom", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7622593", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are certainly other reasons. The pineal gland in the middle of the brain is a vestigial eye, and is photosensitive; the amount of light it receives has effects on consciousness. That's why Catholic and Buddhist monks shave the tops of their heads, and also why Sikh and orthodox Jewish men always keep the tops of their heads covered -- different faiths benefit from different conditions of consciousness. There may be more to it than that, but that's certainly a factor.\nI inevitably wear hats outside, for what it's worth.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7631553", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does the long beard have any benefits?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7634369", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's saved me hundreds of dollars on shaving supplies. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7636929", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The question about beard above (which was asked by someone else) caught my attention!\nOnce a Turkish occultist, Ata Nirun (may he rest in peace) claimed that the priestesses of the Vril Society in Nazi Germany had unusually long hair, in order to enhance their mediumistic receptivity, like a kind of antenna. When I saw the question above, I thought, maybe long beard had a similar function :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7644865", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't noticed any particular magical effect, for whatever that's worth.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7642561", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "And so you can afford cell salts!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7644609", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They're cheaper than any other medicine I know -- $16 or so for 1000 tablets.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7609025", "title": "Affirmation Question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!\nI've been using the affirmation technique you outlined in a post here since September 2019. I have one affirmation that is general, as you suggested, and\nanother that is specific.\nI can say TSW with certainty.\nYet, the one affirmation seems to be bringing me into situations where other of my personal issues are coming up, as a way of working the specific affirmation of \"I am strong\". ...And I'd say I'm getting stronger, both physically, and in the other spheres of body, mind, emotions.\nAt that point it has me wondering if I should change my specific affirmation to something so I can shore up that part of my character, which needs, well some strengthening... or would continuing with the one be the best option?\nI had also wondered about using a third affirmation for a short period of time to deal with the issues?\nIt had been /is my plan to continue on to September until choosing another one to make it a whole year as you recommended.\nJournaling would be another option of course.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7623105", "title": "Re: Affirmation Question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd recommend journaling for now, and considering whether you want to go to a different affirmation in September. Dealing with the issues may be the best way for you to become stronger just now.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7657665", "title": "Re: Affirmation Question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for re-Affirming what I thought was also the best course. I just wanted to bounce the idea off someone. I journaled last night and felt better. Sometimes you just have to drain the swamp. It makes sense that by continuing to use the Strength affirmation until September, that I will continue to grow in Strength. I am about halfway there, so no waffling now!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7609281", "title": "Exercise", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello all,\nBecause autoimmune issues come up here fairly persistently, I thought I would share this: unicorn wellness studio. Com. Tandy presents half-hour workouts online that are grounded into current astrology. She has autoimmune issues herself and has a lot to say about meeting yourself where you are at and handling low energy days.\nHopefully someone finds this helpful,\nHappy Monday!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7609537", "title": "Geomancy Question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Whether or not a specific impulse I keep feeling, to do something which would be rather self-destructive, comes from someone working hostile magic.\nHouse 1: Puella\nHouse 12: Puer. Puer springs to the 11th house.\nSextile between Puer and 11 and Puella in 1 is the only mode of perfection, nor do either of the significators occur elsewhere in the chart. On the other hand, the 11th house is the house of the person I suspect is responsible, and Puer makes for a reasonable description of them.\n1. Would you read it as \"Yes, but only indirectly-- or perhaps unintentionally\"?\n2. How much use do you make of the Index and Part of Fortune? In this case the Index leads to the First House, and the Part of Fortune to the 11th! Are those worth taking into consideration?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7623617", "title": "Re: Geomancy Question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In my experience, if the only mode of perfection is a relatively weak aspect, the answer is \"No, but...\" My guess is that it's not hostile magic as such, but someone in the 11th house is doing something not quite magical along those lines -- for example, fantasizing repeatedly about you doing the self-destructive thing.\n2) I use the index pretty often and the Part of Fortune only in money questions. In this case, the Index, as the hidden factor in the situation, is you; this suggests that the impulse is by no means entirely someone else's doing, or even that you may be doing things to encourage your friend to fantasize, etc. about whatever it is.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7610817", "title": "The Path of the Arrow", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm beginning to Re-read DF's \"The Mystical Qsbslah\".  I feel that I've read too much over the years and practiced too little.  On p 52, paragraph 15, she refers to the path of the arrow as a swift, direct Way of Illumination free of certain dangers, but one that confers no magical powers.  I noted in the margin that that did not seem to me to be a disadvantage.  But where to begin and what practice to follow if one's aim is illumination, a good rebirth, but no magical powers.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7625665", "title": "Re: The Path of the Arrow", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the path of the mystic. If you want to practice that, prayer is your central practice, and Evelyn Underhill's fine book\nMysticism\nis a good place to start reading up on it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7611329", "title": "Tax season", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nplease remind us where to find the day and time of Saturn for a given locality to receive the greatest advantage in tax processing. I want to make sure I rely on the right source.\nI would like to do it this year just as I did last - btw this is another one of the TSWs - it worked exactly as you recommended - it worked actually even better then I even expected. The IRS acceptance message came in RIGHT after we submitted! Literally seconds after!! This never happened before and our taxes were always pretty straight forward. I couldn't really believe it! It was so astonishing how incredibly precisely your advice worked! I mean I was really stunned how powerful Saturn's magic was! I know it sounds dramatic but it was so instant and so powerful. I was pretty thankful to Saturn too, I can tell you that.\nI highly recommend it to those who still need to submit!\nJohn, thanks a lot for this great guidance!\nBest, A.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7625921", "title": "Re: Tax season", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The day of Saturn is, not surprisingly, Saturday, and the hours of Saturn can be found using a planetary hours calculator --\nhere's a good one\n. I\"m glad to hear you had such good results -- but not at all surprised. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7611585", "title": "Cabalistic and Elemental Crosses", "user": "barefootwisdom", "content": "As ever, thanks for hosting Magic Monday. I learn a lot every week, even when I don't have a question of my own! This week, I would like to ask about something that's been on my mind for some days now...\nWhat's the difference between the Cabalistic Cross and Circle of Presence (from Golden Dawn style ritual), and Elemental Cross (from the Dolmen Arch and similar style ritual)?\nI'm going to treat the Cabalistic Cross and Circle of Presence from your polytheist GD work as if they're basically interchangeable, and note the two different sets of gestures involved (one hand like the Christian sign of the Cross, or two-handed) closely resemble the two different sets of instructions you provide, in various places, for the Elemental Cross. So that's not it.\nI also note that different versions of the Cabalistic Cross can activate either the heart center or the solar plexus, so that's not it either.\nPerhaps a difference in the \"minor\" energy center at the top, crown center (Cabalistic Cross) vs. pineal gland (Elemental Cross)? But not all versions of the latter involve more than one center at all, so that's out, too.\nBoth rituals (and many others beside) seem to have the effect of centering the ritualist, both at the center of the working space and of the cosmos.\nThe most likely place that I can see a difference is this: The Cabalistic Cross and Circle of Presence both focus on a single divine power, whether we think of that monotheistically (as in Christian versions of the GD) or \"henotheistically\" (where that God or Goddess is the source and center of\nmy own\nuniverse, the center of my attention and devotion, at least for the duration of this ritual act). Whereas the Elemental Cross seems to be intrinsically a four-fold thing, where none of those parts has any particular centrality or priority over the others.\nOf course, the word \"Elemental\" in the name may also be a bit of a giveaway, pointing in this direction. I suspect that, to the extent this is a/the salient difference, it points to a larger distinction in how the two magical systems approach their work: focusing on a single \"center\" vs. balancing a complex set of powers.\nThat's the fruit of some careful reflection on my end. Can you offer any thoughts that might take me further? Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7626177", "title": "Re: Cabalistic and Elemental Crosses", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It sounds to me as though you've made a very good beginning in your meditations on the subject -- and yes, this is the kind of subject that's best approached through meditation. Keep at it and see what else you can learn!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7643329", "title": "Re: Cabalistic and Elemental Crosses", "user": "barefootwisdom", "content": "Now why does that advice not surprise me? ;)\nIn all seriousness, thank you for the encouragement!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7614145", "title": "Catholicism and the LBRP", "user": "kevinprice1", "content": "About five or six years ago I spent a year of daily practice working through \"Learning Ritual Magic.\" That was my first dedicated spiritual practice and it dramatically deepened my experience of daily life. From there I bought \"Circles of Power\" and \"Paths of Wisdom\" as well as your edition of Regardie's \"Golden Dawn\" and worked with them nearly every day for about a year and a half.\nA bit over two years ago my grandfather who I was close with passed away at the age of 95. He was a devout Catholic. I was raised Catholic but had left the church in my teens (I am now 36). Around the time of his passing, I started feeling drawn back to Catholicism in a powerful way. I also started getting strange synchronicities such as three different people giving me copies of \"The Imitation of Christ\" (Kempis) and then learning that this was my great-great-grandmother's (the first of my family line to make it to America from Ireland) choice devotional text. Apparently, she read it daily for the last sixty years of her life and then my great-grandmother also became obsessed with the book towards the end of her life.\nMy grandmother (the wife of the grandfather whose passing seems to have triggered this) passed away last month and my devotion to Christ has grown with her passing. She and my grandfather were devout and none of their seven children or 13 grandchildren have stayed with the church. With all of this, my daily ritual practice has shifted to the rosary, reading from \"The Imitation of Christ,\" nightly meditation on \"Divine Intimacy,\" a traditional Carmelite book of Catholic meditation, devotional prayer and a bit of Bible reading, as well as starting the day with the LIRP and ending with the LBRP as they are described in \"Learning Ritual Magic.\" Last year I started teaching at a Catholic school so now I attend mass daily and try to go to a Traditional Latin Mass on Sunday. I typically go to confession once a month.\nAnyway, I'm wondering what you make of all of this. If you had told me five years ago that starting a magical path would have led me here I would have thought you were crazy. However, I am finding this to be a very deep and fulfilling experience and my Catholic practice is making me feel connected to everything in a way that no other spiritual practice has. Also, I'm wondering about the Christian LBRP that I've seen discussed here. The Golden Dawn LBRP feels completely energetically aligned to me with the rest of my practices. Am I missing something? Thank you so much for all that you do. Your work has changed my life in so many ways.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7626433", "title": "Re: Catholicism and the LBRP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, you're not missing anything. The LBRP comes out of Christian magical traditions -- that's why it incorporates the Sign of the Cross and invokes the archangels at the quarters. if that's what feels right to you to do, keep at it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7615681", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No questions, just gratitude.  Thank you for all your effort on our behalf, JMG.  --Sidney", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7626689", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're welcome and thank you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7616449", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nMore generally, while I understand (and can certainly appreciate) that epidemics are no small matter, the market panic of recent weeks--and particularly today, with its circuit-breaker trigger--seems excessive and disproportionate.  Is there a possibility of some other outside influence being involved here?  And how might one discern if that was indeed the case?\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7626945", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The market was massively overbought and could have plunged for almost any reason, or none at all -- and it's had two very good reasons. The CoVID-19 pandemic is crashing the tourist industry worldwide and also messing with foreign trade, so a lot of countries and companies that depend on tourist dollars or on trade are pulling money out of markets to stay solvent -- that's one source of massive downside volatility. Now Saudi Arabia and Russia are in an all-out price war over crude oil, and the Saudis as well as every other nation that depends on oil revenues is having to scramble to pay its bills, which means even more money is being pulled out of the market. The drop in fuel prices will help cushion things here in the US, but a lot of countries are going to be in a world of hurt; if the price of oil stays at its current level for more than a few weeks, in particular, I'm not sure Venezuela's current government will survive. It's going to be a wild time!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7652545", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you think all these current events are preliminaries for the grand mutation on Dec 21?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7653313", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I think it's all the consequences of the eclipses in December and January. The Grand Mutation is a shift that will unfold over a couple of centuries.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7620545", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I'm hoping this question is not stupid or pointless, but since last summer when I took a quite wonderful trip to Glastonbury and other points in southern England, I've been seeing symbols before my eyes--my physical eyes, not a visualization--usually when I wake up in the morning, and during meditation, now that I'm doing that regularly. Generally with eyes closed, but not exclusively. Most often the symbol is an 8-spoked wheel with a lot of concentric circles forming the wheel. Sometimes now I see a 5-pointed star, and occasionally a Christian cross (definitely something I didn't expect, or want, for that matter). Is this a normal feature of meditation? Is there a standard meaning for the wheel symbol, or should I work it out for myself? I'm assuming it doesn't mean I'm losing my mind or anything, but it does seem curious.\n2) In a fiction work I was reading, I ran across the phrase \"the 7 veils of existence are stripped away,\" when a character has a shattering moment of realization about what he wants and what he must do. Is there an author or work where I could look up the 7 veils of existence? (Internet search didn't turn up much that looked useful.) I see someone posted a question about \"3 veils of negative existence,\" which makes me wonder if this writer got it a bit garbled.\nThanks much for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7627457", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's neither stupid nor pointless. Your trip seems to have jolted open a previously dormant talent for clairvoyance -- Glastonbury in particular will do that. I'd encourage you to meditate on the symbols you see, and see what they have to teach you.\n2) It's a reference to the \"dance of the seven veils\" from Richard Strauss' opera\nSalome\n, which got picked up and used as a metaphor all through later literature.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7621057", "title": "Physical Culture, Dion Fortune, Alternative Medicine", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG:\nThank you once again for hosting Magic Monday; I have a few questions this week.\n1) I'm thinking of incorporating a physical culture practice into my daily routine.  I'm considering the Five Rites (i.e. the Tibetan Rites of Rejuvenation), would this conflict with the flow of energies in Golden Dawn banishing rituals? Are their more compatible exercise I should consider?\n2) You mentioned previously that the Golden Dawn tradition is excessively Solar, and that Dion Fortune introduced a Telluric current into her version of the GD (e.g. fewer grades, having both a Solar Logos and a Planetary Spirit).  For someone doing a Dion Fortune influenced GD practice what else might be needed to find balance between the Solar and Telluric currents?\n3) What are things to consider when seeking a licensed alternative healthcare practitioner, what kind of red flags should I lookout?\nThank you in advance for your time and consideration.  Peace and blessings to you.\nSincerely,\nAnon.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7628225", "title": "Re: Physical Culture, Dion Fortune, Alternative Medicine", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The Five Rites have become a common set of exercises in Golden Dawn circles since Donald Michael Kraig many years ago included them in his book\nModern Magic\n. They seem to fit very well with the GD system and I'd encourage you to go ahead with them if that seems appropriate to you.\n2) It's a little more complex than that. The solar imbalance of the GD wasn't a matter of solar vs. telluric, it was solar vs. all the other planets, and Fortune corrected that by discarding the GD grade system in favor of one adapted from Masonic sources. If you're engaged in solitary practice you should be fine. The rituals used to attain adeptship in solitary GD practice -- for example, the Bornless One ritual, the Watchtower ritual, and the fine ritual for spiritual development included in Regardie's\nThe Golden Dawn\n-- don't fixate on solar symbolism and so don't run into the same problems.\n3) That's not something with which I have much experience, since I've mostly provided my own health care. Anyone else?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7657921", "title": "Re: Physical Culture, Dion Fortune, Alternative Medicine", "user": "scotlyn", "content": "If I may, and if it is not too late for a reply.\nI say the following as a practitioner of acupuncture.\nWhen asking around, focus firstly on results. Every \"type\" of practice attracts people who are bluffing, or dabbling, as well as people who have gone deeply into whatever wisdom and skills that branch of healing works with. The difference will show up, over time, by the results people have - \"the proof of the pudding\" as they say. Good results, consistently, are the fruit of serious study and practice  of ANY branch, so don't get overly hung up about the \"type\" of branch.\nSecondly, follow your own gut when meeting the practitioner, or speaking to them over the phone. Every healing occasion includes you. If you are unhappy with or distrustful of your practitioner, then you will be missing the important half of the encounter, which is your own full and whole-hearted participation.\nIf you hear of a practitioner who has a consistent record for good results, and you get a good feel when you engage with them, then you are probably onto a good thing, and less likely to be wasting your precious time and money.\nBest wishes for your healing and recovery!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7621825", "title": "Remember past lives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Happy monday Mr. Greer:\nI'm coming back after a year to thank you and Mr. Mathiesen for your life changing advice on how to protect myself, looking back, I can't believe all the difference it has made in my life a little ritual that I my eyes looked incapable to do anything against such hate and anger. But it did! And more than I ever expected. Now I know my destiny is aligned with my will!\nThat been said, I would like to know your opinion in something that has happened to me almost a month ago. When I was trying to sleep I \"remembered\" something that never happened to me. In this  \"memory\" there were people I know, but they weren't there in the roles they are now. This memory turned into a incontrolable rain of emotions and thoughts that didn't let me sleep, until I wrote them down at 4 am. I wanted to know if it could be a past life memory or some kind of medium experience.. I don't know how could I call it?\nThanks again!\nPS. I started psicological therapy this week because of some anxiety issue's I want to work on, should I tell this to her?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7628481", "title": "Re: Remember past lives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That could be a past life memory, yes. As for your therapist, well, see how well she deals with you generally before deciding that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7629761", "title": "Re: Remember past lives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!\nI will meditate now in the influence it can have on my relationship with this people and solve this karma we have..\nThanks a LOT", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7624385", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nDo you know if the Greek kingdoms in Bactria and Northern India (after the conquests of Alexander the Great) had any influence upon Buddhism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7628737", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Quite a bit.  Here's a Buddhist statue from the Bactrian kingdom of Gandhara:\nThe influence of Greek sculpture on it stands out like lumps!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7630529", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Other than the artistic influences, did any of the ancient Greek philosophical schools have any influence upon the doctrines of Buddhism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7634625", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Last I checked, scholars are still debating that. There's a great deal of literature on that; you might want to look into it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7637185", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "The influence can go the othger way, too.  There are  (IIRC) a few approving referenceas in early Christian treatises to the\ngymnosophistai\n\"naked sages\" of India.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7627713", "title": "Geomancy & SoP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nI've been doing the SoP daily now for about 8 months now according to your version with different names of God, and really like it and seem to have good results with it. Meanwhile I've been doing Geomantic readings, although not as often, but feel pretty confident with the shield chart at least and feel that the magic system with talismans/gamahes you present in the Geomancy book might be worth a try.\nAnyway, I have read here that SoP can be used for more then the balancing/protecting effect and rather can be used to perform magic for other purposes. Would you consider this combination of SoP & Geomantic talismans as compatible and safe?\nIf so, what book(s) should I read to better understand the symbolism of SoP and enhance it to crank up the force?\nAlso, is there any problem with having a talisman on me when doing the SoP?\nThanks, Ola", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7628993", "title": "Re: Geomancy & SoP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The book you want -- the one book I've done so far on the practical applications of the SoP -- is\nThe Druid Magic Handbook\n. Yes, you can combine that with geomantic talismans and other aspects of geomantic magic.\n2) That shouldn't be any kind of problem.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7627969", "title": "Using magic to get rich...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Let's just imagine that I wanted to use some magic to get filthy rich.  Is there one of your published works that would be useful for this?  Thanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7629505", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "None of my published books discuss that, because it's so very simple. The secret to achieving anything in life is to put that one thing ahead of everything else, and treat every moment of your life as a tool you can use to achieve your goal. You want to become filthy rich? Fine. Make that the goal of your life. Treat every dollar that comes into your hands as a tool to get more dollars. Treat every expenditure that doesn't further the cause of becoming rich as a waste. Assess every action and every relationship in your life in terms of whether it will make you richer. Get up every morning thinking about some new way to maximize your wealth. If you do that, I promise you you'll be insanely rich sooner than you expect.\nOf course most people who want to use magic to get rich don't want to do that; they want the magic to make them rich while they continue to loaf about, drifting aimlessly from one temporary goal to another that contradicts it. If you do that, no matter what workings you do, you won't get rich -- and you won't become a competent mage, either, because magic requires exactly the same unity of focus. That's why mages don't get rich -- their will is focused on magic, not on money. If they're any good, they make enough money to pay their bills and keep them well supplied with occult books, but beyond that? A waste of time that could go into magic.\nWill one thing, and one thing only, and if it's within the realm of human possibility, you'll achieve it. There -- I've just told you the supreme secret of magic. Can you use it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7639489", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"Will one thing, and one thing only, and if it's within the realm of human possibility, you'll achieve it.\"\nIs this why you advise one course at a time? If you try to do two, after all, you're defusing your will...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7645121", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Bingo.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7640769", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the same commenter, but I would say the tricky thing about that is to be able to will something single-mindedly and one-pointedly. There's probably a lifetime of magical training involved to arrive at that point, to bring the lower will in harmony with the higher will, and if you can achieve that, then you're probably on the way to enlightenment anyway, and thus beyond material desires ;).\nIf the psychologists are right, then willpower is a limited resource; all of us, to a greater or lesser extent, are prisoners of our habits, and an over-exertion of willpower is more likely to lead to burnout and relapse back into our old habits. Making a lasting change in our own lives remains one of the hardest problems we are confronted with, in my opinion.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7645377", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I said it was simple. I didn't say it was easy...  ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7642817", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not OP)\nOk, so that makes sense. A endless torrent of fleeting desires doesn't do much, and willing precisely one thing all but guarantees its achievement.\nBut what about a middle ground, where you have two or three consistent and long term goals? Is a person who thinks they can get away with that really stuck closer to the loafer side of the equation, or is there a way to get some real power while still juggling a small-but-plural number of goals?\nSay, to pick an example at random, you're one of the greatest living occultists but also want to find time to write first-rate fiction. Are you dividing your overall potential achievement in half to keep up both goals? Or is it a matter of sublimating a secondary goal into a primary goal so that the secondary goal's achievement is a flower blooming on the tree of the first? (The Weird of Hali seemed pretty magical to me . . . .)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7645633", "title": "Re: Using magic to get rich...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course there's a middle ground. I find it best to maintain a single broad focus and find ways to weave other goals into the overall pattern -- thus making enough money to cover my bills by writing and blogging and astrology is a goal, because that enables me to put more time into occultism than I could if I had to work for somebody else. As for\nThe Weird of Hali\n, that wasn't even really my idea -- the first volume downloaded itself into my imagination over about a week, nearly intact, and I wrote it in a frenzy of typing; the final book set in that world, which I'm writing now, is going very slowly because the rush of energy from the inner planes is almost used up.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7631297", "title": "Vibrating Names", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI was catching up on last week's Magic Monday this morning after reading here and I think I accidentally posted my question to that thread.  My apologies.\nI struggle with vibrating the gods' names in the SOP.  Do you have any suggestions for someone like me who has more of a cartoon character voice than a resonant one?\nMaria", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7634881", "title": "Re: Vibrating Names", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Relax. One of the best ceremonial magicians I know sounds like a blender chopping up ice cubes when he vibrates.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7632321", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've started practicing astrology, and in particular have cast my chart, as well as those of my siblings. We all appear to have our ascendant within less than half a degree of each other, which I found rather interesting. Does this sort of thing happen, or is it likely I've made a mistake here?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7635137", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Doublecheck your work using one of the online astrology sites, such as astro.com. It's entirely possible that that's what happened, though.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7636673", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) I already did! How often do you see such family resemblances in charts?\nb) One of the more striking things about it is that this appears to mean we all have a Uranus-Neptune conjunction conjunct our ascendants: the eldest with both in the 12th, me with Uranus in the 1st and Neptune in the 12th, and the youngest with both in the 1st. How does a planet conjunct the ascendant from the 12th work?\nc) The upcoming Jupiter-Saturn conjunction will be within three degrees of our ascendants as well, and so am I correct to think that this means that 2020 will likely mark a major turning point for all three of us? Exactly how will depend on the charts of course, but does that seem likely to you?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7645889", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't specialized in natal charts, so I'm far from sure how to answer any of these points. If they were mundane ingress charts I'd be better prepared to answer!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7646657", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for admitting you don't know. It's far too rare a thing to see these days...", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7633089", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "Last week I spaced out that Monday was Monday and so forgot to report back to interested parties: Thank you to everyone who had kind thoughts and prayers (and a working ;) ) for my cat who suffered under poor veterinary management and ended up with a second metabolic disorder while being treated for a first... I'm happy to say that he's much improved! He may still have one or both of the issues at a subclinical level (there won't be blood tests for awhile), but from a symptom perspective, he's on the mend and no longer wavering between this world and the next. I see in his expression day after day, \"Gee life is good. I'm glad I get a bit more of it.\" We declined further monitoring/testing/treatment in favor of simply reducing his original medication significantly, changing his diet, and letting him do as he wishes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7635393", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Many thanks for the update. May your cat thrive!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7633345", "title": "Divination and Metaphysics", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Arch Druid,\nI was wondering if you could explain your perspective on the metaphysics driving divination.  To my untrained eye it mostly looks like randomness and self deception, so I would like to know why you think a supernatural worldview explains this better than a more mechanistic one.\nTo give an example of the kind of thing I am talking about, suppose I flip over three cards in a tarot card deck for the past, present, and future, and then reflect on each image the way one doing a reading normally would.  Suppose I get something like an inverted lovers card for my past, the devil for the present, and the fool for the future.  I might conclude from this that I have a past relationship which went terrible wrong, is troubling me in some way during the present, and that I should address this if I don't want to become a fool in the future, although I certainly don't need to be quite so literally all the time.\nI can totally see why a person going through this kind of exercise on a daily basis would make them reflect on suppressed memories and other things lurking in their unconscious. It seems like a healthy practice that could assist the average person in a way similar to going to a therapist could (although the divination method is a lot cheaper and less intrusive then telling a therapist all your secrets).\nBut those who use tarot cards usually describe the experience as interacting with a non physical intelligence.  They talk about it as if there is someone, a non human person, talking to them through the cards.  I can posit the existence of these immaterial beings who communicate with us through an indirect manner, but why not just say this is a placebo affect?  We have used random chance to create a pseudo conversation partner that provokes us to personal reflection, but that does not mean another mind influenced which card we chose, does it?\nIs the reason why you interpret divination the way that you do because of something particular to divination, or is it because of a larger argument coming from your over arching worldview (such as the ones you wrote about in your book on A World Full of Gods?).\nI hope that does not sound like an aggressive question.  I am just trying to wrap my head around the intellectual foundations for magic in general and divination in particular.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7635905", "title": "Re: Divination and Metaphysics", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't concern myself greatly with the philosophical underpinnings of divination, or for that matter of any other aspect of life. I can't prove beyond a shadow of a doubt, after all, that the food I'll be having for dinner shortly actually exists! (Like most occultists, btw, I don't hold that supernatural realities exist -- I simply hold that nature seems to be  considerably more expansive and interesting than a narrow mechanistic view would permit.) Since a mechanistic worldview is just as arbitrary and faith-based as any other, I use whatever set of terms will communicate best to my audience; my most recent book on divination,\nThe Coelbren Alphabet\n, includes a game-theory explanation of divination as one of three alternatives, none of which I present as the sole truth. Since what matters is that practicing divination has useful outcomes, I let people believe whatever mythologies they prefer -- mechanistic, theistic, animistic, you name it -- and simply focus on the practices.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7633601", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI'm curious how your subjective experience of magic compares with that of a novice. Phenomenologically speaking, after so many years of practice, is there anything that occurs in your consciousness which confirms beyond a shadow of a doubt that you are engaged in something more than make-believe, which would not occur to a novice, or would not occur to a younger, less experienced version of yourself? I assume that the novice's practice is more \"faith-based\" than the initiate's, in that he has to develop his subtle faculties over a long period of time before anything truly impressive can happen, just as a musician has to put in long hours of practice before he can play a piece of music half-decently. But let's say that a novice could suddenly gain access to your state of consciousness in the middle of some ritual or practice: would anything seem immediately different or striking from his own consciousness?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7636161", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a question I have no way of answering. I have Aspergers syndrome, and so my experience of the world (as far as I can tell from reading and conversation) differs sharply from that of most people anyway, and any attempt I might make to put myself into the mindset of my own novice years suffers from all the usual difficulties with subjective memory. I also dropped out of the consensus about reality of the Western cultural mainstream in my teen years, when I first took up magic, and what (for example) you would or would not consider proof that magic is \"something more than make-believe\" is not something I know much about -- nor, to be frank, is it something that interests me greatly. If other people want to disbelieve in magic, that's hardly a concern of mine -- in fact, it makes some aspects of my work much easler.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7637953", "title": "Any Update on Shipping of Sacred Geometry Oracle?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI wondered if you had any update for shipping the SacredGeometry Oracle.  I thought it was coming out early this year.\nThanks,\nCandace", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7646145", "title": "Re: Any Update on Shipping of Sacred Geometry Oracle?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There have been some delays due to the complexities of getting cards as well as a book. I'll make an announcement when I have a firm shipping date.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7638209", "title": "On the personhood of an unborn baby", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am pro-choice on the topic of abortion, due to the fact that I do not consider an embryo to be a person for the same reason that I do not consider an acorn to be an oak. I would think that the process of the pregnancy itself is what gives that being its personhood, in the same way that the sowing and germination of an acorn is the process of giving it \"oakhood\" so early enough, an abortion is not a murder.\nIs there an occult consensus on this? What do different canons say?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7646913", "title": "Re: On the personhood of an unborn baby", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Different writers have different positions on this. One very common take is that the soul enters the unborn body at the time of quickening -- the point at which the baby can be felt moving by the mother. (That was the legal definition of when life began in many countries until fairly recently.) But occultists tend to have varying opinions about most things, and this is one of them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7638721", "title": "A question about music", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the Brecken Kendall novels, you treated us to a discussion of what things in the music we know had certain effects on the human mind. I was wondering where Asian music fits into this pattern? I have often found it wandering and pointless, or simply tinkle-tinkle-tinkle. Some Middle Eastern music has the same effect. It may be due to the pentatonic scale; it took me some time to get into The Blues because of unfamiliarity with their musical conventions. Or to note that, here in the states, the Indian pow-wow rhythms took a while to discover and appreciate.\nPat, hoping to expand her appreciation of other music", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7647169", "title": "Re: A question about music", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Musical styles are languages. Tonal music -- the classical music of the west, which relies on tonality rather than other organizing principles -- makes sense to anyone raised in a Western culture, not least because all our children's songs rely on it. (cf. the discussion of \"Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star\" in\nThe Shoggoth Concerto\n.) Other musical cultures are different languages, and you have to learn to understand them if you don't grow up with them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7647681", "title": "Re: A question about music", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but this raises a question for me then: I find traditional Japanese music inherently appealing and it makes a great deal of sense to me, as if I speak the language. I have no ties to that culture, so what sort of factors could lead someone to have such intuitive grasps of a foreign musical language?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7649473", "title": "Re: A question about music", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may have had a recent past life in Japan.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7638977", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I did something very basic last night, which seems to have radically shifted my consciousness in ways I wasn't expecting, and if today is anything to go by, may very well have defused quite a few of my bad habits. I bought a weekly planner, and filled it out for the week ahead.\nI found that today I was vastly more productive (doesn't surprise me), but that it also partially defused my habit of getting distracted with the internet, which I was surprised about. It seems part of what was driving it was uncertainty as to what to do with my time; and so I gravitated towards the habit of least resistance.\nThis strikes me as an example of a \"change in consciousness in accordance with will\", so I'm wondering: did I unwittingly perform magic here? If so, how do I keep it going? Is it as simple as just continuing to make and keep plans?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7647425", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We all practice magic, all the time. Mages do it deliberately, to further the goals they choose; everyone else does it unthinkingly, to further goals chosen by their subconscious motivations. As for what to do now, why, you've got a talisman and a ritual that works with it -- keep working with those and see what happens.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7640001", "title": "Waking/Sleeping Visions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nRecently (within the last couple of months) I have had a few visions upon going to sleep or waking up.  These are not dreams and I am awake, able to open my eyes and then close them again where upon the vision is still there.  They are inside the blackness of my closed eyes, they appear like dimly lit black and grey pictures but they have much more reality than when I imagine something.  If I imagine something I guess I see it as nothing, an image made of nothing that I am able to see, but these are much clearer and have a reality to them, also I am not controlling them, I am receiving them.\nThey don't seem to be memories, the appear more symbolic, but as if someone had created a scene with the intention of being viewed, however their framing strikes me as somewhat old fashioned, like something out of an old painting rather than to modern sensibilities.  By that I mean there is much negative space framing them, the image sits in the middle of this framing darkness.\nThe first time I experienced this it was a night I went to bed earlier (I was at my in-laws) and upon closing my eyes I started to get a weird sense of scrambled lighting that became more focused and I realized it was a bombardment of images (perhaps close to 10 per second) that had this rich clarity but I could not process them properly.  I felt overloaded but I also could not understand what I was seeing.  I was totally sober and opened my eyes several times only to have them recommence upon closing them again.\nThese images are not scary to me, there isn't an emotional content to them at all and I do not think they seem like dreams (it is hard to say for me since I am asleep, but my sense in dreams is that they are an impression of seeing things without actually seeing things - different from my imagination although I can typically change them, at the very least I act in them).  These pictures anyway have the quality of looking at something real in that I can't just choose what I see or don't see, my mind is reacting to something fixed.  My sense is that I am being shown something, possibly, either by a part of myself I do not normally have access to or by something outside myself.\nI have had four of these visions now, the subsequent ones are slower and I've been able to write down what I saw afterwards and to think about them.  I wondered if you knew of anything like this or had any advice.\nI googled it and learned there is a type of hallucination that these seem to correspond to, but really that didn't tell me anything useful, it just seemed like a \"nothing to see here\" dismissal and my instinct was that these had meaning since everything about them struck me that way.\nThanks,\nJohnny", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7647937", "title": "Re: Waking/Sleeping Visions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "These are called hypnagogic and hypnopompic imagery, and they're traditionally governed by the god Mercury. The occult explanation is that you're getting a glimpse of part of the astral plane. Yes, it's real, and yes, it's meaningful; pay attention to it and see what it has to teach you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7640257", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!\nI'm finding myself drawn to learning some form of cartomancy that uses a standard deck of playing cards, rather than tarot or the like. (Though of course I'm aware tarot began life as a deck of playing cards!) Do you have any recommendations on where to start?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7648193", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not something I've explored, but I know a lot of people get good results from it. Give it a try and see where it takes you!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7641537", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nDo you know why Aleister Crowley nicknamed his son as \"Aleister Atatürk\"? It baffles me as a Turkish citizen. As far as I know, Crowley and Atatürk have nothing in common.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7648449", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I have no idea at all. Crowley was an odd duck and did odd things -- he may have been stoned on drugs when he decided to do that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7649729", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hahahaha :)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7642049", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My knowledge of astrology is limited to what can be gathered from the ingress charts you've posted to the Well of Galabes and Ecosophia, but now that I've started meditating, my mind has started using various astrological themes to make sense of what I'm looking at. In particular, I took notice when I realized I had explored something from a Uranian perspective, and then I began to explore it from a Neptunian perspective.\nThis has happened twice (both times I saw I had adopted a Uranian answer, and set out to explore another option, which suggests to me I have a strong Uranus-Mercury link)\nI've started looking into basic texts, but I have two questions:\na) What sort of factors could lead my mind to settle into astrological symbolism? This seems especially odd as I've not given it too much thought. Is this a potential theme for meditation?\nb) I have no idea what time I was born. Do you have advice on how to proceed if I want to start using astrology for myself?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7649217", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "a) Astrological symbolism is very deeply rooted in our culture -- we talk about people having jovial or saturnine personalities, and so on. It's a very accessible symbolism for most people. If it works for you, pursue it -- and yes, meditating on that might be helpful.\nb) If you can afford to consult with a good professional astrologer, they can do what's called a chart rectification, and figure out your approximate birth time based on when important events happened in your later life. Otherwise, you can still study most if not all of your planetary placements.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7649985", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "b) How hard would it be to learn how to rectify a chart myself?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7651265", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Plan on first learning natal astrology inside and out, and then learning how to do progressed charts. You figure out the rough time of birth in rectification by paying attention to the planets that move quickly, especially the Moon, and watching for aspects that come and go; once you've gotten that, you find important events in the person's early life and then find the birth time from which a progressed chart would predict that event in the right year. It's not easy, but some people are very good at it.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7642305", "title": "geomantic query", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nCan you confirm my sense of this geomantic chart? And perhaps point to any hidden advice it might be giving, that I haven't seen?\nThe question is: What are my prospects of seeing [new romantic interest, whom I just met] within the next two weeks?\nMy initial thought is that this should be a 7th house question.\nThe chart was:\n1. Fortuna Minor\n2. Puella\n3. Caput\n4. Fortuna Major\n5. Fortuna Minor\n6. Amissio\n7. Caput\n8. Caput\n9. Caput\n10. Rubeus\n11. Conjunctio\n12. Populus\nRW. Fortuna Major\nLW. Conjunctio\nJ. Acquisitio\nS. Carcer\nThe only modes of perfection between the 1st and 7th are a trio of aspects:\n1st passes to 5th for a dexter sextile\n7th passes to 3rd for a sinister sextile\n7th passes to 9th, for a dexter trine\n(7th also passes to 8th, but forms no aspect.)\nI read this as, the two parties are dancing around each other but the thing won't actually happen within the time period specified. The aspects alone are pleasant, but insufficient to guarantee the desired result.\nSo my questions are:\n(1) Is there anything in this particular chart that I missed, or that you would read differently?\n(2) More generally, what do you make of a situation with lots of aspects but no other perfection?\n(3) It occurred to me that insofar as there's no serious relationship, the 5th might also be implicated in terms of flash-in-the-pan romance, casual dating, socializing, going out for dinner. Since that wasn't the house I had in mind prior to casting the chart, I'm inclined to disregard it (despite the fact that the chart would then perfect by occupation!). In what kinds of questions would the 5th be relevant, as distinct from the 7th?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7650241", "title": "Re: geomantic query", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, that's basically how I would read it. Since there's no mode of perfection, the answer is \"no.\" Mind you, more than two weeks from now might be a different story.\n2) I treat it as a \"no, but...\"\n3) I'd take the 5th house involvement as a reference to the fact that you're attracted to the person.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7643073", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for another Magic Monday.\nI have two things I'd like to ask about the first being in regards to communicating with higher beings. I've been meditating on things a lot lately and one thing that had always had me curious is how you know if you had been given a message so to speak.\nDuring one night of meditation I had something pop into my mind when thinking about gods, or at least in the framework how Americans view a deity and as if out of nowhere the thought, \"People worry too much about the word god,\" which I intuited being that people worry to much about the word and what it brings to mind, or whatever they're told it means, instead of actually trying to know or experience it for themselves. What struck me was for whatever the idea is worth, it shot across my mind with a clarity as sudden as flipping on a light switch, which as I type that it brings to mind cartoons and light bulbs over the head, but I digress. Would that be an example of something 'higher' for lack of better way to put it, giving me a lead, or would you say it was just something my mind took as very novel?\nThe second question has to do with \"How To Be A Mage,\" I just got it Friday and I've had to force myself to put it down so I could digest the ideas. That said, given how you describe it as being stylized to provoke, in your opinion would it indicate that I'm missing some points if having read through over half of it I found it to make far more sense with a small objection about the Catholic bend? That part in itself only bothers me when set against the modern church since I myself was catholic until my parents divorced and they stopped taking me to church. I myself just mark it as being that I'm a young man in my twenties who feels like society has no real place for young men of my \"class.\"\nAlso do you have any musings on what Peladan would thing of the current Catholic Church with what you know of it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7650497", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Whether that was a higher being or your own higher self is a question I can't answer, but that's the way many people experience communications from the higher planes.\n2) I also thought it made enormous sense, but I could see what Peladan was trying to do. If it works for you, read it repeatedly and see how many of its suggestions you can apply to your own life.\n3) I think he'd be horrified by the dumbing-down of the ritual and the uglification of the churches. He was very much a traditionalist.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7643585", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nAre the following mythical elements related to one another?\n1 - Water and wine in the Biblical story of \"Mariage at Cana\".\n2 - Red and white springs in Glastonbury.\n3 - Red and white dragons in Merlin legends.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7650753", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a fine theme for meditation!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7646401", "title": "mercury retrograde", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Perhaps more of a comment than question, but isn't it curious that the Dems used this latest retrograde to push forward their least articulate candidate, who not only seems to be showing signs of cognitive / speech impairment, but also has a history of actual plagiarism?\nNext comes the convention..", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7651009", "title": "Re: mercury retrograde", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's as though they're deliberately making every possible magical mistake. Eerie.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7651521", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "Oh, I almost forgot! The Nyogtha Variations was VERY satisfying. :D", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7653825", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you! Both the Brecken & Sho stories were kind of a gamble for me, pushing my writing into unfamiliar territory, and I'm glad they worked.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7651777", "title": "SOP as a defense mechanism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and fellow students,\nIt only happens every few months now, but last night I was awakened in some pain from a psychic visit from Cousin Tony.  Tony, a retired Cop, likes to hurt people when he has sex with them.\nI woke up in some pain.  I was not frightened and I started to do the circulation of light from the Sphere of Protection.  The pain lessened and I fell asleep.  It started again almost instantly. Again, I whirled the lights and he desisted.  I suspect he may not have had such a good experience as he would have liked.\nWould you advise using the Circulation of Light as a defense like this?  It seemed to work pretty good the last few times I tried it.\nMaxine Rogers", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7654081", "title": "Re: SOP as a defense mechanism", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sorry to hear your astral pest is back. Yes, the SoP ought to help.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7652033", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Late question today, but something has been on my mind lately and I couldn't wait until next week to put it to the venerable Archdruid. It seems that most occultists, even the most advanced, don't practice for more than 30 minutes to an hour a day. Outside of this practice time, they mostly do what everyone else is doing: commuting, working, sleeping, etc. I think you would be hard-pressed to identify an occult practitioner in a crowd on the street. In my opinion, it's hard to practice for 30 minutes a day and think about it as anything more than a hobby, or something that one occasionally dabbles in, and certainly not as a serious calling or philosophy of life.\nChristian monks have a concept of continuous prayer, and in Buddhism, there is this idea that enlightenment is just like normal life, only about 2 inches off the ground. Which brings me to the question: How does one lead the \"occult lifestyle\"? Is there something we could be doing 24/7, some way we should be thinking, some attitude we should adopt, to be fully \"in the know\"? Could this even be a dangerous thing to want?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7654337", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To begin with, occult practice is\nintense\n. It brings through a lot of energy in a hurry and causes sudden shifts of consciousness that can be very disorienting. That's why 30 minutes to an hour a day of practice is a good maximum: more than that and you risk mental instability. Devoting the other 23 hours a day to ordinary well-grounded activities helps keep you balanced.\nSecond, remember that monks can afford to spend all day praying or meditating -- they've got big well-funded institutions to cover their bills. Occultists don't. We have to earn a living like everyone else, and that means that we can't spend 24 hours a day in states of awareness that would interfere with earning a living.\nFinally, there's a reason you can't identify an occultist in a crowd. For how many centuries did occultists have to worry about being burned at the stake, or killed by a mob, or losing their jobs and being confined to an asylum, if word got out that they were occultists?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7652801", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nSome chapters in The Secret Tradition in Arthurian Legend mention \"Atlantean royal bloodline\" that is said to survived in Celtic countries. When we think about the foundation myth of Merovingian Dynasty - where there is a sea monster \"Quinotaur\" associated with god Neptune, it also seems to be influenced by Atlantean myths.\n1 - What is the occult significance of these kinds of myths?\n2 - Do they concern ordinary people like me who has nothing to do with any royal bloodline or those of us who are not of Celtic origin?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7654593", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) They make great themes for meditation.\n2) Well, do you have a theme for your daily meditation tomorrow?\n;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7656129", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, during the next meditation session, I will try not to think about the direct literal implications (monarchism, racialism etc.) of these legends :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7656641", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Au contraire, you should explore those fully, and not just as bogeymen. Why are those implications there? What might they be trying to teach, other than in a simplistic political sense? Are there hereditary psychic gifts, and if so, what does that imply? And so on.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7657409", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Even if there is a grain of truth in hereditary psychic gifts, it wasn't strong enough to save King Arthur from the doom that he had created; or similarly, not strong enough to save French monarchy from the wrath of its own people!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7653057", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You have a section in your Magic Monday FAQ about the possibility of people having been animals in a past life. This dragged up a memory about a subculture that gained some popularity some years ago called \"Therianthropy.\" In short, Therianthropy was a subset of the larger \"otherkin\" subculture for people who (in some sense or another) spiritually identified as being a non-human animal. While I don't doubt for a second that these movements were/are largely populated by people wanting a reason to feel special, I wonder if this phenomenon could be explained by this being their first human incarnation, and resulting in some adjustment issues. In your opinion, could that be a reasonable explanation for these sorts of beliefs/behaviors?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7654849", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's entirely possible that some of the people in question remembered fragments of an animal life, but the vast majority of those I encountered seemed to be guided by entirely human motives. A desire to feel special was part of it, but there was also a very widespread sense that they did not want to be what they had been taught they were by their society, and fantasizing about being an animal was a way to express that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7653569", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nThanks for taking the time to answer these questions. Hope this one squeezes in before the deadline!\nI did a house chart today to see if I will be offered a freelancing position from some friends I know who have a company and who I have reached out to for that kind of work.\nI got the following:\n1: Populus\n2: Acquisitio\n3: Puer\n4: Rubeus\n5: Albus\n6: Caput Draconis\n7: Populus\n8: Conjunctio\n9: Acquisitio\n10: Carcer\n11: Acquisitio\n12: Conjunctio\nRW: Fortuna Minor\nLW: Fortuna Major\nJ: Via\nI considered the house of the quesited to be the 10th (Carcer). This perfects with translation on both sides with Acquisitio in the 11th and 9th, translating to the 2nd house. This seems to be a fairly positive reading, as Acquisitio would represent gain, especially in the 2nd house representing money. The figure also appears in the 11th (my friends, who own the company), and the 9th, which I assume would mean I will gain some type of deeper knowledge through this work.\nOne concern I have is about Carcer in the 10th, which is not usually a good figure. I am alone at home a lot and considering this is freelance work, it could be pointing to a continued situation where I work from home and don't interact as much with others as I'd like. Or it could mean stability...\nAlso, there is a square aspect between Populus in the 6th and the house of the quesited. Could this mean that my personal relationship will suffer if I take the job?\nOverall I'm inclined to read this as positive, but would like your take on it. Des my interpretation sound pretty valid?\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7655361", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, this is quite a positive reading.\n2) I'd take this as suggesting that this particular job won't really go anywhere.\n3) No, 6th house is the house of health and also of service industries. It may mean that you'll get ill as a result of it, or that there are many other people competing for jobs of this kind.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7657153", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sorry, meant 7th, but no need to answer, as the post is already closed. Thanks for the response!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7655105", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG- I had a quick question about the practices of solar and lunar etheric charging described in “Paths of Wisdom”.  In the book, you mention that these should be done before 10am and 10pm respectively, but I thought I recalled you writing a comment here that, at least as far as solar charging goes, the purpose behind this is to make sure it’s done before the sun reaches its zenith. Is the principal the same for lunar etheric charging (done on a clear night , standing in the moonlight of a waxing moon, before the moon has reached its zenith)? I found myself wondering the week before last, since during the first few nights after the new moon the moon was visible but on its way towards setting well before 10pm. Or have I misunderstood, and the time is important for other reasons?\nAlso, I was a bit surprised to find two portions of the middle pillar ritual as described in LRM (the visualized descending white light from the heavens and the ascending green light from the center of the earth) missing from the description in “Paths of Wisdom”. I’ve been continuing to practice the version from LRM, just a bit curious as to the reasons for the discrepancy and, since I believe LRM was the later book, how you came upon the expanded version.\nThanks much!\nNPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7655617", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You want the solar and lunar energies when the luminaries are actively rising, not \"up there\" above you.\n2) No two descriptions of the Middle Pillar exercise in my books are the same. That's partly to frustrate fundamentalists and people who obsess about nitpicky details, and partly because I've experimented with a lit of different variations over the years. You can practice either version.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7655873", "title": "A very particular geomantic chart.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wanted to ask the oracle if it was a good idea to move to a new apartment in the summer, and I got the mothers Amissio, Fortuna Maj, Via, and Conjunctio. These, in turn, give themselves as daughters, and all these give carcer as nieces, and Populus as witnesses and judge. Your book says that conjuctio in the fourth is neither favorable nor unfavorable.\nIs this the oracle telling me to please ask again later? I was pretty baffled by the chart.\nJP", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7656897", "title": "Re: A very particular geomantic chart.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, what it's saying is that it doesn't matter -- it's six of one and half a dozen of the other.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/81997.html", "year": "2020", "month": "03", "day": "16", "time": "12-03AM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt7715149", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I’m currently working my way through the AODA first degree, with the goal of joining the GCC and eventually becoming a bishop. (I find it interesting there seem to be a few people doing it! I hope it’s a good sign for the future of the order) I’ve decided to try to get as far as possible with it now, and so I decided to look at what requirements of the later degrees can be knocked out now, and start on them. So, for example, I’m putting a lot more than the minimum time into my bardic exploration, so as to be able to use it a few years down the road for the third degree project.\nI’m now wondering how this relates to the “will only one thing” you discussed last week. While I suspect I could get a few good meditations out of it, here’s what I’m currently thinking: my will is focused on “Become a bishop in the GCC”, and the steps getting me there are in a way less important than the goal. For example, I’m meditating to bring that future into existence, not for the sake of meditation itself.\nCurrently my will is focused on bringing that future into manifestation, and so that requires certain concrete steps, but I’m taking them with the big picture goal in mind. This implies there’s at least two types of will: will to do, and will to bring forth; an active and a visionary form. If you lack the active form, you end up with provisional living, and if you lack the visionary, you end up drifting through life, always doing something, but never accomplishing anything.\nDo you think this analysis makes sense? Is there anything you’d add to it?\n2. For the AODA earth path, I’ve decided to make two super simple changes so as to spare more energy for the third one. I have a very unhealthy relationship with the internet, and want to change that. I suspect part of it is that I have no idea what life was like prior to the existence of the internet, since I’ve had home internet for literally my entire life.\nI’ve since realized that my goal is a negative one: cutting internet, and so it reinforces the appeal of the thing. I reframed it as “going analog”, which has helped a great deal, but I’m still unable to craft a simple, clear, and coherent positive goal.\na) Am I correct to think that positive goals are much better than negative ones?\nb) Do you have advice on how to craft such goals?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7716429", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's entirely appropriate to have one primary focus of will, and have other secondary purposes unfold from that. Someone who wants to become filthy rich, for example, will have a long series of secondary goals subordinate to that desire: cutting useless expenditures, getting a job with a higher salary, excelling at that job, being promoted, etc., etc. You're pursuing a saner goal, but the principle is the same: the goal of walking to a distant place is broken up into individual footsteps, each of which has to be taken in turn. Your differentiation between active and visionary will is sometimes seen as the distinction between will and imagination; one way or another, though, it's valid.\n2a) Yee.\n2b) Focus on what you want to draw to you. Why are you cutting your internet use? What will you do with the time you free up? What benefits do you expect to gain? Make those the center of your intent.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7735629", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Do you know good sources which discuss will and imagination?\n2b) This raises three questions for me:\ni) I have no idea what life was like before the internet: I've had access to it at home since the day I was born. I'm not sure what life without it, or even just in a sane relationship with it, will look like. What I know is I don't like how much I use it.\nIn this case, am I correct to think it makes sense to focus on one aspect of it at a time, while I figure out what my positive goal overall is? For example, starting out with the goal of getting better sleep by not using the internet right before bed?\nii) Am I correct to think journaling could be useful for figuring out what positive the goal I aim for should be?\niii) Do you think the fact that contemporary American culture is flooded with negative goals (\"Don't eat this; don't smoke; stop drinking; etc) is part of why so many people flounder about, unable to achieve much of anything?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7738957", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I wish I did. Most books on ceremonial magic reference the two, but I don't know of a good detailed book on them and their interaction.\n2) Yes, yes, and emphatically yes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7762509", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Doesn't the will/imagination distinction look like a binary? How do you resolve it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7769933", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a great theme for your meditations!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7715405", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any idea what the ever living frack is going on with the over the top reaction to the coronavirus?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7717453", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are several things involved. First, the corporate media is desperate for clickbait -- a lot of mainstream media outlets, CNN and MSNBC among them, have suffered disastrous declines in viewership over the last few years and they're facing a serious loss of ad revenue, and whipping up a panic is one way to improve their stats. Second, the Boomer generation has become increasingly frantic about the approaching statistical end of its time on this planet, and this epidemic -- which is primarily lethal to the elderly -- has suddenly brought home to them the hard reality that no amount of botox will keep the Reaper at bay; thus a lot of them are coming loudly unglued. Third, we've got a very high level of social stress just now, with the cage match between the establishment gerontocracy and the populist insurgency rising toward its peak, and people are jittery -- thus anything shocking will tend to make them wig out. Combine those three factors with the ordinary human response to a pandemic and I think that pretty much accounts for it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7724621", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the OP). Hm, that would go some way to explaining the phenomenon, but not totally. Basically, governments and the media have decided that this virus is bad enough that they need to collectively shoot themselves in the foot by tanking their economies to prevent the spread of it. If the virus isn't that bad, then why would they inflict such economic damage to themselves?\nOK, I take your point that death is a pretty good motivator, but I wonder if people everywhere are so fearful because they know deep down how fragile the food and health-care systems are - that hospitals don't have the resources or space to cope with a sudden influx of patients, for example, as already seen in northern Italy.\nAlso: equally as many people are worried about the economic fallout, so there's a feedback loop between anxiety at falling stock markets and anxiety at the spread of the virus (see the price of Bitcoin? So much for cryptocurrencies being a safe haven, which is why I've stayed far away from them).\nLastly, I think that wealthier and middle class people in the West have had no experience of real hardship for the most part, and suddenly everything they've seen in Hollywood movies such as Contagion and Outbreak are coming to pass, and they're going bonkers.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7739981", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Governments aren't shooting themselves in the foot -- they're taking advantage of an exogenous crisis to deflate some dangerously overinflated markets. Had the markets just kept on zooming upwards until the bubbles popped, a lot of national leaders would have been blamed for the consequences -- and in particular, that could have messed over Trump's chances at reelection. Instead, the virus will be blamed for the crash, and once the outbreak is over -- a matter of a couple of months, to judge from China and Korea -- markets will pop back up again and, memories being short, all will be well.\nBut you're right, of course, that people have watched way too many pandemic-apocalypse movies -- and that too many of them have no experience of actual hardship, much less something that could, you know, actually kill them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7725389", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To add to my earlier comments, here's a half-formed thought: the other thing potentially at work is perhaps that wealthier and middle class people realize somewhere that their lifestyle has helped spread the coronavirus - it's basically been spread by air travel. In the same way that a good horror movie evokes fear by twisting some aspect of culture to expose something dark in it, the spread of this virus evokes fear because it's showing that air travellers are helping to spread it. The virus has taken something our culture celebrates, the freedom of air travel, and turned it into something to fear.\nAlso, and this might be pushing it, the current conflict between globalists and localists is at play here too. Those wealthy and middle class air travellers who don't support Trump and his protectionist policies (and that's a lot of them) are suddenly confronted with a virus which is shutting down borders. I can't put my finger on it all yet, though...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7740237", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those are both excellent points.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7733325", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may, could I ask how you think this coronavirus situation is going to play out in the months ahead, both in terms of the virus itself, and the economic and political consequences?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7737677", "title": "A thorough discussion re: COVID-19, CWD, etc.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is Joe Rogan interviewing Michael Osterholm on a wide range of infectious disease topics, starting with Coronavirus, of course, but also Lyme Disease, Chronic Wasting Disease, etc.  You can get at least 90% of the program just from the audio, so give it a listen.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E3URhJx0NSw\nJust now, he's explained that Native Americans traditionally burned over northern forests, which helped reduce mice and ticks, but with fire suppression, deer are carrying ticks into moose habitat, and the ticks are killing the moose (both by disease transmission and simply blood loss).  It's great thread of systems thinking.\nA noteworthy comment on hand-washing (from the program above): it doesn't hurt, but most COVID-19 transmission is airborne. But you can DO hand-washing, and you can't stop breathing (or get a respirator).\nLathechuck", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7740493", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a suitable subject for post over on my main blog, not a brief comment here -- and we're getting kind of far from the point of Magic Monday, which is to talk about occultism. So I'll pass for now, until I have a chance to post something at length.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7739213", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "BTW, I've had several people try to respond to this by posting wildly overblown claims about the CoVID-19 outbreak, with links to a variety of doombat websites. That sort of thing is harmless entertainment most of the time, but in the midst of a crisis when people are already under too much stress, it's not harmless at all. It seems to me that one of the requirements of good citizenship is not to spread panic -- or, in my case, to allow my online forums to be used for that purpose.\nI'm pretty sure, by the way, that at least some of the rumor-mongering is deliberate and organized -- my guess is that various people want to drive stock markets down further so that they can buy stocks at fire-sale prices and make a bundle when the outbreak is over and stocks pop back up again, as of course they will. \"Do not feed the profiteers\" might be a good sign to hang up on the internet just now...", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7784781", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Shouldn't the Boomers have already started dealing with it? What drives this terror of death?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7787085", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Keep in mind that most people in my generation have been pretending to themselves since their teen years that they are the most important generation in history, the ones that were going to change the world once and for all, blah blah blah -- and now they're at the end of their rope and all the gaudy dreams of their youth have guttered out. Most of my fellow Boomers sold out, not just once but over and over again, and now the Grim Reaper is whistling a cheery tune as he sharpens his scythe and they can no longer pretend that they still have time to live up to their long-abandoned ideals. Of course they're frantically running for as much toilet paper as they can get; I'll leave it to you to guess why.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7734349", "title": "Iron irony", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "We could be looking at:\n1) Return of the repressed from youthful rebellion days. A throwback to the unquestioning obedience of authority which brought us a) WWI & WWII (right), and b) the fervour of the Internationale (left)\n2) A last-chance grasping for Holy Unification that  replicates the Feeling (but not the substance) of:\na) One Nation Under God;\nb) One Generation of StarDust in pursuit of Common Goals\n3) War is being sighted on the horizon of the West via the high-tech super-duper laser scopes made by reputable weapons manufacturers. War: coming soon to a venue near you!! Bound to be hailed as a savior who rescues the failed economy, gives the peasants an uplifting Noble Lie that motivates them to eat synthetic margarine instead of butter; accept meat rationing as a fact of life; surrender civil liberties left, right, and anticlockwise; continue to\nsupport the rich in the beurre-steak-and-ale style they are accustomed to. And to obey Daylight Savings time for God alone knows what reason. Something somebody said about the state of Denmark. Hmm, now, what was it....?\n4) Gearing the entire medical services industry towards enriching insurance company CEOs instead of protecting the general health and well-being of the nation now comes back to bite everybody in the place where they put their wallet. But, but....it seemed like such a good idea at the time!\nIf the Age of Aquarius (ca 1879) is about individuals deviating from the herd response and the Land of Liberty hosts a tamanous orientation, then why is it so still easy to align people like iron filings on paper held over a magnet with just a few strokes of brass-faced media nibs dipped in money-ink? Because peoples as a whole never learn from the past but only from personal experience? Whom the gods would destroy they first make meek?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7740749", "title": "Re: Iron irony", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No lack of irony in today's diet! With regard to the age of Aquarius, though, remember that it takes some centuries for the transition between ages to complete. Plenty of people were still following the habits of the Arian Age long after the Piscean Age had dawned.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7766093", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My guess is the cognitive dissonance of the \"Orange man bad\" club now criticizing him for not taking actions, when the actions which would work would be border control....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7770445", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good point. Yeah, that's got to have some brains tied in square knots.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7773773", "title": "The mystery of the disappearing toilet paper", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "If I may insert my observation here. Along with COVID-19 the United States seems to suffering from an epidemic of a new and strange virus. One that forces people to hoard toiled paper. Down in the South where I live there's still plenty of food on the shelves of supermarkets, despite the panic buying but all the toilet paper and paper towels are gone. This behavior is irrational, nobody NEEDS toilet paper to survive a pandemic, so I say its a new virus.\nAlso an interesting observation: Dollar General stores seem to be well stocked on toilet paper so the virus seems to affect the more wealthier parts of the population. If you're making 70K or more a year you're in the risk group!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7777357", "title": "Re: The mystery of the disappearing toilet paper", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Family Dollar store a block from my apartment also seems to be well stocked. Given the apparent origin of the virus, is it possible that people have just gone batsh** crazy?\n;-)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7715661", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm potentially interested in doing the work with the Druidical Order of the Golden Dawn, but find the communion ceremony from the GCC very rewarding, and I'm not willing to give it up. Would it be safe to practice the DOGD material, and also continue to practice the communion ceremony?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7716685", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't generally recommend working with the two systems at the same time -- they work with different energies in different ways, so you're more or less trying to walk and swim at the same time! Have you considered the system included in\nThe Druid Magic Handbook\nor the one in\nThe Dolmen Arch\n? Both of those are entirely compatible with the GCC work.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7715917", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No question at the moment. Just thought you might find it amusing that I know a guy who refers to Trump as the Orange Demon. This is the first time I've seen a member of The Church of Progress be so on the nose.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7716941", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's funny, in a sad sort of way. I bet in any other context he'd insist that demons don't exist.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7721805", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Indeed. He's as materialist as they come. Interestingly enough he's married to a woman of the Baha'i faith though.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7717197", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Hallo JMG and others,\nI have a question about ritual clothing. Do you use ritual clothing during magical ceremonies and if so, which kinds of ritual clothing? I myself do magic mostly in ordinary clothing, since some other clothings which I tried are somewhat cumbersome; nowadays it is not as easy to find good fitting clothes as it once was.\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7717965", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I use a plain white robe with a cord belt for major rituals, and ordinary clothes for daily practices -- my morning Sphere of Protection, meditation, and divination are done in pajamas, slippers, and a bathrobe.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7722829", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does it matter what kind of fabric you make it of?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7741005", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. I normally use cotton, for what it's worth.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7753037", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I ever get into ceremonial magic, I will test the power of fuzzy bunny slippers and report back.  😄", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7753805", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The first time I ever saw Dolores Ashcroft-Nowicki in a ritual setting, she looked like everyone's favorite batty grandmama, a plump little woman in a black robe with a long silver braid down her back, round rimless glasses, and blue plush slippers with a little bow on each. It was absolutely priceless. Then she pattered out to the altar at the center of the space, raised her hands, and the wave of power she let loose practically blew the windows out.\nSo mystic bunny slippers are not outside the bounds of possibility...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7759693", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It would also be a good name for a band.\nI had not heard of Dolores; is she another writer in the field?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7760461", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes -- she's the head of the Servants of the Light, a magical order in Dion Fortune's lineage, and the author of many books on magic. Here's a good picture:", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7775821", "title": "Yes!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "She looks like she's at home in her own skin. So does my Asatruar go-to writer, Diana Paxson. It's a rare author I can say that of; you, of course.\nPat", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7758925", "title": "Magic and fuzzy bunny slippers", "user": "slclaire", "content": "I can report that my seriously fuzzy slippers are fully compatible with AODA's magic practice! They have been tested on a near everyday basis during each of the past three winters.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7775565", "title": "Me, too!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Pajamas, sock hose, and a ratty house jacket I've had forever. Hands and face washed, but hair not combed. Ritual? The old black cotton robe I made decades ago, no hood, and the two upholstery-department cords. Haven't done a major ritual since I got here.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7779917", "title": "Re: Me, too!", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Well, currently I often use pajamas, sometimes street clothes, depending on time of day.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7742029", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I use ordinary clothing but try to modify it a touch--long shirt/sweater in the winter, topless in the summer--because otherwise drawing the line upward during the final Circle of Protection step gets my fingers tangled up with the hem of my shirt. :P I take off my glasses, likewise, because they're kind of an obstruction in the first part afterwards, and I've been doing it barefoot--though after seeing JMG's post about wearing slippers, I will joyfully start doing same on chilly mornings!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7717709", "title": "Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Hi JMG and Magic Monday Readers,\nI uploaded a new Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite that you can download for free.  Free sheet music & lyric video are still in the works.\nhttps://queeniemusic.bandcamp.com/track/orphic-hymn-to-aphrodite\nI was also recently honored to have my song Sister Moon featured on the OBOD Podcast, Episode 155:\nhttps://www.druidry.org/druid-way/resources/druidcast-obod-podcast\nAll my best to everyone.  It's getting ugly around here because of Coronavirus.  The schools in Illinois closed at end of day Friday for the next three weeks.  Today, our governor closed every restaurant and bar for the same period.  I've made the decision to close my studio for the same period in response to public pressure.  I don't really feel I have a choice.  I ask for your prayers on my behalf that I am able to land on my feet from all of this.  I am the breadwinner for my household.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7718221", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Congratulations on both of these. I wonder -- is there any way you could livestream a performance or two and ask people to tip you via some online method? A lot of people are going to be very bored over the next few weeks, as they hole up in their homes to keep the virus at bay, and live music -- even over the internet -- might be very welcome to a lot of them.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7718733", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kimberly,\nYes, a lot of people are in your predicament.  I will pray for everyone.\nJMG, would it be possible to do a mass provide-for-needs spell amongst and for our little group here, and, if so, how would we go about it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7720781", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd arrange it secretly, using PMs rather than open comments or posts, so that anyone who wants to mess with it will have a much harder time working out the details. You'd choose a symbol of your intention -- something clear, coherent, and in keeping with traditional magical symbolism -- and you'd make the intention wholly positive. Then everyone would work with that symbol using some straightforward contemplative or ritual process -- it could be as simple as lighting a candle and concentrating on an image -- on the same day each week. Repeat until your will is accomplished.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7734093", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "causticus", "content": "If you have no objections, I could set up a Discord chat server to coordinate this, and perhaps other MM-related things. And for anyone unaware of what Discord is, it's a live chat (text-based) platform, where anyone on there can set up an individual server for whatever topic, group, or endeavor they may want to establish a chat for.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7741261", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "By all means. Be a little selective about who joins, though...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7759181", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "causticus", "content": "Thank you. And most certainly; vetting is key. With the way these are set up, anyone who clicks the invite link can join, but there is a tied permission system whereby only those vetted by the admins/mods can see the actual discussion channels which are accessed by particular access roles. Also, cosmetic roles can be added as well for things like which kind of practices one does, what pantheon one is partial towards, ect. All pretty spiffy stuff.\nHere's a link btw for anyone reading this:\nhttps://discord.gg/4k7cNVC\nIntroducing yourself and showing you are a genuine MM reader/participant will get you verified.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7802445", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been itching to do something like this since reading DF's Magical Battle of Britain. I'll sign up as a perennial commonly planted in the fall ;)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7763277", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "open_space", "content": "I would be up for that. Let me know if it happens though the selective part seems important per JMG suggestions. Any ideas on how to do that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7776077", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "causticus", "content": "Cool, nice. Yeah I guess we would have to start off by bringing on people who use identifiable monikers on dreamwidth then devise a way to be able to somehow verify people who participate here anonymously. I'm sure we'll be able to devise something.\nAnyway if you didn't see above, here's the server link. If/when you join use the same name as you do here so I know who it is joining.\nhttps://discord.gg/4k7cNVC", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7779149", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi! Can you tell us what the minimum tech stuff we need to participate? When I clicked through it says my tablet (a samsung, a few years old but not terribly out if date?) is not compatible. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7790925", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "tunesmyth", "content": "Laughingsage, may I suggest that you invite anyone interested who can’t join Discord to just PM you? I suspect this won’t be an isolated case. (And, are you sure that a platform called “Discord” is a good vehicle for a group working? I know it’s probably ironic, but...)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7720525", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kimberly,\nI love your Orphic hymns! Been listening to them as part of doing planetary charities. Can you give music lessons over Google talk or Skype? Not the same of course but it might be worth exploring to keep things going.\nFingers crossed there is financial relief for people this time. I think there will have to be. The elites don't want a repeat of Occupy, only this time with a lot more people.\nPositive waves, everyone! 😻", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7723085", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Thanks so much, I was hoping people would use them for planetary charity.  I've written ones for Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, the Sun, the Moon, Mars, Pluto, Neptune, Ceralian Demeter, regular Demeter, and a third tune without words for Demeter, Hera, Adonis, and Gaia so far.  Mercury, Jupiter, and Venus are published and the rest are in the works.\nOnline lessons are a good suggestion -- many thanks for it.\nI do wonder what kind of financial reset this will cause.  I've always thought the upper middle class around here can't afford their big houses and SUVs any better than I could, it's just that they don't know what I figured out years ago.  If I were still in that class right now, I'd be absolutely terrified and with good reason.  There is much relief in being used to what the upper middle mistakenly thinks of as a state of deprivation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7782477", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kimberly,\nSo true! My family collapsed early and beat the rush but not exactly intentionally. Someone who sells windows and other repairs in the richest urban county in the state told me a couple years ago that lots of apparently well-off clients of his weren't paying him. I get the Titanic deck chairs sensation going anywhere near there. But I feel occasional glimmerings of hope that all the good work done here and elsewhere will ease the path forward! Very thankful for these blogs. Am gonna look for bunny slippers at the thrift store!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7722573", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Thanks so much for the neat suggestion, JMG.  I'll think about it.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7723341", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ha, Now I have you Kimberly!  I will be repaying your prayers with interest.\nMaxine", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7729485", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Kimberly,\nAlong the lines of previous suggestions, I'm wondering if you would consider online guitar lessons, (if you teach that). I'd planned to start last month but have held off due to current events. Be warned though, I've not got one musical gene in my body!\nGawain", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7729741", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Keeping you in my meditations, and you've got my sympathy as well. (And my thanks for the hymn--she's one of my patrons!) My BIL is a chef and had *just* gotten hired after months of looking (and my sister has migraines and musculoskeletal problems, so can't work) so I know what you mean.\nI understand the concern, am worried about my parents and elderly acquaintances, but am also keeping my fingers crossed for those whose livelihoods will be affected. (Having sympathy for the extroverts among my social circle, OTOH, is more of a challenge for me. :P)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7736397", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "bridgeofsighs", "content": "Have you seen this you tube vocal coach Kimberly?\nhttps://youtu.be/WPWv-T2EsoM\nI get the feeling she makes most of her money with online classes.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7742797", "title": "Re: Orphic Hymn to Aphrodite", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Thanks everyone for your prayers and well wishes.  I'm low on energy today from having to contact so many people this morning and afternoon, but I was able to arrange a delayed payment with my commercial landlord to give me time to secure a loan.  This experience has already been a valuable lesson about resilience.  Take good care of yourselves and may you be blessed.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7721293", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When I realize I've goofed something up during a ritual I usually go back to the error, redo it from there and go on. Is that what you recommend, or is it better to start fresh from the beginning? Just ignoring it doesn't feel right for sure.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7722317", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I tend to go back to the error and start from there; I've never gotten the sense that it's necessary to start over from the beginning.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7724877", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI have been working with the DMH, and for the past couple of months, trying to get ready to awaken the two currents. However, Ogham readings keep telling me not to do the workings, so as suggested in the DMH, I keep going back to the more basic practices. Is there anything more specific you could advise doing in order to become ready to awaken the two currents?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7741517", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you considered doing a divination with that in mind? Since I have no way to judge what might be the issue, that might be the best option.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7725645", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I saw a documentary series about mathematics that included a debate about whether maths was discovered or invented. That is whether the structure of the universe is fundamentally mathematical, or if that's just the best humanity has been able to knock together to explain the world we live in. What's the occult theory of what numbers are?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7743565", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on which occultist you ask. Some occult traditions take one of these approaches, some take the other. I tend to go for a third option, which is that mathematics are hardwired into the human nervous system as an evolutionarily successful approximation to reality.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7725901", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there an occult explanation for the sense of the world not being the same again after an event? I don't really have a word to describe it but it feels like a changing of the guard in the zeitgeist. I have the sense of this pandemic feeling in much the same way as the 9/11 attacks in regards to changing the world. In fact 9/11 was the only previous time I've felt this way.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7743821", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, there's certainly a tendency for collective consciousness to shift decisively at certain moments in history, usually catalyzed by dramatic events. That may be what you're sensing.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7745357", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I feel the same way, as though something has changed permanently and 2019 is now \"the past\" in a way it wasn't just after New Year's.\nI think I felt the same way right after 9/11, but I was 13 years old at the time and utterly unaware of egregors and zeitgeists, so I couldn't quite place it.\n- Barrigan", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7726157", "title": "The Order of Spiritual Alchemy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings JMG:\nThank you for assessment of this silly-apocalypse.\nWhere might I find information on the OSA?\nYou made mention of this in one of your books. This\nWork sounds intriguing to me.\nI currently  am in Port Angeles, WA at the moment. As you know, a wee beach town at the top of Olympic Peninsula. People up here are a little nervous but still going about their business.\nMuch love and light to all,\n-Elizabeth from Seattle", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7744333", "title": "Re: The Order of Spiritual Alchemy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Order of Spiritual Alchemy has been inactive for some time now. I've received the initiations and have the full set of teaching materials as they existed when I became a member; down the road a bit I hope to have the time to get those revised and start a website based version of it. Step by step...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7726413", "title": "Hooray for Regardie!", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "I recently purchased and read his \"fine little essay 'The Art of True Healing',\" and have done his life force circulation exercise several times following my usual MPE. It's pretty breathtaking! And it seems to be, not directly healing my \"Yesod issue\" so much as making the inputs in my life that have a negative impact on that unbearable - amplifying its response to them.\nSo, for example, where a spoonful of refined sugar, or one too many puffs of cannabis would make me uncomfortable before, such things have now become  wholly unbearable. It's an unusual approach to healing in the West for sure! (And another fine example of the louder signals I talk about on my own DW journal, where I have posted a new weird tale this week.)\nAlso, am I correct in thinking that the SOP's circulation of the light is based on this ritual?\nGrover", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7744589", "title": "Re: Hooray for Regardie!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting! Yes, the SoP circulations are partly based on that ritual.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7726669", "title": "Sphere of Protection", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have been doing the SOP described on this site for the last 2,5 months. Recently however I switched to the SOP described in the DMH, since I intend to follow that program trough.\nI noticed a change in the procedure. The opening in the dreamwith version includes the centers in the middle of the head and belly, but closes with the solar plexus center. The DMH version does not include the belly center at all, but focuses very much on the solar plexus.\nWhy the change?\nI notice, that the immediate focus on the plexus helps me with the elemental invocations, but what does the inclusion of the belly center mean? I am a complete beginner and have no understanding what this would mean.\nBest regards.\nV", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7745101", "title": "Re: Sphere of Protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The DMH version is intended to be used with the rest of that book's program of training, which includes work with the womb and heart centers but focuses on the solar plexus. The focus on the head and womb centers in the version I put on Dreamwidth is based on the one I intend to publish shortly for a new system of occult study and practice, and makes use of different energy centers. Each occult system chooses between 1 and 12 of the 360 energy centers in the human body to work with, depending on the fine details of the work to be done.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7786829", "title": "Re: Sphere of Protection", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Thank you,\nSo I take it, it is not wise to combine the two by adding the womb center to the DMH elemental cross.\nFor the time being I will stick to the DMH version.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7787341", "title": "Re: Sphere of Protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's correct.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7726925", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You said one of the benefits of tai chi chih is it circulates etheric energy round the whole body rather than concentrating it in certain areas. Are there ways to do the same with astral energy, as most rituals seem to focus it down the centre line.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7745869", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Astral energy naturally circulates very easily -- the challenge there is to get it to concentrate! It's etheric energy that tends to get stuck and need circulation.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7727181", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I'm remembering this right, last week you said the effect of light on the pineal gland was why some some systems require growing the hair, while others require shaving it. Presumably no physical light can get through scalp, skull, and deep into the brain. So is there an etheric component of light that can penetrate the rest but be blocked by hair?\nYou also said previously that baldness is a natural process that serves a purpose. What is it? That being the case, what would the guy in the Order of the Essenes course who got his hair back through force of will, have done to himself?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7746381", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The human body is actually translucent to red and infrared light -- put your hand against a strong light and you can see some of the light that leaks through. So in fact the pineal gland can be affected by physical sunlight as well as the sun's etheric radiation. As for the purpose, my guess is that the states of mind facilitated by light reaching the pineal gland are good to have in male elders -- though here again that may be a matter of opinion, as some cultures make good and sure that baldness doesn't succeed in letting light in...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7727437", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few weeks ago someone posted about the Bolsheviks' use of will in the pursuit of revolution. That isn't something I've come across. But if you read books like Tony Cliff's three volume biography\nLenin\n, some things do stick out. When Lenin writes about all the things a revolutionary needs to know and needs to be able to do, it sounds a lot like a course of occult study. Things like dialectics and historical materialism held a similar importance and equivalence to occult philosophy. So it is possible they developed some of the same mental capabilities.\nHaving said that, I don't think any significant figures in Bolshevism had any background in ritual. Post-revolutionary attempts to replace Orthodox rituals, such as 'Octobering' a baby in place of Christening, were notoriously awful; boring and stupid.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7746637", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. You're right that leftist revolutionaries never do seem to be very good at ritual -- the attempted cult of Reason in post-revolutionary France was just as inept.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7768653", "title": "Lenin", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "There's no reason to assume that Lenin was into the occult, although there are some quotes that do sound very much like excerpts from occult philosophy, for example (this is a loose translation): \"The weapon of criticism can't replace criticism by weapons, a material force must be countered by another material force, but a theory can become a material force too should it possess the masses people.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7748173", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "https://www.jacobinmag.com/2017/04/gramsci-russian-revolution-lenin-trotsky-soviets", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7727693", "title": "Hedging my bets", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hopefully this isn’t excessively long…\nI’ve had an idea in my head for a while to plant hedges as fences on my farm.  I finally decided this was the year to do it, procured seed for a few different types of trees and made plans to sprout them.  The plan was to get them started in the garden then plant them in their final position once they could out compete grasses and whatnot.\nSo I did a reading regarding growing my trees from seed.  I’ve always had issues growing from seed so it was my main concern.\nI got:\nJ: Colled\nLW: Ffordd\nRW: Elw\nI took that as a no.  I was a little surprised by that so I asked if I would be better off not trying to plant trees from seed in the garden.\nI got:\nJ: Bendeth Fach\nLW: Gwyn\nRW: Lllosgwrn y Ddraig\nI took that as a yes and as a hint to seek help.  I asked if I would have better success getting someone else to grow my seedlings.  I know plenty of green fingered folks that would be happy to do it and it would perhaps get me a little more of a guarantee for success.\nI got:\nJ: Colled\nLW: Mab\nRW: Pen y Ddraig\nI took that as a no.  I’ll speed things up.  I asked if I should even plant trees as hedges: Colled.  I asked is my hedge idea a good idea: Colled.  I got irritated and asked should I just abandon this idea and I got Ffordd four times in a row and stopped the reading.\nI asked if I should choose different trees than the ones I obtained seed for and got:\nJ: Cyswllt\nLW: Carchar\nRW: Ffordd\nI didn’t know how to take that one.  It seemed favorable so I asked about a specific type of tree that is native, grows abundantly on my property and is a typical hedge plant where hedges are used.  I got colled… again.\nSo I decided to get really simple.  Should I plant a hedge?  Cyswllt.\nAm I doing something wrong?  The repeated colled result seems like a hint I'm not taking.  I feel like if I keep pursuing this line of questioning I’m going to start irritating the oracle (and no doubt try your patience with an endless wall of text).  Have my interpretations been off?  In the past when I got a yes to a question it was a clear yes but with this I feel like I’m working through a flow chart that keeps sending me back to the beginning.  Help?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7746893", "title": "Re: Hedging my bets", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It sounds to me as though the oracle is saying that this whole idea is inappropriate for some reason and you need to let it drop.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7758669", "title": "Re: Hedging my bets", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sigh.  Kinda had a feeling.  It's worth noting that I don't have any other examples of hedges in the style of England and Ireland in the US.  Perhaps there's a reason.  Anybody out there have any theories?  They seem to be such a pragmatic solution to the permanent problem of fencing on the farm.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7779661", "title": "Re: Hedging my bets", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Do you know how they make/made real hedges in Europe? Its not just a matter of planting trees, you have to let them grow to a certain height, then cut them and bend them, so they grow together.  It seems to take a certain amount of skill. There are some YouTube videos on it so that you can see how it's done, but really, it'd  be much easier and faster to just do it with metal wire fencing and posts (of black locust if you can.) It would take qhite a number of years to get a hedge to the point that it would stop animals.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7785293", "title": "Re: Hedging my bets", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Years ago I came across an old US Dept of Agriculture pamphlet on making literal hedge fences from the hedge tree also known as Osage Orange. It's native to the Midwest and there is no better firewood, burns hot enough to melt a stove pipe if you're careless.\nThere were thousands of hedgerows planted here in the Midwest after the dust bowl years, as a conservation measure. The pamphlet (which was lost on some old hard drive but maybe still findable on the interwebs) even calculated the cost per foot to hire some guys to dig the trenches.\nThe instructions (in case you get a favorable reading at some point) were to freeze the balls over winter to free the seed, then plant them every 6 inches in a shallow trench. Once the saplings are a few feet tall you bend and weave every fifth one diagonally through the other four, so they look like counting tallies. Keep the side sprouts trimmed and in a few years you have a fence tight enough a rabbit would have trouble squeezing through and strong enough to contain a bull. All the trimmings are a plus for winter firewood.\nI've wanted to try it for years since the horses invariably pull the electric fence down, so finally last fall I collected a 5 gallon bucket full of hedgeballs. They are now a seedy mush waiting for a warm day. 🌱", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7727949", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Did your current project of an occultist programme to increase wisdom and encourage revelation develop from your earlier idea of 'occultism lite'? Will it also involve the Sacred Geometry Oracle?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7747405", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. I spent quite a while mulling over the possibilities and meditating on them, and got a very clear sense that it's time to get a good solid system of occult study and practice -- one that doesn't focus on magic -- into circulation again. The Sphere of Protection, discursive meditation, and the Sacred Geometry Oracle will be three of the core elements of the system -- but there'll be plenty more to give people constructive tools to work with.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7786317", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Will it be possible to keep the LRP instead of the SoP? I tried switching over and up ended going back.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7787853", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Much of the system I'm designing can be used from within any set of practices that includes a basic protective ritual, discursive meditation, and a divination practice. So you should be able to work with most of it.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7728205", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What intensity level of magic does someone need to be practising in order to pass the point of no return and have to keep it up for the rest of their life?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7747661", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's impossible to know in advance. If you want to avoid it, you need to avoid magic altogether. Otherwise, as Robert Browning put it...\n\"For mark! no sooner was I fairly found\nPledged to the plain, after a pace or two,\nThan, pausing to throw backward a last view\nO'er the safe road, 'twas gone; grey plain all round:\nNothing but plain to the horizon's bound.\nI might go on; nought else remained to do.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7777613", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This may have been said sometime before...or may be very obvious, but if I can ask a beginner question. What makes someone need magic? What changes occur with practice (or just certain practices) that make continuing necessary? How would one know they have reached such a point?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7782989", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Basically, what happens is that after a certain amount of practice -- the amount varies from person to person -- you're sufficiently sensitive to magical energies that if you don't keep up banishing rituals and other basic practices, you have trouble keeping your head free of outside influences, and your life becomes a mess. If you keep up the practices, on the other hand, you influence your surroundings rather than being influenced by them, and life becomes a lot easier.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7783757", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does this effect carry from life to life?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7788109", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To some extent, yes. People who have practiced magic -- or any kind of serious spirituality, for that matter -- tend to return to it in future lives.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7728461", "title": "Heathen and Celtic Golden Dawn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "First, thank you for providing this forum and answering questions.\nI've been practicing the Heathen Golden Dawn rituals you posted here since September (Middle Pillar since October). That's my only experience with anything \"magical\" other than a brief attempt at the SoP, but I found the GD rituals suited me much better. I'm what you may call a \"recovering atheist\", in large part thanks to following your writings for years.\nWhile I'm waiting for the HGD book I picked up a copy of Celtic Golden Dawn, since it's kind of a \"sister project\" and might give some hints what the Heathen version will be like (?). Which leads me to my questions:\n1) The CGD says the summoning mode of the LRP can be used to counteract a lack of vitality in yourself (p.71). I assume this applies to the Heathen version as well? Following from this, is it okay to do the banishing mode (plus MP) in the morning and the summoning mode in the evening, or should you only do one of these per day? Does the MP perform the same role as the summoning LRP?\n2) Would it be possible to incorporate the tree working from the CGD in a Heathen GD practice, or would that be an inappropriate mixing of systems?\n3) A few quick questions about the HGD book itself: will it have an over-the-top deluxe edition in the vein of Dolmen Arch? And will the content be presented as a 1920s correspondence course, or in a more straightforward textbook form?\nThank you again for your time!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7748429", "title": "Re: Heathen and Celtic Golden Dawn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that's appropriate in both systems.\n2) Correct me if I'm wrong, but isn't reverence for sacred trees something you find in Heathen as well as Celtic traditions? That being the case, the tree exercise ought to be applicable to both.\n3) Probably not, and we're not sure yet.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7728717", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Due to current conditions, I would like to ask if everything is still on track with the second volume of the Dolmen Arch?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7748685", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so. I've done the first set of page proofs.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7728973", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "logicalmagic83", "content": "Greetings, JMG.\nMy question concerns tarot. I listen to a podcast where at the beginning of every show, the hosts draw a tarot card as the card of the week. When describing the energy and meaning of the card, they speak as though the energy of that card applies to the listening audience as well as themselves. I have no issue with this as I find the show useful, educational and the hosts are engaging interviewers. I'm fine with using some of my energy in being a listener.\nBut by listening to the show, does that make me a querent? Is it rather like implied consent? I'm having a hard time locating the line between participant and observer in this situation. The following week the hosts revisit the past weeks' card to see how that energy played into their daily lives. They also request audience feedback and I have noted some synchronicities between the cards they draw and the ones I draw and study in my morning practice. And yes, I agree that this is a topic worthy of meditation. : )", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7748941", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, if you choose to participate in the show to the extent of listening to it, knowing what the score is, you're giving your implicit consent. You should certainly meditate on that, to learn the most from it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7729229", "title": "Geomancy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Archdruid,\nMay I ask you for help with my divination? I consulted geomancy last night because doctors wouldn’t give me clear instructions. This is not a demand for medical advice.\nI’ve been down with laryngitis and then heavy flu for a total of four weeks now. The last laryngologist in my European town on his last day in office (then closing like all others due to Coronavirus) prescribed me an antibiotic while telling me that it was up to me to decide about taking it or not. I know that a bacterial infection can sit in your throat at the same time as a viral influenza, but I haven’t been tested for Streptococcus and wouldn’t want to put undue strain on my immune system in times like these.\nMy sixth house question was: \"Will Med X cure my laryngitis without imposing undue strain on my body?\" I got the following figures. I know about the classical rule that Cauda Draconis in the first house means you’ve already made a decision, but I assure you that I don’t know which that is. Could it also mean that it’s too late to take this step (taking the med)? At the same time, the reading perfects several times. How would you interpret it?\nI Cauda Draconis\nII Via\nIII Cauda Draconis\nIV Puer\nV Via\nVI Via\nVII Cauda Draconis\nVIII Acquisitio\nIX Tristitia\nX Fortuna Major\nXI Populus\nXII Puella\nThank you for your advice and may you and your loved ones be safe and in good health!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7749197", "title": "Re: Geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a favorable reading, with multiple modes of perfection, so the answer is certainly yes. I suspect what the Cauda Drac is saying is that you're on track to get better anyway, but the medication will help.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7729997", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am largely ignoring the news and trying to focus on the job, but there is this tension \"in the air\", which I am trying to shut out, but with less success than is ideal. Is this some aspect of the astral field or Jung's collective unconscious? Does the Archdruid recommend a double serving of banishing in such cases? Head Chef Israel Regardie probably had some good recipes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7746125", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "It's a bit of the same at me. In the news most ist now about the Coronavirus or related things. It has become difficult to find anything else. Abot the vibe, on the one hand, the vibe here in the German city where I live isn't overly crazy, but a bit strange it is indeed. So far, banishing rituals work quite well.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7749453", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Banishing is important, but it's also important to fill the banished space with something more positive, or the negativity just seeps back in to fill the vacuum. If you've developed the necessary chops to do serious ritual magic, a ritual of spiritual development would be helpful; if not, affirmations are always useful.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7730509", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nHave you ever read the book \"Inside the Priory of Sion\" by Robert Howells? Some chapters of the book have some cryptic allusions to sacred geometry and earth energies around Rennes-le-Chateau region and its relation to Templars and Freemasons. Given your current research topics, this book may be interesting for you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7749709", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, it's been a good long time since I looked into the Priory of Sion hoax. I'll see if the libraries here have a copy.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7753549", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "By the way, this book is different from most of the other books about the PoS hoax (like conspiracy theories on one hand or official PoS propaganda books on the other hand). The author (Robert Howells) is well versed in Western esoteric lore and his main correspondent - Nicolas Haywood - is an interesting representative from PoS who has a solid background in Rosicrucianism and alchemy. The impression that I got from him is that, Nicolas Haywood seems more interested in spiritual aspects of the PoS mythos than its monarchistic goals - unlike the current clique which governs the order.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7754061", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! That's good to hear.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7730765", "title": "The Possible Effect of Magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello,\nI have a question concerning some minor physical health problems lasting several months; could they have been occurring in relation to practicing magic?\nI am a beginner; have been doing some basic practices since September 2019. I am a more or less solitary apprentice – well, I can discuss magic with one of my friends.\nBefore that I had lots of problems. I believe they were somewhat connected with the gargantuan effort to find and verbalize “the” deep meaning of life. As fast as possible, of course.\nI ended up solving serious mental health issues for more than 10 years.\nBouncing between extremes in moods (mania/depression), cognitive abilities (from academic excellence to a state, in which I couldn’t understand a sentence longer than 3 words – and back… and forth), even between accepting the illness and totally refusing it, I was very confused as what to do.\nSeveral years later, around the time I started practicing magic, I realized what was to become my main goal in life: Live. Exist. Bear what you have to. Breathe if you can. I don’t even know if that is any sort of a real goal – probably not, because it –just – is.\nI think my current problems might be just an effort of my body to sort of “clean some of the mess” when given a little rest - and space to do so due to daily meditation and the Lesser Banishing Ritual of the Pentagram exercise. But is it a viable explanation?\nThank you.\nMarketa", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7750221", "title": "Re: The Possible Effect of Magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that could well be involved. Make sure that you get plenty of rest, stay well hydrated, and eat a diet that includes respectable amounts of protein, fats, and carbohydrates -- what used to be called balanced diet before the food cranks got at it -- so your body has everything it needs to deal with the mess.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7731021", "title": "Clairvoyance follow-up question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week I asked about symbols I see, and you said it indicated a talent for clairvoyance. Could you say more about what clairvoyance is and how it works, how it could be used?\nSomeone else asked about seeing scenes and you called it hypnogogic imagery. Is that basically the same thing as clairvoyance, or how is it different?\nThanks; your answer last week was very encouraging and really kind of cool.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7750989", "title": "Re: Clairvoyance follow-up question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are several different kinds of clairvoyance; the one you probably have is the ability to see things on the astral plane -- one of the subtle planes of being, the realm of dream, imagination, and concrete consciousness. Each of us has sense organs on each of the planes where we have fully developed bodies -- the material plane of dense matter, the etheric plane of life force, and the astral plane of concrete consciousness -- and part of the process of occult training involves learning to awaken and use the sense organs on the etheric and astral planes. You've basically got a head start on the process, probably because you did some work developing your astral vision in a previous life.\nAs for what you can do with it, that depends on subtle details that will become clear over time if you take up occult practice. Some people with that gift find that they can use it to see other people's auras -- the aura is the outer layer of the astral body, and if you can see it clearly you can perceive what's going on in their emotions, and also sometimes diagnose health problems. Other people find that their gift is helpful for interacting with spirits or for perceiving the same sorts of patterns of events about to happen that astrologers track.\nHypnagogic imagery is sometimes but not always clairvoyant in nature. The label simply refers to any spontaneous imagery you see as you're going to sleep; the equivalent seen as you wake up is hypnopompic imagery.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7774797", "title": "Re: Clairvoyance follow-up question", "user": "causticus", "content": "Interesting on that last bit. I've occasionally experienced very vivid, quickly-flashing imagery when in that transition state when I'm drifting off to sleep or when I can't quite asleep yet I'm in a quasi-dreamy state. My only spiritual experiences seem to come in that type of state and sometimes with a burst of rapid creative thoughts that come to me shortly before waking up.\nBTW, is there any practical way to develop astral clairvoyance, like practices I can do to be being able to read the auras of people and animals? Or does this come about naturally when I get good at practicing certain magic systems?", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7731277", "title": "SOP & Eastern Exercises", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am quite interested in your recent post about your project concerning the Sphere of Protection and eastern exercises.  You wrote, \"This isn't a book about magic -- it's occultism in the sense found in Manly P. Hall and The Kybalion, the quest for wisdom and revelation through study of occult lore and practice of meditation and certain other related disciplines.\"  Not that middle path between magic and mysticism (if that's what it is) might be just the thing.  In books by Gareth Knight, you and others I read ahead through the practices described later in the book and see described the manufacture and consecration of magical tools, and I object to myself, \"I'm not going there.\"  But I know I need a practice, and mysticism, obedience and devotion doesn't seem to be it either.  Though I don't always agree with you, thank you for your efforts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7751245", "title": "Re: SOP & Eastern Exercises", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm glad to hear it. I think a lot of people are looking for something like what old-fashioned occult schools used to offer: a set of practices that can be used for spiritual development, without being oriented either toward ritual magic or toward devotional mysticism. The project's well under way, and I already have a publisher lined up; I'll post updates here as details come in.\nAnd I don't expect anyone to always agree with me, btw. My opinions are often very strongly held, but I'd find the world very boring indeed if everyone agreed with them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7731533", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nConcerning Tarot, I’m having trouble relating the astrological and Qabalistic correspondences of a card to the meaning of that card in a divination. Let me illustrate my usual process with an example: Let’s say that I draw the Three of Cups (Rider Waite deck). I observe that this card is associated with joy, festivity, merriment, abundance, social support, and so on, and draw the obvious connections with my query. I also know that it corresponds to the element of water, which is related to emotions, feelings, and nurturance.\nThen I would go through the astrological and Qabbalistic correspondences. In astrology the Three of Cups corresponds to Mercury in Cancer, the planet of the intellect and communication acting in the water sign of the Crab, and the suit of Cups is governed by Venus, the planet of Beauty, Attraction and Love. Qabalistically, it’s the expression of Binah, the third Sephirah, acting in the Briatic world of Creation, through the archangel Tzaphkiel, the Contemplation of God. But how can I relate this trivia to something meaningful in my divination? It seems that the most relevant aspects of the card are those that are on the illustration. Any tips?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7751501", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good! You've noticed that the connections aren't obvious. Now the question is whether you take the next step, and begin to seek out the non-obvious connections. Only you can decide whether you're willing to do that, of course, and that's the whole point of the test that you're facing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7752525", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "And I'm guessing that learning how to draw the non-obvious connections involves sharpening my occult faculties with daily practice, and of course, a hefty dose of meditation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7753293", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ding! We have a winner. ;-)\nYes, exactly.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7731789", "title": "Experience of the Inner Worlds", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr Greer,\nI want to be a Christian Druid. To attain this goal I am planning to work through Gareth Knight's \"Experience of the Inner Worlds\" and subsequently your \"Druid Magic Handbook\", maybe in combination with the OBOD course.\n1) Does this make sense or will I end up terribly confused?\n2) Do you think I could start practicing the things from your Druidry Handbook (especially the sun and earth path) while working through Knights book?\n3) During earlier MMs you advised to complement Knights book with a banishing ritual, so I‘d take the time to learn the SoP beforehand. Or would it be better to do the Christian Banishing for the year or so it takes to work through Experience of the Inner Worlds and learn the SoP later?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7751757", "title": "Re: Experience of the Inner Worlds", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It makes perfect sense.\n2) Yes, you can do that, but use Knight's work in place of the Moon Path exercises.\n3) The SoP is compatible with Knight's work, so I'd encourage you to learn it, using one of the Christian versions of it, and practice Knight's exercises in a space you've cleansed with the SoP.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7732045", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nDo you use social media at all? If not, do you have any advice on how to find satisfying social relationships and a sense of community in modern society, particularly in a Western country like the US, while refusing to hand over one's personal info to Zuckerberg et al? It seems that nothing happens these days unless it’s online. A couple of possibilities come to mind, but none of them are particularly satisfying:\n-Organized religion. The advantage is that they have an existing structure, shared philosophy and regular in-person meetings. However, the disadvantage is that it’s mostly dominated by older people (50+) and not really a thing in large metropolitan areas, and in my opinion, you also have to be a believer to be an honest participant.\n-The partying and club scene. This is dominated by college-aged people and not suited for everyone.\n-Meetups, hobby groups, and so on. The first problem is that most of these organize online, and if you’re not on their platform then you are invisible. The second problem is that people often use them to meet up for the activity, but little else. You can probably find an activity partner, but you won’t find someone that will attend your funeral.\nIt seems that the Internet has taken the wind out of a lot of activities and institutions that used to bring people together and give them a sense of belonging. There might be a generational effect here too. I’m younger than 30, so I may be seeing things from a different perspective than you are.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7744845", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m 60 and get quite annoyed when I find something I might be interested in and get told to sign up with Facebook.  Facebook is evil and I want nothing to do with it.  I guess that now that hermitage is suddenly in vogue I will have the last laugh, but I’ve missed several interesting things.  Usually what happens is I explain I don’t use Facebook, could you maybe put me on a mailing list, and the nice lady I’m talking to fumbles for a moment with the idea that someone is not on Facebook, and says “well, it really is easier if you sell your soul [oops, I meant ‘use Facebook’]” and that’s that.  If you find a way around this problem, please share it.\nGrumble.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7747917", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "I have observed the same thing. And, additionally, I have observed that it has become more and more difficult not only for me, but for others, too, to keep social connections afloat. The communication gets shallower and more superficial, and social occasions dwindle. But a few connections still exist and are stable.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7772237", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I suppose we could start a social-media site for non-Farcebookers...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7752013", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm really not the right person to ask about this, as I have Aspergers syndrome and don't do a lot of social activities; my idea of a pleasant evening usually involves a glass of halfway decent bourbon and a really good book. Just now I'm enjoying being even more of a hermit than usual, and I say \"enjoying\" without the least trace of irony! No, I don't do social media either.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7754317", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "But you must have been more social at a different part of your life, given your married status, no? Or was that a question of making the appropriate offerings to Aphrodite?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7760205", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My wife and I met when we were both going to the same college. I was a little more social in those days, but not much, and a lot of what drew the two of us together at first is that we both enjoyed quiet evenings at home.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7732301", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If bone grafts are spiritually dangerous, is there anyhing the tissue bank or transplant tream could do to make them safe? If someone is a donor, is there anything they can do while still alive to make their components better for whoever ends up with them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7752269", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a good question to which I don't think anyone yet knows the answer. It would take a good deal of experimentation to settle the matter one way or another.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7732557", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good morning JMG,\n1. Concerning archangels in the Qabalah, are the archangels who are associated with the first Sephiroth (Kether, Chokmah, Binah…) more powerful or senior over those who are associated with the later Sephiroth (Tiphareth, Netzach, Hod…)? It seems that Metatron, Raziel, Tzaphkiel and company play almost no role in Western popular religion or myth whereas the superstars like Michael and Gabriel are all assigned lower down than their status would demand.\n2. Are there any plans to publish revised editions of your magical textbooks (LRM, Paths of Wisdom, CGD, etc.) to incorporate the questions and feedback received from readers over the years?\n3. As I’m sure you’re aware, Rhode Island is very close to Pilgrim Nuclear Station in Massachusetts, and a couple of other stations in New York State and New Hampshire. Do you have any concerns about a possible nuclear incident on the East Coast in the foreseeable future, and have you made any preparations for that eventuality?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7755597", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Not at all. The ones you hear about are the ones that are far enough down the Tree that their activities have a relation to ordinary human life that we're capable of comprehending. The archangels of the higher spheres are basically entirely beyondf our comprehension.\n2) My books\nPaths of Wisdom\nand\nCircles of Power\nhave already been released in new editions by Aeon Books, with various revisions, and\nInside a Magical Lodge\nwill be appearing soon, along with\nThe UFO Chronicles\n, an updated version of my book\nThe UFO Phenomenon\nwith a lot of new research in it. We'll see about the others.\n3) The dangers of nuclear power plants, while real, have been highly exaggerated by the doombat brigade. (The main problem with nuclear power, and the reason why it's quietly going out of use, is that it's an economic disaster -- it never pays for itself.) The Pilgrim nuclear plant is some 50 miles away from us, in a direction from which the local winds essentially never blow, so I'm not particularly concerned; my chances of being killed by lightning are almost immeasurably higher.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7732813", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello John, this is Aziz, I occasionally comment on your main blog.\nI was wondering if you ever worked on or at least read anyone else's work comparing the Nordic (Yggdrasil) and Jewish-Hermetic trees of life?\nCheers", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7755853", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've been working on a Heathen equivalent of the Tree of Life as part of the Heathen Golden Dawn project I'm developing with coauthor Sven Eriksen. I'm sure other people have explored the same thing, but I don't happen to know of any.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7780429", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Edredd Thorson's \"9 Doors of Midgard\" has something that seems like such.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7733069", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How frequently are revival movements also millenarian?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7756109", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Revival movements almost always turn millenarian the moment they discover that they're not going to win. It's the standard response to approaching failure: start claiming that Jesus or the Space Brothers or somebody will win for you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7733581", "title": "Solstice Water", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nFor the last little while, I've been in the habit of collecting rainwater for magical purposes, as it seems a better alternative to tap and there aren't many natural springs where I live. It occurred to me the other day that the date the water is collected may have occult significance and aid certain workings - in particular, for the last couple of years, we've had a downpour on the summer solstice, and I still have rainwater leftover from that. How could solstice water be put to effective use?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7756365", "title": "Re: Solstice Water", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. I think you have a lot of experimentation ahead of you!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7733837", "title": "Lesser Banishing Ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nWhile working with the Heathen Lesser Banishing Ritual the past two days, as I vibrate the name of the North, Idun, I visualized without my consciously trying, a flow of energy joining me from the North.  It left me feeling a sense of warmth and gladness that Idun seems to be communicating with me.  I'm totally uncertain as to what to do with it at this point though.  Any suggestions would be appreciated!\nThanks,\nPrizm", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7756621", "title": "Re: Lesser Banishing Ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Accept it gratefully and see what it brings you.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7780173", "title": "Re: Lesser Banishing Ritual", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Prizm, I think that's from the apples that are always in Idunn's keeping, and only in her keeping.  For the Æsir, they renew life and strength.  Warmth and gladness sounds about right for how they might affect mere humans.  I'd say you're being given an uncommon gift there.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7735117", "title": "Ovate Tree Working", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The ovate tree working in CGD instructs to put the front of the body against the tree for those with an excess of nervous influence, and the back against the tree for those with lethargy and sluggishness. If I experience both of those, is it ok to do whichever I feel drawn to, and switch it up as inclined?\nAlso, for the cell salt experiment, my natal chart says that my Sun is at Sagittarius 16°14'\nIs that 16 degrees Sagittarius? And the 14 is just a decimal? So I'm reading it that my cell salt combination would be: Silicea 1, Calc. Phos. 3, Nat. Mur. 3, Ferrum Phos. 2\nIs that correct?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7756877", "title": "Re: Ovate Tree Working", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that's precisely what you should do.\n2) Yes and yes. The 14' isn't quite a decimal; there are 60 minutes of arc in every degree, so 16° 14' is 16 degrees 14 minutes, or 16 degrees plus 14/60 of a degree.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7736141", "title": "Working through Baggage", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Through journaling and occult reading, I am working to understand the severe anxiety I suffered several years ago, and trying to find a way to deal with bits of anxiety and depression as they pop up in my life today.\n1. I do the DMH-SOP every morning, just the standard version with the Welsh gods. Do you think I should modify it to invoke stability and banish mental imbalance? The SOP seems to already do that, in a subtle way.\n2. In Psychic Self Defense, Fortune states that the neurotic pulls mental disturbance toward himself. Therefore even when magical means give him temporary reprieve, if the root cause is not figured out, those channels will remain open and he'll basically invoke his mental disturbance. In the introduction by a communicating entity in the Cosmic Doctrine, a visual is painted of a person carrying their thought-forms with them like strings to a kite. If I am pulling my worries and fatalisms toward myself, is there a visual I could use to stop? What came to mind was picturing myself covered in water, therefore the thoughts slide off me and don't stick. Do you have any suggestions?\n3. In Giulia Enders' book Gut, she talks about the \"gut-brain\" wherein conditions in the intestines trigger moods. She says this is not yet well understood. Do you or the commentariat have any ideas of occult connections or avenues of exploration for this? I'm trying to attack this issue from all sides. This reminded me of Fortune's explanation of the endocrine system's connection with the neurotic's repression of a natural instinct, causing it to overflow and manifest in mental disturbance. Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7757133", "title": "Re: Working through Baggage", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'd leave it as it is for now, and let it do its balancing work. It will help stabilize you over time.\n2) That sounds like a very good image. You can also use an affirmation:  \"I release all worries and fatalisms...they fall away from me into nothingness.\" (Silently repeat the first half while breathing in and the second half while breathing out.) Yes, you can combine this with the imagery.\n3) You might consider keeping a food diary, and noting how you feel after each meal. If some foods are troubling your digestive tract and triggering unhelpful moods, that could teach you what to avoid.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7736653", "title": "Divination", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You said that divination is a process not a product.\nCould you expand on that please?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7757389", "title": "Re: Divination", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The work of casting and interpreting readings teaches you much more than the end result ever will.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7736909", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Here in Seattle, we suddenly have a population that's washing its hands in cold or lukewarm water a _lot_ (repeated washing in hotter water will rough up your skin, as we're all finding out real fast) and eating a lot more home-cooked food. We're also more likely to sing and/or breathe deeply, and a number of people are trying to drink more water. Without a morning commute to contend with, I suspect a lot of people are getting a little more sleep.\nFrom an occult perspective, what might be the upshot of this? Am I right in imagining that as a populace we're getting our ether bodies in better shape than they've been for a while? Might this have something to do with the suddenly lowered level of shrieky political yelling that I've been observing locally?\n— Ergane", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7757645", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That might well have a lot to do with it! If that's the way people are reacting, it will be interesting to see if they learn from the experience...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7737933", "title": "Journaling and the Transcendental Function", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThanks for hosting this and hope that things are going as well as possible there.  I wrote a few weeks back and have a follow up, also a question.  I was the one who said that I couldn't possibly imagine going through my numbingly voluminous magic journals.  I finally got to the point in the LRM course where one does exactly that.  What I realized was that while I couldn't read them word for word, begin to end, I could take sections and look at it more impressionistically in terms of the tone and the general sort of person it seemed to be.  And that was very helpful and generally fit in with how I'm coming to see my strengths and weaknesses.  So thanks and thanks for your patience.  With an earth stellium in the third house and none in air, one of the bad tendencies is atrophied planning and deciding and instead tending to fill notebooks or otherwise blindly labor as a diversion, so I'm excited to gradually introduce new habits to swing the balance.\nThe other question is about the idea of Jung's you mention in LRM about how if you feel deeply split between two ideas and hold both in mind, the Transcendental Function will resolve them into a synthesis.  I've heard this before and suffer from chronic all-sidedness indecisiveness, so found it interesting.  I made a list of my five biggest overall elements of indecision and tried for seven days a row each thinking about the two sides of the dilemma.  So far I'd say the results are interesting.  Usually one or both side will seem at the beginning \"wrong\", but as I work with the fantasies, it is often just two poles of the zodiac, usually one's I have big placements in, so I think, not wrong at all.\nOn the other hand, I don't think I have had the coalescing effect happen.  I'm curious whether it's something you've seen and in what circumstance - if ok to tell.\nI suppose when I finish all five I should do the sixth - being decisive vs indecisive :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7757901", "title": "Re: Journaling and the Transcendental Function", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The activation of the transcendental function can take time, and how it manifests varies quite a bit from person to person. You may simply find yourself realizing that the conflicts aren't as important as you thought. Also, yes, working on the binary between decisive and indecisive would be a fine idea!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7738189", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI am considering adapting the SOP so as to call for an increase in my vitality.  I have performed an Ogham divination to see if this would be a good idea, and got this result:\nFirst card (me): Quert Reversed\nSecond card (action): Mor\nThird card (result): Oir reversed.\nI interpret this as suggesting that it is long past time that I did this, that it will have a new and unexpected effect, but that it will take time to take effect, and I may need to wait for an external influence to trigger it.\nWould you agree with this interpretation?\nThank you very much for your consideration.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7758157", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that seems about right.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7738445", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nWhat's the difference between Qliphoth and Underworld spirits?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7758413", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The term \"underworld spirits\" is very broad and vague, and includes a great many categories of spiritual beings; some are helpful to human beings, others indifferent, and still others inimical. The Qlippoth are a specific set of spiritual beings who are left over from the universe before ours, and they are invariably dangerous to us.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7738701", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does a polytheistic worldview have a basis for the belief in the inherent value of beings/persons? I was having a conversation the other day in which a GK Chesterton quote happened to come up: \"if [people] were not created equal, they were certainly evolved unequal. There is no basis for democracy except in a dogma about the divine origin of man.\"\nWhile polytheism certainly posits a divine origin for mankind in some respect, it does lack the \"all people are beloved children of The One And Only Creator God\" dimension, as per Christianity, which provides most of the backbone for treating one's fellow man as possessing at least as much value as oneself. Wondering what your thoughts would be on this.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7759949", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The faint (or not so faint) sound of an axe being ground is never absent from Chesterton's prose, is it? He was well enough educated to know that democracy was born in ebulliently polytheist Greece, too, so in this case I think he was being deliberately dishonest.\nAll that democracy requires is the recognition that a community thrives best if it grants its members equality under the law. Human beings aren't equal in any other sense -- no one of us is exactly equal to any other, a point C.S. Lewis was wise enough to stress -- but we agree as a community to grant each other equal rights in respect to the legal system and the process by which we choose lawmakers and executives. That's democracy. Now of course you can also get there from monotheism, but it's an embarrassing display of bad faith for Chesterton to quietly erase the historical origins of democracy in the western world in yet another attempt to cram his doctrines down other people's throats.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7739469", "title": "Non-Believers", "user": "miles_l", "content": "How do you deal with those who don't believe what you believe? Yet you are required to work with them? What suggestions in occult material is there?\nRecently had an interview for a different position at work. Didn't do well. Was good though because it popped in to my head what my problem with interviews are. It is the fact that I thought everyone was in on the fact of how useless they are. I was shocked to find out that those interviewing me truly believed that an interview is the best way to find who is the best for a skills based job. I thought it had been known for decades that an interview uses different skills than those used on the job.\nIt showed me how much I have been using alternative methods to not deal with these sorts of situations. So I was shocked by real people believing what is logical to me and many others. Though I guess the same question could be used for politics, I would like to keep it out of there.\nThank you for any suggestions you and the commentor's might give. For some reason this really has my head spinning.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7760717", "title": "Re: Non-Believers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I assume that most people don't agree with me, and just take that as one of those facts of life. That forces me to think about what I believe and what they believe, and to pay attention to the places where I need to work with their belief system.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7739725", "title": "Astrological Prediction of Coronavirus", "user": "smj", "content": "Hello JMG\nDoes this pandemic appear in any of the analyses you've posted over the past few months? If I'm not mistaken, the closest prediction was drought and crop failure in southern Asia, from the solar eclipse of 26 Dec.\nSMJ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7760973", "title": "Re: Astrological Prediction of Coronavirus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In fact, I predicted an epidemic in east Asia in the January 10 lunar eclipse chart. Here's the passage:\n\"The Moon afflicted in the 8th house is a sign of difficulty, predicting increased mortality in the population; this could be something as simple as an unusually bad influenza season, or it might indicate an epidemic of some more serious kind.\"\nNext time that occurs, I'll know that it has to be taken even more seriously than I thought back then!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7795021", "title": "Re: Astrological Prediction of Coronavirus", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The Brexit post got it too.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7797837", "title": "Re: Astrological Prediction of Coronavirus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "True enough!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7800653", "title": "Re: Astrological Prediction of Coronavirus", "user": "smj", "content": "In your analyses you only mention it in passing - is it not clear from the charts that it would be as major as it is?", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7741773", "title": "birds", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Strange question perhaps, but do know of any deity associated with birds? As an avid birdwatcher I'm wondering if there's any offering I could make to send good wishes to the birds (beyond the obvious physical ones I already do of food, housing, trying to protect habitat)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7761229", "title": "Re: birds", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Welsh deity Rhiannon, who appears in the first and third branches of the Mabinogion, is associated with birds, and has\nthree magical birds\nwhose song can wake the dead and put the living to sleep. Might be worth considering.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7775053", "title": "Re: birds", "user": "dfr1973", "content": "Odin's ravens; Hera's peacock, Zeus disguised Himself as a swan; didn't the Morrigan have battle ravens also?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7742285", "title": "some random questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. Does a person's body have an egregore separate from their soul? It strikes me that an egregore might be considered a sort of bottom-up origination of consciousness, so that you get a group-mind for Catholicism, or the U.S., or beauty pageants or what have you. But reincarnation, as laid out by Dion Fortune, points to a top-down organization, meaning a person's subtle bodies have organized a body of matter for incarnation on this plane.\nCan these two modes coexist, or is it one or the other?\n2. Regarding the recent discussion of the difference between mage, mystic and occultist, it seems like it would be prudent for the devotee of any one path to spend at least a little time developing the virtues of the other two.\nFor instance, Aleister Crowley may have had power, but he certainly seemed to lack wisdom. A person who prioritizes love but never develops power may run the risk of being exploited by those of malicious intent.\n3. Are the solar and telluric currents, or anything like them, available to souls in the afterlife? Or is it only while living that a person can tap into these powers?\nThanks,\nCliff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7761485", "title": "Re: some random questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The body doesn't have an egregor, but the etheric body fills something like the same role.\n2) That was certainly what Dion Fortune recommended.\n3) Depends on the nature of your afterlife. Many people spend the after-death state in something like a dreaming state, and so they don't have the chance to tap into much of anything, except subconsciously. With spiritual development it becomes possible to retain consciousness in the after-death state, and the possibilities broaden considerably.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7763533", "title": "Re: some random questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) What sort of practices are helpful for retaining consciousness in the afterlife?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7771213", "title": "Re: some random questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Regular meditation in this life, so that you develop your mental sheath into a mental body. If you have the talent for astral projection, that's also helpful.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7742541", "title": "Astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there anything in a chart that suggests the potency of a given effect? I know the phrase 'the stars do not compel' implies only an increased probability of any given event predicted by any given astrological alignment or position.\nI've been suitably impressed in that, for the past few years, you have demonstrated that likelihood subsequent events and trends can be successfully mapped onto and predicted by mundane charts far more reliably than any of the prognostications made by the Expert Pundits and Knowledgeable Columnists promoted by the major news media sources. I note the said events and trends were, in and of themselves neither particularly improbable nor of particular historical noteworthiness in their import.\nWhereas the effects predicted by the recent Eclipse Chart seems to be, well, off the charts. 'Economic effects' is putting it a bit mildly. Is there something about this particular alignment that might have suggested this degree of disruption?\nBruce\nRenaissance Man", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7755085", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm inclined to think this is one of Pluto's \"parting gifts.\" We're approaching the Saturn opposition of the demotion chart (Feb. 2022), and there's a parallel with Pluto's \"welcome gift\" of the First World War during the converse Saturn opposition of the discovery chart (~Sept. 1915).  That it happens in close proximity with a Mars-Jupiter-Saturn-Pluto conjunction doesn't help.\n- Barrigan", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7761741", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the reasons I've been working so hard with mundane astrology is that we don't know a lot of the fine details of mundane interpretation. The lunar eclipse chart certainly came true in a much more dramatic fashion than I was expecting! Still, let's see what conditions are like in early May, when the eclipse effects are over.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7744077", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does the occult philosophy have a solution for the Fermi Paradox?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7762765", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Fermi Paradox isn't a paradox at all. It's a proof that limitless technological progress is impossible. Set it out in a syllogism:\nMajor Premise: If limitless technological progress were possible, then we would see evidence of advanced extraterrestrial civilizations elsewhere in space.\nMinor Premise: We do not see evidence of advanced extraterrestrial civilizations elsewhere in space.\nConclusion: Therefore, limitless technological progress is impossible.\nThe only reason this isn't obvious to most people is that our culture has blind faith in the possibility of limitless technological progress, so people flail around for ways to justify that faith and avoid noticing what's right in front of their faces, for all the world like Creationists trying to scrape together reasons to keep believing that the world was made in 4004 BC.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7769421", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Their limitless technological progress, being limitless, has allowed them to hide all evidence of their existence from us.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7771981", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Using exactly the same logic, I can prove that there's a small shoggoth perched on top of your head at this moment. It's a special kind of shoggoth, you see -- invisible, intangible, odorless, and weightless. Prove me wrong!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7773261", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can’t prove you’re wrong because you’re right.  She’s been there for years.  Actually I quite enjoy her company , except when she drops cheese-polenta crumbs in my hair.\nYou’re making the same point I was making.  This Fermi paradox is insoluble unless you set limits at the start.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7781453", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The Fermi Paradox is only a paradox if all its premises are true. The obvious \"solution\" to the \"paradox\" is that one or more of its premises are false, and by far the most likely candidates are those premises which assume without evidence that interstellar travel can be made possible and viable.\nSolutions that try to reconcile all the premises by tacking on further premises, like the premise that all advanced alien civilizations are purposefully hiding their existence from us, are also possible but far less plausible because they rely on more unproven assumptions.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7745613", "title": "Infectious diseases and preventative magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Assuming that there was some terrible infectious disease at some point in the future, what emergency magic would you recommend to boost ones immune system and prevent disease?  What long term practices would ensure that one was in the best place etherically and physically to avoid illness?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7763789", "title": "Re: Infectious diseases and preventative magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't try to use a saw to pound nails or a hammer to cut lengths of lumber! If you want to boost your immune system and prevent disease, there are plenty of sources for good information on that, and they don't have much to do with magic. (Remember that magic was very popular in the 14th century, and the Black Death still happened.) That's not to say that magic is useless -- it's to say that there are better ways to build up your natural immunity and preserve yourself against infection.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7747149", "title": "Prayer Requests", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Can you recommend a good general blessing to use when people ask for prayers for their situations?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7764045", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm -- I don't happen to have one to mind. Anyone else?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7778125", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Both of these are deeply Christian, the first is Catholic/Orthodox.\nWe fly to thy protection, O Holy Mother of God.  Do not despise our petitions in our necessities, but in thy mercy hear and answer us.\nAlmighty God, the fountain of all wisdom, who knowest our necessities before we ask and our ignorance in asking: Have compassion, we beseech thee, upon our infirmities, and those things which for our unworthiness we dare not, and for our blindness we cannot ask, mercifully give us for the worthiness\nof thy Son Jesus Christ our Lord, who liveth and reigneth with thee and the Holy Spirit, one God, now and for ever.\nSamChevre", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7773517", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "emmanuelg", "content": "Are you asking for an all-purpose, covers-all-situations general blessing?  I'm not sure that such a blessing is a good idea.  Indeed, it may not always be a good idea to offer, or give, a blessing as for example \"O Lord, keep our gang members safe as they go forth to murder the members of the other gang.\"  When you bless, you take on some of the suffering of another person.  It may move you to help in ways you have not forseen.\nThat said, I have a very few general blessings for specific situations.  For example, a blessing for a new baby;\n\"May the grandchildren of this child\nTell their grandchildren\nWonderful stories about your life.\"\nThis one came to me as a blessing for a young Mom who was not sure she wanted a baby, but decided to have it anyway.  It sometimes seems to apply to other new babies--I don't use it for every baby I know of...\nAs you pray, you may find revealed to you a specific blessing that would help that person with their particular problem.  Go with the flow..", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7780941", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Interesting - what I have in mind is when people ask for prayers for friends/family members, usually because they're going through an illness, grieving, lost a job, that sort of thing, would you avoid giving a general blessing (maybe that's not quite the right word) for that sort of thing? My thought was that it doesn't take too much for me to give a quick prayer when people ask for these, and maybe just have a standard formula to wish people that I don't really know well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7775309", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The four immeasurables can easily be readdressed to an individual:\nMay  have happiness and the causes of happiness.\nMay  be free from suffering and the causes of suffering.\nMay  rejoice in the well-being of others.\nMay  rest in equanimity, free from attachment and aversion to those near and far.\n(from\nMay all beings have happiness and the causes of happiness.\nMay all beings be free from suffering and the causes of suffering.\nMay all beings rejoice in the well-being of others.\nMay all beings rest in equanimity, free from attachment and aversion to those near and far.\n)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7780685", "title": "Re: Prayer Requests", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Ha, yes, that is the general one I use now! Left over from when I used to practice Buddhism years ago. Always found it interesting in that, from what I understand, that these (the Brahma Viharas) are the one meditation that the Buddha incorporated into his teachings pretty much unchanged from yogic practices he had learned. Apparently recommended them to monks meditating in forests who felt threatened by malevolent spirits.\nI was wondering if there was anything like this in any of the esoteric traditions of the West. The only thing that comes to mind that's even close, I think from Wayne Dyer or Marianne Williamson, who recommended just imagining the person bathed in white light and wishing them well.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7750477", "title": "SOP versions - follow up", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nI have been busy trying out the DMH Elemental Cross as a replacement for the SOP opener you presented here. May I check a few details please?\n1. Arm position: the rays of light are at right angles meeting at the solar plexus. Am I correct that the arms however are angled downwards (first with bent elbows, then straightened) so that the hands reach the horizontal light rays (first with palm up so the light crosses the palm, then palm forward with arm at same angle), and so that the body and arms form something like the Awen symbol?\n2. Apologies if this has been covered elsewhere: the blog SOP says to imagine white light descending from infinite space, and I have assumed the sphere itself is supposed to be white in that version. The DMH instructions say to imagine golden light rays from the sun overhead. Are the small spheres in the third eye and solar plexus area golden too, and finally what of the sphere of protection itself? It would seem odd to have them different colours, but I have always thought the closing SOP itself is always white.\nI've done a few performances already and I think it is more powerful for me than the other version.\nMany thanks,\nMorfran.\nP.s. @ Maxine Rogers: thank you for your encouragement last week to try the Circulation of Light. I have been picturing it in my head and I believe will manage it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7764301", "title": "Re: SOP versions - follow up", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that's correct.\n2) In the DMH, the elemental cross is done in golden light throughout, including the little spheres, but the sphere formed in the closing is pure white.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7750733", "title": "Enhancing Memory", "user": "brianantbur", "content": "Greetings, Mr. Greer. Thank you for being a light in these dark times.\nI was recently reading about Near Death Experiences, and noted the consistency of Life Reviews and how vivid they are. Which made me wonder, is there a set of practices that would allow you to review, in vivid detail, any moment of your present life? Meditation comes to mind, but I have not found a set of medications that focus on reliving a memory. Have you, Mr. Greer, ever come across such a practice? Would a natural magic potion, imbued with herbs that enchance memory, facilitate reliving a memory?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7764557", "title": "Re: Enhancing Memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. That's not something I've experimented with, so I don't know; ordinary memory has always served my purposes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7782733", "title": "Re: Enhancing Memory", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Not related to magic, but this reminded me of an exercise from Dominic O' Brien's memory training. In his books on mnemonic techniques, he includes some exercises like these to experiment with different facets of memory.\nThe steps he laid out for this one (\"Time Travel\")\n- Choose some specific starting point from your past, like a school playground, a museum, and attic, a corner of a garden, and try to picture little details of the space involved\n- Try to recall people connected to this place, their voices, the way they laughed, certain mannerisms\n- Try to recapture the sounds you once heard in this place, a squeaky door, a train that would pass by, children playing outside, music that played at the time. Then smells, like soil, fresh flowers, polished wood. Then how the surroundings felt to touch, stone walls, iron gates, fabric coverings, etc.\n- Try to remember your emotional state at the time: generally happy, melancholy, carefree, unsure, in love, etc.\nSee what memories arise as you choose different spaces from your past, and focus on them through the sense impressions that you had.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7754573", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For the cell salt experiment, you kindly offered to let me know which cell salts I would need to take if I let you know my birth day and year - it's the 25th of May. I re-posted this query in case you weren't checking the older post, I hope you don't mind. Thanks in advance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7765069", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No trouble at all -- and I'm still checking on both posts. Your natal sun is in the first ten degrees of Gemini, so the cell salts you need are:\nKali Mur. 2, Calc. Fluor. 3, Mag. Phos. 3, Kali Sulph. 1", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7754829", "title": "Dragons", "user": "alexandermarcus", "content": "Good Afternoon JMG,\nI have recently been pondering the dragons from the rising dragons exercise (from the Druid Magic Handbook and the Dolmen Arch) and the currents they represent, and have a few questions:\n1. Do the dragons and the spear have a set of correspondences in the Microcosm and Macrocosm the same way that each of the cantrefs do? Are the dragons and spear the same kind of things as the cantrefs?\n2. I've been given reason to suspect that my dragons - whatever it is they correspond to in my person - are blocked, or perhaps misdirected. Precisely I was told that they are eager to help but need to be given jobs.\na) what do the dragons correspond to in the person?\nb) what kind of jobs are appropriate for them?\n3. I would like to learn *a lot* more about the dragons and the spear.\na) If I were to scry the spear and dragons, what method and portal might I use? (I'm familiar with the method of scrying from the Druid Magic Handbook)\nb) What sources do you recommend for studying the topic of the spear and dragons? I'm not exclusively interested in the Celtic version, as I know the same symbols/process occur in many cultures.\nI feel I am on the edge of falling into something significant here, so any push you can give me would be much appreciated.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7765837", "title": "Re: Dragons", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'll want to read, study, and meditate on the story of Lludd and Llefellys from the\nMabinogion\nand the story of Merlin from Geoffrey of Monmouth's\nHistory of the Kings of Britain\n. Beyond that, why, you're stepping onto ground that hasn't been adequately explored in centuries, as far as I know. The information you have is pretty much the information I have -- so the quest is before you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7755341", "title": "Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI just  recently realised that Neptune is aquarius ruler. I was never particularly interested in astrology, and had this ideia that my ruller was Saturn. Was it ever? When did it change an why?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7766605", "title": "Re: Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, the modern ruler of Aquarius is Uranus, not Neptune. The discovery of a new planet is a major event in astrological terms; it doesn't happen by accident. It marks the appearance of a new factor in human consciousness and the broader energetics of the solar system. Saturn ruled Aquarius until Uranus was discovered in 1781, just as Jupiter ruled Pisces until Neptune was discovered in 1846.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7768909", "title": "Re: Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) Do new planets affect the fay like they affect us?\nb) Do we have any way to tell whether planetary discoveries affect other planets? Ex, did Uranus come into focus on Mars at the same time as on Earth?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7772493", "title": "Re: Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "a) You'd have to ask the fay.\nb) You'd have to ask the Martians. In both cases, the necessary experiences haven't yet been recorded and studied.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7772749", "title": "Re: Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) How do I contact the fay?\nb) How do I contact the Martians?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7777869", "title": "Re: Aquarius ruller planet", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My point.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7759437", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do you think about \"The Illuminatus!\" trilogy by Robert Shea and Robert Anton Wilson?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7766861", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've still got the paperback copies I bought when it first came out. It's enormous fun, and a great satire on conspiracy theory.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7761997", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can Sufism be categorized under \"Western tradition\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7767117", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on how you define the label \"Western tradition,\" of course. Definitions vary.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7762253", "title": "Druidic Fall", "user": "alexandermarcus", "content": "Last week (\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/81345.html?thread=7583169#cmt7583169\n) you observed that druid revival cosmology doesn't map on to the exitus-reditus schema. I'm wondering: what's the closest equivalent in druid revival cosmology to a myth of the Fall?\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7767373", "title": "Re: Druidic Fall", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There isn't one. In Druidry we don't fall, we rise.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7765325", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been thinking about this would be high risk if I got the coronavirus, with medical issues in three different categories that are considered risky by themselves.\nFor years I have been comfortable and accepting about many of the things to do with death that still scare most other middle aged people. It's usually the elderly who see these things the way I do.\nBut there's one thing that still bothers me a lot: what certain people, whom I'd much prefer to survive, would say about me, being unfairly represented, and especially the way that things like that now get a much wider audience because everyone is online and because even minor news is online, like news reports about local individuals who died.\nI know it is just a small fraction of time in the greater scheme of things. I am comfortable with drifting away into the sands of history or being, if people still try to do family trees in 200 years time, just a name that I never even liked much myself.\nBut for maybe 40 or 50 years, if I were to die soon, there will be a few people who knew me, and, via them, information that's unfair and wrong out there saying, more and more occasionally as time goes on, stuff about me to others, and I won't still be around to at least not seem like the kind of person they are describing. This really bothers me. I always think carefully about the reputations of the dead and that they are rarely as simple as they seem, so I try to do my best by others about this.\nIf I died when I was older and had sorted a few more of these things, or outlived some of these people, or it happened decades in the future when fewer people were using the web, that would be better. But I think it's a good idea to be at peace with it anyway even when knowing people will talk. It can only be psychologically beneficial. I have spent years thinking about it already and it hasn't changed much, when many other things that bothered me have changed over that time", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7767629", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not at all sure what to say about this. If that bothers you, it bothers you -- but I have to say that what people might think of me after I'm dead is not something I can imagine worrying about.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7771469", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.\nIf there is anyone reading who has come to terms with this, especially people who aren't very elderly (with many contemporaries already passed away), it would be great to hear from them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7774541", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "emmanuelg", "content": "You could write an autobiography, and tell your side of the story.  Thanks to their autobiographies, I know a great deal about one of my great-grandparents and the outline of another one's life.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7781965", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you. That crossed my mind a while after I posted and it helps to see it affirmed. Explaining some things might involve making public things I wouldn't want to, if it went online. But to write down my side of stuff seems like the most logical solution.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7765581", "title": "Mentats!", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "JMG,\na few years ago you were talking about training real-world Mentats.\nCould you remind me what the proposed training was? I remember formal logic and rhetoric and also general knowledge of history and other bodies of knowledge.\nIf I had to guess it would also include Discursive Meditation and the Art of Memory. From the point of view of occult philosophy, would such practices potentially lead to personal enlightenment? Or is it insufficient?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7768397", "title": "Re: Mentats!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The foundation of the training would include the art of memory and discursive meditation, so the mentat would be able to think quickly and clearly with plenty of raw mental material at hand. Exactly what subjects of knowledge the mentat should learn, on that foundation, would have to be worked out on the basis of experience; there are some kinds of knowledge that seem to make people stupid when they deal with anything outside their specialty -- many modern sciences seem to have that effect -- and those should be excluded. Experts can be consulted on such issues; the mentat is a synthesist, drawing together information from every relevant source.\nSuch practices would not lead to personal enlightenment, and might in fact get in the way. If you want enlightenment, seek enlightenment; if you want to be a mentat, that's a different kettle of pundi rice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7770701", "title": "Re: Mentats!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is a mentat?\nAccording to spellcheck, it’s a “Me Tater.”  🙄", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7773005", "title": "Re: Mentats!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "https://dune.fandom.com/wiki/Mentat", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7774029", "title": "Re: Mentats!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah.  I got bored with Dune when matters came to a screeching halt after the hero fell in love.  I remember him worrying that it would not end well and thinking “Dude, you are so right!  Get back to battling the intriguing villain!”\nThe villain was Baron Somebody and thoroughly vile.  I was really enjoying him and then the writer dumped him to focus on the hero’s GF.  Grrr.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7776333", "title": "Re: Mentats!", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "Well as for what I personally want, I want to become aware of the higher planes of existence, so I can participate in them more fully and consciously. I think that falls more on the enlightenment side of things. Though being able to think clearly and quickly is also a nice thing to have.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7766349", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why would someone want to be a magician?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7769677", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To borrow a quote from Louis Armstrong, \"Man, if you gotta ask, you ain't ever gonna know.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7767885", "title": "Geomancy and Lesson Plans", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With the plague abroad in the land, the schools are closed, and so we began homeschooling today. I started Reading Class with my 8 year old with the story of Thor and Loki traveling to Jotunheim. He liked it, so we're doing another story about Loki tomorrow.\nThinking ahead in my lesson planning I did a Geomancy on the 9th house question, \"Would it be appropriate for me (1) and my kid (5) to make an offering to Thor together (9)\"?\n1. Populus\n2. Conjunctio\n3. Rubeus\n4. Populus\n5. Populus\n6. Conjunctio\n7. Rubeus\n8. Populus\n9. Conjunctio\n10. Rubeus\n11. Conjunctio\n12. Rubeus\nI read this as not especially positive or negative, though Rubeus participating in the translation made me pause. Would you go ahead with it, or no?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7776845", "title": "Re: Geomancy and Lesson Plans", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, let's review the basics. In a house chart, if you have a mode of perfection connecting the significators, the answer is yes; if not, the answer is no. Do you have a mode of perfection connecting the significators? Yes, Populus is your significator and that of your son, and it springs to the 8th house, into conjunction with the 9th, the significator of Thor. Meanwhile Thor's significator, Conjunctio, springs to the 2nd and 6th houses, into conjunction with your significator and that of your son. Meanwhile, Rubeus -- what color is Thor's beard? -- makes a translation by appearing in the 10th house (next to Thor's significator) and the 12th house (next to your significator). That is to say, you've got three different ways of saying \"YES!\"  If you see that as not especially positive or negative, all I can say is that you're a difficult person to please...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7769165", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nThank you once again for another Magic Monday.\nI'm currently working on lesson 7 in LRM and I've been doing the meditation that involves the sentence \"Out of the  One comes the Two; out of the Two comes the Three; and out of the Three comes the One as the Fourth.\" Connecting the numbers to the Sephiroth on the Tree of Life, one thing that struck me is that it seems to imply that the lower Sephiroth are recapitulations or \"higher octaves\" of the three Supernals. I would make the following assignments: Kether = the One, Chokmah = the Two, Binah = the Three, and Chesed = the One as the Fourth, implying that Chesed is a higher octave of Kether, Geburah is a higher octave of Chokmah, and so on. This would imply that Sephiroth 1,4,7,10 - 2,5,8 - and 3,6,9 are intimately related somehow. For the first sequence, the close relationship of Kether (1) to Malkuth (10) appears to be corroborated by Dion Fortune, who says \"Kether is the Malkuth of the Unmanifest.\" Others, however, appear more difficult, in particular the relationship between Binah (3) and Tiphareth (6), Binah being associated with limitation and form, while Tiphareth is the center of the Redeemer. The former I would associate with natural selection, the latter with mercy and forgiveness, and so it does not seem to follow that \"Out of the Five comes the Three as the Sixth.\" I probably have some work ahead of me to figure that one out.\nDoes this seem like a worthwhile train of thought, or am I spinning my wheels?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7783245", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A good solid meditation. Take it as much further as you can.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7770189", "title": "Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have a couple of questions about memory methods.\nI've been reading 'Memory Craft' by Lynne Kelly and working out some exercises based on it. By the way, I could wholeheartedly recommend this book to anyone who is looking for an extremely accessible and practical introduction into a variety of memorisation techniques. It includes the classical memory palaces but also there is a good number of techniques from oral and semi literate cultures that Lynne has studied, tried out, and presented in her book. All with numerous lively examples of how one would approach using these techniques to memorise information.\nSo trying on some of these methods I feel a bit strange about some of them. So here are the questions:\n1. One of the methods is using one's body as a memory palace. Every part of the body could be assigned to memorise a particular concept through usual means - colourful characters that stand out enough to be memorable on their own but also engaged into activities that are hard to forget. The usual guidelines is to put something as violent, sexual, outrageous, disgusting, or all of those combined as possible - the stronger the emotional response the better. For me, placing these images around my body would be an excellent way to memorise - visualising for me is more like tactilising (or kinaestethising...) and body awareness exercises were always easy for me generally speaking. However, I don't think I would feel good about placing some images associated with strong emotions into my body. I can imagine that remembering the 7 deadly sins by placing images of them around one's body and reviving them from time to time to keep the memory alive could produce some rather unpleasant results. Or is there a safe way of doing that? And if it is indeed risky... Let's say I memorise the same 7 deadly sins by walking around my neighbourhood and visualising, as vividly as possible, emotionally disturbing examples of these sins in people's front yards. Wouldn't it be risky too? Or what would be the way of using a place for a memory without affecting the place?\n2. I'm thinking of building an imaginary memory palace to remember all the correspondences of the Tree of Life. More than that, I would love to go through all my notes and map some of the records into this palace. It would also be possible to memorise the events of the Pathworkings and the meditations after them using this palace. The idea I have is to build 10 round rooms connected by corridors, basically replicating the diagram of the Tree of Life as a building or, possibly, a natural setting. The question is, wouldn't the work of building such a memory palace (and traversing it later when recalling different parts of it) get in the way of the actual work through the initiatory system I'm trying to commit to memory? Or is visiting the memory places of such a palace not going to be problematic without all the ritual setting and intentions of Pathworkings and visits to the Spheres?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7770957", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Oh the joys of living down under! I see that I missed the window for this Magic Monday questions. I have this message saved and I will post it again next Monday.\n:}", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7777101", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, you haven't -- it was 8:50 pm my time when you posted this. I'll get an answer up for you after dinner.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7778893", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Oh I see, I mistook the UTC timestamp on the post for your local time.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7784013", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you're going to memorize the seven deadly sins at all, put even more energy into memorizing the seven corresponding virtues. The best way to make sure that concentration on negative influences doesn't become problematic is to do it much less often than concentration on positive influences.\n2) Quite the contrary, doing that will help lay additional groundwork for the initiatory system. I can say this with confidence because I did exactly that while originally learning the Tree of Life, and had excellent results.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7786573", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "1. I was giving 7 deadly sins more as an example of something that would be helped by grotesque and possibly violent imagery. I am interested if placing such an image onto a body part or somewhere in the house would produce an unwanted change there. For example, if I decide to use my body to remember everything I could about the figures of Geomancy and, more specifically, my head to store vivid images of intoxication, deception, and cruelty associated with Coch. There is obviously more to Coch than that but it still feels that it's probably not the best of ideas to have it done this way. I would also feel bad about populating someone's frontyard with scenes representing Coch. Or is there a way to utilise this imagery just for the sake of memory without inviting the corresponding energies into the place where they are visualised?\n2. This is really good to know. Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7788365", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1. Coch has positive as well as negative aspects; meditate on the figure until you can find them. Remember that you can also use puns and other indirect ways of indicating things -- for example, \"violins\" as a pun for \"violence.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7790157", "title": "Re: Safety precautions with memory methods", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "1. Thank you. This makes sense.\nI'm still interested though to what extent the images that are formed for memorisation can affect the energy of the place where they are visualised.\nIf someone would use their living room to memorise the history of Auschwitz, and they were of a materialistic bend with no reservations about what that could do to the energy of the room, would they invite the vibe of a concentration camp into their house?", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7771725", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been considering the issue of historical astrology, and how the very old sources treat Venus differently from current ones. What's occurred to me is that Earth's influences during the Age of Pisces and Age of Aquarius would be subtly different, and the same thing could apply to other planets. This is likely extremely theoretical, but do you know if there are ways to look into this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7784269", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Move to another planet, stay there for 2,160 years, and take notes? Other than that, I can't think of one.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7785549", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "About what I figured. Although it might not take the full length of time: it would presumably be based on the precision of the local equinoxes. Maybe in a post-human existence I can follow up on it.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7776589", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI've been trying out the little ritual where I water element banishing symbol over a glass of water and then mentally infusing it with golden light. Immediately upon drinking the water I feel a sudden boost of energy and the water itself has a bit of a \"sweet\" taste. Are these  probably just placebo effects or does this simple ritual have very concrete affects like that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7784525", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Simple rituals done with focus and intention can very easily have effects like that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7778381", "title": "Tried & True Defenses Against Fear", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nIt occurred to me just a minute ago that it’s magic Monday and that I ought to come on here and ask you a question. Then, instead, I thought, “Why not go over to counterpunch first and see what they have to say about current events?” Lo and behold, I click on the first link that appears interesting and you are mentioned in it!\nhttps://www.counterpunch.org/2020/03/13/four-reasons-civilization-wont-decline-it-will-collapse/\nPerhaps you knew already, but there it is, in case you didn’t.\nAnyway, what are some of your favorite magical responses to disarm the cold clutches of dread and fear?\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7785805", "title": "Re: Tried & True Defenses Against Fear", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. I'm going to pour a good solid glass of something alcoholic after I close down Magic Monday, and raise it to celebrate victory. If Counterpunch has been forced to argue against me, citing me by name and trotting out all the standard canned talking points that people have been trying to use to prop up apocalyptic fantasies for years now -- well, I recall Gandhi's famous line: \"First they ignore you, they they laugh at you, then they fight you, then you win.\" They're fighting me now. The sequel follows promptly.\nSeriously, I'd like to thank all my readers and commenters for their support and encouragement over the years. This is one very, very sweet moment for me.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7786061", "title": "Re: Tried & True Defenses Against Fear", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As for fear, read or watch something really funny. That's the best cure I know.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7779405", "title": "servitors and Tulpamancy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Archdruid.\nI've been reading about the extremely popular occult practice of creating servitors and Tulpas. I once asked you what you thought about this practice and you said that these \"beings\" were traditionally called life sparks. That is to say that a mage would take a spark from the fire of their life and imbue it with a specific intent.\nI've noticed that many of the younger generation of occultists pointedly ignore the warnings about the creation of tulps and servitors, and use them to specifically create a being to help them fulfill their desires.\nThe process of imbuing these sparks with intent involves giving the spark a way to interact with the physical plane. I find that particularly dangerous because the tulpa doesn't exist on the physical plane outside of the creators body, yet many practitioners have reported successes - such as gaining access to wealth they didn't earn, or information that was secured out of their reach.\nThe only thing I can think of that accounts for these successes is that tulpas are interacting with the subtle-bodies of other people, ones who have no ritual defenses, and influencing them to act on the physical plane. If this is the case, what that means is that the creators of the tulpas are essentially violating the selfdom of other beings without their knowledge or permission. The karmic blow back from these actions are going to be intense.\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7790413", "title": "Re: servitors and Tulpamancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's very likely what's going on, and yeah, the blowback won't be pretty.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7781197", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can you recommend some texts or perhaps books on discursive meditation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7788621", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My book\nThe Druidry Handbook\nhas an extensive chapter on it. One of these days, time permitting, I want to do a really thorough book on the subject, but that hasn't happened yet.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7781709", "title": "Quick OIW Clarification", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Need a quick clarification on how the sign of the Bounty of Nature is formed from the Ritual of the OIW in the CGD. I'm having trouble picturing how the left arm is situated.\nWhen the text states \"Extend your left hand down and out to your side in a straight line, hand extended...\" does this mean my left arm needs to be pointed straight down parallel to my legs or is it held away from the side at some angle?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7788877", "title": "Re: Quick OIW Clarification", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Held away from the side at a 45° angle. That's what \"down and out to your side\" is meant to communicate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7791693", "title": "Re: Quick OIW Clarification", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7782221", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening, JMG! I think I'm near the cutoff point so I'll try to be brief.\n1) I'm practicing the SOP using the names of Jesus and- so far I'm only up to the calling of Air - and wondering why you assigned The Good Shepherd to Spitit Below and the Lamb of God to Spirit Above. To me the image of a watchful shepherd giving his life for those in his care seems better suited to the idea of Spirit Above giving life to the world below it, while the Lamb of God, referring to Jesus's humbling and death would seem to align with Spirit Below. Is there something I'm misunderstanding about the nature of Spirit Above vs. Below or do you think I could safely try these with the opposite attributions?\n2) I've also been re-reading Psychic Self-Defense and I'm struck by how often Fortune describes material manifestations - windows and boards cracking, people being flung around the room, etherix projections carrying tangible weight, etc. Inbyour experience, is this kind of thing typical for advanced practitioners of occultism? Have you experienced projection of the etheric double?\nThanks as always for your answers!\n- Fred N", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7789133", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can certainly reverse the two if you think it fits better. I'm by no means a specialist in Christian symbolism.\n2) I've experienced some things that brushed against material manifestation, but nothing quite that dramatic! As for the projection of the etheric double, I've done it using a specific Golden Dawn formula, the creation of an animal body of transformation -- the reality behind the legends of shapeshifting. (The formula's covered in my book\nCircles of Power\n.) It was really quite weird.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7783501", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm not sure it's quite magic, or not consciously, but it's done by a person who had dabbled with occultism in the past, and it feels like it has some power, a phrase on a social media page that would really get under the target's skin to make him feel targeted. In a way that would sound woo to non-occultists. It's not on the target's own page so he can't delete it.\nWhat can be done magically against this aside from trying to avoid the page, in question?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7789389", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Write the phrase in soft pencil on a piece of toilet paper, use it for its intended purpose, and flush it with the rest of the mess. I mean this quite literally. Repeat if necessary. You'll be startled by how effective that is.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7785037", "title": "SOP, yoga and misc questions.", "user": "open_space", "content": "1) I think I recall you saying something along these lines but wanted to double check. Is the SoP safe to do with balancing pranayamas used for Hatha yoga? For example alternate nostril breathing or rhythmic breathing? If I understand correctly this helps settle the suttle body instead of circulating energy like visualizing kundalini rising. The yoga group I am part of is starting to grow in the US and a lot of them are interested in occultism so I thought I would give a try to the SOP and see how it relates to my practice to have some first hand knowledge. My practice doesn’t involve circulating energy or working with kundalini or concentrating on the chakras for example so I think it should be ok. Per what I understand the problem happens when two practices circulate energy in two different ways the cause a Prana depletion on some key points like the issue you had on the kidneys a while ago. Maybe akin to try to move water from a river in two different directions that leaves some ponds without water? I’ve heard the recommendation of keeping an eye on my energy levels like having a decreased sense of general vitality or the extreme opposite correct?\n2 ) My other question involves karmic entanglement in relationships. I think that the way our current society treats borders and boundaries has gotten into our minds, it definitely got into mine. I am happy to say a daily affirmation is working wonderfully to take care of that! How does one avoid getting karma from our daily interactions? For example I assume if advise is not phrased as an option or suggestion but rather as an instruction one would share some of the Karma from the results from such advice?\n3-. Is the family tie, energetically or karmically speaking particularly stronger than other ties? For example if one member of the family has some issues that originate from toxic interactions in the family and the rest of the family members start working on the things that helped caused those issues and start working spiritually on themselves would that help rise up the stumbling member indirectly too? Maybe some group directed prayer can help as well? Collective affirmations between the family members?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7789645", "title": "Re: SOP, yoga and misc questions.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that should be safe. The Golden Dawn used to teach alternate-nostril pranayama, and ordinary rhythmic breathing is part of every Western magical system I know of. Yes, keeping an eye on energy levels in both directions is a very good idea.\n2) That's not an easy question to answer! Since the Sanskrit word\nkarma\n, literally means \"action,\" we create karma every time we do anything at all; the important thing is to approach our actions in the world from a spiritual perspective, and use them where possible to bring blessing and healing to all. The Bhagavad Gita has quite a bit to say about this, for what it's worth.\n3) Yes, very much so. All living things share one life, but the closer the connection -- of blood, or of love -- the more of the One Life flows between those who share that connection. The important thing is not to try to force the troubled family member to do anything -- that way lies trouble. If everyone else in the family works on their own issues and maintains healthy loving boundaries, the troubled one will receive the guidance he or she needs indirectly, and will be able to act freely in response.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7787597", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey, JMG and all.\nTSW data point.\nI have started doing geomantic readings and charging 100 mxn (around 5 bucks). The problem is finding clients.\nSo last night I did a ceremony invoking Mercury with the hexagram ritual, and reading his orphic hymn off of The Art and Practice of Geomancy. I gotta say, the rhyming verses in those versions made a huge difference in the power of the ceremony, despite me normally doing my rituals in Spanish.\nSo I invoked him and I asked him with prayer for him to send me clients.\nToday an acquaintance I haven't interacted with since 2015 asked me about these \"geomantic readings\" that I mention in my Twitter bio. He's agreed to pay for one.\nAve Mercurius!\nA book donation to a local library would be an appropriate gesture of gratitude, right?\nThanks as always.\nJP", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7789901", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Congratulations. Yes, libraries are great recipients for Mercurial charity; make sure to give it on a Wednesday during an hour of Mercury.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7791181", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "hannemaniac", "content": "Not a question so I hope it's ok to post late since it's timely. A newsletter I subscribe to included a set of cases of Covid-19 sent by an Iranian homeopath to Dr. Rajan Sankaran in India. Dr. Sankaran is one of the most well-known and respected homeopaths in the world. I've uploaded the file here\nhttps://file.io/vcI4pL\n.\nAccording to Dr. Sankaran, the genus epidemicus remedy for the Covid19 illness is Camphora. He recommends the 1M potency, available from any homeopathic pharmacy for around $10-15. The file includes instructions for both treatment and prophylaxis. A 30C potency, available at many organic food stores, would probably also work adequately but might need more repetition.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7794253", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I get a 404 page when I try to access the file. Do you know of another place online where the file can be accessed?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7802701", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hmm, I had trouble uploading it to several registration-free sites for some reason, but here's another try. I'll email it too, in case this gets taken down again. https://file.io/1zErm1", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7802957", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "hannemaniac", "content": "I don't know why that happened but I'll forward the original email.  I also\nuploaded it again here https://file.io/1zErm1.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7803469", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, I’m not the original poster but was also interested in the info.  I Googled the following, without any quotes, and was able to obtain the information that I believe the OP had in mind: rajan sankaran homeopathy covid-19.\nHope this is useful, and thanks for all you do!\nPOC in ID", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7803725", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks to all who posted links! It can also be accessed here:\nhttps://homeopathyplus.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Homeopathy-for-Coronavirus-Covid-19-Infection-Dr-Aditya-Kasariyans-and-Dr-Rajan-Sankaran.pdf", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7807309", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "hannemaniac", "content": "As a side note for those interested in obtaining this, I was unable to find Camphora 10M anywhere so far. The Indian pharmacies are probably the best bet right now. The 1M is available from Urenus, which sells on Amazon. Everywhere else I've looked is not currently stocking it.\nThe LM, or Q, potencies (LM 1, LM 2, etc.) are probably exchangeable for M and even 10M in a pinch, and I have this in my own kit already, but I went ahead and ordered the 1M from Urenus directly and via Amazon to make sure I have what Dr. Sankaran recommends on hand. Helios in the UK may stock it--they usually have literally everything--but I couldn't find it on their website.\nIn a real pinch, ANY potency of Camphora could help. Put the pellet in 4oz water, and give half a teaspoon as often as needed until there's a notable response. You can see how often that is, and continue that pattern for awhile to avoid symptoms returning in the interim. For example, if symptoms return or get worse toward the end of 2 hours, give a dose every 90 minutes. You can repeat every 5 minutes if necessary. It's much harder to overdo dosing and cause an aggravation in an acute illness, especially severe illness, which by definition is a violent reaction by the life force.\nBe sure to stir, or tap the glass on a book firmly (a canning jars with a lid works well) before each dose. That is thought to prevent the vital force adapting to the remedy, causing it to lose some efficacy. Keep it in the fridge or add a dash of high proof booze to keep the water from souring.\nA few extra tips, try to avoid treating fevers below 104°F unless there's a medical reason, as the fever itself is a great antiviral. For every degree of temperature elevation you have to increase fluid intake by at least 10% per degree. If there is sweating, double that and don't forget to add a pinch of salt. Gatorade and the like should be diluted 50%. None of this is meant as \"medical advice\", just common sense info every parent knows hopefully! (What I used to tell my patients before quitting allopathy).\nThere's anecdotal evidence, currently being tested, that chloroquine might help. Tonic water isn't what it used to be, but hey, maybe an excuse for a prophylactic G&T :d Would NOT recommend this for anyone already ill, since you don't want to be taxing your liver when acutely ill.", "replies": []}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/83179.html", "year": "2020", "month": "03", "day": "22", "time": "11-35PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt7845611", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I recently came across something called the Draconic Zodiac, using the moon's north node as 0 Aries, and found my natal chart made a lot of sense when cast with it. I strike people as having a lot of Scorpio, and yet I only have Pluto there. With the Draconic chart thought, my sun, moon, Mercury, and Venus are all in Scorpio. Do you know anything which discus Draconic charts? I'm using internet websites at the moment, and he quality is, well, about the same as most of the rest of the internet...\n2) Last week, I mentioned wanting to cut my internet use, and we discussed positive goals. Now, I spent the week mulling it over and came up with a half dozen possible goals. Am I correct to assume it's best to pick one to focus on, instead of diffusing my efforts across a few?\n3) I have a question around Pluto: I currently have Pluto transiting over my ascendant, and am hardly feeling it. On the other hand, progressions involving Pluto hit hard, and I find they fit what I'd expect to see if I treated Pluto as a full planet. This, combined with observations that astrology books in the 1930s and 1940s tend to discount Pluto, have lead me to a somewhat odd hypothesis: in the progressed charts, the status of the planets is what they were at the date the chart matches.\na) Does this sound plausible to you?\nb) Am I correct to think the best way to look into this would be looking at charts for people who were born before Pluto was discovered, and seeing if progressions to Pluto matter? Also looking at people born before 2006, but that can come later.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7845867", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I should add as well: my ascendant is not in Scorpio, nor does Pluto form any close aspects in my chart.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7846123", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't think I'd ever heard of it before. Still, on first principles, it would be a potentially interesting lunar zodiac.\n2) Yes, absolutely. The will, like sunlight, is made strong by focus and made weak by diffusion. Concentrate it like a lens on one point, and fire will be born there.\n3) Hmm! It's at least worth investigation, and yes, that would be one way to look into it. I first started doubting Pluto's status as a full planet when I went through a simultaneous Pluto transit to two important planets in my chart and nothing happened. I'll take a look at my progressed chart and see what results I get.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7846635", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Well, looking at it, it seems my Draconic natal chart gets a great deal which my tropical chart misses. So perhaps I'll have to write the book I'm looking for...\n3) Honestly, any doubts I had about Pluto's status vanished: since 2015 it's been conjunct two natal planets, opposite another, square another, and crossed into my first house! It should've destroyed me, but I barely felt it at all.\nOn the other hand, my progressed moon sextiled(!) Pluto a few months back, and I got hit with it hard....\nWell, time to start research!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7880427", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "If you want another datum:\nI have Pluto angular in Scorpio (10th house), sextile a Capricorn ascendant but making no other Ptolemaic aspects.\nOver the course of fall 2004 through winter of 2011-12, Pluto transited over Saturn, Uranus, Venus, and Neptune, but I didn't really\nnotice\nanything.  Although the Pluto-Neptune conjunction is about the time I discovered \"alternative\" media, so that might have something to do with it...\nTransiting Pluto moved into my first house in January 2013, about the time I moved out of my parents' house.\nProgressed Ascendant in Aquarius squared natal Pluto in April 2016, at about the time I was handing in my two-weeks' notice\nwithout\nanother job already lined up.\nProgressed Mercury in Capricorn sextile natal Pluto in November 2016.  Nothing significant I can think of going on in my\npersonal\nlife then.\nProgressed Moon in Taurus opposite natal Pluto in May 2017.  Nothing significant again, although a friend did die of cancer a couple months later.\nCurrently approaching a progressed Sun sextile natal Pluto, which goes exact in June.  I haven't yet\nfelt\nanything that would seem to be suggestive of this, other than minor inconveniences related to governmental responses to the current pandemic.  Doesn't mean nothing will necessarily happen.\nAs for draconic vs. tropical charts, I'm afraid I can't help with that; my natal north node actually\nis\nat 0 Aries.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7851499", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the OP): On 2), I often struggle with choosing focused goals. For example, I'd like to a) practice growing vegetables now that spring is here, b) learn more about homeopathy and/or cell salts, c) practice more music, d) keep studying Druidry, e) and read more books! Lots of goals, very little time. Is there some advice you could give to help pick one of these in order to focus on it? I suppose divination would be one method...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7861995", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Man, just saying I can really really relate to that! A core part of my learning right now is to unlearn the belief that more is better in terms of goals and accomplishments - which is basically the consumerist mindset translated to personal growth! It's very humbling, but I think it will bring good results the more I focus in and actually learn and master a few specific things, rather than \"wanting' and \"trying\" to accomplish a bunch of things, which usually leads to feelings of failure.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7866347", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Divination is a good approach. You can also simply sit with the choice for a while and see which of them is more important than the others. Finally, sheer randomness also works. The important thing is to choose one thing at a time -- it usually doesn't matter which one.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7860203", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I took a look at an ephemeris for it, and found out Uranus, Neptune, and Pluto never go retrograde in this zodiac: they never move fast enough when retrograde. That's really weird....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7898091", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder: JMG, do you think this might be a manifestation of the primal powers of those planets?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7902187", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a fine theme for meditation!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7846379", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You gave this advice once: \"Start with your own natal chart. Make sure that Mercury isn't in the signs of its detriment or fall (Pisces or Sagittarius) and that it isn't in a conjunction, square or opposition aspect with Mars or Saturn. (If it is, check to see if Jupiter is okay -- not in Gemini, Virgo or Capricorn and free of those dame aspect -- and if Jupiter's messed up, see if the Sun is free of those aspects and not in Libra or Aquarius.)\nWe'll assume that Mercury is free of those problems. (If not, substitute the name of the other planet for Mercury.) Find a day and a time when the Moon is applying to Mercury by trine or sextile, and when neither the Moon nor Mercury is part of a square or opposition aspect with any planet, or a conjunction with Mars or Saturn. That's your time to submit the manuscript.\"\nWould this be the same for releasing an album? Considering my Mercury is square Mars, and Jupiter is not in a great position, I'd use Sol... so would this mean finding a day where, for instance, the Sun is in Taurus and Moon in Cancer?\nIs having my Mercury square Mars bad?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7847147", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, music belongs to Venus, not to Mercury, so your first thing to do is see if you can get Venus in good condition (not in Aries, Scorpio, or Virgo, and not in negative aspect with Mars or Saturn), and then get the Moon applying to Venus by trine or sextile, while neither the Moon nor Venus is in square or opposition to anything or in conjunction with Mars or Saturn. That's when you release your album.\nThe Sun is also an option, Remember that it's not enough to have the Moon in the right sign; it needs to be approaching an exact aspect, not moving away from one, and within 8 degrees or so of completing the aspect, the closer the better: say, Venus is at 18° Taurus and the Moon is anywhere from 10° to 18° Cancer or Pisces, the closer the better.\nAs for your Mercury-Mars squares, squares in a natal chart are challenges. They're not \"bad\" in any simplistic sense; they represent the enduring conflicts in your life, and as you learn to cope with them, they become your core sources of strength. People who have no squares or oppositions in their natal chart tend to be kind of bland.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7846891", "title": "Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, and thanks for hosting these. I've been dealing with some writers block, and I have done the exercises that you've specifically outlined to help one deal with this issue. However, in the process of doing so, I've noticed that I often think to myself \"I have writer's block.\" So, I've been trying to replace that with the mantra \"I create.\" I believe that even if it doesn't help, then it won't hurt. Have I chosen a good mantra?\nThanks again!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7847403", "title": "Re: Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's potentially workable. You could also try something more focused like \"I've outgrown my writer's block.\"", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7850731", "title": "Re: Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear anonymous,\nI write too. Depending on your personal predilictions, you might benefit from the books of Julia Cameron and/or Dr. Eric Maisel.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7906795", "title": "Re: Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "May I ask for a link to the exercises for writers block? That could be useful for me. Thanks in advance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7913451", "title": "Re: Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The exercise is very simple. Every day, for 15 minutes by the clock, write. Do not let yourself stop writing even if all that comes out is \"I don't know what to write, my mind is completely blocked, what should I write,\" and so on. Just keep the pen moving, or your fingers going on the keyboard -- and\ndo not let yourself stop to correct anything you have written\n. Writer's block is a neurological issue; the part of your brain that creates and the part of your brain that edits are incapable of working at the same time, and when you try, your brain freezes up and you get writer's block. Do not edit while you're writing; don't even try to assess what you're writing while you're writing. Just barf it out onto the paper or the screen, save it, and edit it later -- that's how you get past writer's block once and for all.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7930091", "title": "Re: Mantra for the Blocked", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That makes a TON of sense. Much appreciated!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7847659", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In your experience does there appear to be much overlap between people who have some precognitive abilities and those who are particularly talented in divination?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7848683", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not in terms of innate talents, no. I've noticed that people with a talent for divination, if they put that talent to work, sometimes pick up precognitive abilities they did not previously have.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7860459", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What sort of things can be done to put that talent to work?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7866603", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't put it to work. Let it ripen in its own time and way, and bring you the gifts that it brings you. That's the healtny way to deal with psychism.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7847915", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does the galactic centre have any role in astrology that you know of?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7848939", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The location of the galactic center hasn't been known long enough for astrologers to have a clear sense of what it means in astrological terms -- though there are some theories, and research is ongoing. Ask again in 200 years or so and there should be a solid answer!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7854827", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you know of good sources which discuss it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7866859", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. You'll probably have to wait around 100 years for that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7867371", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If it doesn't exist, I'll just have to write it. Here's my plan: first, learn as much as possible about the astrology, take the astronomy as a theme for meditation, and see what comes up; finally, test it against the reality.\nDoes this sound like a good way to approach it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7871723", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Very much so. Go ye forth and do that thing!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7877099", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can't help but pipe in. I recall a few years back reading about the galactic centre and how it has been used in vedic astrology. Can't remember off the top of my head whether the author was David Frawley or some other Western author/vedic astrologer...\nRon M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7878635", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7848427", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nRecently I went back to practicing the SOP again, after some earlier attempts last year that got interrupted by the Watcher (I managed to reach the fourth Gate).\nMy plan was to start slowly by doing the Elementary Cross and the Circulation of Light.\nSo far, whenever I did the Elementary Cross it caused a really nasty headache at the location of the forehead centre. The last time it was so bad that I felt nauseous and had to go to bed early - I subsequently slept for about 11 hours.\nIs there something I could do to improve this situation?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7849195", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you get that kind of a negative reaction you probably shouldn't be practicing the ritual at this time. Do you get a similar response from the Lesser Ritual of the Pentagram?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7853547", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have not tried the LBRP yet.\nAt the moment I do the (daily) Christian Banishing that was introduced some months ago on this blog.\nMaybe you remember, I asked last week about starting Gareth Knight's Experience of the Inner Worlds and then procceeding to your \"Druid Magic Handbook\". Your advice was to prepare the space for Knight's exercises with the SoP - so I planned to start with the Elemental Cross and add a new direction/element each week.\nI am  under the impression that the SoP is more powerful and at the same time more versatile than the Christian Banishing. So I'm not sure if the CB alone can clear the space sufficiently for Knight's exercises.\nWhat I didn't mention in my first post was that I did both banishings, one in the morning, one in the evening. Maybe this is overloading my system and I should stick with only one?\nDuring my first attempts of learning the SoP last year I developed a uncomfortable steady feeling of pressure behind my forehead but never such a strong headache. Last year the feeling of pressure went away some time after I stopped doing the SoP.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7867115", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that was overdoing it. Take a full week off from all banishings and other ritual work to let your etheric body heal, and then try one ritual again -- not both.\nFor what it's worth,  the Christian banishing ritual done by a believing, baptized Christian has as much power as any banishing ritual anywhere -- it's not as versatile as the SoP but it's got plenty of force. It should be more than adequate for Knight's work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7870443", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ok, I will do this. Thank you!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7887595", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "One more question: Can I do the tibetan rites during the week?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7894251", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. Get plenty of rest. If you want exercise, take a walk.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7899883", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "mo_drui_mac_de", "content": "I, for one, have gotten far more juice out of the past season practicing the Banishing Ritual of the Cross (as I call it, as that sounds rather less like a ritual for banishing Christians — though I’m sure we’ve all met a fair few in want of a good banishing!) than I have in the year I poured into attempting first the polytheist LBRP and then the SoP. Both of those had a very slow albeit tangible cumulative effect — they transformed my living space from a chaotic frenzy that felt like bugs under the skin (a result of the unstable family members that live on the floor above me, and their unmanaged pack of chihuahuas), to a state of calm and peacefulness, at least in the small space I share with my wife. But it was arduous going, and no one banishing had any more than a barely noticeable effect. It’s only been a couple months doing the BRC, and I see the crosses traced out in bright golden flames, crackling audibly, and I’ve started detected a whiff of frankincense. There is also a highly noticeable improvement in my own mood and behavior on days that I perform compared with those on which I forget, which was not perceptible with the other two rituals.\n- Scott H. /|\\", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7860715", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP: what sort of things can cause such extreme reactions? Is there a risk if I get a minor headache when I do it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7867627", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're putting a little strain on one of your subtle centers. Try consciously relaxing the upper half of your face before and afterwards; if this communicates at all, make your eyes \"soft.\" Most people find that this helps.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7870187", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What about tension or pressure (not necessarily a \"headache\" in the forehead/upper nose area during meditation or other concentration?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7871979", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Same thing. Before and after your practice, take a few moments to consciously relax the upper half of your face, making your eyes \"soft.\" That will help clear things up.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7849451", "title": "actions as offerings", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For some deities, there are obvious actions that can be offerings whilst stuck at home: learning and cultural activity for Athena and Apollo, housecleaning for Hestia. Exercise for Mars. What about Zeus?\nPerhaps a list of these for gods in different pantheons would be useful and posters here could put one together?\nEspecially as people may need to conserve supplies, and increased action offerings could substitute for food and drink offerings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7864043", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yes! I'm interested in a corresponding deity for Hestia in the Irish pantheon. I've been developing a relationship with Brid over the last couple months, but don't know the rest of the pantheon very well. I've felt a draw to Hestia - or at least what she represents - ever since I first heard of her, but don't feel drawn to the Roman or Greek pantheons as a whole.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7900651", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "mo_drui_mac_de", "content": "Brid is very much the corresponding Irish goddess to Hestia, as goddess of the hearth. The Dagda is another hearth-god, in the event you needed a masculine deity for your home fire and cookpot. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7905003", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I've been wondering, why is he called THE Dagda, instead of just Dagda?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7913707", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If I may:\n\"Dagda\" is a title, not a name. His actual name is Eochaid Ollathair, \"Eochaid the All-father.\" \"An Dagda\" means \"the excellent god,\" and is a title of respect used by his worshipers for him; another is Ruad Rofhessa, \"red one of great knowledge.\"", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7867883", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That sounds like a good idea. If you've got the spare cash, remember that charitable donations are always suitable offerings for the gods, and can be done by mail or over the internet!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7869675", "title": "Re: actions as offerings", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "I stopped doing food offerings to Demeter a while ago because it attracted flies and ants.  Music ended up being a much better offering, at least in my experience, as it can be combined with prayer.  I have been composing music for the Orphic hymns.  Here are links to the ones I have recorded and published so far, Mercury/Hermes, Jupiter/Zeus, and Venus/Aphrodite, with free sheet music so listeners can potentially learn, deconstruct, and reconstruct the songs:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLvB95QZ1cF29R-JbRpGGXfgEMEGf3np_D\nhttps://queeniemusic.bandcamp.com/", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7849707", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does it matter that the SoP was created in a time and place where major events like this (the pandemic and shutdown) didn't happen and weren't expected?\nMight older rituals be more relevant?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7868139", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The SoP was created in a time and place where pandemics were quite common. The United States in the 1950s had several large epidemics. There was an ongoing polio epidemic which peaked every summer until the vaccine was finally introduced in 1955. The tuberculosis epidemic of 1950 killed 34,000 people in the US, and the Asian flu pandemic of 1957 killed 62,000 people here. Most people alive then also remembered the widespread shutdowns and rationing during the Second World War. That being the case, the SoP is at least as well suited to our present situation as any ritual you care to name.\n...and this is why I keep on pointing out that if you got your knowledge of history from a modern US public school education, you know nothing about history. I bet your teachers never mentioned any of those epidemics, did they?\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-23 06:59 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7869931", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't get the point of erasing that history....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7872235", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's all part of the mythology of progress. The idea is to convince people that things are so much better in the modern world than they were in premodern times, and erasing the continuity of epidemic disease as a normal human experience is part of that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7898859", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "But a lot of people don't seem to think of the 1950s as modern (judging from the reaction mention of that decade evokes from a lot of people)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7902955", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Maybe so, but it was the first decade in which the current managerial elite had undisputed power, and so erasing any problems other than those that could be blamed on the benighted deplorables is part of the narrative.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7921643", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "There is something that has been buzzing around in my mind when you or the commenters talk about the reasons behind some social collective behaviors, in this case, the reason why the bits of history that don’t go accord to the myth of progress just get deleted from the collective knowledge. The people that wrote those books in this case, probably didn’t have that intention precisely on their minds, at least consciously or what is worse they could’ve been convinced that they were doing a good job on putting history down. It feels to me that this sort of behavior, or blindness happens because it is the natural next step from the narrative that they have currently in their minds handed down since the onset of the blind belief in progress you talk about because people don’t question themselves back that much to see the whole situation in context. To put it more simply, it feels like a snowball effect where eventually the whole snowball just splats down from its weight just because people, collectively can’t see that it is rolling down the hill. 1) What is it that can have such a strong effect on the consciousness of people for centuries? Is it really just the greed of a few and ignorance of the masses?\nThis makes me put an enormous value on the questioning of my own consciousness, to the point that it is about freaky. If this is so big, and it is indeed going to splat down over the course of the next years and unfold for the next centuries, and I didn’t see it. What else is there on my consciousness rolling that I am not aware of and on what other things can I get it rolling? I still don’t have the slightest idea of what occultism is, but is seems that it can help me a bunch with that finding that out..\nI do have some a less convoluted question!\nI have been journaling and putting the sign of the zodiac the sun and the moon is at everyday so see what comes up as well with the phase of the moon. When should I consider it a change? when it first crosses the line into the next zodiac or when it is completely on it?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7922155", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a huge question, and the answer is \"a whale of a lot.\" Most of what shapes the world of your experience is hidden from the ordinary, habitual thinking of the mind. Yes, occultism is in large part about getting past that.\n2) I'm not sure what you're asking here. The sun and moon each pass into the next sign of the zodiac at a specific moment; they go from 29° 59' 59\" of Pisces, say, into 0° 0' 0\" Aries, and that takes them at that moment from Pisces to Aries. There is no delay between crossing over and getting completely in -- it's like jumping into the water -- one moment you're in the air, the next you're soaking wet.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7874283", "title": "epidemics", "user": "ritaer", "content": "My mother almost died during the Hong Kong flu. Ironically the expectation that anyone who was really ill had the flu kept the doctor from realizing that she really had infectious mononucleosis, which was little known at the time. \"Mono\" can cause spontaneous rupture of the spleen, of which she was one of the earliest reported cases.\nRita", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7849963", "title": "Elvish", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey jmg\nDo you think, jmg, that the elvish languages tolkien mademay be used as a magical/sacred language such as Latin or Hebrew is used?\nI ask since Tolkien used his linguistic skills to make the languages as beautiful as possible, and I wonder wether this beauty could have the power to attract something sacred, like how peladan said art can let humans experience the divine?\nJ.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7872491", "title": "Re: Elvish", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's been tried. So far, at least, those experiments I know of never got much result.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7850219", "title": "Placement for plants in a garden", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I find myself in the fortunate position to be planning a garden for our new house, and have some questions about placement for some plants based on the concepts of your Encyclopedia of Natural magic.\nI have read elsewhere that St. John’s wort would be more effective in keeping wandering spirits at bay if placed in the back of the house, which in my case is South (I’m in Australia) but being a solar plant, would it better align with the north from an elemental perspective?\nKnowing you are well versed in Japanese culture and magic, could you advise what would be the best quarter to place a sakura tree?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7872747", "title": "Re: Placement for plants in a garden", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In the northern hemisphere, it would be good to put it in the northeast, to protect against the unlucky influences from that direction. I'm not sure whether that would become the southeast on your end of the planet, or not! (Divination might be useful.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7850475", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\n1. Are there any of the rituals or exercises in the DMH which are hard on the heart?\n2. Newbie question: are homeopathy and cell salts complete systems in of themselves, similarly to how Golden Dawn is one system and Druid magic another, such that each system accomplishes the same ends with different means? Or are they complementary, so that one can use elements from both systems when needed?\n3. Even sillier newbie question: With cell salts, can you touch the pellets with your hands, or should you use a teaspoon?\n4. Are cell salts compromised by caffeine?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7873259", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you have serious heart disease, you should not practice any form of ritual magic. If you have a mild heart condition, the DMH material should be fine.\n2) It's a little more complex than that. Cell salts make up a complete system -- what used to be called \"biochemic medicine\" -- but the same 12 remedies are also used by homeopaths within their own system. I use cell salts only, but that's simply because that's what I know -- there are other people who use homeopathy and include the cell salts in their work.\n3) Biochemic medicine uses the 6x potency, which is a sufficiently low dilution that you can touch the pills with your hands without problem. I typically put the pills into my palm before tucking them under my tongue, and have good results.\n4) Again, cell salts are low dilution, so they aren't compromised by the things that mess over high-dilution homeopathic remedies. I drink lots of tea and have never had a problem with that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7886315", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I am currently in the process of trying to get a diagnosis whether I have heart problems or not with my family doctor. Sometimes I have a flutter in my heart, sometimes a slight ache in that area, but EKG results apparently have been fine. If I do have heart arrhythmia, should I avoid the DMH practices?\n2) And a follow up question about homeopathy, if I may. I've been trying to learn more about homeopathy over the past couple of days, and since posting my question earlier, my wife stumbled across quite coincidentally a documentary on a German news channel which was trying to warn people against homeopathy. If all it takes to prove that homeopathy works is to run a few double-blind studies to quiet these critics, why don't homeopathic practitioners do them? Do you happen to know if any double-blind studies have been done with cell salts?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7887083", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Heart arrhythmia's a minor heart problem, especially if it responds well to treatment. It shouldn't keep you from the DMH work.\n2) You can find a good bibliography of studies showing the effectiveness of homeopathy\nhere\n. It's very easy to do a double-blind controlled study to \"disprove\" homeopathy; rigging a study is easy, especialy when it's done by people who go out of their way not to understand what they're testing. You might look up the phrase \"replication crisis\" online to find out just how riddled with fraud the scientific community is these days...", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7894763", "title": "testing homeopathy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The major problem in testing homeopathy against allopathic methods is that homeopaths and allopaths are not talking about the same things when they describe disease. To take the common cold as an example. There is a range of symptoms and order of onset that constitutes 'having a cold' in most people's minds. If you have those symptoms you take whatever measures have worked in the past. A conventional doctor would confirm your diagnosis, if you were in a clinical trial for example, by testing for whichever rhinovirus was going around that season. A homeopath would listen to all your symptoms, including things that an allopath would never ask about, such as your dreams, which side you like to sleep on, whether you like warm or cool rooms. Then based on the totality of symptoms they would prescribe a remedy--one person with a 'cold' might get Allium because they presented with thin mucus and runny eyes, another might get a different remedy because they presented with a sore throat followed by thick green nasal mucus. To an allopath if both people have the same virus they have the same disease, and would be given the same treatment, to a homeopath they don't have the same disease at all. So how would you set up trial groups that would meet the standards of both systems?\nAs far as caffeine, it is my understanding that the problem is coffee, not caffeine. My homeopath has never forbidden tea or cola and has even recommended dark chocolate. However even decaffeinated coffee is a no-no. Fortunately I don't like coffee. Other forbidden substances include camphor and similar herbs, such as tea tree oil, as well as other influences such as electric blankets or heating pads and dental work. (Doesn't mean you let your teeth fall apart, just have to renew any constitutional remedy after being drilled.)\nThe major problem with homeopathy for most Americans is the expense--since they spend so much time on patients they must charge fairly high fees, especially for the initial appointment which may be as long as 1 1/2 to 2 hours. And insurance doesn't cover it. The remedies are quite inexpensive.\nHope this helps. I have been seeing a homeopath since 1982. I was diagnosed with asthma in the 70s and used to carry an inhaler. I haven't needed one for decades--knock wood. Depression, which is what I actually went for, also under control--by which I mean that I don't take any medication on a regular basis.\nRita", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7850987", "title": "SOP", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear ArchDruid,\nMy question is about the use of the 'sword mudra' when tracing out the symbols of the elements in the SoP ritual. I am guessing that this particular way of doing it energizes the gate that we are opening?\nIs that correct?\nCould you say a little more about the implications of tracing out the elemental symbols using the sword mudra?\nFrom Under the Acacias,\nThank You.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7873515", "title": "Re: SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a good question to which I'm not sure anyone knows the answer. I practice the SoP with the hand held in the \"sword mudra\" because that's the way I was taught to do it, and pass it on to others on the same basis, because it works.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7851755", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nRe the Canberra ingress chart where you mentioned some blunders were possible.\nWell, in Sydney they let 3000 passengers of a cruise ship despite there being positive covid cases. All allowed to freely disperse back to their home states, so far 48 have tested positive.\nThen of course, the Bondi beach fiasco.\nThis morning, pictures of hundreds lining up at Centrelink offices across the country hoping to get unemployment benefits. The website had crashed due to overload.\nNot sure if you are aware, but the coalition has an extremely tight relationship with the top end of town and a poorly disguised contempt for workers.\nDuring the GFC the labour Gov deposited money directly in everyone's bank as a stimulus measure. This lot would rather be sneezed in the face, than give checks to the 'undeserving poor'\nHelen in Oz\nPS it has now been one week since any of us have been able to see Mum.\nWe constantly ringing to check how she is and miss her very much.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7873771", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is one of those cases where I'm sorry to hear that my predictions were accurate. :-(", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7852011", "title": "Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nHave you heard about this thing in India yesterday where the Prime Minister asked pretty much the entire country to stand up and clap and ring bells simultaneously for five minutes at a specific moment yesterday while concentrating and projecting their thoughts and feelings of gratitude towards healthcare workers etc and determination to overcome the coronavirus crisis etc?\nObviously a billion people didn't do it, but from what I'm told it was pretty successful and many millions to tens of millions (if not hundreds of millions - no one did a count) did actually do it. I am not in India now, but my parents  (who live there) did it.\nhttps://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-sounds-bells-conches-claps-reverberates-as-country-appreciates-essential-service-providers-1658513-2020-03-22\nIs this basically a magical ritual? Chance of success/working/helping the situation?\nCould there be a connection between this and the fact that India has had an unusually low number of corona cases till date? Of course testing is very low and it is a hot country but 400 cases in a country of 1.3 billion (same as Slovenia with 2 million people) is incredibly low. Russia's also very low with 400ish cases for a 150 million population but that's a different question..", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7874027", "title": "Re: Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. Yes, that's a magical ritual; people used to do the same thing during eclipses to help dispel the negative influences those bring. Do you happen to know whether the time was chosen by way of astrology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7895531", "title": "Re: Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you know of any timing that could be auspicious, if one wanted to copy that ritual on a small scale?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7903211", "title": "Re: Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not off hand, no -- it's not something that's included in Western magic and astrology, so you'd have to talk to a Vedic astrologer.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7907307", "title": "Re: Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am the OP.\nI don’t know for certain but almost certainly yes. I have some passing familiarity with the basic system my parents use to find or avoid auspicious and inauspicious times and I would be shocked if a much more sophisticated version wasn’t applied to this. For one thing it was in the evening instead of morning which is a bit unusual.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7913963", "title": "Re: Pan-India clapping gratitude ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this. One of my other readers has mentioned the same thing, and this is very good to hear -- astrology used to be a standard tool of political action, and it's good to see Modi bringing that back into use.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7852267", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You've described Christian banishing rituals and meditation, is there also a form of divination particularly suited to Christians?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7864555", "title": "Christian divination", "user": "ritaer", "content": "A traditional folk practice was Bibliomancy--opening the Bible at random with eyes closed and putting a finger down, then reading the verse your finger touches as a message.\nThrough years of Christianity some leaders regarded the use of astrology as legitimate for Christians, as God had placed the heavenly bodies for signs. Other Christians have taught that any effort to learn the future displays a lack of trust in God and ban all such practices.\nBut, as JMG as stated in the past, there have been occultists in every generation who believed that their practices were compatible with their Christian faith. Several years ago I read a blog entry by Rufus Opus on his 'Head for the Red' site in which he explained his particular combination of Neoplatonic sorcery and Christian belief. It was quite interesting--I think the site is still up, but it may take a bit of hunting to find that entry.\nRita", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7874539", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Bibliomancy is certainly an option. There's also a Christian divinatory deck called, if I recall correctly, \"Angel cards\" that's become widely used among Christians, and that might be worth looking into.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7882219", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Most kinds of divination are forbidden for Christians.\nHowever, you could  look into astrology. Even this traditionalist Catholic website seems to be ok with it, provided you do it with the right attitude: https://www.fisheaters.com/astrologybackground.html\nA puzzling aspect is that in spite of all the noise  there seems to be a lot of lot casting in the bible...\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleromancy#In_Judeo-Christian_tradition", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7899627", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Depending on which branch of Christianity you’re in, divination is something you’re going to find an official condemnation for  in almost all its forms, while at the same time almost all of them have well-known practitioners who are otherwise “orthodox” company men. Case in point: Hans Urs von Balthasar, who was a theological mentor of the last pope (Benedict XVI) and was appointed to be a cardinal, infamously (at least in the circles I used to run in...)  wrote the afterword to a book on the tarot.\nFor me, personally, I think if the Christian God were all that upset with divination, then the New Testament wouldn’t contain glowing approval of the astrology that led the Magi to the Christ child... but, that’s just my opinion :)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7852523", "title": "The mystical art of muscle testing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Two Magic Monday’s ago Syfen replied to my post by asking what exactly muscle testing is.\nMuscle testing, also known as applied kinesiology, is a technique used by various alternative health practitioners, most regularly by chiropractors. In a clinical setting it involves testing the strength of one of the patient’s large muscles (commonly the posterior deltoid or biceps femoris in a prone position) while touching or manipulating a point on the body. If the point being contacted is misaligned, injured, imbalanced, or otherwise problematic, touching it will weaken the entire organism, including the muscle being tested. This allows the practitioner to zero in on the exact disturbance that wants correction. Yes, the body wants to be in balance and wants disturbances rebalanced. In fact, sometimes an obvious problem will not test weak until some other problem that the body wants addressed first gets identified and corrected. Some bodies behave more willfully than others, and some seem downright cantankerous.\nMany different kinds of imbalance can be tested. Meridians’ primary contact points can be muscle tested in set sequence to decode complex imbalances. Then the causative meridian’s points can be tested to identify which needs adjustment. Simple vertebral subluxations can be muscle tested easily. For more complex subluxations the bone can be tugged in the corrective direction (tests strong) or tugged in the direction of imbalance (tests even weaker.) Muscle disorders can be identified by pressing on the target muscle or by touching the muscle’s regulatory points on the torso and cranium while testing for body weakness. Further specificity can be gained by spreading the fingers apart or pinching together along the muscle body; whichever one weakens the body indicates over-release or over-contraction of the muscle.\nAnyone can practice muscle testing themselves by having a friend start by testing the normal strength of a large muscle group (commonly the lateral deltoid while standing) followed by testing while either person touches suspected imbalances. When the muscle tests weaker, you have found a point where some kind of attention would strengthen the entire organism. What kind of attention? That’s where experience, training, and artistry come into play — there are as many types of imbalance and adjustment as there are healthcare modalities.\nAs for muscle testing as a mystical practice, the same idea of the whole organism weakening under any increased stress or disorganization can be applied to asking simple yes/no questions. A true/yes/balancing answer tests strong while a false/no/imbalancing answer tests weak. This is more difficult to practice than the contact point testing, which works on everyone. Because the stress/disorganization comes from holding a question, but not its answer, in your mind, you have to be able to get out of the way enough to think about the question but let your body answer it for you — no easy task! Some personalities try very hard to control the outcome and can’t let their body/instinct/subconscious respond at all. Also, if you don’t trust the friend testing your strength, especially for revealing questions, you may find it very difficult to access your body’s truth. Again artistry and experience come into play as triangulating in on food allergies, long forgotten injuries, or herbal remedies by only asking yes/no questions can be a complex dance. If you ask a vague question, your body may respond to its own understanding of it, which may be quite different from your conscious understanding!\nSome people can practice muscle testing on themselves. Others find it too difficult to hold the muscle being tested at a constant resistance, the limb doing the testing under willful control, and the mind in a relaxed, pass-through-conduit state but still concentrating on a question. Although I have met people who test by trying to break a circle of their index finger and thumb, I have never found that technique to work well at all. Our finger muscles are under our active conscious control so much of the time that it becomes difficult to relinquish that control to let the body speak through them. I prefer testing the large muscle of my iliopsoas by pressing down on the thigh of my lifted leg.\nAsking your body or subconscious for answers to questions is always an act of supplication, never of domination. Be very, very careful asking questions using muscle testing because your deeper self can become quite resentful if it feels you are trying to steal goodies from its cookie jar. That’s dark magic, and it will burn you badly. I worked with health care professionals using applied kinesiology for many years before tentatively attempting to use it myself for similar contact point work. It was years after that that I cautiously began using it for questions about my body and its health. Any time I am unsure whether a question is in my body’s interest I ask, “Is it OK to ask you this question?” When I get a no response, I do not ask it, period.\nTo reinforce that point I will conclude with a paragraph from the previous post: We all have far more contact and connection with our strangely intelligent and willful bodies and psyches than we tend to recognize. Our bodies are continually monitoring and adjusting our blood pressure, glandular secretions, chemical imbalances, temperature, immune responses, etc., etc., etc. Our bodies know so much that never comes into our conscious awareness, and, if we can figure out how to respect them enough to communicate with them as equals, they are happy to share that information. The body truly is a temple, complete with oracle. Our bodies’ goals like health and survival may be very different from our personalities’ goals like wealth and power, and they will certainly not share their truth with us if we try to control and manipulate them. They may well lie to us if we try, even to their own detriment. Never try to harness a wild thing; content yourself to follow alongside it wherever it is going.\nChristophe", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7908331", "title": "Re: The mystical art of muscle testing", "user": "syfen", "content": "Thank you for the insight, is there a good introductory book on the subject you could recommend?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7921131", "title": "Re: The mystical art of muscle testing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Actually, I have never seen any books on muscle testing, good or bad. Finding a chiropractor, acupuncturist, masseur, etc. who practices it is the best way I know of to get experience with it.\nBeware the New Age gurus who learn the least bit possible of some technique and then hang out a shingle to start imparting their deep wisdom. I've met a few New Agey types who treat muscle testing like some kind of parlor game. Danger, Will Rogers, danger!\nIf you are going to the Ecosophia potluck in June, I would be happy to give you a lesson in muscle testing there.\nChristophe", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7914475", "title": "Re: The mystical art of muscle testing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh, so that's what my chiropractor has been doing! He'll push down on my outstretched arm, and I'll resist easily. Then he'll touch a point on my jaw and my arm drops under the slightest pressure. I figured it had something to do with the subtle bodies, but wasn't sure how to ask. Thanks for this.\n-Cliff", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7852779", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With the connection between physical culture and the occult, would practising each have helped the other? Or would it have meant less energy and will left for magical achievement? Because from the old photos it certainly wasn't their physiques that suffered. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7874795", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There was a huge overlap back in the day between physical culture and occultism, and many people practiced both of them with good results. In my experience -- yes, I've worked with a range of physical culture exercises, and am still doing so -- they reinforce each other: vibrant physical health gives you more energy for magical working, and the more willpower you use, the more you have.\nDo you have a particular physical culture system in mind to try out?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7885035", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm close to finally being over a lower back injury, and the barbells and kettlebells are calling to me again. I was thinking about getting back into the StrongFirst system - https://www.strongfirst.com/ - a combination of old-time strongman methods and modern science. But I have joint hypermobility and this has been only the latest of several injuries and I'm doubting whether that kind of heavy training is worth the risk. Whichever way I go there'll be a delay as I was planning to go to the osteopath to give my sacrum a final pop, but the quarantine has delayed that. Do you know any systems that have good results with a low risk of injury?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7886059", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You might consider starting with something a little less strenuous to build up your core strength before hitting the iron again. On the one hand, Genevieve Stebbins' system of exercises might be worth considering -- she was a leading adept in the Hermetic Brotherhood of Luxor as well as a teacher of exercise and gymnastics, and her best book can be downloaded for free\nhere\n. The other thing that comes to mind is Maxalding, one of the classic systems of muscle control; the website that once hosted the lessons has gone dark, but you can access it via the Wayback Machine\nhere\n.\nMaxalding is far and away the best thing I know if you've got a history of injuries, and it also combines well with other forms of exercise -- a lot of the great old-time strongmen combined muscle control methods with weightlifting to get their spectacular physiques. Stebbins' work might be a good thing to do next, as you're working toward a full recovery of strength and flexibility before you pump iron again.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7853035", "title": "Archangel Raphael’s association with Air", "user": "rationalist858", "content": "Hello JMG. So I recently started practicing the LBRP and I’ve been wondering... Why is Raphael associated with Air, when the name Raphael means something like the “healing of God”? To me, healing seems like Water, not Air.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7875051", "title": "Re: Archangel Raphael’s association with Air", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of the classic traps beginners fall into. Don't try to understand the symbolism; simply let yourself work with it and absorb it by osmosis, and after a while you'll understand why this and other apparently odd bits of symbolism are what they are.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7853291", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When you do divination, do you ever ask what actions will benefit your next life as well as this one?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7875307", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not something I pursue by divination, but it's certainly an option.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7853803", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWhat do you think about \"Ancient Aliens\" hypothesis? In relation to that question, how would you interpret legendary civilizer characters like Anunnaki in Mesopotamian mythology or \"Watchers\" in the Book of Enoch?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7875563", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I read Erich von Däniken's\nChariots of the Gods?\nwhen it first came out, and even then my take was that he was taking perfectly good mythology and decking it out in cheap science fiction drag. If the basic teachings of magic are correct, there are intelligent beings of various kinds who do not have physical bodies -- or at least whose bodies are not of the same kind of substance as ours -- but who can and do communicate with human beings under some circumstances. The usual term for those beings is \"spirits.\" If spirits exist -- and my experience certainly suggests that they do -- there's no need to dress them up like astronauts and pretend that they come from other planets.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7854059", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nMy preferences aside, I am being directed to devote effort to delving into my psyche, examining unresolved issues, and the like.  I've decided to ramp up my reading of Jung, but are there any occult tools or techniques which are particularly useful for this endeavor?  I'm adopting my regular meditation practice accordingly, but thought there might be other avenues I could utilize as well.\nThank you.\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7876075", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the core practices of Jungian therapy is active imagination, which is the same thing that occultists call pathworking. You should certainly include that as part of your work, as it's a very good way to let repressed contents surface so you can deal with them. (If I recall correctly, Marie-Louise von Franz wrote a book on active imagination, which might be worth consulting.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7881195", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Doing a quick look-up, would that be\nAlchemical Active Imagination\n?  I'll see if I can find it.\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7886571", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the one!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7854315", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nIs the text of Tao Te Ching amenable to interpretation from the point of Western occult philosophy? Would its stanzas be good themes for daily discursive meditation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7876843", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes and yes. Take it line by line, and you've got about a year of first-rate meditation themes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7877867", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Which translation would you recommend?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7878379", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Whichever one appeals most to you.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7895019", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I don't know any Chinese, so I can't critique the quality of the translation, but decades ago I found a copy of the Modern Library hardback, and it's been my old friend ever since: \"The Wisdom of Laotse,\" edited by Lin Yutang (1948).  It includes selected relevant passages from Chuangtse in the commentary to each section.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-23 11:21 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7890667", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "If I may piggy back on this. Would Patanjalis yoga sutras be a good theme for DM too? Since sutra means thread I would assume that maybe... What is being threaded by it? Hmm Would that work as a starting point or is it too broad?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7894507", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I know the Theosophists used to pay very close attention to Patanjali, and some of them did discursive meditation -- Ernest Wood in particular wrote some fine books on that theme. So it's probably worth trying. As for where to begin, why, try it and see!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7854571", "title": "Affirmations and pandemic protection", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, I’d like to ask a question, but it may be clearer if prefaced it with a story from Indian tradition – so here it goes.\nOne day a traditional healer saw a mysterious woman enter the village at dusk. As she came close to his house, he asked her who she was. “The goddess of cholera” was her reply. “Go about and do your business”, replied the healer, who then asked her, “how many of my village will you be taking?” The goddess said, “ten”. She continued to walk into the village. Soon after, cholera spread through the village, keeping the healer very busy. Eventually, one evening the healer saw the goddess leaving the village and he angrily accosted her: “You told me that you would take ten people of my village and fifty have died – why did you lie to me?” “I did not lie”, the goddess replied, “I took only ten… the other forty died of fear”.\nAt this time, it is, of course, important for all of us to walk the middle path between fear and foolhardiness regarding our health and the health of our communities/nations and take care of our physical and mental health. My question is: do you believe that an affirmation such as “I am healthy throughout the Covid-19 outbreak” would provide some useful additional protection from this virus?\nOn a related note, yesterday at 5 pm (local time), the entire country of India made a tremendous amount of noise (gongs, blowing of instruments, clapping, etc) at the request of Prime Minister Modi. The stated reason was to show support of the country's health workers who will have an up-hill battle in coming weeks. Vedic astrologers, however, noted that yesterday Mars entered Capricorn, where he is exalted, and traditionally the initial act of declaring war is the blowing of conches, banging of drums, etc. At this current time, Mars is the only planet who can challenge the supremacy of the lunar nodes Rahu and Ketu (dragon's head and dragon's tail, respectively)who are both strongly placed in their own nakshatras (lunar mansions) and are largely \"blamed\" for the current pandemic. There is every reason to believe that the Prime Minister has timed this declaration of war against Covid-19 based on the advice of vedic astrologers. Thought you might find this point interesting and perhaps worthy of comment.\nRon M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7871467", "title": "Re: Affirmations and pandemic protection", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's interesting. Sunday at 6 pm (local time) musicians in Germany where encouraged by the government to play \"Ode to joy\" out of Beethoven's 9th from their windows. I'm no astrologer, so I don't know if there is some significance. Could also be the symbolic last gasp of a failed megalomaniacal superstate project...\nhttps://www.dw.com/de/mit-beethovens-ode-an-die-freude-gegen-die-coronakrise/a-52886153", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7877611", "title": "Re: Affirmations and pandemic protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the EU's anthem, isn't it? Probably the latter, then...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7884267", "title": "Re: Affirmations and pandemic protection", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Cheers to that.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7877355", "title": "Re: Affirmations and pandemic protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Don't think of affirmations as being \"against\" something, such as a virus -- it's an affirmation, not a negation!  Affirm health, without referencing the virus: \"I am filled with the golden light of health,\" for example, and visualize your entire body and aura full of golden light as you do so.\n2) I was just wondering, in response to another comment, whether Modi used astrological timing for that. I gather he did -- and my guess is that the results will be very good. (I barely know the first thing about Vedic astrology, other than it's not the same as the kind I practice, but by all accounts it works very well.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7855083", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm doing the SoP, facing south for the opening and closing, and have a question about the calling of the elements: I'm adding them in in the order given, but doing them in that order for the ritual would involve spinning around like crazy. Does it work if I do it starting from where I face to begin? So for me, fire, water, earth, air; for people facing east, air, fire, water, earth.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7901419", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think you missed this question. Given the number of questions you get, I think it's easy to do, but just thought I'd bring it to your attention.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7903723", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, you need to do them in the order given, and yes, that means you have to turn around a bit. The sequence of the elements is important.\n(And yes, I missed this one -- thanks for the reminder.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7855339", "title": "Rank Beginner", "user": "miz_bean", "content": "Mr Greer, I'd like to ask your advice and that of other commenters who might have experienced a similar situation to what follows.\nI am a lifelong atheist who has never felt any spiritual tug, and have been frankly contemptuous of those who claimed to have experienced the divine. As I get older and more fully realize how vanishingly tiny my knowledge really is, I find myself increasingly drawn to try to experience the vast and rich worlds you and others describe. I have your Druidry Handbook (unread) and Mystery Teachings from the Living Earth (which I read along with on Ecosophia), as well as several others of your occult books.\nMy dilemma is two-fold:\n1. I expect to feel deeply foolish and self-conscious for a time in starting any spiritual practice. How should I handle that?\n2a. The greater issue for me is my home. My husband was brought up a born-again Christian but has fallen far from those beliefs, and while he won't call himself an atheist, he has no kinship with any belief system. My influence was instrumental in that. I have no desire to open myself to his gaze unless and until I become strong in a new path.\n2b. I have no space in my house I can retreat to each day. My husband works a rotating shift, meaning that the hours he is at home vary from day to day and week to week, and I no longer work a paying job. Further, our dynamic by and large is dominated by his needs. My character tends to denigrate and doubt my needs (if I can even identify them).\nHow do I move forward? I feel as though I'm suffocating just writing this.\nThank you so much.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7865067", "title": "Re: Rank Beginner", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "The answer will (IMHO) depend in part on how mutually respectful of one another and how open to one another you and your husband are.  Can you talk over pretty much anything else together?  If so, tell him what you just told us.  His response may surprise you.  Everyone does change over the decades of life, even one's husband, though it makes many people uncomfortable to acknowledge those natural changes.  He, too, may be changing, and may not have known how to broach the subject of his own changes with you.  He may even be changing in the same direction you are--that's a natural enough sort of change as one ages and draws ever nearer to one's own death.  To paraphrase Samuel Johnson, \"There is nothing that so focuses your mind as the certain knowledge and constant awareness that you will die much sooner than you like.\"\nIf not, if you are always somewhat cautions about opening up to one another about anything, then it might be easier to start by talking about being more open to one another in general with respect to change.\nOr ... would even that *very clearly* be more than he could ever handle?  Is he very rigid, and seems to hate to talk about anything at all profound, or to think that you and he might not agree on any point, however minor?  Do you feel like you have to walk on eggshells with him?  Then you can try to implement the desired changes in your own life while \"flying under the radar.\"  With his schedule so variable, \"under the radar\" means your schedule of practices, too, will need to be equally variable.\nIf that seems too hard for now, you could try working to change the \"energy\" in the house that you share, without letting him know what you're doing.  Since it's your house, too, you do not (IMHO) need his consent to work on the house's \"energy\" by occult means such as hoodoo floor washes and so forth.  (See our host's many accounts of such things in previous posts.)  Just doing occult cleansing work of that sort on your shared house will *inevitably* change him as well as you, whether he would go along with it or not.  It might even lead eventually to more open commnunication between the two of you.\nWhat may also help you a lot just now is keeping in view that the sort of things we talk about here often do not really require any sort of \"belief\" (in the religious or spiritual sense) at all.  Do you have to \"believe\" that your hammer will work in order to drive a nail with it, or can you just start hammering and see what happens?  Me, I just start hammering.  Do you have to \"believe\" in all the nutritional science out there to cook a meal that you'll both enjoy and will be good for you both?  I'd wager that you just start cooking dinner.  A lot of the things we talk about here require no more belief than hammering a nail does, or cooking a meal.\nBut be cautious, and keep in mind that there may be a personal cost even so.  There are marriages that can't take even the least of the strains that are naturally caused by each partner's variable growth in wisdom, love and knowledge over their years together.  The things you are now interested in will definitely change you, even if you do nothing more than read about them steadily for a number of years.  So please do weigh the risks and the benefits to yourself beforehand.  You can minimize those risks, but nothing you (or anyone) could do would ever make them go completely away.  Can you live with those risks?  And also, can you go on living without taking those particular risks?\nBest wishes as you wrestle with all this stuff--it is a very hard road to travel!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7876587", "title": "Re: Rank Beginner", "user": "miz_bean", "content": "A thousand thanks for this, Robert. I have learned to truly respect your wisdom.\nI love the idea of starting with a change in energy, especially in the midst of this virus outbreak. I'll do some digging and planning. And perhaps I could begin by just insisting that I need a space and time for meditation.\nBest wishes.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7881963", "title": "Re: Rank Beginner", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just some reflections from my own experience:\nWhen I first started seriously exploring occult/mystery teachings about 3 years ago, shortly before my wife and I were married, it was a source of serious stress and fear for her. We were both raised along the lines of \"spiritual but not religious,\" and while the occult was not threatening to her in and of itself (we were both taught to be \"agnostic\" about such things), the fact of my taking it seriously made her very scared for our future compatibility...etc.\nI'm happy to report that 3 short years later there is zero fear and stress related to it. I think that's mostly due to simply the building of trust and love between us day-to-day, and that she can see that my learning and practice in these areas help make me a calmer, wiser, more balanced, more loving person, and thus she has nothing to fear. It has also helped her be much more open-minded, though this was not something I forced or insisted on. It just happened naturally.\nMany blessings on your continued growth and learning!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7878123", "title": "Re: Rank Beginner", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Accept that you'll feel that way, and allow yourself to feel it. There's nothing wrong with feeling self-conscious and foolish, and once you've let yourself do so, you won't be dissuaded by such things.\n2a) Obviously I don't know you or your husband, but I don't recommend that spouses hide this sort of thing from one another. Consider facing your fears and admitting your doubts and your attraction to the spiritual realm to him.\n2b) In that case, you might start with a simple affirmation, which you can do silently wherever you are: \"I accept the reality of my needs.\" Repeat that many times each day. Watch things begin to change.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7855595", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The reaction to the COVID-19 epidemic is baffling to me. I can't seem to get through to people that there's such a thing as \"middle ground\"; nor does it ever seem to enter the equation that there are drawbacks to extreme measures. Is this just a result of panic, or do you think there's more to it than that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7878891", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think it's panic fueled by the delusion that bad things like this aren't supposed to happen any more -- at least not to the comfortable classes! (I've noticed quite consistently that the higher on the social feeding chain a local grocery store is, the more panic buying goes on there.) One downside of the myth of progress is that when something happens that's supposed to belong to the primitive, ignorant past -- for example, a pandemic -- believers in progress wig out completely.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7881451", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "\"I've noticed quite consistently that the higher on the social feeding chain a local grocery store is, the more panic buying goes on there.\"\nWe have three grocery stores near here, two fairly successful chains and one that's more obscure and almost went bankrupt a year or two back. When Mom and I stopped in at the last on Friday, it had a better selection of fruit and vegetables (the first time we'd seen potatoes)  than we'd seen in weeks.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7883243", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, then an awful lot of people who claim to have gotten over progress still buy into it.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7885803", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've met very few people who have really let go of faith in progress. There are some, but most people who insist they don't believe in progress have a thin veneer of faux-cynicism over a lot of frustration -- they want progress to happen, they're convinced that it ought to happen, and they're angry and upset that they didn't get their jetpack on schedule.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7905515", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "Hear, hear!\nFWIW, in my experience so far it's precisely the CNN-watching salary class that's gone cuckoo-cachoo over all this, while my working-class friends are doing their best to maintain normalcy.\nI was out walking by the river yesterday when my plumber friend drove by. He turned around and came back to see if I needed a ride or if was just getting some exercise and fresh air. I held out my hand to shake his through the window then hesitated, sheepishly asking if that was OK. He grabbed my hand with his meaty paw and said \"give me some of that coronavirus!\" Then took my left hand in his left hand and we just kinda wallowed in rational adult friendship for 10 seconds or so before releasing, laughing, and heading our separate ways.\nOn his way off he leaned out and said, \"I've read the Bible more than once and I don't recall Jesus ever talking about social distancing...\"\nQuite the contrary, my friend, quite the contrary...even when dealing with lepers.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7910635", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How many of them do you think will snap out of it after this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7914219", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea. It'll be interesting to see.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7855851", "title": "hidden motivations", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A bit of a long story, but I'm inviting discussion from the commentariat and wondering if anyone else has had a similar experience within the current situation.\nWhere I live we've been encouraged to stay home and practice social distancing to slow the spread of the virus. During the first week I had a somewhat cavalier attitude toward this, and was still going out to visit with one friend or two each day. I am young and healthy and not afraid of catching coronavirus.\nA couple of days ago my girlfriend suggested (over the phone) that we both be more careful and strict about not seeing people outside our homes, because she's started to be concerned about the risks to her aging parents. I was surprised by the strength of the feeling of resistance that arose in me at that moment, but I told her her request was reasonable and that I would limit my contacts until it seemed safe to do otherwise.\nThe next morning I went out for some (solitary) exercise, and in the course of my run I was chased for several hundred yards across the local golf course by an unfamiliar black dog. On my way home I encountered three more black dogs, one of which barked at me aggressively. A black dog has frequently figured in my dreams over the years, and I think I am ready to name what it means to me.\nThe fact is that I wasn't taking coronavirus prevention seriously because I've been secretly rooting for the virus, against the humans. For years I've watched environmental problems grow worse and wished there were less humans in the world. The notion of a pandemic always presented itself as the cleanest and simplest route to a cleaner and less overburdened world. Now it seems I've got my wish.\nFrom a utilitarian perspective, someone who wished to slow environmental destruction would do well to go around licking doorknobs at this time- for the greater good! But I don't think morality works that way, or karma. What I realized is that I'd been letting my unconscious feelings draw me passively into harm's way- other people's harm, that is. And those feelings can be neatly summed up as a murderous hatred for humanity.\nWell, that was nice to know. It explained why that day's Tarot spread had the Devil in the position of the significator (me!) and why that black dog has popped up so often in my dreams, and now in waking life. I've been lying to myself about the murderous rage that's been dogging me for years, pretending instead to be a nice guy who wants to help people.\n1) To use the language of the Cosmic Doctrine, it seems I've fallen short of outright 'positive evil' in my lax attitude toward the virus, but I have allowed myself to be passively pulled into the current of Chaos, rather than stepping completely aside and letting it pass me by. From a karmic perspective, though, is it accurate to say that there's no real difference, and that I've risked terrible consequences for myself and others?\n2) How can I discharge this huge weight of hatred and rage that I now realize I've been carrying around? Journaling has helped bring it to light (hence this post), but what other steps can I take to be free of it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7865323", "title": "Re: hidden motivations", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I don't think you are alone in this. Since the first edition of _The Population Bomb_ (1968) we have been steeped in messages that there are too many people, that we are destroying the planet and so on. You would have to have lived in a cave not to have absorbed and internalized that message. For Westerners this may be intensified by our Christian cultural background--Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God--the message that all humans, even those who appear to be living righteous lives are miserable vermin in the eyes of their Creator is part of our culture. This sermon appears in literature anthologies for American literature survey courses, so even if you were not raised as a Christian you could have encountered it.\nRita", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7879147", "title": "Re: hidden motivations", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) There's a difference from a karmic perspective, because the actions are different. Deliberately willing harm is one thing, letting yourself be drawm passively into a pattern that causes harm is another -- but both have very unwelcome karmic consequences.\n2) You've taken the crucial step -- a step a vast number of people are still refusing to take -- in admitting that you're not a \"nice guy,\" you really do have all this hatred and rage inside of you. So does everyone else. As I pointed out a while ago\nin a blog post\n, today's attitude toward hatred and rage is identical to the Victorian attitude toward sexual desire; most of us pretend that we don't feel it, that only those awful people over there (\"hate groups\") would ever indulge in it (\"hate speech\"), and so our psyches are festering swamps of repressed hatred and rage that seep out in various more or less destructive ways we go out of our way not to notice. Acknowledge your hatred and rage, accept that these are normal, necessary, healthy human emotions, let yourself feel them, and you can release the repressions in a controlled, conscious, and constructive way.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7907819", "title": "Re: hidden motivations", "user": "causticus", "content": "Quite interesting. I think that daily SOP practice for the last 6+ months straight has made me acutely aware of the hate, anger, and general grumpiness that churns around inside me on a daily basis. Only now I seem to do a better job of observing the phenomenon internally, processing it, and expressing those feels outwardly a lot less than before. The feelings are still there, though I'm able to better analyze them now instead of just blindly reacting.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7910379", "title": "Re: hidden motivations", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! This gives good food for thought. The act of discovery was one step in freeing myself from this, and the act of confession was a further step- both felt great. Now I'm facing this thing rather than hiding it or running from it.\n1) What would you recommend I do to address any bad karma I may have accumulated by allowing myself to be drawn into a pattern that causes harm, in this case, by wilfully putting myself into the pool of possible COVID-19 vectors? Aside from staying home henceforward and, as they say, keeping my nose clean?\n2) If the black dog from my dream is a symbol of repressed hatred, then I think what you're saying is that I need to take my dog for a walk, but on a leash rather than letting it run free, chasing me around. Any suggestions on how to do this? Or will the next step only become clear with meditation and reflection on my part?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7914731", "title": "Re: hidden motivations", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Spend some time meditating about this and see what occurs to you. It really does vary from person to person.\n2) That's an excellent metaphor. Yes, it's going to take meditation and reflection.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7856107", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Feel free to delete this if you think it's too dangerous, but am I wrong to worry about how Hughes' most recent working could be tampered with?\n\"May I be free of suffering; may I be at peace.\nMay you be free of suffering; may you be at peace.\nMay all beings be free of suffering; may all beings be at peace.\nMay all be healed and blessed.\"\nWell, to be free of suffering is to not exist in the Buddhist cosmology (from which Tonglen is drawn); and we say \"rest in peace\" to the dead. I know there are plenty of young people who are looking at the epidemic and calling it things like \"Boomer Remover\" and hoping it spreads, and kills, like wildfire, and some of them are involved in the occult.\nThe blow-back would be intense, but I'm not sure they all grasp that; and I'm sure some of them would take it. How bad do you think it could get?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7879403", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You know, that was the first thing that I thought of when I read his spell, too, and so I'm pretty sure that it must have occurred to a few thousand basement-dwelling, Kek-worshiping chaos mages, too. Yes, it would be very easy to gimmick that into a death spell. I'd expect to see some unexpected outbreaks of fatal illness, maybe CoVID-19, maybe something else, among practitioners of Hughes' latest folly, followed by parallel outbreaks among the basement brigade. I doubt it'll influence the overall course of the pandemic, but it may cause unnecessary misery and mortality in a few places.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7883499", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm assuming the working lacks the power needed to get truly destructive then?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7885547", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Hughes' methods and those of your standard chaos mage are fairly lightweight, all things considered.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7906283", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "But if I were going to lay money on one or the other, I'd put my dollars on the Chaos mages.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7914987", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, given a fight between the two, they'd win hands down -- they at least understand how to focus on a single intention, and don't try to make their rituals an occasion for virtue signaling.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7856363", "title": "Second Saturn return", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI wrote to you about my second Saturn return late last year and you helpfully suggested that it appeared I'd been given an opportunity to work through some issues in advance during the previous couple of years. That does indeed seem to be the case and I'm grateful for that time to sort out a number of nagging matters prior to getting started on the next phase.\nMy second Saturn return is just starting and I'd been wondering what would happen, what the theme might be, but things have suddenly become clearer and it feels like the way ahead is now being set. Some 20 years ago, a lifelong interest in all things growing became an obsession, and 15 years ago I qualified in horticulture and set about learning and growing ever more, taking on clients and exploring possibilities. It's been good and I've learned a great deal.\nNow we find ourselves in this new reality, facing a global pandemic and shortages of just about everything - BUT, I have seeds, knowledge and space for growing, so that's the direction it feels right to be taking. Growing food, sharing with my community, making sure folks around me are okay, growing edibles for those whose gardens I work in. Following a successional sowing calendar to ensure an ongoing variety of fresh edibles.\nPerhaps my time has come? It feels like it's all falling into place.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7879659", "title": "Re: Second Saturn return", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's very often what happens at the second Saturn return. Saturn is the planet of old age, remember, and by the time your second Saturn return arrives you're approaching that status -- so it can be a very positive, stabilizing time if it's embraced and accepted.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7925995", "title": "Re: Second Saturn return", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, reassuring reply. Well, as long as I get through this, it should be, as you say, positive and stabilising.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7856619", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would using CBD oil leave the same sticky film on the aura that cannabis does?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7879915", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. Since CBD is a fairly new product, you'd have to discuss the matter with some good clairvoyants and see what they thought.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7856875", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much do you remember about your earlier incarnation when you first tried magic?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7880171", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Quite a bit, at this point.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7857131", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "@ weirdtales, I saw the reference to the art of true healing. I cannot find the author's name in that thread. Can you or anybody help me here. Thanks very much.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7863787", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "It was the featured book that week, by Israel Regardie.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7869419", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "Or...the featured author at least!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7884779", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a more recent edition of the book on my desk(2007 edition). The book is edited by Marc Allen.\nLuciano", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7857387", "title": "discursive meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI have a couple questions about proper discursive meditation, which I have been practicing for about a year.\n1. I’m a professional writer of non-fiction. The quality and texture of discursive meditation seems very similar to what happens when I conceive and arrange a long essay or story. Similarly to a trial attorney developing a case, or a member of the clergy devising a good sermon. One must explore all angles of the topic, and then weave them into a coherent whole. Attorneys, clergy and professional writers often take a certain angle on the topic, of course; if you don’t, it renders the end result almost meaningless. Is this a good understanding of discursive meditation, or are there aspects I am missing?\n2. The four-fold breath is tricky to maintain when following a long course of thought. Sometimes I manage it, but counting in the background is effortful. Sometimes it does seem like the breath helps the thoughts…travel. Is there something to this? Or should I stop worrying about the breath timing when I start meditating on my chosen theme? (Usually I practice four-fold breath alone for five or six minutes, and then meditate for five or six minutes.)\n3. Occasionally when I try to start the breath practice I get really hot and my breath rate speeds up and it gets uncomfortable to continue. Does this indicate anything in particular, or just that today isn’t the day to meditate?\nSincerely,\nMs. Krieger", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7880939", "title": "Re: discursive meditation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a very good start. There are other aspects to discursive meditation, but they unfold over time with practice. If you start with the understanding you have, you'll have good results.\n2) You don't keep doing the fourfold breath while you meditate. You do the fourfold breath for five minutes or so first, to clear your mind, then you change to ordinary quiet breathing and begin the meditation proper.\n3) Are you by any chance menopausal? If so, try imagining that the heat is energy, and the energy flows through your feet and diffuses itself in the ground. My wife also found that a good way to respond to hot flashes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7926251", "title": "Re: discursive meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for your considered answers. I’ll keep meditating with this in mind. (And not menopausal yet, but I will experiment with grounding the energy now and keep the technique in mind for the future.)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7857643", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You said that devices that alter brainwaves and change states of consciousness do too much of the work for you. Are their any technological aids that can help spiritual practice without becoming a crutch? The same way as if you're trying to stay in the aerobic zone, a heart rate monitor is a very useful thing to have, but you still have to do the running.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7870699", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "emskewis", "content": "I wonder too about the influence of incense on brain activity. I recently quite going to a liturgical Gnostic church. There were a number of reasons for that but one them was that I felt my state of consciousness was being unduly influenced by the frankincense, etc. After Mass I was high as kite. It felt like cheating, I felt drugged. Thoughts on this, anyone?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7881707", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Biofeedback machines can be useful. They don't do the work, they just let you know how relaxed you're getting, and so on. There was some first-rate work done with them in the 1970s, before the scientific community sold its soul to the pharmaceutical industry and skeptics started insisting that anything that didn't make a profit for Merck and Sanofi had to be crackpot pseudoscience.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7857899", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. Can a self-confessed skeptic successfully practice magic with an open mind, while maintaining some reservations about the metaphysics involved? Is it acceptable to suspend judgment about such issues until one has direct evidence from experience, while still obtaining good results?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7882475", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A lot depends on what you mean by \"skeptic.\" If you have a genuinely open mind and are willing to accept that magical practices can have effects, even if those effects are psychological and psychosomatic in nature, yes, you can certainly get good results from practicing magic. If, on the other hand, you're the kind of pseudoskeptic whose faith in rationalism and materialism is as absolute and unthinking as a medieval peasant's faith in the wonder-working bones of the local saint, no, you should stay away from magic -- you won't benefit, and your attempts to argue away the results of your practices will annoy the rest of us no end. ;-)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7882987", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For what it's worth, that was me for a while too. I then explored various materialistic justifications (ex: placebo effect), before finally deciding that the simplest explanation is that those occultists are on to something!\nSo it's a viable approach.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7858155", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. I’m having some trouble grasping exactly what the five classical elements (fire, water, air, earth, quintessence) are. I assume these are not simply the building blocks of matter like a primitive form the periodic table, right?\nIn Learning Ritual Magic, you cover them in a single sentence: “The five elements are not static, unchanging counters. They are moments in a process of transformation.” I’ve been mulling over this sentence for 2 or 3 months and still don’t understand what it means. Can you offer some clues?\n2. Why do you think that certain spiritual beings are congenial to humanity? What interest could they possibly have in helping us? (Anticipating your response, I can’t ask them myself because I’m not yet privileged enough to have a direct line of communication ;-))\n3. Semi-serious question, but why don’t psychics play the lottery more often? Perhaps they can sense that large amounts of unearned wealth will destroy them? ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7885291", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The five elements are modes of manifestation. They occur on every plane. You've doubtless encountered people who are free spirits, people who are fiery, people who are airheads, people who are all wet, and people who are really down to earth, right? Those are the four elements on the plane of personality. On every other plane of being, you'll find things that fit into the same categories. They all flow into one another, the way that ice (which is solid, i.e., earth) melts into liquid water and then evaporates into vapor (i.e., air) -- a complete airhead can get down to earth, though you're likely to see an emotional outburst with a lot of tears on the way!\n2) What interest do human beings have in pets -- or, for that matter, in service animals?\n3) It's a valid question, but the answer requires a bit of occult philosophy. Human beings have bodies on the material, etheric, and astral planes -- the planes of physical substance, life force, and concrete consciousness, which includes the emotions and the imagination.  On the mental plane, the next plane up, we are still evolving bodies -- what we have at this point is a mental sheath, a sort of rudimentary structure that over many lives will evolve into a mental body. Psychism works through the mental plane, and the more developed your mental sheath becomes, the more psychic capacities you have.\nDesires, however, belong to the lower end of the astral plane -- and yes, this includes the desire for wealth, and the desire for anything you can get with wealth. The more you focus on your desires, the less attention you can pay to the mental plane, and so the weaker your psychism becomes. So as long as you're trying to win a lottery payout, and are fixated on that desire, your psychism isn't going to work well.\nThis is why many beginning diviners can do good divinations for other people but get lousy results when they try to cast a reading for themselves. You can get past that, but it takes plenty of practice and a certain amount of calmness about the issues that affect you directly!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7911147", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP.\nOn the mental body and psychism. Does natural precognitive abilities mean the person likely was a occultist in a past life? Or would any intellectualy demanding profession have been enough to develop it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7915243", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are many ways to develop the mental sheath, and no one of them is enough by itself -- that's why it takes many lifetimes to finish the process. Natural precognitive abilities can have several possible sources; training in a past life is one of them, but there are also family bloodlines in which psychism appears, and many other potential sources as well.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7858411", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For JMG and the commentariat, I have a disturbing story to report of something that happened to me recently, and which skewed my perception of the occult towards TSW. I’ve been maintaining a daily magical practice for about 3 months, and while I can’t prove that the following story had anything to do with it, especially at such an early stage, it seems too uncanny to ignore.\nA few weeks ago I had a disturbing dream involving cars being wrecked, as if in a junkyard. As I was going down the street, it looked as if all around me there were broken down cars, being crushed or destroyed in various ways, some of which looked like twisted piles of metal with shards of broken glass sticking out. Later on in the dream, I was chased around by a car trying to run me over.\nFor reference, cars are not a usual topic in my dreams, or even remotely an interest of mine, so this dream proved to be extremely odd. Needless to say, I went around that day with a justified fear of cars, driving way more cautiously than I normally would, being more wary of pedestrian crossings, and so on. Sure enough, when I got back home, I found in the mail a large bill for a car repair expense, on the order of two months salary (thankfully, I have insurance). I suppose it could have been worse: I didn’t get into an accident myself, but the experience proved to be eerie.\nI mention this because it’s the first really “prophetic” dream that I’ve had. Of course, I can’t prove one way or another that this wasn’t coincidental, or that it has anything to do with my magical practice, but this seems to be an example of the kind of intuition that JMG often talks about as something that is developed through magical practice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7887339", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. Yes, that's the sort of thing that happens.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7858923", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I read an article recently that as of 2020, the video game industry is worth something like $135 billion worldwide. What are your thoughts on the growth of entertainment media in recent decades? It seems that the global Western monoculture has turned the consumption of pictures on a screen into the central cultural act, comparable to the role played by the Mass in Medieval Christendom.\nIt appears that Aldous Huxley (Brave New World), Marshall MacLuhan, Guy Debord (Society of the Spectacle), and others were right about the effects of electronic media, capitalism, and consumerism on society. In parallel with the accelerating crises of our civilization, we see the populations of the world, the privileged and increasingly the less privileged as well, retreating further into distractions. Do you see this as a disturbing trend, or an exercise of individual freedom?\n2. If you were to design a saner educational system, do you think that occultism might have a place in it? I came to this shore relatively late in life, after meandering around with philosophy, history, psychology, and so on, while having the vague impression that there was something else out there. It certainly would have helped people like me to be exposed to these ideas earlier on, and in a less distorted form.\n3 One long-term effect that I hope the coronavirus epidemic will have, is to teach us just how much economic activity can be stopped without affecting our quality of life that much, perhaps even improving it. International travel, the tourism industry, and their offshoots can be shut down overnight, and the planet would probably breathe a sigh of relief. Having people work from home instead of engaging in the useless 20th century ritual of commuting to an office can declog the cities at rush hour and spare everyone from a source of chronic stress. Another obvious lesson has to do with the importance of borders, and local production of essentials like food and medical equipment. In retrospect, I think it will be seen as a cheap lesson, which all too many people will be happy to ignore.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7888107", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I see it as a transitional phenomenon, not all that different from a fad.  The television age is barely 70 years old, and it's already losing ground as the monoculture of the networks gives way to interactive experiences and live-action activities begin to stage a comeback.  Much of what drives it, of course, is the simple dreariness and misery of life in an industrial society devoted to the mass production of ugliness and boredom; as that society continues to fray about the edges, I expect to see the obsession with media gradually lose its grip on the lower levels of society, while the privileged retreat further and further into an assortment of media-enabled fantasy worlds. That story does not have a good ending for the privileged...\n2) If I were to design a saner educational system, its core principle would be diversity of educational experience. I'd take the charter school principle and put the pedal to the metal, so that parents had a choice of schools for their kids with many radically different curricula on offer. The mandatory mediocrity of today's educational monoculture is one of the worst things about it; since we don't know what kind of education will do the best job of fitting children for a future we can't predict, having a very wide range of schools teaching different things is much wiser than insisting that every child learns exactly the same things. That being the case, it would be entirely suitable to have some schools that teach occult philosophy, just as there would be other schools that teach Christian theology, rationalist materialism, or what have you.\n3) It's not impossible that some of those lessons will be learnt.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7908587", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "I'd love to see someone drop a well-illustrated, impeccably-referenced book covering just how quickly and thoroughly the planet recovered when we all sat still for a couple of months in 2020.  Pictures of clear water running through the canals of Venice, satellite images comparing smog coverage over industrial China before and after the outbreak, that sort of thing.\nSuch a project might, just maybe, get at least a few people to drop their devout belief in phony-baloney Muskophilic bullshale in favor of some real problem solving approaches.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7915499", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That would be great. I wish I had the funds and the skill as a photographer!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7859179", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "One of the major topics of Jung’s work is the distinction between the conscious and unconscious minds, and how both aspects of the psyche have a certain kind of intelligence. As a former card-carrying member of the cult of rationalism, one way that I can be reconciled with astrology is that, relating it to Jung, it serves as a way to bring contents that are already present in the unconscious mind into consciousness. It seems that the framework of symbols allows the conscious mind to relax and provides an opportunity for the unconscious to speak up. I’ve begun to see it as an elaborate Rorschach test that bypasses the conscious mind with its filters and limitations and allows the unconscious contents to emerge. If Jung is correct, then the unconscious “speaks” in archetypes, and it is not surprising that nearly every technique of divination heavily relies on archetypes and symbolic representations of some kind.\nI don't mean by this to denigrate astrology, but I think the power of the technique is not so much in the stars as in ourselves. It is our own intuition about things that is generally correct, and can be honed with practice, but this intuition is primordial and difficult to express in language, which developed at a much later stage of human evolution, so it is through techniques of divination that we can tap into it and give it a voice. Moreover, to the chagrin of rationalists, these intuitions are not “scientific,” and don’t fit neatly into an experimental or empirical paradigm.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7888363", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If that set of interpretations works for you, then by all means run with it. Jung was a capable astrologer, btw, and interpreted the art much the same way you did. The one thing I'd encourage you to do is to keep an open mind about the one part of Jung's theory that rationalists tend to back away from -- his theory of synchronicity. You might find his book on the subject worth close study.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7859435", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "A few points this week:\n1) I finished the Fool's Journey last Thursday morning after 24 weeks of near-daily discursive meditation - the first sustained effort at meditation I've ever made!\n2) For the last few weeks I've been picking up a random smell here or there that didn't have anything to do with me or my family. The first was pipe tobacco one evening while I was reading in my armchair, the second was a lot less pleasant while taking a bath early one morning..., and the third was the smell of meat sauce (for spaghetti) made with pork sausage and bell peppers. We did our best to replicate it for dinner that night, and it was delicious and very satisfying. What's up with these smells from our old house? Am I slipping into her history on the astral plane? My wife says I breathe like I'm sleeping when I'm really focused on a book, and I often doze in the tub for sure.\n3) My wife has been looking into a TCM approach to helping me with my male parts, and has decided that I have \"excess yin.\" I've made several adjustments in my diet and activity to correct that and it's going pretty well. The spaghetti sauce I got via Betty Crocker's astral cookbook was one of those helpful things!\nWhen I started thinking about how my life was different in 2019 than before, the excess yin diagnosis made plenty of sense. I took a year off gardening, it rained a whole lot, I smoked a lot of weed, and (after not having indoor plumbing for 7 years) I took a hot bath almost every day in pure celebration of living in the 1st World again. The real issue began as the year turned cold in November too. All seem like very yin moves to me.\nI find this stuff fascinating and want to do a bunch more exploring down this rabbit hole. Any thoughts would be appreciated!\nGrover", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7888619", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Congratulations!\n2) Clairflairance, as I suppose you'd have to call it (from French\nclair\n, \"clear,\" and\nflairer\n, \"to smell or sniff\"), is a surprisingly common form of psychism. William Butler Yeats used to perceive phantom smells that alerted him to things -- burnt feathers, for example, when one of his children was getting ill, or cat urine when noxious spirits were about. You may be getting that effect.\n3) If the diagnosis and treatment seems to work for you, then go with it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7909099", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "2) \"Clairflatulence\" would be a good term for the second of the smells I picked up...hey, um, is it too late to take a pass on this particular superpower?? Could I trade it for the X-Ray vision glasses in the back of this skiffy mag perhaps?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7915755", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. You rolled the dice, and that's what turned up. Just as well -- if you had the kind of x-ray vision promised in those skiffy mags, and could see through clothing, just how many of the people you know would you really, truly want to see naked?", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7859691", "title": "Earthquake", "user": "kayr", "content": "Hi JMG,\nHere in Salt Lake we have recently experienced a 5.7 earthquake and of course, many smaller after shocks.  Naturally, everyone is unsettled by this.  Is there something from occult practice and thought that it would be good to know about this situation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7888875", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. Earthquakes are the province of geologists, not occultists.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7891179", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "kayr", "content": "Thanks.  Is there no effect on telleric currents then?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7893483", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Quite possibly, but that end of magical lore has been neglected for many centuries and I don't think anyone alive today knows what that effect might be.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7896299", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I heard the trumpet fell off of the statue of the angel on the main LDS temple. Is this true?  If so what kind of omen would it be?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7904235", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a fine theme for meditation!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7909355", "title": "Re: Earthquake", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "I recommend taking a gander at the Judgement trump in a standard tarot deck before you sit down to meditate on that one...", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7859947", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWhich books would you recommend to learn about polarity workings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7889387", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Dion Fortune's novels, especially\nThe Goat-Foot God\nand\nThe Sea Priestess\n. Most published nonfiction books about polarity magic are dreadfully bad -- Harris and Berg's\nPolarity Magic\nin particular, the most widely available example, is full of bad advice that will reliably blow up in your face. Fortune's novels, on the other hand, are full of useful lore.\nIf you can find a copy, Alan Richardson's book\nDancers to the Gods\n-- which gives the journals of two of Fortune's students -- is useful in correlation with the novels. It's out of print, though, and not too easy to find.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7889643", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How about \"The Keys to the Temple\" by Penny Billington & Ian Rees?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7893227", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I read it very quickly in draft in order to write a blurb for it, and my recollection is that it's pretty good, but I'm going to have to reread it to remember why I thought that. ;-)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7890411", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "I'm most of the way through Dion Fortune's \"The Sea Priestess\" and I for one can highly recommend it for that purpose!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7860971", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is it OK to do the Middle Pillar more than once a day? I do it once combined with the LBRP, but I got Regardie's book \"Art of True Healing\" and  want to work with it on its own. So I'm wondering about doing it twice - once with the LBRP, and once by itself, using some of Regardie's variations.\nAlso a question came to me about magically infused vinegars. I've been using them for a while (for magical, culinary, and medicinal purposes), and then I suddenly wondered: How does the vinegar hold a magical charge when vinegar is one of the most potent banishing substances?!?\nFinally, what, in your estimation, is the most accessible system(s) of divination? I'd like to incorporate a daily divination, but have struggled to commit to it. Partly it's the time it takes to interpet, reflect on, and revisit. I've worked mostly with geomancy and tarot, and while I find them ok, I'm wondering if there are others you'd suggest. Is the Coelbren system simple and straightforward?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7889899", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't recommend it -- you can overstrain yourself unless you've been practicing it for several years. Most people just do the LBRP and then practice Regardie's variations within the space thus cleansed.\n2) Good! Vinegar works for the purpose of banishing because it dissolves forms on the lower etheric plane, which is where many noxious spirits and some kinds of nasty magic do their work. Aromatic plant compounds, by contrast, function on the upper end of the etheric plane where it borders on the astral -- that's why they can have such powerful effects on human emotions and passions, which are astral phenomena. So an herbal vinegar is doubly effective, because it sweeps the lower etheric plane clean and then puts a beneficial influence into the upper etheric plane.\n3) That varies wildly from person to person. Some people find geomancy very accessible -- I'm one of them -- and have a much harder time with, say, runes; for others, it's the other way around. I'd encourage you to try several other oracles and see which ones work best for you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7861227", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the role/significance of the in-breath and out-breath during affirmations? Is it essential?\nI've been using it with one affirmation without any particular attention to breath and am getting good results. I'm ok if doing it without regard to breath makes it somewhat less potent, but I don't want to work against myself if that's a concern.  I tried a second affirmation coordinated with breath, based on your suggestion on a previous MM, and I found that the focus on breath coordination distracted me and stressed me out. Is it ok to leave the breath aspect aside for now and work with the affirmation anyway?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7890155", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course you can set it aside if it doesn't work for you. Most people find that it helps, but you're not \"most people.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7861483", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recently read a book on daily life in the 1950s, and it really drove something home to me: TV dramatically changed things, very quickly going from a toy for the rich to the centre of American society.\n1) Given the nature of occultism, TV, since its on the material plane, is not a cause, but an effect. From an occult perspective, what caused it to effectively take over America in the 1950s? What changed which brought such a destructive force into manifestation so suddenly?\n2) Are there subtle effects of putting it in such a central place? Do you know anything which discusses the matter, from any perspective?\n3) TV seems to be at the heart of the consumer economy. I'm assuming this is because it allows advertisers access to people's imaginations in a way that earlier technologies didn't. Do you have advice for how to reclaim my mind? I'm taking the first step of avoiding it as much as possible, but screens are everywhere.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7890923", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) America in the 1950s was obsessed with imposing a fictional image of reality over the top of what was actually happening. Television was an expression of that, a way of manufacturing fake \"experiences\" that had no existence off the screen.\n2) Yes.  Marie Winn's classic book\nThe Plug-In Drug\nis one place to start learning about them.\n3) Television is meant to replace your imagination with images manufactured for you by corporate sponsors. The first thing to do is to stop watching, of course. The second thing to do is to cultivate your own imagination as much as possible -- via a creative art if that appeals to you, and if not, simply by encouraging yourself to put time every day into daydreaming. You might also consider starting a dream journal, recording your dreams as soon as you wake up, and think about them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7891691", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not OP) Fascinating. So instead of imagining, say, myself becoming a competent mage or musician, TV replaces that with images of me driving the latest truck, so that I focus my willpower on \"achieving\" that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7892971", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Exactly. That's not a bug, either -- it's a feature.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7896811", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Somethings never change....\n2) Thank you!\n3) Well, then my budding music hobby is a good thing to work on!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7861739", "title": "vibrating deity names", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is more of a question for the commentariat: Are there videos available that include someone vibrating divine names? I've been trying to vibrate names for a couple months now during my SOP, and I've been a choral singer for decades, but I feel like I'm not getting it quite right as I rarely feel any vibration. I thought it might help to see and hear someone else doing it.\nThanks all for this wonderful forum. I look forward to this every week.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7862763", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I tried recording it, and found it doesn't quite capture it. I wonder if JMG could discuss it more, but I think recording devices miss the subtle planes, and so I never can get a good result from a recording.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7864299", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Here's a video I made of myself doing the SoP, vibrating the names.  Hope this helps:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dsD3LkfgFVs\n\"Vibrating\" technique: Try humming through your closed lips as loud as you can, until it's a buzzing sound through your upper palate.  Then open your mouth.  Practice incessantly this until the sound is quite focused/projected.  This technique is of course helpful for singers of all types.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7871211", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Aha, so it doesn't need to be loud. That makes it hard to detect by watching a video. Thanks for the description! It looks like I need to put in the time feeling how the vibration changes with any change in mouth and tongue positions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7911915", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Correct!  It does NOT have to be loud.  In fact, you'll get better at it much faster if you start with a soft head voice (\"falsetto\" in guys is the same thing as head voice, it's the soft, mousy, baby-ish, high part of your voice) and you gradually focus it like a laser beam, being observant to the changes.  Just as it's an angle of air that produces sound in a transverse flute, not simply the amount of air, it's the way you shape the air column that produces vocal vibration effect.  I'm planning on doing a video on how to do a hybrid or mixed voice -- I will try to post it here next Monday.  The technique is used in all sorts of singing.  It's singers who DON'T use it, for instance Adele and Meatloaf, who end up losing the ability to sing because of vocal nodes.  One person who uses the vibrated head/chest mixed voice undetectably is Idina Menzel.  I'm not a huge fan of her genre, but my hat is off to her where vocal technique is concerned.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7875819", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "Kimberly, I got chills every time you sang the names of the deities.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7911403", "title": "Re: vibrating deity names", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Awww, thanks.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7862251", "title": "Hexagram rituals", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,\nAny tips on the correct performance of the Supreme Hexagram ritual? Regardie's book is a bit confusing in that part...\nAlso, I'm curious why you chose to give Greater hexagram rituals in Circles of Power. If I understand Regardie's descriptions for the lesser version, you can use that to invoke/banish the various forces of a specific planet by tracing from the point associated with that planet. And he uses the 4 forms of the hexagram rather than the earth form at each quarter.\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7891435", "title": "Re: Hexagram rituals", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The original Golden Dawn papers give only two hexagram rituals, the Lesser and the Supreme -- the former using the 4 forms, the latter using the standard (earth) form. In\nCircles of Power\n, I used the term \"Greater Ritual of the Hexagram\" for what the GD papers call the Supreme RoH, and I used the standard (earth) hexagram throughout because I found that it gave better results in practice. Of course your mileage may vary.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7862507", "title": "Astral static", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The phrase \"astral static\" came up on the other blog.  Can you elaborate a little on how this manifests in one's awareness in everyday life and in meditation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7891947", "title": "Re: Astral static", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. The astral plane is the plane of concrete consciousness, the realm where most of our ordinary thinking takes place as well as the realm of imagination and dreams. It's not an empty void waiting for our minds to fill it -- there's plenty happening there all the time, and very often the thoughts that \"enter our heads\" do exactly that, and come from outside. That's astral static. Some of those outside thoughts are fully formed patterns of thinking that radiate from a human or nonhuman source; others are the broken fragments of old thoughts and feelings and daydreams; and the lowest sub-plane of the astral plane is full of astral crud, heaped up like garbage after a wild party. That's why in some states of mind, all sorts of random junk will come seeping into your mind out of no source you can trace. The more you can attune your mind to the higher sub-planes of the astral, the less you have to deal with such things.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7908075", "title": "Re: Astral static", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7863019", "title": "confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG and thank you for hosting this forum.\nI am pecking this out on my phone and apologize if it isn't all that coherent.\nI'm sure you are getting tired of dealing with the coronavirus questions, but this is only indirectly related. I live in New Orleans and the virus has impacted this city more so than most (likely due to Mardi Gras last month). While I tend to fall into the camp that feel like the world is overreacting to the virus, I cannot deny that I am cycling between to high anxiety/panic and the smug feeling that everyone else is losing their minds over nothing (not literally \"nothing\", just overreacting.)\nMy questions:\n1. Is there a name for someone that is \"tapped into the zeitgeist\" or Jung's collective subconscious (or whatever it is I feel)? I have always been sort of tuned into others feelings, both on individual levels and across communities.\n2. What can you recommend for dealing with this, whether developing it for some reason or trying to minimize it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7892203", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The usual term is \"empath.\"\n2) I'm very nearly the last person on Earth to ask about this, as I have Aspergers syndrome and so am on the opposite end of the spectrum -- I don't perceive other people's feelings at all. Anyone else have suggestions?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7902699", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can share what's worked for me so far, though I'm still near the beginning of my journey with recognizing and working with my empathic qualities.\nIt seems to me that the key is coming to a clear awareness of the energies as they affect you. This is hard, because at first they feel overwhelming, and have a tendency to sweep you along with them. So anything that helps you \"see around the edges\" of the influences will help.\nIn my spiritual system (the Tibetan religion of Bön), we have specific techniques for developing \"spaciousness\", such as putting your attention on the vastness of space, or trying to hear the underlying music of silence. But anything that helps you develop stability of mind, and a sense that \"I am not [only] this energy\" should help. Journaling about what you're sensing and feeling might be an easy place to start.\nIt's also been surprisingly helpful just to recognize that empathy is a powerful gift when used well, and that it's worth learning how to manage the overwhelm that comes with it. At least for me, it's easy to interpret it as something being \"broken\", but really it's more like having a really acute sense of hearing: very useful, if you can manage to keep your eardrums from blowing out!\nI hope this helps at least a little. Good luck with the journey!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7912427", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for this, it sounds like a good start.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7909611", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am somewhat in the middle - I suspect I'd be diagnosed as at least mildly Aspergers if I were tested, but I also can sense some kinds of emotions fairly strongly (mainly the ones related to fear and aggression).  I'm also Christian--I can't say if these things would work for non-Christians.\nFor me, some churches - particularly older, stone or brick churches with a history of liturgical worship (generally Catholic or Anglican/Episcopal) are sane-making.  Just spending time in one regularly helps a great deal with thinking clearly, and not being overwhelmed by the mixture of being jostled by other people's emotions and finding people unpredictable.  I also find praying the Rosary, and visualizing the mysteries, to be very helpful to maintaining balance and clarity of mind.\nSamChevre", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7912683", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for giving this phenomenon a name! I have been reluctant to allow Dune to be my guide on this issue.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7893995", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "violetcabra", "content": "From what you describe my experiences are pretty similar to yours.  If my experiences are anything to go on you might be stuck with the receptivity for the rest of your life and probably beyond.  I wrote my little book on spiritual cleaning and protection (\nhttp://www.lulu.com/shop/http://www.lulu.com/shop/violet-bertelsen/spiritual-cleaning-and-protection/paperback/product-24466073.html\n) in large part in order to cope with this. I found that by cultivating a spiritual clean and protected space and aura I could find a measure of relief.  To sum up the book very briefly, prayer, banishing rituals, natural magic as discussed on the Magic Monday FAQ and in the subtler end of herbal literature seem to work very well.\nEdited (spelling error)\nDate:\n2020-03-23 11:18 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7913195", "title": "Re: confused", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks to you as well violet, I have appreciated your contributions to Mr. Greer's blogs over the years and will delve into your linked book as time permits in the next few days.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7863275", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If you had truly unlimited resources for occult research, so you could do the same for magic that the Soviet Union did for sports science, what would the priorities be? Where would you start?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7892459", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not JMG,\nIn that case, occult research would seize to be \"occult\" anymore, and would become a part of the mainstream science (for better or worse).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7893739", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Correction to my typo: cease to be (not \"seize to be\").", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7892715", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd start by improving magical education, because that's the sort of project that would require a lot of people who know their way around the history, philosophy, and practice of occultism. A good standard edition of the classic works would be one place to start; a school, probably online to start with, that would teach a good general curriculum in occult studies and certify those who had successfully completed it, would be another. A third would be to fund good English translations of the many important occult works that aren't available in any modern language, or are only available in one; English has become the de facto language of scholarship in much of the world, so getting a good set of English translations would make research much easier.\nThose would be enough to keep me busy for the rest of this incarnation. The next steps in the process would be up to a new generation of researchers, and would depend on what the first steps opened up.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7863531", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG-\nI have a question on the middle pillar exercise. I've done it for years in the form you give out in LRM, but recently I bought and read Regardie's True Healing, and decided to try his version, which visualizes/circulates energy a bit differently. I have a few questions:\n1) When I do Regardie's version I can very clearly sense a glowing shell of light/energy on the out-breath, but nothing even close to the same on the in-breath... is that expected?\n2) Was there any particular reason for the form of MP you gave in LRM as opposed to others? (I'm aware of quite a few variations and have done my own to direct energy in various ways when I needed to heal a weak point, for instance).\n3) One of the reasons I bought True Healing was it seemed like it might make a good gift for those not necessarily completely comfortable learning a whole system, a gateway drug if you will. But then, I've always banished before doing the MP, is it safe to do it in the absence of any banishing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7895275", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's quite common. Concentrate on the idea of there being a glowing shell of light/energy while you're breathing in, and you'll have improved results.\n2) I give a different version of the MP in nearly every single book where I teach it at all. That's partly to frustrate would-be fundamentalists, and partly to stress that there are many different ways to do the ritual.\n3) Given the current state of collective consciousness, I wouldn't do it without a banishing first!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7864811", "title": "plant alchemy", "user": "ritaer", "content": "JMG,\nI am thinking of planting some herbs to give a try to the plant alchemy in your Natural Magic book. St. Johns Wort seemed like a good one to try, but I thought of trying a moon related plant as well. Any recommendations? I live in Sacramento, CA area.\nStay well,\nRita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7895787", "title": "Re: plant alchemy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you considered Rosemary? It's assigned to the Moon by some writers, and it balances St. John's Wort nicely.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7865579", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nDo you think that facing towards the direction of Kaaba in Muslim prayer have an occult reason? If so, what can it be?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7896043", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a way of directing power toward the egregor of the Muslim faith. Many religions have such arrangements in place as ways to concentrate energy on their collective egregor, so that the religion retains its emotional and spiritual power.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7906027", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does iconoclasm also serve a similar purpose?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7916011", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's meant to destroy other centers and focal patterns of power.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7865835", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Archdruid,\nIs it true that Knights Templar revered Mahomed (given their relations with Ismaili Order of Assassins), and their persecutors mistook it as \"Baphomet\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7896555", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, there's something much subtler going on with that name. In traditional Jewish Cabala, it's common to conceal holy names using various ways of encoding, and one of the simplest is called the \"Atbash cipher.\" What that word means is that you flip the Hebrew alphabet, so that the first letter and the last letter are exchanged, the second and the next to last, and so on. Thus Aleph is replaced by Tau and Tau by Aleph, Beth is replaced by Shin and Shin by Beth. So if you write Baphomet in Hebrew -- Beth, Peh, Vau, Mem, Tau -- and you put it though the Atbash cipher, you get Shin, Vau, Peh, Yod, Aleph...which is the Hebrew spelling of the name of Sophia, the Gnostic goddess of wisdom.\nThat was the secret of the Templars. They encountered, most likely in the Holy Land, one of the surviving Gnostic sects, and adopted that as their secret teaching. I'm pretty sure, for reasons Jessie Weston covered in her book\nFrom Ritual to Romance\n, that it was either a Naassene sect or something similar -- one that saw Christian orthodoxy as incomplete rather than wrong. But that's why the Catholic church turned with such savagery on the Templars: the Church had just finished committing genocide against one set of Gnostics, the Cathars, in southern France, and all of a sudden another set of Gnostics popped up right in the heart of the Church's most powerful military order. (Of course the greed of Philip IV of France also had a lot to do with the fate of the Templars; it was, as most historical events were, overdetermined.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7902443", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Did the Templars outside of France (which survived persecution) at that time transmit those Gnostic teachings to the following generations or other societies?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7904491", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's some reason to believe that they did so in Scotland and Germany, at least, but for obvious reasons it was kept very quiet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7906539", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How about the Neo-Templar and Neo-Cathar groups which surfaced in 19th century France? Is there any evidence that there is a continuity between these and the old Templars' teachings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7916267", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't had the chance to look into those lineages -- kind of odd, as I've inherited two of them via initiations I've received. There was certainly something live and potent in both of those, but what its source was is a question I can't vouch for.\nOne thing to keep in mind is that when a lineage goes extinct, it's sometimes possible to pick it up on the inner planes and bring the old energy back down into manifestation again. That's pretty clearly what happened with the system of magic taught in my book\nThe Celtic Golden Dawn\n-- its rituals have much more kick to them than a newly invented set of rituals should have, and I'm pretty sure that what's behind that is that I got close enough to the workings used by the old Druid/Golden Dawn hybrid orders that the contacts were picked up and the energies of those older traditions flowed into the new one.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7903467", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Many thanks for this, John Michael!  That clears something up nicely for me.  I have been wondering, on and off, about \"Baphomet\" for many, many years.  Yours is the first and only explanation that feels right.\nCertainly there were (and probably still are, very much on the QT) Gnostic communities in the Middle East at the time the Templars were there.\n\"Baphomet\" also figures prominently as the master hieroglyph in ibn Washiyyah's Arabic-language treatise on ancient writing systems and alphabets, written about two centuries before the Templar order was founded.  Here's a link to his image of the master hieroglyphic itself:\nhttps://www.pinterest.com.mx/pin/306737424599967452/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7904747", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hugh Schonfield, of all people, seems to have been the first person in modern times to notice this. (I suspect that Cabalistically literate occultists in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were aware of it but kept it as a very secret teaching.) I had the same reaction -- \"Okay,\nthat\nmakes sense of it!\"\nThat's fascinating, about ib Washiyyah. Do you happen to know if that work of his has been translated?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7907563", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "It has been translated, and into English at that, by an Austrian scholar named Joseph von Hammer-Purgstall: \"Ancioent Alphabets and Hieroglyphic Characters Explained; with an Account of the Egyptian Priests, their Classes, Initiation, and Sacrifices\" (1806).  See pp. 22-31 of the English opart, and p. 90ff. of the Arabic.  You can find a PDF at hathitrust.org and very likely in other places as well.\nHammer-Purgstall also published an entire monograph on Baphomet in Latin, which I haven't read yet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7917035", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens -- Hammer-Purgstall, of all people! His monograph on Baphomet has usually been considered a hatchet job worked up on Metternich's orders as propaganda against Freemasonry and other secret societies of the time, especially the Carbonari; Peter Partner's useful history\nThe Murdered Magicians: The Knights Templar and their Myth\ndiscusses this. On the other hand, Partner didn't mention the book by ibn Washiyyah, which I just located and downloaded; many thanks for the heads up.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7926507", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I just checked, and the Internet Archive has three different scans of Hammer-Purgstall's \"Ancient Alphabets\" as well as a quite recent English translation of his \"Mysterium Baphometis Revelata.\" You'll have to search for \"Joseph Hammer\" without \"Purgstall.\"\nIbn Washiyya also authored a massive and extremely valuable work on agricultural magic, \"The Nabatean Agriculture.\"  My colleague here at Brown, the late David Pingree (who could read Arabic and about a dozen and a half other dead languages as easily as English) thought it one of the most significant occult treatises  ever written in Arabic.  It's never been translated into any Western language, but not too long ago a good summary appeared (with translations of selected long passages):   Jaakko Hameen-Anttila, \"The Last Pagans of Iraq: Ibn Washiyya and his Nabatean Agriculture\" (2006).\nI read some of Hugh Schonfield's books a very long time ago, but I must have missed or forgotten what he had to say about Baphomet -- alas!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7908843", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "By the way, when you mentioned Naassenes (which must be related to the word \"nachash\" - serpent in Hebrew), it reminded me of an interesting book that I have recently started to read - \"The Serpent Grail\" by Philip Gardiner and Gary Osborn. In that book, the authors investigate the serpent symbolism in various myths around the world as a healing and enlightenment symbol and it's possible relation to Grail legends. So far I haven't seen them mentioning Naassenes, but given the common sponsorship of Templars and early Grail romance writers (plus the abundance of dragon symbolism in earlier Celtic grail/cauldron legends), it wouldn't be far fetched to relate Templars to a serpent-revering branch of Gnosticism.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7866091", "title": "Bellingham", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG,\nI’ve been in Bellingham for the last 25 years or so. Would the occult bookstore you mentioned happen to be Widdershins? It closed shortly after I moved here, but I knew the woman who owned it. She was an important member of the local pagan community, but unfortunately passed away last year.\nAs a data point, it baffles me every time you post something about the decline of Neopaganism, as the pagan community here is growing and thriving. A local NROOGD/Georgian Wiccan coven has been revitalized with young people, although I declined to join as Wicca isn’t my thing. Several other groups have been formed due to the limitations inherent in covens. However, as a loosely coordinated collective of various traditions, we as a community have been putting on public ritual events for all 8 of the seasonal Wheel of the Year rituals consistently for 10 years. That is, up until disease panic forced the cancelling of the recent Ostara ritual. Perhaps Neopaganism is failing elsewhere, since we draw people from several counties away and even Canada, but it doesn’t seem so from here. We average about 80 people per ritual, and concern has arisen for the limitations of the space we use as we continue to grow. Maybe we are fortunate to have several skilled ritualists to take responsibility for each event. I only get to lead one per year, but distributing responsibility for the rituals prevents burnout. Anyway, we seem to have a working model and I thought I’d mention it.\nSarkos", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7897323", "title": "Re: Bellingham", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope, the bookstore I have in mind was called Akasha, and it was open for business in the early 1980s -- I lived in Bellingham from 1980 through 1983. As for Neopaganism, I'm glad to hear it. Though I'm not a Neopagan myself, I know a lot of people have found Neopaganism spiritually satisfying, and it's good to know that at least in some places things are still continuing.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7868395", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nWhat kind of practice would you suggest as a substitute for those who can not practice daily rituals, and who revere a panentheistic principle rather than personified deities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7897579", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You might want to talk to some panentheists and see what they recommend.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7900395", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As far as I know, a simple daily ritual is composed of three general steps:\n1- Relaxing and centering the body, emotions and thoughts.\n2- Invoking a higher power (or multiple powers or deities).\n3- Formulating a protective shield to banish unwanted or excessive energies.\nI guess, in step 2, one can invoke an impersonal principle (the One/All/Tao/etc.) instead of anthropomorphic deities.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7901163", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I thought you said that you couldn't do any daily rituals...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7903979", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hahahaha :)\nI only have some basic theoretical knowledge about these rituals, but I couldn't practice them because I was worried (an I am still worried) about being influenced by the egregor of a particular religion or a quasi-religious group.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7868651", "title": "4chan at it again", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi JMG\nShould we be concerned about this?\nhttps://imgur.com/7ikT5iF\nmany thanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7899115", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Given that their attempt to start a worldwide Ebola pandemic via Ebola-chan failed completely, I'm not too worried. It'll be interesting to see if the pandemic starts fading out now that this is under way; if so, that'll be a good indication that the chans have fallen victim to what we should probably call the Hughes effect -- the form of magical blowback in which the results of a spell are the opposite of those at which the spell was ostensibly aimed.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7901675", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you think this effect might inhere to publicized, participatory internet workings?  It seems that it this has happened with most internet workings that I know of that posted all the details, intent, etc.  Do you know if there have been successful internet workings where all the details were made public?  I can't think of any off the top of my head.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7917547", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Every example I can think of has either failed dismally or has blown up in the faces of the people who were doing it. You may well be on to something!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7905259", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "Italy's new cases have notably decreased over the past couple of days.  That's probably more to do with being on lockdown day 11 than anything else, but if astral effects can propagate backward in time...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7917291", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, they apparently started the working two days ago, and to judge by the blowback from Hughes' workings -- do you recall the way that he launched his attempt to stop Kavanaugh from being confirmed to the Supreme Court, and all resistance to the confirmation within a few hours? -- the Hughes Effect seems to be more or less instantaneous...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7920875", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You hypothesized that the Hughes Effect is due to people screwing with the ritual once they know the method, right? I'm wondering what would be an effective way to do that here. Perhaps reframing the transfer of energy as a propitiatory offering, and asking the visualized being to accept it and depart in peace? Anyone have any other ideas? I really enjoy these magical warfare case studies that crop up here from time to time!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7922411", "title": "Re: 4chan at it again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, there are lots of ways to mess with it. One that comes first to mind is to work on the connection between Corona-chan and Corona brand beer -- the original Corona-chan image has a bottle of the beer in one hand. You could change the chant into a set of syllables that amount to \"buy lots of Corona beer\" in Hittite, or what have you, and redirect the whole thing into making profits for the beer company. That's akin to the folks who messed with Hughes' working against Kavanaugh by adding the words \"of Canada\" to Hughes' \"you will never sit on the High Court\" -- you can always give the energy an easy way to flow, and bleed it off.\nThere are plenty of other options, ranging from the hilarious to the really rather nasty, but you get the idea.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7869163", "title": "SOP, affirmations, and sigils", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, I have quite a few questions for you today. Thank you in advance for taking the time to read and answer!\n\n\n1) I've been practicing the SOP, as described in your Magic Monday series, for several weeks now, although I'm taking it slow (only up to the calling of Air so far). I'm interested in testing out the version with the Circulation of Light, as I've seen several commenters remark that it seems to pack more of a punch. Do you think it would cause any problems if I continued my regular morning practices with the MM ritual, while testing out the older version in the evenings? \n\n2) If you think that should work ok, how would you recommend adapting the opening and closing invocations for use in a Christian context? The \"Father\" and \"Son\" would appear to work the same in both, but I'm not quite sure how to convert the \"Holy Spirit\" portion from arising out of the Earth to the four horizontal beams of light. My best guess would be something like: \n- raise arms up to side, beam of light rises up to fill body, say \"And of the Holy Spirit\"\n- Beam extending to the right: \"May the Lord's power protect me\"\n- Beam extending to the left: \"May the Lord's mercy bless me\"\n- Beam extending back to front: \"May the lord lead me into eternal life\" (alt: \"May the Lord's will be done on Earth as it is in Heaven\")\n- Cross arms: \"AMEN\"\nDoes that seem workable to you? (I would also welcome feedback from any commenters who have experimented with a Christian version of this ritual)\n\n3)I'd like to start using an affirmation to improve my work ethic. The one I had in mind was \"I achieve my goals through dedication and focus\". Do you see any obvious traps in that phrasing?\n\n4)You've mentioned that affirmations and sigils work on the same principles. Is it ever helpful to combine them - say, create a sigil out of your chosen affirmation to carry with you, display in your work space, use as a visualization, etc? \n\n\nThanks again for this invaluable resource!\n\n-Fred N", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7900907", "title": "Re: SOP, affirmations, and sigils", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'd recommend choosing one version or the other, and stick with that for the time being. Twice a day can be too much for beginners.\n2) For the Christian SoP, the standard approach is the Sign of the Cross, exactly as it's done in ordinary Christian churches: same words, same gestures, visualizing the four rays shining out at once as you say, \"and the Holy Ghost.\" You can certainly try the more complex version you've sketched out here, though.\n3) That should work fine.\n4) I haven't tried this, but it would be worth experimenting with.\n3)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7918059", "title": "Re: SOP, affirmations, and sigils", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! That makes sense, I had wondered at one point whether it could be adapted to use the Sign of the Cross. One more question that I forgot to ask earlier: since the initial rays are visualized as radiating out to infinity, in theory the circles/sphere formed by the rotation would as well. Is that the way you generally picture it, or do you just kind of fudge it and picture the sphere as stopping at a certain distance from yourself?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7922667", "title": "Re: SOP, affirmations, and sigils", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I fudge it and put the sphere about 6 feet out in every direction.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7870955", "title": "Weird of Hali", "user": "emskewis", "content": "Hi JMG:  Ok, this may be a weird question. There were a number of deities I got to really like while reading the Weird of Hali books. Are these beings part of a operative pantheon and can they safely met and worked with. I particularly like Youndeh and Nylarthotep. Thanks, Elizabeth in Seattle", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7901931", "title": "Re: Weird of Hali", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Several other people have had the same reaction. I'm a little unsure what to say, as I tend to discourage people from using fictional pantheons in magic -- the results are generally just as fictional -- but at this point people have been invoking Lovecraft's pantheon in magical work since Kenneth Grant started the New Isis Lodge in 1954, and apparently getting good results, so this may be the tentacular exception that proves the rule.\nYou might be interested in\nthe Weird of Hali Tree of Life\n, which I worked out while writing the books. I also worked out, at the request of another reader, a version of the Sphere of Protection for the WoH version of the Lovecraft pantheon. The directions are assigned as follows:\nEast/Air: Nyarlathotep\nWest/Water: Cthulhu\nSouth/Fire: Phauz\nNorth/Earth: Yhoundeh\nSpirit Below: Shub- Ne'hurrath\nSpirit Above: Hastur\nInstead of \"by the hawk of May in the heights of morning\" et al., of course, suitably eldritch language can be used...\nBy the winds that blow from the peaks of Leng...\nBy the waves that roll over drowned R'lyeh...\nBy the undying flame in the temples of Khem...\nBy the depths of the earth where the shoggoths dwell...\n...and so on. Have fun!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7873003", "title": "Pentagrams", "user": "weirdtales", "content": "Just reading Violet's little book on Spritual Cleaning and Protection and an issue has come to my attention. She describes the banishing pentagrams she draws as \"starting at the top and going downwards to the left...\" And for invoking, \"starting on the bottom left and going upwards...\"\nIn the LBRP, I do my banishing pentagram the 2nd way, the way she describes for invoking, as it's described on p. 378 in \"Paths of Wisdom.\" As someone who's been dealing with a very uncomfortable health issue for the last 4 months, I just want to make sure I'm not messing myself over with this, inviting trouble into my life potentially.\nSeems like something that would have an objective \"right way\" to do it to me...\nThanks as always for your time!\nGrover", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7917803", "title": "Re: Pentagrams", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, there's no \"objective right way,\" any more than there's an objectively right word for that four-legged barking critter facing you. Is it a dog, un chien, or ein Hund?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7876331", "title": "Book info?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey hey JMG,\nAre you familiar with \"The History and Practice of Magic\" by Paul Christian?  It was my father's and I am curious but I don't remember having heard you mention it before.  Do you know anything about it?  Reliable, potential issues, etc?\nThanks,\nTim", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7918315", "title": "Re: Book info?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a classic piece of 19th-century occult literature, thus worth careful study but veiling what it has to say under various evasive maneuvers. The English translation was edited by Ross Nichols, the founder of the Order of Bards Ovates and Druids and a first-rate occultist, so it's certainly worth study.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7880683", "title": "SOP/DMH protective workings", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG.\nThank you for another Magic Monday.\nMy partner is currently entering the second trimester of pregnancy with our 3rd child. We are both fortunate enough to be able to work from home temporarily with the pandemic, and are taking all the precautions we can since the potential effects of this virus on pregnancy are unknown.\nI practice my SOP in my own room where usually only I am. I wondered if there were any safe health protection workings (for mother and foetus) that you might recommend, bearing in mind that I am still new to this?\nI noted the water blessing one that you posted before: I am happy to try this, but just wondered if there was something more you might recommend.\nI tried to find the instructions for the latter without success: from memory it is simply to trace the water banishing symbol over the glass of water (presumably with intent to banish anything negative) then imagine golden light streaming down from the hand to charge the water?\nMany many thanks for all your diligent help,\nMorfran", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7918571", "title": "Re: SOP/DMH protective workings", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Since you're still a beginner, this isn't the time to do any major workings. Use the water blessing -- yes, you've got the right method -- and when you're doing the SoP, invoke blessings on the entire household, and banish all harmful influences from your partner and unborn child as well as from yourself.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7882731", "title": "Consent in Beneficent Group Workings", "user": "tunesmyth", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have a question that came to mind after the idea of a group working to help magically support Magic Monday readers who are going through tough financial times due to corona virus.\nWould you say it is necessary to receive consent from the targets of a purely beneficent working, if the targets are a large and often changing group of people? Such as in the theoretical case of a working for the benefit of \"Magic Monday Readers\", who for the most part are probably open to being helped in this way?\nAnd if you think so, would you say that the following is a workable way to achieve consent without harming the effectiveness of the working?\nEvery week for the duration that the working is performed, one of the people involved in the working posts a short notice stating that there is an ongoing group working to benefit the Magic Monday community; and that if the person reading it is open to being affected in positive ways by it, that they just give a quick moment of mental assent. (And if not, just not to worry about it.)\nOn the negative side, this would confirm and continually advertise the existence of such a working, which might leave it open to destabilization by mischievous forces.\nDo you have any guidance to offer on the matter?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7918827", "title": "Re: Consent in Beneficent Group Workings", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you need to have consent, and you can get it that way -- but you would certainly be at risk of attracting hostile forces. As for the offlist stuff, drop me an email; yes, I have some suggestions.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7883755", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "After reading The Magical Battle of Britain I’m starting to think that one of the objectives of practicing magic is to establish a link between the material and spiritual worlds.\nIt seems to be a mutually beneficial arrangement too; the human is being lifted to a higher plane of consciousness and receives all the blessings and joy there.\nThe gods and spirits seem to be interested in the material world, but they don’t have physical bodies and matter seems to be too dense for them, so they need conduits for their power to perform their works in the material world.\nSo maybe this is one of the reasons why magic is called the Hermetic Art, because it is Hermes’s work was to establish connection between mortals and the spirit world (messages from gods and guiding souls to the underworld).\nDo you think there is something valuable to this line of thinking?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7919083", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well done. You've grasped a central them in Dion Fortune's theory of magic -- one that gets misplaced a lot of the time. Yes, it's not merely valuable but essential.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7884011", "title": "The Spirits of the Land", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear ArchDRuid,\nAs a fourth generation American whose ancestry goes back to two European lands, I wonder about the idea of working and developing a connection with the spirits of the land, when in a sense I don't have a land, at least not in the way generations after generations of native Americans did, for example.\nI wonder if we are in a way 'starting over' like the tribes that came across the Bering straights must have done. But they had an animistic outlook that kept them connected, and a cohesive tribal culture, whereas we modern wanderers are shackled with the idea of scientific materialism, and have no tribe like our ancestors did.\nTo make it even more fluid, I now reside in a desert region in the Middle East, far from any of my ancestors, or the land I was raised in, North America.\nI believe you have wondered some yourself: I just wonder how long it takes to establish a real connection with the land, and what happens when we suddenly change the land we live on?\nFrom Under the Acacias,\nGunnar", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7919339", "title": "Re: The Spirits of the Land", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It takes generations, and normally it also takes several generations of ancestors buried in the region where you live. Lacking that, there are earth contacts you simply can't pick up, and it's necessary do do without them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7920363", "title": "Re: The Spirits of the Land", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "How large would you consider a region? Say I have anscestors buried through the North central Appalachians, in WV and PA, would a part of NY that has a similar feel, and part of the general \"north-central Appalachian region\" be part of what you would consider a \"region\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7922923", "title": "Re: The Spirits of the Land", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to figure that out by experiment.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7886827", "title": "God, The Unified Theory, and Agnosticism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Arch Druid,\nI wanted to ask you about the final reality.  Whatever that thing is that rests at the bottom of cause and effect, jump started the big bang, or however else you want to describe it, what is it like?\nDo you think of this thing as a personal God akin to something out of the world religions?  Something with a personality and desires?  Something that we can have a relationship with?  If so, do you pray to that entity?\nConversely, do you think of it as an abstract principle?  Something like a Platonic form or the unified theory of physics?\nOr are you generally agnostic about this and default to saying we are social primates with six inch brains and probably should keep that in mind?\nOr is there another possibility I left out?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7919595", "title": "Re: God, The Unified Theory, and Agnosticism", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Human beings aren't capable of knowing anything about the final reality. Our brains are six inch long masses of fatty meat, so limited they're not even capable of solving the three-body problem. All we can work with are our own experiences and the symbolic statements that have been handed down by others. That being the case, I don't worry about it, and keep busy with the things I can actually know.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7921387", "title": "Re: God, The Unified Theory, and Agnosticism", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "What about the possibility of transcending the human by becoming a more essential self? Franklin Merrell-Wolff (and others) report not only contacting this Ground of Being, but Being it at their core.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7923179", "title": "Re: God, The Unified Theory, and Agnosticism", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the reasons I value classic occult philosophy is that it stresses just how much higher the Great Chain of Being extends above us. Of course it's possible to transcend the human -- but that moves us one notch up the ladder, not instantly all the way to the top. Mind you, that one notch is an immense, life-changing experience from our standpoint...but from the standpoint of the cosmos, it's a little like moving from a life as a blue-green alga to life as a paramecium. A paramecium has vastly greater capacities than a blue-green alga; it has cilia that enable it to move, and chemical senses that allow it to \"sniff\" its surroundings; it inhabits a much vaster world than a blue-green alga, and were an alga to suddenly gain the state of conciousness of a paramecium, it would doubtless think that it had risen to the ultimate ground of being. Meanwhile we watch them both through microscopes.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7887851", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm getting into astrology and working my way through my progressed chart, trying to get a sense of how the various aspects manifested in my life, but I've noticed something odd: I have two aspects involving outer planets, a Saturn-Neptune sextile and a Uranus-Pluto sextile, which have both been within a degree of being exact in my progressed chart my entire life.\nI haven't found much which describe what to do with outer planets aspects, but am I correct to think that those aspects are always active, and form the background, sometimes much stronger (when something else is involved), but always on, so to speak?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7919851", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Outer planet progressions are normally very slow -- those same sextiles should also appear in your natal chart, for example -- and most astrologers simply take them as they appear in the natal chart, which is of course the background for every progression.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7889131", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "miz_bean", "content": "I am so grateful for the kindness and support. I'm learning to trust and willing to try.\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7920107", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7897067", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nI was the commenter one or two weeks ago who asked you about the problem of evil, and how different prophetic religions like Christianity, Buddhism, and the Gnostic movement dealt with it. Your response was that the problem of evil is only a problem for those who have a pre-conception of what the universe ought to be, and find themselves disappointed as a result, and that the likes of Siddharta Guatama were basically privileged whiners.\nIf I understand correctly, your position implies a radical acceptance of the world as it is, warts and all - with all the evil and cruelty of human nature, and the seeming indifference of the natural world towards our wellbeing. But this leaves open the question of why suffering exists, on a spiritual level. The materialist answer is easy: random chance combined with evolutionary selection created animals that are self-interested and optimized to win in the struggle for survival, not for any higher concept like justice. Nietzche famously called Christian morality \"slave morality,\" and claimed that it is upheld only by those who are too weak to satisfy the will-to-power and become heroic ubermenschen (ironically, Nietzsche himself was an invalid).\nAs I'm sure you're aware, it doesn't take too many leaps of logic from here, despite Hume's concept of the is-ought gap, to arrive at Social Darwinism, exemplified (in fiction) by the likes of Gordon Gekko and Patrick Bateman, and in real life by countless imitators. I'm sure that many captains of industry and \"leaders\" currently at the helm of the United States have privately, if implicitly, adopted this as their philosophy of life, and behave accordingly. After all, if these are truly the rules of the game, why wouldn't individuals optimize their strategy accordingly? If we live in a Darwinian universe, even a concern for ethics or justice can only be another power play, a strategy among others to advance one’s genes, as valid as any other.\nI think that Schopenhauer's attitude to suffering is much more appropriate and humane, that it is the fundamental evil and a moral tragedy, and that life itself is evil unless this world can be redeemed somehow. If materialism is correct in that there is no higher plane or moral oversight, then this life is basically the closest approximation of the Christian Hell. The only escape is the possibility that we are here for a particular reason, to serve out a punishment or to learn some harsh lessons for reasons that must remain unknown to us, at this stage. Perhaps this earthly life is a kind of trial or penitentiary, as Schopenhauer said, intended as a purging by fire before we can rise to the next level? But I essentially have no evidence for this view, so it remains an absurd leap of faith, an empty consolation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7921899", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "For what it's worth, I devoted two of my novels --\nThe Shoggoth Concerto\nand\nThe Nyogtha Variations\n-- to exactly this theme. The basic argument, to put things the way that shoggoths do, is that \"the universe has no eyes, but we have eyes.\" In less gnomic terms, it's absurd for us to ask why there's suffering in the cosmos, or why anything at all is in the cosmos;  we have about as much chance of figuring out those things that the dust mites in Isaac Newton's wig had of understanding his\nPrincipia Mathematica\n; the universe does what it does, without reference to human moral notions; it neither loves us nor hates us, it is wholly indifferent to us, and a robust acceptance of that reality is the foundation of human sanity.\nWe are not the cosmos, however. Unlike the cosmos, we are capable of perceiving the moral consequences of our actions and managing our actions accordingly. Hume's is-ought gap is essential to sanity here -- the fact that the cosmos as a whole behaves in a certain way does not place any obligation on us to act that way, or for that matter to refrain from acting in that way. Ethics, in this way of thinking, is the sum total of human knowledge about how to live well; it's not a set of rules handed down from on high, it's an ongoing exploration, fallible and incomplete but a lot better than no guidance at all.\nI find much to admire in Schopenhauer's epistemology and ontology, but the practical side of his ethics can be tested by checking his own biography -- \"by their fruits ye shall know them\" is good advice -- and his insistence that life is misery and woe clashes entertainingly with his lifelong passion for gourmet food, music, and prostitutes. Recognizing that ethics applies only to conscious intelligent beings such as humans -- and shoggoths! -- and that the universe is as amoral and as lovely as a waterfall or a storm provides a much saner approach to living well and dying well.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7927275", "title": "fairness of life", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I friend of mine picked up from, I believe, the SF author Fritz Leiber, the slogan--\"life isn't meant to be fair, life is meant to be life\"\nWith my kids and shortened and amplified it to: Life isn't fair, but people should be.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7897835", "title": "Blocking Mind-Readers!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Arch-Druid,\nCan I stop other people from reading my mind?\nIf so, then how?\nI became aware of this a few years ago, and it seemed to get worse after I started practicing yoga and meditation. I notice that people around me will say or do things that let me know that they know what I'm thinking: sometimes they will repeat a word or phrase I just thought of, other times they will react to my thoughts as if I had just said them out loud instead of thinking them in my own mind, whether it's words or images.\nWhen I try to think of what's causing this, here are some ideas --\n-- Am I just paranoid?  I don't believe so (although it has induced a kind of paranoia at times), because I'm not paranoid in any areas of my life and I don't let these weird incidents control my behavior.\n-- I wonder if maybe my mind is somehow stuck on the astral plane, and I'm accidentally broadcasting my thoughts to all and sundry?\n--I wonder if it has to do with the kind of people who live and work around me in this strange little west coast city:  lots of drug users, homeless, yogis, witches, occultists .. and Scorpios.  Some people seem to have a natural or unnatural ability to read minds.\n-- And astrologically, I have natal Neptune conjunct the ascendant, so I wonder if this is just like having a window perpetually open into my mind?  But still, there must be a way to at least close the blinds on that window?\nThank you for your time.\nSigned -- Mr. Open Book", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7923435", "title": "Re: Blocking Mind-Readers!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you naturally broadcast your thoughts, which is what it sounds like, it's going to take you a long course of study to learn to control that capacity. Standard occult training will help, but it's going to take you a lot of trial and error to figure out how you're broadcasting and then learn how to stop. Unfortunately I don't know of any study program focused on that goal.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7927531", "title": "Re: Blocking Mind-Readers!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder if playing poker for reasonable stakes would be good training in not broadcasting thoughts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7928811", "title": "Re: Blocking Mind-Readers!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! That would certainly provide an incentive.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7898347", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nYou've mentioned that Yin and Yang as described in Do-In divide things differently than Yin and Yang as described in most Traditional Chinese Medicine sources.\nIs this basically just which foods are classified as which, or does this extend to other areas of the practice? If so, did you have issues with this specifically when you were practicing Tai Chi, and would you expect it to cause issues with studying other traditional Chinese practices after learning Do-In?\nIn the same vein, if you've ever had the chance to glance through an acupressure book from another source, did what you saw make sense from the perspective of someone educated in Do-In, or did it look like something completely foreign?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7923691", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's not Do-In, it's the macrobiotic diet that has different ideas of yin and yang than classical Taoist theory. Do-In is the Japanese working of the Chinese healing art Daoyin, and it's entirely compatible with the rest of trad Chinese medicine, right down to the meridians and points.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7898603", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's funny how so many questions I want to ask here dissolve into an answer or into \"what a fine theme for meditation\" while writing them down. I think so far I have deleted much more questions than submitted... Still, two questions today:\n1) Concerning meditation - A while ago, as my meditation sessions became more and more unpleaseant, I cast a geomantic chart whether it would be ok for me to meditate without some kind of magical protection. The answer was no. Then I asked whether it would be ok to learn and perform a banishing ritual like SOP or LBRP and the answer was no (not for the first time...). There's a certain small prayer I recite frequently and I asked whether this would provide protection if recited before meditating and got a no. Do you have any advice here?\n2) Concerning cell salts - I was unable to find ferrum phosphoricum in D6 (or I believe x6 in the US?) potency so far. The salts you can get are usually D6 except f. phos. and another one, which are D12. Do you have any idea, why this exception? Or what will be the difference between taking D12 and D6?\nThanks,\nNachtgurke", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7923947", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Hmm. You might ask whether there's some other protective method you should use, and if not, whether you should be meditating right now at all.\n2) Yes, D6 is 6x. You must be looking at the Dr. Reckeweg brand. Can you find the Adel brand? They have D6 potencies of all the cell salts.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7905771", "title": "Dietary Affirmation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr. Greer,\nI’m trying to overcome the programming I’ve undergone by our diet culture to re-establish a healthy relationship with food.  I’m thinking a good affirmation would help and am thinking of using “The food I eat fills me with health and vitality.”  I also think it might be helpful to repeat it to myself when I’m eating.  Any advice?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7924203", "title": "Re: Dietary Affirmation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That sounds like a good one to try. Use it for a year and then reassess!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7907051", "title": "Geomancy question about buying rental property", "user": "lterrell", "content": "I've been using geomancy to get answers about buying potential rental properties (to rent out). I'm not sure if I should be issue be using the 4th house for Buildings or the second house for profit & loss.\nAlso,I've used both questions like \"should I buy ... Address?\" as well as \"would buying ... Address be profitable?\" I'm assuming the second question is the better and more precise question.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7924459", "title": "Re: Geomancy question about buying rental property", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The first question will get you a 4th house answer, the second a 2nd house answer. If you're interested primarily in making a profit, the 4th is the one to watch.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7909867", "title": "Divination and my Relationship", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG!\n(Although this is heavily related to divination, I think this is also falls very hard into the \"Give me life advice\" category and if you feel like it does too much so and isn't related enough to occultism I completely understand abstaining from answering.)\nSome necessary background, I've been learning and using the I ching and the Tarot since last August. (In conjunction with a Kraig's Modern Magick style ceremonial magick practice, meditation, LBRP, MP, etc) I mostly did divinations as needed, not as a daily practice where I re-evaluated each day. I think I'm at a low level of competence.\nI am currently in a romantic relationship, that has been going very well, we were friends for years previously, but in the last few months became romantically involved, and got serious fairly quickly.\nIn the last couple days my divinations in regard to our relationship have been turning more negative.\nThis could totally be one of those classic blunders where there's one thing you're extremely afraid of and keep finding it in every reading, but of course I want a second opinion.\nI use a tarot phone app fairly frequently, and that's what started me on this subject. When I asked for an oracle on our relationship I pulled the devil.\nWhich in some interpretations could be positive I suppose, binding together in relationship, coming into being, but I also generally read the devil as expressly negative.\nAfter this I switched to the I ching, as I find it generally harder to make readings what you want them to be (as opposed to what they likely actually mean) especially when lots of emotion is involved.\nI asked the question \"what do I most meet to learn in my relationship with hername\", cast it, and got the response inner truth changing to limitation.\nWith the changing line \"cockrow penetrating to heaven perseverance brings misfortune\" wilhelms commentary that stuck out to me being \"A man may count on mere words to awaken faith, this may succeed now and then, but if persisted in, will have bad consequences.\nFor a long time I have been curious about non-monogamous relationship arrangement's, and was open with my girlfriend about this when we started our romantic relationship. I said I didn't know if I was monogamous or wanted to be committed, and the only thing I could promise is I would always be honest and tell her how I felt. We broke up for a short while because of this, because I brought up the fact that I was still curious about dating other people about a month and a half into our relationship. This lead to a temporary split up (1 week ish) that was extremely painful, and I decided I just wanted to be with her as a life partner, as the other kinds of relationships I was interested in weren't as important to me as this primary one, and I choose her with commitment.\nThis breakup also caused her a lot of pain, and caused a lot of confusion for me, because of the diverging feelings I felt at that time. I really struggled with what I felt like I was \"supposed\" to do at that time, (Supposed to in order to fulfill my highest self and be the best person I can be) and eventually settled on, in a very intentional way, the only way to be committed or to feel comfortable in a relationship despite my fears is to choose this person over those fears over and over again, and to accept that, and laugh as much as I can at all the uncertainty, and simply do my best.\nMy girlfriend know's what she wants, which is a committed monogamous relationship, eventually with children, to pursue writing, to be of benefit to the community, etc.\nI am 21, she is about the same age, and as you do at this age I've been trying to figure out what the best thing to do with my life is, especially via divination, contemplation, etc.\nAt this moment I really want the kind of life I can see us having together. She's really beautiful, funny, accepting of my spirituality, we have the same views on a lot of things and have mature understandings of the things we disagree on, we work well together in practical ways, enjoy each others company, and I think she's a really great person, I am interested in having children, she also supports my life goals (Learn and practice sustainable farming, continue practicing magick and developing spiritually etc)\nSo Wilhem's commentary about mere words awakening faith touched on a fear I already have in myself, that I am terrible, that my words of commitment are meaningless.\nI am so scared that I'm not gonna be right for her in some way, having made a commitment to myself and her, or that our relationship won't work out. Mostly because I fear inflicting a ton of pain on her and her family, and it being my fault, and also being scorned because of it. Selfish and unselfish motivations all in one, in this highly emotional pattern that ties in with patterns I've recognized occurring since early childhood. Some of it is self negativity and over ascribing everything to being my fault, in order to avoid responsibility. (because if I'm so bad I'm not responsible for fixing what I'm not \"able\", according to this narrative, to fix) If I don't like her or the relationship doesn't work out in my head, it's automatically my fault, I've failed her and everyone, that's the way it feels emotionally, although I can recognize it as what it is at least to this degree.\nAnd to be clear I am committed to her in my words and actions for the foreseeable future, but not yet committed to marriage. And I'd say the only specific times I've been feeling uncommitted in heart and mind is recently in this fear and paranoia around these readings.\nSomething I've picked up recently in conjunction with the use of the I ching is flipping one of the coins I use for it to get answers to yes or no questions. When I asked the I ching for an oracle on continuing to do this I got Treading (Right Conduct) transitioning to Innocence, changing line (Walking a smooth even path, perseverance of a dark man, brings good fortune) I interpreted it as it being okay to continue this practice. (When I asked after a lot of this happened)\nBeing in a state of heightened emotion, knowing the thing I was most afraid of: I asked \"Are you suggesting that I break up with hername\" the answer came back heads, yes.\nFurther coin tosses, and divinations gave me more to think about, I'm shortly going to be moving in with her, and it gave me a positive indication on that. Coin tosses answering yes or no questions also seemed to indicate to me that if we did break up it would not be my fault, and this issue would not stem from me but from her, although I have no idea what this issue could be, although I was given some answers on perhaps why, but I doubt my ability to impartially interpret anything in this case.\nI was visiting her later the same day, and talked to her about all of this. She put to me the very common sense question of \"Are you going to break up with me  solely based on divinations?\" I said no. I wouldn't make a major hard life decisions based on divinations unless it confirms something I feel inside myself previously or whatever the divination is pointing to becomes reflected in my experience of material reality.\nShe told me she feels like she can trust me completely, and really wants to pursue a long term stable relationship, and eventually get married. She's not worried about it. I love her, and I don't want to disappoint her.\nAnd for the record, I have no conscious issues with our relationship, no logical problems I can think of, except for my own neurosis around messing up and not being good enough, or not being able to fulfill our dreams together, and it being my fault, or it somehow in some way I can't define being opposed to the development of my higher self. I often look to divination as a guide for that subject.\nWe did a tarot pull together with a physical deck of hers, and when she pulled a card on \"how our relationship will go\" she pulled queen of pentacles.\nHer divination on the subject of our relationship seem to be neutral (four of swords, single card draw) to positive (Queen of pentacles).\nWhile mine, to this day, a couple days after that, remain negative.\nI ask the tarot questions like \"give me an oracle on marrying hername\" and get answers like 10 of swords, or the devil. I certainly see parralells between the Inner truth, changing to Limitation, and the devil card. Or similar things when asking \"Does my higher self want me to marry hername?\" things like the 10 of swords, and if I ask if my higher self wants me to leave, I get the hermit. Or if I simply ask what my higher self wants me to do, I also get the hermit. Which I could either interpret as, go off alone, be a hermit, or as make your own decision according to your own truth.\nWhen I interpret it as there will be some intense suffering in the future if I marry her or continue the relationship, please give me an oracle on marrying hername/going through that difficulty anyway, I get answers like the hierophant and temperance. I know I have my free will to choose. I don't want to break up with her, but there's also a part of me that's worried my stubbornness in this will somehow lead to spiritual stagnation, or not fulfilling my highest self because of my decision to stay. That part of me is like \"Don't be a coward! Give up everything else for spiritual development, that's what matters! If the cards say it it will be better for everyone in the end!\"\nIs this simply a reflection of my inner state of fear and paranoia at this moment? Is that why her divinations are different? Could it simply be me being not a skilled enough diviner to see what is actually going on? Is your take that I am being a competent diviner and I'm clearly being told that there will be some misfortune in the relationship unless I leave?\nAny idea what's going on here? am I just psyching myself out?\n(I also did a ritual intended to help her, with her permission the night before all this started, but I don't want to extend this post longer and I don't see a direct correlation between the ritual and this)\nThanks for reading that very long account, and I truly appreciate your advice,\n-WM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7924715", "title": "Re: Divination and my Relationship", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Set aside your divinations. It sounds to me as though you've gotten into an internal echo chamber where your fears are generating feedback loops; that's something that happens, and it's one of the reasons a lot of older books tell you never to try to do readings for yourself. My recommendation is that you put your tarot cards and your I Ching in a box and leave them there for at least a year, and if you need oracular advice, ask someone else for a reading during that time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7926763", "title": "Re: Divination and my Relationship", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you. That's sound advice.\nI was also the commenter under a similar name a few weeks ago that asked about transitioning to the CGD from more traditional GD practices, and how it may combine with Hatha Yoga. Would you also recommend I abstain from Geomancy, and don't proceed past it in the courses until the same time frame has passed?\n-WM", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7910123", "title": "The Astral Plane", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,\nIs the internet a physical manifestation of the lower end of the astral plane? How does a person progress from the lower astral to the upper?\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7924971", "title": "Re: The Astral Plane", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The internet reflects the lower astral because it reflects the consciousness of those who use it. To get from the lower astral to the upper astral it's necessary to refocus the consciousness away from blind obedience to psychoneurotic obsessions and biological drives, toward the human capacity for reflective awareness and creativity.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7911659", "title": "Grounding", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI've been using your advice on affirmations (100x/day) and very basic meditation (up to 10 min so far) for about 5 months now, with very good results.  I do these exercises every workday morning, and I've definitely noticed a change in my overall mental, and a huge reduction in some recurring negative thoughts that I had.  Just wanted to throw that out there for a data point, and offer you my sincerest gratitude.\nI am also curious to know your thoughts on the exercise of grounding, ie putting your bare skin on the earth.  My mother practices it and I've heard lots about it.  I'm curious what you think of the science behind it (valid/fake/misunderstood?) and also if there is an etheric or astral explanation beyond the material.\nSecondly, if you do think grounding is a beneficial exercise, is skin to ground contact important, or can you get the same benefits through a layer of clothing?  I always hear that it has to be skin, but I can't think why my pants would inhibit any energy exchange if I'm sitting directly on the ground.\nI hope you and everyone else are staying safe during this time.  My thoughts and prayers go out to everyone here.\nCym", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7925227", "title": "Re: Grounding", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. Grounding is useful stuff; it puts you into contact with the telluric current, one of the two main currents of subtle energy. It's best done with bare skin, especially the soles of your feet (fairly easy to arrange) or the base of your spine (not so easy unless you can visit a nudist colony or a nude beach), but there's some benefit through clothing that's made of natural fibers -- cotton is fairly permeable.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7916523", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few disparate queries this week:\n1. Any recommendations for workings to promote health and recovery in light of recent events? I'm making sure to follow the CDC guidelines as much as possible, but a little extra help is always welcome.\n2. Could a donation to a relevant Patreon, GoFundMe, or similar be suitable for planetary or deity charity?\n3. As a fellow Aspie, do you have any advice (magical or mundane) for coping with the inevitable bouts of social or sensory burnout? It doesn't take much for my energy reserves to run low, and I've been trying to find some options to manage it.\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7925483", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Stand by a window, opening it at least a little if possible, and imagine yourself breathing in golden sunlight from the world outside. Take deep, full breaths, hold them for a little while, and let them out slowly. You can combine this with a healing affirmation if you wish: on the inbreath, \"I draw in the healing power of nature,\" and on the outbreath, \"I radiate health and vitality to all around me.\"\n2) Yes, very much so.\n3) Lots of solitude is the only thing that's ever worked for me.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7920619", "title": "Opening ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey jmg\nWhen doing the opening and closing ritual do you need to do the cabalistic cross 4x for the beginning and end of each LBRP or is one cross at the start of the 1st LBRP and another at the end of the 2nd enough?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7925739", "title": "Re: Opening ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You do it four times, once at the beginning and end of each LBRP. Make a point of concentrating on it and doing it as powerfully as you can; it's not just a formality, it can become a really powerful magical rite all by itself if you put serious effort and concentration into it.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/84104.html", "year": "2020", "month": "03", "day": "29", "time": "11-45PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt7954312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a way to avoid being consumed by schadenfreude?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7954568", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You actually have to work hard to be consumed by that, or any of the unfashionable emotions. Let yourself feel what you do in fact feel; don't pretend that it's anything but what it is; don't let it influence your actions or your judgments -- if necessary, by postponing decisions until you've gotten over it; and don't put any energy into it, either by feeding it or by resisting it. Just accept that it's something you're feeling at the moment, an ordinary human reaction to an ordinary human situation; let it flow on by, and then go on with life.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7955336", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1) last week I wrote to you about strong headaches after doing two different banishings in a day for some days. As per your recommendation I stopped banishing for a week and took plenty of rest.\nMy plan would now be to alternate the Banishing Cross (aka Christian Banishing) with the SoP and switch to SoP only as soon as I have added all 7 Gates of the Elements. Good idea/bad idea?\nIn the last few days I had the chance to go through W.E. Butler's \"How to read the Aura\", which brought up some questions - mainly concerning the etheric body:\n2a) I have a strong suspicion that my etheric body was already damaged/leaky even before my double banishing frack-up. Butler glowingly recommends re-charging via regularly exchanging energies with trees. Would this in combination with a lot of sunlight be sufficient to patch things up or is there more I could do?\n2b) Does the SoP strengthen the Etheric Body?\n2c) Butler describes five energy centres, that are common in western teachings (I suspect he means Golden Dawn style - I know Gareth Knight uses 7 and the Druid Magic Handbook has 3). Am I right to suspect that the five \"Tibetan\" rites work on these five centers? If so, do they have a regenerative effect on the etheric body?\n2d) If one tries to develop clairvoyance according to Butler's method by using a mirror to scry, is there an additional safety measure that should be considered before scrying (i.e. banishing the space beforehand)?\n3) I think Saturn has a very strong influence on me, in good and bad ways. Is there a simple way to balance out the negative things, or should I see an astrologer about that? I feel that many things improved when I started wearing my golden wedding ring after my wedding, so I contemplated going full solar for a while - wearing yellow, burning frankincense, drinking infusions of St. John's worth and so on... Would that have an effect?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7956616", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, I recommend that you do one or the other. At this stage of your training it's not going to be helpful to switch off like that.\n2a) Start with those and see what results you get. A lot of people have damaged etheric bodies.\n2b) Indirectly, yes. It strengthens the astral body, and the astral body then recharges and balances the etheric body.\n2c) Nope. If you read the original book by Peter Kelder, you'll find that it refers to these seven centers:\n2d) Follow his instructions exactly as given, neither adding nor subtracting anything, and you'll be fine.\n3) It depends on the fine details of your astrological chart, so yes, you should consult an astrologer.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7999624", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In re: 2b, does the LBRP have the same effect with respect to the astral body, or not? Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8000648", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, you need to add the Middle Pillar exercise for that.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7956360", "title": "My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Hi JMG,\nHere's a post I made about the evolution of my Aurora, Illinois garden:\nhttps://kimberlysteele.dreamwidth.org/1834.html\nAdvice and suggestions are VERY welcome!  I study medicinal plants and herbs and I'm in Zone 5.\nI composed a guitar/voice arrangement of the Orphic Hymn to Saturn, sheet music is in the works still:\nhttps://queeniemusic.bandcamp.com/track/orphic-hymn-to-saturn\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ukgsPNRPyU", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7957384", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You probably know about medicinal plants and herbs than I do, then!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7961736", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "I highly doubt that!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7962504", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I mean it quite seriously. I've only ever dabbled in medicinal herbalism; my main interests in alternative health care are cell salts and acupressure.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7959688", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kimberly,\nI grow a lot of Saint John's wort in my garden.  The pollinators love it and it makes a good antidepressant tonic, antiseptic, linament for nerve pain and is strong protective magic.  I also like to grow Angelica which is a big showy plant, protective and good for pleurisy but what magical garden would be without it?  Betony, borage, cinquefoil, roses, purple cone flowers, lilies and the \"bread\" poppy.\nViolet just showed me a picture of the baby plants she is growing from my seeds.  I am happy to post some of my seeds to you.\nDear JMG,  May I ask you to give my email address to Kimberly?\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7961992", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Cool!  I would love more seeds!  Saint John's Wort is prolific in the wild in East Michigan where the soil is sandy.  I was obsessed with identifying plants of various Midwestern regions as a teenager, so when we traveled to Michigan, I used to hunt plants to ID them whereas a \"normal\" kid would have gone swimming.  Imagine if I had a phone with a camera in it back then!\nI put some borage seeds and papaver somniferum when Moon was in Taurus (thanks JMG's Natural Magic) in a few days ago along with lots of vegetables.  Going to try to learn how to tincture this year.  My email address is my first name dot my last name at comcast dot net.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8012168", "title": "Re: My Garden & New Orphic Hymn to Saturn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Kimberly,\nThat Orphic Hymn to Saturn is simply beautiful, both as music, and in your lovely performance of it!  Thank you very much!\nSincerely, William Allen", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7956872", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. I've been meaning for a while to gain a more intuitive understanding of the Tarot, and with that end in mind, I’ve begun to think about the cards (mostly the Major Arcana) as they relate to situations in my daily life. For example, the global events of the last couple of months bring to mind XVI. The Tower and XIII. Death. For me, the Tower represents the punishment of human hubris with nemesis by the universe (or forces of nature, or God), and Death represents upheaval leading to a new beginning, the recycling and composting of the old, the negative, destructive side of the cycle of life. Another example: in my mind, those individuals who suffer from addictions (either to substances or habits) are under the energy of XV. The Devil, whose inverted pentagram symbolizes the domination of spirit by matter. Does this seem like a worthwhile little habit?\n2. One interpretation of the Great Work can be formulated purely in the terms of analytical psychology. It’s the achievement of wholeness or individuation, the bringing into consciousness and interpenetration of all aspects of the psyche, the dissolution of complexes. Thus we achieve the Circle, the complete Self. Another interpretation is more spiritual/religious: as our awareness expands we become conscious of divine truths about the nature of reality; we approach higher consciousness and union with the divine. Are these interpretations in conflict, or equally valid? Is it a matter of personal preference?\n3. Not really a question, but one thing that struck me in working through LRM (now on lesson 8) is the gradual nature and slowness of the approach, and the gentleness with which concepts are introduced and left to ferment in the student’s imagination. “Hasten slowly” seems to be the driving pedagogical approach. With the gradual approach, it seems that the student’s unconscious mind is left to do a lot of the heavy lifting, and by the time an insight rises to consciousness, it already has firm roots planted in the unconscious, which makes the student’s understanding natural and sustainable. I find myself having to slow the pace and remind myself that if I rush things, it will only make things harder for me in the long run. Unfortunately, \"Ars longa, vita brevis\" holds true...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7957640", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, and in fact that sort of thing is recommended in some esoteric schools.\n2) I see both interpretations as attempts to talk about something that reaches beyond human understanding, using varying sets of symbols, which are necessarily inaccurate but the best we can do. The important thing is to do the work and experience the results for yourself.\n3) Got it in one. We designed the course the way we did because we found that a lot of students benefited from that slow and somewhat indirect approach.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7957896", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI've been doing the heathen LBRP for about four months now and the heathen Middle Pillar for a little over two. I've gotten comfortable with both exercises at this point. I have struggled a little with a few of the visualizations during the MP. I have trouble with visualizing the perthro is silver in the second sphere of light and I have had trouble visualizing berkana on the final sphere. Aside from these two little troublesome spots I can usually clearly visualize everything else in both rituals.\nI have been struggling for the last six months with recurring pain from an overuse and poor form injury. The form has been fixed and I have been had a lot of rest for the last six months as well as other treatment and I have mostly healed but I do suffer from minor pain that has obstinately refused to heal.\nEarlier this week, after my normal practice of the LBRP and MP, I performed the LRP but traced the pentagrams clockwise and, pausing before the final hammer sign formed the intention of asking for healing energy. I got a strong feeling to burn some frankincense, I did and then performed the final hammer sign. While doing the visualization for the hammer sign, the sun appeared black (still bright, but black) and so did the hammer when I formed it.\nThe next day, my pain was markedly improved so I repeated the extra LRP. This time all the visualizations were black and when I traced the lines for the pentagrams I could not get myself to visualize them in anything but black.\nAgain, my pain was improved the following day and I repeated the whole thing but this time, all my visualizations were in black. Everything, even during the MP. I normally can form the initial sphere of the MP in bright white with ansuz in dazzling gold, but I tried as hard as I could to visualize it as normal but could only see it in black\nAfter this, I paused my practice because I wanted to ask if you had any idea what might be going on here?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7958664", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're doing the Lesser Invoking Ritual of the Pentagram rather than the banishing version. Obviously you needed more magical energy, and that's one way to get it. Try doing the invoking ritual in the morning and the banishing ritual in the evening for a while, and see what results you get.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7974536", "title": "Upping my Practice?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI do the Heathen banishing ritual, followed by the Middle Pillar, every morning.  It didn’t occur to me that perhaps an invoking version ought to be done as well.\nYes on that?  If so, same advice as for the original poster?\nWould invoking be identical to banishing, but draw the pentagram to the right rather than to the left?\nOther advice?\nThanks!\nOtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7980424", "title": "Re: Upping my Practice?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If your practices are going well, you don't need to add the invoking ritual daily. I encouraged OP to do so because of his experience with it.  If you'd like to experiment with it, though, by all means -- you might consider\nthis ritual\nfor opening and closing a temple space, which can easily be reworked for Heathen use, and which uses the invoking as well as the banishing ritual.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8009864", "title": "Re: Upping my Practice?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!  I’ll keep doing what I’m doing, and will keep this in mind.  Or just wait until the Heathen Golden Dawn rolls out. 😃", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7958152", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you think the unusual length of peace and stability in the Western World is of Plutonic origin? It seems odd that it lasted this long, and Pluto rules things repressed, so I'm wondering if it might have somehow hidden the historical norms. Of course, this would also explain why it started coming undone now...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7958920", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In a certain sense, yes -- nuclear weapons are extremely effective at preventing war among major powers, and they're certainly ruled by Pluto.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7968904", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "I read somewhere (it was a while back and I don't fully remember where; it may have been your old blog) that since the radioactive portions of a nuclear weapon continue to decay as it's not being used, the missile could evolve into a dud over time.  I suspect the Saturn return of Pluto's deplanetization may be the point at which several such missiles cross over that line.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7980680", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nuclear warheads have to be rebuilt every few years -- radioactive decay is one issue, and another is that the fission trigger requires very precise tolerances and uranium and plutonium are so soft that they tend to slump over time and require re-machining. Every nuclear power is constantly rebuilding its warheads -- otherwise they're duds.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7974024", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder if the period during which Pluto was closer to the Sun than Neptune (1979-1999) has any significance...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7980936", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an interesting question, and one that can only be settled by close historical research combined with the astrology.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7958408", "title": "The Art of Memory", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI am trying to locate a book I think I remember you writing.  It is on the Art of Memory but though I search mightily on Amazon and other locations, I cannot find a trace of it.  My poor old memory does need some help.  What book title would you recommend for someone trying to learn the Renaissance are of memory?\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7959432", "title": "Re: The Art of Memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The book that I did on the subject was a translation of Giordano Bruno's book\nOn the Shadows of the Ideas\n, and it was a limited edition; it'll be back in print later this spring. The book I recommend, though, is Frances Yates' classic history\nThe Art of Memory\n, which covers the basic technique very well in the opening chapters.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7989896", "title": "Re: The Art of Memory", "user": "daveotn", "content": "You may also be thinking of two articles our esteemed host wrote on the Art of Memory which are still hosted on the AODA's publication page:\nhttp://aoda.org/publications/articles-on-druidry/arsmemorativapt1/\nand\nhttp://aoda.org/publications/articles-on-druidry/arsmemorativapt2/\n.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7959176", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nLate night start here, but thank you once again for hosting these Q&A sessions.\n1. What would you do if you had the Philosopher’s Stone? Would you reveal the formula to the public? (After writing this question, it occurred to me that the whole idea of the Stone might have been to serve as a cautionary exercise in ethics, along the lines of “What would you do if you could do anything?” and that it was only the most foolish who actually tried to make it)\n2. Do you think that something like a Copernican revolution in magic might one day occur, where the assumptions of the art would be turned upside-down and fundamentally redefined? What kind of discovery could lead to such a revolution? Has something like this happened in the past?\n3. People born between roughly 1990 and 1996 have a Uranus-Neptune conjunction in Capricorn within a 5 degree orb. What do you think might be the generational effect of this aspect?\n4. I’ve been thinking lately that there may be a way to reconcile science with occult philosophy; that if we conceive of science as being a science of the material plane, then occult philosophy is a science of the subtle planes. In this view, the two are basically compatible, although employing different methods. Neither has the full picture because we're just not smart enough to have the full picture.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7960456", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The formula for the Stone has been revealed to the public countless times. It remains cryptic because the secret of the Stone is the mutual transformation of the alchemist and the prima materia; you make the Stone by becoming the kind of being who can make the Stone, and the prima materia becomes the Stone by making you into the kind of being who can transmute it.\nLege, lege, lege, relege, ora, labora, ut invenies!\n2) That happens on a regular basis. The last such revolution was the work of Eliphas Lévi. Doubtless we'll get another when our culture has mutated to the point that current models no longer make sense to us.\n3) My studies of natal astrology have not proceeded far enough for me to have an informed opinion. (I've mostly studied horary, electional, and mundane astrology so far.)\n4) It's perfectly possible to reconcile science and occult philosophy; occultists do it all the time. It's the scientists who by and large refuse to have anything to do with such a reconciliation. The usual scheme is more or less as you've outlined; science explores the material plane, occultism explores the inner planes which we are capable of perceiving (the etheric, astral, and mental planes), and religion explores the inner planes that are beyond our capacity to perceive (the spiritual, causal, and divine planes, in one analysis).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7973000", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) That's interesting, because most people start with natal astrology and then move on to the other ones. It seems that the literature on natal astrology is much larger than any other branch of astrology (of course, the signal to noise ratio is also lower).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7981448", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course -- most people are fascinated by personalities; we're social primates, after all. In my case, though, I got into astrology because I wanted to be able to elect proper times to consecrate talismans; that led to horary astrology, because I like divination, and then to mundane astrology, since politics and society interest me. I also track transits across my natal chart daily. Natal analysis? Doubtless I'll get to it someday.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7979144", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What would you say the the Uranus-Neptune conjunction indicated in mundane astrology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7981704", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on which house it's in and how it relates to other planets in the relevant chart. Your question is like asking what the letters \"QU\" mean; without a glance at the rest of the word, it's impossible to say.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-30 07:01 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7982216", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Wouldn't it be the same with regards to natal astrology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7983752", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. That's why, when people pop up here and say, \"I've got Mercury conjunct Saturn, what does that mean?\" I respond by telling them that it depends on the rest of the chart.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8007048", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, what does that Latin mean?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8016008", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"Read, read, read, reread, pray, work, so that you will find it!\"\nIt's a classic alchemical maxim, and for good reason.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-31 03:17 am (UTC)", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7959944", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nIn recent years, the media has been obsessed with a particular online phenomenon that it has dubbed the “incel phenomenon.” Without going into too many details, it appears to be a diverse group of young men frustrated by certain aspects of modern sexuality and dating norms, many of which, as the name implies, are long-term celibates, involuntarily so, and who congregate in various online venues to discuss their problems, commiserate, and offer advice. The discussion around the topic is highly polarized, with the cultural mainstream unilaterally denouncing them as violent misogynist extremists, and the incels themselves, finding that they have no avenue to respond, retreating further into their own insular communities, which, unsurprisingly, have often been a breeding ground for views that might be described as ‘hateful’ (to use that problematic term).\nIs such a phenomenon historically unprecedented, a unique product of the post-sexual revolution environment? And secondly, assuming that the laws and culture will not change to assist incels, would you have any recommendations from an occult perspective for them, such as specific magical practices, to help them with their problem? My guess is that there must be some psychological blockage at play, some issue on the subtle planes that make them unable to attract a partner, and this issue must be common enough to affect large swathes of men in a generation. Thinking about it, this seems like a perfect test for the efficacy of magic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7962248", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, I'm familiar with the incels. To my mind, they're caught in one of the clearest modern examples of what Gregory Bateson called a \"double bind.\" The basic structure of the double bind is that there are two sets of rules -- an overt set and a covert set -- and they contradict each other. Those who obey the overt set are praised but surreptitiously punished; those who obey the covert set are denounced but surreptitiously rewarded; and those who refuse to play the game or, worse still, try to discuss what's going on, are targeted with overwhelming abuse to try to force them into subservience to the game.\nThat's the situation the incels are in. Our culture teaches young men a set of notions about dealing with women that guarantee that most of them will be perpeutally one-down, forever chasing after sexual favors that are always dangled in front of them and usually withheld, and then blamed for a failure that has been imposed on them by the entire structure of the game. Those who do the one sane move they have and stop playing the game are then targeted for abuse as mentioned above. There are things they can do, but it's going to take changes in society -- not just changes for individuals -- to resolve the whole mess.\nIt's worth noting that young women are being fed a hugely counterproductive set of notions about men, too. Compare the way that men are portrayed in romance fiction to the way that women are portrayed in pornography and you can see some of the ways that both sides of the gender struggle are set up to fail.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7963528", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Very much this.\nI recently had a thought that last decade progressive social norms pivoted to require a kind of \"skilled disingenousness\" that nerds are particularly bad at. I think that's why so many of us reacted so strongly to having our favorite stuff picked apart for anything problematic: when they said, \"This is racist/sexist/etc.\" it never occurred to us that they just wanted us to take our lectures, make the appropriate self-deprecating gestures, and then go back to what we were doing.\nI have no evidence that this was done as an intentional response to computers and fantasy/superheroes going mainstream, in order to kick nerds back down the social hierarchy, but that's what it feels like.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7981960", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It wouldn't surprise me at all if it were intentional or, shall we say, semi-intentional. A lot of people do things on the basis of half-conscious, half-unthinking reactions.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7988104", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Tolkienguy)\nAs an Autistic man who has had minimal success with women (which I suppose makes me an incel, though I don't like using the word because the incel community seems kind of creepy in multiple ways), this kind of seems to ring true, and I tried to think about what the overt and covert rules might be.\nTo start off with, I once ran into a \"woke\" dating advice site that went on for multiple paragraphs about how it's sexist and backwards to complement a woman on her looks, and I've heard that from other progressive places...and yet, most women seem to like being complemented on their looks, and go to great lengths (makeup, etc) to look physically attractive.\nI've come to wonder (perhaps this might be influenced by my-compared to the norm on this forum-socially conservative beliefs, and by growing up and living all my life in the South) if the issue is that most women have been told, and honestly believe, that they're supposed to be progressive, and that not being progressive is some kind of shameful surrender to the patriarchy...and yet, deep down, most women like traditional gender roles and want a man who will take care of them and provide for them. Or to put it another way, the majority of women want a traditional marriage, but if they ever admitted it, they'd be yelled at (internally by themselves, and externally by their friends and the rest of society) for being a stepford wife.\nAnd if that's true, the solution would be to fulfil the traditional male gender role but pretend not to do so, to both the rest of the world and your wife/girlfriend...gah, sounds horrendously complicated.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7990664", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that's an important part of it. I highly recommend picking up a cheap bodice-ripper romance novel, the kind of thing sold to women by the bushel basket. Read it, and then compare (a) how the romantic male lead behaves toward the heroine with (b) how men today are supposed to behave toward women. (While you're at it, notice whether the character of the romantic male lead makes any sense at all.) It's a fascinating glimpse into the other side of the double-bind.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7967880", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Let's just say that an atomized populace with a materialistic outlook and very weak family cohesion is good for some people's business interest. The goal is to get rid of cultures, nations and families and break this all down to a mass of costumers. The other side of the coin to incels are those women who are told to have lots of partners and end up alone and infertile in their fourties and fifties. Both have a lot of disposable income to spend on the toxic garbage that nowadays clutters our planet...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7977608", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "As a woman who's had a lot of partners, who will be in her forties in about three years, and who will likely be unpartnered and will certainly be infertile by then: it also gives us a lot of spare time to garden, write, travel (ideally in non-toxic ways, true), run games, help our neighbors or aging parents, read, take up magic, etc.\nPartners and kids are great for those who are so inclined, but OH NOES YOU WILL BE ALONE IN YOUR FORTIES is not quiiiite the dire threat some seem to think.\nI'd also point out that current society's lack of a widespread and accepted alternative to creating your own nuclear family is *almost* as new as anything else nuclear. Monastic and scholarly communities were common in most nations, desert hermits are far from new, and even the Victorian era had its Eccentric Spinster Aunt/Bachelor Uncle role, in which many people were happy and did a lot of good for their relatives and communities.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7985288", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello, I'm sorry if have offended you with my comment.\nI did not intend to criticize people like you who invest their gifts and lifetimes into genuinely positive pursuits.\nI think, however, that the cultural and economic forces that fuel the atomization of our societies and the pollution of our earth are also at the root of the incel phenomenon and other problematic developments.\nAdvertisements are constructed to suggest a lack, the advertised products promise to fill this lack. It is much easier to sell stuff when your customers are isolated and share no strong social bonds.\nFunnily enough, the \"nuclear family\" is in itself a way of \"atomization\". If you look at history or other contemporary countries like Italy or India you'll see multigenerational monolocal families which are able to provide a much better safety net for \"Spinster Aunts/Bachelor Uncles\" than the monoculture towards which we're goaded to by Mr. Global.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7992456", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Thanks for the correction, and I totally agree on that!\nPart of the problem I see is very much that society does sell the \"you are nothing without a partner/kids\" model hard, to all genders (just a different model when it's coded female versus made), in part to fuel a lot of other industries.* I'd like to see less of that, more recognition of extended families--and more communities of purpose, religious or not, where single people can support each other. From what I've heard, the Masons/Grange/etc go some way to fulfilling that on a non-residential (at least before old age) level, and I've also seen it a little in the growth of co-housing, so fingers crossed!\nFor my part, I think one of the ways to combat both the incel attitude and the materialism thing is to recognize that no external entity is going to make you a complete person if you're not already, and trying to base your identity around that is foolish and self-destructive at best. That applies to having a SO, driving the coolest car, being at the top of the corporate ladder--if you're not satisfied on your own, then no other person/thing is going to do it.\n* The cultural influences set up to sell weddings, various expensive toys, designer clothes for three-month-olds, etc are...a heck of a thing.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7991176", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "jjensenii", "content": "What was it JMG said, \"Knowing only one story is death?\" The idea that there is a single template for everyone's life is attractive because it means not having to expend effort finding out which story is the best fit for your life, and the risk of being wrong, but it's harmful to those who for whom the one story doesn't work.\nI think we need both the \"Fooling around in your younger years can lead to loneliness later\" story and the \"Tying yourself down to a spouse and kids is a burden not everyone benefits from\" story, and a few other stories besides.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7993224", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Precisely! And we need more ways to help people find out what they really want in time to go after it practically--that if they want to have a family, they need to make that a priority and openly and honestly find other people who do. If they don't, they need to recognize that and be aboveboard about it. And not having the One Story hanging over anyone's head will help a great deal with that, albeit it'll still probably take some people a while to figure things out, as that's (IME) how being young works.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8011400", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "slclaire", "content": "On our third date, my now-husband told me he had had a vasectomy and had no desire for a white-picket-fence kind of life, and that if I wanted either or both of those things, I needed to look for someone else. While I did want to be married, I didn't want children, and I didn't want the standard suburban existence most of the people I knew settled for. Thanks to his honesty, we've been married for 31 years and counting.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8038024", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Both of you sound awesome!\nI've had my tubes out for a few years now, and should I ever Actually Date again, I'll bring that up on the first date. (One of the advantages of dating apps, though I understand the disadvantages of same, is that you can generally put that right on your profile.) I regret trying to convince myself that I could maybe make myself want kids and monogamy for four years or so in my twenties: I feel like both I and the guy in question wasted a lot of time as a result.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7970184", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Speaking for myself: on the one hand, I think we *generally* need more cultural options for people who want to opt out of the dating world/live their lives without romantic partners/etc.\nOn the other hand, what I've observed of at least large parts of the incel community has a regrettable tendency to two things:\n1) Not wanting to do the work that would make them more likely to attract a partner. For at least some sects, they don't need subtle-plane causes--\"I shouldn't need fashion/fitness/basic hygiene\" is not going to end well if you want a date, and less physically, desperation/self-pity is not sexy from any gender.\n2) Being really quite hostile/resentful of women as a whole or specific women who aren't interested in them, and same toward the guys women *do* like. I wasn't a fan of \"oh men are so shallow and awful because they don't want to marry me/because they want people who aren't me\" back in the Bridget Jones era, and I don't much like the gender-flipped version either.\n(As someone who's happily single, I also admit to rolling my eyes at the Not Having a Girlfriend is WOE AND PAIN AND OPPRESSION section--as with 2, I saw the same thing from a bunch of girls in college, and I didn't think much of them.*)\nAspects of dating are legitimately awful. And no matter what you do, sometimes people you're really into won't feel the same way about you, and that hurts. I don't blame anyone for deciding that's all too much trouble, *until* they start judging other people's sex lives/deciding that other people are obligated to date them or sleep with them or whatever/harassing or harming others, obvs.\n* ETA: Heck, I see it occasionally now--mostly third-hand, because I don't have the patience to deal with it myself--from women who are in relationships with guys who clearly make them unhappy, but won't break up because \"well what if I don't find anyone else.\" What if you don't? Being single is great! You can do what you like, when you like! Nobody wants you to make dinner, unless you get a cat! The only underwear you have to pick up is your own!\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-30 12:11 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8010888", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Their adoration of hatred and violence, and their cheers for others' hatred and violence (against both the women who don't date them and the men who date those women) is alarming. They sound like delusional KKK members who wish violence on black people or Jewish people. They sound literally irrational, paranoid. One can only hope that as they reach maturity their worldviews will become less toxic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8016264", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The corporate media has systematically focused on the wackjob end of the incel scene and erased all those who don't belong to that end. It never ceases to amaze me how many people never notice such shenanigans...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8016520", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Also, I think a lot of them are exaggerating because they value getting the attention....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8017288", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The incels, or the media? Yes on both counts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8020360", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was thinking both too ;)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7960712", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. Since you recommend a maximum of 30mins to 1hr a day of magical practice (for safety reasons), what, if anything, can be done outside of that brief practice window? In the same way that most mainstream religions have prescriptions for how to live a virtuous life outside of attending worship services, is there something we could be doing to constantly progress in the Great Work when we’re not actively practicing?\n2. In last week’s MM, you mentioned that the internet is what it is because it reflects the consciousness of those who use it, so it’s not surprising that large parts of it consist of cheap entertainment, pornography, and memes. What would a “redeemed\" Internet look like? And more broadly, what would a culture look like that focused on the higher end of the astral plane? Has anything like this ever been achieved in practice?\n3. In my opinion, a writer has an intellectual responsibility to educate himself on a topic before he puts pen to paper, that is, to learn what has already been done before he attempts to add anything new to the body of knowledge. But this process of learning seems endless: we can spend a lifetime on it and never finish. However, without it, a writer is unprepared and immature. At what point in your own career as occultist and writer did you decide that you knew enough, that you were ready to create and contribute- was it after a certain age? And how do you balance the twin responsibilities of continuing education and contribution?\n4. Do you have a theory on procrastination, and why so many people suffer from it? Have you dealt with it yourself? I can say from experience that often, there is an enormous emotional resistance to doing something that you know is good and necessary, like a wall of pain and fear that prevents you from taking constructive action. It seems like exactly the type of situation where magic would be useful.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7982728", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) What you do alongside your magical practices is have a life. That provides the stabilizing influence you need so that magic doesn't unbalance you, and it also provides the field of experience in which you learn to apply the subtle lessons of consciousness you learn from magical training.\n2) That's like asking what a square circle would be like. It's not just the content of the internet that reflects the bottom-feeding end of the astral; to borrow one of Marshall McLuhan's few real insights, the medium is itself the message. As for a society that focuses purely on the upper astral, it's been tried over and over again -- that's what most plans for social reform amount to -- and it always fails, because most human beings can't maintain that for long. \"Out of the crooked timber of humanity no straight thing was ever made.\"\n3) This attitude explains why you have problems with procrastination. You've set up an arrangement whereby the inner critic -- the voice of internalized authority Freud called the superego -- can always insist \"But you haven't learned enough yet.\" Every writer is unprepared and immature, because the only way to prepare and mature is to write. Some of the things in my early published books embarrass me now; accepting that this is going to happen is an important step toward achieving anything at all.\n4) See my previous answer. I suggest journaling, so you come to understand the emotional habits and childhood programming that are getting in the way of your ability to do what you will.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7985800", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2a) Why do you use the internet so much then? Is it just the best option available to you at this time?\nb) In what way does the internet tie into the lower end of the astral?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7990920", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "a) I don't use the internet very much. I'm not on social media, I don't use any of the various streaming-media services, I don't play online games and I avoid most websites. I use this journal and my blog as convenient ways to get certain ideas into circulation, that's all.\nb) What a fine topic for your next week of meditation!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8008072", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember once having a casual conversation with a professor of Egyptology who was complaining about the trouble he was having deciphering the handwriting of a particular Coptic scribe. He clearly knew enough Coptic to have gotten to that stage in his scholarly work. After a bit I asked him if he had ever considered writing a Coptic textbook. He said, and I remember it to this day, \"I don't know enough yet.\" (I'm like, to  myself, If you don't know enough yet, who the heck does?)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7960968", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Bit of a random question.\nDoes Occult Philosophy have anything to say about the era in the recent past when-- according to the archaeological evidence-- multiple human species (H. erectus, Neanderthals, Denisovans, the floresiensis \"hobbits\") lived at the same time?\nIf not, what do you think of it?\nAnd do you ever suppose that the regular and rather casual mention of giants, dwarves, dog-headed men and the like in older literature might point to the survival of various archaic hominids into historic times, or even into the present?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7974792", "title": "Dog-headed men", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When I first read about the \"dog-headed men of Africa\" in a medieval bestiary, my first thought was \"baboons!\" For what that's worth.\nAs for giants - if your source is Mediterranean, imagine a visitor from say, Scandinavia among the shorter, more compactly built (guessing at that from Greek vases) Acheans. Dwarves, of course, exist in the human population and always have; it wasn't hard to find an actor to play Tyrion Lannister.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7996808", "title": "Re: Dog-headed men", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, but don't you suppose that if I wanted to a straightforward recapitulation of the conventional wisdom I wouldn't have brought this up on a site like this one?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7982984", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Traditional occult philosophy has it that we're the fifth intelligent species on this planet -- that's what the old talk about \"root-races\" translates out into in terms of modern language -- and each such species has various forms over time. Beyond that it doesn't go very far. I think it's quite possible that the era of multiple human species has left traces in folklore and folk memory; that was one of the things I borrowed and reworked in my fantasy series\nThe Weird of Hali\n, where there are six other intelligent species in the world right now -- they're just hiding from us, for good reason.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7997064", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's interesting. I didn't realize that about The Weird of Hali-- I've only read the first book, and the second will have to wait until after The Current Situation ends.\nIt's occurred to me more than once that some of the issues with our species in general might stem from the lack of actual human biodiversity. That is-- supposing dolphins are at the same level as we are, at the border of Abred and Gwynfydd, it's hard to imagine that they would have as easy a time as we do considering themselves especially unique, given that there are dozens of species at roughly the same level of cognitive development, but very different to outward appearance!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8000904", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may well be right. Equally, though, from an occult point of view, it may be necessary for the souls going through human incarnation at this stage of the cosmic process to wrestle with the temptation to feel unbearably special!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7961224", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How does a person reconcile their own experiences of Christ as a loving, tolerant figure who accepts some very unorthodox Christians and even non-Christians with some of the things he (supposedly) said in the Bible?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7983496", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The New Testament as we now know it was voted into existence by two church councils at the end of the 4th century CE. None of the people who took part in those elections, obviously, had ever met Jesus of Nazareth, and they all belonged to one particular end of the very broad Christian movement -- the end that turned into the established Christian church. A lot of other Gospels got left out of it, as you may know, and some of them have at least as good a claim to authenticity as the ones that made the cut. So the portrayal of Christ in the New Testament is not necessarily accurate. (Nor, by the way, does it say anywhere in the Bible that the Bible is inerrant, or literally true.)\nMore broadly, the old woman who taught me her method of Bible study used to shake her head sadly when anyone referred to the Bible as the Word of God. \"The Word of God is Christ,\" she would say, and quote the first chapter of the Gospel according to John. \"Anybody who can't tell the difference between the Son of God and a printed book has real problems.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7984520", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Which Gospels that have been left out would you say are most interesting?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7986056", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Gospel of Thomas has always spoken to me very strongly. I also like the various Valentinian gospels and epistles.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8015752", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do you think of the idea that the God of the Old Testament and the God of the New Testament are different rather than the same God?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8016776", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Gnostics certainly thought so. I don't really have an opinion -- not my religion, not my deities.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8012424", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would love to hear more about her method of Bible study if you care to elaborate. Were there lessons that were applicable to studying other scriptures or writings too?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8017032", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. Her rule was that you should read one chapter out of the Bible each day, first thing in the morning. Start by saying a brief prayer to the Holy Spirit for the gift of understanding, and then read your chapter, slowly and carefully, paying attention to every word. Then think about it for a while -- what can you learn from it? How does its teachings apply to your life? Finish with a few minutes of extempore prayer about whatever's on your mind, and close with the Lord's Prayer.\nOne other rule: DO NOT TRY TO START WITH GENESIS. She used to say that if you got through the begats, and most people don't, you'll grind to a halt somewhere in Leviticus and never start again. Her advice was to start with the Gospel according to John, then the other three Gospels, then the rest of the New Testament. Repeat the whole New Testament three times, and if you've made it a solid daily habit, then do the Old Testament. If you find your eyes glazing over in the legal sections of Exodus, skip the next three books, which are mostly laws for the Jewish people, and go straight to Joshua; begin there, and read all the way through the rest of the Old Testament.\nOf course you can use it with other scriptures and writings. I used it to work my way through the Enneads of Plotinus, with very good results.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7961480", "title": "Dion Fortune and The Qabalah", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI am a long time reader and appreciator of the clarity with which you write on various subjects.  I have started reading Dion Fortune’s “Mystical Qabalah”. This week I took the following sentence from it as a subject for meditation:\n“Pantheism and polytheism had their day and a new and more spiritual culture was due.”\nIn your opinion is this just Dion Fortune reflecting her particular prejudice? Do you know what it was that she saw as less spiritual about polytheism and more spiritual about monotheism? I appreciate your elucidation.\nEric", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7984008", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune and The Qabalah", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fortune was a Christian -- a decidedly unorthodox Christian, granted, but Christian enough to go to church regularly. The sentiment she expressed there is a standard bit of Christian rhetoric that helped feed into the modern mythology of progress -- the claim that Paganism was fine enough in those primitive days, but we outgrew it and of course we all know better now. I take wry amusement in the fact that some atheists now use exactly the same rhetoric on Christians!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7962760", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nIIRC, you said you considered your book on Atlantis to be a disappointment and were not sorry to see it go out of print. I loved it and really liked how you tied together a wide range of material and perspectives. I thought your conclusion made a huge amount of sense and is the most plausible interpretation based on the evidence. Is there any chance of a revised edition someday, perhaps via a different publisher such as Aeon?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7984264", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Down the road a bit I'll be writing a new book on the Atlantis legend and its relation to human civilizations before and during the last Ice Age. That book will include everything in the original book that's worth keeping, and a great deal more.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7963016", "title": "Etheric injuries etc", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG\nTwo questions from me:\n1. It looks like the UK has followed the Indian example (along with various other countries) of the nation clapping at a fixed time to show appreciation for the NHS and healthcare workers. Again it sounds like there was a good turnout but I’m assuming the timing was probably not fixed astrologically for the UK (unlike India).\nSome pictures and description here:\nhttps://www.bbc.com/news/in-pictures-52063866\nAny thoughts on what the benefits could be and how it could compare to the Indian ritual?\n2. I’ve been training martial arts fairly intensively for the last year or so (a couple hours a day or more 5-6 days/week). I’ve had my share of minor injuries and improved fitness, but I’ve had one recurrent problem which has caused me to lose a LOT of training time. It’s essentially falling or rolling slightly awkwardly from a throw and landing on my back with a sharp pain which then results in severe muscle pain and back spasms - some kind of muscle strain. Typically I can barely move for a couple of days and then it slowly eases up. Usually I’m back to light training in a week and full training in two weeks.\nIt’s not a serious problem or injury (although very very painful) and I usually recover fully - it’s annoying to lose training time regularly to the same problem.\nI currently follow the usual medical advice (take painkillers for the intense pain in the first few days, then taper them off and stay as active as possible and go back to normal activity in a phased manner). This is fine as far as it goes but I am wondering if there is more I can do.\nI am currently on my 5th training break (even before the corona lockdown) in the last 9 months because of the same injury and I am sick of it. It feels like that area has become more and more delicate so where last year it took a pretty bad fall to trigger it, now even lighter falls and smaller mistakes are triggering it.\nWhen I am fully recovered this time (it’s taking longer than before), I am going to start targeted muscle building exercises for my lower back.\nAll of that is a long winded way of asking if injuries - especially recurrent injuries in the same area like this - have an etheric component and if there is anything I can do on the etheric level to encourage healing of that area and especially reverse this tendency of the area to become more and more delicate and bring it back to full recovery. For example, I get some relief by using cold packs and pads on that area and I accidentally turned my shower to cool (not really cold) yesterday and the sensation on that area of the back was really nice and I wonder if that was etheric.\nBut I guess my general question is whether injuries like this have an etheric component and whether there is any healing to be found from that angle, in addition to the normal meds. I have no spiritual or magical practice to speak of (I used to practice discursive meditation fairly regularly but have stopped for the last few months).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7981192", "title": "Re: covid response and astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Piggybacking on this question, I noticed that the UK lockdown was announced at the dark moon, the day before the new moon. Magically could this strengthen it, as it is in effect a type of banishing?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt7984776", "title": "Re: Etheric injuries etc", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If it wasn't done at a properly chosen time, it's probably just applause.\n2) Yes, there could be an etheric component, and there could also be an astral (that is, psychological) component. You might consider doing some serious journaling to try to figure out if the latter is involved. With regard to an etheric injury, the obvious approach -- since you're a martial artist -- is to find a competent acupunturist. The acupuncture meridians are etheric in nature, and Chinese medicine also has a long history of treating martial arts injuries!\n3) Possibly, if it was done with that intention.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8014984", "title": "Re: Etheric injuries etc", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!\nI don't know a good acupuncturist here (although can look) but I do know a very good one in India near where my parents live. He's an Indian guy who trained for years in China to learn their system but after he returned he combines Chinese acupressure with Indian traditional medicine with good results.\nI had good results when I went to him for a previous cycle of the same back injury a few years ago - especially from the acupuncture itself (the Indian medicines not so much).\nI just find it hard to take him seriously when he has one of those \"You have been selected to be one of the 1000 Leading Citizens of the World Awards - just send $100 to this address to receive your special certificate\" kind of certificates on the wall..", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7963272", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lloydgd", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI would like to take part in the cell salt experiment and want to double check with you that I’ve got the correct combination. I was born 10° Leo but was a month premature.\nIs the following correct: Mag. Phos. 2, Kali Sulph. 3, Nat. Phos. 3, Calc. Sulph. 3, Silicea 1.\nI live in UK & we are in lockdown for 2 weeks, which will then be reviewed, so not sure when I can receive the cell salts as many websites have temporarily ceased trading & delivery is slow.\nwith best wishes, Lloyd", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7986312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that's the correct combination. By all means start when you can!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7987592", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lloydgd", "content": "Thank you....", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7963784", "title": "Geomancy love question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had a short but intense relationship with a girl.\nSince we broke up, I bumped into her twice randomly, around town; I've never had this with any other girl I dated before.\nThe second time around, I encountered her just as I left my office; I was going to a date, while she was walking with another guy. She was walking right in front of me, headed the other way, and she definitely saw me from a distance as she walked there, but she looked straight ahead as I passed her by. I felt like my heart broke for a second time, but I was wondering what sign the universe was trying to send me with this.\nI had a dream where I met her at a bookstore, I touched her and she disappeared, but after a while she appeared again.\nAnyway, given all this, I felt like we had some unresolved karma between us.\nI cast a chart with the question: Will E reconcile with me?\nFour Mothers:\nVia\nCarcer\nAmissio\nVia\nFull Shield Chart here: https://imgur.com/gmWFVrW\nRW: Fortuna Major\nLW: Populus\nJudge: Fortuna Major\nThe RW and Judge of Fortuna Major seem quite positive to me. I'm interpreting it as saying that it will turn out well.\nI think Fortuna Major as the RW describes my situation well: my external conditions probably don't look very good; a startup that I was working on failed to get enough traction when the virus hit, and I stepped down from the company and am applying for jobs. However, I feel mentally and emotionally much more collected after the chaos of the last few months, and I'm also launching a podcast. I have this feeling of \"I'm going to get through this\".\nPopulus as the LW and the Way of Points leading to double Conjunctiones seems to indicate that she's seeing other people, maybe more than one. That's fair enough, I've been dating other people but she was really my favourite out of every girl I've dated.\nFortuna Major as the Judge seems to indicate that it will turn out well? Since this is a Yes/No question, I would want to interpret it as \"Yes\", but I don't want to deceive myself.\nWould like to see your thoughts on this, JMG, thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7986568", "title": "Re: Geomancy love question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In a shield chart, if you get two or more favorable figures as Judge and Witnesses, the answer is Yes. Fortuna Major is the most favorable figure of the sixteen, so you've got a definite yes. One thing to keep in mind, though, is that it often means delay at the beginning, so things may not resolve right away.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7964296", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI hope it's OK to ask quite a few questions this week, meditation has been fruitful!\n1. I have spent the last few weeks meditating on the descriptions of the Druid gods listed in the appendix of the DMH. Where can I find more information about them beyond what is in the DMH?\n2. One thought struck me during meditation: I think I remember you writing elsewhere that if you meditate on or worship fictional deities, you get fictional results. If a lot of the Druid Revival lore comes from Iolo Morganwg and if much of it is considered a forgery, then wouldn't the same principle apply?\n3. About focused goals, the will, and focusing on one thing at a time: I've been wrestling all week with trying to choose a single goal to focus on, and it has been a big struggle. It's simply hard to pick just one interest from a number of them to work towards. I'd like keep up the DMH practices, to make music, learn to grow vegetables, learn more about the cell salts, in my free time but there are also the goals that I have to work towards because of my day job. Clearly, it's hard to do any of these well with a limited amount of time per day, and each activity is full of rabbit holes in themselves.\nI may have made a breakthrough during meditation though: I suddenly remembered from looking at the AODA study program that a number of my goals are actually part of it in terms of the Earth Path and the spirals (I am not part of AODA, yet, I'm still working at the DMH first). I realized that actually I can weave many of my goals together under the umbrella of Druidry, and that really, what I'm trying to do with many of my goals is to learn from them, to study the universe and I suppose to gain wisdom from them. So that's my overarching goal, and all of these things are different facets of that. Is that a good way of approaching this problem, or am I still trying to have my cake and eat it, too? :)\n4. I am reading Manly Hall's Self-Unfoldment Through Disciplines of Realization (I'm not doing the practices, simply reading it out of interest). He talks about how gaining wisdom should be a natural process and it should be effortless. I don't in all honesty think I really know what wisdom even means, and therefor I feel even a little silly saying as above that my goal is to gain wisdom, when as Hall writes wisdom essentially is a by-product of consistent meditation and practice. I wonder if there's a danger in making wisdom an abstract goal, and thus moving further away from it as I try to move towards it?\nIt's a similar thing to what he writes about poise: I don't really have poise, but it sounds like something I'd like to have! :) But Hall warns that you can't imitate poise, it has to come from internal factors. But building those internal factors implies that you shouldn't care about the outward appearance of poise. But it is the outward appearance of poise that drew me to the goal of having it in the first place.\nHall also implies the same thing when he writes about the Taoist monk who doesn't have a bad temper, he/she has moved beyond temper completely. I'm still puzzling through this but it seems that trying not to have a bad temper is going to be counterproductive in the same way... thanks for any pointers here!\n5. I've understood vibration such that tuning in to the higher planes involves vibrating at higher frequencies. But when one is angry or anxious, it feels like one is vibrating at a higher frequency, and when one is calm, it is the opposite. Why is that, or have I misunderstood something?\nThanks again!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7991688", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1)\nThe Book of Druidry\nby Ross Nichols and the Druid-oriented books of Lewis Spence are about what you'll find in English.\n2) This is a great example of the way that our culture systematically denigrates its own spiritual options. If a spiritual movement in some conveniently non-white culture were to take to worshiping a new set of gods and practicing a new set of rituals, nobody would go stomping around dismissing those as \"forgeries\" -- nah, we'd hear all kinds of babble about how creative it is for a new spiritual movement to follow its own unique vision, blah blah blah. The Druid Revival didn't come up with its deities as props for a novel or a movie, you know -- it developed its pantheon as a way to talk about the immanent spiritual forces/entities its members perceived at work in nature.\n3) That's a good first step. Keep meditating!\n4) Excellent. Did you think Hall intended his meaning to be obvious?\n5) This is a fine example of what happens when a metaphor is stretched beyond the point at which it means anything. \"Vibration\" in terms of the planes is a metaphor; saints and sages do not emit high-pitched buzzing sounds...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7965832", "title": "Ancestors", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was too late to add a question to this thread last week:\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/83179.html?thread=7884011#cmt7884011\nHow close do the ancestors need to be? If someone moves to an area where some of their ancestors lived 150 years ago, and probably for hundreds of years before that, but the ancestors in between lived in various different places, does that have any relevance? And of course going this far back, one only shares a fraction of DNA and culture with them if a person has ancestors from a few different regions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7991944", "title": "Re: Ancestors", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd probably have to experiment to find out. I don't know that anyone's set out any kind of hard and fast rules for that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7966088", "title": "Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I find the ending white sphere from SOP difficult on my nerves, causes my body to shake when ibtry to build and maintain it even for a minute.\nBesides regular practice or SOP, what else can I do to help stabilize and stregthen my solar plexus?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7992712", "title": "Re: Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Are you tensing your body while you concentrate on the image? That's common, and can have various unhelpful results, including the one you've described.\n2) Sit in a comfy chair or on a sofa. Relax.  Draw in a long, deep breath, expanding your belly as far as you can while not expanding your chest. Then, while holding the breath, expand the chest and suck in the belly. Let the belly out again and flatten the chest; then expand the chest again and suck in the belly. Repeat a total of three times. Then let out the breath and relax completely, going as limp as you can.  Breathe normally for a minute or so. Repeat twice more -- so you're doing three cycles, each of which involves three back-and-forth movements. This is an old occult practice for activating the solar plexus.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7994248", "title": "Re: Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What does activating the solar plexus do?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7995272", "title": "Re: Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It stabilizes and strengthens the etheric body, and also has health benefits.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8006536", "title": "Re: Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG\nRegarding 2) above, can you outline any similar practices to activate the heart center?\nBest wishes,\nJR", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8017800", "title": "Re: Weak Dan tien/solat plexus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The solar plexus exercise will energize all the viscera. If you want to work on the heart center, though, that's done by cultivating the habit of love.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7966344", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIn order to do scrying with tarot cards, is it necessary to know about their Cabalistic correspondences?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7992968", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, not at all.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7966600", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Archdruid,\nWould you recommend reading The Chronicles of Prydain after The Mabinogion or before it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7993480", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. Lloyd Alexander's\nChronicles of Prydain\nwere among the delights of my childhood, but I haven't read them in decades -- most of the kid's books I liked back in my insufficiently misspent childhood don't do much for me now, for the same reasons that I no longer play with toy trucks. If you want to read them as well as the Mabinogion, I don't imagine that it makes any difference which you read first, but don't confuse them -- Alexander borrowed a lot of names and props out of Welsh legend, but plugged them into a good lively kid's-fantasy formula.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7967112", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much of Do-In and cell salts are things you do regularly, and how much are just for when you have a specific problem?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7993736", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I do a basic Do-In sequence daily, and take cell salts quite regularly. One of the things that you have to do with alternative health care is monitor your body's condition on a daily basis -- since alternative modalities are subtler and work best when used at the first sign of a health condition, it's best to pay attention to your body and treat the little symptoms when they first occur, rather than waiting for things to spin out of control and then trying to fix the damage with chemical poisons or surgery.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7967368", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If you do a banishing ritual in a place with really bad energy, so more 'heavy lifting' is required, how does it feel different? What part of doing it is actually harder?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7994760", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That seems to vary from person to person. For me, the visualizations are harder to maintain and there's a sense of \"heaviness,\" as though the air has become thick and moving through it is harder.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7967624", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "I have a somewhat strange question: Can magic help when a printer needs to be repaired, or otherwise serviced, so it prints correctly again? Normally, this would be a thing of the material plane, but are there other aspects to it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7995016", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Under normal circumstances, the appropriate magical grimoire to use for printer repair is a repair manual, and the appropriate mystic implements are screwdrivers and the like. Do you have a specific example in mind, or is this an abstract question?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7998600", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "No, this question was rather abstract it was about the principial question if non-material magic in such circumstances is useless or not.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8001160", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As a rule, the planes are discrete and not continuous, and if you want to make something happen on the material plane, your approach needs to include material causality (though it can also include influencing embodied or disembodied beings on the immaterial planes...)", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7968136", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a Christian version of the Middle Pillar / Central Ray? As there's already banishing, meditation and divination, that would give them the full set. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7996296", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It would be the easiest thing in the world to create one. Try this:\nFirst, perform the complete Banishing Ritual of the Cross.\nSecond, imagine a ray of light descending from infinite space to form a sphere of light just above your head, around eight inches in diameter. This sphere is white and contains a blood-red cross. When you have formulated it clearly in your imagination, vibrate the word IESOUS three times. (This is the Greek version of Jesus. Give each vowel its full pronounciation: \"ee-ay-so-oos.\")\nThird, bring the ray of light to your throat, and form another sphere. This one is violet and contains a blood-red cross. When you have formulated it, vibrate the word CHRISTOS three times.\nFourth, bring the ray of light to your heart, and form a third sphere, which is brilliant gold like the sun, and contains a blood-red cross.  The word THEIOS is vibrated here three times; again, pronounce each vowel -- \"thay-ee-oss.\"\nFifth, bring the ray of light to your genital center, and form a fourth sphere.  This one is green and contains a blood-red cross. HUIOS is vibrated here three times -- \"hoo-ee-oss.\"\nSixth, bring the ray of light to your feet, and form a fifth center. This one is black and contains a blood-red cross.  The name vibrated here, three times, is SOTER.\n(The words, of course, are Greek for \"Jesus Christ, Son of God, Savior,\" and their initials spell out the Greek word for \"fish.\" That sequence was used by Christians to identify themselves to each other in the earliest days of the church, and it identifies the practitioner with the Christians of those days. The five red crosses symbolize the five wounds Christ suffered in the crucifixion.)\nSeventh, return the attention to the center at the top of the head. Bring a current of white light a few inches wide down the left side of the head and neck,  the left shoulder and arm, and theleft hip and leg, down to the center at the feet, and then back up the right leg and hip, the right arm and shoulder, and the right side of the neck and head, back to the center at the head.  Repeat this a total of four times; if possible, synchronize with the breath, so that the energy flows down with the outbreath and up with the inbreath, but it is more important to visualize the whole course than to make it happen within a single breath.\nEighth, in the same way, bring a current of white light from the center above the head, down the midline of the front of the body to the center at the feet, and then back up the midline of the back of the body to the center above the head. Repeat a total of four times.\nNinth, turn the attention to the center at the feet. Breathing in, draw a current of energy up the Middle Pillar of the body from that center to the center above the head; breathing out, allow it to spray like a fountain out and over the whole body, cleansing the entire aura, pooling at the feet and being drawn back up the Middle Pillar with the next inbreath. Do this a total of four times.\nTenth, make the sign of the cross with the usual words. This completes the exercise.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8005256", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why use Greek?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8006280", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Because those five words in Greek were so important to the symbolism of the early Christians. Besides, using a language you don't speak helps you concentrate on the sound, and gets your thinking mind out of the way.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8007560", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "mo_drui_mac_de", "content": "I’m working through Knight’s Experiences of the Inner Worlds, using the Banishing Ritual of the Cross before leading into his Sphere of Light. (I know you never described them in your posts here, but visualisations have seemed to accrete on to that ritual, in the form of golden light forming a cross through the body into infinity, similar to the Elemental Cross in the SoP, and the crosses and circle drawn between them being drawn in crackling golden flame.) Would it be safe to use the Middle Pillar as described above in tandem with Knight’s course, or should that be postponed until the course is complete?\n-Scott H. /|\\", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8018056", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea, never having tried it. I'd say pray about it, and then experiment.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8010120", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would you kindly link me to the banishing ritual? a christian friend of mine is going to love this", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8018312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "At this point I'm not sure where in the last several Magic Mondays it is. Anyone?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8033416", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/75847.html?thread=6893127#cmt6893127\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/78324.html?thread=7150324#cmt7150324", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8034440", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Many thanks for this. I should probably publish this, the Christian Middle Pillar exercise, and the rules for scripture study as a Dreamwidth post for the benefit of Christian readers.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8042120", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have to say, I do like the version with the angels, so I hope you don't leave them out :-)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8034184", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "joshuarout", "content": "Is it this, by any chance?\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/75847.html?thread=6893127#cmt6893127", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8034696", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of two versions, yes. Thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7968392", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "This brushes against The Topic, but is predominantly a geomancy procedural question.  If I am reading\nThe Art and Practice of Geomancy\nright, general lockdowns would be a 12th house question, right, since they refer to restriction and limitation?\nFor questions about them ending, would that then be a 3rd house question (4th from the 12th = end of restriction?)\nFor questions of the type \"will X be banned?\", would that be the 12th from the house associated with X (restriction of X), or just the 12th of the radical chart?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7996552", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes.\n2) Yes.\n3) I'd just use the 12th house of the original chart.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7969160", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "oligopsony", "content": "Hi JMG (and others!),\nAfter a long period of rock-solid confidence in metaphysical materialism I’ve found myself drawn towards the spiritual and occult. Part of this is a possibly-paranormal experience I had a few years ago (during another such kick,) part of it is that my information diet encouraged me to (I started alternating my nonfiction reading between grounded factual stuff and wacky speculation I was likely to disagree with, on grounds that I want to avoid getting stuck in a epistemic rut,) part of it is Earl Fontanelle’s history of esotericism podcast, and part of it is just that I cycle through obsessions. In a podcast interview you mentioned a type that I seem to fall into: the the curious skeptic who’s torn between wanting to believe there’s truth to this and being terrified that it is, without really having a great explanation for either emotion. (For now at least I am bracketing such judgments.)\n1) Insofar as I seem to correspond to A Type, pretend that this first question is whatever it would be best for that type to ask.\n2) In selecting a system to work with (if one does), is emotional resonance with the symbols more important, or something like temperament, or something else? For instance I think a lot of the Abrahamic melange of the Golden Dawn system resonates with me, but I think you’ve made some comments that it can turn you into an asshole, which I wouldn’t want (though I’m putting that more crudely than you did and may simply be misinterpreting.)\n3) What is a good introductory guide to pathworking/active imagination?\n4) I would like to make myself more conscientious - the FAQ says to try starting a conversation with yourself or that aspect of yourself; do you know of a good guide to the subject? (Another MM commenter mentioned a recommendation to do mantras, and I have been using one to apparently good effect.) Is Gendlin’s “focusing” isomorphic?\n5) Nonwithstanding my atheism, when I defended my dissertation, I interacted, sort of, with two gods - the first being the mascot of my school (people leave offerings at his statue, which I did) and the second being the muse Clio, who I mentally noted to thank somehow if it went well (although I don’t remember the details.) The defense went as well as I could have hoped but I’ve been in a rut revising it into a book ever since. Obviously aforesaid conscientiousness would help, but maybe I have unpaid debts to Clio as well, since I didn’t do anything for her other than give her a line in the acknowledgments. (Although presumably she is honored by good historical work generally?)\n6) Are there any good comparative investigations/surveys of contemplative practices around the world that you know of?\n7) Do you know of anyone who has attempted work on reconstructionist Neoplatonism, by analogy to reconstructionism of other belief systems? (I guess this is in an odd position in that the formal theology of the system is better attested than the ritual practices, which is the opposite of many other cases.)\n8) What’s the most “fascinatingly wrong” general theory of magic that I probably haven’t heard of?\n9) What makes a good object of discursive meditation? Should it be something that you endorse but want to understand better, or anything suitably dense and poetic, or just anything at all that you’re interested in? Can discursively meditating on the wrong subjects hurt you (obvious example - discursively meditating on how mean people are to you despite how great you are, or whatever - but presumably there could be less obvious ones?)\nI know that’s a lot of questions - certainly do not feel obliged to tackle all, or even any, of them! And thanks in advance!\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-30 01:18 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7997320", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Why, you should meditate on it, of course.\n2) It varies from person to person. Take up the system that appeals most to you, for whatever reason it appeal to you.\n3) They're all about equal, and amount to \"sit down and try it.\" Pretty much every book of mine that includes instructions on meditation has an introduction to this end of practice.\n4) Again, the best guide is to do it, and learn from your results. I'm not familiar with Gendlin's \"focusing.\"\n5) If you want to get right with Clio, the usual practice these days is to make a donation to an appropriate charity -- that's becoming the de facto equivalent of offering up a bullock. Find a history-oriented nonprofit and make a donation of $9 or $81 to it in her name.\n6) I don't know of one.\n7) Nobody needs to reconstruct it. There are plenty of people who practice classical Pagan Neoplatonism these days, and there have been since the Renaissance. If you know your way around the old literature you should have no trouble figuring out how to start a practice; if not, I recommend Sallust's\nOn the Gods and the World\nas a helpful starting point, followed by as much Proclus as you can stand.\n8) My divinatory powers are not up to figuring out what you might or might not have heard of.\n9) Why, what a fine topic for your next week or so of meditations!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8045960", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "oligopsony", "content": "Thanks! (Both for the more concrete answers and the \"shut up and practice\" ones, which I'll take as an agenda.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8001672", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "7) Here are some good resources for that:\nhttps://hellenicfaith.com/theology-philosophy/\nhttp://opsopaus.com/OM/\nhttp://web.eecs.utk.edu/~bmaclenn/other-res.html#neurotheol", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8003720", "title": "Focusing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dunno what you mean by isomorphic, but Eugene Gendlin’s focusing technique allows the nonverbal part of awareness to communicate with the verbal part of the awareness. The example of a ‘felt sense’ is the relief you feel in your body when you remember exactly what it is that you know you have forgotten. You could remember something else, too, but if it is not the specific thing you just know is hovering outside of awareness. Not the toothbrush, not the slippers, oh! It was the cold cream. Only when you remember the cold cream do you get the relaxation, relief and release.\nTo use it, one concentrates on the non-verbal complex of feelings generated by the issue you want to work on. You get a felt sense of it and then you ask questions about the felt sense(FS0). “What is this FS0?” (Anxiety) What IS it about this FS0? (Scary! or Helpless! or Boring...)\nYou accept the name or word that gives the sensation of relief. Otherwise you keep asking till you find the word that has the best fit. Once the FS0 is named or identified it reveals other layers of questions to pursue. It may shift to FS1 or FS2 which triggers another round of questions until you obtain a clear answer about the origin and nature of the issue and what you need to do about it. If anything.\nIt is essentially a form of guided self-analysis similar to divination. It uses intuition and subconscious awareness without any symbolic tool other than your own vocabulary. Words are symbols too—just somewhat less colorful and richly complex than I Ching or tarot cards.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7969928", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I'm working along on the Paths of Wisdom stuff, and it's going well for the most part, but visualization is a bear. In particular:\na) On the first energy rotation, trying to picture it going up both the front and back of that side of the body *and* hitting the energy centers usually results in one of these getting glossed over.\nb) When I visualize the sphere images, distance/size tends to waver a lot.\nShould I be spending more time/effort on these particular components, or just keep doing them for a few minutes each, and trust that regular practice will work this out eventually?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7997576", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, that. Remember that that was my first book, and some of the details are idiosyncratic. Don't worry about having the energy contact the energy centers -- just keep it flowing down your front and up your back.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7998088", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Awesome--thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7970440", "title": "Hu Gadarn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Bore da, JMG. I haven't been practicing the DMH - I'm fairly certain that ritual magic isn't right for me in this lifetime - but I have been contemplating the Druid Gods mentioned therein. I think that I have a preliminary grasp of each of them as individuals… except for Hu Gadarn. I genuinely can't perceive what differentiates him, in domain or essence, from Belinus the solar year god. Any chance that I could get a hint to inform my meditations?\n- Accidental Mystic", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7997832", "title": "Re: Hu Gadarn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Prynhawn da! I trust you've seen this image or some equivalent:\nTry meditating on that image and all its details -- the sun, the sea, the coracle, the oar, the plough, the first step onto the new land, Hu's legendary role as the figure who led the Cymry from Deffrobani to the island of Britain -- and see whether that gives you the help you need.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8013448", "title": "Re: Hu Gadarn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you; I'll do so.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7971208", "title": "Scents and spirits / powers", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear ArchDruid,\nI read that burning a scented candle is not advised as spirits / powers are sensitive to scent and it may keep them from approaching: this seems to be consistent with specific incense scents being used for offerings to specific deities / powers.\nSo, my question is, is scent an issue at all when doing the SoP? If I splash on some Brute or Old Spice and do the ritual, or even a scented soap or deodorant, is this something to be avoided, or something you would not worry about?\nFrom under the acacias,\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7998344", "title": "Re: Scents and spirits / powers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ask the spirits. Most spirits like some scents -- that's why it's common to burn incense to honor and invoke them -- but very few like all scents. Talk to them and ask them to communicate to you what their preferences are, and then listen for the answer.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7971976", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the last decade or so, a fringe philosophical movement has grown on the internet known as antinatalism, describing itself as a principled opposition to having children. Antinatalism holds the position that all human reproduction, no matter the context, is immoral. Its literature includes David Benatar’s Better Never To Have Been: The Harm of Coming Into Existence, the essays of Schopenhauer, the work of Thomas Ligotti and Emil Cioran, among others. For those who are more ecologically minded, there is also the Voluntary Human Extinction Movement (VHEMT), which argues in favor of human extinction in order to save the biosphere. One of the most popular antinatalist arguments (though not the only one), is the so-called Benatarian asymmetry, invented by the aforementioned philosopher David Benatar, which is a game-theoretical-like utilitarian argument, illustrated using a table, that human existence is always a net harm for those who are brought into existence. For reference, here is the table: https://i.stack.imgur.com/Cfd8b.png.\nIn a brief form, the argument is as follows: If X exists, then there is pleasure (good) and pain (bad). However, if X does not exist, then there is an absence of pain (good), but also an absence of pleasure, which, crucially, is not bad. That is, if someone is not brought into existence, they do not experience a deprivation from the pleasures they are missing out on, so this lack of pleasure is not a harm. However, the absence of pain is a good in-and-of-itself (this is where the asymmetry part comes in). The net hedonic balance in the two cases is thus, for existence: pleasure (+1) + pain (-1) = 0; and for non-existence: absence of pain (+1) + absence of pleasure (0) = +1.  Therefore, the non-existence of X is preferable to their existence.\nInterestingly, it seems that most antinatalists are not against sexuality or pro-celibacy, which sets them apart from historical religious movements like Gnosticism, Quakerism, etc. They only seem to be concerned with the narrow issue of reproduction. Putting aside the practical impossibility of implementing their ideas (many antinatalists will concede this), do you find their ideas compelling? Are you aware of any historical precedents for this line of argument?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7978888", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not JMG, but to me this sounds a lot like a poorly digested version of Christian self-sacrifice. I would predict that this philosophy does not have much traction in non-western cultures.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7990152", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "oligopsony", "content": "Just about everything tends to get rounded off to being Christianity (socialism! neopaganism! obsession with celebrities!) so I’m skeptical about this kind of move in general. It’s not hard to find parallels to antinatalism in Buddhist thought for instance, probably easier than Christian - which doesn’t mean antinatalism is going to get widespread traction in non-western countries; indeed it has not and likely will not gain much traction in western countries either. A vice of the internet is making it easy to mistake an interesting idea for one that most people, who do not trawl the internet for interesting ideas, have ever heard of.\n(You may say that something far less formal related to habits around family is more widespread in the west, but then broadly similar patterns follow in other rich, crowded places like Japan and Singapore.)\n((All of this is orthogonal you the merits of antinatalism, of course.))", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7999112", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I class antinatalism along with eliminative materialism and strict solipsism as absurdist philosophies -- belief systems whose proponents pretend to believe in them, but very clearly don't. In the case of antinatalism, if these people actually believed what they claim to believe, they would kill themselves, since their own logic makes that the only ethically justifiable approach to life. I know of none who has actually done so, and thus I conclude that they're not serious in their beliefs.\nAs this may suggest, no, I don't find their arguments compelling -- quite the contrary. Again, like eliminative materialism and strict solipsism, the logic of their position is so constructed that it's unfalsifiable on its own terms, but that's no argument for the truth of a belief; as Karl Popper pointed out cogently, a statement that cannot be falsified by any conceivable evidence or argument is intellectual masturbation.\nOf course, it's also relevant that I'm an occultist who has some reason to accept the reality of reincarnation. The existence of any form of afterlife confutes their attempt to equate death with an absence of experience and so renders the entire argument of Benatarian asymmetry absurd. There is ample evidence to support the claim that an afterlife is at least as likely as the nonexistence of the self after death, and it seems to me that the entire antinatalist position is rendered untenable by that.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8000392", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, and I neglected to address your question about historical parallels. Yes, it's a very old belief that has been held by a variety of thinkers; you'll find ancient equivalents on the Indian subcontinent and among the more extreme Gnostics, and of course there's Schopenhauer, who made that same view the least convincing and least effectively justified element of his philosophy. Of course he was also a great example of my first point; his supposed conviction that all pleasure was merely an invitation to further pain and that life was unrelieved misery didn't keep him from indulging his desires for classical music, gourmet dining, and prostitutes, or from fleeing from Berlin to escape the epidemic that killed Hegel so that his supposedly melancholy existence would go on for years of further misery and despair!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8002952", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I actually wrote a\nblog post\n(https://spellofwordshome.wordpress.com/2019/12/28/never-to-have-been-a-critique-of-benatars-antinatalism/) dissecting Benatar's brand of antinatalism recently. To summarize it: Benatar presents an incoherent idea of what it means for nonexistence to be better than existence, his asymmetry is supposedly based on a set of moral intuitions and yet is deeply unintuitive, and he contradicts his own philosophy by saying death is bad. This last point in particular applies to nearly every form of antinatalism I've encountered.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8011912", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I think Benatar is arguing from a false premise here--indeed, from a howlingly bad false premise.\nHe posits that pain is bad.  Pain is in deed unpleasant, but it is very far from a bad thing.  Pain (and any other sort of suffering) is one of the very best \"thrust blocks\" in existence that anyone has for leaping ahead into greater wisdom and kindness.  There are good reasons why homespun philosophers think so highly of the \"school of hard knocks.\"\nIn fact, I would rather stand his argument on its head and claim that a life without any pain or suffering would be one of the very worst sorts of life at all.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8043912", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I believe Ligotti quotes Benatar in\nThe Conspiracy Against the Human Race\n- if not Benatar, then another antinatalist philosopher.\nIn essence, Ligotti says that by having children, you become responsible for all the suffering they'll experience, and the suffering their children will experience, and so on.\nBut later in the book, he talks about determinism, in his quest to prove that human consciousness doesn't exist, and says that a determinist court of justice would not hold a murderer to be guilty of anything, because the murderer never had an actual choice.\nWell, hold on:\n1) If I have kids, I could argue that I'm not responsible for their suffering, my parents are. And really they're not, but their grandparents are - and so on and so on, into absurdity.\n2) These two arguments are contradictory. If determinism obtains, then I am no more guilty of inflicting suffering on future generations than I am of committing murder, because whatever choice I may have is an illusion.\nLigotti's book is full of contradictory nonsense like this. Emotionally, it has the tone of an abuser trying to destroy your sense of reality while pleading concern for your well-being.\nAlso, Benatar's table there is nonsense on stilts. Reducing the complex spectra of human existence to a simplistic plus-minus scheme ought to be an omen of the long-delayed death of modern philosophy.\n-Cliff", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7972232", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On the other blog's open post, you discuss with Winston the after death state and the part of the astral plane to which the consciousness is attuned. What are the practical methods by which one can move their habitual state of consciousness to a more advantageous state? Especially without the help of mainstream religion...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8001416", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, that's one of the central points of occult training, you know...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7972744", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) What are your thoughts on the recasting of Stoicism as a self-help philosophy in recent years, stripped down of its religious and metaphysical contents? The self-improvement book isles are full of pop Stoicism books now, and many an online life coach advertises himself as a master in the ancient art of ataraxia. The whole thing reminds me of the treatment that transcendental meditation got, but it seems strange that this otherwise obscure Hellenistic-era philosophy got pulled out of obscurity. Maybe this represents some unconscious realization that we all need to become more stoic in the years and decades ahead?\n2) How do you manage your internet use? Other than posting on your blogs, answering comments and emails, updating patreon/subscribestar, etc. how much time would you say that you spend on the internet in a given day? You mentioned in previous MMs that you don’t browse video content and don’t use social media, but do you spend any time on forums, other blogs, news sites, and so on? Do you maintain any kind of “internet discipline” where you unplug after an hour, or impose any restrictions on screen time?\n3) What does your workspace look like? What do you have on your desk right now?\n4) Are there any texts (or parts of a text) that you have memorized verbatim, like some devout Christians who memorize the entire Bible? Do you find any benefit to doing so, from a magical or religious perspective?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8003208", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's inevitable -- and in fact Theodore Roszak predicted it decades ago in his book\nWhere the Wasteland Ends\n. At this point there's a great deal of money to be made by teaching well-to-do people not to notice how miserable, lonely, angry, and resentful they are, and dumbed-down Stoicism can be turned into yet another tool for doing that -- it meshes very well with what I've come to call mindlessness meditation, the lobotomized form of vipassana meditation that's become the most popular non-chemical tranquilizer among the comfortable classes these days.\n2) I don't manage my internet use. I find the internet dull, by and large, and use it only when I have some specific purpose in mind. There are a very few forums that I visit to keep track of what certain groups of people are thinking and saying, and I have a selection of news sites I use to keep up to date on issues that matter to me, but I don't need to impose restrictions on screen time; I leave the internet as quickly as I can, and go do something more interesting.\n3) A wilderness of clutter and apparent chaos. There are probably more than a hundred things on my desk at this moment. There are bits of notepaper with cryptic notes on them; for example, one says...\nLiber M vel Mundus\nLiber T vel Tacenda\n...yes, I know why, and no, I'm not going to explain. There are books, photocopies. a rat made of alabaster, a letter opener made to look like the Sword in the Stone, a little glass bottle containing some liquid mercury I salvaged years ago from a broken thermometer, and much more. That's the way I like my work environments to be.\n4) All the rituals I use regularly are memorized. So are rituals I've done a lot in the past -- for example, I can still recite verbatim the fairly extensive lines spoken by the Conductor in the Initiatory Degree of the Independent Order of Odd Fellows. So are quite a few poems and some other oddities. My mind resembles my desk...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8006024", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have an Excalibur letter opener too.  Never think to use it, but it looks nice on my desk.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7973256", "title": "Beith - Luis - Fearn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI practise Ogham divination based on the Beith – Luis – Fearn order. When I started with DMH, I meditated on the elemental attributions of the fews and I made a decision to change them so that they fit my order. I could see Saille as water of air and Nuin as earth of air much better anyway, so I thought there won’t be much harm in doing that. Now I am on the page with the Dolmen Arch and the Pentagrams and I feel stuck. I feel my approach can’t hold much longer because then it won’t comply with the other diagrams either. Should I forget what I have been doing and relearn  and remeditate on the fews and elemental attributions according to the order you present in DMH? And if I do, won’t I make a mess of it for myself? Are my previous ogham readings flawed?\nBy the way, I am surprised at the book you are introducing today. I am Czech, but I have never heard of Franz Bardon. Thank you for letting me know.\nHana", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8003464", "title": "Re: Beith - Luis - Fearn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a challenge that a lot of people face if they start with the modern order. The choice is yours -- change it, and change all the subsequent diagrams, or go back and redo the meditations. Either approach will work. No, your previous readings aren't flawed.\nThat's interesting, about Bardon. The Czech Republic has a very long and extremely rich occult tradition -- Prague was for many years the most important center of alchemical studies in Europe, for example. Is that something you've heard about? If not, you have many discoveries ahead of you!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7973512", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. I believe that many online communities, not all of them political, have constructed fairly strong egregors in recent years, and social media and the Internet seem to facilitate this sort of thing. In many flamewars in the current year, one gets the impression that it’s not so much two people arguing, but two people channeling their respective group minds into the online arena. There is a lack of humanity and authenticity in so much communication on the internet; undoubtedly many accounts are bots, but people are starting to feel more robotic in their communication. Is there any way to get in touch and understand such egregors without actually feeding them? I think it would be fascinating to have some kind of encyclopedia of internet egregors, like a modern bestiary...\n2. It seems that a significant number of high-achievers in intellectual and creative fields throughout history have been single and often celibate men. I'm thinking here of a whole group of philosophers, scientists, and artists, among them figures like Leonardo da Vinci, Isaac Newton and Nikola Tesla, and examples could be found from other cultures and civilizations as well. Obviously, one could come up with a whole list of counter-examples, and I don’t mean to imply that all high-achievers belong to this category, but the fact that so many fit the pattern seems anomalous. In Jungian terms, I think there might be some underlying archetypical expression here, which concretizes as the Wise Old Man in our imaginations. What do you think is the reason for this?\n3. In LRM you write something to the effect that handwriting communicates to the nervous system in a way that typing on a keyboard doesn’t. Are the advantages of hand-writing really so significant compared to typing? Are your journals and book manuscripts hand-written?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8003976", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) There's a very straightforward way to observe online egregors: lurk. Don't engage, don't participate, don't say a thing. In Lovecraftian terms, become the Lurker on the Threshold, and you'll be able to watch the egregors slithering rugosely about.\n2) Robert Heinlein made an intriguing comment many years ago: most of the top creative geniuses among our species are either celibate or all the way to the opposite extreme. That makes sense, as creative energy is creative energy, whether it expresses itself through that particular bodily center or not!\n3) It depends on whether I'm trying to communicate with my nervous system or not. My journals are handwritten, my book manuscripts are typed.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8006792", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Some of those guys may have been gay—I think it is the general belief among historians that da Vinci was.  So being uninterested in women doesn’t necessarily mean “gay.”  And I guess “uninterested in women “ is the better way to phrase it since the rigid gay/straight dichotomy didn’t exist back then.\nOr they could have been impotent, for all we know.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7973768", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. Is there any way that I can have better dreams? My dreams are usually dominated by a feeling of anxiety or unease, where I’m put into a strange or stressful situation, like taking an exam that I’m not prepared for, or being chased by a wild animal. This has been the case for more than a decade. I almost never have a dream that can be described a pleasant or relaxing.\n2. In the last year or so I believe that I have more or less discovered my purpose in this incarnation, which alleviated a lot of doubts and existential anguish that I had. Unsurprisingly, this purpose has to do with the subject matter of this blog (occultism and philosophy, basically). While I plan to diligently apply myself to this purpose, it’s also shaping to be quite a lonely path, and the lack of communion with my fellow-beings is troubling. I’m sure that many people on this path can sympathize. Is there anything I can (or should) do about it?\n3. I’ve developed a fear response to the ten of swords after having it come up in a divination, which unfortunately ended up being accurate. I find it unpleasant and scary to look at now. Is there anything I can do about it?\n4. This may be a taboo question, but is it normal that I find the Lovers and Star trumps in the Rider-Waite deck… err… somewhat arousing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8004232", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Have you tried journaling? Written dialogues with the characters in your dreams can bring a lot of buried psychological content to the surface.\n2) That's one of the enduring realities of the occult path. There's a reason why Manly P. Hall calls it the Way of the Lonely Ones! All I can suggest is that you take the opportunity to hang out with other occultists when you have the chance.\n3) Have you considered meditating on it?\n4) Good heavens, yes. The Art Nouveau style -- and Pamela Coleman Smith was very much in that tradition -- is a very lush, sensual style, and most heterosexual men do find Smith's nudes, shall we say, pleasant to look at. (I don't happen to know whether lesbians have the same reaction.) Another artist in the same style is Alphonse Mucha, as per the following example:\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-30 11:53 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8011656", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"I don't happen to know whether lesbians have the same reaction.\"\nYes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8018568", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. That's a data point I didn't happen to have, and I know from conversations with lesbian friends (and from looking at art created by lesbians) that there are significant differences between what pushes buttons between lesbians and straight men.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8021384", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not JMG)\nI’ve been having weird dreams for the last few months.  Could it be a symptom of Coronavirus that dr’s haven’t noticed yet?\nOr could it be the sewage-like egregor we all wade in these days?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7974280", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My boyfriend experiences a decrease in vital energy after sex. Is this normal, and is there anything we could do to keep him from feeling so depleted?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8004488", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's quite normal. The male orgasm releases a lot of energy into the partner's energy body; the female orgasm is less efficient at transmitting energy (understandably, since on a reproductive level, the point of the energy release is to set processes in motion within a woman's body). One thing you can try is, after sex, lying close together in as much skin to skin contact as possible, and your arms around him. In that position, feel yourself breathing energy back into him with each outbreath -- say, for seven slow breaths. See if that helps matters.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8013192", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7975048", "title": "Banishing rituals suitable for two people", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "While in social isolation, my partner has taken an interest in sharing my ritual practice, and I proposed to share responsibilities for the spiritual housecleaning and banish together. My practice is the delightful Christian banishing ritual that you posted here some time ago, but my partner is not thrilled about it. Hence, I thought I might tailor the Sphere of Protection to our needs, but how is it performed as a group ritual? Or do you know of another such ritual that would be appropriate?\nMany thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8005000", "title": "Re: Banishing rituals suitable for two people", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All banishing rituals are meant to be done by one person, acting alone. If two people are both doing ritual work, the best thing to do is for each of them to do whatever ritual practice they prefer for basic training, and then learn or work out one of the simpler forms of lodge ritual, which can certainly be done by more than one person.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7975304", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was enormously affected by my reading of Ioan Coulianu's celebrated book Eros and Magic in the Renaissance_. It really opened my eyes. (PUN THOROUGHLY INTENDED!)\nIt raised a number of questions for me about the nature of photography and videography (and now digital 3D-ography and I'm sure Smell-o-Rama on the way etc.). For example, what does it mean for ten or a thousand or a billion people to see the same image? Are we dealing with some kind of web of pneumatic streams, or is there some sense in which mechanical reproduction cuts that network? (Is this was Walter Benjamin was searching after in \"The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction\", only to be mislead by his Marxist ideology?)\nTake it the other way: what does having thousands and millions of images involuntarily made of someone (say, a celebrity or a major politician) do to them? Is it a \"death by a thousand cuts\"?\nAny leads to appropriate further reading much appreciated. (It's not to this point, but I'm already planning on getting around to making a point of really meaning to remember to remind myself to put Coulianu's book about gnosticism on my list. Yes, that's how far behind I am. :grin:)\nAnd thanks again for your presence in the world. It is a genuine gift.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8005768", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mechanical reproduction doesn't seem to be any kind of issue -- people have been using photographs for magical purposes since about fifteen minutes after the invention of photography. So I'd tend to think that the \"pneumatic streams\" model is closer. I don't know of anything that's really explored this, but then it's not a field I've really looked into.\nAs for getting behind, you have the opportunity to do a little magical training right now. As soon as you are finished reading this, take some definite action to get Couliano's\nThe Tree of Gnosis\n. Why deliberately weaken your will? That's what you're doing, of course...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8010632", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "What you are suggesting here is that having the intention to do something and reminding yourself that you need to do it but not doing it weakens your will? In my case at least that would explain procrastination very clearly as a well of self-induced, ever diminishing will power that spirals into never doing anything, wanting to do everything and setting up myself for imminent frustration. “O.O” I need to get some definite action about a bunch of things I want to do and scrape the ones I don’t for good! This also makes me think about the importance of paying attention to the “everyday magic” that we do in our lives as well as the diffusion of will by having too many disparate goals that has been mentioned on the last MMs. Thank you very much! That last sentence gave me a much needed rush of energy and motivation and linked some concepts in my mind. I hope it as helpful to the OP too. I am sure it will. :)\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-31 02:48 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8018824", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. Yes, exactly.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8038792", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember noticing this danger when making to-do lists for myself years ago. I'd write four or five things that I really needed to get done, and but then I'd starting thinking, feeling more ambitious, and end up with ten or fifteen tasks, including some that were obviously not realistic. Eventually I'd catch myself adding some worthy task I'd had on a dozen lists before and knew perfectly well I wasn't going to do that day either, and realize that at that point the whole list was shot; now I might not even do the few things I'd set down to do in the first place! It was a to-do wish list. It was so strange to notice though, the kind of compulsion to list these things I meant to do or dreamt of doing even as I was admitting to myself that I couldn't or wouldn't do them. I started to recognize this process whereby I avoided mundane chores I could and ought to accomplish by grouping them with more ambitious, more interesting things that I knew I was in no danger of actually doing.\nI talked with my sister about this process once (she'd had the same experience) and we decided it would be better to have two lists: a to-do list strictly for things that should and will get done asap, and a never-to-do list on which to safely put  the things we \"really should\" or \"would like\" to do but know goddarn well we won't. The never-to-do list is great! It's wonderful to say, f it, I should do that but I'm not gonna. And the things I really do need to deal with have a place to sit and stare at me and make me uncomfortable. Meanwhile the to-do list is unsullied and I can get things crossed off it without the drama.\nJust a memory that popped up when I read this thread. Have a good day, all!\nJonathan.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7975816", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "avalterra", "content": "My wife and are *very* slowly working through the CGD. I mean really slowly... no, slower then that. But, we are very consistent in our daily practice (the fortune of working at home jobs). Yesterday at breakfast, I was feeling very odd. I couldn't put my finger on what I was feeling but the feeling was very strong. Out of nowhere my wife said to me, \"I feel really odd, like something's going to happen\". I replied, \"I feel very odd too.\" We went about our day and thought that maybe it was just the pandemic (although it really hasn't affected us that much). I was cooking dinner when my wife called out, \"something's burning.\" Boy was she right. The apartment building one door down from us has a two story back porch made entirely of wood. The whole thing was on fire. The electrical wires were popping off and spraying sparks everywhere. We grabbed the cat and got out of the house. The fire gutted the building and thanks to quick response from the fire departments there was little damage to the other building nearby. It was really scary. Here is the story with pictures and a video (I know you don't do the flicker images, but for anyone else who is curious) that captures just how bad it was.\nAm I right in thinking that our practice has sharpened our intuition and that is the \"odd feeling\" we were getting?\nAV", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8000136", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "avalterra", "content": "Forgot the link, here it is.\nhttp://40southnews.com/fire-consumes-4-plex-in-maplewooed/", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8019080", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a normal consequence of magical training, so the two of you may be taking it slowly but you're clearly doing the work.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7976072", "title": "Pantheons...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding pantheons to invoke for the SOP, is it be problematic if one or more of the deities invoked is regarded as an antagonist of the others, or is frequently a force of destruction?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8019336", "title": "Re: Pantheons...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You should probably pray to each of the deities involved to see if they're good with it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7976328", "title": "Astrology and healthy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI've been told I probably have pneumonia and to stay away from the hospital for now. I've noticed a pattern of having the hardest time breathing during the plantary hours of Mars, Venus, and Mercury. I'll need another day or two of tracking to be completely sure of this...but the theory is holding well so far.\nQuestion: if I'm looking to help myself out with natural magic, am I looking for ingredients associated with those planets? Or simply for planets that promote health?\nAny other suggestions are welcome!\nThank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8019592", "title": "Re: Astrology and healthy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Just focus on planets -- and herbs -- that promote health and healing.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7976584", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When someone reaches Gwynfydd, where do they live and exist? Do they still look human? Are they still on earth, some other aspect of earth, or somewhere else? Can someone still in human form ever see and interact with them directly?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8019848", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The traditional lore has it that as human beings, we can't understand the answers to those questions, because the realm inhabited by dwellers in Gwynfydd has properties that can't be translated into terms that make sense to us.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8020872", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I like this lore! I rather like knowing we're small, and that there are mysteries we can't understand.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8022920", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It really does make more sense of life.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7976840", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Will your new occult system include pathworking or similar use of imagination?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8020104", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so. To my mind that's a very valuable part of occult training.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7977352", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nIn terms of natural magic, what differences might you expect (if any) in the properties of 1) rainwater (or other collected precipitation, such as snow) and 2) artesian well-water?\nThere is a private artesian well nearby to which the owners allow public access (with the expectation of a small donation) and I was wondering if there might be particular magical uses for such water.\nThanks!\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8020616", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Water that comes from underground has a distinctive energy based on the mineral composition of the strata it flows through. What that energy is, though, differs from place to place because the underlying rock is different. You might try getting some and using scrying or divination to try to get a sense of its energy. Water from the sky, by contrast, has a distinctive energy based on the season and time of day when it's gathered. The solar current is shaped by time, the telluric current by place...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7977864", "title": "Anorexia", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In \"Monsters: An Investigator's Guide to Magical Beings\" Anorexia is linked to Demons.\nBased on my own experience, having a daughter with Anorexia nervosa, the description in the book is accurate and helpful for those who wants to understand Anorexia. The text also helped me to see more clearly the difference between the victim and the monster (which is indeed very, very creepy). I also want to share this observation: the very good team of psychologist that are treating my daughter, use the terms \"the uninvited guest\" and \"the monster\" to describe the Anorexia nevosa...\nMy questions:\n1) Regarding prayers to make life less pleasant for the demon, can I do it without asking the victim (my daughters)? I wold like to do it that way, because if I ask for permission, the demon steps in and says something like \"I'm want to have my eating disorder, I love it, don't ever dare to pray\".\n2) If you or anyone else here has insights in relation to Anorexia and magic, please share!\n3) When we started to disturb the demon with more effective methods a few weeks ago, both me and my wife was visited by and old hag type of being during sleep (I did the LRBP with quite good results, but most effective for me personally). Any thoughts on a possible connection between the hag and the demon we tried to disturb?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt7987336", "title": "Re: Anorexia", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would encouraging your daughter to do the SoP be a possibility?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8021128", "title": "Re: Anorexia", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Your daughter is not in her right mind, and you have parental authority over her, so you can pray for her.\n2) Regular practice of banishing rituals, and also rituals such as the Rose Cross ritual of the Hermetic GD or the OIW ritual of the Druidical GD, is essential. You need to keep your own energy clean and you also need to call down positive energy into your home.\n3) Quite possibly the same entity. It's a good sign that it's feeling threatened enough to hassle you.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8039304", "title": "Re: Anorexia", "user": "yuccaglauca", "content": "(JMG: This isn't a question, so I hope you'll excuse the Tuesday post. If you don't put it through, I'll take the hint.)\nI was a hardcore reductive materialist in high school. Then I dated a girl with Anorexia. When I became emotionally and energetically close to her, the perception of a malicious \"thing\" that was \"made of consciousness\" and at least semi-independent of her was clear and concrete enough that I was forced to philosophically reject materialism within hours of first becoming aware of it.\nI was an active participant in the Angry Atheist scene (back when that was internet-cool). I knew all the aggressive rhetoric used to explain away spiritual things, and I steeped myself in the propaganda whenever I had the chance, but the experience was too visceral to deny.\nI settled on the explanation that what I had experienced was a fractured part of her own consciousness, mostly because I found Chaos Magick literature and explanations the most palatable at first, but the line of consciousness existing independently of matter was crossed nonetheless.\nIt may be relevant to note that she was a participant in the Pro-Ana/Pro-Mia scene, which was thriving at the time.\nPro-Ana/Pro-Mia started out with collections of tips to avoid eating and hide purging, but lead into things like thinking of Ana and Mia as deities who would be disappointed in you for eating (or eating without purging), reciting prayers to them for help ignoring hunger pangs, and making blood offerings (from the self harm that was almost universal among high schoolers back then, at least in my experience) to them.\nThat sounds more dangerous to me now as a Ceremonial Magician than it did to me when I first learned about it as a Chaote, although I never did think it was a good idea.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-03-31 02:50 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7978120", "title": "fasting", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,\nHow does fasting affect the subtle bodies?\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8021640", "title": "Re: fasting", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It sensitizes the astral and etheric bodies, making them much more receptive to outside influences. That's why it's good to fast before visiting a temple or other holy place.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8022152", "title": "Re: fasting", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So if you suspect there's etheric or astral pollution where you are, then is fasting a bad idea?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8022664", "title": "Re: fasting", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8033672", "title": "Re: fasting", "user": "joshuarout", "content": "For what it's worth, my experience:\nWhen I began fasting purely for health benefits, I unexpectedly encountered frequent astral/etheric annoyances. I suppose they were there all along, I simply hadn't notice them so clearly before. Banishing helped, as well as a stricter cleansing & ordering regimen of my space, along with natural magic remedies, smells (such as frankincense oil), music, and deity images.\n~JR", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7979400", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've started the Dolmen Arch, and have found the practices seem to work great for me, except for the daily recollection. If I attempt it right before bed, I find I have a very hard time falling asleep for at least a half hour after I finish it.\n1) Do other people have this problem?\n2) Do you know how to address it?\n3) What I've taken to doing is doing it a little before I go to bed, and then spending a little time before going to bed. Is there an issue with adding a little bit of the day after the exercise?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8021896", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, this is a problem some people have. You can certainly do it a while before you go to bed, or what have you; you can even do it first thing in the morning, thinking back over the previous day.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8023432", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Awesome. I think I'll start doing it in the morning then. I'll add it to my morning routine after my meditation.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7979912", "title": "Letting up on Divination and CGD", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG!\nThank you for your help last week.\nI was the guy who really overdid the Tarot and I ching asking questions about my relationships and getting into a fear loop. I'm moved in with my girlfriend at this point and all's well. I intend to honor your advice to put my Tarot and I ching away for a year, and haven't done any divination since reading your response.\nI also commented a few weeks ago asking about transitioning to the CGD from my DMK Modern Magick style practice, I started the seed but after soaking it for 24 hours and keeping it moist for a few days, a ton of tiny (I'm gonna call them) mites showed up on the seed.\nI don't know if they had eggs already in the seed packet I used, or if they were attracted to the seed sitting on my window sill and the moistness or what, but since it hadn't sprouted I assumed it was over for the little guy, so I rinsed him off, put him under some leaves in the grape vines and returned him to the earth.\nBecause of that I decided to wait till after my move so I could be around more and give the seed proper attention. I'm moved now, but now this divination thing has happened. So I wanted to ask, would you recommend abstaining from geomancy, and therefor not starting the work in the CGD at this time? Or starting it but avoiding the geomancy?\nShould I work on something more unrelated to divination like Natural Magic at this time?\nThank you for your help!\n-WindMan", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8022408", "title": "Re: Letting up on Divination and CGD", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd encourage you to leave all divination alone for a while. You can certainly do the CGD Ovate Grade work without doing the divination, though you'll have to catch up on that later; alternatively, yes, you can try something that doesn't have a divinatory component.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7980168", "title": "\"Green Wizardry\", Art of Memory", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Someone I know is setting up some channels on her occult-related Discord server about learning about gardening, food preservation, appropriate technology, and was asking what a good catch-all term for this sort of thing might be. I mentioned your concept of \"green wizardry\" but she didn't want to use the term if you'd object to it, so I said I would ask. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8008328", "title": "Re: \"Green Wizardry\", Art of Memory", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh, can I get an invite to the server? One of my favorite occult communities is one.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8023176", "title": "Re: \"Green Wizardry\", Art of Memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "She can certainly use it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7982472", "title": "An unorthodox communion", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Yesterday I decided to make a small ceremony of communion with the Sun, now that it's in Aries and partly to celebrate my own birthday which is today.\nI don't have a kitchen in the room I rent, so I always eat from other places, and I found a new burger place near my house, with some excellent burgers. I got a cheeseburger with fries and a soda, and placed it on my altar with a yellow candle and some sandalwood incense. I did an opening ritual with both lesser banishings, then I invoked the sun with the greater pentagram ritual and read him his orphic hymn. Then I asked him to bless the food and I ate it in his presence. It felt like he was eating through me, so I was very concentrated on the sensations of the meal. When I was done I thanked him and closed the ceremony.\nI shared this experience in a group of members of a local OTO lodge that organized a talismanic magic workshop last year (I'm in it because I took the workshop), and everyone took it as quite offensive. I don't know what to think of this. I did a geomantic chart to ask for the results of the ceremony (though retrospectively I should have done it before it and not when I got doubtful)and it had Carcer on the right, Laetitia on the left, and Tristitia as the judge. I'm not sure if it means that I shouldn't have done the ceremony, or I shouldn't have talked about it. What do you think?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8001928", "title": "Re: An unorthodox communion", "user": "readoldthings", "content": "Not JMG.\n1. You mis-read the geomantic chart. Tristitia has an odd number of dots, and is thus one of those figures that can never be a Judge. I sometimes take mis-readings as themselves meaningful, though. In this case, I'd see Carcer as representing the OTO group you are part of, Laetitia as the ritual, and Tristiatia as the result. In other words, the OTO group-- including you, insoffar as you are part of it-- is sharply constrained in their actions by their own limitations, which includes the culture of bullying and a--holery that is part of the OTO and the Internet generally. Encountering Joy in anyone, they do their best to turn it into Sorrow.\nBut, like I said, the whole thing is a misunderstanding. When you re-read the chart, do so with that in mind, and also with the following in mind:\n2. The ritual worked perfectly. You called on the God. He responded, and you shared something together. You made the mistake of sharing it with a bunch of jerks-- but don't worry about it; they can't take it away from you. In your case I'd get out of the Facebook group that you probably used to share your experience and focus more on your magic and its results than what other people think, especially if those people are either 1. in the OTO, 2. on the Internet or, 3. and worst of all, both.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8023688", "title": "Re: An unorthodox communion", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a perfectly valid approach to a magical communion, and the OTO members are being a bunch of putzes. Magic does not have to be pompous!\nreadoldthings is right about the geomancy chart, though. Always count the number of points in the Judge; if it's an odd number, you've made a math mistake somewhere.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8035464", "title": "Re: An unorthodox communion", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for this. Also readoldthings!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7985032", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You've mentioned a good bit about ethical magic, but I was wondering what your take was on the ethics of prayer. When is consent necessary to pray for someone?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8023944", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Any time you're trying to change them or change the way they live, you need their consent. A general blessing -- \"[name of deity], please bless X and protect them\" -- is another matter; that's fine to do with anybody.\nAs with magic, if you're a parent you can always pray for your minor child, and if you're the guardian of someone not in their right mind you can always pray for them. Otherwise, get consent!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7985544", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To clarify something, I do the daily ritual like this:\nQC LBRP QC MP QC\nBut then I saw something one or two weeks ago (now can't find of course) where it was suggested:\nQC LBRP QC QC MP QC\nSo LBRP is one ritual opened/closed with QC and the MP is likewise another? Or would you recommend the first (combined) variant?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8024200", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The first is the version I've always done and it's the version that's been standard since the days of the original Golden Dawn. The second -- well, I think it probably deserves a Certificate of Redundancy Certificate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8025480", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would there be any risk to the one with the Certificate of Redundancy Certificate?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8027016", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, but there would be no benefit either.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7986824", "title": "Ars Notoria", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,\nAre you or any of your readers currently working with the Ars Notoria? I have some questions that have emerged from meditations I'm doing based on a suggested working on learning in the Druid Magic Handbook.\nRegards,\nSyfen", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8024712", "title": "Re: Ars Notoria", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, that's something I haven't tried yet. Anyone else?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7987080", "title": "Elder & Younger Gods in SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI hope you and your wife are doing well. I have been enjoying the new Dolmen Arch book, and expect it will be keeping me busy for some years.\nMy question is about setting up the elder and younger gods in the SOP. Right now, I have the younger god in the east for air, opposed by the elder god in the west for water, and I have the younger goddess in the south for fire, opposed by the elder goddess in the north for earth. Is this the traditional setup, or am I being eccentric in this arrangement?\nI am asking because I wondered if male and female should be opposite one another in the directions. My way seemed intuitive to me, but I occasionally go about things bass ackwards, so I thought I should check.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8025224", "title": "Re: Elder & Younger Gods in SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The traditional version was to have the elder deities in east and north and the younger deities in west and south, but I know a lot of people who've varied that. It does seem to work better to have god facing god and goddess facing goddess, since the point isn't to try to raise a charge of polarity energy between them!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8025736", "title": "Re: Elder & Younger Gods in SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "since the point isn't to try to raise a charge of polarity energy between them!\nWould you mind elaborating on that? Is it a sex magic thing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8027272", "title": "Re: Elder & Younger Gods in SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. That's a core technique of one particular school of magic, the one Dion Fortune founded: you get two people who are sexually attracted to each other but are not lovers, sit them across from one another, and use the energy that flows between then as a source of magical power. It's not as effective now as it was in Britain in the 1920s, when there were a huge number of people full of seething sexual frustration!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7989384", "title": "Astrological Interpretation", "user": "steveinnc", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI've been trying to understand my natal chart, and how to relate it to my personality.  I'm aware of your advice that the chart should be taken as a whole, and not to get hung up on any one part of it, so while I am trying to understand it piece-by piece, I am not stressing.\nThe situation is that I am a solar Libra, and Libras are supposed to be very social, and to put it bluntly, I am not.  While mulling that over, the thought came to me that retrograde could mean recursive, that is operating on the self rather than being externally directed.  With that in mind, I also have a retrograde Saturn and Mercury.  Could these be interpreted as showing a tendency to self-limitation and self-analysis (in the manner of their signs and in the area of their houses)?\nAm I on the right track with this.\nThanks!\nSteve.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8026504", "title": "Re: Astrological Interpretation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is a great example of why sun-sign astrology is drivel. The position of your sun does not determine whether you're social or not. You need to look at Mercury, the planet of communication; Venus, the planet of pleasure and creativity; and Saturn, the planet of solitude and withdrawal, just for starters. You also need to examine the rulers of the third and fifth houses of your natal chart, and any planets that are in them.\nThat your Saturn and Mercury are both retrograde is a part of the puzzle, because those do tend to indicate a mind turned inward rather than outward. Here again, though, you have to combine that with all the other indications in your chart!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7990408", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI know that you are not interested in Wiccan type of magic, but I wonder if there is any exception. Do you recommend any author from that ecole?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8011144", "title": "wiccan magic", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I'm going to jump in here, as a long time Witch. In studying three different systems (New Reformed Orthodox Order of the Golden Dawn, Kingstone and Gardnarian) and reading books about others such as Dianic and Fairy, I have yet to discover any distinctive Wiccan magic other than the concept of raising and releasing the cone of power. Since this is a group exercise involving dancing, chanting, etc. while concentrating on a goal and using a group cue to release the energy toward that goal, it isn't really practical to try alone. The bits and pieces of spell work in various books combine candle spells, poppet work, chanting, etc.--pretty much all from the folk magic spectrum. What JMG has described as the theories of E. Levi about magic being a matter of concentrating the will seems to be the basis for most of these. Much mention of focus, visualization and so forth. Witches also use a variety of divination: some do astrology, some tarot, some runes, etc.\nIf you are attracted to the god and goddess of the Craft or to the seasonal and monthly celebrations, the idea of working magic in a group of close friends, etc. then Wicca may be the path for you, but I can't honestly claim that there are any secret ways of working magic that you can't find elsewhere.\nNow it seems to me that the type of magic JMG has described in his book on Natural Magic is an obvious path for Wiccans to adopt.\nRita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8040328", "title": "Re: wiccan reading", "user": "ritaer", "content": "It might sound strange, but \"The Idiots Guide to Wicca and Witchcraft\" is actually fairly sound and comprehensive. Although I have no idea where they got the weird stuff about dragons. The authors are Zimmermann and Gleason. \"Her Hidden Children\" by Chas Clifton is good on history of Craft in the US. Ignore Kelly's \"Crafting the Art of Magick\"; his speculations about Gerald Gardner do not stand up to basic logic. For more reading suggestions, \"The Well-Read Witch\", by McColman, though it was printed in 2002 and may be a bit out of date.\nRita", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8026760", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. I've never had the least attraction to it, I haven't read the literature, and so I have no recommendations to make. Rita knows infinitely more about Wicca than I do!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7992200", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This is a really odd question: but I've noticed that a surprisingly large amount of the time, when I check the number of comments on your blogs, it is the number of the last bus route I used. Is this a random coincidence, or is there something more to it?\n(I've already checked to see if I'm imagining it; I record all positives and negatives on this weird effect, and so far it seems like it's a much larger number than I'd expect)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8027528", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Welcome to the wonderful world of weird things that happen around magic. Carl Jung called this \"synchronicity,\" and it most often appears in exactly this sort of absurd way.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8029064", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Now that I think about it, it started when I began doing the SoP.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8032392", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Heh heh heh.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt7995528", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "More of a comment than a question, but I'd appreciate your thoughts...\nI'm on Book 7 of the Republic. I'm finding that, the more time I spend reading Plato himself and the Platonic thinkers, the more time I spend thinking analogically.\nNoticing that, it occurred to me that an analogy is an underlying pattern of order that can be applied to multiple particular situations. To give an example-- at Home School the other day, my son wanted to make tinfoil boats and load them with pennies, to see which would sink first. Of course, the one in which the pennies were most concentrated was the first to sink. I then had him bring me a staff from my weapons closet, and I demonstrated that a thrust with a staff weapon is more damaging than a slash, for the same reason. His mother then pointed out that the same lesson can be applied to life in general-- the more focused your will is on a particular task, the more quickly and effectively you will accomplish it.\nWell. Another way to say \"underlying pattern of order\" is \"mental plane phenomenon.\" And, like I said, the more time I spend reading Plato-- and considering his words in meditation, as I have been-- the more time I spend thinking this way. In other words, reading Plato and trying to understand him seems to function as an initiation, helping to raise the consciousness to the level of the Mental Plane!\n...And even as I'm typing this, it occurs to me that Jesus spent much of his time speaking in parables.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8027784", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent. That was exactly what Plato was trying to do, you know, and he remains as famous as he does because, tolerably often, he succeeds at it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7995784", "title": "Rain during Aries?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It is due to rain here in the next day or so, and I recall you previously mentioning there is some significance to rain collected while the Sun is in Aries. Am I recalling correctly? Would rain collected during the astrological hour of Mars be similar?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8028040", "title": "Re: Rain during Aries?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Rain collected when the Sun is in Aries or Taurus has a greater charge of life energy. It's not a Mars thing, it's a springtime thing; I'm pretty sure you'd want to do that with the Sun in Libra or Scorpio in the southern hemisphere.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7996040", "title": "Cell salts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI've been doing some research and I'm a little confused. Are cell salts made the same as homeopathics? by which I mean can I buy homeopathics with the right name and then study cell salts and how to use them?\nThanks so much", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8028296", "title": "Re: Cell salts", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Cell salts are homeopathically prepared, but they're usually low potency. Look for 6x if you're in the English-speaking world and 6D if you're in Europe; the higher potency dilutions don't have the same effects.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7998856", "title": "Prayers needed for dying skunk", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Last night, a skunk who is a regular at the feeding & watering station in my yard went into the final stages of what looks like distemper.  This poor creature is now in the final stages of a horrible illness by a fence in the alley near my backyard.  Please pray to the gods to end the skunk's terrible pain and suffering.\nI called at least a half a dozen wildlife services, including the local Department of Natural Resources which is supposed to be the go-to place to have dying wild animals removed from public areas and euthanized.  I was repeatedly told \"we don't do that\", forced to leave detailed messages, re-directed to various know-nothing, do-nothing pencil pushers.  Consequently, I called a private service to ask if they would come out and do it and they said \"Yes, for $150\".  I almost gave them the go-ahead.  I'm still not sure I have made the right decision by not paying the money this afternoon and shortening the skunk's ordeal.  We have warned our neighbors about the situation because they have kids and a puppy.  I asked my Ogham about it though and they affirmed my decision not to have the skunk euthanized.  I am still holding off.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8028552", "title": "Re: Prayers needed for dying skunk", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ouch. Prayers on the way.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8036232", "title": "Re: Prayers needed for dying skunk", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is shooting the poor little critter legal where you’re at, or if not, is local law enforcement lenient about the 3 S’s?  (To Shoot, to Shovel, and to keep Silent.). I can’t think of any other way you could put it down yourself.  When my dad raised rabbits he would slaughter them with a knock on the head, and a skunk’s head is about the size of a rabbit’s, but I wouldn’t want to get that close to a skunk.  I fear your good deed would not go unpunished.  Also, the skunk may have rabies and not distemper.\nYou ran into the same run-around we got last year when there was a rabid skunk on our street.  None of the dog owners could take their dogs out for a walk once it got dark.    Fortunately, the next morning the lady on our side of the street, 3 houses up, found the skunk dead in her yard.  Several of us had volunteered to put it down the night before but the cops said they weren’t allowed to put it down and neither were we.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt7999368", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "I gather that Dion Fortune, at least in some of her books, was torn between the old religious sensibility of rejecting the material plane and its desires for a purely spiritual life and the newer religious sensibility of finding a balance between the spiritual and the worldly things. Any thoughts?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8028808", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8002696", "title": "Abstract emotions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is meant by 'abstract emotions'? I came across this twice recently, once in the discussion of the solar current in The Druidry Handbook and then also in the most recent Cosmic Doctrine chapter. Are all emotions considered abstract, or are specific emotions abstract?\nThank you for your books, blogs, and Magic Monday. I have always been a spiritual person, but had no idea how to express & develop that part of myself until I started reading your Ecosophia blog. Nothing I encountered before felt right. Now, I am slowly building a spiritual practice based on your teachings (SOP, meditation & divination).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8029320", "title": "Re: Abstract emotions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All emotions can be abstract. You can feel love for one particular person -- that's a concrete emotion -- or you can just feel yourself filled with love, with no specific object -- that's an abstract emotion.\nYou're most welcome; I'm glad to have helped.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8005512", "title": "Geomancy on magical protection", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am practicing geomancy, and I am considering participation in a group working the existence of which will be public knowledge, so there is the possibility of magical sabotage that affects the participants if parties with different agendas become involved.\n(1) When using geomancy to check the effectiveness of various forms of magical protection in this case, am I right to consider it an 8th house question (magic performed by the querent)? Or would it be 12th house (concerning hostile magic performed against the querent)?\n(2) How does the 8th special question re: magical workings works? Do I consider this at the same time as the rest of the reading, or is it meant to be its own reading? Right now none of my protection options both perfect *and* receive a positive 8th house magical workings figure. But perhaps I am trying to pile too much into one question.\nThanks very much!\n(By the way, spellchecker wants “geomancy“ to be “bromance”, and “querent” becomes “queer team”. This amuses me.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8029576", "title": "Re: Geomancy on magical protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's primarily an 8th house question, because you're doing magic, but you should watch for any connection to the 12th.\n2) It's its own reading.\n3) You have a kinky spell checker...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8007816", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, is there any divinatory way I can learn which store has Charmin and paper towels, rather than running from store to store?  Already tried asking—if anybody has found some it’s always gone when I get there.\nThis would be a good time to market a Ouija board on which the picture of the moon has been replaced by a picture of a roll of toilet paper.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8029832", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on how good you are at divination. Any oracle will tell you that if you're skilled with it, but there isn't some special toiletpaperomancy that will do the thing by itself.\nYour mileage may vary, btw, but I simply asked the staff at the local dollar store when they expected more to be in stock, showed up tolerably early on that day, and got my two packages without any fuss. Sometimes the simple approach is best.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8008584", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How does the hoodoo bath work on the astral level? I know you said it is less effective on the astral than the banishing ritual, which makes total sense, but I 'm curious how it has any effect there at all. What is the role/magical properties of cayenne pepper? It's not in your encyclopedia of natural magic. I often wash with cold water and vinegar and/or salt, and I'm curious how adding the cayenne and then offering it to a tree makes a difference.\nAny advice for meditating on the geomantic figures?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8030088", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The astral effects of natural magic badly need to be studied by capable clairvoyants; not enough is known about them. As for cayenne pepper's correspndences, I have no idea -- I learned to use it as part of my training in hoodoo, where it's handed down as a recipe that works.\n2) Do it daily!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8008840", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nEven though Arthurian legend is a story of failure, it was successful at staying popular for centuries and attracting many diverse traditions (like Celtic cauldron myths, Atlantean legends, Black Madonna/Mary devotion, Templar legends etc.) into itself. What made it so successful in staying popular and devouring elements from various unrelated traditions? Does it have a life of its own like a thoughtform?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8030344", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You know, that'll give you at least a month's worth of meditation themes. Far be it from me to get in the way of the discoveries you'll make for yourself!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8009608", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "I suppose its close enough to April 1st so I wanted to ask you about the controversial figure of Aleister Crowley, more specifically:\n1. What did he do right and what actual level of competence in magic did he achieve (in your estimation)?\n2. What did he do wrong and what lessons can we learn from his follies?\n3. He and Dion Fortune have made very similar definitions of magic. Who was first?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8030856", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My take is that Edward A. \"Aleister\" Crowley was a minor figure on the fringes of the English magical scene who would be completely forgotten today if Grady McMurtry, a much more serious magician, hadn't taken up Crowley's rambling legacy and turned it into a workable spiritual path. I have yet to see any evidence that the man could magic his way out of a wet paper bag; his supposed magical discoveries were all plagiarisms or pastiches of other people's work, and -- well, let's just say that if you start life rich, handsome, well educated, charismatic, and talented, and the result of a life spent practicing magic is that you end up as a burnt-out drug addict in a small town nursing home with an estate valued at 16 shillings and a name you've personally made a laughingstock on three continents, you're doing it wrong.\nHe did invent his version of the definition of magic you've mentioned; Fortune had to add the words \"in consciousness\" to make it useful, though.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8012936", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh my goodness, my cousin just linked me this\nhttps://online-learning.harvard.edu/course/predictionx-omens-oracles-prophecies", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8031112", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fascinating. I gather that the skeptic (or, shall we say, \"Skeptique\") contingent is losing its grip on the academic scene.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8013704", "title": "Ritual practice", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi\nJust wanted to post an update. I've been working on the LBRP (or summoning, depending) and I've noticed that my initial observations hold: a Banishing ritual leaves me with more focus, a Summoning with more energy. At this point, so as not to wake my sleeping semi-permanent house guest (long, sad story) I 'vibrate' silently. That is, I can actually feel the vibration in my body, even though I'm not making an audible sound.\nI'm going to move on to the Middle Pillar exercise.\nAs soon as I mentioned to a pagan friend my idea about looking at pre-viking divinities and pre-viking names, in order to avoid the nasty associations accrued in recent years thanks to certain misanthropic, antisocial, and, in my opinion, far too publicly vocal groups, she mentioned that there is a movement in Eastern Europe to explore and revive the most ancient Gods from the mists of as far back as anyone knows or can extrapolate. Have you heard anything of this?\nBruce\nRenaissance Man.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8031368", "title": "Re: Ritual practice", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Excellent!\n2) A little.  I know there are Pagan groups in Poland and Lithuania, at least, who are reviving the worship of their ancient gods. There's also a Neopagan who goes by Ceiswr Serith who's done significant work into the Proto-Indo-European deities, insofar as those can be reconstructed.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8035976", "title": "Re: Ritual practice", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "To judge both by the few surviving old sources and by recent folklore, all of Scandinavia and Eastern Europe was originally a patchwork quilt of entirely different pantheons and practices.  Most likely this area was originally the home of a number of unrelated small tribes, each more or less equal in strength and size to any of the others; and they borrowed rather freely from one another.\n(About a century ago, Franz Boas and his students showed pretty conclusively that a similar situation obtained among the Native Akmerican tribes in the Pacific Northwest.  There are several distince families of languages there, as well as distinct genetic heritages and distinct cultures.  But the boundaries between distinct langauge families, distinct cultural patterns, and distinct genetic ancestry do not align with one another.)\nIn Scandinavia and Eastern Europe there are now three distinct Indo-European language families: Germanic (Scandinavian), Baltic, and Slavic.  But most of that region was previously settled by peoples who spoke a quite wide range of non-Indo-European languages, and--to judge by archeological evidence and by their descendants' folklore--had a quite wide range of cultures (including religious practices).  In general, the pattern of Indo-European settlement there seems to have been one of coexistence and mutual adaptation rather than conquest and extermination.\nAll of which is a long-winded way of saying that there is no single ancestral pantheon to be reconstructed, but very many pantheons.  You can choose and pick between them, of course.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8014216", "title": "Proportional Math", "user": "joshuarout", "content": "Dear J.M. Greer,\nCan you recommend any books or resources to learn more about the proportional mathematics techniques mentioned in your books A Magical Education and Celtic Golden Dawn?\nRegards,\nJR", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8031624", "title": "Re: Proportional Math", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of any that have been published since the 17th century. It was standard math back then, though, so you might consider using online archives to find really old textbooks of mathematics.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8014472", "title": "Physical culture", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Quicky this week.  Do the exercises from the Tibetan rites play well with the 10 essential exercises rom your swordsmanship book? Or should one stick do just one set.\nOther Dave", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8031880", "title": "Re: Physical culture", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea. Someone would have to try the combination and see if it works well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8015240", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG -\nSeveral months ago I did the green candle thing to try to generate some work opportunities. I missed it one morning and stopped doing it. I’d like to take it up again. Should I continue where I left off, or should I start over again?\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8032136", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You should start over from the beginning. You can pick up after a day or two, but if you let it go for several months, you need to go back to the beginning.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8015496", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Late question today, but you mentioned once that it would be a good idea for someone to perform lots of banishing rituals if they ever found themselves in Las Vegas. What is the reason for this? Is it the spiritually corrosive Ahrimanic energy of the place that tends to attract undesirable entities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8032648", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That among many other things. You've also got large numbers of people engaged in mindless, addictive behaviors rooted in unthinking passions, which is basically a buffet counter for low-grade parasitic entities.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8017544", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is it safe to say that, if one has a mind and a willingness to learn and persist, the doors of magic are wide open, that everything will be revealed in due time, that this is not an art restricted to the gifted or the Chosen Ones(TM)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8032904", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not only is it safe to say that, it's essential to understand it. There are no Chosen Ones in this work; there's simply a lot of work to be done, a lot of patience and hard work to put into it, and portal after portal after portal waiting for you to open them.\nAmong the reasons I dislike those novels and films about the boy wizard and his chums is that they helped feed the Chosen One fantasy, which was already way too common among would-be occult students. It's the people who think they're the Chosen Ones who are inevitably the first to go running for excuses when it's time to apply the seat of your pants to the seat of your meditation chair and do some serious occult work!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8024456", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a journaling question: how do you handle having an issue which appears to underlie a lot of other problems, but which your subconscious refuses to discuss? Simply put, there's one issue which has come up three times now, but which my subconscious will not discuss, always immediately switching topics. The new topics are always ones which I feel I should address, and I make a fair amount of progress, but I'm a little concerned about the fact my subconscious is actively refusing to address something....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8033160", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Tell your subconscious that it's okay, and you can discuss the matter when it's ready to do so. You can also ask it why it's avoiding the subject and whether there's something you can do to make the eventual conversation easier. Many people have a lot of childhood fear and trauma wrapped up around various issues, and giving your subconscious the space and time it needs to get past that is generally a good idea.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8025992", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "Good evening JMG!\nI started this post a few hours ago and I am sorry to see that my effort of writing as best as I can and being somewhat precise with my inquieres has taken me again to the deadline of this MM. Four minutes left for a final review of it...\nSince I know about it I’ve had an intense desire to do, and get very good at ceremonial magic and other branches of occultism. Something that resonated quite strongly with me was something that you mentioned about western occultism focusing on bringing the spiritual dimensions of life to the material, in contrast with other methods that focus on enlightenment only and leaving the material behind. This focus appeals to me very much and would like to know more about it. 0) Does The Circuit of Force talk about this?  Currently I am doing a yoga program that takes a good chunk of my day and I still have at least a good full year before I can consider if I want to go deeper on it or not so pursuing a full Magical curriculum doesn’t seem to be a great idea just now, which was confirmed by divination. Something that Dion Fortune said makes me think that it wouldn’t be a waste of time at all though and could actually be beneficial for my future magical pursuits. “It is one of the aims of the Hatha Yoga technique to develop the etheric double into an effective instrument of the astral forces.” 1) I am not sure I fully understand what she is saying there but is it something along the lines that developing the etheric body makes it more conducive for the effects of magic to come down through the planes?\nI have been wanting too, since it seems to be missing from my routine to be a complete set, on adding a banishing/invoking ritual like the LBRP/Central ray combo or the SoP. From SundaraYogaShala’s comment on the SoP post, a recommendation seems to be to leave a few hours and a meal in between these two as well as keeping an eye on energy levels. 2) Do you think one is more fit than the other for this purpose?\n3) Last week I mentioned that I’ve been journaling and keeping track on which zodiac the moon and sun are, as well as the phase of the moon, weather and my mood as a header for my divination journal. Is there much that can be taken from this practice? If so, should the sun and moon positions be matched against my natal chart to make better sense of it? I don’t know a thing about astrology but figured keeping track of some major celestial objects could help.\n4) Have you read the book the Etheric Double by A.E Powell? If so, what do you make of it?\nBy the way, the lady at the Theosophical Society’s Quest book shop in Seattle where I got your Geomancy book before everything shutdown seems to remember you quite fondly and replied enthusiastically to my query about it  “Oh yeah, we have all of his books” while my attention was grabbed by your “The New Encyclopedia of the Occult” on a stand next to the cashier desk.\nAll the best", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8033928", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "0) No,\nThe Circuit of Force\nis more practical in its focus. There are bits of the subject you're interested in scattered through many of Fortune's essays.\n1) Yes, that's what she's saying.\n2) The SoP is more flexible in terms of what spiritual disciplines work well with it, and I know of a number of yoga practitioners who are also doing it, so that might be your best bet.\n3) It's a good habit to establish. Don't worry about making sense of it yet; over time, it'll help you develop an intuitive awareness of cosmic cycles.\n4) It's a good solid intro to traditional occult lore about that subtle body.\n5) I'm glad to hear it! My wife and I lived on Capitol Hill for many years, and I spent a lot of time at the Theosophical Library studying the classics. It's one of the things I miss about Seattle. Please say hi for me when you're next there, once the outbreak's over.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/84956.html", "year": "2020", "month": "04", "day": "05", "time": "11-44PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt8064732", "title": "Tarot", "user": "hungryghost108", "content": "Funny that you post a Tarot book, since I was debating whether or not to ask you a Tarot-related question.\nI’m just beginning to explore the Tarot, and I wonder if you have any specific books or resources you, with your unique perspective, would recommend.\nAlso, I’m wondering whether you think Tarot counts as magic under your specific definition about altering the state of consciousness of the practitioner. I am more interested in it as a form of meditation/introspection than divination.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8065500", "title": "Re: Tarot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Tarot is the Swiss army knife of the Western occultist -- 78 blades, each with a different function! ;-)  Seriously, it's one of the core tools of the tradition, and divination is only one of its many uses. As a source of themes for meditation, and of imaginative doorways for the exercise that occultists call Pathworking and Jung called \"active imagination,\" it's unrivaled. Two books by Gareth Knight --\nThe Magical World of the Tarot\nand\nThe Treasure House of Images\naka\nTarot and Magic\n-- will give you plenty of material to work with.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8066524", "title": "Re: Tarot", "user": "hungryghost108", "content": "Thank you very much.\nIt’s funny...I don’t even remember why any more, but yesterday I was taken by the impulse to delve into it. It’s always been something that vaguely interested me, but I hadn’t taken it up.\nOn that impulse I downloaded a Tarot app (I know, I know...) and drew exactly one card. That one card ended up being so incredibly appropriate for my current situation that I’m inspired to delve deeper.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8067036", "title": "Re: Tarot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A lot of people seem to be reacting to the current situation by following an attraction to spirituality of one kind or another. That strikes me as a very sensible response to troubled times.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8064988", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At one point he claims to give \"Mephistopheles\" true name. What do you make of this? (When I first got this book the Police song, \"Wrapped Around Your Finger,\" was on the charts-an intriguing synchronicity...) Why do I suspect that Ursula LeGuin points to a better approach to this naming in the original Earthsea Trilogy??", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8066012", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As I noted,\nThe Tarot\nis a mixed bag. That's by no means all Sadhu's doing -- the whole French magical tradition seems very weird from an Anglophone standpoint. (I'm sure ours looks just as weird from theirs.) My advice with any of the more puzzling features of the book -- you knew this was coming, didn't you? -- is to meditate on it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8072156", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've considered this for many years, and after reading your comment on the subject a few months back, I connected it to Earthsea, with all its Jungian aspects.... I think Le Guin was on to something when it came to getting \"the name\" right ...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8084444", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Remember that Le Guin was the daughter of the pioneering anthropologist Alfred Kroeber, who worked with so many Native American tribes. She grew up in an environment saturated with magical traditions and folklore. (Look up Ishi sometime if you're not familiar with Kroeber's background.) She knew an enormous amount about magic, so it's not surprising you find her work useful!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8065244", "title": "Thanks for the prayers for the skunk", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Hi JMG and Readers,\nI asked for prayers last week about the skunk who was dying in the alley behind my yard Monday night.  The skunk, who most likely had distemper, was still alive and moving a bit on Tuesday morning.  I immediately hired a guy from a local service and he shot the skunk at my request with a powerful air rifle.\nI wrote some of my thoughts about it here:\nhttps://kimberlysteele.dreamwidth.org/2063.html\nThank you for your prayers.  I could feel them and I know they helped.\nKimberly", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8082140", "title": "Re: Thanks for the prayers for the skunk", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Kimberly,\nDid you get my email last week?\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8094172", "title": "Re: Thanks for the prayers for the skunk", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Hi Maxine, sorry, I did not, my Comcast email has serious problems.  Please re-send it to improbable world (no space) at gmail dot com.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8065756", "title": "Settling energies", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was wondering if there is a good somewhat easy method of settling earth energies when dealing with aggressive neighbours who believe in we are all one (and anyone who isn't should be attacked) and use psychedelic drugs. I've made a lot of improvements in this ongoing war of mine with the latest being tourmaline along our boundary which helped enormously against aggressive attacks but being an empath whose very connected to the earth I find my time outside still to be hugely interrupted by their consciousness in my garden, any suggestions for getting them to pull back?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8066780", "title": "Re: Settling energies", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The methods that are good aren't easy, and the methods that are easy aren't good. My advice would be to consult a feng-shui person; they're very good at working with that sort of issue.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8082396", "title": "Re: Settling energies", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi,\nHave you tried a honey-pot spell?\nMaxine", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8066268", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. Why do you think that Tarot, astrology, yoga, and other ‘alternative’ spiritual practices have become so strongly associated with women in recent decades? Lots of popular books, articles and other materials on these topics are created on the assumption that the audience will be overwhelmingly female. Correct me if I’m wrong, but this seems like a historical novelty.\n2. One the common characterizations of Jews in conspiracy and anti-Semitic literature is that they’re secretive, closed off, and are plotting to take over the world. Do you think this perception might be a Christian projection of the Shadow? It’s an interesting bit of historical trivia that it was the Christians of the first four centuries that met all of those criteria, rejecting mainstream Classical society and claiming a monopoly on religious truth (later enforced by violence when what became the institutional Church gained political power). In effect, Christians did have a plan to take over the world and implemented that plan successfully. Could there be a collective guilt in the Christian psyche that was externalized onto the Jews?\n3. Is there any occult significance to the US flag having 50 pentagrams on it, and would it make any difference to add or subtract any of them? I know that the US has had different numbers of 'stars' in different configurations over the course of its history, but the current 50 have been around for long enough that we can probably assume it's the definitive form.\n4. What are your thoughts on the concept of 'mental illness' as an organic disease as currently promoted by the medical and psychiatric establishment? Obviously, the profit motive and corruption of the pharmaceutical industry can be pointed out here, and on the other end of the spectrum, the psychiatrist Thomas Szasz famously argued that it's a category error to apply a model of biological illness to the mind, which is not a biological process. Do you see any middle ground between these two extremes?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8067292", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's not really a novelty, at least not in the English-speaking world. Back in the day, religion was one of the very few fields of activity where women were allowed an active role in public life; by the 17th century, you had women taking the lead in alternative religious circles, and major 19th-century alternative religious movements such as Theosophy and Christian Science were run by women and largely staffed by them as well. Cultural habits all through the English-speaking world continue to remind women that alternative spirituality is one field where there's no glass ceiling.\n2) That's doubtless part of it, yes. Another part is a kind of inferiority complex that's hardwired into most versions of Christian theology -- after all, if you accept the Old Testament, the Jews were God's original chosen people, and the various Christian countries are Johnny-come-latelies.\n3) The current 50 have only been around since 1959, when Alaska and Hawai'i became states. It's entirely possible that there will be 52 in the not too distant future, if the various movements to split California into multiple states bear fruit. Thus I don't think it matters how many stars there are.\n4) Sure. Szasz's extreme is indefensible -- I can guarantee you that if the wholly biological event of a stroke or a concussion affects your brain, it will affect your mind as well -- and so is that of the medical establishment, which simply wants to sell as many pills as possible. In the middle is the recognition that some mental conditions do seem to have a biological origin, some do not, and still others seem to combine biological and nonbiological origins. A sane science of psychiatry would work on differentiating among these.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8072924", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you think that a sane psychiatry would focus more on etheric levels in order to effect changes that simultaneously trickle down to the brain and other aspects of the mind both physical and non-physical? Would this potentially be a way out of the dilemma? I mean, I'm sure it's possible that science could come understand the brain better if it really focused its efforts on doing so - if it wasn't so corrupted by Mammon. But the brain seems like such a complex, delicate thing, I find it hard to see how blasting it with chemicals could ever be anything other than a very rough technic with inevitable, serious downsides.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8084700", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To my mind, a sane psychiatry would work at all levels -- mental, astral, etheric, and physical. There are forms of mental illness that really do seem to be physically based, and since the planes are discrete and not continuous, a physical ailment needs a physical treatment. Those modes of illness that are primarily etheric, astral, or mental, however, need to be treated accordingly -- and it would probably be wisest, in dealing with any such illness that isn't obviously purely physical, to start on the mental plane anyway and work step by step downward from there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8087516", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a reason you think it would be best to start with the mental plane?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8089052", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Because the process of causation naturally moves from higher to lower planes, and once you fix the mental plane, problems further down will tend to unravel more easily.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8073180", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "About answer No. 1: It seems that elderly middle-class and wealthier women tend disproportionately towards pop esotericism, like yoga, mindfulness meditation and such things. I'm not sure what is behind it; but the trends mentioned don't seem to play a role among lower-class people and those on the fringes on society.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8085212", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Granted, but women lower down the class ladder have their own alternative spirituality. They were the ones I watched buying house blessing incense at the dollar store and heard sharing recipes for \"doll-baby\" (poppet) spells at coffee hour after Eastern Star meetings...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8089820", "title": "House blessing incense", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks. Remind me to hit the Dollar Tree website for house blessing incense! If they carry ut here these days.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8119260", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I always thought the Eastern Star crowd was pretty well off?\nOne thing I’d like to know is why young white and Asian PMC women affect that nasal whine when they speak?  (One writer, I can’t remember who, called it Quacktalk.). It’s excruciatingly unpleasant to listen to.  Maybe it’s a status marker?  “Because of my parents’s money and my sex, you, peasant, must listen to me for just as long as it pleases me to force you to do so.”  Or maybe that guy JMG is always mentioning as encouraging incompetent anti-Trump magic tried to hex a duck 🦆 one day. (Why a duck?  Why NOT a duck?). Whatever he tried to do to the duck didn’t work and instead he put the Quackspell on millions of young women.  Whatever causes quackspeak, I sure hope a cure is found.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8122588", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Good heavens, no. Most American Masons these days are lower middle class or in the skilled-trades end of the working class.\n2) I have no idea. A nasal whine is traditionally the mark of being spoiled rotten -- do you think that might have something to do with it? ;-)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8067548", "title": "The Art of Memory", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThanks to you for writing it and thanks to the fellow last week who put me on to the Ancient Order of Druids in America articles.  I have memorizes my 4 garden circles, my letters and my numbers but 9 is giving me problems.  This week, I will be trying to put it all together.\nMaxine\nPS I thought the Art of Memory would be much harder than it actually was.  I recommend anyone who is interested to have a go.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8068828", "title": "Re: The Art of Memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. The Art of Memory is a very valuable tool; some people find it easier than others, but anyone who has a working visual imagination can use it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8068060", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Over the last few months I have, during rituals, sometimes felt surges of certain elements, as if they might become overwhelming. \"out of control\" was a phrase I thought of, but that is disrespectful and silly as I am not hugely experienced, nor a wizard in a fantasy movie.\nI am not sure to what extent these surges matter or if they are simply a powerful experience of ritual.\nAround midwinter, I had one with some norse ice and snow spirit images, in a non-SOP ritual, and in the month or so after that occasionally with earth and winter during the SOP. Both of these are an element I am relatively comfortable with so it was exhilarating as much as worrying.\nThen a while ago, this would now be in spring, also during the SOP I had one with spirit below. I had been reading some Latin American fiction, and during the ritual phrases like \"Latin American earthquake goddess\" kept popping into my head. That scares me! It is also not something I feel an affinity with. I am in Europe. I haven't felt it as strongly since, but the idea or feeling is there most of the times I do the SOP.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8069852", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is a common experience, and nothing to worry about. You're simply tapping into your own capacity to experience the elements more richly and deeply.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8068316", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why does r/occult seem to be obsessed with King Paimon? I visit the sub occasionally, and there are usually mentions of him. Are they messing around with dangerous entities? Cos that's what it looks like to me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8069084", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Seems like\na movie involving Paimon\n(https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffewing/2018/06/29/hereditary-and-the-economics-of-serving-the-demon-king-paimon-spoilers/) came out a couple of years ago. Could just be a pop-culture-driven fad.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8070108", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The whole fascination with demonolatry in the pop-occult scene baffles me. Yes, they're messing around with dangerous entities, and I havea no idea why.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8071644", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder how much of it is related to TDS and the \"Magical Resistance\" being promoted by people like Michael P Hughes? It seems to me that the Magical Resistance played a big part in getting the ball rolling when it comes to the current popularity of demonolotry in the pop-occult scene.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8085468", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm sure that helped spread it, but the demonolatry thing was already fairly widespread before Hughes started his misbegotten crusade.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8075484", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "I suspect it's partially a case of \"Christianity says it's evil, therefore it must be good.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8085724", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No doubt that plays a part!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8123356", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "I'm a former Satanist so I may be able to shed some light on this.\nThe answer lies in the \"pop\" prefix. In America, there is a very limited view of the occult and magic. There's Christian magic, which sounds oxymoronic to those who are starting out, and despite there being a abundance of it in the West, always feels out of place due to mainstream Christianity's hatred of the occult. New Age and Wicca  that feel as if they are for women. And there's the Dark Side. (I know I'm oversimplifying but I'm in a hurry and writing this on a small tablet.) The last is so popular because it is so frequently depicted in Media and those who turn to the occult are usually dissatisfied with Christianity to begin with.\nEarly on I became unhappy with the lack of depth in Satanism after I started reading widely but found no alternatives. The Christian influence was extremely pervasive and I felt a strong aversion to it. I wasn't drawn to New Age or Wicca. I heard from someone that there were people worshipping the Greek and Heathen gods which I reacted to in the same way as when I learned of Otherkin. Druidry didn't get so much as a chuckle when I heard there were modern day ones. I assumed Druids were Wiccans too embarrassed to call themselves Wiccan. In the case of Hellenism and Heathenism my dismissiveness was that it was so far from the image I had of serious occultism, the image that came almost entirely from the media, and the then unknown influence of Progress, the notion we had moved past such things.\nTL;DR: The image of the occultist is of a dark shadowy figure thanks to the Media and Western history and most are happy to play their assigned parts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8123868", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fair enough, and thank you for this. I gather you've found your way to something more interesting.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8126428", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "Indeed.:)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8134108", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I can understand that, yeah. I've often commented that I'd far rather people think I fit the Jack Chick image of pagans than the \"painfully sincere Granola Girl who probably thinks she's actually a tiger\" one in pop culture. Ended up just being very solitary until I found a more sensible bunch of people rather than going full Satanist (they seemed just as doofily sincere in a more Hot Topic kind of way, and/or were way too Ayn Rand for me) but I know the impulse well.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8070876", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "moops25", "content": "I think the reason you may see Paimon mentioned more in recent times is because of the movie Hereditary. There's more to it, but I don't want to spoil the movie for you. It's a great flick.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8090844", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "From the late Middle Ages (at least) onward, Paimon has been one of the four demon kings associated with the four points of the compass and (by some) with the four elements as well: Urieus (E), Amaymon (S), Paymon (W) and Egyn (N).", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8068572", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recently was researching a geomancy question online and ran across a link to \"The Geomancer's Handbook by Jose Bacelar\" — on opening it I got suspicious since it was clearly an uploaded PDF of a book without the front cover or front matter. I flipped ahead a few pages to see if there was an author name on the top of the pages, but finally went straight to the end, saw your photo on the back cover, and closed the tab.\nDo I need to purchase a copy of that book to avoid problems with my divinations going forward, or does my lack of intention (and knowledge) cover me? I purchased your later\nThe Art and Practice of Geomancy\nquite a while ago, if that makes any difference.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8070364", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't worry about it. You ran across it by accident, didn't make use of it, and you've already bought my book on the subject, so you're good.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8093148", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi! I have a adjacent but different situation, where I was browsing some books online back in my more uncaring, selfish phase. Luckily, I began to take my responsibility to support authors more seriously, and stopped that nonsense a while ago, before I stumbled upon Ecosophia. I received two of your books as Christmas gifts recently, but I did read part of a pirated copy before, of one of those books, and of another different one. Do I need to directly buy the specific book that I looked at years ago, or is the working vague enough that a different one of your works will \"absolve\" me? Do I need to directly buy a copy rather than receive it in order to do so, or has the act of having asked for a gift of a purchased book done enough?\nAlso, I'd like to both thank you for giving free access to the SoP, which has been wonderful, and apologize for taking advantage of pirated copies of your books in the past. I was younger and dumber, but as someone who has always loved books and writing, I really should have known better.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8094428", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. Getting a book as a present is fine, so long as the person who gave it to you got it in some legal fashion. On the other hand, if you're using any material from the book you read in a pirate edition and don't own, that material isn't going to work for you until you make it right by buying a copy (or having someone else buy one and give it to you). That's the specific intent of the working: anyone who steals any of my books will receive no benefit from what they stole.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8095964", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You make no ethical distinction between stealing a physical good and illegal file-sharing? The latter doesn't deprive you of a copy of the book, even though an argument could be made that it deprives you of potential revenue, which isn't quite the same thing as taking what you already own.\nThis raises the controversial issue of intellectual copyright, but as a person who is actually involved in the business of writing, you may have a better grasp of this than I do.\nHowever, as a wise man once said: \"It is difficult to get a man to understand something, when his salary depends on his not understanding it.”", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8098012", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "From my perspective, there's no difference at all, because either act deprives me of part of my livelihood. I don't own the copies of my books on sale at bookstores -- the bookstores own them -- but their theft makes it harder for me to support myself by my writing. The same is true of e-theft.\nAs a writer, I get between $1 and $2 for every copy of one of my books that somebody buys. That's what pays my bills and makes it possible for me to devote all my work hours to research, study, and writing. Those who steal my work, electronically or otherwise, are stealing my income just as much as though they mugged me and ran off with my wallet. If someone is going to do that, I feel it's perfectly reasonable for me to return the favor, and see to it that they get no benefit from their theft.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8108508", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One other thing. It's because enough of my readers are honest, and buy the books they need, that I can afford to put chunks of my time into my weekly Magic Monday ask-me-anything sessions, and the various other free services I try to provide to the occult community. If I had to flip burgers for a living, I couldn't spare the time for that, or for the translations I do (very few of which bring in much income), or some of the other activities I do to pay forward the help I received when I was first getting into magic.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8107740", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ahh, so it isn't a \"punishment\" that sticks around and messes with people per se, just a sort of generalized way of making the book next to worthless for the pirater. Well that's interesting and quite amusing, because I remember going, \"whatever, this dude is delusional\" while reading one of the pirated books from back then. My attitude towards magic and occult stuff has, before I encountered Ecosophia, usually been more like, oh cool! Ideas for fantasy; idk if this is real or not. Maybe that ridiculous sense of total rejection was the working doing its job! Very cool stuff.\nI am not using, and haven't used any pirated book for quite a while. The other book (besides the Druid Magic Handbook, which I received as a gift) was some book on Atlantis and stuff.\nOne more question; how does this work with libraries and library loan? I've gotten a couple of your books that way, though of course I buy when I can. I assume it's fine, but I thought I'd better make sure. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8108252", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Libraries are fine if you haven't previously pirated the book. The library paid for the book, after all!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8112092", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What if someone unwittingly buys a pirated copy?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8118236", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If the copy's not legal, it's not going to do them any good. Sorry.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8069340", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. One of the most important goals of magic is learning to recruit all parts of the mind, both the conscious and unconscious. How do I know when my unconscious mind is working towards my goals and intentions, and has a favorable view of them? Dreams would be the obvious place to look, but unfortunately my dream life is pretty unremarkable no matter what I do.\n2. I find that my subtle faculties are more acute at nighttime than during the day. I have more spontaneous imagery come to mind, the process of visualizing is easier, my intuition is sharper, and I generally feel that the boundary with the other world is thinner at night. Is this kind of thing normal, and do you think it would be a worthwhile experiment to shift my magical practice to the evening or even late at night? I currently do the LBRP, MP, meditation, and some relaxation exercises soon after waking up in the morning, which seems to be the most popular choice.\n3. Is there anything I can do to gain a more intuitive understanding of the 12 astrological signs as archetypes? I’m looking for some symbolically-dense images that I can meditate on similar to the Tarot cards.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8070620", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's something that takes many years of practice and increasing sensitivity to be sure of, though the regular practice of divination, and of imaginatlve practices such as pathworking, will help.\n2) I have no idea if it's normal or not, but don't worry about that. Experiment with it if you think it's worth the attempt.\n3) I don't know of a set of images like that. My sense of the zodiacal signs was improved by reflecting on the seasonal cycle and thinking of each sign as typified by the weather and other conditions when the sun is in that sign.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8078300", "title": "Zodiac images", "user": "rationalist858", "content": "Concerning number 3, what do you guys think of this?\nhttps://doorofperception.com/2018/09/johfra-bosschart-zodiac-paintings/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8082908", "title": "Re: Zodiac images", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Wow, those are great, thanks!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8132572", "title": "Re: Zodiac images", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think I’d love it if that guy illustrated a fancy leather bound edition of Lovecraft or C.A. Smith.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8069596", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening Mr Greer,\nI have a difficult question. Jason Miller said: \"Don't be afraid to be firm with the gods.\" In my life very recently, my woman who is a foreigner has been prevented twice now from coming to my country, first by the action of robbers and secondly by the death of her aunt, both very sudden and sad occurrences. Of course, I am certain that this is not mere \"bad luck and circumstance\"; I have thrown all of my admittedly very novice sorcerous skills into this very endeavor; I thank God and the gods that she and I have met, but I am becoming very angry and upset that our meeting has been stymied by seemingly \"random\" occurrence, especially as I carry out a daily theurgic worship of the day's ruling Deity, to include a candle, an offering of water and incense, and a recitation of the Deity's Orphic hymn. The day before yesterday, when she told me her aunt had died suddenly in a car accident, preventing her from coming to me, I became so infuriated with the gods that I actually extinguished the candle on my altar, and threw out the offering to my Lady Venus. I am still very upset with God, the gods, and circumstances.\nHaving written all of this out, I'm not even sure my question is. It feels like I am slamming my face against the wall here. Are the gods toying with me? I am not some fellow who can easily meet or romance women -- quite the opposite, I can assure you -- and when she and I connected, I was so joyous and hopeful, it really felt like fate or destiny was bringing us together. And yet now, so many things keep occurring which prevent our union. And what's worse, I don't /want/ to stop my offerings to the gods. For the past many months, I have carried out a daily offering to all spirits (simple incense and water) and also the aforementioned simply theurgy. But I was very upset when I heard of her aunt's death, so much so that I swore not to give any offerings, or any prayer, or anything else to the gods until she is by my side.\nI just don't know what to do. I care about this woman quite a bit. But it seems like some random happenstance leaps in our way every time we draw close to one another. I guess I am asking, is what I am doing in cutting off all prayers and offerings right? Should I do something else? I feel so confused, even as I type this message out; like there is a miasma descending upon me even now. For what it is worth, the SOP is \"my magic\"; I perform it pretty much every day on exiting the shower. When I tell people what to do to become healthy and grow more vibrant, I say, /1/ lift weights and /2/ practice the Sphere of Protection ritual daily. But I just feel lost and alone, and very sad and confused.\nPersonally, I very much thank you for all you do, to include this weekly Q+A. You have certainly set an example for those who dare claim to be moral agents in this world.\nAndrew", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8071132", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The gods have many, many better things to do than to toy with your life. How are your divinatory skills? Have you considered doing some divinations to try to figure out what's going on here/ And -- I hate even to suggest this, but I know of some examples -- are each of these unfortunate events followed by a request for more money from you?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8071388", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for the response. To answer your question, I have been practicing geomancy (having read your excellent book) for about a year, and my own several geomantic inquiries to that effect have all said that she is being honest and up front with me. Further, I paid for a divination from Sam Block, someone who I view as a very competent and masterful sorcerer, and that divination likewise said the situation was entirely as it seemed, that she was not attempting to just get money from me. In point of fact, her aunt left her a very large house, which she is now trying to sell; I have not sent her money after these things occurred (this was my worry as well). Perhaps this is meant to teach me to trust and believe in God and the gods after all. I very much want to believe: even now, I want to put all of my belief, trust, and love behind the gods, and carry on with my daily offerings. It hurts my heart to have stopped giving offerings. But it is very painful and frustrating. For what it is worth: when she is at last by my side, I will be \"on the hook\" for weekly offerings to my Lady Venus and my Lord Jupiter for a year and a day. I vowed to perform these offerings before she and I met, and I will certainly carry them out, no matter what. I'm just feeling very saddened by circumstance: it may well be that lockdowns due to the plague prevent us from being together for several months, in addition to the misfortune we have personally experienced. I'm still not even sure if I have a coherent question from all of this. But, I am very glad that you provide this forum where many people may share knowledge. I am also grateful for you, personally, that you so generously give of yourself in this manner.\nAndrew", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8083676", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Consider the possibility that the gods are granting you exactly what you need in order for a relationship to flourish: time to learn to handle impatience and frustration in a less temperamental manner. Meditating on the work of Epictetus might be useful for you.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8085980", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fair enough. In that case, accept that the situation is what it is, and remember that even the gods find the world frustrating from time to time. Any good book of Greek mythology will remind you of that!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8071900", "title": "Working alone", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi John Michael Greer,\nAlthough a long time reader of your blogs, I have never before practiced, but now after some preparation I started the practice 3 months ago. First the SOP and Meditation presented on this blog. Two months into practice, after adding all the 7 elements I changed the SOP to the DMH version, which I intend to follow. I also do Ogham divination and have a journal.\n1. I seem to be a complete muggle, and I do not think I have an all too great a feeling for it.\na. I do kind of see that performing the SOP sort of calms me, clears my mind, gives me more energy/focus, kind of like a week cup of coffee, or a cold-ish shower.\nb. I sometimes get useful advice from my divination\nc. By analyses I am better at visualizing in SOP and color breathing. And I can sometimes perform 5 minutes of breathing + 10 minutes of meditation. (some of the time is actually focused)\nAll in all, a technical progress without any \"revelations\".\n2. The actual question is, also because I read Dion Fortune's Self Defense and she references several timer calling on support from more experienced colleagues;\nI am doing this on my own, under nobody's guidance but the DH, DMH and this blog.\na. Would I be better served by joining a group? Is that required, or recommended?\nb. To my knowledge, there are no such groups in the vicinity. How would I find one?\nc. Is it safe to practice on your own?\n3. Maybe a general question; What would be the recommended \"path\" for a new occultist?\nThank you\nV\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-06 08:27 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8086236", "title": "Re: Working alone", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) This is completely normal for a beginner. If you'd never tried to play a musical instrument before, and you decided to start learning, you'd be about at the same stage in terms of your playing after three months. Magic isn't easy; it takes the same kind of patient, relentless practice that music does.\n2) I don't recommend that beginners join groups. There are some good magical orders out there, but most of them are very slow to accept new members, and there are a far, far greater number of groups that are useless or actively harmful. It's usually far better to study and practice on your own for at least a few years, so that you develop some skill and also some knowledge, and have some basis to assess any group you encounter thereafter.\n3) There's no one path. You choose a system for your initial work and follow it -- and that's what you've done.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8089308", "title": "Re: Working alone", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Thank you,\nI guess I kind off overreacted after reading the Psychic self defense. So I work further and see what comes along. If it is in the cards;\n„When the student is ready a master shall appear.“\nBest regardas,\nV", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8072412", "title": "Emotional Awareness", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear ArchDruid,\nMy emotions are partially numbed. Not altogether, but I would like to expand my awareness of my feelings. When I try to look inward, sometimes I just can’t find anything there. I have read this is not uncommon in men, especially if they are raised in a ‘macho’ culture. I haven't suffered any serious physical abuse, but I was pretty much a social outcast in my Junior High and High School years, which did do some emotional damage.\nMy question is: is the issue of expanding awareness of ones emotions addressed in magic, and if so can you recommend any practices, books, or other resources that might be of help?\nFrom under the acacias - Thank You.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8086492", "title": "Re: Emotional Awareness", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Magic as such doesn't address this to any great degree, but there are certainly resources. It's important to have a working knowledge of psychology, since you're basically getting in under the hood of your own mind; the system I recommend for occultists is Transactional Analysis. (Eric Berne and Claude Steiner are two authors worth studying in this context;\nGames People Play\nby the former and\nScripts People Live\nby the latter will give you a good grasp of the system.) That will also give you some tools to work with. I also recommend the practice of journaling, as discussed in the Magic Monday FAQ -- it's a good way to get suppressed issues to the surface of your mind.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8072668", "title": "Do-In", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nDo you have a book that you could recommend for learning Do-In/acupressure? I have some basic knowledge of massage, but I would like to improve it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8083420", "title": "Re: Do-In", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nI googled Do-In and there seems to be little online about it.  You said that you do daily Do-In exercises.  Is it possible you could do a thread about what they are so we could give Do-In a go?\nMany thanks.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8087260", "title": "Re: Do-In", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Do-In was very popular for a while in the 1970s and seems to have fallen into almost complete oblivion since then. I know of three authors who wrote about it, and their books can still be found in the used book market. Michio Kushi's\nBook of Do-In\nis encyclopedic but very difficult to use. Jean Rofidal's\nDo.In\nand\nDo.In: The Philosophy\nare considerably better. My favorite author, though, and the one I've mostly learned from, is Jacques De Langre, whose two books\nThe First Book of Do-In\nand\nDo-In 2\ncombine good solid instruction with some of the most entertainingly crazy theory I've had the pleasure to read.\nDoing a good, user-friendly, and sane book on Do-In is a project I've had in mind for some years, but I'd need a photographer and a model or two, since photos are very useful in making sense of the techniques. Someday, maybe.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-06 07:18 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8073436", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi again John, it's Aziz (your fellow esoterica enthusiast from Arabia).\nI'm not sure if the March open post is over or not, but if you don't mind we can continue on that subject here. I was asking on how to know which sephira one's in, and you answered \"check if you have a physical body, etc\", did you mean that other sephira(s) can only be accessed through astral travel or it's something else?\nAnother question...\nI've always been thinking about this, but don't you think magicians evoking and commanding a spirit to appear is ethically wrong? I'm more of a Taoist when it comes to this, as I believe a spirit will appear by its own will if need arise, but then again there's so much to learn and gain from these arts and grimoires.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8088796", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) As long as you're physically incarnate, you're in Malkuth. What you can access is the reflections of the other spheres in Malkuth -- Yesod of Malkuth, Hod of Malkuth, and so on. To reach Yesod itself requires many lives of focused effort.\n2) I consider commanding and forcing spirits to be unwise as well as unethical; you get much better results by developing relationships of mutual respect and assistance with the Unseen. My work with spirits has mostly been with angels, planetary intelligences, and elementals, precisely because you don't command these -- angels, of course, can't be commanded by any merely human power; intelligences are, as you'd expect, curious about us, and will work with human mages so long as appropriate astrological conditions are met; and elementals are eager to work with humans who treat them appropriately, especially in the mage in question has receive certain initiations (for example, those in the Rosicrucian lineages), which I have.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8104668", "title": "Rosicrucian lineages", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there any books on Rosicrucianism that offer self initiation techniques?\nThanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8107484", "title": "Re: Rosicrucian lineages", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, that's one where you have to join something. My connection to the R+C current comes via the Societas Rosicruciana in Civitatibus Foederatis (SRICF), which is limited to Master Masons, and the Societas Rosicruciana in America (SRIA), which isn't, as well as the Rosicrucian degrees in the Scottish Rite, the Golden Dawn, and a couple of other organizations it's not appropriate for me to name. There are plenty of Rosicrucian options out there, if you're willing to put up with an old-fashioned occult correspondence course or two.\n\"For we be brethren of the Rosie Crosse,\nWe have the Mason Word and second sight\"\n-- there are a fair number of 'em out there.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8073692", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI'm continuing to read Manly Hall's Self-Unfoldment Through Disciplines of Realization, which is such a great book. There are a lot of ideas in it that seem connected to aspects of the SOP, where the SOP uses ritual to enact some of the themes he suggests that the reader meditate on. The book has made me consider the differences and similarities between it, the DMH, Dolmen Arch, and the Kybalion, in the basic sense that I understand each of them so far.\n1. Is it true that aside from the DMH, each of these came from roughly the same occult tradition? I wonder if Atkinson and Hall knew each other, for example.\n2. Are there any dangers with reading Hall's book (not doing the practices) while pursuing the DMH? In the DMH or perhaps here on MM you're referred several times to how Druidry tries to incorporate things like normal human emotions and experiences, it tries to be of this world rather than trying to escape it. In Hall's book, unless I've misunderstood something it appears that he takes more of the Eastern view of things where you eventually become calm and 'placid' enough that you, for example, avoid emotional extremes both positive and negative. If I've understood that right, then that would appear to be one area in which the systems differ.\n3. This question is more specific to the DMH, it came out of this week's meditations on the solar and telluric currents and the symbolism around them. At the beginning of the DMH, the solar current is described as being also known as the current of knowledge, the telluric current the current of power. My realization this week was that the lunar current, being a factor that resolves both currents into a ternary, becomes the third ray of Awen, and perhaps could also be known as the current of peace, as then knowledge and power are reconciled.\nWhere I'm starting to confuse myself is here: the three fews in a daily Ogham reading also fit with the three rays of light, where the ray of knowledge comes from the past and the ray of power reflects the potentials from the future, which may imply that the solar current corresponds to the past, and the telluric to the future. However, in the first part of the Dolmen Arch, the descriptions of the cantrefs for Spirit Above and Below show that these correspond to time to come and time past respectively. To make it simpler for me to communicate (<-> = corresponds to):\nSpirit Below <-> Telluric current <-> Current of Power <-> Future few in Ogham spread <-> but time past in Dolmen Arch?\nSpirit Above <-> Solar current <-> Current of Knowledge <-> Past few in Ogham spread <-> but time to come in Dolmen Arch?\nI'll continue to meditate on this, but could you give me a hint to what I'm missing here?\nThanks very much, as always!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8089564", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Not the same tradition, but the same broader movement. I don't know if Hall and Atkinson met, but Hall certainly knew Atkinson's work.\n2) You can certainly read it, and think about it. Just don't mix the practices.\n3) You're not missing anything. In every set of symbolic attributions you run into paradoxes like this. That's inevitable, because the subjects we're studying reach beyond the capacity of human thought.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8100316", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!\nI was thinking about what I wrote in 2) a bit more since I posted it. I mischaracterized Hall, I forgot that he's drawing on many religions in that book, and although it's not explicitly stated, doing the practices as outlined in Self-Unfoldment is discursive meditation. Also, there's perhaps an undercurrent of aiming for balance throughout that book via the practices, and nowhere does he state that the practices, like I first implied, have anything to do with trying to escape this world. My tendency to oversimplify got the better of me...", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8074204", "title": "Bullies.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How can I get less upset about office bullies that strive to pick at my buttons underneath the radar of the adminstration?\nHow would you recommend I stop allowing myself to get bothered by it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8091100", "title": "Re: Bullies.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "First, I recommend journaling about any childhood experiences of being bullied that you have. Very often what makes this sort of situation difficult is that events in the present stir up unresolved emotions from the past.\nSecond -- and don't do this until you've done a lot of journaling on the subject! -- choose an affirmation suitable to the situation and repeat it frequently. You can find instructions for that\nhere\n.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8074460", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWhy does Christian bishops wear a mitre which looks like the fish-hat of Oannes in Mesopotamian mythology? Does it have another reason than the \"fish name\" of Jesus?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8091356", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't think anyone knows for sure. My guess is that it's a reference to Christianity as a religion of the Piscean age.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8108764", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I note that rising sea levels are kind of on the nose for the Age of the Waterbearer...\n- pretentious_username", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8115676", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At one point, I was taught that it had to do with the Petrine connection, beginning with Western bishops who recognized the Bishop of Rome as the successor of Peter, “the Fisherman.” Eastern bishops, by purposeful contrast, where mitres that mimic the headgear of Byzantine royalty.\nDo I have a source for that? Nope, so only take it for what it’s worth :)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8074716", "title": "Dispel", "user": "ferngladefarm.com.au", "content": "Hi John Michael,\nOut of curiosity, are blow back effects to be expected when you attempt a dispel?\nHave you noticed that over the past decade or two, we have somehow lost the ability to talk about a subject, without actually mentioning the subject? Am I imagining this lack, or do you believe it is a deliberate shift in our collective consciousnesses?\nCheers and thanks for taking the time to allow us to pester you with questions! I've been giving a massive amount of free advice to distressed people of late. Comes with the territory I guess.\nChris", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8091612", "title": "Re: Dispel", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It depends on the strength of the spell you're trying to break. If it has any real power behind it, yes.\n2) No, you're not imagining it. Our civilization has dumbed down pretty considerably over the last couple of decades.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8091868", "title": "Re: Dispel", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) What do you think is behind it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8094940", "title": "Re: Dispel", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Cognitive dissonance. It's almost impossible to think clearly when you're trying to pretend that what's happening all around you isn't happening and can't possibly happen. Our civilization is in decline, but most people still believe in the ideology of perpetual progress; until they finally let go of that ideology, they're just going to have more and more trouble thinking.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8074972", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nWhen I get a sexual arousal, if I do nothing to discharge it physically but focus on a mental image (as in creative visualisation), would that be a kind of \"polarity working\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8095196", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not exactly, but it's part of the essential basic training for polarity work. An actual polarity working requires two participants, one who generates the energy and one who takes it in and directs it; both of them need to know how to direct sexual energy away from the genital center and put it to other uses -- which is what you've learned to do.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8075228", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Archdruid,\nI have two questions about tarot that are related to each other:\n1 - There are many legends and speculations about the historical origins of tarot in occultist circles. What do you think is the most plausible origin story?\n2 - Was tarot invented by occultists in the first place or taken up by them later?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8095452", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "One of the great weaknesses of modern occultism is that it so often fails to pay attention to what's actually known about history. Italian art historians found out many years ago that the earliest version of the tarot was invented between 1418 and 1425 in Milan by Duke Filippo Maria Visconti and/or his secretary Marziano da Tortona. The trumps as we now know them are one of dozens of competing versions known in late Renaissance Italy, which were inspired by the original deck. The tarot was originally a deck for playing card games -- tarocchi, the game played with them, is still popular in some parts of Europe.\nThe first known use of tarot cards for divination was around 1750, at which time just about every kind of cards were used for divination; the rise of the tarot to its current position as the most widely used divinatory deck didn't begin until J.-B. Aliette (\"Eteilla\") began using them as a divinatory deck in Paris in the 1780s. Once that happened, though, occultists went to work on the deck, expanded and adapted its symbolism, rearranged the trumps as needed (in most modern decks, Justice and Strength have been switched from their original positions), and turned it into the superbly functional occult tool it has become.\nThe same thing could be done just as well with other decks; there's some very creative work being done these days with the Lenormand deck, for example. The more the merrier!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8096732", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"there's some very creative work being done these days with the Lenormand deck, for example.\"\nHmmm... Where can I learn more about it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8097244", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Feed the word \"Lenormand\" into your favorite search engine and you'll get plenty of places to start.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8103388", "title": "Sola Busca tarot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any view on the Sola Busca tarot?  I have a deck and there is nothing spiritually uplifting about any of it.  It was used by power hungry elite Northern Italian families in the 15th century who were always trying to out do each other.  I think this deck has a tainted egregore but like it as a historical artefact.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8107996", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's been quite a bit of handwaving about it in recent years, and some very dubious theories that claim to relate it to traditions of nasty magic. As far as I can tell there's no basis for these; it's a typical Renaissance elite playing card deck with the history (and pseudohistory) of ancient Rome as its theme.\nThat said, I haven't worked with it. I prefer to work with late 19th and 20th century decks designed by occultists, since they have symbolism better suited to my purposes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8116188", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do you feel about the Thoth deck?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8118492", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you're into Aleister Crowley's teachings, it's the deck to use. I worked with it for a while, but I'm not a Thelemite and I also find it rather ugly, thus prefer not to use it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8134364", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I'm also irked (having been recently reading a book on Tarot that had some interesting general insights but was based on Thoth, leading to some gaps in translation) at Eddie Alexander's insistence on calling the Knight the Prince and the King the Knight, as I might have mentioned in a general post. I don't know if it's due to a spurious attempt at Arthurian symbolism or just the need to Be Different, but it sets off all my We Have Food At Home New England instincts. (YOU HAVE A PERFECTLY GOOD KNIGHT ALREADY OMG.)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8116444", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "open_space", "content": "What would be some examples of 19th and 20th century tarot decks?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8119004", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Rider-Waite tarot, the Knapp-Hall tarot, the Golden Dawn tarot, the Oswald Wirth tarot, the Thoth tarot, and the Esoteric Masonic tarot are good examples of decks of this vintage designed by occultists, and loaded with occult symbolism.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8113628", "title": "Re: Sola Busca tarot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm not JMG, but I am a historian with a background in Tarot and playing card history, so I hope neither of you mind if I chime in.\nIn my opinion, the Sola Busca Tarot was developed as a teaching tool, as many early Tarot decks were.  The Sola Busca is based on the history and mythical history of ancient Rome (ie what people at the time believed about ancient Rome, some of which was mythology rather than actual history), and the figures depicted in the cards represent both good examples of people to emulate and bad examples of people to avoid emulating.  This was bog standard in Renaissance Italian Tarot decks, which were widely used (in the form of teaching games) to train the children of the upper classes in proper behavior, good citizenship, etc.  We've got loads of documentation on the didactic uses of early Tarot.\nOn the other hand, Peter Mark Adams' theories, given in his book\nThe Game of Saturn\n, have almost no credible basis in actual fact.  Further, some of his claims (the Ammon material, in particular) go in direct opposition to the actual iconography and symbolism of the deck, and to documented historical fact.  Frankly, if Mr. Adams said that the sky is blue, I'd look out the window to fact-check him.\nThat said, given that a lot of black magicians have apparently fallen for Mr. Adams' theories, they may currently be using the Sola Busca for black magic, which could produce a tainted egregore.  My own copy of the deck seems to be quite clean and unimpaired, but YMMV.  Then again, I don't use it for divination, but for study of symbolic images, which is a different ball game.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8114652", "title": "But where do the trumps come from", "user": "candace_k", "content": "So I understand that the first deck was invented at that time, but what I don’t get is why those ideas and images were put into use.\nI know there are games played with Trionfi.  But what I don’t get is why the set of images used for Trionfi were used.  Why not just priests and angels in terms of hierarchy ?  Why yes, I have meditated on the question.  I didn’t come up with any good insights.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8075740", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Since some commenter or commenters asked about occult dimensions of being on another planet, I would like to cite some observations of people, who were on the moon. Charlie Duke spoke of the \"serenity and peacefulness\" of the moon. The astronauts averred that they didn't feel alien on the moon; several of them cited an overwhelming sense of beauty. Jim Irwin noted, that he felt the presence of God, while he was on the Moon.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8095708", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. Thanks for this.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8115420", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For a wonderful overview of the effect of traveling to the moon on the lives of astronauts, I recommend the book \"Moondust: In Search of the Men who Fell to Earth\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8075996", "title": "Daily recollection expansion", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Merry Jupiter-Pluto JMG!  Or so one hopes.  Thanks for hosting this.  I have a question about recollection.  I've been doing daily recollection for about a year and have gotten a lot out of it - for example I think of myself as having a \"bad memory\" but can now remember all kinds of little microdetails I wouldn't have been able to remember before 5 minutes after they happened.  My question was about expanding it.  I was just reading Regardie's \"Middle Pillar\" and he talks about doing it all the way to birth as a way to release the blockages of repressed memories.\nI wasn't very clear from him if you just \"do it by doing it\", that is, every day make a fresh effort to remember every experience of your life backwards.  So far I made a few attempts and wouldn't say it was especially successful, plus I'm not that happy about my life so I felt a bit down.  Do you think though this could succeed if one kept trying and would be worth doing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8096220", "title": "Re: Daily recollection expansion", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recommend trying to do that every night! If you decide you want to do that, and divinations indicate that it's a good idea, choose one day each week to put an hour or so into remembering a part of your life -- say, a particular year, or some other section of your memories. (Many people find that it helps to write things down as you remember them, but your mileage may vary.) I don't recommend more than one hour once a week, because most of us have a lot of wretched memories to process, and yeah, the experience can be depressing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8101852", "title": "Re: Daily recollection expansion", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks, that sounds like a saner plan that would avoid excessive depressingness.  One of the things I'm trying to focus on until the solstice and maybe beyond is unsnarling neuroses through a lot of dreamwork and journaling, so that could fit in.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8076252", "title": "India’s 9 minutes of light/fire", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don’t know if anyone has felt “a disturbance in the Force” over the past day or so, but on Sunday, April 5 at 9:00 pm India time (3:30 pm Universal Time Coordinated), about 1 billion people conducted another ritual for the Covid-19 situation at the request of Prime Minister Modi. For 9 minutes, people all over the country extinguished their electric lights, and with oil lamps in their hands said silent prayers for healing and strength. Quite a few of the revered Hindu / spiritual leaders recommended various affirmations regarding purity, strength, health, etc., at the individual and collective levels.\nThis is the second mass-ritual requested by India’s Prime Minister regarding Covid-19 (the previous being the “clapping Sunday” [March 22] which was briefly discussed two MMs ago).\nNot only was the time of the ritual “9” pm and for “9” minutes, but in numerology, April 5 is also “9” (4+5) and the Prime Minister’s public request was 9 minutes in duration. So, what’s the deal about all these 9s? In Vedic astrology, the number 9 is associated with fiery planet Mars (the planet of war), who is presently in exaltation and is presently the strongest planet for confronting the astrological cause of the virus. Also, as per Vedic astrology, on Sunday (the day of Sun, who presides over fire), the Moon was in the “fiery” constellation Leo and in a lunar mansion owned by Venus (hence, “healing fire”). So, lighting lamps for battling the virus makes sense from an astrological-magic perspective. (The previous ritual was associated with air/clapping). Quite wisely, the PM has not announced whether more such rituals will (or will not) occur.\nI guess my question is whether these events should be considered to be a form of thaumaturgy.\nRon M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8096476", "title": "Re: India’s 9 minutes of light/fire", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Modi knows his stuff. Yes, that's a well-designed work of collective magic, and I notice that India's had surprisingly few cases of the coronavirus...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8097756", "title": "Re: India’s 9 minutes of light/fire", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Either directly or indirectly. That is, he might have the good sense to be consulting astrologers and taking their advice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8098268", "title": "Re: India’s 9 minutes of light/fire", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. Knowing who to consult and whose advice to follow is a useful skill!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8076508", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThere are some baffling points in Islam that got my attention:\n1 - According to Islam, Jesus did not die on the cross but his persecutors were somehow deceived to believe that they killed him. There are similar views to this in some Gnostic sects.\n2 - In Islam, archangel Gabriel is attributed with the role of revelation (like transmitting the messages of the God to prophets). When we think about the Kabbalistic attributions of Gabriel (moon, water, Yesod etc.) this may imply the usage of mediumship in early Islam.\nAccording to some legends, Mahomed was trained by a Christian priest - Waraqa ibn Nawfal who was the cousin of Mahomed's first wife, Khadija. In fact Waraqa openly supported Mahomed since his first revelation. Waraqa was well versed in both Old and New Testaments. It is also said that he was a member of the Nestorian sect, but this doesn't make sense given his open support to Mahomed; because the Islamic view on Jesus is closer to Monophysite doctrine rather than Nestorianism.\nWhat do you think about any possible influence of unorthodox Christian sects on early Islam?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8096988", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. I don't know the first thing about the subject, though -- it's not something I've had any reason to study.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8076764", "title": "Revival Druidry Resources", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Bore da, JMG! Thanks for the pointers concerning Hu last week; it helped immensely. In answer to someone else's query about the Druid revival pantheon, you noted that there wasn't much information available in English. Does that imply that resources do exist in another language? Welsh, perhaps? Or French; I recall you mentioning a lively community there. Mostly just curious, but I've been looking for an excuse to learn another language…\n- Accidental Mystic", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8098524", "title": "Re: Revival Druidry Resources", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's material in Welsh, certainly, and also in Breton and French.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8117724", "title": "Re: Revival Druidry Resources", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Which language would you most recommend for someone wanting to engage really deeply with the lore and philosophy of revival Druidry?\n-A.M.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8119516", "title": "Re: Revival Druidry Resources", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can do that with any of several languages. Welsh, Breton, and French all have a great deal of Druid Revival material that's never made it into English. I'd encourage you to do some divination, and also learn a little about each language and decide which one interests you most.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8077020", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nA grab-bag of questions for you this week:\n1) Does it mean anything in particular if one casts a shield chart and the four mothers replicate themselves exactly in the four daughters?  (I of course ended up with Populus as Judge, which is a mathematical consequence of such a thing.  The two witnesses were Acquisito.)  The mothers were Carcer, Rubeus, Fortuna Major, and Puella, as were the daughters.  The nieces came up as two pairs of Puer and Laetitia, producing the aforementioned witnesses and judge.  I had asked what I ought to be focused on learning during this \"down time\" of the health crisis.  Other than getting a positive sign for learning generally, I'm unsure what the result indicates.\n2) Re scrying.  I obtained some of that artesian well water I asked about last time.  When scrying to determine its nature and qualities, is there anything in particular I should do/ask/concentrate on?  I made one attempt, but got nothing but vague swirling.\n3) Do you have any opinions or thoughts re the Grand College of Rites?  I stumbled across it as I continued to research the various appendant bodies.\nThanks.\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8098780", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In my experience, Populus as judge very often means that a lot of other people are involved in the question -- as of course is the case now. (You've got that downtime because of a collective event.) The character of the witnesses determines the answer in that case. As far as I know, having identical mothers and daughters doesn't mean anything special other than that.\n2) Try to contact a spirit associated with the well. They're more likely to be talkative than the water itself.\n3) I haven't joined, because one of the requirements of membership is that you take an oath not to try to revive any of the old rites they keep in cold storage!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8103644", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nThanks.\n1) I wonder if the twin Acquistos point to gains from learning both within and without the self.\n2) I'll try reaching out to a spirit of the well.  I don't have much experience with that sort of thing, but there's no time to learn than the present!\n3) That last bit rather floors me, I must confess.  Why would a group dedicated to preserving traditions be opposed to reviving those traditions?  I'd think one would encourage such a thing...\n--David BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8105948", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3) One problem that Masonry has faced from time to time is that of too many degrees and orders and organizations for the available stock of Masons. The GCR was founded to address that problem, so the York and Scottish Rites and a few other groups could count on getting enough members to stay in business!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8116700", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) It would be like working in the Secret Archives of Vatican and not using the forbidden occult manuscripts there :)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8077276", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm getting extraordinary results with the Middle Pillar ritual at the moment. I don't want to go into specifics just now, but suffice it to say I could never have believed it could do for me what it's doing. It actually seems to defy logic and has me asking, how is the possible? I guess the answer is: magic! TSW...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8099036", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. As for defying logic, magic does that all the time. Get used to it. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8077532", "title": "A lesson in muscle testing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On the other blog Scotlyn asked, “So I am very interested, but completely untutored, in this idea of using muscle testing to communicate with a body, whether it is a patient’s body (which I will seek further learning sources to improve upon) or my own body. In relation to the second, though, I wonder would it be a big ask for you to briefly illustrate with a step by step example of you DOING this? Eg. Question, technique, reaction, answer. The HOW of it. Also, if the answer sometimes might be “I don’t want to tell you” how do you distinguish that from a “yes” or a “no”?\nIt turns out there are a lot more details to describe here than I had expected. So let’s call this a first lesson, describing the most basic form of muscle testing. There’s certainly plenty here to practice and mull over for a week. Next week I can describe testing physical imbalances on oneself, without a partner. Then the week after that I can describe testing yes/no questions (I assume that is what the Japanese acupuncturists are doing with the O-ring technique, though they may be directly testing the flow of chi). The danger of trying to steal the body’s wisdom and needing to be able to distinguish “I don’t want to tell you” responses only comes in when you start muscle testing questions. So today I only went into the physical how of it:\nBy far the easiest form of muscle testing is doing it on another person to test the physical imbalances currently in their body rather than trying to test questions being held in your mind. As an acupuncturist, you already know how you get a sense of what imbalances a client is experiencing and then test out your hypotheses by asking them questions, comparing pulses, and noting their body’s response to your needle placement. This form of muscle testing will add another way you can test out your hypotheses/hunches. If the client is lying supine on the table, the easiest way to test is by having them hold an arm out to the side in crucifixion position; you then press gently floorward on their forearm while they resist to test the neutral strength of their pecs. Keeping their neutral strength in mind, you touch a point on their body which you believe is somehow compromised and press down on their forearm again. If they test weaker, your hunch was accurate. If they test as strongly as before, move on to test your next hunch.\nFor acupuncture this might follow the taking of pulses in order to verify which meridian showed up weak, problematic, or distrupted. If touching the contact point for the meridian tests weak, you can then have the client touch that contact point to maintain that weakening effect, while you either touch points along that meridian or the contact point of another meridian to discover what point will re-strengthen their body when you again press down on their forearm. Thus you can test out some pretty complex interactions among the meridians this way before having to commit to needle placement. This testing is particularly useful when multiple meridians have gone haywire, as you can test through the sequence of the meridians to discover which one has thrown the others off, whether by being too weak or too strong. Obviously, you would want to get some practice with friends or coworkers before trying this with clients.\nLet’s move on to testing current physical imbalances outside a clinical setting. Either you or your friend can be the one looking to decode an imbalance, or you can alternate back and forth. Whatever the case, at any given time one of you will be the subject and the other will be the aide. The subject usually sits or stands with an arm outstretched in crucifixion position, though any muscle can be used effectively for testing. Because the lateral deltoid is relatively weak, the aide can press floorward at the elbow to prevent muscle fatigue, and the subject can change the arm being tested as needed. Either party can touch points on the subject’s body where an imbalance is suspected.\nSince pain often gives us only a vague idea of the source of disorder, testing larger areas than a fingertip can be very useful. Subject or aide can place an entire hand flat on a suspected region of the subject’s body and move their hand around following their hunches until the subject’s arm tests weak, indicating that a point that needs work is somewhere under where the hand is making contact. Without removing the hand completely, lift it until only the four finger tips are touching in a line and test the subject’s arm’s strength. Slide the finger tips back over where the flat hand had been touching, while repeatedly testing until the subject’s arm weakens again. Now lift all but one finger and test each of the fingers separately until the subject’s arm weakens again. That is the point of imbalance that the body was signaling it would like to have worked on somehow. If the point is in no way tender, you can test a little halo of points around it to find the exact point that tests the weakest, and hopefully at least a little tender. It sounds awfully complex and slow, but it is quite a bit faster than randomly touching tiny points on the body until you stumble on a winner. Knowing your body and its habitual imbalances and compensations helps considerably.\nThere are all kinds of ways to beneficially work on the points the body reveals, but the most common by far is simply to press on them until their tenderness goes away. Yes, that’s called acupressure. When does your body feel you have pressed a point long enough? When you can touch it and have your arm test strong again. Will there be points where no amount of acupressure can balance them? Of course. Those points may be revealing a more complex underlying disorder, or they may just want different attention. Rubbing the spot or tapping it with your fingers may be all that’s needed. On the other hand, if you have found a subluxation in your spine, your body probably wants it adjusted back into alignment. If you have found an abscess, your body certainly wants it treated in some way other than by pressing on it! There is a lot of nurturance and rebalancing you can do on your own, but by no means can you fix every problem. Some a professional can help with, and some we just have to live with.\nAnything that presses on or distorts the body can be muscle tested for its benefits/drawbacks. You may really love that pair of shoes even though they’re a size too small, but your body may hate them. Test your strength barefoot and then test with the shoes on — if it drops considerably, you might not want to wear them. Some things are only subtly imbalancing, so you might have to walk for a whole day in those shoes before your body would test noticeably weaker than walking a whole day in comfortable shoes. If you are a chronic pronator with a pair of orthotics that just don’t seem right, test with and without them — if you test weaker with them in your shoes, they are causing more imbalance than they are correcting for.\nOK, I did get a problematic pair of orthotics from a podiatrist who would not believe that my interphalangeal joint was injured, not my metatrasophalangeal joint (IP joint injuries are a blind spot for podiatrists). By having my boyfriend test my strength while I stood on the orthotics and adjusted little cardboard wedges under them, we determined where the orthotics needed felt pads glued to them. It was so successful that we went on to test and alter the orthotics while I stood in relevé and then just on the injured foot in relevé, mimicking the push-off phase of a regular gait. Lo and behold, the pain and swelling in my big toe, which I had lived with for four excruciating years, disappeared in under a week. The body knows what it needs! Given the test, treat/alter, test again nature of partnered muscle testing, it is great if the aide/boyfriend is doing something that can be easily interrupted and gone back to. If either the subject or the aide gets annoyed with the other, it can turn into a miserable process. Don’t do that to each other. Try again later or find another muscle testing partner.\n— Christophe", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8077788", "title": "Middle Pillar Translations", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nDo you have any ideas about how the king and queen scales could be adapted to the Rite of the Central Ray? I was reading some Regardie and thought a lot of his Middle Pillar work might be worth giving a try.\nAlso, I've noticed that you said that the Astral body feeds the etheric body. How much do the subtle bodies affect each other up the chain, i.e. etheric affecting astral, or do they primarily trickle down?\nMany thanks as always.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8099548", "title": "Re: Middle Pillar Translations", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Take Regardie's instructions in\nThe Art of True Healing\n, start experimenting, and see what results you get.\n2) It's pretty much all a matter of trickling down. One of the basic principles of occult philosophy is that the higher planes create and shape the lower, not vice versa.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8103900", "title": "Re: Middle Pillar Translations", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This would seem to imply it's always best to try to act on the higher planes. Is this accurate?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8105692", "title": "Re: Middle Pillar Translations", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on what you're trying to do. The planes are discrete and not continuous, remember, so very often the best thing to do is to act on the plane where you want change to happen. If for some reason that isn't an option, go up a plane and see what you can do there.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8078044", "title": "Cider", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings, Archdruid!\nI have been enjoying this particular cider for some time:\nhttps://stormalong.com/cider/legendary-dry/\nThe clerk gives me a funny look when I call it it the \"tentacles of horror\".\nBe well.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8099804", "title": "Re: Cider", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nice. I wonder how they managed to get the Terrible Old Man to sit for a portrait!\n;-)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8104412", "title": "Re: Cider", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Ah, it's good to see old Stormalong John on a beer  Thank you!!  I must get and try sone soon,\nTo me way hey, you Stormy\nWalk him along, John, carry him along\nTo me way hey, you Stormy\nCarry him to his burying ground", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8078556", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the mechanism of telekinesis? Is it caused by etheric projection?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8100060", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never seen an actual demonstration of telekinesis that I found convincing, so I remain agnostic as to whether it's possible at all. If it's possible, etheric projection is certainly one possible explanation.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8079068", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. (a) In your experience, is it possible to attract nature spirits to urban and/or suburban backyards? If so, would working enchantments on the yard make it possible to attract them? Even if this is unlikely, would it still be a good idea to periodically leave small offerings out in my yard?\n(b) Is it safe to exchange etheric energy with a Maple tree? I have a very large and old Maple in my backyard and it seems like the centerpiece of the entire block.\n2. I duly apologize if this has been asked before, but do you have any insights on what the next pseudomorphosis to hit North America might be as the Faustian culture starts drifting back out to sea from whence it came? Or has this already been in the works? Since the aftermath of British adventurism in various corners of Asia, in addition to the efforts of Madame Blavatsky and those approximate to her, words like Dharma, Karma, Reincarnation, Yoga, Qi, Tao, ect., have become de-facto naturalized into the contemporary English lexicon. Might this be a hint at the possible cultural synthesis to come? Also, is this sort of synthesis what you mean when you often refer to \"Occult Philosophy?\"\n3. In past comments, you've alluded to a date of 1879 for the beginning of the Aquarian Age. May I ask where you came across that date? Because I find it quite fascinating, in that just a few years after that date, Nietzsche declared \"the death of God\"...which I interpret in retrospect to actually mean the death of the Piscean concept of divinity (perhaps he himself was totally unaware of what exactly he was channeling?). And anyway, if we do the math and assume each astrological age is 2160 year in length, then the date we entered Pisces would be something approximate to 281 BCE. And this is precisely the time when the cauldron that produced prophetic religions and Axial Age ideologies in general started churning. In India, just a couple decades after this date, the Emperor Ashoka effectively consolidated and politicized Buddhism and used it as a tool to project his own political influence. And in the Mediterranean world, the Macedonian Ptolemy dynasty in Egypt got into the business of creating religions by fiat. By this, the great city of Alexandria became perhaps the greatest epicenter and broadcaster of Axial Age belief systems. Wasn't the intermingling of politics and religion one of the major themes of the Age of Pisces? Finally, would now being in the Age of Aquarius mean the probably decoupling of politics and religion, at least a lessening of that force relative to how prevalent it was during Pisces?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8100572", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes and yes.\n2) It depends on which nations come out on top in the scramble for global hegemony once the US finishes retreating from empire. Chinese and Indian cultures are likely candidates for the next pseudomorphosis; another is Mexican culture -- not because it's likely to become a global superpower soon (that's at least a couple of millennia off) but because Mexico's close, culturally vibrant, and populous.\n3) Quite a few late 19th century occultists held that the Aquarian age began late in 1879; some others argued for 1900. The huge cultural changes that have happened since either date -- equivalent to those that kicked off the Axial Age 2160 years earlier -- make me think that they were right. Yes, the Piscean age (ruled by Jupiter in those days and Neptune in ours) was especially the age of political religion, and yes, one of the great themes of the Aquarian age is the unraveling of that unholy fusion.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8079324", "title": "Benzoin", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The first time I burned benzoin I could tell it was \"doing something\" and having some sort of effect I'd never experienced previously with incense. Would you be willing to describe a little bit about how benzoin works?\nThank you,\nEric", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8100828", "title": "Re: Benzoin", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't worked with it. Why not repeat the experience, meditate on the results, do some research, and come to your own conclusions?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8101596", "title": "Re: Benzoin", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "An excellent plan! Is anyone willing to share a recommendation for resources to research and study different types of incense? I've seen mention of Agrippa's planetary recipes, for instance.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8114140", "title": "Re: Benzoin", "user": "joshuarout", "content": "For what it's worth, C.W. Leadbeater wrote his opinion about benzoin in The Science of the Sacraments:\n'There is a science of perfumes, and evil powers as well as good may be invoked by such means. Nearly all the incenses prepared for church use contain a large proportion of benzoin and olibanum, as experience has shown that these are both pleasing and effective. Benzoin is almost savagely ascetic and purifying; it deals trenchantly with all the grosser forms of impure thought, and is excellent for use in a great cathedral crowded with somewhat undeveloped individuals. For smaller assemblies of less bucolic minds it needs a large admixture of other elements to produce the best results.'\n- and in The Hidden Life of Freemasonry: 'Two of the most important constituents of such incense as is useful for our work are benzoin and olibanum. The benzoin is a vigorous purifier, and tends to drive away all coarse or sensuous feelings and thoughts.'\nThe following page mentions these, and some other references by other authors on incense:\nhttps://cwleadbeater.wordpress.com/2017/01/24/leadbeater-on-incense/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8123100", "title": "Re: Benzoin", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for these excerpts. I’m looking forward to experimenting more and appreciate these leads!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8079580", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. If the rituals we practice, such as SoP, are a 'weak sauce' magic by design, in order to introduce slow gradual change in the initiate then what would be the 'strong sauce' magic?\n2. Would it make sense to focus on practices that carry over into future incarnations? Which would be anything that works on the astral and mental bodies. Since if I remember right these bodies survive between incarnations. By that measure SoP should qualify since it works on the astral level? Meditation would also qualify.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8101340", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) To answer that question would be to encourage the clueless to give themselves third-degree burns. I'll pass, thank you.\n2) No, it wouldn't make any sense to do that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8105436", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but regards 2)\nIs the reason that we live in the material plane first and foremost, and so we need to focus on it, working with the higher planes, while helpful, is less important than working on the physical plane?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8109020", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. We're not here by accident, after all.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8117468", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does the West even have anything that would qualify as 'strong sauce'? There is the Picatrix which has gotten impressive results for some and clearly shouldn't be toyed with but when I think 'strong sauce'it conjures images of Yogis and Taoist internal alchemists.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8119772", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The West has an enormous amount of \"strong sauce.\" Nearly all of it's either squirreled away in the private teachings of surviving occult orders, or veiled behind several layers of symbolic protection. The Picatrix, btw, includes quite a bit that isn't obvious -- and for good reason; the clueless could mess themselves over good and proper with some of the material in that text.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8079836", "title": "Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, I wanted to ask for a moment of your time because I am struggling with the role of conspiracy theories in occultism. I am often encountering people who point to big, in-depth conspiracies they’ve “uncovered” via online sleuthery. My only occultist friend is persistent in pointing me in the direction of QAnon and other conspiracies of “occultist elites” or the supposed occult domination of the media and entertainment industry. “Waking up” to these “truths” is a big part of occultism as he understands it. I’ve also run into similar ideas in other places. I’ve been working with your books and material for a few years, and I know that you appreciate students who quietly put in the work, but I’ve wrestled with these topics for a while now and would appreciate any insights you’d care to offer.\nThat said, my questions are:\nDo you think there is any validity to these claims?\nIn the Well of Galabes, you mention the idea that occultists might get messages from the Inner planes that are not literally true but are more along the lines of food for meditation. Could some of these ideas be things that the people pushing the theories would be better off exploring in meditation than accepting literally at face value?\nIn Paths of Wisdom, one of the functions of Tiphareth is imagination. I am taking that, at least in part, as choosing the information that comes in from the senses and giving it form and using it to assemble a worldview. Most of the worldviews of these occultists seem to revolve around the idea that we are essentially helpless and manipulated by a nearly all-powerful cabal who break all of society’s taboos for nefarious purposes with impunity. How do you sort out what is true in objective reality in something like occultism, which deals with hidden and subjective phenomenon as a matter of course?\nThank you for your time and teachings, they have changed my life in profound and positive ways.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8080860", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "If I may add one observation, the way the left today understands the world in quite a similar way as the occultists described in the last paragraph.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8111580", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For what it's worth, my conspiracy-minded friend would probably be considered alt-right in the parlance of our times, although I'm not sure he'd classify himself that way. I have noticed a tendency for the left to blame just about everything on the Trump administration if that's what you mean.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8112348", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That has been my experience as well.  For a concrete example I have a relative who describes the corona virus as a dark side cabal plot started at Harvard with the express purpose of killing millions and encouraging repressive government.  However as Gaia has moved into a higher frequency she will allow no more pandemics.  So she and the “light counsel” have mitigated the virus.  It has in fact already been cleared from the timeline.\nThere are some mine fields out there and yes the individual is still a big fan of the Secret and a full congregant of the church of progress.\nOther Dave", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8102364", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Conspiracy theories along that line are mostly baloney, but there is a small grain of truth there: any successful ruling elite would be pragmatic enough to harness both material tools and subtler (thus, occult) forces to sustain their hegemony. For example, during the Cold War, both the US and USSR governments employed dozens of psychic spies.\nAdditionally, more than a hundred years ago, William Walker Atkinson (even though himself was deeply involved in occultism) wrote these lines in a book:\n\"This is one of the most powerful forms of Influencing\nEn Masse, and is used with great effect by many of the 'strong\nmen' of this age, who have acquainted themselves fully with the secrets of the ancient occultists. Ancient Occultism and Modern Finance seem far apart, but they are really working together to further the interests of some of these powerful minds of the day—and the public is paying the bill.\" (Practical Mental Influence)\nThese examples demonstrate that the ruling elites take practical occultism seriously, at least.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8102620", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, let's cover some basics first. Do conspiracies exist? Of course. Are you going to find out the truth about them by hanging breathlessly on anonymous claims splashed all over the internet?  Um, no. Anonymous leaks to the gullible are among the standard modalities by which actual conspiracies spread their disinformation. Look into the history of the UFO phenomenon, for example, and notice how often claims that support this or that story of alien contact are being spread by someone with connections to US Air Force intelligence. That's not accidental; the UFO brouhaha has been the most important form of camouflage the Air Force uses for secret weapons testing since 1947, when it was originally used to distract attention from high altitude balloon tests. The U-2, the SR-47, the first two generations or so of spy satellites, stealth technology (remember all those UFOs that looked like black triangles?) -- those and much more sheltered behind a mythology of alien contact that was systematically spread by the Air Force as disinformation.\nThe whole Qanon business is more of the same. Who exactly is behind it, and what their specific goals are, is an interesting question I don't expect ever to be able to answer. The one thing you can be sure of, in dealing with any of these supposed \"leaks,\" is that an assortment of government agencies are aware of every word that everyone posts regarding them -- nothing anywhere on the internet, remember, is actually private -- and records are being kept. That means among other things that none of the supposed leakers are actually leaking anything that could land them in legal trouble. Just as in the UFO business, when somebody official claims to be giving you secret information that nobody in power wants you to have, assume that it's disinformation that someone in power wants you to believe and you won't go wrong.\nFinally, the notion that we're all helpless pawns of some omnipotent cabal -- or of anything else -- is about as far as you can get from genuine occultism. At the heart of the occult path is the recognition that, as Paul Foster Case put it, \"All the power that ever was or will be is here now.\" The power you have over your life is limited only by your willingness to embrace it and accept the consequences. Fairly often, the reason people flee into conspiracy theories and the like is that it allows them to blame someone else for their own unwillingness to accept their own power and their own potential for greatness...with all the risks and challenges that acceptance brings with it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8104924", "title": "Re: Conspiracy theories in occultism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't really accept any of the conspiracy theories I have encountered and most of them seem moderately absurd; I do respect my friend enough to at least listen to what he has to say on occult topics, although sometimes his insistence on the truth of these things makes me uncomfortable. Not having friends or contacts in the occult world, it's sometimes difficult (for me) to discern what is garbage or what has some legitimacy. Sometimes it seems like a chunk of the world has developed a case of schizophrenia; I have run into conspiracy theorists outside the occult world enough to wonder if I am somehow attracting these types of people into my sphere, so to speak. Thank you for your answer.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8080092", "title": "two questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Two apparently unrelated questions this week:\nIs a monthly divination best performed on the full moon or new moon?\nLast week you posted a diagram of energy centers, “currents in the desire body.” I’m wondering specifically what the center on the right side of the torso signifies. Something similar to the solar plexus chakra, since it’s in that vicinity? Internet search didn’t turn up any discussion of this diagram.\nThanks for all you do.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8103132", "title": "Re: two questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Experiment and find out!\n2) That's the spleen center, the energy center through which your etheric body absorbs energy from the sun. It's distinct from the solar plexus. The diagram can be found in Max Heindel's\nThe Rosicrucian Cosmo-Conception\nand in old editions of Peter Kelder's\nThe Eye of Revelation\n-- the original source of the Five Tibetan Rites exercises -- among other places.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8106204", "title": "Re: two questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Had I done an appropriate divination first, I would have known you would say that!\n2) I'm a little confused. The spleen is on the left side, but the diagram shows this center on the right.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8109276", "title": "Re: two questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The diagram may have gotten flipped around in the printing process; it's supposed to be the spleen center.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8080348", "title": "Occult Philosophy", "user": "moops25", "content": "Hi JMG,\nJust wondering if you can help me understand something a bit more clearly.\nHow or where does the theory of Evolution in it's current scientific form, fit into the overall picture of Occult Philosophy ? I know Blavatsky wasn't overly thrilled with evolution's answers or lack of them as she saw it, so where does Occult Philosophy stand with it today ?\nCheers, Steve", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8104156", "title": "Re: Occult Philosophy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on the occultist. Blavatsky was trying to define occultism as a third force, distinct from the standpoints of orthodox religion and materialist science and standing aside from their endless quarrels. Some occultists still hold to her theory, but many others don't. The Druid Revival tradition embraced a version of evolution not too far from Darwin's long before Darwin published\nThe Origin of Species\n-- you'll find it in detail in the writings of Iolo Morganwg, who died in 1826. Me, I tend to think that the scientists have the evolutionary process more or less correct on the material plane; the problem with science isn't that it's wrong, so much that it's incomplete, because it leaves out the influence of the other planes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8106460", "title": "Re: Occult Philosophy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The idea of falling back to Annwn sounds similar to \"survival of the fittest\".", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8106716", "title": "Re: Occult Philosophy", "user": "moops25", "content": "Great, I was always a little confused as to how much \"science\" occultists were willing to allow in.\nOne of my favourite books is Secret Wisdom : The Occult Universe Revealed by David Conway. He sums it up this way and it's an answer I've always been content with, he states ...\n\"To avoid misunderstanding, let me make plain at once that no self-respecting occultist would nowadays deny that man's physical body evolved, in it's final stages, from ape to hominid and from hominid to man. The external view of evolution sees in this only the cumulative effect of a long series of gradual, perhaps accidental, mutations which results in a qualitative, as well as quantitative, change in the whole, the latter thereby becoming greater than the sum of its constituent parts. Occultists, on the other hand, would insist that evolution necessarily means that such qualitative innovations are possible only because they are already implicit in the simple unity from which they have slowly evolved : thanks to evolution, the universe does not BECOME greater than the sum of its elements, it merely expresses through them it's own antecedent greatness. The more complex and numerous the material elements available to it at any time, the more it can reveal of itself, just as a thinker can better express his thoughts, the more comprehensive his vocabulary happens to be.\"\nCheers, Steve", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8109532", "title": "Re: Occult Philosophy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Conway's well worth close study.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8080604", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I don't find watching movies/TV/Youtube enjoyable. Whenever I try to explain this, most people immediately react by insisting there's something I need to watch right now. Do you know what's going on here? My current best guess is people hate their TVs, and so can't stand the thought there's someone who doesn't do it, and are desperately trying to get such people to watch it, since otherwise they have to grapple with the fact they too could choose not to watch it.\n2) Not a question, but I asked a little while ago about planning as a way of magic, and I think I know why it works: planning forces you to look at the future, to think about it, and decide what is worth it when viewed from the perspective of the future. I now suspect this is why people hate planning: they are terrified of the future, and want to avoid it. The irony is that not planning just makes the future worse.....\n3) I've heard a lot of people have been dreaming a lot more vividly since the Covid-19 epidemic started. Do you know of any ocuclt phenomena which might cause it?\n4) I've been journaling to try to find out why my mind resists any effort to reduce my internet use. I've succeeded, and suddenly using the internet for anything other than things where I lack the option to avoid it (such as Magic Monday) is no longer an option, since without the various subconscious ideas holding it in place, the boring and disturbing nature of the internet is now enough to make me want to avoid it.\nHowever, I don't have anything else to do with the hours I've suddenly freed up, and so I'm quite bored. This is a temporary phase, and I know it'll pass, but I see why you always say you want to build something, not just tear things down.\nI assume time will help, and I'm journaling to figure out what I want to do, but are there other steps you can think of for how to fill the void I've just exposed?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8081116", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not JMG)\nI’ve been having weird dreams for several weeks!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8092892", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) People do this any time you express dislike for something they like. If you say you don't like mushrooms, people will shower you with recipes for mushroom dishes that they believe will change your mind! People simply like to feel like their subjective opinions are justified and that anyone who gave their favourite things a fair trial would come to agree.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8093916", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP here: I don't like tomatoes and have never run into it for that....", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8105180", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) People are very defensive about their TV habit. I get the same kind of nonsense all the time, and it reminds me very much of the people I know who have serious drug habits and are always trying to get others to use.\n2) Of course. That's very often how karma works -- the efforts that people make to avoid facing something are exactly what guarantees that they'll have to face it.\n3) Hmm! I have no idea. My dreams have been pretty much as usual, for whatever that's worth.\n4) Well, what have you always wanted to do if you could find the time?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8107228", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) The Plug in Drug sounds appropriate....\n2) Hmm. In Utopianism then the extreme example of this?\n3) As are mine. It's just interesting that some people are reporting it.\n4) I don't know. Lack of time was never an excuse I used to avoid things...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8109788", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "2) One of several.\n4) Good! That's not something most people can say. You'll definitely want to take up a hobby, a craft, a subject of study, or some other way to use the time, though.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8122844", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I guess I’m lucky.  When I don’t know anything about the latest must-watch, they pity me but don’t pester me, maybe because I have nothing against TV in general.  If there was something interesting on, with a reasonable number of commercials, I’d watch it if I could.\nI no longer remember how to turn on the TV; Sonkitten has assembled some esoteric ritual involving 3 remotes and whenever I ask him how to do it he runs through the demonstration so fast it doesn’t help.  I don’t mind this, partly because there is nothing on that I want to see and partly because I am pretty sure he has set things up this way so he has some defense against being subjected to Fox News 14 hours a day.  His grandma suffered from Fox Geezer Syndrome; it went on, loud, the minute she got up and stayed on till she went to bed.  I can hardly blame Sonkitten for setting up a defense.If there is something not-cable-news I really want to see (I think the last one was 4 years ago), he makes sure I get to see it.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8081372", "title": "Geomancy", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "Salutations JMG, long time lurker, first time poster here.\nI've been excitedly delving into Geomancy with the help of your excellent book on the subject, but I've been having some significant difficulty. I'll try to pare my befuddlement down to a few questions:\n1) How important is the Reconciler to the shield chart? Frequently I've done many readings that seem to say \"Some difficulty in the past, but through hard work you can achieve your goal\" but when the reconciler is brought into the chart the reading suddenly shifts to \"doom and gloom, you will fail\" with a figure like Carcer or Cauda Draconis. The reconciler is \"the result of the result\" right? When is it appropriate to bring the Reconciler into the question, beyond when the chart seems unclear? For me it keeps throwing both charts into chaos by reversing the judgement rather than clarifying it.\n2) In a house chart, is the meaning of the figures or the connections between the houses more important? Are the mechanics of the house chart tightly bound to the question asked, or their own connections? For example, I asked \"Will I catch the flu\" and got RW: Carcer, Judge: Amissio, LW: Fortuna Major. Sounds pretty good right? Through isolation (Carcer) I will not possess (Amissio) the flu, and although the isolation may be long and tough the future looks bright (Fortuna Major). But when I put the figures into a house chart, Carcer performs a translation between the 1st House and the 6th House, which contains Amissio again. Initially I interpreted this as the quarantine being the third factor that prevents me from catching the flu (Amissio). But on further rereading (and rereading, and highlighting, and rereading again) I'm not so sure.\nDoes the perfection of a chart like this always mean \"yes\" even when you're hoping for a no? Which is more important, the mechanics of the house chart tying directly into the question, or the meaning of the figures to the diviner? I encountered a similar issue when asking \"Will my friend catch the flu\" and received a direct Occupation of the 6th house with Fortuna Major. Is the fortunate figure more important here, or is the mechanics of the house chart (perfection always equals \"yes\") the important thing?\nI guess I'm asking if the house chart answers \"Yes/No\" or \"Fortunate/Unfortunate for the Querent.\"\n3) If the figure of the Quesited passes to a different house (say, Albus in the 7th passing to the 6th for a question about love), can a third figure perform a Perfection by Translation between the first house and the passed figure? Again, is the figure more important or are the house chart mechanics the guiding force?\nEdited (Missing or miscapitalized words, further clarification on 1))\nDate:\n2020-04-06 06:39 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8110044", "title": "Re: Geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I rarely use it. The witnesses and judge are usually enough to give a clear answer.\n2) Okay, first of all, don't take the figures from a shield chart and plop them into a house chart. Choose one or the other and stick with that, or you'll end up always being confused. If you set out to do a shield chart, leave it at that -- and in that case, the answer is no, you will not catch the flu; staying at home (Carcer) will cause you not to catch it (Amissio) and everything will be fine (Fortuna Major).\nIf you set out to do a house chart, the presence or absence of a mode of perfection gives you a yes or no. The character of the figure or figures in the houses of querent and quesited tell you whether it will be fortunate or unfortunate.\n3) No. A translation is only valid if it's between the houses of the querent and the quesited; you can't add up a mutation and a translation to make a chart perfect! Again, if you have one of the standard modes of perfection, the answer is yes; if not, it's no; and the characteristics of the figure tell you how that \"yes\" or \"no\" will affect you and the quesited.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8112604", "title": "Re: Geomancy", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "2) Oh really? Wow, yeah I've been doing a shield chart and then a house chart. I guess that would screw things up, no wonder I've been having so much trouble. Is there a specific reason that you can do only one or the other?\nIs there any benefit to casting a Shield chart instead of a House chart then? It seems the House chart gives a lot more detail into the \"how\" of the matter, but maybe there's different types of questions each chart is better suited to?\n4) How closely do the Witnesses and Judge adhere to the past-present/result-future model? In chapter five you wrote \"The figure that appears as Left Witness gives information about the quesited, but this information focuses on what the quesited means to the querent.\" For a question where you hope the answer is \"No\" how does a favourable figure interpret? Does it adhere strongly to the future-tense (\"You escape breaking your leg, and are overjoyed\") or does it only display how you feel about your desired outcome (\"You would be very happy if you didn't break your leg, it's up to the Judge to decide how things play out\")?\n5) One thing that seemed intuitive to me was to follow the Way of the Points in the Shield chart and note which of the Four Triplicities it ended up in, so for a question about love if the Way of the Points ends up as Populous in the fourth Triplicity I might guess that I may meet a future love interest through a group of mutual friends, especially if Populous shows up as the left-most figure in the Fourth triplicity. Am I barking up the wrong tree again? Are the Triplicities and Way of the Points separate systems that do not interact, or can something be read from where the Way of the Points ends up within the Shield chart?\n6) On page 123, discussing example 6-8 you write \"...while that of the quesited is Via, which is an unfavorable figure in many contexts.\" Why is this so? I can understand that Via acts almost like a mirror, inverting many figures and changing bad into good and good into bad, but isn't \"change\" and \"long journey\" a neutral and slightly optimistic concept? Is there a mechanical reason, or is this a subject for further meditation?\nTo that end, how much of Geomancy differs between Geomancers and is thus a subject for meditation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8120028", "title": "Re: Geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "2) It depends on what you want to know. I find shield charts really useful for \"what's the current situation and how did it get this way\" questions -- combine the Way of Points with the four triplicities and you can unpack a lot of information from a reading. I find house charts really useful for \"is this a workable option\" questions.\n4) I've never noticed geomancy caring much about how I felt about anything! As for the specific interpretation of a given Left Witness, daily practice and study will teach you the intuitive skills you need to tell which is which.\n5) As noted above, I combine them all the time, and get good results.\n6) It's very much a modern conceit that change always tends to be for the better and journeys always end in better places. The middle ages saw things very differently, and that's where the traditional lore comes from. My advice is to compare your readings to the events that follow them, and see how Via works out for you. As for your final question, that's also a good theme for meditation!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8081628", "title": "Assorted SOP queries", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good day John Michael,\nThank you for continuing to offer this space for everyone; it's awesome.\nI have a few disparate issues but I'll try to be as succinct as I can.\nFirstly though I don't wish to be someone who only reports difficulties! So I'll start by saying I really feel like I'm getting into the DMH, and can count a good few TSW moments, for instance:\n- Had to complete an overly complex job application recently that was driving me nuts. Near the 11th hour, fed up, I went outside and did the active colour breathing for Air, requesting that my mind be fully focused on the job app. Went inside, and the remainder of it pretty much flowed out of me. And I got the invited to interview.\n-Doing the SOP the other day, at the invocation of Fire I swear I felt a sort of heat wrapping itself round my raised arm! It was eerie and encouraging.\n-I am doing daily Ogham, and whilst I've a long way to go in learning I'm amazed at how the same cards come up in the same position over and over in response to the same question on similar types of day when I'm struggling with rather samey challenges :-)\nOK difficulties:\n1. I much prefer the circulation of light to the static sphere, but like others I am having trouble with the third stage. Visualised slowly I understand how the 3 movements combine but I have great trouble with this step: first and second rotations (overhead from behind, down and back up, followed by left round to right) are moving fast in combination, but how am I supposed to then add SLOW movement of third rotation (left overhead down to right) when the former \"left\" and \"right\" positions are already spinning fast around me due to rotation 2? Any tips?\n2. I really want to get all 3 of the \"cauldron legs\" operational, but I continue to struggle getting comfortable with the sitting posture in meditation. It seems no matter how I adjust (sit further forward, sit further back, sit more upright, put a book under my short legs) eventually a sense of strain develops somewhere, usually the legs or lower back, that is not painful but is a distractingly agitated/nervous feeling. I do the relaxation as thoroughly as I can, but it only partially helps. I don't know if I'm over or under analysing my posture. Would reference to a mirror help, or does it sound like I need a different posture?\n3. My partner is 16 weeks pregnant and is having a rough time: nausea lasting longer than her previous pregnancies, exhaustion, heart burn, headaches. None of which are helped by our lockdown situation, of course. She did ask me whether there might be any SOP-related or other beginner-friendly Magic Monday helps for the nausea and heartburn in particular. I presume, in general, doing the SOP for a pregnant person is a no-no due to the FAQ rules, but if there is any natural magic or lesser DMH spell suggestions I'd be grateful (I understand there may be nothing for it though).\nSorry for the long post and thank you again,\nMorfran.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8110300", "title": "Re: Assorted SOP queries", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Remember that the whole sphere rotates. If you get a child's beach ball or something similar, and rotate it in various ways, that can help get the visualizations clear.\n2) Stick to that posture like grim death. The fact that it's uncomfortable tells you that you're succeeding in relaxing far enough that locked-up tension and suppressed emotional energies are coming to the surface. Put up with the discomfort, no matter how miserable it gets; in time the tensions and emotions will drain off, and you'll be much healthier and be able to go into deep relaxation any time you get into that posture. \\\n3) No, there really isn't anything you can do at your current stage of training. Sorry!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8081884", "title": "OBOD studies", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG and readers,\nA while ago, there was some discussion of a couple of people needing to use pornography right after OBOD rituals.  Well, I am struggling through the Bardic grade.  I was on Gwers 13 for over a month and it dug straight down to the deepest layers of repression from my childhood.\nLesson 14 is already eliciting very strong discomfort.  I know it is good and will improve me in the long run but I think some people will have an even harder time with these lessons and revert to old, comforting behaviors, even if they are negative.\nSo, I suspect it is not some malign presence in the lessons but just discomfort with what the lessons bring up.\nIn so many ways, the OBOD work is a great boost to my Druidry.  I would recommend it without hesitation.\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8110812", "title": "Re: OBOD studies", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That makes a great deal of sense. Thanks for this!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8083164", "title": "new divination systems and divination in general", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "I have wrapped up the first level of a set of meditations that were very productive and that seem to have resulted in material that could be a \"new\" (?) divination system. I'm now at the testing phase to see if my initial work was headed in the right direction and I wonder if you can tell a bit about the process you used to work with newly conceived systems (recognizing that you were likely working with historical\nand\nnewly devised information, I put \"new\" in quotes because for all I know, I've reinvented a wheel or my meditations were inspired by tracks in space or what have you).\nMy thought was to NOT do a morning divination but to do an after-the-fact reading. This would help me avoid going through the day with a bias or awareness that would cause me to alter my behavior or approach to situations (effectively canceling out a reading if I tried to avoid whatever looked less than favorable) and potentially allow me to reflect on how the theme played out naturally, if it did. At least, that's what several morning divinations vs. several evening readings suggested to me. How does this sound and is it similar to what you've done?\nWith all this in mind, I've been giving some thought to what this system might look like, in terms of how a querent would go about querying, as well as how to conceive of the whole system's symbolism. (Thought that's not turned up a \"must have\" characteristic at this point) I wonder if you've come across any material that catalogs divination systems, or looks into a wide range of systems to point out themes and practical similarities or divergences. I know, a search engine is my friend, but just wondering if you've got any familiarity with general every-mancy.\nMany thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8111068", "title": "Re: new divination systems and divination in general", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My approach has always been to treat a new (or \"new\") oracle the way I treat any other divination system; my readings usually provide me with guidance rather than predictions, so I've never found it useful to focus on after-the-fact divinations. Of course your mileage may vary.\nIn outline, once I've designed (or discovered) the oracle, I make a set (of cards, Coelbren sticks, or what have you) and then start using it for all my ordinary divining needs, turning to something else only on issues of high importance when I need to be sure I get the answer right. Six months to a year of that is enough for me to get a really good sense of how the oracle likes to communicate.\nAs for general catalogs of oracles, no, I'm sorry to say I don't know of anything like that. If you find one, let me know!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8111836", "title": "Re: new divination systems and divination in general", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "Interesting to consider the difference between guidance and predictions and the 3rd, after-the-fact, thing that I don't have a name for (post-dictions? :D) I'll chew on that a bit and maybe I'll keep alternating.\nThe reasoning behind my question (just FYI or for others in the same situation and not a contradiction of your practice) occurred to me when I got a morning reading that suggested I'd have less than optimal success working on projects approaching physical completion or having tangible material aspects. So instead of doing what I'd had planned (building a bookshelf, making marmalade), I worked on some logistical and planning aspects of things and everything went smoothly. But now I don't know if the reading was correct because I took the guidance!\nI kind of figured that maybe if I were allowed to bumble my way through the days, then look and see what the readings says, I might get confirmation that the oracle is correctly delineating useful patterns. So far, when I do my morning readings, then look back at the day, I'm getting \"unclear\" as the result. Not sure if that's because I've not tapped into a functioning system or if my foreknowledge is skewing things.\nObviously more to chew on!\nAnd... I'll let you know if I come across such a source!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8120540", "title": "Re: new divination systems and divination in general", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If the advice you get results in things working out smoothly, I count that as a successful reading!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8122332", "title": "Re: new divination systems and divination in general", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "I see! I was trying to add an intermediate step to try to flesh out my descriptions a bit (still a little thin) and to see if I could get more details to include. So no wonder my attempts were slightly at odds with each other. Huh.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8083932", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been doing daily cold showers. I can't tell what part of the effect is etheric and what is cold shock, but I do feel better. One thing I'd recommend is sticking your fingers in your ears while you hose down your head. If you get water in your ears every day, after a while they start to feel strange and then need to be kept dry for four or five days to return to normal.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8111324", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Useful advice!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8084188", "title": "Dr Traverner and New Thought", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG:\nNo question this week, but I found this article on Dr. Theodore Moriarty that you might find of interest: http://www.jamesnorth.org/blog/the-singular-mystery-of-dr-moriarty\nTake care, and many blessings.\nAnon.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8120796", "title": "Re: Dr Taverner and New Thought", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I own PDF copies of both of Moriarty's books, and noted on first reading\nThe Seven Aphorisms of Creation\nthat it and\nThe Secret Doctrines of the Rosicrucians\nshare a lot of material, but I'd thought -- due to some apparent mistakes in Moriarty's book -- that he'd based his book on Magus Incognito's, and gotten it garbled. It'll be interesting to see if further research bears out North's hypothesis.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8133084", "title": "Re: Dr Traverner and New Thought", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The \"unpublished letter from Bowen\" that is shown as evidence(!) for this hypothesis contains a lot of factual errors. Even if it did not contain any factual error, still a personal letter like this would not prove anything. Let's say I write a letter to someone which contains a claim like \"I'm the actual author of Da Vinci Code, not Dan Brown.\" Would this prove anything?\nBesides, the academic research of Philip Deslippe clearly shows that William Walker Atkinson is the sole author of The Kybalion, The Secret Doctrine of the Rosicrucians and the \"Yogi Ramacharaka\" books.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8134620", "title": "Re: Dr Traverner and New Thought", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There are some disquieting elements in that blog post:\n1 - The author equates New Thought movement with New Age and popular self-help stuff like \"The Secret\" type of books, which is far from truth.\n2 - The author treats New thought movement as something completely separate from genuine occultism. He should be reminded about the history of his own lineage - Dion Fortune herself had a background in Christian Science which is a branch of New Thought.\n3 - The author treats Atkinson as an average New Thought writer. However, Atkinson was an initiate of Hermeticism and Theosophy - just like Theodore Moriarty was.\n4 - The claims about the authorship of those books (The Kybalion and the other ones mentioned in the blog) require hard evidence, not some subjective statements written in a piece of private letter.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8135132", "title": "Re: Dr Traverner and New Thought", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "On North's own showing, Moriarty remained in South Africa until about 1910, so any works preserved by his students came into circulation after that date.  His own books of Masonic practice appeared a little before that, in 1908 and 1909.\nOn the other hand, Ramacharaka's \"Fourteen Lessons in Occult Philosophy\" was published as a correspondence course in 1903, and as a book in 1904.  His \"Advanced Course in Yogi Philosophy and Oriental occultism\" appeared first as a book in 1905.  The two volumes formed Ramacharaka's \"Yogi Philosophy,\" vols. I and II.  (Volumes III, IV and V in that series appeared in 1906, 1907 and 1908, but are not relevant to North's claims.) \"The Kybalion\" first appeared in 1908.   These are years when Moriarty was still in South Africa and most heavily involved in writing and publishing his Masonic books.\n\"Yogi Ramacharaka\" first appears as the author of any Yogi Publication Society volumes during the years when Atkinson himself was hiding out for a few years in Los Angeles (instead of living at home in Chicago), while one of his business associates in Chicago was having trouble with the law.  From style and from content, it seems highy likely that \"Ramacharaka\" began his literary life as a practical means by which Atkinson could hide from the law; but it proved a marketable pseudonym, and Atkinsonb continued to use it as late as 1912.\nPhilip Deslippe has pretty convincingly shown that \"The Kybalion\" is also Atkinson's work, who thus is all three of the \"Three Initiates\" who wrote it.  (Does the phrase \"three initiates\" include the authors \"Akinson\" and \"Ramacharaka\" alongside of the anonymous author of the Kybalion?  Three in one, like the oil?)\n\"The Secret Doctrine of the Rosicrucians\" is a different matter.  It appeared in 1918, after Moriarty had returned to the UK from South Africa.\nI should note that the official semi-annual Catalog of Copyright Entries includes only those books for which the author or published completed the entire process of obtaining a copyright, right down to the deposit of two copies in the Library of Congress.  It does not include valid copyrights for which copies were never sent to the Library of Congress for deposit. Thus one needs also to check for copyright renewals a few decades later if one wants to get the full picture.  As it happened, \"The Secret Doctrine of the Rosicrucians\" does not appear in this Catalogue under the year in which it was first copyrighted, but it does appear when its copyright was renewed in 1949, and in that entry its author, \"Magus Incognito,\" is identified as one Clifford Edgar Brooksmith.  In the National Union Catalogue of Pre-1956 Imprints both editions of the \"Secret Doctrine of the Rosicrucians appear (1918 and 1949), and for each of them the anonymous author is identified as Clifford Edgar Brooksmith.  So far as I can find out, this man never published any other book, and I have not yet managed to find out much else about him.  There is just one \"Clifford Brooksmith\" listed in the Social Security Death Index.  He was born in 1899 in Illinois, and died in 1979 in New York (city). If this is the right Clifford Brooksmith, he was only about 20 when he wrote his book.\nThe sum of all this: James North is mistaken, though it seems to be a sincere mistake, about Moriarty, Atkinson and Ramacharaka.  I am inclined to explain Bowen's letter as reflecting some of Moriarty's own myth-building about his earlier achievements, as well as a certain amount of deliberate deception.  Sampson Dunn may be meant as a \"cover\" for Moriarty himself.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-07 05:58 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8135388", "title": "Re: Dr Taverner and New Thought", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, that makes sense. As I noted in my response, there are mistakes in\nThe Seven Aphorisms of Creation\nthat make it look as though Moriarty quoted from Magus Incognito rather than vice versa.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8143580", "title": "Re: Dr Taverner and New Thought", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Indeed, I noticed how you mentioned that.  Well spotted!   I haven't seen Moriarty's \"Seven Aphorisms of Creation\" myself.  Is it readily available somewhere on line?\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-08 12:47 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8153564", "title": "Re: Dr Taverner and New Thought", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of an online source for it. Let me see if I can find my PDF copy -- once that turns up I'll email it to you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8154844", "title": "Re: Dr Taverner and New Thought", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Thank you!], John MIchaell!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8084956", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMH,\nI have a few questions this week if that's ok:\n1.\tIs the process of opening one’s psychic centres the same thing as clearing them of blockages? All I can find online is about chakra clearing and it's confusing about what's actually going on.\n2.\tWhat causes those blocks? Do they accumulate over multiple lives or does the slate get wiped clean with each new life? Have they anything to do with karma?\n3.\tI’m going to make a protective herbal amulet for my daughter (7) to bring with her when she’s staying at her dad’s house. Would it be ok to douse it in lavender oil after making and consecrating it? I want to tell her that it’s just a lavender bag to go under her pillow to help her sleep.\nDot.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8121052", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, not quite, but they're related. Opening the psychic centers is the process by which you get the ability to use them to tap into various levels of astral and etheric energy. Clearing them is the process by which you get gunk out of the way so you can open them. It's like the difference between running water through a pipe and cleaning the pipe so water can run through it.\n2) They're generally either karmic in nature, and thus passed on from previous lives, or the result of trauma in this life.\n3) Be sure and consecrate the lavender oil you're going to use -- or make it, douse it, and then consecrate it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8086748", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How much does furniture matter in rituals, if you have to use a small space?\neg there is part of a couch in your circle but not at a cardinal point, or you aren't just drawing that SoP Spirit Below circle as if it was on a table, but on a table and imagining it float through it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8121308", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can ignore furniture if you need to. When I first started practicing, I used a small corner of the bedroom for my practices -- about four feet by three feet -- and simply pretended that the furniture wasn't there.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8087004", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nAs a candidate in the AODA, I'm learning the SoP and have in the past few weeks read the series you provided on that topic. Somewhere in it or in the comments, you state the need for a gender balance if you call on deities.\nI come to druidry from a goddess tradition and have adapted the SoP to call on 6 goddesses\nEast/air: Eostre\nSouth/fire: Brigida\nWest/water: Nehalennia\nNorth/earth: Epona or Holle\nBelow: Holle or another goddess I have yet to meet in my meditations\nAbove: Anna/Ana\nAfter the aforementioned notice of gender balance, I wonder what your thoughts are on a goddess-only SoP. Would it work or is something essential missing here?\nThank you!\nJudith", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8121564", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recommend it. If you focus everything on one side of any binary, you can count on having the other side of the binary pop up constantly in its extreme and uncompensated form, as the energies of the cosmos try to right the balance.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8087772", "title": "SoP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI have two things on my mind.\n1. Eyes open or closed  – The instructions for SoP imply that visualization is done with eyes open. Is it also possible to visualize with eyes closed in some cases? For example when you rotate light around somebody far away like Maxine did some time ago. Also, it seems to me easier to do it with eyes closed. And how about during meditation?\n2. Gods – I need to explain the situation at some length, the questions come at the end.\nIn my SoP practice I am currently using the set of Welsh gods you suggested. I have been practising for about 5 months without previous knowledge, connection or relationship to them, I just wanted to try out. It seems to me now that the names do not mean to me much more than at the beginning. Except for the word Awen. I always look forward to vibrating it. It feels very soothing. My relationship to god(s) is somewhat vague. I notice people here on MM mentioning experiences that show that they can contact them, feel their presence and distinguish whether the gods are happy or not happy with the interaction.\nI only have one strong experience of god’s presence which happened a few years ago and was really powerful. It happened during a major personal crisis of mine. I won’t go into details, but I know somebody wanted to get in touch with me and let me know of his existence. It felt like a male power and consciousness. It was accompanied by synchronicities that I take as a proof I wasn’t out of my mind. I also know the meaning of the encounter. He wanted to let me know that I should stop thinking about god as a theoretical concept and start developing a relationship. It had never before occured to me that I could actually speak to god or ask for help. From then on I started to pray and it came natural to me to call him Father. And since I didn’t want to be a member of a single parent family I also added Mother. It also felt pretty natural. I usually pray in bed and I feel like Father is above me and Mother feels like the very bed I lie in and the Earth beneath it. I would be quite content with this system only I do not know if it isn’t too childish or inaccurate. All the gods mentioned here have names, sometimes names that are difficult to pronounce. I don’t even know whether the one who contacted me had a name. So my questions are: Should I keep trying to invoke the Welsh gods and perhaps to meditate on them to see if I feel more connected? Should I leave them out and do just the elemental invocations? (I would probably be fine with that) Should I try to find out what was the name of the god that contacted me? If so, how?\nThank you,\nHana", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8121820", "title": "Re: SoP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's entirely up to you. Some people do it one way, some the other.\n2) There's nothing wrong with using terms like Father and Mother for deities -- it's very traditional, in fact. (Jupiter, for example, was routinely addressed as \"Pater Deorum Hominumque,\" \"Father of Gods and Men.\")  I would encourage you to pray to the two deities in question and ask them what they would like you to do, and then still your mind and see what surfaces. Listening to the gods is as important as praying to them...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8088028", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I presume the chart of the Tree one constructs in LRM is to be filled out with the path letters and their Atziluth colors in PoW prior to travelling each path?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8122076", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly do things that way. I didn't specify because different students have different needs.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8088284", "title": "art of memory", "user": "syfen", "content": "Archdruid,\nI've had your translation of the art of memory sitting on my shelves for some time now. I finally cracked it open and realized that what's in the book is way in advance of the garden of memory article you published on the AODA Website.\nSo, is this one of those layered occult systems that must be unpacked by meditation and practice?\nRegards,\nSyfen\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-06 11:17 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8123612", "title": "Re: art of memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Bruno's system is far and away the most difficult and complex system of mnemonics ever devised. There are several simpler systems given in the last part of the book, which you can use to work up to Bruno's core method -- but yes, if you want to work with it you're going to have to put in a lot of time and sweat.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8088540", "title": "prayers to the angel Heniel", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG\nA little over a month ago i asked for some practices to help my Dad and my Wife reconcile after some hurt feelings.  You recommended that I address some prayers to Heniel on successive Fridays during the correct planetary hour.  I have done that four Fridays in a row now.   My main question is that on the last two Saturdays my Wife got really worked up about my Dad.  It seems like she may be fighting the positive energy coming her way.  I am not sure if that is happening but it was very noticeable, prayers for peace, wife gets mad.  I have permission to pray about this and use \"my magic\" but she dosen't know the details of this practice.  Does my observation ring true to you?  If so should I do any thing extra or just proceed with the Friday prayers.  Also does any of the hours of Venus work better, right away ,mid da,y one of the night time hours?\nThanks again John Michael\nWill Oberton", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8124124", "title": "Re: prayers to the angel Heniel", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very likely your wife is feeling the pull toward reconciling with your father and is responding by getting angry in an attempt to push back. I'd encourage you to keep on doing the working. All of the hours of Venus are equally strong.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8125660", "title": "Re: prayers to the angel Heniel", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you very much", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8090076", "title": "Vibrating the SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG:  Would it possible to ask whoever posted examples of vibrating the sounds during the SOP to allow you to post a link to all of the ones she performed?  I think it was Kimberly.  Thanks. Luna", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8124892", "title": "Re: Vibrating the SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you go to the first page of comments, she's near the top -- send her a PM and I'm sure she'll point you to it (if she doesn't read your comment and reply right here).", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8090332", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In cases where due to retrograding, there are three Jupiter-Saturn conjunctions in short succession, which one is used as the chart for the Great Conjunction?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8125148", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The first one.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8092124", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I've read a reference here several times to a simple ritual where you trace a water blessing symbol over a glass of water and then imagine it filled with white light, but I can't find a reference to what the symbol is or how to trace it. Could you enlighten me? And, could it be used on a jug of water that sits out and is gradually consumed by a family over the course of a day, or would you have to drink it right away?\n2) I'm trying to get a hold of your book \"The Secret of the Temple,\" which is taking some time at the moment, since I don't want to get it on amazon. What I'm itching to know is: is it the sort of thing a not-rich person with a few acres in the country would be able to test and replicate? Could you make a building the size of a garden shed to use the principle to support something like a market garden?\n3) Are there any contraindications to wearing silver jewelry on an ongoing basis? I have a silver necklace that I got instead of a ring when I got married and wear it most days, and while sleeping. Any potential issues with unbalanced lunar energies or anything?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8125916", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can use any symbol that represents blessing to you. I use the three rays of light, /|\\ , which is a Druid Revival emblem of divine light. You should drink it right away; the charge won't last long.\n2) It should be possible to make the effect work on a small scale -- even a little shrine, just large enough to hold an incense burner, might be sufficient. (I've seen Shinto shrines that small, for example). It would certainly be worth making the experiment.\n3) Am I correct that you're female? If so, it should be no trouble at all. If male, you'll want to wear some gold to balance it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8126940", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP but, what are the negatives if you regularly wear a silver necklace as a male?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8127452", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It will tend to feminize you -- not to a drastic extent, but noticeably. Silver is the Moon's metal and resonates with feminine energy, as gold is the Sun's metal and resonates with masculine energy.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8092380", "title": "Age for abstract knowledge", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'll try to be succinct about this. I've encountered in a few places the idea that children shouldn't learn to read, (or other things that involve a lot of abstract thought), until they're seven years old. I believe that was Rudolf Steiner's perspective, hence Waldorf schools don't usually teach reading until after that age. Joseph Chilton Pearce says something similar in his book Magical Child.\nAs far as you know, is there any occult basis for this view? I imagine that Steiner didn't get it out of nowhere. From the little I know of his thought, he believed that the spiritual development of human beings took place in something like 7 year cycles. I'm especially curious what you think, given that the Magic Monday FAQ says that it's after 7 years old that children are safe around ritual magic. Is there any basis in the occult traditions you've encountered that suggests there would be risks or drawbacks to a pre-school child learning to read earlier than this? I forget if it was Steiner or someone else who warned that trying to get children to do and learn things in advance of when they're truly ready (even if they're interested and practically capable of doing so) could throw a wrench in the works of the development in terms of the soul or subtle bodies. Perhaps akin to the note in the FAQ that ids shouldn't learn ceremonial magic until after puberty.\nYour thoughts? I'd also be interested in any sources that you can recommend which discuss childhood from the perspective of traditional occult philosophy, so that I can look up these questions myself.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8097500", "title": "Re: Age for abstract knowledge", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not JMG)\nWhat did Steiner propose doing with kids like me, who figure it out on their own before age 7?  Or was he not aware of any?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8114396", "title": "Re: Age for abstract knowledge", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OP here: that is part of what I’m wondering!  I learned earlier too, and it’s clearly not the end of the world or anything. I’m partly wondering because I’ve read this guy named Glen Doman who has fascinating material about how even very young children can learn reading, math etc as early as babyhood - indeed in many cases learn much easier than many kids do around age 6 when they typically introduce it in schools - since babies and toddlers are sponges for everything they are exposed to. I find Doman’s stuff very compelling, and am interested in other perspectives. I’m all for tapping the maximum of human potential (that’s what Doman is all about), but am also wary of the notion of trying to turn kids into prodigies without a clear understanding of why and the larger implications.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8126172", "title": "Re: Age for abstract knowledge", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, Steiner got his theory from a Theosophical teaching that has the various levels of the self maturing in seven year cycles. I'm far from sure what to think of it. I learned to read at two and a half, and it's quite possible that some of the consequences of that have not been good. Still, I don't think it's wise at all to impose one standard on all children, since every soul that comes into incarnation has different gifts, different karma, and a different life to live.\nSteiner was one of the few people I know of in the occult tradition to get into things like educational theory; just off hand I can't think of anyone else who dealt with it in any detail.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8092636", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a generically good time to perform magic seeking employment, specifically converting a monthly contract into a permanent hire in a medically related field? Would it be best to try and find the particular planetary ruler of the subspecialty and perform the spell during that hour, or is there another more appropriate choice given the desire of converting irregular to regular employment? I’m assuming this should also be done during the new or waxing moon if possible- is that correct? Thank you as always for hosting this forum and soliciting questions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8126684", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fridays during a waxing moon in the hour of Venus. Friday is the traditional payday in America, so became the standard day for doing employment magic, and Venus makes you agreeable and pleasing to a prospective employer.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8093404", "title": "Astrology and the Star of Bethlahem", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Arch Druid,\nI was wondering if you knew if there were any major differences and/or unique quirks concerning the astrology of the ancient Persian Zoroastrian priests that the Bible says followed a star to find Jesus.  I am particularly interested in being able to use this as a touchstone for conversation with Christians.  If there are any resources of astrology in the Bible that you would recommend that would also be really helpful. Thank you for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8127196", "title": "Re: Astrology and the Star of Bethlahem", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Persian astrology is a very rich and complex field; some aspects of it were taken up into modern astrology. There's a very good blog on the subject\nhere\n. As for astrology in the Bible, you can find some pointers\nhere\n.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8093660", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nIn ancient times, were the mythical stories used as vehicles to convey exoteric teachings of the mystery cults to uninitiated public?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8127708", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. Plato practically admits as much in introducing some of the mythic stories in his dialogues.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8094684", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nWould you recommend reading The Circuit of Force, after reading the Mystical Qabalah?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8127964", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Read Regardie's\nThe Middle Pillar\nand\nThe Art of True Healing\nfirst. Those will give you the basics on which Fortune's later book is founded.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8099292", "title": "astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nOn a different magic monday someone asked how to find a fortunate time to release an album. ...I have been looking for this comment without success. All I can remember was that Venus rules music and to start there... Note to self: take better notes!\nI will be starting a reflexology practice. Can you please tell me what to look for to find/choose a good opening time/birthday? I guess you could call it?\nI assume this starts with Mercury and ...and help please, I'm rather new with astrology and most of what I can find is birth charts only.\nThank you in advance, magic monday keeps being so helpful!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8128220", "title": "Re: astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You choose a good starting date by figuring out which planet rules the subject, and then finding a day of the week corresponding to that planet in which the planet is not in its detriment or fall, not applying to square or opposition to any planet and not in any aspect to Mars or Saturn, and if possible in an applying sextile or trine aspect with the Moon or Jupiter. Music is ruled by Venus and thus your day is Friday; healing is ruled by Mercury so its day is Wednesday. For the rest, you may need to talk to someone who knows more about astrology and can point you to a good day.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8101084", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nCan the photo of a sacred place be used for scrying, if the practitioner visited that place before?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8128476", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Even without the previous visit, yes. Try it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8102108", "title": "Magic and the Orgasm", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. What are the correspondences to the orgasm- elemental, planetary, energetic, and so on? All I can find online are correspondences for genitals and fluids but not the frenzied build up and release of an orgasm itself.\n2. Are there magical means for increasing the intensity and pleasure of an orgasm?\n3. What would the consequences be of sexual activity with ‘beings’ appearing during sleep paralysis?\nThank you,\nKojo", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8128732", "title": "Re: Magic and the Orgasm", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You know, I'm going to pass on this entire subject. I know there are a lot of young men these days who are desperate to get laid by spirits, and I'm not greatly interested in running an astral sex-advice column.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8102876", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have found Iyengar yoga to have a lot of benefits without the annoying/dangerous features of other types of yoga that I have practiced. Also the teacher regularly doles out the spiritual insights that line up really well with CGD occult studies, although I have kept that to myself for now. My question is if there needs to be a period in between yoga and RM like there is with sex. Thanks and hope you are enjoying the spring weather.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8128988", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know that anybody's tried it. You may need to experiment and see.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8106972", "title": "Goals of Alchemy, Spread of Monotheism", "user": "joshuarout", "content": "Dear J.M. Greer,\n1) I'm curious about the practice and goals of alchemy, especially spagyrics. There seems to be a great deal of confusion even among practitioners (on forums that I've read), and even some fraudulent claims, so I'm rather baffled about it. Along the lines of your article 'What Magic Can't Do,' what would you say that alchemy or spagyrics can and can't do? What are its goals, or some clear achievements to chart progress along an alchemical path?\n2) Concerning the spread of monotheisms in Late Antiquity, what are some factors that may have made the traditional religions and pantheons vulnerable to suppression? I've been thinking in particular about the traditions of Egyptian polytheism, which had survived for so long. Were there degeneracies that set in, some fatal factor or lack of 'immune resistance'?\nThank you for providing this forum.\nRegards,\nJ.R.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8129244", "title": "Re: Goals of Alchemy, Spread of Monotheism", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Spagyrics has three main goals. The first is the production of natural medicines. The second is the creation of elixirs that will speed the spiritual evolution of the practitioner. The third is developing the necessary skills for the mineral and metallic work. Most spagyrists do all three.\n2) Religions by and large are only good during one zodiacal age; when they survive into a second age, they do it by completely reformulating themselves. Think of the way that the temple worship of the ancient Israelites morphed into Rabbinic Judaism and you can get some sense of how this works! Most of the other faiths of the ancient world were not able to make that transition, and lost power as the Sun moved into Pisces at the equinox, while the Piscean faith of Christianity had plenty of power. Of course now the tables have turned...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8113372", "title": "Chthonic deity ritual", "user": "lunarapprentice", "content": "I recall something you’d written recently in MM that to worship most any deities in a pantheon, all one needs is an alter with candles, incense, and a representation of the deity. In the case of chthonic (subterranean) deities, e.g Hades, Hekate, Dionysus, would this be appropriate? If not, what would be an appropriate ritual set-up?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8129500", "title": "Re: Chthonic deity ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. You'd simply need to use a different incense. For celestial deities, frankincense was the standard in classical times; for chthonic deities, you'd need something with a darker and earthier scent.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8113884", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nDo you know of any work which combines astrology with modern statistical methods of forecasting?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8129756", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, that's still waiting for you to create it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8114908", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nIf someone wanted to craft a special tarot deck to be used with the Wheel of the Year diagram in Druidry, what kind of practices would you recommend to get the inspiration necessary for that work?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8130012", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Lots of meditation and pathworking. Also, get some classical drawing training if you don't already have that -- there are too many ugly tarot decks made by people who never learned how to draw, and so didn't have any sense of proportion and visual grace.  As the Sar Peladan used to say, \"Drawing is the Catholicism of the arts; outside of it there is no salvation.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8115164", "title": "Planet migrations?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I seem to remember somebody here talking about some piece of lore that large numbers of spirits moved from incarnating on Venus to on Earth at some point in the distance past.  Does anyone know where this came from or have any details of the notion?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8130268", "title": "Re: Planet migrations?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's in Theosophical lore. The idea was that Venus was inhabited long ages before the Earth, and certain spiritual beings -- not great boatloads of them, just some important ones -- came here in the early days of life on Earth.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8115932", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Archdruid,\nIs it possible to fit a correspondence between 24 paths of the Wheel of Life and 12 zodiac signs + 7 planets + 5 elements?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8130524", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a fine set of topics for meditation!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8116956", "title": "GRA", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would you know of a working Western system based on the GRA structure of the Tree of Life?\nI'm aware of Aryeh Kaplan's book on the Sefer Yezirah, which appears to favour the Gra version; and of the El Gran Tarot Esoterico deck, which, according to Christine Payne-Towler, is oriented toward the same.\nHowever, the Kaplan is specifically Jewish in its parameters (as opposed to a 'Christian' or 'Western', esoteric development of it); while the Esoterico deck is a deck only (and Marixtu Gruler's LWB for the same is minimal). I'm guessing there may be something in the French Tradition as the (Spanish) Esoterico deck seems to be based roughly on Levi's attributions in outline.\nIs there an esoteric system of practice that works from, and elaborates on, the GRA beyond these items?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8130780", "title": "Re: GRA", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not familiar with one. The only GRA-based systems I've ever seen were very specifically Jewish in focus.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8117212", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've heard from someone who had Covid-19 that it was if there was an evil entity with them. I find it interesting, especially since it's apparently a common thing. Do you think there's something to it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8131036", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know, but it wouldn't surprise me greatly.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8162268", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(different anon)\nI can't help but wonder if old memories of their role as a viral reservoir could be partly behind the symbolism connections between bats and death/underworld/etc...", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8117980", "title": "Pain", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there any occult teachings/practices for dealing with physical pain?\nYou mention the stoics often enough and I recall one of your characters in your deindustrial-future short stories having bowel cancer and referencing stoicism as far as how he would deal with it.  Would it just a matter of accepting what you can't control, or are there meditation or exercise methods that would effect this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8131292", "title": "Re: Pain", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never encountered any. Stoicism's certainly what I use.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8118748", "title": "Livestreaming some Orphic Hymns", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Hi JMG and Readers,\nI am going to be live-streaming some of the Orphic Hymns I've written so far every night at midnight Central Time from now until May 1.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjNTgJMen15PCFGzfU7vyzA?view_as=subscriber\n-Kimberly", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8131548", "title": "Re: Livestreaming some Orphic Hymns", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Many thanks for this!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8120284", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1) You've written that with your Asperger's, you are more or less unable to decipher other people's expressions and emotions. Do you have memories from your past lives of recognizing facial expressions?\n2) I've recently learned that Rosicrucian societies only started appearing after the appearance of two or three Rosicrucian Manifestos, back during the Reformation. Where did these manifestos come from? Is it anything resembling the origins of the UFO craze, with occultists bringing a set of ideas into manifestation in order to keep the world from exploding?\nThanks,\nCliff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8131804", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Dimly, yes.\n2) Yes, exactly. The first and third manifestoes were invented by a crew of merry pranksters at the University of Tubingen in Germany in 1605 or so, with the goal of encouraging the occult-friendly side of the Lutheran movement; the second was created by a different group a little later, for much more political reasons. Frances Yates' book\nThe Rosicrucian Enlightenment\nis a good introduction to the background of the R+C.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8124380", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey jmg\nWould I be right in assuming that the energy of the moon when it is dark is the moons true energy, and that the energy of the full moon is the moons energy when modified by the sun?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8132060", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, because the Moon's energy is an energy of change. Its \"true energy\" is the sum total of the influences of all its phases.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8125404", "title": "Adepthood", "user": "alexandermarcus", "content": "Good evening!\nI've taken note lately of a couple of occultist authors who refer to themselves as Adepts. I'm wondering:\n1. What does the title \"adept\" refer to? What do you mean when you use it?\n2. Do you consider yourself an adept? If so, why not use the title?\n3. What do you make of the practice of an occultist self-applying the label?\n4. I've seen you refer to individuals as adepts (for instance Franz Bardon), but as I recall only dead individuals. Is their being dead significant for you in applying the label?\nI promise I'm not trying to put you on the spot here, I'm just trying to get a better grasp of the term. Part of me is suspicious of people self-applying it, but then again, if someone's earned it, they have the right.\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8132316", "title": "Re: Adepthood", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm going to answer this in a slightly indirect way. In the Chinese martial arts there's a title, Sifu, which denotes a master-teacher of a martial arts lineage. You never call yourself Sifu; it's purely a title that other people use to refer to you, and they, not you, decide when you've earned it. Clueless white guys who go around labeling themselves \"Sifu\" are the subject of wry jokes among Chinese-American martial artists.\nThe title \"saint\" in Christianity is much the same, except it's usually not conferred on living people. You don't just up and call yourself a saint -- or if you do, everyone takes that as proof that you're not one. A person becomes recognized as a saint by others, and the various old Christian churches have more or less elaborate ways of formalizing the process.\nThe title \"adept\" falls somewhere in between those two examples. Technically speaking, it refers to an alchemist who has accomplished the Great Work, or (by extension) to a mage or occultist who has achieved a similar level of mastery in the work of self-transformation. A person who goes around proclaiming that he's an adept proves, by that proclamation, that he's not one. (To know, to dare, to will, and what?) There are living people I believe to be adepts, but as I haven't had the brass-balled nerve to grill them about their spiritual experiences I don't know that for certain.  With some dead people, the question's pretty clear one way or the other, and so it's not at all inappropriate to refer to Bardon, say, as an adept; Dion Fortune described her teacher, Theodore Moriarty, as \"an adept if there ever was one,\" but he was dead when she wrote that. It seems like a sensible habit to follow.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/85690.html", "year": "2020", "month": "04", "day": "12", "time": "11-43PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt8179898", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. Do you have any activities for winding down at the end of a long day? This could be any semi-passive activity that you use as a distraction from studying and writing, and that doesn’t require too much mental focus. Most Americans fill that slot with TV and surfing the Internet, but I imagine you’ve figured out something more interesting and thoughtful. Or is such a thing antithetical to the magician’s path?\n2. Can you describe your personal encounter with the Watcher on the Threshold? In particular:\na. At what stage did you first encounter it?\nb. How did you know that it was the Watcher and not some other phenomenon?\nc. How was the confrontation resolved?\n3. In The Magician: His Training and Work, W.E. Butler states that the biggest spiritual danger of magic is the sin of pride – that is, the Luciferan pride of considering oneself superior to others for being in possession of secret knowledge and techniques.  How do you avoid falling into the egocentric trap of seeing yourself as being above the uninitiated, ignorant herd, etc.? In doing what you do, isn’t there a temptation to believe that you have all the answers?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8180922", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I enjoy reading, and so I like to wind down by sitting on the couch with a good book.\n2) Me and the Watcher go way back. I had several run-ins with the fear that is the first enemy of a man of knowledge -- yes, that's another way of talking about the same thing -- over the period in my teens when I was studying magic half-seriously. It was immediately clear what it was, because I'd read enough accounts of the same thing, and the confrontation was resolved in the one way it's possible to resolve it: I committed myself to the work and just kept on going through the panic, and came right out the other side.\n3) Any occultist who thinks he has all the answers hasn't yet started asking any of the real questions. I went through a brief period of thinking I knew it all, early on in my magical training, then had the salutary experience of running face first into alchemical literature -- specifically, John Dee's\nMonas Hieroglyphica\n-- and realizing that I literally had no idea what he was talking about. The longer I study and practice, the more certain I am that the old-fashioned occultists of the late 19th and early 20th centuries were right, and humanity (including those of us who practice occultism) are just taking our first tottering baby steps in a cosmos far vaster than any of us can imagine.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8229306", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP -\n2) This got me wondering whether there could be a \"chronic\" form of the watcher? I asked here months ago what to do when being ground by fear and anxiety. For a very long time, since my early childhood I would say, a deeply rooted fear and panic which finds a slow relieve only by going forward - for a lack of a better term - is the major driving force behind my spiritual endeavors. At the same time, whenever I indulge in spiritual practice - be it meditation, divination, whatever - fear and panic will come soon and I feel a strong urge to drop my practice like a hot iron...\nThe situation is not made easier since my divination regarding regular practice of a banishing ritual and regular discursive meditation yield negative results, basically telling me - if I interpret it correctly - that meditation would principally be a sensible thing to do, still I'd regret it if I did. For now, I have the feeling that journaling is the thing to do. A prospect to which part of me reacts with, well, fear. I can't explain why, but to write down the things that haunt me and that really matter is terrifying to me...\nNachtgurke", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8231098", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That doesn't sound like the Watcher; it sounds to me like the legacy of a really problematic previous life, the memories from which are close enough to the surface of your consciousness that you can sense them. Not an easy row to hoe!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8190138", "title": "avoiding egocentrism", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "Getting some perspective on your own level of attainment can happen from reading difficult books as JMG says. It can also come from direct contact with other people who are fully engaged with the same pursuit, discovering that they have forgotten more than you ever learned, and that you would fit right in with the half dozen students in their advanced beginner course. Or, at long last, after toiling in isolation for a long time, you finally get to meet some peers to talk shop with, and they are making jokes of the kind that come from relaxed familiarity about something you Take Very Seriously.\nThere is no substitute for the solitary grind, but I think balancing that by contact with colleagues is healthy. If you can find a community that maintains some standards without cutthroat competition, this can be very pleasant and it prevents you from having to go up a hat size.\nAll of that is true in any occupation that requires both some talent and a lot of application.  Some fields of magic have specific dangers. One is that since it is a fringe interest in our culture, anybody with a bit of charisma and half a clue can set themselves up as a teacher and gather acolytes. If somehow none of the acolytes ever go on to set up their own independent groups while remaining on good terms with their former teacher, that's a teacher to stay away from.\nPaths that encourage identification with a deity as a part of their practice attract people who suffer from low self esteem and want to repair themselves. A little of this can do some good if it is kept within bounds. Too much can lead to making a fool of yourself, or being a PITA to your friends (hopefully a temporary phase) or in serious cases, ego inflation that is compensatory and does not ever come to terms with the underlying psychological problem. Sooner or later, you must acquire self knowledge or you will not progress.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8216762", "title": "Re: avoiding egocentrism", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "How would you go about finding colleagues in this pursuit? It often feels like a lonely path but I wouldn't even know where to look for like-minded people.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8241594", "title": "Re: avoiding egocentrism", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "I can tell you how I did it but you will have to do things differently,  because times have changed.\nI got started in the pre-Internet days when things were less out in the open. The way I made my first contacts was by seeing a couple of zines on sale in a feminist bookstore that related to my interests, buying them, reading them, and writing private letters to the editors. One of the magazines was published in a far off state, and they sent me a rudimentary correspondence course for awhile. The other zine was published near to where I live. Its editors replied to me and two of them arranged to meet me in a public place. I poured out my heart, and they put me in touch with a local group that was doing something related to my interests. This group was ethical and highly networked in the local Pagan community.\nOnce I had that first introduction, a world opened up to me. That only happened because I was fortunate enough to live in a place where the various Pagans and occultists got along with each other and weren't playing dominance games, and there were diverse groups.\nI had opportunities to join some groups, but being the sort of person I am, I had some authority issues, so I studied a little while longer on my own and then gathered a few like-minded women to study together in an egalitarian fashion. I should say that by the time I attempted that, I had read dozens of books that were recommended to me; I just didn't know how to do anything. Meeting in a small group for three years gave me enough experience and basic knowledge to move on. I went through the swelled-head period I described in my previous post, but fortunately I didn't make any serious enemies.\nThings have changed a lot since then, and the means of communication are different, and your personality and aspirations are probably very different.  But I think there may be some some things that still apply. If you can make a personal contact with someone who has some discretion and also has an interest in helping people connect with other people, they will make you one or two introductions. If you are polite, discerning, and cautious, you can probably find your way to the people you want to meet. The people you want to meet are not the ones who are easiest to find on websites and social media. One or two of them might be commenters on JMG's blogs. You will need at least two out of these four: patience, persistence, good luck, help from a guardian spirit or deity.\nI hope this helps; it's the best I can do without knowing you.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8180154", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) If a member of America’s privileged classes, say, an eccentric billionaire with an interest in occultism (not me, sadly), offered to become your patron, would you take him up on the offer? Let’s say the terms would be as follows: he would give you a certain amount of money per year, enough to live on very comfortably with no questions asked and no strings attached, and give you complete creative freedom. In return, he would ask for the opportunity to ask questions and receive your advice on various occult and spiritual topics, perhaps with some in-person consultations a few times a year. He would also ensure that the arrangement would remain private, if you so wish. Essentially, you would play a role similar to the private chaplains that served the European nobility hundreds of years ago. Does this sound appealing to you?\n2) You mentioned in the past that you used to work in retirement homes. Could you share any experiences from that time, lessons you’ve learned, perspectives gained?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8181434", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You lost me at \"no questions asked and no strings attached.\" In the real world, that's never how things work, and anyone who claims to be offering such a thing is dangling bait on a hook. In the real world, if somebody pays your bills and supports your lifestyle, they own you, and you can expect the leash to be yanked sooner or later. I'm happy to say that I make enough money these days to cover my expenses with room to spare -- and so if a billionaire wants to ask some questions, why, he or she can have a flunkey post them to Magic Monday!\n2) It's an experience I highly recommend. People these days are terrified of old age and death, and spending time taking care of the old and dying, and occasionally helping to wash a corpse, is a good way to get past that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8180410", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. In the Tree of Life, it is often said that there is a gulf separating the Three Supernals from the rest of the Tree, symbolized by the invisible Daath, positioned on the Lightning Flash between Binah and Chesed. However, there are several Paths between the lower and upper Sephiroth of the Tree: the 13th, 15th, 16th 17th  and 18th Paths. What’s stopping someone from just taking the 16th Path up from Chesed to Chokmah and skipping Daath entirely? Or does Daath somehow intersect all these paths?\n2. I’ve often heard both Mars and Venus described as the desire force in astrology. However, strictly speaking, shouldn’t Mars be thought of as the desire force, while Venus is the attraction force? Mars is how we pursue, Venus is how we attract or draw towards us that which we value.\n3. Am I correct in assuming that the symbols and correspondences of the Sephiroth and Paths on the Tree of Life are more relevant to Pathworking and ceremonial magic than to Tarot divination? Does the knowledge that Elohim Gibor is the divine name of Geburah, or that Lamed is the letter of the 21st path, or similar bits of lore, have any bearing on a divination using the Tarot?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8181946", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can certainly make the attempt, and in terms of pathworking and other purely symbolic and imaginal ways of working with the Tree, you can do that. In any deeper sense? Until you've had the Daath experience, those paths are closed and barred. It's like passing through the Veil -- that needs to happen first by way of the Path of the Arrow, the 25th path in the GD reckoning, in order to make the other paths traversable.\n2) Yes, of course. \"Desire\" is a vague word -- do you mean the desire that sends you chasing after things, or the desire that draws them to you?\n3) Depends on the individual diviner. I know some people whose Tarot treadings are pervaded by intricate Cabalistic references, and others who don't use the correspondences at all. Which works best for you?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8195002", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the Daath experience?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8203706", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a subject for a chapter, not a brief comment.  You'll find it discussed in detail in my book\nPaths of Wisdom\n.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8180666", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nLast week, in response to another question, you mentioned that silver feminizes and gold masculinizes. In what ways, exactly? Physically? Socially? Emotionally? I have a friend considering medical gender reassignment and I'm curious to know if wearing the relevant metals could aid that process.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8182714", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Etherically and astrally -- that is to say, on the levels of subtle energy, emotion, and imagination. If your friend has a male physical body and wants to transition to a female body, silver jewelry might indeed be helpful; she should also burn a violet candle on Mondays and a green candle on Fridays, and ask the help of the Moon and Venus.  If your friend has a female physical body and wants to transition to a male body, gold jewelry will help, and he should also burn a yellow candle on Sundays and a red candle on Tuesday, and ask for the help of the Sun and Mars.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8191930", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I presume a female who wanted to be more venusian could wear copper and a Male who wanted to be more martial could wear iron or steel?\nWhat do you think of the new age obsession with crystals? I think that they can have a subtle influence but nowadays people are putting too much faith in them to sort their problems out magically.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8203962", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, exactly.\n2) Quartz is ruled by the Moon astrologically, and one of its features is that it mirrors back to you what you expect and desire. So it's very convenient if you want to delude yourself...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8194490", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "mmelvink", "content": "Hi JMG,\nJust to piggyback here: I have Moon and Mercury talismans from Chris, both silver, but wear nothing else metallic. (Uranus is the strongest in my chart, but haven't attempted any talismanic harnessing there, for obvious reasons!) Just for balance, since I am male, I suppose it would be better to add a bronze or gold-plated one to the mix, no? If so, Jupiter is probably my best bet -- while retrograde, it's fairly well dignified too (in own triplicity and term, etc.). Does this Moon-Mercury-Jupiter silver-gold combo sound like it might strike a good balance?\nThanks as always!\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-13 11:15 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8204218", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You could also simply wear some gold or iron jewelry, without worrying about the specific planetary consecration. Still, yes, if your Jupiter is in good condition a gold-plated Jupiter talisman would work well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8207290", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "This is fascinating: I'm rather comfortably female, but that's never been a big part of my identity except for sex/flirting/dressing up. In terms of expressing emotions, being interested in children, being into combat/violence, etc., I fit the \"male\" archetype (at least as the 20th/21st century version goes)...and I've always liked gold and copper jewelry a lot better than silver.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8210874", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Gold and copper would have interesting results -- the masculine energy of the Sun plus the feminine energy of Venus. Not inappropriate, but interesting!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8229562", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I'm intrigued--I don't think I've worn the two at once much. Should try it out!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8231610", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP\nIf you can't afford gold, how well would steel work as a substitute?  Stainless?\nIf the sun is afflicted in your chart, is gold a bad bet regardless?\nAny masculine or feminine energy from a Saturn or Jupiter talismans?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8236218", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Sure, if you want a Mars energy.\n2) Only if you consecrate it. Plain jewelry shouldn't be an issue.\n3) Not really. It's the inner planets (Moon through Mars) where gender's a thing; the outer planets (Jupiter through Neptune) not so much.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8255418", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was the one who asked that question last week - a little proud to see it still stimulating discussion this week! One of the things I love about magic Monday is the interplay between things that other people ask that I learn a lot from, even though I never would have thought of the questions myself.\nAs it turns out, I'm male, so I'm glad I asked the question, since I don't feel like being feminized (I have a transgender [M-F] sister and while it seems to be working for her, it's definitely not for me). I feel and identify very much as male and masculine (though I like to think I'm well-rounded as well!). I wore the silver almost daily for about 3 years, and am glad I trusted my intuition that said it might be an issue.\nAny other advice beyond wearing gold jewelry? Copper, you say, is also feminine due to Venus energy? Would other solar herbs and stones, like frankincense, carnelian...etc be worthwhile as well?\nI'll consider the steel for Mars energy. I could use a little more of the warrior spirit, I think.\nAlso, why is gender a factor in the inner planets but not so much the outer?\nThanks JMG and everyone for these stimulating discussions!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8260026", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, and you can also use martial stones, of course.\n2) I'm far from sure why the inner planets should be so powerfully gendered while the outer planets are not; that's simply the way things seem to work.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8181178", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You've mentioned a few times about a revolution of the living against the dead in Ancient Egypt, can you recommend a written account of this event? It sounds like some quite interesting history.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8183482", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You won't find one, since the people who kept the records in ancient Egypt were from the classes that were most negatively affected by the events in question. Look into the archeology and history of the First and Second Intermediate Periods, and specifically what happened to the property set aside to support offerings for the dead during those periods, and you'll find plenty to study.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8204986", "title": "tired of supporting the dead", "user": "ritaer", "content": "As I read this question and answer it suddenly occurred to me that Henry VIII's dissolution of the monasteries could be seen in a similar light. One of the major tasks of monks was to perform masses for the souls of their wealthy patrons. While this did not involve putting plates of food in tombs or dressing mummies in new garments on a regular basis as in Egypt, Peru and other nations that maintained cults for dead aristocracies, it did mean setting aside money gifts, tracts of land, buildings, etc. for the purpose. Obviously, especially in the early Middle Ages, monasteries served other purposes, including charity to the poor. And Henty and his friends definitely profited from 'privatizing' all that church property. But inequality in death has to rankle when it accompanies inequality in life. Lord Oppressor gets a nice tomb and priests praying for his soul every day. Poor old Father Peasant gets a corner of the churchyard and a share of the All Souls Day prayers. Do you know of any commentary from the time that would support this view?\nRita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8211130", "title": "Re: tired of supporting the dead", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't, but it's a fascinating perspective and worth research.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8181690", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. Under the common attribution of the levels of being to the 4 elements (material / earth, astral / swords, mental / cups, spiritual / wands), is there a particular level of being associated to the quintessence (5th element)?\n2. How does someone get routine practice in astrology? Are there any effective exercises that can be done on a daily basis, other than looking at a new chart every day?\n3. Are you familiar with the works of Origen? He was an early Christian ecclesiastical writer who, despite being enormously talented and having a prodigious work output, was never included in the official club of Church Fathers, mostly because his theology would later be deemed heretical. He advocated for a concept of universal salvation, where all souls would eventually be reconciled with God, including Satan. It's surprising how few Christians are aware of how diverse early theological opinion was, and how varied the interpretations of the significance of Christ was, before the institutional Church tossed everything down the memory hole.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8184250", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I classify the levels differently. For me, it's earth/pentacles/material plane, water/cups/etheric plane, air/swords/astral plane, fire/wands/mental plane, and spirit/Trumps/spiritual plane.\n2) Track transits across your natal chart every morning -- that's what I do. Every day some of the planets in the sky are making aspects to some of your natal planets, and the Moon is whipping through 12° to 15° of arc, hitting various aspects with your natal planets at different times. You can use this to elect good times for doing things -- I submit manuscripts to publishers, for example, when something's making a favorable aspect to my natal Mercury or to the ruler of my 10th house -- and it's also a great way to develop a sense of astrological cycles.\n3) I've read about Origen, but since I'm not a Christian I've never really pursued a study of his work. You're absolutely correct, though, that Christianity was much more diverse then -- and indeed it's been much more diverse all along than the various institutional churches want you to think.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8200122", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) Would it matter if we did it the night before? My morning routine is fairly full right now....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8204474", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, sure. Just do it every day.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8182202", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I’m reading a book called The Qabalistic Tarot by a certain Robert Wang, and it contains the following interesting passage on Tarot divination:\n“The cards [of the Minor Arcana] are rooted in Yetzirah, the world of Angels, as opposed to the Archangels of Briah or the Gods of Atziluth. The cards are Astral Images, illustrating the world of matter below, and symbolically reflecting the worlds of mind and spirit above. For example, the TWO OF WANDS reates to Chokmah in Atziluth, as does the KING OF WANDS. But neither card is precisely the same as the Chokmah in Atziluth upon which one calls with the God Name Yah. The TWO OF WANDS may be said to represent the effect in Yetzirah of the power of Chokmah in Atziluth, as the KING OF WANDS personifies the action of Fire of Fire in Yetzirah. Yetzirah is the Formative World through which higher principles pass down into our lives. It is a world of images reflected from above and below, which explains why the Tarot works so well for divination.”\nDo you agree that the Minor Arcana are “astral images,” rooted in Yetzirah? This idea seems to overturn a lot of what I thought I knew about Tarot divination (yes, this is probably going to happen a lot in studying occultism).\n2. In The Mystical Qabalah, Dion Fortune says concerning astrology:\n“Astrology is so elusive because the uninitiated astrologer works on one plane only; but the initiated astrologer, with the Tree as his ground-plan, interprets on the four planes of the Four Worlds, and the effect of, shall we say, Saturn, is very different in Atziluth, where it is the Divine Mother, Binah, to what it is in Assiah.”\n“The Tree of Life, astrology, and the Tarot are not three mystical systems, but three aspects of one and the same system, and each is unintelligible without the others. It is only when we study astrology on the basis of the Tree that we have a philosophical system.”\nAre you aware of any Qabalistic astrology books or resources? My impression was that Qabalists interpreted astrology pretty much the same way as anyone else.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8184506", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's not one of Wang's better moments. No, I don't agree with him; the minor arcana, like all phenomena, exist in all four worlds.\n2) That was my impression too. The Golden Dawn in its early days had its own system of \"initiated\" astrology, but that worked very poorly, and somewhere in the course of its history the \"initiated\" system got dropped and students just went to work with Alan Leo's very good books on standard astrology.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8197306", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) How about C.C. Zain's (Elbert Benjamin) textbooks?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8204730", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Zain's work is good but it's very much off on its own -- he was passing on (and developing) the system he inherited from the Hermetic Brotherhood of Luxor, which is radically different from the Golden Dawn system. From what I've heard, though, it works quite well, and if that appeals to you, by all means.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8182458", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. Several times in the past, you’ve mentioned that the key to all magic is learning to will a single thing strongly, with complete mental focus, for an extended period of time, and that the majority of people, instead of being conscious and aware of the consequences of their actions, instead go through life half asleep, as if in a daze.\nIn the course of an individual’s magical development, once they wake up and are no longer acting out of blind habit or impulse, are there any general guidelines for how to best choose goals towards which to apply the will, and to determine their worth? I imagine that journaling, meditation, and divination are involved, but does the choice of goals depend solely on a person’s subjective values, or is there some objective hierarchy of goals, with the Great Work sitting at the top and everything else flowing neatly downwards from there? I’m assuming you would personally disapprove of somebody using their newfound magical attainment to watch TV all day, but is such a choice wrong in an absolute sense?\n2. Is there any difference between the application of the magical will and the concept of the ‘flow-state’ as described in the field of positive psychology? For those who are unfamiliar with it, the flow state is most likely to occur when the level of challenge offered by an activity is perfectly matched by the skill level of the participant. When someone is in the flow-state, they describe it as a state of being completely immersed in the activity, ‘in the zone’, to the point where they lose track of time, of the environment, and of themselves. This seems very close to the idea that the will, when properly applied, is effortless. Is the flow state an example of the skillful use of the will, or an unconscious abdication of it?\nI get the impression that ‘using the will’ is akin to being in a self-aware, meditative state 24/7, where the attention is turned inwards on itself, and the magician is constantly monitoring their own state of mind and internal processes. However, I assume even adepts occasionally have moments when they slip into a temporary state of unconsciousness, when they’re absorbed in what they’re doing, and are no longer ‘aware of being aware’. Therefore I suspect that I’m operating under a misconception.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8185018", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In occult theory each soul has a True Will, a basic orientation toward acting in the cosmos, and one of the points of occult training is to get out of the way of that and let it express itself in a balanced and appropriate fashion in the context of one's present incarnation. Meditation, journaling, and divination are among the tools that can be used to do that. Your True Will is not mine, and so there's no one standard for everyone.\n2) I have no idea. I'm not familiar with the state in question.\n3) No, not at all. Nobody can maintain a self-aware meditative state 24/7 without going crazy. When you're good at using your will, you set it in motion and then get out of the way; you live your life, sleep eight hours a night, get lost in a good book from time to time, let yourself go in the arms of your lover or spouse, and so on -- but the whole time the will is in motion, and whenever you reach a situation where doing A will bring you closer to the fulfillment of your will and doing B will take you further away from it, you do A -- very often, instinctively, and sometimes without even noticing it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8191162", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have a will related question. (forewarning incidentally this involves Covid) I don't intend to sound too full of myself so please bare with me. I was volunteering with regular schedule at my kid's school and due to business and being disorganized it was becoming a struggle for me. I came up with a thinking ( I remember thinking of it quite intensely like \"this is what needs to happen\"): \"something needs to change, something needs to happen so I will be relieved of this duty\". Promptly 2 weeks later the quarantine hits and I'm relieved of this very duty. You're probably rolling your eyes: she's delusional thinking her wish willed such large consequence into action . So sure, but it's not the first one, I admit the scale is huge ( but my localized action was covered so to speak) but things like that happened before. It usually involved a focused intention, not really a prolonged thinking, but more a summoned realization of something I really wanted to happen; it is so crystal clear that you feel it like the most truthful realization. It involved people coming into new roles ( mostly minor changes but some big ones as well) or things changing their regular function, like just someone showing up in my life with the exact looks and job I envisioned. Or subjects appearing the next day/ days with the exact features, colors, names I thought of. Usually it's fairly timely too. This happens also in the negative, when I want intensely a situation not to happen, then ( mostly overnight) a completely new situation develops. I recall the negation happens more randomly and the less emotional the intent the better it works. I do not control this \"something\" very well, just sometimes I'm able to catch the focus like that. Seems a type of TSW? I know when it works the feeling is of going into the center of my body but it is not a material place, it feels like folding my thinking inwards.\nIs this just a normal occurrence sometimes for everyone and can I train myself to use it intentionally, how? And should I use it? Some of the consequences were quite significant to my and people's lives ( job loss, marriage .. yep).\nThanks a lot, A.\n(btw, I haven't done the hexagram working yet you suggested for my traffic ticket -still plan to do it but not ready yet with the ritual- but following happened: I thought, again intensely, this citation needs to not go on my record! I thought this few good times contemplating Raphael and some 3 or so weeks later received a check from the city to reimburse a difference of my fine, no letter though. City is shut down right now so cannot verify but I have a feeling that I already forwarded the intention to Raphael, is it possible to work like that? )", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8205242", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a simple but effective way of doing magic. Yes, you can develop it; yes, you can use it -- but be careful with the ethical dimensions, as magical action tends to have instant karma for good or ill.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8207546", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Interesting - I have had some similar experiences, but not as dramatic. A while ago I thought how nice it would be not to need to work - then came the shutdown. A few years ago I read quite a bit and thought about the Antarctic forests of the Eocene, and then got the current job as an antiquarian in a house which is near a patch of forest.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8208058", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you.\nDo you think I could practice it by doing small deeds? And perform a divination first? Or do you have something else in mind?\nBTW at the begin of this year I asked my tarot what would be the theme of this year and it came as \" Five of pentacles\" - well, that was a slam dunk! ( Question: for result of this year it came with \"ace of swords\" - which should mean all kinds of new ideas or realizations, probably of somber kind?)\nSo last week I asked how long the restrictions will last and it said \" three cups\" - which I interpret as 3 Spring months, which would go into May? I wanted to confirm so asked \"are 3 Springs months correct thinking?\" and it came back with Queen of swords and the roses really stood out so I think it will end when the roses start to bloom ( late May, usually June here in PNW). Would you agree?\nAlso I asked if Trump will be reelected ( for fun sort of, I thought he will) - Page of Pentacles - yes, correct?\nMy tarot is very patient with me as you see..", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8211386", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you should certainly start small, and use divination to guide you. The tarot readings seem very much on the mark!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8182970", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few questions:\n1. I know you don't do dream work but I'm betting you know a good book on the subject. What would you recommend?\n2. How long did it take you to finish Hall's Self-Unfoldment system?\n3. If a person were a real glutton for punishment, what old occult work would you say best hides its secrets, while having a nice pay off in the end? And perhaps a related question, what old occult work uses the most tactics in obscuring its treasures?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8185530", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'm sorry to say you'd lose that bet. Anyone else?\n2) Twelve months. I treated it as the 12-lesson correspondence course it originally was.\n3) For the first question, of the ones that I've studied in enough detail to know -- and that's a small fraction of the total literature, of course! -- it would be a dead heat between Hall's\nSelf-Unfoldment\nand George Winslow Plummer's\nRosicrucian Symbology\n(which you can download for free\nhere\n, in case you're interested). As for the second -- well, it would be a book of alchemy, no question. John Dee's\nMonas Hieroglyphica\nis a great example, and so is Fulcanelli's\nThe Mystery of the Cathedrals\n; I've wrestled repeatedly with both of these.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8187578", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "Hah! Even the title of Fulcanelli's book is a clever tactic. If I had come across that in another context I'd never give it a second glance because it sounds like a book on Cathedral architecture.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8188346", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"Fulcanelli\" was very, very good at that. I put the name in quotes because there were several people behind that label, of whom Eugene Canseliet and R.A. Schwaller de Lubicz were the most important.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8192442", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but a few questions about Hall's Self-Unfoldment, if I may: Is the extent of the correspondence course simply the book itself, or is there other equipment required? The book itself only suggests discursive meditation as the practice required to go through it - just wondering if there are any other practices involved in doing that course.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8205498", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'll want a copy of the Knapp-Hall tarot deck -- go to the Philosophical Research Society's website at prs.org to get the New Art Tarot version, which is larger and better printed -- and pay very, very close attention to the booklet that comes with it. Hall liked to squirrel away bits of his practical methods in different places, and his tarot deck is the other half of the method in the book. (Among other things, the trumps are the images you're supposed to contemplate. I assume he passed on that tidbit privately to his more promising students -- that's the usual way that was done.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8209082", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I had a look at the description of that deck on the PRS website. I didn’t realize Hall’s System had to do with the Qabalah. I don’t know if this is a silly question, but are there advantages and disadvantages in Hall’s system versus that of the Dolmen Arch? I guess they are both occult systems that aim towards the same thing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8211642", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hall's system is specifically meditative in nature, and aims entirely toward personal transformation. The Dolmen Arch has a somewhat more magical focus, and also covers a lot more ground -- memory training, subtle energy work, healing, etc.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8220090", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In addition to the other things you outlined, I presume that the Dolmen Arch also includes exercises for personal transformation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8220346", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8192186", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You may want to have a look at Fraser Boa's book called the Way Of The Dream, which is a book length interview with Marie-Louise von Franz about dream interpretation. Von Franz was a student of Carl Jung's, and it's also a good primer on Jung's psychology.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8219578", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "Not OP: Thank you for the recommendation, von Franz is always worth a read and I haven't heard of that book yet.\nMy recommendation would be \"Inner Work\" by Jungian psychologist Robert A. Johnson. I found it very accessible and helpful.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8183226", "title": "Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG. I was going through the archive on the blog and I read somewhere that you've done some sort of workings to prevent your books being pirated. Back before the quarantine I bought the DMH but I was working on an extremely filthy construction site, so I didn't want to bring a book out to get covered with concrete dust and the grime that seems to seep into my fingers even while wearing gloves. So while on lunch break I thought \"Ah, I know! I bet there's a pdf on libgen! I can downloaded a pdf to my phone so I can work on memorizing all the Ogham fews and correspondences during lunch breaks!\"\nI also remember about 3 years back when I was trying to get started studying occult topics I ended up getting burned buying really crappy books so many times I just started pirating books by default and only buying the paper copy if it proved to be a good book, which probably saved my hundreds of dollars. I believe I pirated your Monsters and Green Wizardry books, which is how I was first introduced to your writing. I've since bought the Monsters book (haven't gotten around to buying Green Wizardry, I really should) and I admit I sometimes take a peek at the pirate pdf of a book that I've bought when I'm too excited to wait for it to arrive in the mail.\nI'm worried my dastardly pdf piracy from three years ago and the pirating of books I already own might be bringing down some sort of curse that's gumming up my magical progress, since progress has been slow and frustrating. What are your anti-piracy workings designed to do, exactly? If I want a digital version of a book I already own, should I buy the digital copy again (and if so, where? I don't like Amazon forcing you to use Kindle everything for digital books)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8185786", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's quite simple. The logic behind my working is that anyone who steals one of my books will get no benefit out of it -- since I get nothing from their ownership of the book, neither do they. What you have to do to get out from under the working is simply to buy a copy of the book in whatever format you have it, and delete the stolen one. As for where to buy it, I don't use e-books so don't know where you would go -- someone else might be able to answer that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8187322", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's actually quite fair and merciful (I'm remembering certain \"Left Hand Path\" authors who vowed to curse pirates with sexual impotency and venereal disease).\nTo clarify, if I had a digital copy of the DMH do I have to buy another digital copy, or have I already done that since I own the DMH in paperback format?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8188602", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You need to buy a copy of the e-book and delete the pirated copy you have to release yourself from the effects of the working.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8190650", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've already deleted all the digital copies, and I found you can buy non-Kindle ebooks off Google Books.\nHere's an interesting question though - in the future balkanized Merika many decades after your death, what happens if the publishing house responsible for your books refuses to sell to one of the other balkanized North American states? Presumably the first thought of one of these other states would be to open their own printing presses and just print your books themselves. So would this doom all future residents of the Lakeland Republic if the publishing house is located in the Atlantic Republic and is barred from opening regional branches or selling to Lakeland due to the embargoes?\nTo that end, how are things set up for hundreds and hundreds of years after your death when, for all we know, your books may be dug out of an archeological dig site to be translated for a civilization that has no connection to the rightful seller?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8205754", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Once my copyrights expire, so does the working, so none of that should be any kind of problem.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8207802", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What about the fact Canada's copyright laws (for example) are different, and so it'll be out of copyright here before in the states?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8211898", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Once the copyrights expire, so does the working. Yes, that will happen at different times in different places.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8193466", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n(I am not the OP)\nI too have been using a version that I got over a download site. I should have known better. I have since reading this post bought all your books that\nI read in e-form, deleted my Ebook and hard drive copy. And when I come home I am going to erase the external hard drive safety copy.\nI am sorry an I should do better.\nI very much appreciate your material, and am certainly going to buy more in the future.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8212154", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you. I appreciate that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8195258", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Huh, I had no idea that it was necessary to buy the same format as the pirated copy. A couple years back I had a downloaded copy of the Druidry Handbook and the Celtic Golden Dawn, and I deleted them and bought paper copies. I thought this put me in the clear, but it seems I need to buy the ebooks as well? I'm happy to do so if needed! It would also explain some of the troubles I had with CGD and AODA work!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8212410", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, the issue is that every copy you own and use must be legal. OP was asking whether he could continue to use pirated e-copies when he's bought the books in print format. If you don't own any pirated copies, you're fine. As for the troubles you've had, well, keep in mind that magic is hard work!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8214970", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for the clarification, I'm glad to know that I made things right back then! As for the troubles, realizing that magic is hard work and it will not be easy has been my most valuable lesson learned over the past 2 years. I pushed through my doubts and fears and joined AODA in January, and have chosen to work through the Dolmen Arch for my Druid path work. So this is probably a great time to say thank you for your work that has brought me to this path!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8218810", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. I received a lot of help and guidance in the course of my training and I've always wanted to be able to pay it forward.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8197562", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Did the historical Golden Dawn perform a similar kind of working for the ones who revealed its secret teachings? (I'm thinking about how Crowley's life ended up in misery.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8212666", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They were much nastier about it. In the Neophyte ceremony you willingly opened yourself to a punitive magical current, which would come into effect if you revealed the secrets of the order. Crowley worked hard at making his life a failure, but the punitive current will have helped that process!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8208826", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can \"not benefiting from\" include not reading them? I have also just deleted some pirated editions of your books. Most of them I had never opened except to check they were the right books, right after they downloaded. Another two or three I had only looked at a couple of times or so and never read them all the way through. I guess those are the ones I might have to buy.\nDo they have to be bought in the same format? So if someone pirated an ebook they have to buy an ebook, not a physical book? Does a PDF count as an ebook? I don't know anywhere you can buy PDFs.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8212922", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As long as you no longer own a pirated copy, you can get the same book in any format you like. If you don't plan on making any use of the books you just deleted, don't worry about it -- the point is simply that if you try using the material from a pirated copy, you won't benefit from it.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8218298", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was in the same situation. From then on I just take a picture with my phone of the pages I want to study on the bus or somewhere where I don’t want to take the whole book and delete them when I’m done. Since that is not stealing I assume that is ok.\nJMG, assuming you use a pdf from time to time, maybe for books that have gone out of print or are hard to find. Do you check in a particular way to see if going through the contents is a good idea?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8219322", "title": "Re: Accidental Hamburglar", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, I use PDFs of books that are out of print and out of copyright. I don't have a specific way of checking, other than divination and a certain amount of raw intuition. (And yes, it's okay to take a temporary picture of pages from a book you already own.)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8183738", "title": "Hoodoo Bath", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIt’s been nuts in my life (and no doubt in the lives of others) lately, and I decided my semi-weekly German folk magic practice of pouring a bottle of dark beer into my bath helped, but not enough.  Hoodoo bath time!  Here’s my question:\nThe times I’ve resolved to take a hoodoo bath, the energy around me shifts as soon as I pull out the bucket and start adding the ingredients.  It’s really weird.  Sort of like lifting up a stone in the yard and being amazed at all of the scurrying bugs and worms underneath it.\nWhat is this stuff?  It feels conscious, but I am only vaguely conscious of “it” until I decide to do something about it.  Then it seems to manifest itself.  Like those panicked critters under that stone in the yard.\nThanks for Magic Monday!\nOtterGirl", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8186810", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Your intention is part of what gives the working its power. Once you set your will on doing a hoodoo bath and put that will into motion, the energies start to move.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8198842", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!  You’ve given me a whole new respect for the power of my will.  TSW!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8213178", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"And the will therein lieth, which dieth not. Who knoweth the mysteries of the will, with its vigor? For God is but a great will pervading all things by nature of its intentness, Man doth not yield himself to the angels, nor unto death utterly, save only through the weakness of his feeble will.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8246714", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That’s beautiful.  I expect to refer to it often, so have printed it.  Who is the quote attributed to?  Thanks again!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8253370", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was written by Edgar Allen Poe and attributed by him to Joseph Glanvill, one of the Cambridge Platonists of the 17th century. Poe used it as the epigraph to his story \"The Tomb of Ligeia.\"", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8201914", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maybe the gods are trying to tell you not to pour the beer in the tub and drink it after the hoodoo bath as a reward!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8246970", "title": "Re: Hoodoo Bath", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ha!  You may well be right.  😆", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8183994", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In his work, Carl Jung often talks about the mental life of the ‘primitive’ as compared with that of ‘civilized’ man. The terms have become dated, but I think his point still stands, that those who are less conscious are less conflicted; they have no problems because they live in the moment, immersed in the unconscious, and any difficulties they encounter produce no internal division, which leads to self-doubt and neurosis – this is similar to the mental state of most animals, young children and very elderly people. The modern man, however, is burdened with consciousness, and with that comes the burden of self-awareness, which is described as a curse in the allegorical story of the Garden of Eden.\nIn that view, is the goal of magic to return to this unconscious state, to remove internal division and follow the course of development that Nature has laid down for us? Are we trying to regain the primordial oneness of the Edenic state, or does magic offer the possibility of freedom, of shaping ourselves, if necessary, against the natural flow of things?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8187834", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I always found those comments of Jung's -- and their many equivalents in the writings of other European intellectuals of the same era -- impressively silly. It simply isn't true that \"primitive people\" live in the moment, immersed in the unconscious -- the Australian aboriginal elder assessing the subtle signs that will help him guide his band across a hundred miles of gibber desert to whichever place will have the best food supply that year is using his intellect as well as his intuition; equally, the Kwakiutl matron who can recount with pride her lineage back twenty or thirty generations and the ritual privileges she has inherited from each of her ancestors is hardly lacking in self-awareness!\nFrom the point of view of occult philosophy, certainly, the view we're discussing is utterly wrongheaded. The course of development that Nature has laid down for us leads directly to self-awareness, and the process of losing that self-awareness in late adulthood has a widely used name: senility. The natural flow of things leads us toward greater individualization, greater freedom, and greater creativity -- and it leads people of all cultures there, not just those who belong to soi-disant \"civilized\" cultures.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8235450", "title": "they think different from us", "user": "ritaer", "content": "Jung is not the first or last to attribute different levels of consciousness and mental abilities to non-European peoples. Who recalls \"The Origins of Consciousness in the Breakdown of the Bicameral Mind\" by Julian Jaynes? I never understood the acclaim given it in some parts of the Neopagan community. Yes he argued that peoples of 3000 years ago heard the voices of gods--but he claimed that those voices were messages from one half of the brain to the other. How is that supportive of religion, the idea that gods are real and external to ourselves? Then he develops a theory that the 'breakdown' of this bicameral mind was caused by natural disasters and wars in the Mediterranean cultures. How then do you explain that peoples in other areas, such as the Americas and Australia seemed to develop the same sort of modern mind? The whole thing was logically incoherent. One Big Name Pagan I discussed it with once was very impressed by the information that the San Blas Indians had whale imagery in their art--I don't recall what relevance this had to Jayne's argument, but somehow it mattered. I pointed out that, since the San Blas indians lived on islands off the coast of Panama it would be strange if they did not have whales in their art. As for the notion that monumental projects such as the pyramids could have been constructed by a society in which everyone is getting their own 'voice of god' to follow---you couldn't build a chicken house that way. But Western Civilization, going back to the Romans at least, has a tendency to either romanticize or denigrate other cultures, particularly those that be labeled as primitive. Sometimes we manage to do both at the same time: according to Tacitus those German barbarians are a bunch of lazy drunks, but they are brave and their women are chaste.\nIn addition to a study of history, I would recommend a basic knowledge of cultural anthropology for a serious student of the occult. And not the antique volumes like Bachofen or Lewis H Morgan, just grab a general textbook at your nearest college bookstore.\nRita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8236730", "title": "Re: they think different from us", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, I remember Jaynes. I thought he brought together a great deal of evidence that people in many cultures talked to gods and spirits, and then completely misunderstood it because of his rationalist-materialist prejudices.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8184762", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nAre you familiar with the branch of social and evolutionary psychology called Terror Management Theory (TMT)? It claims that the driving human motivation is the fear and awareness of death, which sets man apart from other animals, and as a result of which we attempt to become “persons of value in a world of meaning.” In order to soothe our fear of death and forget that we are dying animals, we attempt to lead a heroic life in a symbolic world of immortal value, often enacted using ritual, thus explaining the origin of culture, mythology and religion as immortality projects. The theory can of course be criticized for being reductionistic and based in scientific materialism, but empirical studies were done showing that a reminder of death causes an increased attachment to cultural symbols - Americans to the American flag, Christians to the Bible, Jews to the Torah, and so on – so I believe there might be something to it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8188090", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I tend to roll my eyes and walk away when that kind of reductionism gets trotted out. The inventors of such projects never stop to consider that we might actually be persons of value in a world of meaning, and that ritual and symbolism might be means of reminding ourselves of truths rather than a way of constructind a world of fictions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8191674", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the original poster\nThank you JMG for such an elequent answer. That really touched my heart. At a time like this I think that will be a good quote to repeat to myself.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8213434", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8200634", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "They also ignore the fact that plenty of human phenomena become baffling if we accept everyone is terrified of death (ex: ritualized suicides)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8213690", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A good point!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8219066", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What's even more entertaining is that the mainstream media is now trotting out Terror Management Theory to explain why those nasty, deluded, terminally un-hip Deplorables support Trump.\nhttps://news.yahoo.com/pandemic-could-actually-boost-trump-204335992.html", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8219834", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "\"Look at them! There must be something mentally wrong with them -- they've stopped believing the obvious lies we push at them and won't keep doing things that benefit us at their expense! How insane!\"", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8185274", "title": "CNN", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "I got rid of my TV about a decade ago and I am out of the loop, so I didn't realize that Reza Aslan, a self-proclaimed Islamic scholar and CNN personality, achieved infamy when he ate human brains as part of his show Believer in 2017.  Believer was intended to be an Anthony Bourdain tour the world show, but instead of sampling local cuisines, Aslan was to sample local religions.  He ended up hanging out with the Aghori peoples, and I'm sorry to say from the segment I watched, I could tell the leader was not only angry, he seemed possessed.  The Aghori routinely try to gain power by messing with the dead, smearing cremated ashes of people on themselves, and eating brains.\nAslan is now known for spewing Twitter rage.  I believe he's being sued for saying the Covington MAGA kid's 14 year old face was \"punchable\".\nMy question is this: Aslan seems obviously cursed, and the Aghori leader seems to be the one who cursed him.  He lost his job at CNN, became a laughingstock, and now is being sued.  Could he have also cursed CNN?  Their ratings are in the toilet.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-13 05:39 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8188858", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Aslan may be cursed, but it's also quite possible that he's obsessed by one or more evil spirits; the effects are similar. It's also possible that he contracted one of the various nasty neurological diseases you can get from eating human nervous tissue. I would not want to be him.\nAs for CNN, I think that whatever's working through Aslan had to take a number and wait its turn. Too much Trump Derangement Syndrome and a bad case of \"get woke, go broke\" is much closer to the head of the line.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8193210", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When you say Aslan may be obsessed by an evil spirit does that mean the spirit might have started to take an interest in him as a result of contact / eating human brains with the Aghori? So he is unwittingly obsessed rather than deliberately obsessed?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8213946", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "He participated in Aghori rituals and took part in their repellent sacrament. From my perspective, that's tantamount to putting out a welcome mat and leaving the front door wide open to malign spirits. Thus I wouldn't call him unwittingly obsessed. Witlessly obsessed, on the other hand...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8225210", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The segment can be found on youtube. Mr Aslan is clearly very uncomfortable in the situation - one could say he is shaling his pants. He tried to call the thing off and get away but his producer told him to go through with it.\nJust hypothetically: What would be the simplest way to de-obsess him or someone in his situation? I imagine he has no magical training of his own.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8225722", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It would take personal spiritual work on his part combined with a serious ritual of exorcism by a trained professional.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8199098", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If there was a reporter with a regular practice of western magic (daily banishings and so on) would he be safe from curses/spells while doing an interview with these Aghori gentlemen?\nThe reporter in this example would of course not be so daft as to let the Aghori have power over him by verbally giving consent to the status of disciple, let himself be marked with cremation ashes to seal the deal and finally ingest parts of a corpse that Mr. Aghori hands him...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8214202", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It would depend on the relative strength and skill of the reporter and the Aghori guru, but the reporter would have a very good chance of getting away unharmed. On the other hand, as you've noted, willingly participating in their rites is quite another matter.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8229818", "title": "Re: CNN", "user": "lunarapprentice", "content": "You'll want to look up Kuru; that's the famous disease of (I think) New Guinea highlanders who used to eat human brains. It is a human spongiform encephalopathy (as a opposed to the bovine form which got some press a decade or so ago). I'm truly gobsmacked that Reza Aslan or anyone would actually eat human brains (raw I take it, but if Kuru is anything like bovine spongiform encephalopathy, EVEN COOKING won't prevent it.). I'll bet the guy is obsessed, jinxed, sickened, deranged, stigmatized, cursed, possessed and otherwise messed over up one side and down the other, 60 ways from here to eternity. I got chills reading about the guy ['shivers' again].", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8186042", "title": "Gurdjieff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI appreciate your candour in recent MM’s with regard to Aleister Crowley. With that in mind, what is your take on another so-called ‘rascal master’, Gurdjieff, and the Fourth Way Movement that derives from him?\nGurdjieff seems to be gaining in popularity over the last many years through variously the Enneagram, Jacob Needleman, Parabola magazine, Jodorowsky, and even the contemplative Christian renaissance. Within the Christian Centering Prayer movement, Episcopalian Hermit Rev. Cynthia Bourgeault champions Gurdjieff as something of a world messiah and prophesies somewhere that Gurdjieff’s book ‘Beelzebub’s Tales’ will be read as scripture in churches of the future. (Gurdjieff seems to loom larger than Jesus in her own work).\nOn the other hand, a proponent of the Sitra Achra/Reverse Tree describes the Qlippothic intelligence of the 11th Path (to be invoked for the character of a ‘stone-cold vampiric warrior’) as a particular fan of Gurdjieff and Ouspensky’s work.\nElsewhere, Tobias Churton recently wrote of Gurdjieff as promulgating a kind of masonry for the secular intelligentsia. He ends up being a kind of 'Ayn Rand' for the spiritually inclined. Although Gurdjieff’s primary demographic seems to be aristocratically aspirational but his work seems to activate latent narcissistic, even sociopathic tendencies.\nAnd now, a new book by Maronite priest Joseph Azize looks to be attempting to link Gurdjieff’s ideas with the hard-core Eastern Orthodox spirituality of Mt. Athos.\nA lot of the Fourth Way ideas are surprising, striking and maybe even highly useful for confronting the self, but so many of the personalities representing the system come across as aloof, cold and contemptuously elitist.\nThat Gurdjieff is embraced with such enthusiasm by Christians at one end and magicians of darker-hued practices at another is well, curious, to say the least.\nAnd about as likely as if key figures in the church decided that actually Crowley’s a good bet and even has the inside track on spiritual growth.\nPerhaps Gurdjieff’s material is neutral and one makes of it what one wishes/wills. Perhaps it is indeed the real deal and I am missing its innate value.\nWhat sense do you yourself make of Gurdjieff as a spiritual leader and of the Fourth Way as a system?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8189114", "title": "Re: Gurdjieff", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I looked into the Fourth Way at one point, after watching a fine movie version of\nMeetings with Remarkable Men\n; it never really turned my crank, so I never pursued it past reading a few books. I also noticed that it seems to feed the same kind of soaring egomania that a lot of Traditionalism does, and I find that repellent. That said, I'm not particularly well informed on the subject; it simply didn't interest me, and I have a lot of other books by a lot of other occult philosophers to study.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8186298", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I’ve been doing the Middle Pillar every day for the past 4 weeks, and I had the most interesting thing happen up to this point – I nearly fainted! I knew when I started the session that it would be out of the ordinary, because after a bit of experimentation, I found a vocal frequency for vibrating the words of power that caused an inner ear buzz, a humming throughout the body, and a tingling in the extremities, especially in the fingertips, and this seemed to match what several authors said that vibration was supposed to feel like. Anyway, after some preliminary work, which went smoothly, when I got to the Middle Pillar, after visualizing the first sphere and vibrating the divine name, I felt a huge headrush and nearly lost my balance. I pushed through, imagining the spheres and the column of light linking them together as you’re supposed to, until I got to the heart area, where it became overwhelming and I was struggling to stay on my feet. I quickly got through the remaining two spheres and then had to sit down for a couple of minutes to recover. The best way I can describe the “energy” is that it felt similar to what happens when you stand up suddenly after lying down for a long time (this wasn’t the case here, as I had been on my feet for a while with no problems) – a dizziness and disorientation, and something like a subtle electrical current spreading down throughout the body, starting with the scalp.\n2. I imagine that most of the rituals that have been the stock-in-trade of occultism for the better part of a century, like the LBRP and the Middle Pillar, are effective even if you don’t consciously perceive anything, by affecting the subtle layers of the mind?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8189370", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Okay, good. Your next task is to learn how to handle that energy without being knocked down by it. You've reached the point at which the centers are starting to activate; you'll likely find over the next few months that any other magical work you do will be cranking up the volume to 11 or so. Keep at it, and the fun really begins.\n2) Yes, exactly. They also affect the subtle bodies -- the etheric and astral bodies and the mental sheath -- and bring about important changes on those levels which further the work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8199354", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not OP) Can an energy knock-down like this also be expected from the Sphere of Protection?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8214458", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The SoP tends to be a lot gentler, and it doesn't focus as intensely on the midline of the body, but it also has beneficial energy effects on the subtle bodies.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8222906", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(New commentator)\nI've had the experience of being nearly knocked over by the response from some of the elements during the SoP. Is this similar to the OPs discussion, or something else?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8225978", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's similar. While it tends to be a lot gentler, there are exceptions!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8233658", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can attest to this happening with the SOP on a gentler scale. Recently when I am doing the circulation of light, I involuntary am pushed back on my heels and have to resist the subtle urge to fall backwards!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8186554", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG, does the Watcher also come into play in more secular situations?  For example, late at night you come upon a wrecked car and you hear and smell gas dripping.  You call 911.  You can wait at a safe distance, or you can cautiously approach the car to see whether you can get the unconscious driver out before the gasoline ignites and burns him up.  All your life you’ve wanted to make a positive difference.  Is this Situation the Watcher seeing if you REALLY want that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8189626", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You could think about it that way. You can also simply recognize that life throws you choices all the time, and the choice you make determines the person you become, and therefore the future you make for yourself.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8187066", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "emmanuelg", "content": "Hi JMG--\nAfter almost a year of fiddling with it, I have found (or developed?) a basic way to link Geomantic readings with magic squares, and it seems to work.\nCertainly, someone must have done this before, and probably got a lot further than I have, so I'd like to read about that.  Are you aware of any texts that describe the use of magic squares in Geomancy?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8189882", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I know of nothing anybody has done along these lines, so it seems likely to me that you've broken entirely new ground. That's not surprising -- geomancy has been somewhat neglected compared to some other aspects of occult tradition. I'm delighted to hear that you've succeeded and look forward to learning something about your system when you're ready to share it with others.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8237242", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No, there have been other people working on it.\nhttps://digitalambler.com/2019/02/18/on-geomantic-figure-magic-squares/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8247994", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks!  I will read up on it.  Hopefully I can post a summary by next week ;-)\n--Emmanuel G", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8190394", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With occultism being the lonely path, how much of that comes from each side? Is it mainly the occultist starting to feel disconnected from others, or other people sensing something is different about the occultist? What levels does the effect work on? For example is it more social psychology to do with scripts and codes of behaviour, or is it etheric and astral, and people can sense 'a disturbance in the Force'. :) Do you see any similarity between it and how people reacted to your Aspergers?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8214714", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, it's from both sides. As you become more aware of magical realities, a lot of what interests ordinary people starts to become really boring to you, and the things that interest you aren't of interest to them; at the same time, yes, you're no longer giving off the subtle \"one of the herd\" signals, and people begin to shy away. As for what levels it works on, that's a good question I can answer only tentatively, with an \"all of the above.\"\nAs for my Aspergers, that's another good question that's very hard to answer, since I've had both in process since my early teens. I've always been (a) interested in things that bore most people and bored by things that interest most people, and (b) the kind of person who stands out as an odd duck, but how much of that is Aspergers and how much is occultism is very hard to say.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8190906", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the correspondence between etheric/astral/mental and Gwynfydd and Ceugant? That is, does Gwynfydd correspond to the astral? Or is the astral really part of \"our\" world (Abred)? What about the lower astral (\"Hell\")? I assume Ceugant is even higher than the mental, since its unaccesible to everyone.\nTidlösa", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8215482", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The realms of Abred, Gwynfydd, and Ceugant aren't planes of being, they're states of the individual spirit. A dweller in Gwynfydd lives in the same world and functions on the same planes as a dweller in Abred, he just does it in a very different way. Ceugant is also a state of being, one that's only accessible to deity, and a deity also lives in the same world and functions on the same planes as the rest of us -- again, in a very different way.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8217786", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Even if Ceugant is not accessible for us mortals, still, is there any way to get a glimpse of it - like the Henosis experience in Neoplatonism?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8218554", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, but we can rise higher and higher through the Circle of Gwynfydd, experiencing ever greater levels of wisdom and love. Ceugant -- the term means \"the empty circle\" -- is at infinite distance above us; we know it's there and we can always get closer to it, though we can't reach it.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8191418", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "arethinn", "content": "Greetings JMG,\nI am almost never online during the period where it's allowed to make Magic Mondays comments, so I just want to slip in quickly and say, thanks for doing this. I often read everything all the way through (except advice about geomantic readings, which go right over my head) later in the week because  I'm not online in the right timeframe to ask my own questions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8215738", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8192698", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is pathworking, and what is the purpose of doing it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8217018", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Pathworking, also known as active imagination, might best be described as the art of focused, meditative daydreaming. In the standard sort of Pathworking, you go on an imagined journey with a specific starting point -- say, a Tarot card, which you imagine becoming a portal that opens onto the scene shown in the card. You step through the portal, wander through the landscape, talk with the beings you encounter there, and then return.\nLike most magical disciplines, Pathworking has several purposes. It's a great way to strengthen your imagination and mental focus, of course. Crucially, though, your imagination is one of the ways that you interact with the astral plane, and with practice, the beings you encounter are, shall we say, less imaginary than they look; they know things you don't and can pass those things on to you. You also learn to attune yourself to the subtle energies of whatever is the focus of your Pathworking, and if you also meditate on the things you encounter in Pathworkings -- and you should always do this -- the result is a great increase in your capacity to tap into those same energies in magical workings of other kinds.\nOh, and if you have any interest in writing fiction, it's extremely useful. I don't have to invent characters and try to figure out what they do and say; I meet them in my imagination and let them do what they do!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8221626", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "I started pathworking on the tarot this past week and was wondering. Should I let it build itself without any conscious effort from my part or should I think about it more concretely like in discursive meditation — trying to relate the images that pop with the whole and discard the ones that drift too much from the subject?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8226234", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Let it build itself. Then take copious notes, and meditate on everything over the next several days.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8192954", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "When you began practising magic, did you still live at your parents' home? How went practising ceremonial magic over with them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8217274", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I lived with my mother when I first started; she was rarely at home and probably wouldn't have noticed if I'd taken up breeding polar bears. When I moved in with my father and stepmother most of a year later, they figured it was just a phase and rolled their eyes -- they did that a lot, and with good reason! I made sure not to do anything involving magic that would annoy or bother them, and so it never became an issue.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8193722", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you know of a method to keep the cardinal directions available to you at all times, as per the way the Australian Aborigines seem to be able to do so?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8217530", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I don't. That would be very useful.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8222394", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I do the SoP, and now if I close my eyes I can use the visualizations: oh, I'm facing earth, that means this is north. It's just a rough approximation, and I don't know how I set it up, nor how to use it, but it does seem quite reliable.\nHave you tried anything like that? I figure you could probably work with it much more than a novice like me could.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8226490", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I don't get the same effect, so it may be something specific to your subtle bodies.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8193978", "title": "Amulets", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I bought some ancient Egyptian amulets online.  How do I consecrate them to renew their protective powers?\nI do the SoP using Celtic deities- is there any conflict between that and having Egyptian amulets? I presume not as they are not the jealous God Jehovah?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8218042", "title": "Re: Amulets", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "At sunrise, burn some frankincense and pray to the Egyptian gods who are associated with the amulets, asking them to bless and empower the amulets. Then hold each amulet in the incense smoke, turning it around several times so it's touched by the smoke over its entire surface. That should do a good basic job.\nThere are old connections between the Celtic and Egyptian traditions. Did you know that beads from Egypt were found buried at Stonehenge? Most pagan deities work well together, but those work together more smoothly than most.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8222650", "title": "Re: Amulets", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"There are old connections between the Celtic and Egyptian traditions.\"\nHmm... I have some questions about that:\n1) Is that connection related to Atlantis legends?\n2) Druids' headdress looks very similar to that of Egyptian priests. Is it due to that connection?\n3) Is Thoth related to Tuatha de Danann?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8226746", "title": "Re: Amulets", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's what the traditional lore claims.\n2) No, what happened was that after the original Golden Dawn blew up in political infighting in 1900, a lot of former GD members joined Druid orders because the British Druid scene was very quiet and non-political in those days. Sometime after that, Druids decided to try a variant on the nemyss, the standard Golden Dawn headgear (which the GD borrowed from the Egyptians), and they found it made a really good head covering for outdoor ritual -- you can pull the ends forward and keep your neck warm, or push them back and direct any cool breeze to the back of your neck! (I can vouch for this.) The end result, of course, was...\n3) Nope. \"Tuatha\" means \"people;\" the Tuatha de Danaan are the people of the goddess Danu.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8194234", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nSince the grail is a feminine symbol, does the grail quest of knights in Medieval romances have anything to do with \"anima\" in Jungian psychology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8220602", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly interpret it that way if you like. The Grail is considerably more than a symbol of one gender, though.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8194746", "title": "LBRP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Recently, I had an odd experience while performing the LBRP, which I've been doing for about 3 years.  When tracing the white light from the center to begin the Pentagram, I felt the word \"gold\" and the light changed from white to gold, and I've been performing it that way since, with gold light joining the blue flames instead of the white.  The blue flames have sometimes become tinged with green, as well.  Is there someone associated with these colors I should know about?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8220858", "title": "Re: LBRP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hard to tell just from the colors. Keep listening and see if you get any more instruction of the same kind.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8195514", "title": "Gardening on church property", "user": "daveotn", "content": "We've expanded our garden this year after a friend of a friend offered us the use of her property (we've filled our own backyard to overflowing already). The property in question currently hosts two small retail businesses, but in the 1950s it was a church - and it's still visibly a church, with the classic white steeple architecture common in American Protestantism. I didn't recognize the denomination - one of those tiny American churches that come and go, not any sort of larger group I'd heard of.\nIs there anything I should be aware of gardening in the back of a deconsecrated church? This is definitely not Secrets of the Temple-type medieval architecture, but I figured it doesn't hurt to ask. (And I am planning to look into the town records just to ensure it really is a random tiny Protestant sect and not a cover operation for the Temple of Dagon or anything really interesting :) )", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8221114", "title": "Re: Gardening on church property", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Unless it was the Esoteric Order of Dagon or something else really interesting, there should be no issues. What side of the church (north, south, east, west) is your garden on?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8224698", "title": "Re: Gardening on church property", "user": "daveotn", "content": "The garden is on the east side of the church and, although the building isn't cruciform, it does roughly follow the classic pattern of having the main door facing west so the congregants would have sat facing east.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8227258", "title": "Re: Gardening on church property", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fair enough. Keep me posted if the garden turns out to be unusually productive!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8195770", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Happy MMonday, Mr. Greer\nA somewhat off-beat situation and question: We live in a century-old farm house situated on a 50-acre spread. One 'rite of spring' is the resurrection of houseflies in most of the rooms.\nI usually practice the SOP in an unoccupied bedroom. One day last week I took advantage of the weather and practiced outside i.e. I did not enter the room that day.\nNext day, when I entered the room, I found about 40 dead flies on the floor and the windowsill; the sill situation not unusual.\nThe unusual part was, every single fly in the room was dead; and the flies on the floor were scattered from one side of the room to the other, looking for all the world as if they had been struck down in flight and lay where they fell.\nWe've been here 20 years, can't recall seeing this before. We looked at mundane explanations e.g. carbon monoxide, but we have detectors in every room. The overnight temperature was maintained mid-60's, and we don't use pesticide sprays.\nI've used that room for practice for more than a year, are you aware of anything similar happening as a result?\nbest regards", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8215226", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not JMG)\nDo you live in Amityville?  😄", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8223418", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "No, that would be my in-laws' place ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8250042", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "😄\nThat is odd—even stumped our favorite Druid of Mighty Wisdom.\nThe only thing I can think of is, do you have an exterminator come for anything else, and, if so, might he have zapped the flies while he was there?", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8221370", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's really quite strange. No, I haven't encountered anything like that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8228282", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "OK thanks,\nFreaked my wife out a bit, she is aware of my practice, and this is the only room this odd thing event occurred in. Maybe the spiders have had enough of the 'patiently waiting in a web' bit, and are making a move.\ncheers!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8196026", "title": "SOP and Meditation posture: a follow up", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey there JMG\nThank you for your response last week on visualising the rotating SOP and on the sitting posture. I couldn't respond then due to time differences:\n1. Regarding trouble getting comfortable in the seated posture, you say to stick to it like grim death. Challenge accepted. I've been grim-deathing it this week and will keep at it. The discomfort is fairly strong and tends to shift around my body like water in a barrel - now here, now there. I try to open myself to the sensations, and it feels like a good practice that way.\nWould it be taking it too easy to leave the  theme-meditation as long as necessary, until things have much calmed down?\nSucceeding at this would mean a lot to me. My introduction to this whole subject as a teenager was reading R.A. Wilson's Cosmic Trigger and I think it's in that book he says: \"Choose a posture, any posture. It will soon turn into Hell\". Or maybe that was him quoting Crowley...\n2. I think I do get how the 3 SOP rotations combine in one sphere; I've done the ball-exercise to check it out. What I'm having trouble with is that the DMH instruction says each rotation should  speed up to a blur before starting the next. If, for example I keep them all slow instead, the triple combination is clear. I have tried it like this, only speeding all 3 up together at the end. Is this acceptable, or less powerful?\nThe specific difficulty I have with DMH instructions is that if rotations 1 and 2 are spinning QUICKLY around me, how to add SLOW movement of rotation 3 to that.\n3. I've been experimenting with different  banishing imagery. If the body is already filled with coloured light brought in via the solar plexus, would there be any problem symbolically with using its removal to signify banishment of unbalance: for example the blue light draining downwards through the body into the water element?\nMany thanks for the assistance,\nMorfran", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8221882", "title": "Re: SOP and Meditation posture: a follow up", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That was classic RA Wilson; he got the idea from Crowley, who got it from an American physical culture teacher (most likely Webster Edgerly, who published extensively on the subject under the nom de plume Edmonde Shaftesbury). It's true, and yes, you can focus on the posture until it eases up for you, and then proceed.\n2) That's perfectly acceptable.\n3) Yes, that would work well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8196282", "title": "Guns and magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Could there be a magical or occult explanation for the high level of firearms violence and armed crime in the United States, compared to other countries with high per capita levels of firearms ownership (Switzerland etc).\nObviously there has to be some kind of cultural difference, plus the US is by far the largest and most diverse country with high rates of firearms ownership, but still?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8227770", "title": "Re: Guns and magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't think there's any need for an occult explanation. You find high rates of firearms violence and gun-related crimes in Latin America and Africa too -- a reminder that the US, for all its current wealth and political clout, is a Third World nation.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8196538", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI've heard of a legend about a 9th century Egyptian alchemist and Sufi master - Dhul-Nun al-Misri. According to the legend he founded a secret society which was called al-Banna (the Builders), based on ancient Egyptian mystery teachings, disguised under Sufism; it is also claimed that the roots of Freemasonry can be traced back to this society. Does this have any grain of truth?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8228026", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Freemasonry started off as a builders' guild in early modern Scotland, which inherited a few scraps of secret knowledge from the Knights Templar.  Once the builders' guild started morphing into modern Freemasonry in the mid-17th century, some of the people involved in it went hunting for scraps of lost traditional lore, and some really odd things ended up in the mix as a result. It wouldn't surprise me at all if some Sufi lore made that leap, along with the rest of the lumber that got hauled in. The roots of Freemasonry run in many directions, though, and at most, that's just one of them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8196794", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings Mr. Greer,\nDo you think that string theory is compatible with occult philosophy?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8228538", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'd have to ask a qualified physicist who's also an occultist. I'm the latter but not the former.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8197818", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hot weather makes me lethargic. When I remember very hot days while invoking Fire in the SoP, I feel this lethargy for a short time too, more so now as the weather is getting hotter again. Lethargy seems contrary to many of the associations of fire: creativity, energy etc. Do I need to do anything differently?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8228794", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nope. Your body responds to heat the way it responds to heat; don't try to tell it to behave in accordance with someone else's symbolism!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8198074", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can't believe I never thought to ask this before, but are there occultist rappers and hip hop?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8229050", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It seems likely, since the African-American community has some very rich occult traditions, but I'm not into either genre of music so couldn't tell you for sure.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8198330", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "violetcabra", "content": "Recently I wrote up a critique of Amy Hale's essay \"The Pagan and Occult Fascist Connection and How to Fix It\" on my blog:\nhttps://violetcabra.dreamwidth.org/40241.html\n.  While writing up the critique and giving her essay a few close readings I was astounded by two things, one I address fully in my critique and one that I address much less:\n1) the first is how totalitarian the implications of the essay are. This I detail in my essay.\n2) the second is how incoherently she wrote the essay.  The ideas she discusses are extremely jumbled together, so much so in fact that I struggled to construct coherent arguments regarding her essay as a totality, rather than in parts.  She has nearly no references for any of her assertions, and her assertions are extremely broad as well as dramatic.  She just sort of piles up assertions on top of each other, as if it's common sense that fascists are slithering around behind the scenes everywhere, as if everyone already agrees with the basic premises.  Reading it without sharing these basic premises, I found it hard to even keep up with her arguments from authority and uncited assertions of dubious facts!\nIf I may, I'm curious your thoughts on this twin tendency towards demagogic, totalitarian thinking mixed together with frothy paranoid incoherence.  Is this just the sort of thing you discussed in \"The Flight to the Fringes, And What Waits There\" alongside \"The Next Twilight of Environmentalism\"?  I talked with a leftist friend the other day who started going on about \"ecofascists\" and praising antifa's doxxing campaigns and I felt that I saw something similar to what's going on with Hale's essay.  From my perspective, it's all so very strange, and even uncanny, to see folks who were anarchist free-spirits one day turn to totalitarian patterns of thinking, acting as if the political sphere of life *must* engulf all other spheres combined with a sloppy but vigorous attitude towards rooting out dissenters and deviationists.\nBasically my question is what are your thoughts on what these trends mean and whither they lead?  It seems to me that this could all go along a variety of different paths of potentiality, and so I'm curious what you see as the most likely.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8230074", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I may be wrong, of course, but my take is that it's a blend of frantic desperation and \"what you contemplate, you imitate.\" They've been screaming about imaginary fascists for so long that they've unconsciously transformed themselves into what they think they're opposing, thus the totalitarian thinking, and they're melting down because their entire worldview is being disconfirmed around them, thus the incoherent yelling.\nCentral to the entire mentality of the privileged left is the conviction that they are (a) the good people, whose moral virtue makes them superior to everyone else; (b) the people who make things happen, in a world in which all other beings and things are purely passive and can only play the roles the good people assign them; and (c) the wave of the future, whose triumph is inevitable because they're virtuous and creative and active while everyone and everything else lurches through mechanical routines. At this point all three of those basic beliefs of theirs are cracking right through the middle. It's very difficult to think clearly when you're in the kind of emotional agony that comes from being forced to realize that you (a) aren't the paragon of virtue you thought you were, (b) don't have the power over the world you thought you did, and (c) aren't going to get the future you convinced yourself you deserved, all at once.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8232378", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "violetcabra", "content": "Many thanks for your considered response!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8251578", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "I was sympathetic to Anarcho-Capitalism for a while and noticed that for a group I thought should be rational and undogmatic they had the same hang-ups as any other ideologues. They practically worshipped Murray Rothbard and many couldn't process the glaring flaws in Hoppe.\nJMG is no doubt right that the shrillness is from them watching their dreams die but they were authoritarian all along. It was simply less obvious.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8198586", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In DnD games wizards can't cast spells while wearing armour. In the real world would wearing a suit of full plate have any effect on your ability to do magic? What about a modern bomb squad suit? :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8230330", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Gary Gygax et al. put in restrictions like that to keep some character classes from mopping up the table with other character classes. Since we don't live in a D&D game, don't worry about them.\nHold it -- was that the rattle of a d6?  Watch for wandering monsters while I venture down the corridor...  ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8199610", "title": "Geomancy question", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI was practicing Geomancy using your \"Art and Practice of Geomancy\" book for about a year but only with shield charts. Lately I moved on to house charts and found them much richer, quite a new experience.\nHowever, I'd like to ask about a divination I did using the house chart: we moved to another region last summer to prepare for the Long Descent - a decision that proved none too early... now we're in a rental apartment, however, and would love to find either a house with a garden or just a garden plot.\nMy question was: \"How will we find our garden\", the mothers were Caput Draconis, Puer, Puella and Rubeus.\n1) Is a \"how\" question appropriate for Geomancy at all? I found the result very difficult to decipher and maybe the question was inappropriate?\n2) Land and agriculture are a 4th house and Rubeus is unfavorable, Caput Draconis favorable for starting something new. I read it as unfavorable but we'll start something better. Would you agree?\n3) Rubeus passes to the 12th house so there is a conjunction with the 1st house. Does this mean that something unpleasant and possibly violent prevents our acquiring our garden but something better (because of the conjunction) will come our way without our doing (since it's the figure of the quesited that passes, not of the querent)?\nThank you sincerely for all your help in this time! I'm sure it's the SOP and meditation that is keeping me sane. Also, the book tips in this forum are much appreciated: I keep Epictetus' Enchiridion in my pocket because of a comment of yours lately and it's a wonderful to meditate upon while wondering what my fellow humans are currently doing out there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8230586", "title": "Re: Geomancy question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) \"How\" questions are very difficult to interpret from a geomantic chart until you get a lot of experience. Still, this one's readable.\n2 & 3) The answer to a house chart always starts with the presence or absence of a mode of perfection. Since you've got a conjunction joining your significator to that of the quesited, you know that you will find a garden; since the significator of the quesited passes to make that conjunction, you know that you don't have to take action -- that the garden, in effect, will come to you. Since the significator of the quesited is Rubeus, you know that something about the garden will relate to the symbolism of Rubeus. It may be as simple as finding a house with a bright red door that happens to have a nice back yard suitable for a garden. Keep an eye out for Rubeus-like things and see what comes your way.\nGlad to hear you're finding the Enchiridion useful! It got me through some very tough times.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8199866", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If somebody uses evil magic, other people treat them like someone who uses evil magic, even if they have no conscious knowledge of that fact. Can that effect carry over into evil magician's next life, so even though they now have no idea about any kind of magic, people still reject them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8230842", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, but there are also a lot of other reasons why someone can be rejected by lots of people. In my case, for example, it was Aspergers syndrome -- other kids didn't want anything to do with a geeky, bookish kid with few social skills.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8250810", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Preach it, brother.  1984 could be staged as a high school play with hardly any studying of lines.  Most of the Party types could just play themselves.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8200890", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm reading descriptions of \"vibration\", and have made a link to something I do all the time: I get the same sensation described as vibration when I play the saxophone. Certain notes have a stronger effect, and with practice I've gotten better at generating it. I have no idea how to create it with my voice yet, but even the more complex tasks, like controlling the location of the resulting sensation with the saxophone is easy enough to do.\nMy question is thus this: do you know of anything which discusses the link between vibration and music?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8231866", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of anything like that, and it's unfortunate -- that's research that needs to be done.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8233146", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you know good sources which discuss vibration in detail then? Sadly I'm working with brief descriptions and not too much detail.\nSince I've discovered the effect, I figure I might as well see how far I can go with it, and so in ten years or so I'll be back, [or on whatever forum you're hosting then] with some answers.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8236986", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The brief descriptions you have are probably pretty much the same as the ones I have. That's something else that needs much work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8249018", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Okay, in that case, I have my work cut out for me!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8201146", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWhich books would you recommend to learn about the occult symbolism in Waite-Smith tarot deck? Is \"Seventy-eight Degrees of Wisdom\" a good start for that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8232122", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of the classics, yes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8201402", "title": "Kundalini?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For the last six months or more Psyche has been doing a nightly psychic centre clearing/opening process on me, sending energy down through my crown. It's been very tough, painful, nausea-inducing, dizzying, occasionally emotional, but it got progressively easier over time. I trusted that she was helping because I could feel the difference in energy in my LBRP and Central Ray exercise, I could feel the middle pillar clearly, although it felt sort of raw and cold and like a vacuum.\nAnyway, the last couple of weeks I've had trouble getting to sleep which is very rare for me, and felt hot. Then last night I woke up in the middle of the night with a ball of heat and pressure at the base of my spine. I drank some water and made myself eat some ham, but it didn't go away and kept me awake for ages. After a while it moved up my spine a bit just like the snake feeling people describe but only as far as my shoulder blades. The crown of my head felt pressure too but it was cool and blue, which was a nice relief from the heat. Eventually the heat must have chilled out and I fell asleep again. It's still there all day today, and my spine feels kind of tired like it had a workout.\nWhat I'm wondering is, would it ok to just let it do its thing? I asked Psyche to protect me during it because I don't want my nervous system fried or my life turned upside down like I read happens to some people. I kind of trust that she's the one setting this in motion and so it must be ok. I haven't done any practices other than the CGD, where I'm at the Water-Fire pathworkings. I've never done any kind of yoga or kundalini exercises.\nAlso, why is it going up through/around my spine when the middle pillar is more in front of the spine and does that matter? I tried to redirect it that way at one stage and it worked a little bit - it went briefly to what I think is the heart centre and made me laugh!\nThank you,\nDot.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8232634", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, and letting it do its thing is exactly what you should do. Spontaneous kundalini experiences happen tolerably often, and not just to people who are doing the yogic practices that are meant to cause it. Trust the one who's guiding you, and let it unfold.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8235962", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Cool, thank you. I was realizing after I posted that  I have no idea how to stop it even if I wanted to!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8238010", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP; if you get a spontaneous kundalini experience, are you supposed to stop doing magical practice?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8245434", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, just keep up your current practices unless you find that your practices cause problems.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8251066", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I should be mopping the bathroom, or frying an egg, or some such mundane task, what do I do if my kundalini suddenly awakens?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8253626", "title": "Re: Kundalini?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Relax. It's not an instant process. It helps if you can take some time, when the sensations are very strong, to flop on the bed or a comfortable chair and let yourself go as limp as you can manage.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8201658", "title": "Hail Mary or Common Prayer for non-Christian Druids", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I read an article written by a gentleman who got ventilated and he mentioned he was delirious heading into it so the only thing he could mentally do was repeat the Hail Mary over and over.\nHe mentioned that he slept peacefully during ventilation and did not remember any dreams, though some have reported bad dreams or hallucinations in that time. It reminded me of the occult view of the astral plane after death. I wonder if the Hail Mary going into it helped him.\nI was also pleasantly surprised to then find out the author is gay. All gay Catholics I know left their faith once they realized they were gay, as if the only option for LGBT people is atheism or agnosticism. I hope in the future that LGBT people of any faith will realize they can continue their faith individually even if the church they grew up in is full of unaccepting people.\nThis got me thinking of what a Revivalist non-Christian Druid might repeat. Is there a Book of Common Prayer for us? The only prayer I know is the Universal Druid Prayer. Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8232890", "title": "Re: Hail Mary or Common Prayer for non-Christian Druids", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd repeat the Universal Druid Prayer. No, there isn't a prayer book for us yet; that's a project someone will have to take on one of these days.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8240314", "title": "Re: Hail Mary or Common Prayer for non-Christian Druids", "user": "readoldthings", "content": "jmg__\nI was going to post a couple of prayers I've put together (to Sul and Hesus, specifically). However, they both and especially the one to Hesus in particular uses phrases drawn from your published work, and some that have only appeared in material you've made available to the DOGD. I did this for two reasons-- 1. In order to tap into the \"track in space\" created by people using and thinking about those phrasings and 2. Because you're one of the only sources for information on the Druid gods out there! But, because of this, I wanted to check with you before posting.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8245690", "title": "Re: Hail Mary or Common Prayer for non-Christian Druids", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Please do post them, and thank you for asking.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8249274", "title": "Re: Hail Mary or Common Prayer for non-Christian Druids", "user": "readoldthings", "content": "Hi! I don't know if this will be of interest to you, but two of the gods to whom I have a particularly strong devotion are Hesus and Sul. Both of them are strongly associated with healing. I put together the following prayers to them:\nTo Sul, who is also named Sulis--\nHail Sulis, Lady of the Threefold Fire.\nTo thee I give thanks for the fire that descends from the heart of the Sun and warms the face of the living Earth.\nHail Sulis, Lady of the Threefold Fire.\nTo thee I give thanks for the fire that rises from the heart of the Earth and warms the waters of the healing springs.\nHail Sulis, Lady of the Threefold Fire.\nTo thee I give thanks for the fire that radiates from the hearth, and warms our homes and gladdens our hearts.\nHail Sulis, Lady of the Threefold Fire.\nHoly Lady Sul, for all thy gifts and blessings I thank thee and bless thee in return. May  I walk in thy divine hand this day and always.\nAWEN\nTo Hesus, a triadic litany--\nHesus, chief of tree spirits,\nR. Be with me (or us) this day, Oh God.\nThou who art chief of the tree spirits, R.\nThou who sit at the first fork of the sacred oak, R.\nThou who art master of the green world and its wisdom, R.\nHesus, chief of tree spirits, R.\nThou who art the Mighty One in manifestation, R.\nThou who art the foster-son of Ced the Earth Mother, R.\nThou who draw upon the healing power of the Cauldron of Ceridwen, R.*\n(*Alternatively, Thou who art friend to Coel, Lord of the Life Force and Sulis, Lady of the Healing Springs, R.)\nHesus, Chief of Tree Spirits, R.\nHesus, guide of Druids, R.\nHesus, patron of Healers, R.\nHesus, teacher of Wisdom, R.\nHesus, Chief of Tree Spirits, R.\nAWEN\nAs I noted above, many of the specific phrases and divine titles here come from JMG's work. The refrain, \"Be with me this day, Oh God\" in the Hesus prayer is something I've seen in other pagan prayers, especially those composed by the person who runs Hearthfire Handiworks, which is also an excellent source for pagan devotional material which might interest you. If so, take a look here:\nhttps://www.etsy.com/shop/HearthfireHandworks", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8202170", "title": "Swedenborg", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do you think Swedenborg's writings? Are they anything you've looked at much?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8233402", "title": "Re: Swedenborg", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I generally don't have a lot of interest in all the many books by visionaries that claim to reveal the truth about the cosmos; there are lots of them, they all contradict one another, and I'm much more interested in seeing for myself than in taking someone else's word for it. I've read a little Swedenborg, just as I've read bits of OAHSPE and the Urantia Book, but not much in any such case.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8202426", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In practical work where angels are invoked, is it safe to assume they’ll refuse to help us with anything that adversely affects the balance of the Universe?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8222138", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For that matter, when we really get down into the core of things, is there really any such thing as action that adversely affects the balance of the Universe? As it seems an incontrovertible law that for every action there is a compensating reaction. Though I suppose it might be a more complicated and time-costly process to compensate for certain things... but this makes the distinction between 'balanced' and 'unbalanced' action one of degree, not kind.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8234170", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good! Angels always carry out what the monotheist faiths call the will of God; you invoke them when you want to align yourself more closely with one or another aspect of that will. For example, it is in keeping with the divine will that human beings shall become more loving; if you want to become more loving and lovable -- and that's the only really effective love spell -- you invoke Haniel, the archangel of Venus, and ask her help. Things then happen. If you try to invoke her for something that isn't in keeping with the divine will, good luck.\nAs for the balance of the universe, excellent! Nothing you can possibly do can unbalance the universe. That balance can work in your favor, though, or the opposite. That's what karma is about -- the universe balancing itself with perfect grace, and in the process sending you into better or worse experiences.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8250298", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is Haniel the angel of Venus like Michael’s the (arch)angel of God, or is Haniel  a synonym for Venus?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8254138", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Haniel is the archangel of the planet Venus; Michael is the archangel of the Sun. Both of them, in Jewish and Christian belief, are servants of God.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8202682", "title": "Video on how to vibrate sounds", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "I'm a music teacher, and one of my teaching subjects is voice, so this is me demonstrating how to vibrate a sound.  I managed to sneak in vibrating the word \"Awen\" towards the end of the video.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H7hOUkJzcCM&feature=youtu.be\nHope this helps.  When I do the Sphere of Protection (SoP), I sing the beginning part known as the Elemental Cross and then also vibrate the names of the gods as they come up.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H7hOUkJzcCM&feature=youtu.be", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8202938", "title": "Learning to read at Waldorf school", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good morning JMG,  No question at the moment, rather I wanted to comment on a question from last MM about Rudolf Steiner’s ideas about learning to read.  I wasn’t able to read MM until we’ll after the doors slid shut :)\nI am no authority! but both my daughters attended Waldorf school from kinder through 6th grade (not in the US where one must be very wealthy indeed to afford Waldorf school).  There is a year between kinder and first grade they call pre-first (age 6) where the students learn all the letters of the alphabet and the sounds they make (in English and Spanish in this case) and how to write them. So in first grade (age 7) when they learn to read, all these puzzle pieces of reading seem to come together rather effortlessly.  My daughters learned to read in Spanish before English as it is far easier to decipher from sounds. The goal here seemed to be not to just teach kids how to read but to be good readers and to enjoy reading.  Waiting until 7 seemed to work out well. So perhaps they do need to make physiological connections in their brains before they are ready.\nAs for myself, I also taught myself to read well before kinder...but I never forced my kids just because I did it.  And JMG’s comment about how learning to read super early may have some downsides certainly gave me some things to ponder!\nYears of observing parents foisting things on very young children and babies like reading and math seem to always have more to do with the egos of the parents than the welfare of the children.  The end result is usually very insecure, nervous children who think they are losers who can never live up to expectations.  Let kids and babies be kids and babies!\nHope everyone is enjoying a productive day!     SundaraYogaShala", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8234426", "title": "Re: Learning to read at Waldorf school", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this! I appreciate the data points.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8203194", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If an imbalance of solar energy leads to ego inflation, does an imbalance of telluric energy lead to ego deflation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8234682", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, it leads to ego disintegration.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8239034", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is that a bad thing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8254394", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Visit a nursing home and spend some time around somebody with advanced Alzheimer's if you want to know what it looks like.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8241850", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are the signs of ego disintegration?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8254650", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "See my comment to the commenter above.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8203450", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you \"demagnetize\" your second-hand books? I came across this while reading Fortune's psychic self-defense, itself a second-hand book. Oh. I've since put the book down. Difficult to put it outside right now. Any suggestions? A book banishing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8234938", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If they feel as though they need it, I trace a banishing pentagram over them.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8248506", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not JMG.\nThe vast majority of my second hand magic-related books give me no problems. However, on one notable occasion the night after bringing a second hand book home, I awoke to a \"night terror\" in which I saw a black cloud hovering around my bookcase.\nI put the book on my altar, performed the Lesser Banishing ritual of the Pentagram, and sprinkled the cover with water with words to the effect of \"let this book be purified of any ill influence clinging to it.\" No problems sense.\nBut again, I don't do it unless there's a problem and they rarely occur even after getting several shelves of second hand occult books.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8206010", "title": "Geomantic Figures", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How do you pronounce the names of the sixteen figures? Thank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8235194", "title": "Re: Geomantic Figures", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In Latin?  This is the usual pronunciation these days.\nPuer POO-er\nAmissio ah-MISH-ee-oh\nAlbus AL-bus\nPopulus POP-uh-lus\nFortuna Major for-TYOO-na MAY-or\nConjunctio con-YOONK-tee-oh\nPuella poo-ELL-ah\nRubeus roo-BAY-us\nAcquisitio ak-wi-ZISH-ee-oh\nCarcer CAR-ser\nTristitia tris-TISH-ee-ah\nLaetitia lay-TISH-ee-ah\nCauda Draconis COW-dah dra-CON-is\nCaput Draconis CAH-put dra-CON-is\nFortuna Minor for-TYOO-na MINE-or\nVia VEE-ah", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8206266", "title": "ghosts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG-\nI have a question about for lack of a better word, ghosts, former humans hanging around some particular place. I recently had some encounters with one, strong smell of cigarette smoke indoors at the place far removed from anyone smoking and some other little things that I consider markers of TSE (This Stuff Exists). Anyway, this particular spirit did not seem malevolent or have any intentions toward me or my family at all. It just seemed to like pacing up and down its former porch (now living room) smoking.\nI've been a GD practitioner for about four years, banishing daily, twice daily of late, so I wasn't particularly concerned about it too much, but it got me thinking, what if this place I was staying in were actually a place I had purchased or was living in long term... what's the right course of action with regard to the dead that want to hang around for some reason? I did talk to it, asked if it needed help in any way, but I did not really receive a clear answer (in the back of my mind I thought about your suggestion that one not work too much with the dead, so I didn't push it).\nBut it got me thinking about what should one do? I know what I would do if it were my relative, but it's not, so what would be the right course of action magically speaking? Can one just banish the dead from wherever they are with no blowback? Should one even if one could? Should one just live with it, even if it's mildly annoying? And what if it's more than mildly annoying?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8235706", "title": "Re: ghosts", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The best thing to do is live and let -- well, \"live\" isn't the right word, of course, but you get the point. If the ghost becomes annoying, banish it -- the Ritual of the Bornless One is extremely effective for that purpose.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8206522", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there already some experiences about the combination of the christian middle pillar exercise and experience of the inner worlds?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8237498", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. Anybody?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8207034", "title": "More Geomancy", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "Salutations JMG! Still working away at geomancy. I've been doing mainly House Charts with occasional Shield Charts and it's far less confusing than doing both Shield and House charts in one reading.\n1) Why do you have to stick to only House OR Shield per divination?\n1a) Should I verbally announce which chart I'm working with ahead of time? Is there some kind of distinction I have to draw for the Anima Mundi, and if so how do I do it?\n2) For questions with a very clear cut Yes or No answer, what does perfection with unfortunate characters mean? I asked \"Will using Dice in geomancy give me accurate readings?\" and I got Via in the 1st house passing to the 8th house where it was conjunct Cauda Draconis in the 9th. Clearly a \"yes\", but the unfortunate figures make it seem like a \"Yesn't.\"\n3) I thought it was under the chapter on ethics, but I can't seem to find where I read that it's disrespectful to ask a question you already know the answer to. Is it also disrespectful to ask the same question twice when you worry a lack of focus or improper technique screwed up the earlier reading?\n3a) Is it acceptable to ask the same question twice if you want to try the other chart type?\nThat's about all for this week, except to say that I'm currently working Bruce Frantzis' \"Water-style\" Qi Gong from the book \"Opening the Energy Gates of Your Body\" which seems different than most Qi Gong because it only pulls energy downward through the body and emphasizes gentle dissolving and flow, rather than the chi concentration and \"fire-style\" Qi Gong like Iron Shirt Packing that pulls energy up through the feet and packs it into small sections of the body.\nWhen I get a solid footing in the system I'll experiment with how the Sphere of Protection interacts and report my findings.\nI'd also like to thank you for taking the time to answer ordinary people's questions, and the immeasurable patience and evenness you show to everybody. I imagine it's like herding a bunch of over eager chicks chirping loudly and insistently at your feet whenever you walk into the chicken pen.\nEdited (Missing words, use of singular instead of plural, clarification)\nDate:\n2020-04-13 05:21 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8237754", "title": "Re: More Geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Because if you don't you'll end up seriously confused far more often than not.\n2) It's more of a \"yes, but...\"  In the case of the reading you describe, it's likely to be \"yes, but there are better options.\"\n3) Yes to the first and no to the second. Ask the question once, and accept the answer.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8247482", "title": "Re: More Geomancy", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "1) Oh yes, I was very confused before. But why? The figures don't change their meaning, and the future doesn't change, so why do the charts see the same figures so differently?\n1a) When the Anima Mundi guides your hand, does it check which chart you're using first? If it does, what is it checking? Should I be announcing \"I'm using the Shield Chart now!\" to make sure my divinations are accurate?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8257210", "title": "Re: More Geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I suggest meditating on that.\n2) All you have to do is decide in advance which you're going to do.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8260538", "title": "Re: More Geomancy", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "I will, thanks!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8208314", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm trying to reclaim my mind, and this means the first steps are eliminating the various hooks which advertisers have implanted. The first steps for this are limiting my exposure going forward, journaling, and a banishing ritual: The SoP, as I'm planning on doing work with the Dolmen Arch and AODA.\nAm I missing anything which would help at this point?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8238266", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those are suitable first steps. Once you have those down, you can try other magical techniques.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8208570", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any idea why so many people seem to equate masturbation with porn? It's baffling that such a simple distinction is lost on so many people....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8238522", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think it's because a lot of people do in fact combine them. Still, you're right that they aren't the same thing in any sense.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8209338", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are the correspondences for being understood and taken seriously? Hermes for communication, or Sun/Jupiter for success? Or an hour of one and day of the other? What other alignments to look for? Particularly ones that are not years away!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8238778", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "For anything having to do with communication, Mercury's your man. Burn an orange candle to him on eight successive Wednesdays during an hour of Mercury, and make a donation of some multiple of $8 to a Mercurial charity.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8241082", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does that 8 come from the order of Hod in Tree of Life, or the Ogdoadic cult of Hermopolis?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8257978", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "8 is the traditional number of Mercury; the planets have numbers that run from 3 for Saturn to 9 for the Moon. Yes, the Cabala uses them too, but the Cabala borrowed the numbers from the older Mesopotamian astrological tradition.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8209594", "title": "a mental tangle of pentagrams", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Greetings.\nJMG, I have encountered and understand your reasons for giving alternate versions of rituals.\nIn the case I have just encountered it is the direction of tracing and starting point of pentagrams for invoking and banishing which varies. In the LBRP given on MM, banishing is anticlockwise. Whereas in chapter 5 of Earth Divination... the opposite direction is stated.\nNow a pentagram is a pentagram is a pentagram; direction and orientation are relative to the coordinates one uses. So, could you help me understand: is the consistency of coordinates within a setting the primary aspect, ie whichever way you trace a banishing figure, just ensure to do the opposite for summoning?\nOr is it more important for the practitioner to be consistent across practices? Thus, as my two-year habit of banishing is with a figure drawn anticlockwise, should I keep it this way when doing the form in the geomantic ritual?\nThank you as ever for your generosity,\nkallianeira.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8239290", "title": "Re: a mental tangle of pentagrams", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Earth Divination, Earth Magic\nuses the Hermetic GD system of pentagrams. The version I posted here uses the Druidical GD system of pentagrams. It's important for each practitioner to be consistent across practices, so do it the way you've been doing it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8209850", "title": "Gypsy Witch cards", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John,\nIn the Weird of Hali books, Justin Martense uses the Gypsy Witch card deck for divination.  In the acknowledgements section for a couple of the books, you indicate that these Gypsy Witch cards are a traditional American cartomancy deck.  I’ve tried to find the deck online, but am not sure I’ve found the set in question.  A couple of sites have a set in a bright orange box with a witch and a black cat sitting at a cauldron on the cover along with the title “Gypsy Witch® Fortune Telling Playing Cards.”  This appears to be a standard 52-card set of playing cards but each card has its own illustration.  Is this the set that Justin is using?\nThank you,\nWill1000", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8239802", "title": "Re: Gypsy Witch cards", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the deck that inspired the one Justin uses. The Gypsy Witch deck is an expansion of the Lenormand deck that's gotten so much attention among diviners in recent years; the Lenormand is based on the old version of the picquet deck and has 36 cards. The Gypsy Witch deck has all the same images as the Lenormand, but adds 16 more cards to bring it up to the full 52-card deck.\nOne of these days, if I can find a good illustrator to work with, I'd like to do a deck that more or less duplicates the cards Justin got from Sallie Eagle in\nThe Weird of Hali: Chorazin\n. It'll be called \"The Black Goat's Oracle.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8247738", "title": "Re: Gypsy Witch cards", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Excellent.  Thank you.  BTW, I thoroughly enjoyed the whole series as well as the Shoggoth duo.  Looking forward to your next fiction series.  In the meantime, I'll be reading RW Chambers, HPL, and others.\nAlso, RE The Black Goat's Oracle, I would definitely be interested in a deck and companion book.\nAnd, hoping to participate in the cell salts experiment, but trying to keep costs down for now as my wife was furloughed.  Maybe on the other side of COVID19.\nWill1000", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8258234", "title": "Re: Gypsy Witch cards", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're welcome and thank you! If you know a good illustrator, I'll see what I can do.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8210106", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThanks as always for hosting this. In recent months, I think I’ve noticed a considerable uptick in the amount of coverage that “mainstream” news sources are giving to occult subjects. For instance, earlier this month, the Economist ran a column about the rise in popularity of a certain type of Buddhist wizard in Myanmar, and this month’s Atlantic has an article on Reiki. Perhaps I’m simply noticing these articles more as my own interest grows, but it really does seem like there’s an increase in coverage...  any thoughts on what’s behind this? Are we simply seeing more evidence of the death of materialism in our society, or is there something deeper happening?\nThanks again,\nRyan M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8240058", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! I don't know. I'll have to watch for it and try to get a sense of its causes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8210618", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Since I'm Canadian, one of the best options for saving which I have access to is an RRSP. Contributing to it instantly reduces my taxable income, and while it's meant to be set aside for retirement, you can take money out at any time. You pay income tax on it, but it's still a good deal, as long as I have savings set aside elsewhere, to cover any short emergencies.\nWhat's fascinating is that there are so many articles about why it's a bad idea to contribute to them, with one argument being that you should plan on having a higher tax bill when you retire. (My reaction the first time I saw this argument was unprintable here)\nI finally realized it's an excuse to avoid saving. What's fascinating is how much the average Canadian could save, if we only adopted slightly lower consumption levels. This seems utterly unthinkable, but it seems strange to me that it should be the case.\nDo you have any idea why so many people are so reluctant to save for the future? I'm well aware some people live paycheck to paycheck, but a lot of them are making enough money to be able to save something, even if it's not a lot, and saving money for rainy days seems like a very common habit in most human cultures....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8239546", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Another Canadian here to the OP: I do save as much as I can but not in an RRSP. Dumb question: why shouldn’t I be worried about a high tax bill when I retire with RRSPs? I don’t know much about them.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8240570", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think that most people these days are terrified of the future. They've been raised to believe that progress is inevitable, and told over and over again that we're progressing -- but a vast number of people have noticed that we're \"progressing\" downhill at an accelerating rate. Saving for the future forces people to think about the future, and most people would rather not do that. As for the articles trying to discourage people from using RRSPs, my guess is that most of those are ghostwritten by brokerages who want you to fork over your money to them instead.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8215994", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI have two questions today:\n1. There is a sentence from His Dark Materials series that stuck in my head: „Alethiometer doesn’t always answer the question you ask. It tells you what you need to know.“ Could it be the case with Ogham too?\n2. I am using a biodynamic calendar for gardening based on the research of Maria Thun. I don’t have much experience with it, I am just doing it out of curiosity. It says Good Friday is not a favourable day to do any gardening, which was supposedly confirmed by experiments. I was wondering if this effect could be based on astrology or rather on the belief of the gardener performing the experiment or on something else. I don’t understand why it should be so.\nHana", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8240826", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's often the case with divinations of every kind.\n2) Hmm! That doesn't make any sense to me. I suspect it's a function of the Christian beliefs behind Steiner's biodynamic system.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8216250", "title": "Dozing off during meditation; a feature, not a bug.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John-\nSometimes, what I want most from self-control and self-awareness is the ability to get a good night's sleep before the early-morning alarm wakes me.  When the concerns of the day make that difficult, a meditation on \"the elements\" has often been what I needed.\nTo revise and extend my previous remarks for the benefit of others who might like to try this: \"Earth\" is this rock on which my soul rides through space, all aspects of the solid state of matter, the soil within which the crops grow, bones, and refined metals which are handy in many ways.  \"Water\" is the seas (in which tasty fish grow), the rivers that carry barge commerce, the rain which waters the crops, blood, and other liquids.  \"Air\" is the weather, the transport medium of pollinating insects and wind-blown pollen, the breath, and other gases.  \"Fire\" includes the coal and gas that burn to spin turbines that pump \"electric fire\" through the wires, photons flung into the ether from (ham) radio transmitters, the plasma state of ionized gas and chemically-reacting flow, sunshine that makes the crops grow, and oxidation of glucose in mitochondria that derive action from will.  (These are examples, not a bounded set.)\nFor all of these elements, I am grateful to the Creator, as I am when I wake up well-rested.\nIs there anything you recommend to encourage sleep?  (You're probably not the slave to the alarm clock that I am, but that's part of the cost of participating in a carpool.)\nLathechuck", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8241338", "title": "Re: Dozing off during meditation; a feature, not a bug.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nice. I don't really have any method for that; I tend to stay up late and sleep until I wake naturally, so haven't really needed anything of the kind for many years.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8250554", "title": "Re: Dozing off during meditation; a feature, not a bug.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah, the virtues of self-employment...\nLathechuck", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8258490", "title": "Re: Dozing off during meditation; a feature, not a bug.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's got a lot of benefits.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8216506", "title": "C-Word and magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nplease feel free to delete or keep offlist, I know it's a touchy topic:\nI'm still flabbergasted at the reaction to the virus by my (mostly upper middle-class) friends and neighbors. They could not be more happy about lockdowns, quarantines, arbitrary restrictions of movement and bans on - well, basically anything that makes us human or a society. It's frankly bizarre. They're locked inside with their kids, shouting for the politicians to tighten restrictions even more, as if the bogeyman himself were out and about on their street. All while for them it's all hearsay - they haven't even had a death (or as much as a sneeze) within their family or circle of acquaintances.\nHow much of this do you think is down to magic? I have family with serious OCD issues and this all feels extremely familiar. Is there a way to put a spell on society to turn it OCD as a whole?\nI'll be happy to read up on this if you have any pointers (currently reading \"Eros and Magic in the Renaissance\" but haven't gotten very far yet).\nThank you so much for this forum,\nJonas", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8242106", "title": "Re: C-Word and magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've been watching it as well, and I think it's an offshoot of the weird obsession with control that's so widespread among the comfortable classes these days. It's unbearable to a lot of people that a virus could just pop up and start killing people, and so they're frantically yelling for the government or somebody to MAKE IT STOP!!!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8251322", "title": "Re: C-Word and magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG and OP, I saw a news story today that the governor of Michigan has decided that garden seeds are non-essential, so Michiganders are not permitted to buy them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8258746", "title": "Re: C-Word and magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course. Don't you know you should be totally dependent on your corporate masters for everything?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8260282", "title": "Re: C-Word and magic", "user": "jpc_w", "content": "Are citizens of Michigan barred from buying the seeds from mail-order seed farms, or just from retail stores?  I’ve seen this mentioned in a few places as being from stores only.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8223162", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a reason why the Dolmen Arch course starts with the opening and closing of the SoP, and leaves the calling of the elements for three months later?\nMost other instructions I've see have you start learning them almost immediately after the opening and closing, so I'm curious what the rationale with having them in the second lesson instead of the first is.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8242362", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I was taught to master the Opening and Closing first, putting a good deal of time and effort into that, and then to add the elements one at a time after that, giving each one at least a week and longer as needed. In my experience that yields better results.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8249530", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Fascinating. Thank you.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8223674", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello and happy Monday,\nIf someone has a miscarriage and then later has a baby, is the soul the same? Or do souls hang around waiting and then go elsewhere if there is a miscarriage or abortion?\nThank you for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8242618", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Like most things involved in reincarnation, it varies from case to case. Sometimes, based on what sources of information we have, the same soul can try for incarnation from a given mother more than once.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8248250", "title": "babies", "user": "ritaer", "content": "I can't speak about the souls, but a study of old family trees will reveal that for earlier generations it was not uncommon to reuse a baby name. If little Arthur died shortly after birth, the next son might be christened Arthur. Seems odd to modern sensibilites, but there it is. Not sure about cultures other than English speaking since I haven't reserched the subject, just noticed it.\nRita", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8224442", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Mr Greer,\nMy question today is about divination. Is there a comprehensive list of the different ways to practice this art? I'm getting the very strong message that this is the next step in my daily rituals. I have a strong meditation practice and my SOP is about a year along. Now I have the attention freed up to add the next leg of this triad, as I see it.\nI'm not naturally drawn to anything at the moment as far as divination goes. Tarot leaves me a bit flat. Possibly the hexagrams of IChing as they do have some aesthetic attraction for me. But I have no idea what is available for a total novice, which I truly am.\nAs always, thanks so much for your continuing gifts of clarity and insight.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8242874", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A complete book on divination would be quite the project! I don't know that anybody's done one. There are plenty of online discussions of different methods -- put the search string \"divination methods\" into your favorite search engine and you'll get quite a few. (Ignore the Wikipedia article, which is worse than useless.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8227002", "title": "Aquarius", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "JMG - I am having a hard time wrapping my head around Aquarius, and all the New Age stuff seems to have an unhealthy fetishization of it and Uranus.  I know before Uranus was discovered, Saturn ruled Aquarius, and am having a hard time squaring (or rather, conjoining) this with Uranus ruling it now, given that the planets seem to be so opposed.\nIs there something I'm missing about the nature of Aquarius?  Apart from further meditation on the meaning of Aquarius and Uranus, is there anything else I should do?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8243130", "title": "Re: Aquarius", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Meditating on that question is definitely a good idea! History can also help, though. Before Uranus was discovered, Saturn had some of the things now assigned to Uranus; Saturn was for example the planet of philosophy, solitude, eccentricity, and antisocial attitudes, which are now assigned to Uranus.\nAquarius has certainly been fetishized in unproductive ways, and the Age of Aquarius is not going to be Utopian -- not by a long shot. It'll differ from the Piscean age, but it will have just as many problems -- though they'll be different ones.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8227514", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi Mr. Greer,\nWhat is your take on Christian baptism? I've been practicing \"I am\" mantra meditation for years. I enjoy working with whatever forces I come into contact with including Jesus, but I don't know if I'm ready to commit to Jesus as my most sacred ideal. For me, the thought of putting on a white robe and having some strange person dunk me in water seems like a creepy death cult thing. On the other hand, joining a church would help me meet young single people like myself and also network for my business.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8243386", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Do not join a church to meet people and network; join a church only if you've decided you want to make room in your life for a relationship with a deity. A church isn't a social club, and joining it as though it was a social club is disrespectful.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8245946", "title": "Maybe you could shop around denominations?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Described in those terms, yeah, it sounds creepy! In Catholicism, which I know best, the closer you get to that is the Sacrament of Holy Orders, which emphatically is NOT for everyone. During their initiation, soon to be priests lay on the floor pretending to be dead, - dead to the World, that's it, - and then are raised again to serve the Will of God in the time they have left on this Earth.\nBut please be aware, different traditions use different rituals for Baptism. In most cases they use pouring or even sprinkling of water over one's head instead of full immersion. Purely from a aesthetic and symbolic point of view, I like best the one where you are standing (or kneeling) inside a tube with a few inches of water, then the priest/minister performing the ritual pours a bucket over your head and shoulders. This, in my opinion, has a lovely symbolism of cleanising of one's past errors and mischeif. Though of course, I don't know who does this and what do they stand for.\nSo maybe you just need to check what Denomination does resonate better with who you are?\nBest regards\nCRPatiño", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8231354", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nThese questions may sound silly but still I want to ask them:\n1 - Would it be okay to ask a goddess of love to give me advice for finding my soulmate?\n2 - Is there an ethical magical operation to lead myself into suitable circumstances where I will find my soulmate?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8243898", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They're not silly at all.\n1) Of course. That's one of the thing that love goddesses do. Be prepared to offer her something in return, though, and also be prepared for changes in yourself.\n2) Of course, but you may not like it. The one infallible and perfectly ethical love spell is to make yourself more lovable. Of course that requires you to accept that you could be more lovable than you are, and that in turn requires you to change things about yourself that keep you from being as lovable as you need to be. Again, love goddesses are good at this sort of thing; just be prepared to see yourself in an uncomfortable light while you make the necessary changes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8233914", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've seen all the people demanding Trump do more about the epidemic, and realized why they want that: it would give them an excuse to freak about Trump's overreach. What is it that keeps so many people, some of them otherwise rational, from thinking clearly about Trump?\nI'm reminded of the description of demonic obsession in Monsters, and beginning to wonder if there's something like that happening....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8244154", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Trump Derangement Syndrome is an astonishing thing to watch. I have rarely seen so many supposedly rational people behaving so weirdly. Two months ago they were screaming at Trump because he was trying to take action about the epidemic; now they've done a 180° and are screaming at Trump because he didn't do enough. My take is that it's a product of severe cognitive dissonance, because the world is refusing to behave the way their ideology claims it should behave -- but you know, it does look increasingly like obsession.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8249786", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wonder now how often ideologies are collective demonic obsessions....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8259002", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They may also be obsessions by egregors. An egregor can function as an artificial spirit, and do many of the things a spirit can do.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8236474", "title": "God names of the LBRP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear jmg\nSomething that has confused me about the LBRP is it’s coice of god names and where it places them.\nAs I come to understand it, it sequence is,\nYHVH-east\nAdonai-south\nEheieh-west\nAgla-north\nAccording to the elemental correspondences of these names YHVH is in the right direction since it corresponds to air & east but Adonai, which is associated with earth & north is in the south.\nThe last 2 are associated with active and passive spirit and take the place of water and earth, why is this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8244666", "title": "Re: God names of the LBRP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nearly every student of Golden Dawn magic notices this early on. The answer is that in the LRP, the divine names for the quarters do not relate to the elements. What do they relate to? That's a great theme for meditation.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8243642", "title": "TSW", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I used planetary time magic in addition to specific prayers during my SOP this morning to be able to get through the phone queue while getting my unemployment application in.\nI am a chiropractor,  a small business owner,  and I was running into resistance from them for whatever baroque reason they had in spite of being unable to work. It’s  impossible to give chiropractic adjustments and maintain social distance, and my husband is immunologically compromised from having had radiation last year.  He's 74.\nI only had to wait three and a half hours, compared to a statewide average of eleven.  They’ll  begin sending me money this week.\nI started the call during the Jupiter hour.  I’d say,  TSW!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8244922", "title": "Re: TSW", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Glad to hear it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8244410", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am doing the cell salts experiment, but just the bioplasma while I wait for the second round of tablets when the moon is in Gemini again. I am also doing the SOP daily for over a year. For the last few weeks, possibly predating than the start of the experiment, my face and neck feel flushed and look a bit red at points during each day, almost every day. Could either the SOP or the cell salts cause this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8245178", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not something I've ever encountered in relationship to either one. You might want to explore whether there's something else in your diet or your lifestyle that might be causing it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8246458", "title": "crystal with meditation or sop", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John Michael,\nDo you (or anyone else) have specific recommendations of use of crystals and sphere of protection, or while meditating. Ideas towards interactions or complementary benefits would be appreciated.\nMore generally than that, do you (or anyone else, please) have insights or ideas on how to best utilize crystals (like, how do you hold or place them, and where, and is it passive, etc). Books, and other sources of their efficacy and practice.\nMy utmost gratitude to you John Michel, and to all the wonderful participants for this wonderful community.\nPeace and blessings\nR", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8259258", "title": "Re: crystal with meditation or sop", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never done much with crystals so can't help you there.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8247226", "title": "Deal gone bad", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI was under contract to buy a house before this whole unmentionable virus came around.  I managed to back out of the deal in time, as it would have made for a seriously stressful situation, but the sellers were pretty upset.  I understand and sympathize with their feelings, but backing out was necessary to protect myself and my family right now.\nIs there a good ritual for breaking any non-physical plane connection with them and wishing them well on their way without contacting them in the physical plane?  I've heard about burning a copy of the original contract or something, but I don't want to do anything to cause them (or me) any harm.  I just want to release any connection that might exist.  Thank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8259514", "title": "Re: Deal gone bad", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Burning the contract is a traditional approach; it doesn't hurt the people who signed it, just the link between them. Before doing so, pray to whatever deities you revere and ask them to bless the sellers and find them a good buyer promptly.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8248762", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a friend who's young daughter is being bullied. She's already a pretty fragile kid, and at those awkward early teen years when all kids are fragile. And someone is telling her she's fat and she should kill herself.\nOn this plane, so to speak, what can by done by law enforcement is being done (not much it seems), but I was wondering if there's anything that might be possible to do on a different plane that might help her? I am reasonable competent in the gold dawn system, I have been at it for five years, but I have never done any working involving anyone outside my immediate family. Obviously I would ask permission, but assuming I got it... what sort of ritual or working would you suggest to help someone in that situation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8254906", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Can your friend get her sympathetic and effective counseling? A good therapist can do worlds for her. That's the first thing, beyond law enforcement, that I'd recommend.\nSecond, if you can get the names or any other object link connecting to the person doing the bullying, a binding spell on the perp is a good choice. (I consider this one of the few situations where the consent of the target is not required, so long as you have the consent of the victim and/or her parents.) Get the name or other object link (a photo, or what have you) and fasten it to a small piece of wood or stiff card, painted red. Have five pieces of red cord. Invoke Geburah in full ritual form, using the divine name ALHIM GBVR and all the other correspondences of the 5th sphere, and bind the perp so that he or she can no longer bully or in any way harm your friend's daughter. Do this five times. Wrap the bound object link in red silk and put it someplace secret. I did this spell once on a friend's abusive boyfriend and he left the state the next day.\nThird, emotional healing work for her is very useful. Do the Rose Cross ritual while visualizing her in the center of the space, every day for a week, then weekly thereafter. In terms of major ritual, a ritual of Netzach -- to help her love herself, to direct healing and blessing energy at her, and to bring her Victory over this -- would also be very good in this context.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8261050", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I know MM is closed, but I wanted to say thank you for this.\nUnfortunately I don't know the person bullying her. I believe that my friend does, but she hasn't told me and I don't think she will in the absence of any hard proof. Is there any way to do this without the name/object?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8261562", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, though it may not be quite as effective without the object link. Once you've opened the temple with the appropriate rituals -- the Watchtower Ritual is good here, though only if you're familiar with it -- take the red card or piece of wood, sprinkle it with water and say, \"You are the person who is bullying (name).\" Then hold it in the smoke of the incense and repeat those words. Then proceed with the rest of the ritual.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8251834", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI posted the death notice of Ira Einhorn, the Unicorn Murderer, on the suspicion that, since we’re an older crowd here, someone might have been interested in the case or known Einhorn, his victim, or both.  Out of curiosity, I read the book.  Could Einhorn have been practicing some unethical spells to entrance rich businessmen and rich ladies?  Such people are normally not fond of loud, scruffy, smelly New Age types, with the exception of Rasputin.  (Rasputin ‘s power seemed to be mainly over women, but Einhorn could fascinate both sexes.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8255162", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so. There's a lot of very grubby magic in the New Age scene, usually gussied up as \"positive thinking\" and the like.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8252090", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "Good evening JMG, I have a few etheric questions.\nDo you know of any system in magic and or a form friendly with it that awakens what the Hindus call the five pranas or practices like organ breathing? (Prana, apana, udana, samana and Vyana) I know those are really good for the health of the body but don’t know if would get mixed up.\nI’ve come across a temple in India that has a shivaling that is allegedly very powerfully consecrated. What would you say the effects of a consecrated object with an energy body with the 7 energy centers maxed out be?\nDoes the CGD system also include working with the lunar current as DMH does or does it remain particularly solar in nature?\nRegarding animal transformation, in CGD I believe you talk about the construction of the etheric body of the animal of transformation around you instead of let loose. If for example you take the case of a warewolf which it casters body is around in a bush nearby. If the etheric body his consciousness is on get disolved by one reason or the other is there a danger involved for the caster?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8255674", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, you probably have to talk to a competent yogi about that.\n2) It depends very much on the nature of the consecrated object and the specific energies that flow through it.\n3) The CGD system is solar in nature. Balanced, but solar.\n4) If you move your consciousness into an etheric body of transformation and leave your body, and the body of transformation is disrupted while you're in it, your body will be found stone cold dead the next morning. Werewolf lore is very explicit about that. I discuss it in some detail in my book on monsters.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8252346", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You've mentioned before that the CGD and AODA ritual work don't mix. Is there a similar issue with combining the AODA and OBD work, or is it safe to combine them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8255930", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those two work fairly well together; I've combined them in various ways with good results.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8252602", "title": "Second lesson in muscle testing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "On the other blog Scotlyn asked, “So I am very interested, but completely untutored, in this idea of using muscle testing to communicate with a body, whether it is a patient’s body (which I will seek further learning sources to improve upon) or my own body. In relation to the second, though, I wonder would it be a big ask for you to briefly illustrate with a step by step example of you DOING this? Eg. Question, technique, reaction, answer. The HOW of it. Also, if the answer sometimes might be “I don’t want to tell you” how do you distinguish that from a “yes” or a “no”?\nThis is a continuation of my comment from last week describing how to use muscle testing to test physical imbalances currently in one’s body rather than trying to test questions being held in one’s mind (that will be next week.) When practicing muscle testing on yourself (without a partner) all the principles presented last week for testing with another person are still applicable. You will still be following your hunches, and testing out your hypotheses. You can also continue to hold a point that tests weak while looking for another point that strengthens that imbalance, though that will require a fair amount of dexterity. You can narrow down from broad, full-hand contact to just a fingertip in order to speed up your testing. You will still benefit from trying acupressure first on any point of imbalance before trying more complex rebalancing techniques. You can still test whether anything that presses on or distorts your body ends up balancing or imbalancing you. And your muscles or your patience may get exhausted before you can finish decoding a complex imbalance, requiring you to take a break and retrace your steps when you are ready to resume testing. If any of those principles are confusing, review last week’s comment for clarification.\nMuscle testing physical imbalances on your own body involves keeping conscious control over the muscles of the arm that is touching points as well as the arm that is applying pressure to do the test, but somehow relinquishing just enough control over the muscle being tested to both maintain constant resistance and allow it to weaken when the rest of the body does. That leaves a lot of room for psychic gremlins to make considerable mischief. Remember, it's an art, not a science! I highly recommend practicing muscle testing with a partner before you try testing by yourself. When being tested by or testing another, the subject will only have to try to hold his or her muscle at constant strength, letting the aide do the pushing. This spreads the complexity out across two people, which is very useful when beginning the practice. Plus it can be fun to share with a like-minded explorer. With two people as witness, it is also more likely that one or both will pick up on subtle weakening or the odd effects of willful attempts by the subject to not allow their body to weaken (to control the test.) We all have our own ways of trying to control life and of lying to ourselves, so no simple example could cover all the ways that trying to control the test could manifest. We’re much more complicated than that.\nAs I mentioned last month, I use one of my iliopsoas muscles to do solo testing. The iliopsoas is primary in lifting the leg and stabilizing the body in walking. It is one of the strongest muscles in the body, so it does not tire quickly. Different positions will allow greater or lesser ease in reaching different testing points. If you feel unsafe trying to reach an awkward point (the middle of your back) or keep your balance while testing, do partnered testing for that point instead. Straining or injuring yourself is not the goal here, nor should solo muscle testing feel like a yoga workout. What I do while standing is flex either thigh forward to around 90° with my knee bent, foreleg dangling. Then I use the palm or knuckles of the fist of my same-side arm to press down on my lifted thigh close to its knee to test its strength. I use my opposite-side arm to touch points suspected of imbalance, while using my same-side arm again to test my thigh’s strength. Testing points on the lower leg is awkward (if not dangerous) while standing, so I test them while sitting or lying down to reach my lower leg or foot. What I do while lying on my back looks identical to the standing test but in a supine position. I flex either thigh forward to around a 90° bend with my knee bent, foreleg parallel to the floor and test as above.\nWhat I do while sitting is flex either thigh up a little higher than the normal 90° bend of the thigh resting on the chair and press down on my thigh close to my knee with my same side-hand, knuckles or even elbow in particularly awkward positions. With the hip flexed so high the muscle will be less strong in resisting being pushed down. Depending on your balance/strength, you may find it helps to lean back against the chair back so that lifting the thigh off the seat only brings it up to 90°. Eventually you want to be able to test while seated upright or even bent forward as this position allows you to test awkward points on your leg or foot. To test points on my arm or hand, I usually sit and just touch points on my same-side arm that is doing the pressing/testing of my thigh. The physical description sounds awfully complex, but once you get a sense of what your own strengthening/weakening effect feels like, you can play around with finding which muscle works best for you to test with. You may well find an easier way to muscle test for your body.\nThe main difficulty that muscle testing on yourself presents is getting your personality out of the way enough to let your body strengthen and weaken on its own (not under your willful control,) while still rationally analyzing and comparing its responses to the pains and imbalances you are feeling. This is no easier for professional body workers, athletes, or coaches than for anyone with less body training. After all, the entity you need to have training and discipline in reining in here is your personality, not your body. Ever met an MD who seemed to have surprisingly limited practice reigning in his run-away ego? That skill falls outside his area of training and expertise. Imagine how hard it could be for famous athletes or surgeons to let their bodies tell them that they can no longer be relied on to perform perfectly as trained, no matter how much willful control they try to exert. There are far too many instances of promising draft picks giving in to despair and drink after an injury, rather than getting to know their new injured body and working with it as a perfectly willing, but limited partner. Many body “experts” have gained deep understanding and experience of the body being wiser in many ways than the mind, but just as many have developed nothing but arrogant disdain for all the fragile, dysfunctioning bodies they have had (and often wasted) the amazing opportunity to partner with.\nAll of us have had those magical experiences where our body’s natural intelligence takes over, and the mind becomes an observer going along for the ride. Some of us may have no memory of having that experience since being children, but it is happening for all of us every day. The problem is that we are rarely aware of our bodies’ intelligence, coordination, and mastery. We can walk for miles enjoying the birdsong and dappled sunlight in perfect coordination, but most of us will become awkward, self-conscious disasters the moment we turn our attention to our gait, stride, arm swing, etc. Trained athletes are no exception, and most lose their mastery the moment they start thinking about it.\nHow do you get out of the way of your body’s skill, while actively paying close attention to its awareness and wisdom? You may be one of the few who always did that naturally (and I am truly jealous,) or you may have practiced long and hard to discipline your awareness to be able to ponder what is outside you, without changing its behavior or frightening it away. The still patience of bird watching is a marvelous metaphor for observing your body just being itself. If you find muscle testing on yourself or even being the subject of muscle testing with someone else to be difficult, begin paying attention to your body as it does the everyday things it does — washing dishes, pushing a wheelbarrow, balancing on a moving train or bus. The mystery of the coordination of instincts that keeps us from constantly falling down is truly worthy of contemplation! And be gentle with yourself. Beating yourself up for completely bollixing up your gait as soon as you begin focusing on it is decidedly unhelpful. That would be like getting angry each time you can’t see a bird in the treetops that an advanced bird watcher has pointed to. Each time you try, you are developing the endless skills that will one day allow you to point out unseen birds to others.\n— Christophe", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8256186", "title": "Re: Second lesson in muscle testing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Christophe, I'm going to ask you in the future to post these to some website or blog of your own. This is not a place for people to post their own instructional essays -- it's a place for me to field and answer questions.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8252858", "title": "Belly Heat", "user": "alexandermarcus", "content": "Good evening, JMG\nI've got some questions about my subtle body.\nMy belly (my whole abdomen, really, but particularly around my navel) is almost always significantly hotter to the touch than the rest of my body, and my feet tend to be cool. Now I always thought this was normal and just because of how far my hands and feet are from my heart, and there relatively high surface area, but apparently other people have a more even distribution of heat. I'm male, for what it's worth.\nI run hot in general, especially when I sleep. I'd rather be in a cold environment than a hot one, almost any day. And feet are not uncomfortable, just markedly cooler than my belly. I had never even noticed the difference until my girlfriend was touching me and pointed it out.\nPerhaps relatedly, I eat a lot, and basically non-stop. Because of this, I'm not often hungry. I'm not fat - I maintain about 190lbs at just over 6 feet. But for years people have remarked on my eating habits, both in regards to quantity and consistency of eating. I also am thirstier than most people, and drink a lot of water.\nI started thinking about this after a recent shamanic healing session in which the practitioner mentioned how much fire I have, and located the fire in my Cauldron of the Earth and related it to the dragons from the Inner Grail Working. (I had told her about my work in the Dolmen Arch, specifically the SoP and Inner Grail Working). Now that I think of it, the Cauldron of the Earth is also named the Cauldron of Warming. This healer is the  one who told me that the dragons \"were eager to help but needed a job,\" which prompted my recent Magic Monday question. (\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/81997.html?thread=7754829#cmt7754829\n) She was really insistent that I had a lot of heat, and needed to temper it or put it to use.\nI would not have thought of myself as fiery, but she's not the first person to contradict that self-perception.\nAll of this is to say: Does this indicate anything on a subtle level, and are there any practices or exercises I might do to re-balance? I do think re-balancing is in order.\nThanks!\nP.S. I realize this may all sound a bit dramatic, and so I want to clarify, this isn't severe enough have me worried about any possible medical conditions.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-14 03:40 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8256442", "title": "Re: Belly Heat", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may want to talk to the shamanic healer about that. That's not a condition I've dealt with, and I'm not at all sure what to suggest.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8253114", "title": "Future book?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nHave you considered doing a book like Modern Magic but aimed at Polytheists? I dont mean a rewrite but a similar work.\n-Russ", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8256698", "title": "Re: Future book?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I proposed such a book to Llewellyn and they turned it down. I did a chapter on the subject in their recent\nComplete Book of Ceremonial Magic\n, so I thought they might be interested, but no such luck. I'll consider reviving the project at some point and placing it elsewhere.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8253882", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I know you're not Christian, but what are your thoughts on churches which gathered to celebrate Easter, despite orders not to?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8256954", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Viruses don't care which religion you belong to. It struck me as a dumb idea.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8257722", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Me too!  In one of the Bible Belt states the police actually arrested one of the intransigent pastors.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8257466", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have two questions regarding the CGD practice.\n1) For the closure breath after the meditation, I decided to use four cycles. Should the current visualization be used for them, or none?\n2) If the incense burns all out (sometimes this happened), should another one be lit?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8259770", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) None. Just let your mind clear.\n2) Yes. It's often handy to keep an extra stick of incense on the altar.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/86579.html", "year": "2020", "month": "04", "day": "19", "time": "11-39PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt8312627", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Today I started the First Degree AODA work, and have noticed Belteinne is next week. I'm interested in celebrating it, but having read through the Druid Grove Handbook see two problems with celebrating it using the rituals there: first, there is no separate Belteinne ritual, and I don't want to start trying to craft one for a while, since at this point I don't have enough experience to even begin to start to figure out how to do that.\nI'm willing to put time in to practice it,but I don't know where to look to find a good ritual. Do you know a simple ritual for Belteinne I could do with basically no background?\n2) I have a lot of free time right now. As an absolute beginner I don't want to push myself with spiritual exercises, but I want to put it to use for developing my spirituality. I'm assuming studying the books I'll need to know later for the AODA second degree would be a wise use of my time, and working through the Dolmen Arch (which I've selected as my Druid exploration), but are there other things I can do?\n3) I'm planning to start doing astrology by hand, but can't find a table of logarithms for calculating planetary motion. Do you know where I could get such a table? Ideally I'm looking for something in print, but something available online would also work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8313651", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The older Druid Revival tradition doesn't celebrate cross-quarter days like Belteinne -- just the solstices and the equinoxes. Gerald Gardner rescued the cross-quarter days from almost total neglect in the late 1940s when he was working on the first draft of Wicca, and they went into some branches of Druidry from that source. AODA doesn't celebrate them. So you can put some time into AODA ritual methods before the summer solstice.\n2) As an absolute beginner you run a real risk of overdoing, resulting in burnout. You might consider using the time to study herbalism, ecology, Celtic legends, or some other field that relates to Druidry but won't risk straining your undeveloped metaphysical muscles.\n3) Most books of house tables have logarithms in the back, and so do old-fashioned ephemerides such as the Rosicrucian Ephemeris. You might also consider learning how to use a slide rule, which works on the logarithmic principle.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8314675", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) I know you've studied Stoicism before, so how well does it and Druidry mesh?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8316211", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Very well -- both focus on the idea of living a life in harmony with nature, and both have no room for the overinflated sense of entitlement that's so common these days.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8330291", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've taken a look and am finding a lot of pop-stoicism aimed at the overly wealthy. Naturally it's very different from the traditional stuff, but do you know a good place to look for the traditional form? Would Meditations by Marcus Aurelius be a good place to start?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8334387", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Yes, beware of \"Modern Stoicism\" .. which as far as I can tell is the mental gymnastic art of trying to square classical Stoic writings with contemporary Church of Progress dogma and sentimentalism.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8335411", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've also been horrified by the way that Stoicism has been dumbed down and turned into yet another non-pharmaceutical tranquilizer for the comfortable classes. (Based on the people I've encountered who have been most vocal about it, that kind of pop pseudo-Stoicism might well be labeled \"Karen Stoicism\"...)\nGo straight to the original sources. The Enchiridion of Epictetus is the one I always find most useful, but Marcus Aurelius is also very popular.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8351539", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a particular translation of The Enchiridion of Epictetus you find useful?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8353587", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've always just used the one in the Harvard Classics, since my wife and I own a set of the latter. It's translated by Hastings Crossley, if that helps.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8353075", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there more than the universe's twisted sense of humour at work in the fact it's the things which are supposed to point out why the life the comfortable classes are living is flawed which get turned into the non-chemical tranquilizers used to justify it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8353843", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I see it as a defensive reaction. The comfortable classes go out of their way to take anything that might show them that they need to change their lives, and turn it into something that they can use to keep from noticing that they need to change their lives, so they can keep up the pretense that they don't need to change their lives.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8352307", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It amuses me that modern stoics seem to go out of their way to avoid noticing that that's what stoicism is about.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8354099", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I doubt it's accidental. Co-opting a potential threat is an old habit among today's comfortable classes...", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8317491", "title": "Stoicism", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi,\nI read a bit of Marcus Aurelius' Meditations every day.  I have been meditating on snippets from The Meditations for a year or so and have found the practice to be a great benefit to my life and my study of Driudry.  I find I think before I speak and Marcus' words often come to me as a reminder before I form my reply.\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8340531", "title": "Re: Stoicism", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Hi Maxine (& JMG too),\nWhat translation of Meditations do you have/like?\nIs there a favored version of the Enchiridion as well?\nThanks!\nBonnie", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8351795", "title": "Re: Stoicism", "user": "barefootwisdom", "content": "If I may, I'm very fond of Robin Hard's translation of Epictetus (the\nEnchiridion\n, or\nHandbook\n, together with the much longer\nDiscourses\n), which appears in the Oxford Worlds Classics series of inexpensive paperbacks. It combines really smooth prose with great accuracy, plus some genuinely helpful endnotes for those who are so inclined.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8357939", "title": "Re: Stoicism", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Thanks!\nB", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8329267", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG included rituals for all 8 festivals in \"The Druidry Handbook\". They're not official AODA rituals, but I found them very useful when I was making the switch to Druid practice, and I still use the seasonal meditations in my Imbolc, Beltaine, Lughnasadh and Samhuinn rituals.\n--Sister Crow", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8312883", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. Have you ever interpreted your natal chart, and if so, do you recognize yourself in the personality that it reveals? (And if we may know, what is astrological sun sign?)\n2. When the Cynic philosopher Antisthenes was asked what he gained by a life of philosophy, he replied that he learned how to converse with himself. In a similar vein, what have you gained by a life of magic?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8314419", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Good gods, yes. Delineating your own natal chart has been the standard way to learn natal astrology for a long time. If I hadn't recognized the portrait, I wouldn't have kept practicing astrology.\n2) I have the life and the work I want. That didn't happen because I got the universe to give it to me; it happened because I used magic to become the kind of person to whom that kind of life and work comes naturally.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8337715", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How did you decide on the type of work you wanted?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8373555", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I knew by the time I was 7 that I wanted to be a writer, and figured out that I wanted to be a professional occultist about 30 seconds after learning that there was such a thing, so it was pretty easy.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8313139", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1. I’m the commenter from last week who asked about a passage from Robert Wang’s The Qabalistic Tarot. There’s another passage from that book that’s been causing me to scratch my head lately. This is where he discusses how the Minor Arcana of the Tarot also have astrological attributions in the form of a planet acting in a sign:\n‘There are, in fact, a number of Minor Arcana cards where the meaning of Planets in Signs differs from that commonly accepted, because the card combines Sephirothic and astrological symbolism. Here it must be kept in mind that the Zodiac is the Mundane Chakra of Chokmah; it appears in the lowest of the Four Worlds. The cards represent the totality of that to which the Signs of the Zodiac refer.’\nAny idea what he means here?\n2. If each Sephirah is active in all Four Worlds, what is the justification for certain Worlds being more closely associated with certain Sephiroth than others? For example, Briah is often held to be closely associated with Chokmah and Binah, but all Sephiroth have an archangelic level, so shouldn’t all Sephiroth be equally active in Briah?\n3. Let’s say I get Two of Wands in a Tarot divination. Twos are usually attributed to Chokmah, and Wands to fire and the mental level of being. This would imply that the Two of Wands represents the influence of Chokmah in the mental realm. But Chokmah is not part of the Ruach and very remote from daily experience – how can it possibly have any influence, and what shape does this influence take?\n4. The Sphere of Yesod is often attributed to the etheric body, which makes sense given its connection to the Moon. However, it’s also commonly attributed to the unconscious mind. I don’t understand how this second attribution is possible given that it’s located at the bottom of the Astral Triangle, the level of concrete consciousness. My understanding is that the personal unconscious corresponds to the Ethical triangle, or the Higher Self, composed of Chesed / Geburah / Tiphareth. The higher you go up the Tree of Life, the more you you ascend into the unconscious, first the personal unconscious and then the collective unconscious.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8314931", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Have you meditated on it?\n2) What's going on here is that two competing ways of thinking about the Four Worlds have been mushed together. There's one in which there's a Tree of Life in each world, and another in which a single Tree spans all four worlds. I suggest that you simply note the discrepancy, and see which version works for you in practice.\n3) This is one of the reasons why I don't use that set of attributions of Tarot to the Tree of Life in my own practice. No, it doesn't make much sense -- nor does it make sense to map the Trumps onto the Tree starting from the top, when the Trumps are so clearly a process of spiritual ascent beginning with ordinary (Foolish) consciousness.\n4) Here again, you're trying to conflate different models that don't necessarily fit together well. If you want to use a psychological model, Yesod is the preconscious or subconscious mind, the \"machine language\" on top of which the operating system of consciousness functions. The higher levels are not subconscious but superconscious.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8319283", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) But in doing so, aren't you severing the connection between the Tarot and the Tree of Life? I thought it was established in the modern Qabalah that they're supposed to be interlocking systems of symbolism, and whatever is expressed in one can be expressed in the other. I don't think I've seen a single resource on the Hermetic Qabalah that doesn't assign the Minor Arcana to the Sephiroth in the usual way.\n4) That makes a lot of sense, actually. So in this psychological model, Yesod corresponds to something like the Freudian id. In that case, do dreams occur in the sphere of Yesod or are they a glimpse of the superconscious levels above it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8320051", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3) No, I use a different way of applying the Tarot to the Tree. There are quite a few ways to do this -- and if you haven't encountered any of the alternative schemes, er, you may need to do some more reading. I suggest picking up Willam Gray's\nThe Talking Tree\nand anything in the French tradition, just for starters.\n4) In Golden Dawn theory, Yesod generates the Sphere of Sensation, the \"screen\" on which dreams, imagination, etc. are projected. The source of the images can be anything from leftover memories of the day (Malkuth) to transcendent influences from the highest planes (Kether).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8329779", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the OP)\nHow coincidental! ;-) I was going to post a question about the relation between Trumps and Paths so, if I may:\nWhich assignment do you use John? I've been studying the one RJ Stewart uses for the Merlin Tarot (which I believe is almost similar to Gray's) which assigns Moon, Sun and Star to the middle pillar, Fortune, Justice and Judgement to the horizontal paths and the rest go up from Malkuth through the Pillar of Form up to Kether and back again through the Pillar of Force.\nTo me it looks that different systems have different allocations, all valid inside their own systems, but Stewart tells this story that Regardie told him that the GD 'official' assignment is a sort of smokescreen and that once you pass through the grades you're told the 'proper' way (which he imply it's Gray's) (see http://www.dreampower.com/regardie.html) Any thoughts on this John?\nMany thanks!\nManuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8335923", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I use one that as far as I know has not yet been published; it was communicated to me some years ago, not long after I joined AODA (and as part of the lore of one of the orders related to AODA) as the supposed real secret version taught by the Golden Dawn. I'll post something about it here on Dreamwidth shortly; it follows an interesting logic of its own, and works very well.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8342323", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "hwistle", "content": "Looking forward to it!\nManuel", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8331571", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Out of curiosity, do you still do any workings with individual Sephiroth? Or have you pretty much seen everything there is to see in the Qabalah, learned the lessons, and moved on?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8336179", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've done systematic work with the Tree of Life four times now in the course of my magical studies, and will doubtless go back to it again at a later date; right now, though, I'm working with other symbolic patterms. I don't think anyone anywhere has ever seen everything there is to see in the Cabala.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8313395", "title": "Basics", "user": "degringolade", "content": "I would like to hear your thoughts re:. Is a spell a prayer and vice versa.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8315443", "title": "Re: Basics", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on how you define those very vague English words.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8313907", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Since you mention the I Ching, I figure this is a good opportunity to get your opinion on a divination I did recently with the Book of Changes. My question was \"How am I doing in my occult studies so far?\" and I got hexagram 63 (After Completion) changing to hexagram 37 (The Family) with line 6 moving. My interpretation is as follows:\nIn the I Ching, hexagram 63 indicates a situation that is past the point of no return. The great river has already been crossed. The trigrams are water above and fire below, antagonistic elements that move in opposite directions, bringing to mind the image of a cauldron of water boiling over a fire. This indicates that a force has been unleashed that must now be controlled. The important thing is not to look back, especially considering the text of line 6.\nHexagram 37 relates to the family structure in ancient China, where the man was active outside the household and the woman inside the household. I see this as a metaphor for the psyche as understood in occult philosophy, with the husband representing the Higher Self and the woman the Lower Self. In the judgment text, it is the perseverance of the woman (i.e. the personality in incarnation) towards the goals of the Higher Self that is essential. Alternatively, the second hexagram could also be a more literal reference to the home, as in \"Stay home. This is where you will make the most progress.\"\nDoes this seem reasonable?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8315699", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, but I'm not at all an expert in I Ching divination, so if you're uncertain of your interpretation you probably need to run it past someone who knows the I Ching a good deal better than I do.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8327219", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, if you have just hung a cauldron full of water over the fire, would it not be best to allow the  experienced housekeeping member of the family tend to it minutely and constantly instead of expecting a boiling cauldron to tend to itself while you go out into the world and tend the fields and the livestock? One is put in mind of those amusing tales where the peasant men and women exchange jobs for a day. Who better than the soul within the house can be sure what's cooking away in the hot pot stays at a perfect simmer? Left untended, it could boil over, put out the fire and spoil badly, even turn poisonous with bacteria proliferating in wet warmth instead of killed off by proper heating. Or come out half-cooked and disgusting. Or else boil too hot, get way overdone, and be served up tasteless and unpalatable. Attention to these details of soul-keeping make a big difference in how much healthful nutrition you get out of the pot.\nIn other words, be circumspect, not open, closely tend to matters within, keep up with what you started, don't get above yourself and start expecting public applause and glittering medals just for doing your own hearthkeeping and homework.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8314163", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been reading Gregory Shaw's book on Iamblichus, which you had recommended as a good starting point for someone interested in Neoplatonism. What other books would you recommend for someone who wants to learn more about the subject?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8315955", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Go straight to the source material: Plotinus, Porphyry, Iamblichus, Proclus. Take it a little at a time.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8315187", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I started the first preliminary exercise to meditation from The Art and Practice of Geomancy two weeks ago and am no closer to getting comfortable with the meditation posture. This is probably because I have scoliosis and when I sit up straight my spine doesn't align properly. Would laying down be okay instead?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8316723", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'll have to judge based on your own pain level, but after only two weeks it shouldn't be comfortable yet. One of the points of the posture is that it makes you become aware of the unnecessary tensions in your body, and it does that by making you feel just how uncomfortable your body always was -- you just didn't notice it.\nVery few people can meditate lying down without going to sleep. Still, if the pain level is too high for you to tolerate, you may need to try that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8317747", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Oh I see. I thought the position was supposed to be close to comfortable after two weeks. The pain isn't excruciating or anything so I'll keep at it for a while longer as it does seem sitting reveals the tensions better. I hadn't noticed how much was in my jaw and realized that is probably why I grind my teeth when I sleep.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8319027", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends entirely on how much residual tension you keep in your body. It took me about three months to start relaxing into the posture.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8320307", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hmm, then should I go ahead and start on the breathing exercise or wait?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8321587", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd say go ahead and start work with the breathing. Try to release a little more tension with each outbreath.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8316467", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What kind of changes does it take to be the kind of person who can act at scale, like all those people who get a mention in the history books?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8316979", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on what kind of raw material you're starting with, of course, and what specific way of acting at scale you have in mind.  It's not a one size fits all kind of formula.  The kind of changes that can make you an effective rabblerouser, say, are radically different from those that will make you the kind of intellectual whose ideas every politician will be following unknowingly fifty years down the road.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8318771", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not OP) Piggy-backing on this question, what is the difference in spiritual status between ‘prominent’ figures throughout history like Plato, Bach, Newton, and so on, and the average person? Are the exceptional gifts of the former group a sign that they mastered the human level of incarnation and were on the cusp of moving on to the next level? Conversely, does our relative lack of exceptional achievements mean that we still have a long way to go?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8319539", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It really varies from case to case. In some cases -- for example, Mozart -- it's pretty clear that he put a lot of lives into music and not much else, so he became a musical prodigy but the rest of his life was still a mess. In other cases -- for example, Plato -- it's pretty clear that he was getting ready to check out.\nThat said, every single person I've ever met had the capacity for exceptional achievement in some field, whether that was something prestigious or otherwise. (I've known people who achieved absolute magnificence in fields such as ordinary homestyle cooking and Masonic lodge ritual.) What keeps most of us from achieving magnificence isn't a lack of ability, it's a lack of will and courage.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8323635", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was thinking more middle of the (silk?) road, like those sorts of people who go from being a poor ninth son of a preacher to owning a fleet of merchant ships. Some people seem to just be able to tap into flows of materiel.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8336947", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh, that's simple. If you want to become rich, all you have to do is focus your entire will on becoming rich. Treat every dollar that comes your way as a tool to make more money; wake up every morning asking yourself, \"What can I do today to earn more money\"; be constantly watching for opportunities to increase your income and get rid of unnecessary expenditures and risks, and put getting rich ahead of everything else in life. You'll be rich sooner than you can imagine.\nIf you read the biographies of those poor kids who became merchant princes, you'll find that that's how they did it -- they didn't sit around waiting for the world to make them rich, or expect to do it in the few moments they could spare from hanging out with friends or wasting money. They flung all their efforts into becoming rich, and achieved it. If that's what you want out of life, you can do the same thing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8373299", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Every time you note this (which I've observed), it reminds me of the English version of the PA Dutch proverb--literally translated \"What you get/take, that's what you have\".  The common English version is \"take what you will and pay what you must.\"\nSamChevre", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8373811", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a good proverb. I think it was William Walker Atkinson who said that the gods show every human soul all the treasures of the cosmos, and say: \"Take what you want, and pay for it!\"", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8317235", "title": "Geomantic Magic Diamonds", "user": "emmanuelg", "content": "Hi JMG and all--\nI have a blog post that gives the basics of using Geomancy in Magic Squares for divination.  I don't fully understand it myself, so any insights anyone has about this are welcome.  Hopefully it will turn out to be useful :-)\nThe title is 'Geomantic Magic Diamonds' on my blog, here;\nhttps://emmanuelg.dreamwidth.org/\n--EG", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8319795", "title": "Re: Geomantic Magic Diamonds", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you for this! I'll check it out Tuesday -- tomorrow I'll be answering questions. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8380979", "title": "Re: Geomantic Magic Diamonds", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks!\nNo worries--Any observations greatly appreciated! :-))", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8318003", "title": "Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "chronojourner", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI just finished your translation (along with Christopher Warnock’s) translation of the Picatrix and I have a question.\nFirst, let me say that I found the work extremely interesting and a great insight into the culture and time period (the tenth century Islamic world).  However, I also found it rather disturbing.  Not because of the animal sacrifice, though I’m sure that would disturb a lot of modern practitioners.  What I found disturbing is what I perceive as very simplistic (almost Harry Potteresque) representation in many of the recipes.  To put it bluntly, either the original author was extraordinarily gullible, or he was using s lot of fake information to hide the real esoteric materials he was trying to impart.  I’m inclined to think the latter for two reasons.  First, all of the prospective authors have good reputations for scholarship, meaning that they were unlikely to be extraordinarily gullible; and two, I don’t think a document lacking real esoteric wisdom (some of which I could see without too much effort) would have survived more than a thousand years and been incorporated into so many subsequent works.\nBut I wanted to get your opinion on it.  I think that many of the recipes requiring strange, exotic, and often toxic materials are intended to lead the uninitiated astray  (which I think you guys suggested in the introduction) and to hide the real meanings behind the text, as well as the portions that hold the accurate materials.  What do you think?  Am I warm?  Because if, in fact, those recipes were intended to be taken seriously, it must have really sucked to be a chicken in a town full of perspective wizards in tenth and eleventh century Al Andalus, especially if you were a rooster with a divided comb.\nOh, and I used your Pangalactic New Age Soul Signature Generator, so I will sign off under my nom de mage,\n-- Puce Transcendent Puppy (AKA, Lenn)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8320563", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's important not to insert modern ways of thinking about the world into texts like Picatrix. We tend to think of \"esoteric meanings\" as referring entirely to the mind and spirit, and material references as wholly exoteric and probably \"blinds.' They didn't think that way. Are you familiar with the doctrine of signatures? If not, the short version is that the material form of a thing -- for example, the divided comb on a rooster -- was a reflection of the spiritual energies that brought that thing into being.\nSo a lot of the recipes in Picatrix do seem to be intended to be used as given. They are, in important ways, comparable to hoodoo workings (which of course also involve a lot of animal parts and the like). The higher dimension of the work, which is of course woven into the text in ways that make it hard to tease out, can be found in the rituals of spiritual and planetary initiation given in the text -- and of course there are things in there that are deliberate blinds, and in fact deathtraps for the foolish.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8382259", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "chronojourner", "content": "Thanks, JMG.  This puts it more into perspective for me.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8325939", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "mmelvink", "content": "Just to chime in as well: It should be kept in mind that the\nPicatrix\nin its Castilian Spanish then Latin translations is not overly faithful to Maslama al-Qurtubi's (d. 964) Arabic original, the\nGoal of the Sage\n(\nGhayat al-hakim\n) -- it's rather shorter, with many deletions and additions, and the more difficult theoretical sections are often garbled (a very common feature of Arabic-to-Latin translations). Some of the grossest operations are among those bits added, so reflect not tenth-century Andalusian Islamic culture but rather the thirteenth-century Latin Christian culture of the translators. In other words, the Latin version is a somewhat darker and less philosophically sophisticated book than the Arabic original, which continued to be popular as a manual of natural philosophy down to the colonial period. It's definitely less Harry Potteresque! ;)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8337203", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course! Since I know Latin rather than Arabic, though, I translated the text I had to hand -- and of course it was some consolation that I was working with the same text that inspired Marsilio Ficino, Giordano Bruno, Simon Forman, and Elias Ashmole, among many others.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8339763", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "mmelvink", "content": "Oh, needless to say! Just thought I'd clarify that it's not as representative of tenth-century Andalusian Islamic culture as the OP assumed, understandably, since the Arabic original has yet to be translated into English or even properly edited, bizarrely but predictably enough. But yes: it's a testament to the power of the text that it was still able to inspire those European greats even in truncated and garbled form! Books are living beings after all, whatever their descent...\nSpeaking of which, I'm sure there are more recent grimoires for which the same principle holds -- its core shines through despite all the vicissitudes of transmission. Any you'd put in the same category?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8370483", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "If someone translated it I'd buy it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8374067", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a scholarly translation of the Arabic\nGhayat al-Hakim\nin process -- iirc it'll be out this year or next year.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8374579", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "Nice :D", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8382515", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "chronojourner", "content": "Liana Saif is working on it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8382771", "title": "Re: Your Translation of Picatrix", "user": "chronojourner", "content": "Thanks for chiming in.  I knew there were differences between the versions, but had not realized that they were that different.  This helps me understand the document better.  I'm definitely looking forward to Dr. Saif's translation.  Thanks again!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8318259", "title": "LBRP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey jmg\nI asked about the meaning behind how the god names in the LBRP are used and I think I’ve cracked it.\nThey channel solar and telluric currents, east to west represents the solar current shooting from the sun then passing into space, and south to north is the telluric currents flowing through the earth.\nJ.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8320819", "title": "Re: LBRP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly interpret it that way!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8322355", "title": "Re: LBRP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So it is a valid interpretation? But also not the only one?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8337459", "title": "Re: LBRP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What a fine theme for meditation!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8318515", "title": "Druidry", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and Readers,\nI had a bad dream a few nights ago where I was in a situation of great conflict caused by my unthinking pursuit of pleasure and in my dream I thought of a line, from The Meditations (Marcus Aurelius), about being jerked by the puppet strings of emotion.   The dream was very lucid but I felt I was looking back on my former life.\nWhen I woke up, I realized it has been such a long time since I had a bad dream or a bad day.  The quality of my life is so drastically improved since I took up the study of Druidry, especially the discursive meditation but a lot of natural magic too.\nI have new, keen eyes to look at the beauties of nature and I am enjoying my life in a way I never thought possible.  I had been unhappy and dissatisfied for most of my life.  Now, I am happy all the time and practice magic throughout the day, just for the pleasure of it.\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8321331", "title": "Re: Druidry", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. That's one of the core goals of the work!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8344883", "title": "Re: Druidry", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Maxine, I feel the same way.  I have to remind myself what it was to be severely depressed, and that was most of my life before Druidry.  My innate sensitivity helps instead of hurts; it has gone from curse to blessing.  Druidry helps me to protect myself from hostile or bumbling-but-dangerous forces while communicating with both unseen beings and understanding the limits of the real people in my life.  In short, I'm finally home.\nJMG, thank you so much for your work, which was my introduction to Druids and Druidry.  It has been life-changing.  May you continue to positively affect more and more people.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8345907", "title": "Re: Druidry", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're welcome and thank you.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8321075", "title": "Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been haphazardly meditating on how and whether the local First Nation (a Coastal Salish group) cosmology fits into the Qabalistic system, as Fortune says Crowley called the Qabbalah a perfect file system, and one can better understand how anything works (better) in the cosmos if you can determine where it fits on the Tree.\nI got sidetracked in Fortune's polarity discussions in the CosDoc - to start, I’ve been thinking about the gender of the earth, moon and sun and other natural forces. Something universal about what these bodies represent in terms of Force and Form, Active and Passive looks compelling using Egyptian, Greek and Christian cosmology, as well as bits of the other European myth structures I was familiar with (which isn’t saying much, granted), which usually had the Moon and Earth as a Feminine force, and the Sun as Masculine. The Coast Salish, however, did not seem to originally gender/anthropomorphize the Earth much, but one anthropological account I found had it as male, and the Moon and Sun are consistently male and female, respectively. Happypandatao has also said on the Other Blog that Hindu female deities are active and male are passive, so it’s not even necessarily universal to proto-indo-european root cosmology to assign the Force/Active and Form/Passive gender split the same way… I think that I have a good hypothesis for this discrepancy that fits based on the law of the planes from the Cosmic Doctrine and Qabbalistic system, and wanted to run it by you –\nHumans that developed agriculture live by the Sun cycle. Thus, the sun-force to agriculturalists is Active to their lives, and, as they are people who markedly reshape the earth, their livestock, and crops to meet their needs, they conceive of themselves as relatively Active on a relatively Passive landscape (taken to high extremes with our culture’s concept as The active force and everything else entirely Inert). So they identify the Sun, as the body that governs/sparks their activities, with Force, male principle. The nature forces of Life, that are receptive to that Force in the life-circuit in the worldview of the agriculturalist are thus feminine – the Moon, the Earth.  (As indeed the Earth eventually gets conceived as passive and receptive to us.)\nHumans that practiced primarily hunting and gathering, with limited intensive practices that were more about tweaking a natural process than directing it (clam gardens, controlled burning, pruning and thinning food forests, rice aquaculture) were governed by the Lunar cycles (e.g. the 13 Moons of the WSANEC harvest cycle), and what the Earth is already doing – thus Earth and Moon are the source of the Force that humans are subject to. Since the Sun-Moon/Earth relationship is still known as a force circuit, therefore, the Sun becomes Female… I guess. Representative of the heavens, the Form that contains the world? I haven’t seen anything in their stories to suggest one way or the other if the Sun as actually receptive to the Moon actually makes sense, or if they would just have it because of the intrinsic need to recognize the polarity. However, another explanation presents itself by looking back to the Tree, where we see a universal applicability in the heavenly body that serves as a symbol of Tiphareth in the Sun…\nTiphareth is the highest concept of god humans can perceive directly, and it’s a human-shaped concept, because it’s shaped to fit our minds.  For a society that views itself as Passive to the natural forces in their life, they might make the Tiphareth astrological body Passive/Female as well, as the highest human-shaped godform perceivable – and, crucially, receptive then, in a circuit not with the Earth and Moon, but to the still higher forms of godhead that we can’t perceive directly.\nIf I’m onto something about the way that humans get their food determining the way they perceive the polarity of natural forces, and thus intuiting the existence of higher planes of the cosmos more easily… then it does give some credence to Daniel Quinn’s theory that the invention of agriculture was the Fall. Earning our keep by the sweat of our brow, and needing to have scads of kids to work the fields - greatly multiplying Eve’s pain in childbirth, as it were – was not an arbitrary punishment, it was the Thing itself -what naturally followed from the Knowledge. Something that was a natural outgrowth of our development as humans, but that would inevitably cut off our connection to higher planes of the cosmos through our understanding reflected through ourselves. Something that, then, we would have to work our way back to as part of our evolution, because at some point we’d have to merge our idea of ourselves as materially like god as active principle in the cosmos, at the nadir of involution. (The Hindus, of course, have a very advanced spiritual system, and old agricultural practice, so perhaps had already gone further than other human cultures on working out that forces switch polarities further up the planes, heading back up the path of evolution ahead).\nI like my little theory, but I still balk at it, because it still looks too much like it buys into the hunter-gatherers are more ‘primitive’ than agriculturalists mindset, or, conversely, the noble savage because agriculturalists are thus Fallen. I suppose it all just comes back to the fact that it’s not really that we tried to control nature as a binary between Good Savages who didn’t and Evil people who did, but rather that all human cultures have had to find the balance of how much control, and when to be active and when passive relative to the forces we work with. I suppose the hunter gatherers who made their giant mammal prey go extinct after the ice age could also be people who Fell by cranking their entitlement to nature up to 11… for that matter, all of the Turtle Island myths about ‘that time humans got arrogant or lazy and didn’t hold their end of the compact with the gods and had a flood/drought/something that made them realise the error of their ways’ would fall in their. So each culture could have started back the evolutionary track regardless of specifically agriculture…\nUh… so the question is… am I onto something, or er, just engaging in mental onanism…?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8321843", "title": "Re: Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're engaging in a useful process of grappling with symbolism. Don't take the results too seriously -- anything you can put in words is not what the symbols are meant to teach you, but you have to go through the words to get to what's beyond them.\nInteresting that the Coast Salish traditions you know of identify the Sun as female! In the Salish myths I know best -- the ones from south Puget Sound -- Moon is the Changer, and male; the Sun is his younger brother, also male. Of course there are lots of variation from one tribal group to another...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8328243", "title": "Re: Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "daveotn", "content": "Sorry if this is too far off-topic, but this subject always makes me think of Tolkien's comment that hobbits and elves viewed the Sun as female. Hobbits are agriculturalists, of course, but the elves are the mother culture and they seem much more like hunter-gatherers.\nSome scholars believe Tolkien borrowed the female Sun for hobbits from Norse traditions, where Sunna is female. I'm no expert on the topic, but I imagine that Dark Age Norsemen did a little bit of agriculture but supplemented it with quite a bit of fishing, hunting, and herding.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8335155", "title": "Re: Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Continental Scandinavia supported itself by agriculture far more than by anything else during the so-called  \"Dark Ages,\" except in the far North and the West coast of Norway.  Iceland not so much, and it is in Iceland that most of our sources for Norse mythology and history were composed.  The few early continental Scandinavian sources that we have for that same mythology and history--Saxo Grammaticus, for instance--differ rather strikingly from the Icelandic sources in many significant ways.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8338483", "title": "Re: Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The Norse did do a good amount of agriculture. They grew barley, which was both eaten and used to brew beer, along with oats and rye, and in the milder climes, wheat. They were also sophisticated enough farmers to employ crop rotation: http://www.vikinganswerlady.com/food.shtml", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8382003", "title": "Re: Agriculture as the Fall again?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "well fiddlesticks. There goes my theory! ;-)\nI will have to read more, but in the anthropology collection I had read, the WSANEC people's Creator god XALS is also a changer figure, though not associated with any astrological body that I can find. He tends to walk the landscape and (to my sense) randomly and arbitrarily change people into rocks (though not randomly to the Saanich, I assume - each rock was a key navigationaly feature or territorial boundary marker, hard to discern why now to my eyes). He also created all the animals and plants the people used by picking up people and hucking them into the ocean or plonking them into the soil, instructing them to continue caring for their relatives, which seems a clear enough instructional story. I think the Puget Sound groups spent more time being enemies with the local groups here than friends, but more time being friends that groups further north up the Strait (though they have saved another related group about 60 km away from cultural death, re-teaching them their oral traditions which were lost in the disease outbreaks).\nThe Shaker Church is also alive and well, here. There's one just down the road.\nI guess more than anything this place seems to like mixing and change, and vast explicit webs of interrelatedness - when you recite your umpteen generations of ancestors, you also mention alllist the other nations they came from proudly. So you'll have people now tell you they're Salish, Cowichan, Penelakut, German, Irish and Norwegian. That seems very Norwegian too... perhaps there's something else underlying that makes these cultures see things similarly... hmmmm....", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8322099", "title": "Nostradamus", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello\nWhat do you make of the quatrins of Nostradamus?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8338227", "title": "Re: Nostradamus", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "These days?  Toilet tissue.  ;-)\nSeriously, you can bend the quatrains of Nostradamus around to kind of predict things that have happened, but when he gives a date his prophecies are inevitably duds. Do you recall this one?\n\"The year 1999, seventh month,\nFrom the sky will come a great king of terror\nTo resuscitate the king of Angolmois.\nBefore and after, Mars reigns by chance.\"\nI've been amused to watch people desperately stretch to redefine 1999 as 2001 and twist \"Angolmois\" around to mean just about anything you care to name, but no great king of terror showed up in July of 1999, you know.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8322611", "title": "Plato and \"God\"", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m reading a dialog of Plato, Phaedo, translated by Hugh Tredennick, and I’m stuck on a simple question: On the second page, there is the line “I could not help feeling that even on his [the soul of Socrates] way to the other world he would be under the providence of God…”; note that “God” is with a capital G. Now God was strictly a Jewish deity at that time, so why is he being referred to when we know the ancient Greeks had their pantheon with Zeus as the supreme deity? Did the translator simply translate “Zeus” as “God”, or is he referring to Hermes who escorted newly departed souls to the realm of the afterlife, or is something else afoot? More generally, can you recommend a companion or guide to Plato?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8338739", "title": "Re: Plato and \"God\"", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In ancient Greek literature it's common to see the term\ntheos\n, \"god,\" used as a generic label for divine presence. Honest translations into English turn that into \"a god\" or \"the god,\" but there's been a lot of stealth Christianization of the ancient Greeks, and this is a good example. The actual text reads θείας μοίρας, \"a divine summons,\" the whole passage is translated\nhere\nas \"I thought that in going to the other world he could not be without a divine call...\" So the Jewish deity -- whom nobody in Plato's time called by the English word \"God,\" by the way! -- was never involved.\nAs for a good companion or guide to Plato, depends on what you're looking for. There's a huge literature on the subject, and it's been long enough since I dipped into it that I'm not sure what to recommend. Anyone else?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8355379", "title": "Re: Plato and \"God\"", "user": "kataskion", "content": "Well, this is just odd. My partner is currently reading the Phaedo and asked me exactly this question the other night, phrased very similarly. We're also reading Gregory Shaw's book on Iamblichus together right now (see a few questions back). He often asks questions here, always anonymously. I assumed these both were his questions.\nI just talked to him and said, \"hey, did you see JMG answered your questions?\" and he looked at me blankly and said \"I didn't ask any questions this week.\" I'm not assigning anything too meaningful to this coincidence, but it makes me feel warm and happy to know that there are strangers out there following the same trails we are. Tracks in space!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8322867", "title": "Postive thoughts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr Greer,\nAbout 2 years ago you gave another reader some excellent advice regarding the self-reinforcing nature of having a negative outlook on life (https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/29585.html?thread=1680273#cmt1680273). This topic has been a struggle for me as well, for my whole adult life.\nOn the one hand I feel that having a pessimistic outlook takes the sting out of bad things happening, since I have anticipated them already and on the other I feel that having an optimistic outlook is only possible when disregarding the state of the world, possibly bordering on being ignorant.\nI'm familiar with the concept of \"ternary thinking\" but I'm unable to see the way of combining these two extremes of thinking into a third way that connects both ideas.\nI was wondering if you had any advice on how to get past the trap of binary thinking around a positive life outlook?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8336691", "title": "Re: Postive thoughts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"If I keep a green bough in y heart, the songbird will surely come.\" Chinese proverb.\nMaxine", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8338995", "title": "Re: Postive thoughts", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. Every day, choose one situation of the kind you tend to brood about, and write out the worst realistic outcome you can think of -- one or two paragraphs is enough. Then write out the best realistic outcome you can think of -- and make it realistic, not pie in the sky.  Then write out a third outcome that falls halfway between the two.\nKeep doing this day after day. At intervals, glance back over what you've written and compare your written outcomes to what actually happened. Notice where what actually happened tends to fall on the worst<-->middle<-->best spectrum.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8323123", "title": "Planetary charity", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have to give to the same organization each time when practising planetary charity for a number of weeks? Can it be different charities all to do with the same cause, or different causes connected to the same planet?\nWhat are causes connected with the Sun? The lists of people on the Renaissance Astrology website do not sound like they are in need of charity. Upkeep of historic buildings (where the nobility used to live) sounds most closely connected but I don't know for sure. Lion conservation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8339251", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, you can make donations to several charities supporting several causes as long as it's all the same planet.\n2) The Sun's a tough one! Yes, most solar people don't need charities. Consider supporting a nonprofit that supports solar energy research, or a charity devoted to eagles and other birds of prey, who are solar as well. Yes, a lion sanctuary would also be a good choice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8341811", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Lady Cutekitten)\nWould a charity for ex-sailors work?  I’ve known several ex-Navy men who got skin cancer—not only are they out in the sun aboard ship, but they get a double dose from the sun reflecting off the water.  And commercial sailors, especially those from 3rd World countries, rarely get medical or retirement benefits.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8342835", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not a traditional Solar charity, but if divination indicates it's a good option, sure.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8341555", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "I want to make a Free Joe Exotic joke here but instead I'll just hint at one.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8342579", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm. That just went whizzing right over my head.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8343603", "title": "Re: Planetary charity", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Well, it's a netflix show about people who keep big cats, so since you don't do visual media that makes sense. It's a ridiculous, absurd spectacle that blew up lately.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8323379", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hi JMG\nFirst of all thank you to our host and all those who make this such an enjoyable and informative read every week.\nNow to my questions.\n1) I recall a tower shaped device related to radionics which improved the fertility of the surrounding land. I remember seeing that you've used it somewhere. Could you please remind me what its called?\n2) I'm thinking of choosing a set of 8 stones to buy from the local rock shop for the stations of the wheel of life as in . Are there any in particular associated with each station? If the planetary corospondances are used to chose what would you use for Imbolic as it corospondes to earth rather than another planet. I have your ENM for reference.\n3) Many thanks to the commented who gave us the links to the wonderful paintings for meditation on the zodiac signs. JMG Would you, or anyone else, know of any similar ones for the planets?\n4) Finally, I have bought several of your WOH books as e-books. To get a friend to read one of them I sent them a copy of one of them, in the same way that you might give a paper copy to a friend. I've only done it this once. I'm just double checking that this is fine with you and your anti book theft working.\nMany thanks for all your work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8339507", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) A Hieronymus earth pipe. Look up the writings of T. Galen Hieronymus and you'll find the directions; somewhere around here I have a picture I took of the corn in my backyard in Cumberland MD, which grew 11-13 feet high the season after I installed the earth pipe.\n2) Planetary correspondences are fine. For the Imbolc station, use something fossil-bearing -- that corresponds to Earth.\n3) I wish I did.\n4) That's fine, but please don't make a habit of circulating e-copies.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8367923", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Great, thanks very much!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8379955", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "2) Will the temperature and zodiac sign of a stone as listed in the ENM make any difference?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8381235", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not really.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8362547", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "These might be close enough. They are etchings rather than paintings but colored ones are available too and they look gorgeous. I didn’t really take a good look besides a google search but he does have one for each of the seven major planets and the moon concerning their interpretation in Renaissance astrology.\nhttps://www.theeternalcircle.net/johann-sadeler-planetary-effects/\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-21 12:02 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8380211", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Great, thanks!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8323891", "title": "Two questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings, dear JMG!\n1) Do you by any chance have plans to publish CGD-compatible hexagram rituals in the future? During the last four weeks, I've managed to surprise myself by conjuring four elemental intelligence-spirit pairs for introductory discussions and would be very interested in extending my experiments to their planetary colleagues...\n2) In \"Osiris and Christ\" you state that \"[i]n the place of blood sacrifices [...] while opening up the higher possibilities of his or her ng\" (Hermes 169-70). What is ng?\nMany thanks, as always!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8343091", "title": "Re: Two questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, in the CGD system we don't work with planetary energies, and invoke the Spheres of the Tree using an Octagram ritual instead. If you pick up a copy of my newly published book\nThe Mysteries of Merlin\nthat's covered there.\n2) A typo. It should have been \"being.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8324147", "title": "Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have an 8 year old son who is very much the opposite of me at that age. I was a nerdy bookish kid who learnt to read so early I can't remember not reading, who did math in his head and followed all the rules etc. My son is pretty much the opposite - a gregarious \"jock\" who is good at every sport he plays, very charming and great insight into people, but a late reader, behind on math in school etc (possibly with a touch of low self-esteem about his academic achievements). He is intelligent - some times he says things with the most astonishing insight - especially about people.\nHis key issues appear to be lack of self-control (especially emotional regulation) and lack of focus (almost the same thing really). Those lead to everything else.\nHe's basically the poster child for a \"fixed mindset\" child instead of \"growth mindset\" - he's the kind of kid who will tell you how amazing he is at [X] and then try do X and fail and give up immediately calling himself \"stupid\" and melting down without seriously practicing or trying (he's good at soccer and loves to talk about becoming a professional - and he may actually have the talent as confirmed by his coach at school - but he *certainly* doesn't have the necessary discipline to train properly).\nIt's really hard for me to deal with him because I was literally the opposite and all his weaknesses were my strengths and vice versa so I struggle with what to teach him - everything he struggles with came naturally to me and vice versa.\nAll of that is an introduction to saying that I have been doing discursive meditation based on your instructions on and off for a few months now and I have started to get him to \"meditate\" for the last week or so. That is, I make him sit down in one place without lying down or moving and just look at the wall for 10-15 mins.\nHe's slowly getting better at that, and I am thinking about telling him to imagine a soccer game in his head in detail during meditation (because he loves soccer).\nIs there any other feasible way to get kids to do meditation? I am less interested in the symbolic magical stuff for him and more in just getting him to train his self-discipline, concentration, focus etc.\nAny other ideas or suggestions or exercises for discipline and focus etc appreciated.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8334899", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Not JMG, and have no advice, but waiting eagerly for any replies, as we face a similar situation with our kids: 2 bookish parents, totally overwhelmed and outgunned by our gregarious and energetic 2nd son...  my sympathies!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8352051", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had a kid like that.  Athletically and academically gifted, no patience.\nThen he discovered ballet, and fell in love, and raw talent wasn't enough, so he had to learn to focus and work.\nAnd that was all.  He still is himself, but he can throw himself into his dance with all the focus required.  He was invited to dance at the Bolshoi summer program in NYC this summer, after a mere five years of ballet study.  As I explained to sports sister-in-law, that's like being invited to go spend six weeks training with the Olympic trainers.\nThis is a good place to pass along a parenting thank you on behalf of said son to Brother Greer.  He asked how to explain how to develop self-control to a friend who had asked.  I paraphrased your advice on the very first bits of will training, and tmy son thought that over and said it made sense and he'd pass it along.  I said I got it from a Druid and Master Mason I know, and he, being a DeMolay, wanted to know how a Druid could be a Master Mason?  \"Supreme Being, not God of any specific religion.  Most pantheons have a top god.\"  So he has something else to think about, besides whether or not the state department is going to let him go dance (teachers coming from Russia).\nBoysMom", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8343347", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Remember that I have no living children and have never spent much time around kids. I really have no idea what to suggest. Anybody else?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8358963", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "According to Jung, children who enter a family often occupy the psychic space that the parents do NOT occupy already. Sort of like expanding into the power vacuum, or a soap bubble that can only take the shape of the empty space other bubbles are not in.\nSo you can go about this process of relating to your Other-ish kids is several ways.\n1) You can spend the time and experience the awkwardness of developing the parts of your Totality that you are not good at -- -- becoming a more rounded and complete person. Your kid who has the native skills will likely try to help you grow up, so to speak into their world. By accepting their help, you open up the space for reciprocity and they may be more willing to accept your help in areas where they struggle. You also will create space for them to grow in areas that your already extant expertise is 'blocking' from their perspective.\n2) You can meditate or pray and seek guidance to find out what set of skills your kid needs to develop in order to get a good solid start on a balanced and satisfying life. This will means sometimes playing to their strengths and encouraging them to Do The Work and reach far beyond what native gifts provide to help them achieve true excellence. Sometimes it will take the form of playing to their weaknesses and using their frustration and dismay to develop coping skills with negative emotions, avoiding punishing self-talk, learning 'tricks of the trade' that help you get by in an area you know you are weak in (like a finger-knuckle abacus for double-checking your poor mental arithmetic), and developing the calm self-acceptance that enables a person to be a good sport and appreciate other people's abilities. Deep breathing before tackling a challenging task or learning a new skill can be one such trick of the trade. What else do YOU use to create concentration and focus when you give a public talk or other task you are not naturally good at?\n3) You can seek out tutors and masters in religious, spiritual, or martial art formats to help both you and your kids to strengthen the inner core that gives you self guidance and try not to worry as you develop these inward muscles of the soul.\n4) You can teach yourself and your kid to use dreamwork, divination, artwork, to explore inner dimensions when the masters are not there to train and correct your beginning efforts.\n5) You can spend time doing practical things together like regular chores, repairing things, making toys out of junk, building bird houses, go-carts, tool safety and clean-up, using a slide rule, etc. Likewise, shared physical things like fishing, hunting, bird watching, scouting, camping, map-making, and storytelling around the campfire.  Physical attunement can bleed over into psychic attunement. Jon Young says that kids who are easily distracted make the best scouts because they are alert and aware to any changes or differences in the environment.\n6) You can daily ask for help and guidance towards the best way to love those around you. This is the hardest path and the most sure.\nNo matter what mode of parenting you choose, it will take a lot of time and work and personal growth in your own soul. It requires nearly all the energy you have to create a healthy adult from the raw material of a child. You might need help from friends, relations and neighbors to achieve the best results. Ask for it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8351283", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "dreamstrike13", "content": "Your son sounds like me. Marital Arts/boxing has been fantastic for my self-control, although you'll need pick wisely. Good rule of thumb is to avoid large ostentatious facilities, all the teachers I have been inspired by taught in very humble training gyms/dojos.  Boy Scouts was fun too.\nIn one of JMG book he discusses walking meditation which might be useful. I'd suggest meeting him on common ground, so if he has a soccer star he's a fan of, getting him to read about how they got to the level of expertise and try and let your son find ways of implement that into his soccer training where he already has a degree of success , then using that blueprint as a means of discussing improvement in other areas? aka your 10k reps. I despised those color coded reading books at school, but wanted to read Jurassic Park even though I couldn't. Comic books were very helpful too.\nAt that age I remember everyone telling me to do this, or that and I'd explicitly do the opposite out of sheer obstinance. Perhaps asking him to help with your fitness, or ball-handling skills could be a way in to him asking for your help in other areas? Just started the book Atomic Habits, which so far has much interesting insight into habit formation as I'm starting to think about all this for my toddlers. GL !!! :)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8356403", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few thoughts come to my mind:\nIf you want your son to meditate, I suppose it could happen that at some point he might just work out the scheme amazing at [X], failing at [X], melting down, with [X] being meditation of course. Could it be that what you really want for him is not to do meditation but to be meditative? Since your son seems to have a strong desire to use his body, why not use this as a vehicle? What about martial arts? I used to practice martial arts as well as train a group of kids (6+). If you can find a good dojo, which is not only into sports ad fighting but also uses martial arts as a way to develop human qualities - concentration, self discipline, patience, resilience, these are the things you can learn there. They might also meditate, at least we did, even with the small kids. And as an aside, you can really boost your bodies abilities and learn a lot of the skills a good soccer player needs ;-)\nGood luck!\nNachtgurke", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8372019", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I am the original poster, the father.\nThank you to everyone especially Anonymous, Nachtgurke and Dreamstrike - there's a lot to take in there and I'm going to meditate on it myself and give it more thought! But I just wanted to post a reply and a thank you before Magic Monday closed.\nIt's funny everyone has said martial arts - as it happens, martial arts is *my* passion and while I've been pretty desk-bound and \"in my head\" for most of my life, in the last year or two I've taken up martial arts myself as a pretty serious (daily) endeavour.\nMy son was one of the reasons for it - as Anonymous said - but not the only one. It's been tremendously helpful for me to engage my own physicality and learn about that side of life, so that I can kind of meet him halfway and \"lead\" him through it. He does indeed come to my dojo and take the kids classes and I spend some time teaching him at home too (which he loves although I am far from an expert still).\nHe likes the martial arts and enjoys it (especially when I teach him - sometimes he struggles in classes where the teachers don't have a \"strong\" enough personality to capture the attention of a wilful high-energy kid and discipline him properly - but he loves the teachers who can keep him in line and teach him). THe same issues as elsewhere apply too - if he doesn't get something immediately he tends to give up easily even though he is talented (he was moved up to sparring with older heavier kids very quickly because he was just better than the other newbies).\nSo the martial arts is definitely good - he likes anything physical like that but he doesn't have the inherent passion for it that he does for soccer. He's not reading books (picture books) or watching endless Youtube videos about it like soccer.\nBut anyway I will meditate on and implement the suggestions given here - much appreciated, thank you.\nI was more asking about how to adapt meditation for children - never expected such a broad variety of advice - this is great.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8384307", "title": "Re: Kids meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maybe my comment can be of some use:\nI've been on the \"other end\" as a teacher, mostly of young men (military academies).\nThe most amazing breakthroughs, recognitions, moments of real and surprising insights happened just after I backed off.\nMeaning I changed a paper from graded to pass/fail.  (The sullen kid from Hawaii wrote that at this point, having seen what we threw at him, he did not feel ready to take on being an officer, the whole mess that goes with that.)\nIt was really intuitive.  Genuine respect matters.  Giving them room to experiment and fail, being honest, all those demonstrated, embodied qualities matter.\nMeaning I gave the kids (students) a task, then faded into the background, simply listening, acknowledging. (Of course, those were rare times given the curriculum.)\nChildren, like most animals, imprint on someone.  Maybe the\nquestion isn't about your son.  Your son will likely copy your behaviors in a few decades.  Can you give yourself room to play, just a bit, without judgment, a bit of space to breathe?\nI've found parent ego to be a consistent, perennial stumbling block (and, thus, useful for meditation).", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8324659", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG\nI have finally completed learning the SoP ritual as set out on this blog, using the Greek pantheon, and am doing the whole thing daily.\nYou mention on a number of occasions the need to combine this practice with meditation and scrying. I have practised traditional (breath-based- meditation for a very long time, and I also consult the I Ching frequently. Will that do, or must I now change, for example, to discursive meditation to benefit fully? Is it possible to vary the kinds of meditation?\nThank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8343859", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That choice is entirely up to you. Discursive meditation has a lot of benefits, but if you've got a well-established practice in a different kind of meditation you may be better off sticking with that. Have you considered consulting the I Ching for advice?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8324915", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I completed over the last two weeks the working to awaken the telluric and solar currents as outlined in the DMH, starting with the telluric current. I've noticed a few things so far:\n- For a couple of days after awakening the telluric current, I felt a sense of well being, but after that there was what I can only describe as a backlash: I went through a few days of being in a really bad mood, my anxieties were heightened, and in a few situations I even acted like a petulant child. The period passed, and reflecting on it now, I see that these traits are some of the negative ways the lower self can express itself.\nI awakened the solar current yesterday, and I still feel good today, but if the same pattern holds, then in a couple of days I should start to feel some arrogance and sense of superiority (negative solar traits), unless now that I've done both workings, the solar and telluric currents should now balance each other out. Does this normally happen with these workings?\n- Invoking Spirit Below during the regular SOP now really packs a wallop! It's interesting to me how the later rituals in the DMH act as 'level-ups' to aspects of the SOP. I had the image that the SOP itself through time 'blooms' like a plant.\n- Because this past week I've been meditating daily to prepare myself for the solar current working, and I've been using purple color breathing, for some reason I had a bunch of insignificant moments where I could predict things about to happen, including a moment where a couple of seconds beforehand, I 'knew' that my wife was about to receive a phone call, and she did. I There were a number of other similar moments all weekend. TSW!\n- My wife, although she doesn't really believe in what I'm doing with the DMH, is approaching my practice with good humour. I told her that I was about to go and awaken the solar current, and she reminded me to wear extra sunscreen.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8344115", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "All of these are normal although not inevitable experiences. See if you can ride herd on the tendency to solar imbalance if it shows up -- that's useful training.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8325171", "title": "Tarot paths", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I think I'll have to get that Grey book.\nIve never really gelled with the Fool at the top and so on.\nJust on the Tarot, as a question to all, regarding the RWS 3 of swords, you always hear it referring to heartbreak.\nIve never really got this. It's the suit of the mind, thinking etc.\nIt makes more sense to me to see it as the head triumphing over the heart.\nLogic over emotion. Not that that's easy or anything and may still involve some anguish, but not necessarily in the very \"Cups\" way that it is usually framed.\nAnyway that's my two cents worth!\nAnyone else see it like that?\nHelen in Oz", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8344627", "title": "Re: Tarot paths", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I tend to see it as a somewhat harsher version of that. Upright -- I do card reversals with Tarot -- it's a situation where you need to ignore your emotions and act on reason even if it hurts. Reversed, it's a situation where you should be paying attention to your emotions but your rational self is getting in the way. Of course your mileage may vary!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8354611", "title": "Re: Tarot paths", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ever considered writing a book on Tarot? Everyone else has..", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8359987", "title": "Re: Tarot paths", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "For that very reason, getting a new one published is very difficult. Editors tear their hair out when yet another proposal for yet another introductory book on Tarot comes over the transom...", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8325427", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIf the planes are strictly discrete, then how come some chemical substances can induce mystical states of consciousness?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8345395", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "For the same reason that you can think of a word (an astral activity) and type it with your fingers (a physical activity, mediated by the etheric plane). The planes are discrete but there are points of contact between them, and chemicals can induce pseudomystical states of consciousness by exploiting some of them. (I've been around way too many acidheads to believe that said chemicals induce actual mystical states.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8347699", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not necessarily drugs, but also burning of incenses in rituals must be activating the same points of contact.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8354355", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Or slightly different ones, yes.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8325683", "title": "Astrology and personality types", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr Greer and all, I've recently started exploring natal chart readings for myself and some loved ones, and am finding it fascinating and enlightening. It also reminds me quite a lot of the learnings I took away from a training course years ago where I categorised myself according to the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator. I'm wondering what your experiences with, or impressions of, personality typing like MBTI or Enneagram are, and whether you know of any worthwhile sources that attempt to map or otherwise integrate one or more system like that with astrology?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8345651", "title": "Re: Astrology and personality types", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's something I've never looked into -- astrology seems intricate enough all by itself! Anybody else?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8326195", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If treating our pets well helps them develop towards consciousness, does that happen in other relationships? For example the plants in your garden, or even using stone for sculpture and architecture? What if the relationship is spiritual, like an apis bull, a sacred tree or sacred stone?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8346163", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so. The more fully and consciously we interact with everything around us, the more we assist the souls in those bodies to pursue their own spiritual evolution.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8326451", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A while back you said if someone does occultism seriously for a couple of lifetimes they'll gain a lot of abilities. But then they may choose to use those abilities for other things. Could you do that consciously? Do enough occultism to keep improving yourself, but not cross the Gwynfydd line. Then you could keep getting better and better at earthly things.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8332851", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why would you want to do that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8383539", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To live the polymath ideal over multiple lifetimes, with the possibility of one day being brilliant at everything.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8385587", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why would you want that, when you could instead move on to more interesting things?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8386355", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Read\nCaravaggio: A Life\nby Helen Langdon and notice how she describes the lives of Cardinal Del Monte and his circle. I'd like to make the most of those possibilites before crossing over and becoming the equivalent of a burlak on the River Styx - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barge_Haulers_on_the_Volga", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8346675", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, because as you turn away from the spiritual you begin to lose the abilities that you've gained. It's as though you were rolling down the highway and suddenly turned off the engine. Sure, you'll coast for a while, but eventually you'll grind to a halt -- and getting back up to speed will require a lot of additional effort.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8326707", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nWould you recommend reading the books \"Phallicism\" and \"Ophiolatreia\" that are attributed to Hargrave Jennings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8346931", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure, if you like to giggle at Victorian pomposity. I don't recommend them as serious sources.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8326963", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm doing the DMH, but I've been reading the Dolmen Arch in advance of actually doing the exercises. In the section on magical memory in the first grade, the exercise is given to recall the day's events in reverse order. I've been actually starting to do this the day after, when I go over the previous day's Ogham reading. I recall the previous days's events in reverse order, then check if my Ogham reading fit those events. Is it important to do the recall the same evening, or can I handle it like I've been doing the next morning?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8347187", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can certainly do it the next morning if that works better for you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8327475", "title": "Sales", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What astrological factors would you take into account to decide when to start an eBay auction?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8347443", "title": "Re: Sales", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mercury is the planet of buying and selling, so you'd want to make sure that Mercury was well dignified by sign or aspect, preferably either rising or approaching the midheaven, not afflicted by any other planet and not conjunct Mars, Saturn, or Uranus. If you can get some other planet applying to Mercury by sextile or trine that's better still, and best of all if you can get Jupiter or Venus in one of those aspects or applying to conjunction.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8360755", "title": "Re: Sales", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you. So starting it during the hour of Mercury of a day would not be relevant, or just overruled by those other factors?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8361011", "title": "Re: Sales", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You could also do an hour of Mercury on a Wednesday with Mercury not afflicted, yes, but you asked about astrology rather than planetary hours, so I gave you the astrology. If you want, you can try to find a day and hour of Wednesday when all the above considerations apply, but you may have to wait a few years!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8371763", "title": "Re: Sales", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not OP) Is there a difference here between natal Mercury and transiting Mercury being well-aspected? I'm interpreting natal Mercury as being the domain or sphere of our life that is subject to influence, and the transiting planets as being the actual influences. If we have, for example, natal Mercury trine transiting Jupiter, this is not the same force as natal Jupiter trine transiting Mercury, right?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8374835", "title": "Re: Sales", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "More or less. I tend to think of the natal chart as showing the patterns that are hardwired into your character and destiny, and the transiting planets as the forces that activate those patterns in different ways. Yes, transiting Jupiter trine natal Mercury is different from transiting Mercury trine natal Jupiter!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8327731", "title": "the doctrine of signatures?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello\nCan we have a brief description of the doctrine of signatures?\nThanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8347955", "title": "Re: the doctrine of signatures?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure\n.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8327987", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "grandswamperman", "content": "1. Are there any plans to incorporate astrology or tarot into the Celtic Golden Dawn system?\n2. You’ve mentioned before that one reason the original GD fell apart was an over-emphasis on the solar. Is that why the system of practice in\nPaths of Wisdom\nincludes lunar etheric charging?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8348211", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Tarot, yes; astrology, no. There's a different system of magical timing found in rough-sketch form in the old Druid Revival literature, and I'll be including that in an upcoming book.\n2) That's part of it, yes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8328499", "title": "Yeats and Marcus Aurelius", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello\n(1) Yeats' Vision has 2 version it appears. Which one would you recommend? and are they presently copyright free?\n(2) As for Marcus Aurelius, which version of his meditations would you recommend?\nMany thanks", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8348723", "title": "Re: Yeats and Marcus Aurelius", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The second edition, originally published in 1937, is to my mind much better. Yeats comments that he had no clue about the Principles as distinct from the Faculties when he wrote the earlier edition. As far as I know, yes, both editions are out of print.\n2) Whichever one appeals to you. There are many translations and his Latin is clear and crisp enough that there aren't many dubious passages.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8328755", "title": "“Bad Vybes”", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG – no question this week, but I thought it would be fun to share with you an arcane occult tidbit that I found a few days ago. No doubt I am not the only person who attributed the phrase “bad vibes” the hippies and the ‘60s (or, at least, the term seemed to die with the onset of the ‘70s). But apparently the term is not all that modern. I just read that in 1607, the enigmatic “Dr.” John Lambe of England  was accused of “practising execrable arts to consume the body and strength of Thomas, Sixth Lord Windsor of Bromsgrove and generalley giving bad vybes”!\nThanks, as always, for so generously sharing your knowledge and wisdom on this site.\nRon M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8348979", "title": "Re: “Bad Vybes”", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens. Can you give me the source for that? I've love to be able to cite it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8355123", "title": "Re: “Bad Vybes”", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I found the quote included in a brief article on John Lambe written by Brent Swancer (whom I have found to be trustworthy in keeping true to his sources), but unfortunately Swancer has not attributed the source. I’ll try to hunt him down on FB and see if he cough up a source. The article is here:  https://mysteriousuniverse.org/2020/04/the-curious-life-and-death-of-the-sorcerer-dr-john-lambe/. I like to check out the website from time to time when I want some “occult lite” and sometimes to have a good laugh (some of the contributors are pretty warped sense of humour). Stay tuned!\nRon M", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8371251", "title": "Re: “Bad Vybes”", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Brent Swancer was under the impression that the quote came from \"A Briefe Description Of The Notoriovs Life of Iohn Lambe, Otherwise Called Doctor Lambe. Together with his Ignominious DEATH.\" (1628), which is available at https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A05033.0001.001?rgn=main;view=fulltext\nUnfortunately, the key phrase “bad vybes” is not in it. The search continues.\nRon M", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8329011", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week I asked whether my experiences of fear and anxiety could be related to some kind of \"chronic Watcher phenomen\". You answered: \"That doesn't sound like the Watcher; it sounds to me like the legacy of a really problematic previous life, the memories from which are close enough to the surface of your consciousness that you can sense them. Not an easy row to hoe! \" ( https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/85690.html?thread=8229306#cmt8229306 )\nYour comment struck a chord and I realized that this may very well be. I clearly remember years ago when I watched myself in the mirror after reading Ian Stevensons \"Reincarnation\", suddenly seeing some minor oddities on my body as well as some experiences in a different light. And over the last few month, there were certain moments when some glimpes seemed to pop up. Very vague, mostly feelings or some odd moments. For example - it may sound absurd - I once put the hood of my pullover over my head in front of the mirror and this gesture seemed to \"overlap\" with some distant memory when I seemed to do exactly the same. As small and casual as the gesture was, it definitely transported some distant emotional content and was truly an odd, remarkable experience.\nDuring the last week I started journaling and did some rounds of divination. I asked, whether memories of a previous life are at least partly responsible for the fears and anxiety I frequently experience and got Amissio first, passing to 9th house - which I suppose is the house to look at - and to 12th. If assigned the house correctly, this means a very strong yes. I asked further whether it is a good idea to consciously deal with those memories and got Caput Draconis 1st and second, Populus 9th passing to 12th so an unambiguous yes again. The cardines show Caput Draconis, Fortuna Minor, Fortuna Minor and Laetitia. I interpret this as \"a lot of small steps are necessary, the result will be fortunate\". To be safe, I asked whether there are also memories of this life I should deal with before and while I got Fortuna Major 1st and Caput Draconis 9th, the chart did not perfect. After that I sat silently for a while and asked how to access the memories and an inner voice said \"just let them come\". To make it short, something did come, not very detailed but still revealing and emotionally a little bit distressing.\nA bunch of questions arise from this... How to proceed? Is there anything I can do to actively work with this and support the process? Are there any precautions I should take? Dealing with memories is not always an easy task. How to be sure I'm not just making things up? Do you have any general advice? ...\nNachtgurke", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8349235", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, the first thing to be aware of is that this sort of thing is perfectly normal. Many people have such memories surface, and it's a normal part of awakening to your own real identity -- your Individuality, as Dion Fortune put it, as distinct from the temporary personality. The inner voice you heard gave good advice.\nWhat I recommend is to let the memories come at their own pace and write them down as they occur to you. Don't worry about whether you're \"making things up\" -- just note them down, and try not to get too emotionally worked up about them. Over time you'll gradually get a clear sense of which ones are wholly accurate and which ones have fantasy mixed in with them, and they'll sort themselves out.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8358451", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ok. I notice it's kind of a step from looking at reincarnation intellectually as a rather likely possibility to actually accepting it as a reality. Thank you for your advice! I've got the feeling that the process of remembering will unfold naturally if I continue paying attention to those odd moments and write them down. If I may ask - was the process of remembering previous lives emotionally strenuous for you?\ncrimson nocturnal cucumber ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8359475", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're most welcome. No, the process of remembering wasn't particularly traumatic for me, as most of the really ugly memories were half a dozen lives back and I'd spent multiple lives dealing with them indirectly.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8329523", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "logicalmagic83", "content": "Good morning, Mr. Greer.\nA few observations today and a question at the end: I've experienced a few episodes of \"tracks in space\" which is a very nifty experience. Most of them are happening while reading various ecology/homesteading texts.\nAs I've developed my daily SOP practice, I've gone from experiencing just a \"routine\" to feeling like I'm accessing more of the other realms that surround me and receiving feedback from them. I don't quite know how to describe it but I'm certainly finding that things have a way of working out and the less I try to push against an obstacle and the more I allow a flow to happen, (while being mindful of how my actions affect outcome) the more options open to me.\nI'm sure this is a basic realization, but coming from my experience of being reactionary and a bit of a worrysome control freak, it's a nice step to notate.\nI’m continuing to study the Essenes lessons and will have an update to submit this week.\nAs always, this community is a welcome and reassuring space full of original, thoughtful thinkers. I’m grateful for what everyone brings to the table.\nLast, I’ve been able to obtain some mid 70s era Mother Earth News issues. The interviews and economic outlooks are rather similar to what we’re seeing today. Are you drawing parallels as well? I was born in 1983 so I haven’t really seen any disruption of this scale until now.\nBest wishes!\n-Kerry", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8349491", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear that things are proceeding so well!\nAs for parallels with the 1970s, yes, I'd noticed that. It's a little eerie, frankly, in that the bicentennial of the American Revolution was in 1976, the 250 year anniversary will be in 2026, and the two decades really do seem to be shaping up in similar ways...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8330035", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nLet's say there are two identically looking bottles side by side. One of them contains ordinary water, and the other one has homeopathic medicine with very low dilution. If someone doesn't know which one contains the medicine, is it possible to detect it via clairvoyance? Was there any experiment with such settings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8349747", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a fascinating question which would have to be settled by experiment -- and no, I don't know of anyone doing so. Have you considered trying it?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8352563", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I haven't developed my latent abilities in that direction yet. I'm a newbie in the field of occultism.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8353331", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Something to look forward to, then.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8330547", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "avalterra", "content": "Do you prefer the 1925 version of \"Visions\" or the revised 1937 version? And why?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8350003", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The 1937 revised edition is to my mind by far the more useful. Yeats himself noted that he had no clue about the nature of the Principles as distinct from the Faculties when he finished the original edition.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8330803", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When I did the sphere of protection this morning, I saw a weird skeletal creature trying to break through the sphere of light. When I finished the ritual it vanished, but I'm a little worried about what it could've been. What do you think it could've been?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8350259", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Probably just a bit of \"astral static\" -- as you pursue magical training you'll go through a phase where odd little imaginal things like that show up. (When I was in that phase our apartment was plagued with astral cats. Our cat found that very annoying, as she could see them and kept on running out into the kitchen to make sure they weren't raiding her bowl of kibble.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8331059", "title": "Geomancy answers for wrong day", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI was doing a daily divination on Saturday around noon, just to keep practicing with the house chart. I used to ask \"What would help me to know about today?\" (in German: \"Was würde mir helfen über den heutigen Tag zu wissen?\") which I changed to \"What's expecting me today?\" (\"Was erwartet mich heute?\") a while ago. I changed it because the first question was very long and it had poor grammar.\nThe answer on Saturday did not fit at all, however it was a perfect match for Sunday! Is it possible that it was too late in the day on Saturday or does the exact question matter? I visualize the sentence written out and try to focus on the current day but maybe \"expecting\" could mean something that's about to happen and not necessarily limited to the current day?\nThanks for your help as always!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8350515", "title": "Re: Geomancy answers for wrong day", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one of those things that needs to be settled by experiment, since it depends on personal factors. Try variations on the question and see what results you get.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8331315", "title": "Cold Water", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Not a question, but some data points for the ongoing discussion of cold showers:\n1) Since the subject came up here, I've switched from just a quick cold rinse to keep my hair shiny, to showering in only cold water, most of the time (doesn't work for shaving, alas!). In just a few weeks, that went from clenching my teeth and making myself stay in for as long as it took to shout \"THAT'S BRACING!\" and recite an \"Our Father\", to gleefully heading in. The change to warm weather is a factor. As others have noted, feel like a million bucks getting out. Even in chilly weather, never felt shivery getting out. I recommend it!\n2) Woke up one morning with a deep ache in one ankle, and the sole of that foot feeling unreasonably tender. Not the first time this has happened, and usually I suffer through it all morning. This time, I turned on the tap and ran cold water over it. And it was fine the rest of the day. Like it had never been sore. Tried that trick again after I pulled something in my leg while out digging the new garden bed... it helped, but it didn't magically make the pain go away. So: brilliant for some things. Not for everything.\n3) Water (whether a shower, or floating in a lake), has always given me some relief from migraine.  It's temporary, but there are no downsides (which you can't say for NSAIDs). Because I always have other things to get done, this is normally something I try *after* the pain is debilitating and I can't get anything else done anyway. Since I'm trying out cold water for everything now... the last couple of times a migraine came knocking, I doused myself in cold water as soon as the smallest niggling pain showed up. It did not prevent me from having a headache for the usual two or three days. But it DID prevent the pain from getting any worse. And that is MAGNIFICENT!  I can function like a normal human being with a tiny niggling bit of head pain (and wet hair...). Sometimes the dousing needed repeating two or three times. The important part is that it worked.\n--I have no idea why this works. Perhaps there is a perfectly ordinary explanation involving blood circulation. But I'm not a scientist and I won't be doing the research on it. This forum and our generous host have provided a useful lens for considering certain episodes of chronic-and-unreasonable pain: namely, that sometimes perhaps they are caused by etheric parasites and such critters don't like cold water.\nWhether that's true or not is immaterial, so long as it works. You can tell me \"improved circulation\" all day long, and my imagination skims right over it, finding nothing to grab onto. Give me a mental image of I-hurt-because-invisible-leeches... and now suddenly I have an image that lets me take appropriate action. It works, and I'll take it. Thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8336435", "title": "Re: Cold Water", "user": "happypanda", "content": "There's much more to this than just a cold shower. The cold shower is one type of Tattva Suddhi - element cleansing. In Tantric traditions every element can be done this way.\nThe mud baths and masques at spas is tattva suddhi for the earth element. At certain wind speeds if you stand in the wind it will likewise cleanse the air element.\nMost interesting to me is what Isha Center discovered when they revived the Tantric Fire element cleansing ritual. If you move a flame oil lamp in a certain pattern around a person's aura it will be as invigorating as the cold shower. They also discovered that (unlike the cold shower) it will cure children with ADHD after a few weeks of regular fire tattva suddhi treatments. The kids never need meds or any other medical treatment ever again for that particular problem.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-20 06:56 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8331827", "title": "Dolmen Arch SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have a question about the SOP instructions in the Dolmen Arch. When banishing for each element, we are instructed to banish something specific, such as \"inappropriate thoughts\" for Air or \"misguided intentions\" for Fire. But then in the banishing instructions for Earth, there is not a specific banishing in line with the others. Is this an error, or is this intentional?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8350771", "title": "Re: Dolmen Arch SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good; you noticed. By all means put in a specific banishing parallel to the others.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8332083", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWhich books would you recommend to study the history of Western esoteric tradition?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8351027", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Start with some of Frances Yates' books --\nGiordano Bruno and the Hermetic Tradition\nis a good starting place. Mitch Horowitz'\nOccult America\nis quite decent as an intro to the occult here in the US. To my knowledge, there isn't a single good one-volume history of occultism, so you'll have to pick things up in bits and scraps from various sources.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8332339", "title": "Bunch-O-Stuff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John\n1.\tMight you consider hosting a Cthulhu Mythos free for all for WoH fans?  I’d love to ask if Nyarlathotep would like Justin Johnson’s “Heavy Delta Blues” for his entrance music.\n2.\tWhat are your conjure magic must-reads and related blues must listens?\n3.\tWhy are firearms such a problem for writers?  In a better than average rework of “The Horror at Red Hook,” The Ballad of Black Tom by Victor LaValle, the NYPD is armed with an obsolete rifle, a machine gun not yet in production, and a pistol not even on the drawing board.  (May I suggest the Bannerman Catalogue of Military Goods 1927 reprint as a resource for writing in the Mythos?)  Given the easy availability of information, mistakes like these baffle me.  If I’m reading Dion Fortune right, I might consider the possibility that something occult is tripping up otherwise competent writers… mightn’t I?  So… what, how, and (most importantly) why?\n4.\tI keep seeing and hearing wishes for a collective-commune-college-village for “our kind.”  Do you think this is anything besides wishful thinking?  Here in Northeast Ohio, there are a number of struggling institutions that could be used to start such a project.\nRusty", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8352819", "title": "Re: Bunch-O-Stuff", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) As in, a Cthulhu Cthursday or something like that? I'll consider it. I'm feeling a little bereft right now -- a couple of days ago I finished writing the last novel I intend to write in the Haliverse,\nThe Seal of Yuen Lao\n, and that meant saying goodbye to a people who have been constant presences in my inner life for six years now; the mere fact that they're imaginary doesn't make the parting any less of a wrench.\n2) My background in conjure is somewhat limited -- I studied with Cat Yronwode and use her students-only textbook as my main guide, though Carolyn Morrow Long's book\nSpiritual Merchants\nis a good history. As for blues tracks, I'm not actually much of a blues fan -- that's something I put into\nInnsmouth\nto add verisimilitude and flavor.\n3) Most writers these days come from the leftward end of the political spectrum and, for reasons I'm still not sure I understand, way too many people on that end of things have a weird set of mental blocks about guns. More generally, though, howlers like that are excruciatingly common in historical fiction of all kinds. It's rare for me to read a novel set in a different time period that doesn't have people using out-of-period slang, say, or behaving in ways that nobody behaved in that time and place.\n4) I have no idea. We'll just have to see if anybody's prepared to act.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8383027", "title": "Re: Bunch-O-Stuff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm not sure about \"weird\" regarding the Left's mental block on guns; I've mulled over the issue before and I suspect there's at least 3-4 reasons for it (some good, some not):\n1) There is at least an implicit belief among large parts of the more activist Left that in practice the Second Amendment is mere words on paper as far as they're concerned - and, moreover, that this *only* applies to them and not to right-wing activists.  (I'm frankly not sure they're wrong about that, for a half-dozen reasons, some of which are historically contingent - I suspect \"showing guns is an excuse for the authorities to kill you, and claiming self-defense gets you the death penalty if you're lucky\" got handed down to varying degrees from least three antecedents of the modern left [the labor movement, LGBT, and the broader civil rights movement] - and and others (\"the authorities are, for obvious reasons, more charitably inclined towards paramilitaries acting to support the status quo\") less so.  In fact, I'm pretty sure the bailey version of that belief is right: it's commonplace in those parts that left-wing protestors simply would not be allowed to get away with everyone bringing a gun to a protest the way right-wing militias are, and I don't think they're wrong about that.)  That's not the only key driver of gun control support on the left (class issues are also involved), but it's one of them - key parts of the left believe a) that they are de facto not allowed to have guns and their opponents *are* and b) past evidence (notably the wave of gun control legislation passed in reaction to the Black Panthers in the 1970s) indicates that realizing their de jure right to bear arms themselves is probably beyond their capabilities - but the other form of equalizing (removing the right to bear arms from their opponents) might actually be achievable.\n2) The successes of the Civil Rights movement and a couple of decolonization movements (at least Gandhi) got fused to the myth of progress, leading to a belief that we'd found a better way of social change than bloody revolution.  (I very much suspect at least some of this is mythologizing a virtue out of perceived necessity deriving from point 1.)\n3) I really wouldn't be shocked if part of both of the above was explicit psy-ops from programs like COINTELPRO, above and beyond any basic intimidation tactics.  (This may also effect writing about guns directly - there's been some declassifications the last few years indicating that one of the CIA's Cold War activities was funding mid-century American art, notably Jackson Pollack (to quote someone else's take, \"when we said freedom of expression we meant it\"); given other intelligence agency actions of the era, the possibility of one or more three-letter agencies funding lefty writers with a distaste for guns sounds quite plausible to me.)\n4) For a bunch of reasons (especially in the US where the white ethnics came into it), the twentieth-century left tended to be an urban phenomenon, and weapons being more strongly regulated in cities was an old commonplace even before guns (with their \"have you looked at what you're using as a backstop?\" issue) became common, probably due to population density and cumulative probabilities of low-odds events.\n- pretentious_username", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8332595", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do you make of the \"It's 2020! How can X still happen?\" Is it just a manifestation of the myth of progress?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8333363", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "Not JMG, but I suspect it is, and my personal response to that:  \"And by the Muslim calendar it's 1441.  Your point?\"", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8354867", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, exactly. One of the central delusions of the myth of progress is \"but it's different this time!\" When somebody says that as they're trying to sell you on the latest soon-to-pop speculative bubble, they're shoveling smoke, and the same is true of the notion that the present is automatically exempt from the experiences of the past.\nI like to answer such bleatings with \"Yes, and X will still be happening in 3020. Deal with it.\"", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8368435", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "The dissident internet right of the chan boards has been mocking that type of utterance for about 5 years now, saying \"Hey, it's the current year!\" whenever that pops up.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8370995", "title": "Current year", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Its become a bit of joke on the internet to make fun of this by saying \"Its current year!\" as in \"How can homophobia exist in current year?!?\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8333107", "title": "What is the will?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Grand Archdruid (Emeritus),\nWhat is the magical definition of will and what is the best way to train it? Would you have a book to recommend on this topic?\nAs a second question, what originally convinced you of the existence of reincarnation? What would be the evidence in support?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8355635", "title": "Re: What is the will?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The will is the aspect of the self that enables you to choose. The best way to train it is to do things for no reason other than to train the will. What kind of things? Anything, so long as it has no reward in and of itself. Set your alarm five minutes early and leave it there even though you don't need the extra time. Make a point of noticing every red thing in the room around you. Decide to be at a certain place you've never visited before at exactly 1:34 pm next Saturday and keep the appointment to the minute. And, of course, set yourself a schedule of magical practices and maintain them no matter what. I don't have a book to recommend; there used to be dozens of them in Victorian times, but they're all long out of print and I doubt you can find them.\n2) Remembering my own past lives had quite a bit to do with that. You might find Ian Stevenson's volumes of research into past life memories worth reading as evidence.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8333619", "title": "offerings vs trash", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nWhen I visit sacred sites I often find \"offerings\" left by others which can take the form of polyester ribbons tied to trees and other bric a brac.  I think that it is a form of service to the nature spirits to remove such detritus but those who have left these things would disagree.\nAm I doing a service to nature, and if not, would there be blowback on me for removing such things?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8346419", "title": "Re: offerings vs trash", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Obviously not JMG, but why don't you ask the tree?  Different trees like different things.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8357427", "title": "Re: offerings vs trash", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can't imagine the tree likes the plastic rags. The objection is aesthetic as much as anything else. But the issue is more that someone else sees it as an act of reverence or a spiritual request for something so is it wrong to remove it?", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8361267", "title": "Re: offerings vs trash", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Years ago someone I knew complained that an unknown person had 'shaled' under a tree she regarded as her favorite tree (on some Pagan owned land). I pointed out that a tree might well regard shale as an appropriate offering--although burying it is simple courtesy.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8355891", "title": "Re: offerings vs trash", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm with Kimberly here. Talk to the tree and find out what it wants!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8333875", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nIs there any (alive) magical system which is entirely based on ancient Hermetic texts (like Corpus Hermeticum, Asclepius, Kore Kosmou etc.)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8356147", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Quite a few people in the Hermetic end of occultism have worked in that direction, but I don't know that any of them have systematized the results into a system. If you're interested in doing so, get some training in at least one established magical system while reading and rereading the classic Hermetic literature, and then see what you can create.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8334131", "title": "Gurdjieff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey John,\nJames from Hermitix here. I've read a lot of your occult books now, many of them which serve as a commentary. I've seen you comment on almost all well-known occultists, and yet, I can't seem to find any place/book where you've commented on the work of George Gurdjieff very much, is there a reason for this? And what do you make of Gurdjieff's 'fourth way' in general?\nRegards,\nJames", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8356659", "title": "Re: Gurdjieff", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I looked into Gurdjieff and the Fourth Way briefly during my first stint in college, inspired by a good film version of\nMeetings with Remarkable Men\n, and decided that it wasn't for me -- partly the teachings didn't have anything like the appeal of the Golden Dawn system, partly everybody I met at that time who was into the Fourth Way had that humorless dogmatic sort of personality one associates with fanatics. (I steered clear of Rudolf Steiner's Anthroposophy for exactly the same reasons.) Over the years that followed I got a clear sense of just how much there was to master in the occult traditions I'd chosen to study, and so I never looked back.\nI tend to class Gurdjieff in the same category as Steiner, Meher Baba, Sri Aurobindo, et al. -- the early 20th century had plenty of figures like that, each equipped with a idiosyncratic system of spiritual development, each surrounded by a cult of personality. I'll probably get to reading the works of at least some of them eventually, but it's not at the top of my list.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8334643", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Greetings Archdruid,\nDuring antiquity and early Medieval age, Ireland was more isolated from the cultural influence of Rome and of Catholic Church than Britain. So, there was not a significant armed or clerical force to wipe out Druidry from Ireland. However, still, Druids in Ireland somehow vanished suddenly. I find this very baffling. What is the reason of this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8359219", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In her book\nThe Rise of Magic in Early Medieval Europe\n, Valerie Flint makes a case that this happened across much of Europe for an unexpected reason: in those days, Christian clerics were better at magic than their Pagan opponents. I think she's likely to be correct. Christianity in its pre-Reformation era was full of overtly magical practices, and those drew on the energies set in motion by the Piscean age; most of the older Pagan traditions were still using the formulae of the departed Arian age. (That wasn't true of Norse Heathenry, interestingly enough -- Odin is a Piscean deity, as you can tell by his association with self-sacrifice -- which may explain why Heathenry put up so much more vigorous a fight against Christianity than most other European religions.)\nNow, of course, the shoe is on the other foot: Western Christianity discarded most of its magical practices at the time of the Reformation and ditched the remainder in the late 20th century in a misguided attempt to be \"relevant.\" Christianity has now become a minority faith in its historic heartlands in Europe and the Middle East, and it's rapidly approaching minority-faith status in the US; meanwhile a lively religious ferment is under way in those regions, out of which the faiths of the Aquarian age, equipped with robust magic in their turn, will doubtless emerge.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8359731", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Might Druidry then be the first stirrings of the Aquarian Age?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8360499", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The Aquarian age began in 1888, by the calculation I use. The first stirrings were quite some time ago! Druidry might end up providing some of the raw material, or not, but a new religious movement comes out of the white-hot incandescence of spiritual experience, not out of a quirky, bookish, deliberately eccentric intellectual faith like mine.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8369203", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"in those days, Christian clerics were better at magic than their Pagan opponents.\"\nHmmm... So, we can also say that Neoplatonist magicians were at least as competent as Christian clerics, since Neoplatonism could survive those times and influenced major esoteric traditions of the West (including even those that are inside monotheistic religions).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8375091", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That would be a sensible deduction, yes.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8373043", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Do you know any dieties off hand who are Aquarian?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8376115", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. The basic themes of the Aquarian age are freedom, eccentricity, innovation, and isolation; Uranus, its planetary ruler, is the planet of the individual, and its discovery heralded the rise of republican governments and the wider spread of the concept of individual rights.  Viðarr, the son and avenger of Odin, is a classic Aquarian deity; craftsman-gods who come into being in solitude and silence, such as Ptah, are Aquarian; a case could be made that Pan, who dwells alone in the wilderness and brings terror (\"panic\") with his shout, is an Aquarian god. On the other hand, the Roman astrologer Manilius assigns Hera to Aquarius.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8335667", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've seen references here on your distinction between the paths of magic, mysticism, and occultism. Which got me wondering why there is no (or none that I know of) Christian occultism. Is that due to Christianity not meshing well with it? What would a Christian occultism look like?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8356915", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not JMG but Christian)\nIt looks like:\n—what the Wiccans call “kitchen magic”\n—Southern black hoodoo\n—Southern conjure magic (the white version of hoodoo)\n—Brazilian umbanda\n—the practices Dion Fortune wrote about\nAnd probably a whole lot of other stuff.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8361779", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The people who taught you that there's no Christian occultism were either misinformed or lying. The vast majority of Western occultism between 600 CE and 1800 CE was explicitly Christian.  Many of the classic grimoires assume that you're a practicing Catholic and will go to Mass and confess your sins before you conjure spirits in the name of Jesus, for heaven's sake! Most European folk magic is robustly Christian, and casts spells and consecrates amulets in the name of Jesus and the saints. If you're interested in high magic, most of the branches of the Rosicrucian movement are explicitly Christian; so is Anthroposophy, Rudolf Steiner's offshoot of the Theosophical movement; so is the Martinist Order, one of the major systems of magical lodge work in the world today. If you'd like a taste of what Christian occultism is like, pick up a copy of Gareth Knight's book\nExperience of the Inner Worlds\nsometime -- it's a training manual of Christian Cabalistic magic.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8337971", "title": "Sleep Magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and Readers,\nI did not write this prayer and I cannot remember where I got it on the Internet.  I am very grateful to the person who did write it.\nI recite this prayer when I want to go to sleep.  At first, it worked fairly well but as I continued to say it, it became much stronger and now, I rarely get past it to the other prayers on my rosary.  I hope other people will try this prayer as the tracks in space phenomenon will only make it stronger.\n\"Morpheus, I invoke you to let sleep be with me.\nPeaceful sleep, restful sleep.\nLet my body be eased.\nLet my mind be calmed.\nWings of darkness, let the night and dreams be clear.\nLet my troubles drift away and let me dream sweetly.\nMorpheus, bless my sleep.\"\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8362035", "title": "Re: Sleep Magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thanks for this.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8340019", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Long time reader first time caller. Thanks for all of your writings. For years every Wednesday I've looked forward to reading the new blog post.\nGiven everything that's been going on I've decided to use some of my newfound free time to start to develop a daily practice of ritual, meditation, and divination as you recommend. I have a few questions:\n1) Why is the air element symbol in the SoP the shape/color it is? Yesterday was my 2nd week of learning the sphere of protection as outlined on the blog and I had some interesting thoughts while considering the symbol during my discursive meditation session and am curious about how it lines up with what others think.\n2) I've been working with the I-ching for 8 years now and feel quite comfortable using it as a daily system. Is it ultimately compatible with the druid path? I'm concerned the metaphysics might not fit well together when it comes to higher level practices?\n3) From what I've gathered the SoP is more potent when you invoke deities, am I missing out by not including them in my practice? I had a rather unpleasant experience with Mormonism growing up and am averse to any sort of diety worship and have been practicing an animist version so far.\n4) Do you have any thoughts or resources on the negative effects of using too many psychedelics at a young age? I'm a bit of a retired psychonaut and used various substances during my adolescent years. I'm living sober these days but can't help but feel there was maybe some permanent or long lasting effect. Specifically, I feel there my psychic defenses/boundaries were weakened and that I may have seen things or had insights that I was not ready for or mature enough to integrate or act on. As a reaction I spend many years sort of shying away from spiritual work and focusing on regrounding myself in my body and in the physical world. I think the overall effect was to create a large gap between my awareness and my ability/maturity to deal with what I was observing leading to lots of cognitive dissonance and overwhelm and a tendency to get bogged down and stagnate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8362291", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The symbols of Air and Earth in the AODA/Universal Gnostic tradition are idiosyncratic. I was never given an explanation of why they're used in place of some other symbol, but they make great fodder for meditation, and they also work very well in practice.\n2) Of all the Asian mystical philosophies, Taoism is probably the closest to the Druid Revival tradition; I know Druids who consider the Tao Te Ching to be among their holy books, for example. I know of no reason why the I Ching should be inappropriate.\n3) If you don't feel comfortable working with deities, don't work with deities. Put more effort and concentration into your SoP workings to make up for their absence.\n4) It seems to me that you've sketched out the standard effects very precisely here. Regular use of a protective ritual such as the SoP, and close attention to grounding yourself in material reality, should help.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8340275", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Good afternoon, JMG\nI've been using a general license to depart before the banishing at the end of ritual- \"May all spitits, all beings who have been drawn to this circle and bound to it be now released to depart to their rightful habitations. Peace between us.\"\nAt the present time, though, I am in the midst of an extended working that engages with a god and His attending spirits. Those spirits have tasks to do, and I was concerned that my general release might mess with keeping them on task, so to speak. Or not- the deity is the one giving them their orders, as He sees best to do to fulfill the task, so I might not have the authority to release them in this everyday license to depart manner. The everyday ritual is a separate thing from the specific working with the god and His spirits.\nWhat I have been doing (because I wasnt sure) is instead saying \"May all spirits, all beings who have been drawn to this circle and bound to it be now released to depart to their tasks and to their rightful habitations. Peace between us.\"\nIs adding in \"to their tasks\" even necessary?\nThanks!\nBonnie", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8362803", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The new version seems quite appropriate to me. By all means stick with it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8340787", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I assume your avoidance of TV is motivated in part by a desire not to expose yourself to images that emanate from an untrustworthy source? It's known in psychology that the subconscious mind believes that every image it sees is real (something that is used to effect in marketing), and Israel Regardie says in the Middle Pillar that we store what we see on a cellular level. In this vein, do you also block images on websites? Admittedly, certain websites are a lot more toxic than others, but all content on the Internet bears the risk of exposing you to an image that is intended to manipulate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8363059", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Mostly my disinterest in TV is caused by the fact that I find it insanely dull, but yes, I also remember that there's a reason they call what's on the TV \"programming\"! Yes, I block images on websites for the same reason, and I also block ads. (If a website won't let me on with my adblocker in place, I go elsewhere.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8341043", "title": "Blessing Candle Questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have permission from six people to dedicate my blessing candle to them & pray to my guardian angel, since they are across many faiths and work in hospitals.\n1. Is it more effective to have a set wording, or can I ad lib with intention?\n2. I had previously been dedicating the candle to all those suffering and all emergency response workers. Should I leave that off for now, so that it is stronger for my six people?\n3. Could this backfire in terms of karma, like if I am praying that they be safe, but it is actually their time to go?\n4. I was thinking of a wording like \"May they be healthy, safe and protected.\" I was also going to picture them enveloped in white light. Is that okay?\n5. Is there anything in the DMH-SOP framework that improve this? Thank you so much for your time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8363315", "title": "Re: Blessing Candle Questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That varies from person to person. Do what seems to feel best.\n2) No, not at all. Compassion is a renewable resource.\n3) No; if it's time for them to go, your prayer will help them be safe in the afterlife.\n4) Yes, that's quite standard.\n5) How far along are you in the DMH? If you've reached the section that discusses using the SoP for simple magical workings, you can certainly use those.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8341299", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear John,\nA couple of different questions:\n- What would you suggest in general for a person who isn't in direct contact with any physical lodge/temple and want to know approximately which grade he is?\n- What books do you recommend the most on planetary magic?\n- What is the classification of symbols that appear clearly as afterimages when we close our eyes? Not in our imagination; but as light shapes projected on the darkness caused by our closed eyelids?\nAziz", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8363827", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) These days I'm far from convinced that the GD grade system is a useful way of thinking about spiritual development. I'd say don't worry about it and just focus on moving ahead on the path from wherever you are.\n2) That depends. Do you want Golden Dawn-style planetary magic? Regardie's\nThe Golden Dawn\nhas the material you need. Do you want old-fashioned astrological planetary magic? Why, then, you're in better shape than I am; the\nGhayat al-Hakim\n, attributed to al-Majriti but actually by Maslama al-Qurtubi, is the supreme textbook of planetary magic, and I'm willing to bet that you can read the Arabic original rather than having to make do, as I did, with the somewhat garbled medieval Latin translation titled\nPicatrix\n.\n3) As I recall, they're called phosphenes, and they're produced by ordinary processes in the visual end of the nervous system.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8384051", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Personally I'm more attuned with the OTO/Thelemic version of the GD system, though I second what you said, as each aspirant forms his own subjective universe and view eventually.\n2) Sorry I wasn't specific in my inquiry, but I'm looking for any good sources on communicating with and invoking planetary intelligences and energies, not necessarily complex thaumaturgic stuff as I'm guessing Ghayat al-Hakim is, I remember reading some negative and spooky experiences by some with that book. I'm fine with anything on the lines of the Western tradition.\n3) Thanks, never heard of that term! And in the light of initiation and spirituality, how is it classified or explained from your own perspective? I've never came across any source or authority that clearly mentioned it so far. I'm just wondering if it's mostly \"lower astral\" and etheric activity or something of a higher type.\nAziz", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8384819", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "2) In that case definitely you want Regardie's material in\nThe Golden Dawn\n. The Z-2 rituals are particularly well suited for work with planetary intelligences and spirits.\n3) As far as I can tell they're purely neurochemical, and so belong to the material plane -- not even astral.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8342067", "title": "advance care directives", "user": "ritaer", "content": "Dear JMG,\nThe current crisis seems to have a lot of people tackling their \"gotta get that done someday\" list. One of my items is an advanced care directive. This led me to some occult questions. I intended to reread your earlier discussions of the death process, but couldn't find them. Would appreciate you pointing me in the right direction, although I think some of it may have been on the Well of Galebes blog, not here.\nAddressing this both from your occult perspective and from your experiences in nursing homes work, I would like your opinion on life support decisions. I recall in your discussion of suicide the idea that the spirit has to hang around until natural death would have occured. Does the opposite happen if the body is being kept going on vents and artificial feeding, after natural death would have occurred?\nAlternately is something of spiritual importance still happening even if the person is unable to communicate. Is there a difference between coma or other unconsciousness and persistent vegetative state? I have heard of people coming out of a coma after years--but it is rare and unexplained.\nLast week, I think, you pointed to advanced dementia as being a disintegration of personality. In your opinion, would there be negative spiritual consequences to saying in advance, 'if I develop dementia, don't treat me for any life threatening event, except for reasonable pain relief.' Or is it possible that living out a period of dementia is part of the plan for those who develop it and should not be shortened by refusing treatments, such as cancer therapy, one would expect if the dementia did not exist. I see TV ads for prescription drugs that include the warning \"may lead to life threatening xx in persons suffering from dementia\" and I just think, \"oh good\" but then I mentally add, \"but I wouldn't want to be taking the medication in the first place, unless it was for pain relief.\"\nHoping this finds you and yours in good health. Kipling comes to mind here \"if you can keep your head when all about you are losing theirs - - - \"\nRita", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8357171", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If you can keep your head when all about you are losing theirs...\n...You have not grasped how bad the situation really is.  😄", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8364083", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) A person who's kept alive by machines, if conscious, simply has a lot of wasted hours. If in deep coma, very often, there's nobody home, and the doctors are keeping a corpse warm.\n2) That varies from case to case, and it's not always the same soul who wakes up in the body.\n3) No, that's quite reasonable. \"Keep me comfortable and let me die naturally\" is perhaps the sanest approach to terminal illness, since it involves dying naturally.\nThanks for asking! Yes, Sara and I are fine, and watching with wry amusement as people run around like headless chickens.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8364595", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) Would you be able to elaborate on that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8366643", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, what do you want to know? It's complex.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8367155", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How could a different soul enter a body?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8367411", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it's just lying there empty, it's not that hard. The soul may not be human; alternatively, it could be the soul of someone who committed suicide and still had things to learn and do, and going into a vacant body was permitted as a way to undo the mistake of suicide.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8375347", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What would be the result of a body becoming inhabited by a non-human soul? Do you actually know of any cases?\nAlso, would the post-coma person retain the memories of the pre-coma soul, just with a different personality?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8376371", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Dion Fortune discusses examples in some of her essays. As for memories, to some extent, yes, those would pass over, as they're inscribed in the cells of the brain.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8372275", "title": "Re: advance care directives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "\"Thanks for asking! Yes, Sara and I are fine, and watching with wry amusement as people run around like headless chickens.\"\nThat's insulting towards headless chickens! ;)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8344371", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nDo prime numbers have any significance in occult philosophy? Since they are divisible by only 1 and themselves, I thought they may represent the relation between \"the One\" and \"the many\", or the unity of universal Spirit and the individual divine sparks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8364339", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That strikes me as a first-rate theme for meditation!\n(The properties of numbers, including their prime or composite status, have been used as themes for meditation since ancient Greek times, so I mean that quite seriously.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8372531", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’ve always found something a little scary about prime numbers, and I could not tell you why.  Is that just me, or did the Greeks et al feel that way about them too?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8376627", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, they saw prime numbers as purer and stronger than composite numbers.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8345139", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Regarding affirmations, you've said before that the literal meaning of the words matters more than the intent. Wondering how this works with words that can have multiple literal meanings. If someone were to use something like \"I am cool\" as an affirmation, which meaning of the word would take precedent?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8364851", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recommend using words with slippery meanings in affirmations, because you can never be sure which meaning your subconscious mind will pick.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8365619", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but is this a case of \"if you have to ask, it's too vague\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8366387", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a good rule of thumb.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8348467", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm starting the Dolmen Arch, and when I looked at the symbolism for the cantrefs noticed each one corresponds to a day of the week. My plan is thus to write down the name and colour in my practice journal, adding other correspondences once I have those down.\nIs there anything else to pay attention to, such as quality of the days? Will writing it down orient my mind towards that cantref in some subtle way I should look for?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8365363", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good. Experiment with this, meditate on it, and see what results you get. That's how magical systems evolve -- and possibilities of that kind of evolution are built into the Dolmen Arch system.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8357683", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG and everyone,\nIs there a magical, or other, cure for chronic ennui?  Everything I do seems kind of pointless.  The dr put me on Paxil, so now I don’t care that everything seems kind of pointless, but I’d like to be the way I used to be, when everything, or almost everything, was interesting.  I’d be cleaning the toilet and think about the miracle of plumbing.  Now it’s just a toilet.  All suggestions appreciated.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8365875", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Normally ennui is a secondary emotion, covering up something else. I suggest journaling -- have a written conversation with your ennui and see what it will tell you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8358707", "title": "Candles for understanding", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week, candles to tune with the opposite sex for gender reassignment was suggested.\nIs there a way to use those for understanding the opposite sex, or would it be better to use them to reinforce your own sex?\n---\nThat was the question for the week.\nI remember something about a mall world being posted here, or on the other blog.\nAnother thread on the subject is active on 4chan's /x/ (paranormal) board:\nhttps://boards.4channel.org/x/thread/24745918", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8366131", "title": "Re: Candles for understanding", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) If you want to understand the other sex, light an orange candle on a Wednesday during an hour of Mercury and ask for that understanding. To begin with, the planet Mercury rules the mind, but it's also sexually ambiguous -- the Mercurial energy is an energy of boundaries and their crossing, and governs all interactions between people and forces of different categories; that's why it's the planet of buying and selling, for example, and also of translation and transport.\n2) Fascinating. I've never had a mall world dream; my repeating dreams for many years were set inside a vast brick school building, but then one night I dreamed of a graduation ceremony and I never went back.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8370227", "title": "Re: Candles for understanding", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My repeating dreams were of plane crashes; many, many different variations of plane crashes. Once I realized that my most previous incarnation died in a plane crash, the dreams stopped and haven't come back.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8370739", "title": "Re: Candles for understanding", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "2. I've had recurring school dreams as well. Not much anymore. They were and still are usually unpleasant.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8385075", "title": "Re: Candles for understanding", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Never had a Mall World dream. My repeating motif involved labyrinthine public restrooms where every stall was unusable in a unique and frustrating way. I think it was my subconscious' metaphor for making choices in situations where all the options are subpar.\nI used to have school dreams-- universally nightmares. I got tired of them, so every time I had one, I'd carefully bring to mind each person I dreamt about (they were all actual classmates), I'd think hard about how that person and I were no longer in school-- we were now adults with our own lives, families, jobs, bills, troubles, etc.-- and I would forgive them, because we were all dumb, hormonal kids trying to deal with life complications beyond our control and no real-world experience. Then I'd ask God to bless them and their families, wherever they were now.\nIt worked. After a couple of months, no more school dreams. Been that way for many years now.\nEdited (added more. )\nDate:\n2020-04-21 08:29 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8360243", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do you think is with the pervasive fear of growing old?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8367667", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Partly it's from the media, which makes a specialty of getting people terrified of things they can't do anything about. It's part of the basic mechanism of advertising -- you feed people all kinds of upsetting stuff, and then show them ads that are all full of happy smiling people and no problems at all, or problems that are quickly and easily solved. That prompts people to run mindlessly out and buy consumer crap in a reflexive attempt to be like the people in the ads.\nStill, there's another factor. If you're wasting your life, the approach of death is terrifying, because it reminds you that you only have so many days to live and if you waste them they're gone. Since so many people waste their lives these days, I suspect that plays a very large role.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8361523", "title": "Our next lives", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr. Greer,\nI was wondering if I could get your thoughts on the later stages for humanity in the reincarnation cycle.  Is it possible for us to eventually become angels, gods, or what have you?  Do you think the sort of beings that people communicate with through magical ritual were once human?  I know that many cultures revere their ancestors, which suggest we can become something more in future lives, but I was curious to know if you thought we had access to more specific knowledge about that in this life.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8376883", "title": "Re: Our next lives", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "According to occult philosophy, humanity is more or less halfway up the ladder of being, and we will eventually become beings that compare to humans the way humans compare to pond scum. Yes, some of the beings one can contact by way of occult disciplines were apparently once human, and others passed through a stage comparable to humanity long before our species evolved. There's a lot of material about this in classic occult writings -- Dion Fortune's\nThe Cosmic Doctrine\nis an example.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8363571", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "grandswamperman", "content": "Would it be possible, or even desirable, to incorporate Uranus and Neptune into the framework of Picatrix-style Renaissance astrological magic?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8377139", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The problem with doing that is that there's no way to make a magical square with sides of 2 or 1 -- 3x3 is the smallest possible magic square, and that is assigned to Saturn. Since so much of the magical symbolism of each planet unfolds from the magic square, that renders things very difficult. My guess is that in some future time some new form of planetary magic will evolve that includes Neptune and Uranus, but it'll take time to come into being.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8365107", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If someone wanted to take the AODA system of spirituality as far as it can go, what would you say would be needed? I'm assuming such an undertaking would require getting the third degree, working within the GCC, and a complete mastery of the Dolmen Arch and Druid Magic Handbook, but are there other steps which you think would be needed?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8377395", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's as far as other people's work can take you. Once you've mastered all those, you'll be doing what every really serious mage does and breaking new ground, creating unique workings of your own which will expand the range of theory and practice for those who will come after you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8366899", "title": "Cattan’s Geomamcie (1591)", "user": "ehu", "content": "Are you aware of this work? There is currently a group working on transcribing it. Was wondering if this might be a good supplement to the volumes on geomancy you helped bring to the public. Thoughts?\nLink to ongoing transcription effort:\nhttps://cattan-transcribe-1591.herokuapp.com/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8369971", "title": "Re: Cattan’s Geomamcie (1591)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Really cool project and platform. Thanks for linking!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8377651", "title": "Re: Cattan’s Geomancie (1591)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I wasn't, and I'm delighted -- Cattan's book is first-rate and deserves more attention. A good transcribed version would be very helpful.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8368179", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, JMG- I’ve got a couple of ritual technique questions this week, if I may:\n1. You wrote here recently that you included a slightly different version of the Middle Pillar Ritual in each of your books. I started out practicing the version found in LRM, but have recently taken to vibrating the divine names four times per sphere as you described in “Monsters”, rather than taking four breaths and only vibrating on the fourth- I’ve found the extra repetitions of the names help to focus and concentrate my mind. I’ve also continued to visualize the descending ray of white light and the ascending ray of green light for four breaths each, which is found in the LRM version but not that in Monsters. Would you foresee any problems mixing and matching in this way, or should I pick one of the two versions and stick to it as written? (I didn’t make any changes to my practice til I’d finished the LRM coursework, for what it’s worth)\n2. Is there an ideal size to the circle you trace out when performing the LBRP? My ordinary practice space is quite small, and the dimensions of the circle i can walk there are quite limited by walls and furniture, so I’m used to tracing something pretty tight. With the arrival of warmer weather, however, I’ve started practicing from time to time in my backyard and find myself wondering if I should work with the size of circle I’m used to, or if I should instead do something closer to tracing the dimensions of the yard itself, and drawing the pentagrams in each corner- curious if you had any thoughts?\n3. I’ve recently started working from home, and my workspace is in the basement, in a previously somewhat dingy, neglected and underused corner of the house (the work is set-up and repair of string instruments, and its the only place I have a workbench set up, which I’d always intended to make more use of, and am now forced to realize said intentions)- I’m trying to make this as pleasant and productive a place to do this sort of work as possible, and while I know that the process of working in a neglected space will change the energy and that cleaning and organization are my other best allies here, I was curious if you had any thoughts as to magical ways, ritual or natural, to sweeten the space and help this process along.\nThanks much!\n-NPM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8377907", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Those versions are pretty much interchangeable. By all means adjust to suit yourself.\n2) Experiment and find out!\n3) Clean it very thoroughly and splash some Florida water in the four corners. Then do a banishing ritual, followed by the Rose Cross ritual (which you'll find in\nMonsters\n). That should make things good and bright.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8368691", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) There was a discussion last week about the gender of the inner planets. I'm curious what gender is traditionally assigned to Mercury? I can imagine it being masculine, or maybe both on account of its \"mercurial properties.\"\n2) In the same discussion, there was mention of burning a yellow candle in prayers to the Sun, but when I looked in Encyclopedia of Natural Magic, it said that yellow was associated with Mercury, with the Sun's colour being orange.\n3) What is the difference between the planets/planetary intelligences and the Roman deities which share the same names? I imagine they're not one and the same, but don't understand the relationship. Are there sources that have discussed this?\n4) Is the astrological cell salt protocol appropriate for children? If so, would the doses need to be adjusted? I know cell salts are quite safe for children of all ages, but wonder about the protocol specifically. If we're born deficient in certain cell salts on account of our time in the womb, I could imagine it beneficial to address that earlier in life, unless there is something I'm missing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8378163", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Mercury is ambiguous in gender -- male in some settings, female in others.\n2) There are varying traditions of color assignment. Choose one and go with it.\n3) Many of the ancient Greeks and Romans believed that they were one and the same, and I'm inclined to thing that they may be right.\n4) As far as I know the protocol has not been tested on children, so I can't offer any specific guidelines here.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8368947", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm considering joining the Druidical Order of the Golden Dawn. Is there much activity/conversation among order members online? I'm really interested in being connected with other practitioners (I'm in the ovate grade and could use some motivation) but don't wnt to be overwhelmed by an email list with a dozen messages every day.\nAt one point there was talk of you doing a study of \"A Vision\" like you're currently doing with Cos Doc. Is that still on the table?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8378419", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It varies; sometimes there's a lot of talk, other times not much. Most of the conversations these days are in a private Dreamwidth communit, for what that's worth.\n2) Yes. My current plan is to to\nThe Mystical Qabalah\nafter\nThe Cosmic Doctrine\nand\nA Vision\nafter that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8369459", "title": "A Vision", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for highlighting A Vision, JMG. I have been curious about Yeat's writings for a while, and this lit a fire in my brain to give it a go.\nApologies if someone else has already asked similar questions, I haven't had time to review all the comments yet.\nIs the system of gyres and whatnot featured in A Vision accessible to someone who hasn't studied the Golden Dawn or Theosophy? I am working my way through the Druid Revival material, and have been participating in the Cosmic Doctrine book club, which may or may not be helpful.\nAlso, does A Vision refer to any of Yeat's other works on Irish legends and folklore?\nAs I'm sure you can tell from my questions, I am a squamous anthropoid toad type person...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8378675", "title": "Re: A Vision", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The system in\nA Vision\nhas very little to do with either Golden Dawn or Theosophical teaching -- it's its own highly idiosyncratic thing. It's about as accessible to you as to anyone...but I warn you, it's not user-friendly.  It takes a lot of hard work to understand it.\n2) Only very briefly in passing.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8369715", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI wonder what is the rationale behind using different names of God inside a single monotheistic religion, such as YHVH, Elohim and Adonai in Judaism; or 99 names of Allah (asma ul husna) in Islam. Is it a kind of safety measure to prevent monotheistic egregor from becoming imbalanced?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8378931", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I can't speak to Islam as I've never studied that faith. In the Cabala, the different divine names are used because the divine unity appears to us in many different forms, which can be more or less classified according to the various divine names.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8371507", "title": "Properties of silk", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi ... Aron Blue here .. Do you have any insights you would like to share on the properties of silk? It seems to have some connection to magic - I’m happy to do the basic research myself but I thought if you have anything to add from your experience or knowledge  I’m glad to learn it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8379187", "title": "Re: Properties of silk", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Silk is a good etheric insulator -- if you want to keep something magically charged (like a consecrated wand) from losing its magical energies or being influenced by outside forces, wrap it in silk.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt10552883", "title": "Re: Properties of silk", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was thinking about this insulative property in regards to cultures which have used silk extensively as clothing, specifically Japan and China, and also India. Could this have been done consciously? By making silk widely available even to families with less means, Gandhi may have been also encouraging an etheric shielding of the people, in addition to building up the \"cottage industry\" base. No way to know, but maybe it's worth trying in etherically \"dirty\" spaces.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8372787", "title": "Another Magic Monday!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was recently reminded of a passage in a book which seems attributed to William Walker Atkinson, ‘The Inner Secet: That Something Within, by X’.  Have you have read this neat and obscure little book?  If so, I am curious how it struck you, and what you may think he meant?\nPage 147 in my copy (or 91 in an online pdf I copied from today) have the passage which stuck my memory recently.  I’m posting it here, if that is okay.\n(Or in a comment below, if that is a better place, I am not much familiar with posting yet)\n\"I progressed rapidly, rising from high places to those still higher. I became\nknown nationally—then internationally—as a “great captain of industry”, and as one who had “arrived” and had “done things”. I became one of those who combined and concentrated separate industries into what were called\n“trusts”. I became a great organizer—a builder of industries—a, creator of organizations. I have been lauded as a world benefactor, and I have been abused as an enemy of the race—all depending upon the point of view of those making the criticism. Personally, I do not regard either of these descriptions as correct; I think rather that I was an impersonal dynamic force building and creating things and conditions which, while serving a useful purpose and service in the evolution of things, will eventually be torn down and their foundations employed as the base of far better things and conditions.\nI neither seek credit, nor do I fear adverse criticism, for what I have done. In truth, I sought neither to advance the freedom of mankind nor to bind it in chains.\"\nHe then elaborates more in an occult context, and I am also curious for your conjecture as well:\n\"I neither seek credit, nor do I fear adverse criticism, for what I have done. In truth, I sought neither to advance the freedom of mankind nor to bind it in chains. I thought but little about such things, in fact. I have tried to cause as little distress as possible; I have endeavored to help individual men, and the race in general, as much as I could—this simply because I “felt that way”, and not from a sense that such was my mission.\nMy “mission” has always seemed to me to be that of manifesting the Creative Energy of which I am a focal point or centre of expression. I built, I created, I put-together—sometimes I was compelled to tear down in order to build better things on the old foundations. Men have sometimes called me ruthless—I may have been so, but, if so, only because the Creative Energy of that Something Within insisted that its work was to be done, no matter what stood in its way. Most positively, I have never maliciously or revengefully worked harm to any one. I have been as impersonal and as elemental as a natural force, both in my constructive and my destructive activities. But, while I mastered—I also served. The Law of Balanced Compensation decrees that “The Master must render Service.” Service is the “other side” of the shield of Mastery.\nMen have accused me of being avaricious, greedy, mercenary—a selfish, a rapacious money-grabber—and, indeed, I do not doubt but that I appeared as such to them, for they could see only the outside of things and not the inner motives. In truth, I have met but few men to whom money as money, or possessions as possessions, were of as little consequence as to myself. Beyond the comparatively small amount of money required to keep me in comfort—to furnish me with reasonable necessities with a moderate admixture of luxuries—money and possessions have meant nothing to me. Money I have regarded as but the counters of the great game which I have played so successfully—the game itself was the real thing to me. I was like the boy who earnestly plays the game for the sake of the game—not for the cheap marbles which are the apparent objects for which he plays.\"\nI look forward to each Magic Monday as there’s no page like it I have seen; it’s really great to see so many active and diverse minds on one page!\nMany thanks JMG and readers", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8379443", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not at all familiar with the book, and that doesn't sound like Atkinson -- but it's very interesting stuff to meditate on.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8383283", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "It's actully by a long-term associate of Atkinson's, Edward E. Beals.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8384563", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I couldn't find any biographical detail about Edward E. Beals. Was he a real person, or another pseudonym used by Atkinson?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8385331", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "I think Edward E. Beals was a real person.  I found him, IIRC, in one or two of the US census returns for Chicago the early 20th century.  Atkinson may have done some editing on Beals' books before they were published, but the styles of the two men seem quite different to me.  Beals and Atkinson seem to have been business partners of long standing in publishing New Thought books.\nNot all of the pseudonymous works published by Atkinson's major publishing outlets were written by Atkinson.   \"Swami Bhakti Vishita\" and \"Swami Panchadasi\" are almost certainly pseudonyms of the esotericist, stage conjuror and con-artist Claude Alexander Conlin (aka \"Alexander the Great, the Man Who Knows\"), according to people who knew the man well in his later years.*  See the biography of Conlin by David Charvet.  \"Magus Incognito\" is Clifford Edgar Brooksmith (or Brocksmith).  Atkinson and Conlin seem to go way back; the relationship between Atkinson and Brooksmith is less clear to me.\n\"Yogi Ramacharaka,\" \"Theron Q. Dumont\" and \"Theodore Sheldon\" are definitely Atkinson, IMHO, to judge by the style and the content.\n_____\n*  Successful con-artists, sincere religious or spiritual counselors and skilled diviners have one thing in common: to be really good at what they do, they have to be really skilled at \"reading\" people, at knowing things about them that the people themselves can not bear to bring up to conscious awareness.  It is not unknown for one and the same person to function in all three capacities, as circumstances mandate.   Since everyone is some sort of difficult mix of morality and immorality, this troubling fact ought not to be a surprise.  Conlin was very clearly all three rolled up together in one body.  --=  PS It's not an inborn skill, not to the extent that I'm speaking of here.  One has to train oneself long and hard, or be trained by difficult circumnstances, to develop it to any high degree.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-21 09:07 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8386611", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you for the clarification. How about \"Elias Gewurz\" books?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8387379", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Elias Gewurtz was a well-documented real person, a Jewish member of the Theosophical Society at London who later relocated to the Theosophical community at Crotona (in California), and who wrote books for other publishing houses in addeition to Atkinson's ventures.  See, for example, Boaz Huss, \" 'Qabbala: The Theos-Sophia of the Jews': Jewish Theosophists and Their Perception of Kabbalah,\" freely available online at academia.edu   (You have to log on to the websiter to read papers there, but anyone can do that for free by way of either facebook or google/gmail.)\nBTW, Boaz Huss seems also to have uncovered interesting new things about the H. B. of L, Max Theon and his wife.  I haven't read those papers yet, but they look promising.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8383795", "title": "Re: Another Magic Monday!", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There is an important quote in the \"Publisher's Statement\" part of that book:\n“If it suits better the purposes of publication to announce the story under\nthe classification of fiction, by all means do so—but here I make the distinction\nbetween the terms, “fiction” and “fictitious”, respectively. In the form and\narrangement of its presentation, this story may be technically classified as\nfiction—but in its essential substance it is fact, actuality, truth. Again, some\nportions of the story may be regarded as allegorical rather than as literal—\nbut, as the transcendentalists ever tell us, there are certain high truths, and\ncertain deep human experiences, which are capable of expression only\nthrough symbols and the forms of metaphor and allegory; many an allegory\nis the expression of actual human experience in the form of symbols. Once\nmore, I suggest that you let the story speak for itself. Those who recognize\nTruth in whatever form it may present itself will know! just how true is this\nstory; those who do not know Truth even when it is in plain sight—who fail\nto see the forest because of the presence of the trees—they will see naught\nbut mere fiction in this narrative. This is as it should be—it does not matter\nin the least.”", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8374323", "title": "Divination and fate", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've been doing geomancy for quite some time following your book.\nOne thing I find myself wary of doing is using geomancy for certain questions with a desired outcome I'm hopeful for. This isn't the case for all questions and I need to ask myself why more deeply.\nThe thing I'm most wary of, I think, is the suspicion that divination could \"fix\" or at least solidify a certain outcome, like how Greek prophecies bring about their own fulfilment.\nWhat is your perspective on this and could you recommend any books that go into the philosophy of divination?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8379699", "title": "Re: Divination and fate", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A good book on the philosophy of divination is badly needed.  Your caution about casting divinations when you have a lot of emotion tied up in the outcome is quite sensible. As I used to tell people when I did geomancy publicly, \"Don't ask the question if you aren't willing to deal with the answer. If you ask 'Will I achieve my dearest wish?' it may say 'Not a chance' -- and if it does, it'll be right.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8375603", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nLast week you mentioned that the result of an imbalance of telluric energy is ego disintegration, which looks along the lines of a case of Alzheimer's.\nHow careful does a person have to be to avoid that? Or conversely, how hard do you have to work to inflict that on yourself?\nAlso, do you know if there's any relation in a person's natal chart to the energies they're best equipped to deal with?\nFor instance, my Sun is in his fall, in a stellium down around my Imum Coeli. Meanwhile, I find the telluric current to be much more congenial to me, while I've had to put some work into appreciating the solar current. I'm not sure if there's a link, though.\nThanks,\nCliff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8380467", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The human energy body is normally self-balancing, so you have to work fairly hard to disrupt it. On the other hand, lots of drugs and certain other things will mess you over so that your energy body won't be able to balance.\nYour natal chart can tell you which current feels more congenial to you; my Sun's well dignified and above the horizon, for example, and I'm a little more comfortable with the solar than with the telluric current. That said, there are many ways to balance the two.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8375859", "title": "Questions about books", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Mr Greer\nA couple of months ago I was in a used book store that was going out of business and liquidating their stock (75% off everything). They had a collection of astrology books, and as I had become mildly curious about astrology from your blogs, and as the owners seemed desperate to clear out everything before they had to make another rent payment, I bought the entire pile. I find however that I am unable to make sense of them. I don’t know enough to know whether that is because they are too advanced for an absolute beginner, or because they are no good. If you have time, could you please look over this list and give me your opinion?\nHorary Astrology Plain and Simple.  Anthony Lewis\nMedical Astrology.  Omar Garrison\nA Practical Treatise of Astral Medicine and Therapeutics. Dr. M. Duz\nA whole series of small books/pamphlets on planetary transits:\ntransits of Venus, of Jupiter, etc.  Francis Sakoian and Louis Acker, and Those Inconjunct Quincunx Transits, same authors\nFocus on Pluto. Virginia Elenbaas\nThe 8th House.   Marc Robertson\nFrom one house to another. Sophia Mason\nLunar Nodes new concepts. Bernice Hill Grebner\nThe 12th house.  Tracy Marks.\nThank you", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8380723", "title": "Re: Questions about books", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Those are all serious books intended for professional astrologers. Stick them on the bookshelf for a while. Once your local library system is open again, get a couple of very basic astrology books to start with, and work up from there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8381747", "title": "Re: Questions about books", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I will do that.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/87224.html", "year": "2020", "month": "04", "day": "26", "time": "11-19PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt8396728", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What a coincidence! I've been working through Lawlor's book for the past couple of weeks now. The book is quite approachable for a beginner in sacred geometry, and the insights are both profound and stunningly obvious once they're explained to you, to the point where you wonder how you could have missed it. Mathematical education being what it is these days (Paul Lockhart has covered that ground pretty extensively in his Mathematician's Lament), it's amazing that most students subjected to it escape with any appreciation for the subject at all.\nA couple of more personal questions this week:\n1. Where do you get your news from? I’ve been looking for a while for an outlet that avoids the pitfalls of current discourse and hasn’t gone overboard with clickbait and sensationalism. There doesn't seem to be much middle ground in the media ecosystem between corporate propaganda, paranoid doom-mongering and vacuous clickbait.\n2. Did the career of a writer differ in any ways from your initial expectations? What were the most significant obstacles on the business side of things? Did you have any trouble with the human element, such as relationships with contributors, editors, publishers, etc.?\n3. Is it possible to reach a balance between doing what you love but can’t make money from, and what you have to do to earn a living? Unfortunately, many people can’t combine what they love with what pays the bills (myself included). This leaves you with the option of doing what you love in your spare time, and spending most of your waking time on something you would rather not be doing. The problem with that, obviously enough, is that many jobs are so draining that you barely have the energy to do anything else. How did you manage before you were a full-time author?\n4. What are you reading right now? What problems are currently on your mind?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8397752", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I read exclusively foreign news sources these days -- the US media is a complete waste of time. I like to balance competing viewpoints against each other: for example, BBC vs. RT -- they almost always take opposite sides on any question of importance. World news also takes on a very different shape if you see how it looks from India, Japan, East Africa, or what have you.\n2) By the time I actually started my writing career I had a good idea what I was in for -- I'd read quite a few books on the business end of writing. The major problem I faced was figuring out how to find suitable publishers on the fringes who were interested in the kind of weird things I like to write. As for the human element, well, of course -- as someone with Aspergers syndrome I'm not good at that.\n3) My approach was to work in low-paying, grueling, miserable jobs, so that I had an extra incentive to get published!\n4) Right now I'm rereading John Crowley's novel\nLittle, Big\nand Matila Ghyka's\nThe Golden Number\n, a book on sacred geometry. The problems on my mind? Fine details of the plot of a novel I've recently started, my first post-tentacle novel; certain elements of another book I'm working on, a manual of occult training; and the upcoming Cancer ingress and its political and economic implications.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8407992", "title": "Reading", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just wondering how many books a month you read on average?  Always impressed by how well read you are.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8421560", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "12-15 books a month is pretty normal.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8423864", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You must be the VIP at the local public library.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8424888", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, it's a busy library and there are a lot of avid readers who go there; the librarians know me and vice versa, of course, but I'm not that exceptional.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-27 07:37 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8424120", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At a rate of 1 book every 2-3 days, do you experience any recall problems? It must be challenging to remember most of what you read. Do you resort to any mnemonic techniques or you don't find it necessary?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8425400", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I have a very good memory for material I read -- it probably comes from having learned to read well before my 3rd birthday, so a lot of my brain growth took place while my neurons were processing and storing written language. I used to win trivia contests at science fiction conventions. (I couldn't do that now, since very little SF written since 1980 or so interests me, but back in the day it was fun, and I got a free ticket to the next year's con three years in a row.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8446392", "title": "Re: Reading", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You might like the one about the HOA from hell, it’s comic horror.  The author, so far as I know, is alive, but you might want to give him a pass in exchange for a couple of hours of laughs.  Then as soon as he dies you can read the rest of his stuff.  He used to specialize in comedy horror but I think in recent years he seems to have switched to the standard horror.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8410296", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) This one is also a good one: https://www.globalresearch.ca/", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8421816", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not a great fan of their ideology, but it's useful to know what people on that end of things are thinking.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8418488", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Matila Ghyka's The Golden Number looks extremely interesting. Would you say it is appropriate for someone with a talent for math but no background in sacred geometry?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8422072", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, very much so. It's somewhat technical but it explains its terms well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8419000", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "4) Does anything really stand out in the Cancer ingress?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8422328", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes.\n;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8428216", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8428984", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'll be publishing a detailed discussion of that for subscribers to my Patreon and SubscribeStar accounts.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8429496", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm the one who asked if anything stood out in the Cancer ingress: thank you for this; I needed a really good laugh!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8396984", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\n1. Is there a 1-to-1 relationship between the Spiritual Self, the Higher Self, and the Personality in Incarnation? In other words, for each Yechidah at any given time, is there is a single Higher Self, and for each Higher Self, a unique Personality? Or could a single Higher Self be in charge of multiple Personalities, and similarly, could a single Yechidah be directing multiple Higher Selves?\n2. Do you consider YHVH to be omnipotent and omniscient, and if not, are its believers simply mistaken?\n3. Does the work in the Golden Dawn tradition, on which your books LRM, Paths of Wisdom, and Circles of Power build upon, commit the practitioner in some way to the Judeo-Christian God? Is some kind of relationship or attachment formed that can’t be broken at a later stage?\n4. In The Middle Pillar, Israel Regardie mentions off-hand that one could do the LBRP two or three times a day to get additional practice. Is this useful for a beginner, or in general? It seems a bit excessive, sort of like taking two or three showers a day. (I assume that it wouldn’t be a good idea to do the Middle Pillar two or three times a day)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8398008", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) According to the occult philosophy I'm familiar with, it's a one-to-one relationship all the way down.\n2) How could you possibly tell if a being was actually omnipotent and omniscient? Nobody's yet come up with an omnipotentiometer, or what have you. All you can say for sure is that a given god appears to be very, very powerful. Since the miracles attributed to YHVH in times recent enough for good evidence to survive are no more remarkable than those attributed to many other deities, yes, my guess is that his worshipers got caught up in what Alfred North Whitehead called \"metaphysical flattery\" and attributed to their god qualities that no being has, or can have.\n3) No. It helps, when you're doing that work, if you have a working relationship with that god, but in my experience he's not the jealous one -- it's some of his human believers, especially those who depend on a full collection plate for their income, who get bent out of shape.\n4) I don't recommend it for beginners. If you're an experienced practitioner and are doing healing work with subtle energies, as Regardie was and did, it's probably safe, and might even be helpful.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8399544", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) Somewhat related, but as a polytheist, are you committed to the ultimate Unity of the cosmos, in the sense of a (Neo)Platonic One, where apparent multiplicities and dualities are resolved? Or is it Many all the way down? If it's the former, wouldn't this One be pretty close to what monotheists call God, although it wouldn't necessarily be a personal god?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8400312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a common misunderstanding of Neoplatonism. The One is not the ultimate unity of the cosmos; the One is the principle by which the cosmos exists. It is apart from everything else, and has no qualities or characteristics, not even existence if this is understood as being something distinct from nonexistence. It is not a god. It does not think, act, experience, or care, much less pick one specific Middle Eastern ethnic group as its Chosen People or have a son who it sends to earth to die on a cross to redeem humanity from its sins.\nThe cosmos is a unity in a certain sense, in that it participates in the One, but it's a unity that embraces infinite diversity, and the multiplicities and dualities are not resolved in it -- they play freely from everlasting to everlasting. So, yes, I accept Neoplatonism as a very useful set of metaphors for the nature of reality -- knowing that metaphors are as close as our brains can get to that subject -- and no, I don't make the howling logical error of confusing a ground of being with a divine person.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8415672", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John, from a cabalistic point of view, would then the Neoplatonic One be a bit like Ain, Ain Soph, or Ain Soph Aur? I imagine it's not like Keter, since Keter is Being?\nManuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8422584", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, in a sense. Neoplatonism and Cabala aren't necessarily an exact fit for each other -- as with any attempt to talk about the indescribable, the various approximations are not identical. Still, there's a similarity.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8423608", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ain Soph seems similar to \"apeiron\" (boundless) - the primal chaos before the manifestation of cosmos - in Pre-Socratic philosophy.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8420280", "title": "The YHWH jealous god thing: a datapoint (ymmv)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello\nI’d like to chime in on the question about working with the judeo-christian God, if I may.\nI’m a former lukewarm Baptist, then 20+ years devout atheist, then practicing polytheist (yes, thanks to you JMG - your World Full of Gods is a most excellent book) and now once again a practicing Christian. I was the one who wrote to you last summer, about feeling like I was being called to go to a certain Episcopal church. I’ve seen the question about working with YHWH or Jesus come up a few times, so I thought I’d share my experience.\nWhile I was still a polytheist, I was aware of YHWH’s existence, but pretty much ignored him. He didn’t seem to mind. (Somebody, maybe it was on this blog, said He requires worship of his chosen people (the jews) and accepts but does not require worship from others.  That seems to jibe with the feeling I got).   If a non-christian  calls on him, he may or may not help, like any other deity who may or may not respond to your requests.\nI started feeling called, however, and went to church. Skipped out communion the first time, as a voice told me “Don’t do this unless you are willing to commit”. The next Sunday, I committed. Was officially confirmed in the church in February, but that felt like a rubber stamp: the real confirmation was done by God months before.\nSo, for you non-christians who are wondering, I would say, just be polite. He doesn’t owe you anything, but as JMG pointed out, often answers non-christian calls for help. If you have dedicated yourself to him, however, you had better not call on any other gods. I made the mistake of doing the CGD version of things ONE time after my conversion, and proceeded to have a very.bad.day.  I now do a SoP calling on the various Names of Jesus and ending with a binding prayer (think of a knight offering his sword to his king) and things have been wonderful. I guess I’m still a polytheist in the sense that I believe there are other gods (and no, they are not the same thing as demons) but I am not to worship them. I may greet them politely when encountered, and I still greet the nature spirits in my garden and the little cluster of (what I think are) air elementals that play in my oak tree, but think of it like a married man politely greeting a woman who is not his wife. There are definitely limits!\nAnyhow, that’s how I see it. To paraphrase Richard Bach, “Everything in this comment may be wrong”", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8411832", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) If the God (or the highest impersonal principle - whatever it is called) were omniscient, then from its point of view, the existence of the universe would be a pointless experiment whose outcome is already pre-determined. If such a being has all the attributes of the Absolute, then why would it need to do such an experiment whose outcome is already known to it?\nAlso, the idea of omniscience and its direct implication (pre-determination) are not compatible with occult philosophy. Because i) Occult philosophy assumes that all of the beings in the universe have some degree of free will, depending on their degree of development (from the simplest particle to the most complex life form). ii) If the Cosmos manifests itself as a Universal Mind and the events are ideas in this Mind, then the exact knowledge of an event and its occurrence must be simultaneous.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8454072", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "You're looking at the problem with the logic of existence within the parameters of time and space, where change always entails the passage of time, for example from an earlier cause to a later effect.  In the part of our existence that lies wholly outside of time and space, there seems to be a thing somewhat analogus to \"change,\" but without any temporal component, any \"before\" and \"after.\"\n(I'm sorry if this is unclear.  It's probably not really possible to understand these words of mine without at least some dim memory, some past perception, of that mode of our existence, where everything that \"was\" and \"is\" and \"will be\" is co-present, no matter \"where\" it might be.)\nAnyway, in this mode of existence the logic of ordinary existence doesn't work, and two logically contradictory statements about \"things\" in it can both be equally accurate (\"true\") within the limits of human language.    In that mode of existence, it is not paradoxical, but highly instructive, to assert, for example, that \"the Gods exist\" and \"the Gods do not exist\" are both equally \"true.\"  What the Gods \"do\" that cannot be better expressed by any other word than our verb \"to exist,\" is so poorly captured even by that word, and by the rules of logic our poor brains are trapped within, that both the affirmation and the denial are equally accurate and equally inaccurate.\nI hope this helps clear things up just a little ...\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-28 01:51 am (UTC)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8397240", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) The Pythagorean Brotherhood is known to have used a signet ring with a pentagram and the word “Health” in Greek written on each of the five points. How effective would this likely have been as a talisman? Do we have enough knowledge to recreate something like this today?\n2) Does the method of burial have any impact on the afterlife? The Ancient Egyptians certainly seemed to think so. What would be the difference between, for example, burial vs cremation? In certain countries with low living space and high population densities (for example, Japan) cremation is basically the norm for everyone, which might have some interesting implications.\n3) Let’s take a hypothetical person that has no inner development whatsoever, no contact with their Higher Self. What would such a person be like? Would they operate purely at the astral level, and have no capacity for memory, will, or imagination? Are these the people that stare blankly into Las Vegas slot machines?\n4) If someone like Aleister Crowley can reach the pinnacle of magic, would I be justified in stating that an individual’s moral character is irrelevant for magical attainment? As long as someone is aware of the less savory aspects of their personality instead of repressing them, so that the self-awareness gained through magic doesn't overwhelm them, the powers of the universe don’t seem to care about someone’s moral purity. You can be a jerk and still be an effective magician.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8398520", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Such talismans currently exist -- I've seen several -- and we have ample knowledge about how such things are made and consecrated.\n2) Normally it's not a big deal. Egypt, like some other ancient societies, had an archaic technology that allowed some specially prepared souls to step out of the cycle of reincarnation; that was later abused by people who saw it as a way to cheat death, and eventually the techniques were lost and it simply became a burial ceremony gone through by rote, with no effect.\n3) Such people aren't hypothetical -- they make up the majority of our species. People don't begin to contact their Higher Selves, even subconsciously, until they've finished learning the lessons of the human level and are getting ready to move on. They have memory, will, and imagination, but only in reflected forms, so the memory is fragmentary and unstable as Hod, the will is mostly submerged in the passions of Netzach, and the imagination simply rehashes the existing stock of images in Yesod, the Treasure House of Images.\n4) Aleister Crowley didn't reach the pinnacle of magic. Come on -- he started out life rich, intelligent, talented, handsome, and charismatic, and ended up as a burnt-out drug addict in a small town nursing home with an estate worth 16 shillings and a name that he had personally made a laughing stock on three continents. If that's the result of a life devoted to magic,\nyou're doing it wrong\n. Crowley crashed and burned on the rocks of his own overdeveloped ego; it's a common occupational hazard of those whose magical practice isn't guided by a good clear sense of magical ethics.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8416696", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP. In regards to number 3, does this imply that those who are actively seeking connection with the Higher Self through spiritual or magical practice in this life are relatively close to achieving Gwynfydd? Obviously \"relatively close\" here meaning maybe still a couple of lifetimes?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8422840", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They're at least on their way. It depends on what karmic issues they have to clear away and what other factors might be involved. On the whole, though, that's likely.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8420792", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) Does this mean anyone practising the occult is probably getting ready to move on?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8423096", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Depends on why they're attracted to occult practice. If it's purely a matter of wanting to use occultism to get stuff or to pad out the ego, no, they're preparing to plunge a lot deeper into matter by way of some very unpleasant karma. If what motivates them is dissatisfaction with living a life centered on material things, a longing (however vague and undefined) for some deeper and truer connection with reality, then yes, they've completed the first stage of human existence -- that of exploring the potentials of the human level in and of itself -- and are in the second stage -- that of preparing to move on to a wider world.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8447416", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What would happen to someone trying to conjure up $ for something he really needs, say, an apt?  Minimum-wage people find it nearly impossible to come up with 1st month + last month + deposit + credit check fee and on and on and on ad nauseam.  Would such a person get hammered by karma?  (Spellcheck wanted “hammered by Karen.”  😄)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8448696", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The alt-right chaos mages from the Chans are getting at your spellchecker, I see. ;-)\nThere's a reliably safe way to do money magic -- it's to do magic to get opportunities to earn money. If you're giving fair value in exchange for fair value, hard work for the cash you need, that's not selfishness, that's ordinary give and take. If it's for basic necessities like a place to live, all the better.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8397496", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "It's the former Japanese monk again:\n1) I left out a detail from the post on the main blog, which is relevant: it was my past life that crafted the ritual which was intended to bring the Japanese emperor back to power. My divination indicate that yes, there is a connection between it and the fact Hiroshima and Nagasaki are the only two places to have been nuked, but also that it's not done working its way out yet. My divination also says it will be done by the time Pluto fades out, and so I'm a little concerned what it might finish with. More importantly, it means I am in some sense responsible for the deaths of millions and horrific destruction (including, as it turns out, the monasteries where the ritual was cast).\na) Am I correct to think I probably still have a lot of negative karma from that?\nb) How can I safely go about addressing the leftover karma? I'm not particularly interested in my next 150 years being as nasty as the past 150 years.\n2) The monk life was born in Chiba, and home appears to mean there for him. Based on my divinations, if I go anywhere near there, I will end up there, and I will die there shortly after I arrive. It will not be a pleasant death either, but rather a nasty, horrific one.\nI've also determined that that fate awaits at least one lifetime, so if I'm willing to embrace it, go there knowing that's the fate that awaits me, would that ground the working and allow my future lives freedom from it?\n3) My last life also did some spiritual work which brought up a lot of past life memories which she absolutely wasn't ready for, and which are coming back to me as I remember being her. Is it safe to assume that if those memories come naturally to me, I'm ready for them, or has that decision caused me issues for any lifetime which remembers being her?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8398264", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) A rather disturbing possibility has suddenly occurred to me: it's possible what's left for the working is for everyone who cast it to suffer death from a nuclear attack. Since my life at the time wasn't in Japan, I escaped it, but that just put it off for a while.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8403384", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, I don't do past-life work myself but find others' stories about it interesting, and I saw your post on JMG's other blog. I'm a few years older than you and used to living with a lot of complicated problems. (Many of them would actually fit your theory about the consequences of having been a drug-addled hippie in the previous one.)\nThis can be applied to plenty of mundane situations too. But sometimes there are big things, or final stages of something, that just can't be tackled, either now or possibly not ever. Do all the other things you can do instead. Possibly things will shift so you can actually tackle the other stuff, but don't get hung up on that. You've got enough else to concentrate on now and in the near future. Do what you can while you can.\nWhy do you have to do all of the work to set this stuff right in this life? You might be able to do a lot of it, and that's fine. Maybe when you're 70 you'll find you ending up in Japan, or maybe you won't and you'll be born there next time or a time after that. Do what you can sensibly do, and leave the rest of it to work itself out.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8399032", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I would encourage you to set all this aside for a while and concentrate on simply living this life and producing as much good karma as you can here and now. It's as easy as it is unproductive to tie yourself into knots about what you may or may not have done in a series of past lives. Your karma and your destiny will work themselves out; focusing on what you can do right here and right now will help them do so. (If your Japanese monk incarnation had any contact with Zen, that's what the nearest Zen master would have told him...)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8409784", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Isn't it the case that past life experiences come when the person concerned is ready for them? Point 3 from the poster of the previous question would be a counterexample. If it is possible that someone remembers a past life without being ready for it, what are possible causes and consequences?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8423352", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's why I emphatically do not recommend doing work to bring up past life memories. If you let them emerge on their own, they'll come when you're ready for them; force the situation and you can land in various kinds of hurt.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8429240", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) What sort of hurt?\n2) Is it problematic to then remember that life later?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8430264", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Emotional trauma, mostly.\n2) Not once you're ready for it.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8427704", "title": "Dot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I'm really confused about karma. You've said that the main way it works itself out is through your character. I can see how that would work with, say, a past self that used too many drugs and messed up their patterns of thought, and that passes through to the next life, who has trouble thinking clearly as a result and this attracts certain kinds of problems to him.\nBut this poor guy's 6 year old past Hindu self's character surely had nothing causal to do with the genocide that accompanied the partition of India? It was nothing personal.\nIs everything that happens to us karma? Or is some of it just random chance, or other people's/group's karma working itself out, or the results of our free will, or our destiny manifesting itself?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8429752", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To say that karma mainly works through character is not to say that it only works through character. There are also other factors, of course. Karma has a role in shaping all events, though destiny, individual will, the will and destiny and karma of other people, and the basic cussedness of the cosmos all play a role.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8441272", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Not the original poster)\nDo the karmic effects of an action depend in part on motivation?  For example, does giving out of genuine concern for another's well-being generate a different kind of karma than giving for the purpose of accumulating good karma?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8444600", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Very much so. Every action is shaped by its motivation -- that's why so often, charity that's done for motives other than actual compassion doesn't actually help much. Action embodies the motivation that guides it, for good or ill.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8447672", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Does that mean the planetary chrities are no good?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8449464", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not at all. It simply means that you don't rack up good karma for doing them. You're doing the equivalent of buying and selling, giving a planetary energy something in exchange for a reciprocal gift.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8448184", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If a transactional approach to karma is self-defeating, how would one focus on creating good karma, as you suggested the OP should do?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8449208", "title": "Re: Dot", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "By focusing on becoming the kind of person who generates good karma, of course.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8398776", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) I would like to use the candles thing for help with vibration, for Celtic Golden Dawn practice. Is it possible?\n2) There is an updated edition if Michell's book, called\nThe New View for Atlantis\n. Is this one of the cases where the old one is better?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8399288", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'm not sure what you mean by \"the candles thing.\" Any hints? ;-)\n2) I prefer the older edition for reasons that are mostly literary in nature. The newer one has some of the mistakes of the original edition corrected, but it's not quite as colorfully written or as wildly visionary!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8399800", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The procedure where a candle with a certain color is lit in the same day of a week, every week, asking for the help of a planetary god with an issue.\nAnd how does one know when to stop?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8400056", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, you can do that. For anything related to magic, invoke Mercury on a Wednesday during the hour of Mercury. Ask for something specific, so you know when you get it and can stop. If you make a donation to a Mercurial charity as well -- nonprofits that help children with speech, language, and reading are a good choice here -- you'll likely have excellent results.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8402360", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I'm getting a bit desperate with this stuff. It's time to ask for help.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8414904", "title": "Where do we find the hours for the planets.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Where does one find the days/hours for planets other than an online search, which may not be accurate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8425656", "title": "Re: Where do we find the hours for the planets.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are planetary hours calculation programs readily available online --\nhere's one\nfrom the Rosicrucian Fellowship, which is free, and\nhere's another\nfrom Chris Warnock which is very inexpensive. You can also simply learn to calculate them yourself --\nhere's an article\nby Chris which explains how to do that.\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-27 07:48 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8428728", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What would be the candle color for Mercury under CGD?\nAre there planet colors for that system?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8430008", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The CGD system doesn't use planets but it does use the spheres of the Tree of Life for comparable purposes. For Byth, the 8th sphere, the color to use is orange, and yes, you burn it on a Wednesday.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8400568", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why is a Ouija board dangerous but a seance isn’t, or at least I’ve never read of one causing Ouija-like problems?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8401336", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Seances can cause serious problems if the medium isn't properly trained; fortunately most spiritualist churches and organizations follow tried and true methods of development and avoid most of the potential problems. With an Ouija board, though, the people who are using it generally have no training at all, and have no way to select what kinds of entities come through, so they routinely land in trouble.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8409272", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember you saying that entities that come through in mediumship can lie (as well as the medium herself, telling people what they want to hear).\nI went to a spiritualist church a good while back and I wonder now if it was a good idea.  Would spiritualists know how to 'screen' the entities coming through, if there are any? I suppose it depends on the training and the medium. Is there any good book on the subject?\nThanks as always.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8425912", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's not a field I've studied myself, but Alan Kardec's books on mediumship are highly recommended.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8438456", "title": "ouija", "user": "ritaer", "content": "It is incredibly easy to manipulate a ouija board. Or so I hear. (wink, wink, nudge, nudge.) Or maybe I just had naive friends in high school.\nRita", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8400824", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "We haven’t applauded our generous host’s donation of his time for a while.\n👏👏👏👏👏", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8401592", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Thank you.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8404920", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Hear, hear", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8406456", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Indeed! Thank you very much, JMG, for your generosity and for Magic Mondays!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8432312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Seconded!  I religiously and meticulously go over the comments here every Monday.  It's truly grand, and appreciated!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8401080", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "vitranc", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have question about exchanging energies with trees. Yesterday I tried to do it for the first time. I found a nice pine at the edge of a forrest, went to it, touched it with my hand and asked, if it was ok.\nI did not feel any negative Response, but I should mention, that I am a muggle and usually feel next to nothing.\nI proceeded with the technique from the Druidry handbook, I took a sitting position with my back to the tree and relaxed. I imagined the tree and its life force.\nSince the atmosphere was clear, peaceful and refreshing and I had a bit of an developing headache, I went on and tried to „clear it“ I concentrated on the headache and how it went away.\n12 minutes passed and I went back inside and after an hour and a half developed a splitting headache and exhaustion. Thinking I did something wrong I even consulted my daily divination, which did predict, that I will rush ahead into trouble. Great. I asked if I did something wrong and got MOR-, PHAGOS-, STRAIF+\nSomething unexpected happened, because you did not head the wisdom, results of ones own actions.\n- did I impose on the tree and got a retaliation?\n- or did I ask for this myself, since my intentionally was focused on the headache in the negative?\n- or was the exhaustion a consequence of my inexperience?\n- I sleept it off and am feeling better. What did I do wrong and how can I cure it?\n- did I in any way harm the tree and how can I make it good?\nBest regards,\nV", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8401848", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Since I wasn't there at the time I can't tell exactly what happened. You might consider doing divination to answer each of these questions; you might also take your Ogham with you when you next go to interact with a tree, and use a one-card reading to get a \"yes\" or \"no.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8405176", "title": "One card yes or no.", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "When doing this kind of yes or no divination how do you distinguish yes and no. Would upright vs reversed be sufficient with the details of the card adding more information?\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8426168", "title": "Re: One card yes or no.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the way I do it.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8419768", "title": "Sometimes a headache is just a headache", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "The following is only my opinion: I think the tree wanted to exchange energy with you, especially since your headache was temporarily relieved.  Since a tree can't cure you of all your ills instantaneously, the headache came back because it is warm outside and everyone's sinuses are on the warpath.  Mine too -- this time of year is gorgeous but beauty comes with a price!  Trees are wonderful creatures but they're nowhere near omnipotent when it comes to human headaches; let's say you had a headache because you were constipated.  The tree can take some of your constipated energy to help things start moving but eating right and getting on the toilet is one hundred percent up to you.  You also drew Oghams that I interpret as positive.  In my estimation, the Forfedha, just like Tarot trumps, are too complex to interpret as ill-dignified and I only interpret them that way when I ask a blunt yes/no question and draw a single Forfedha.  I think Mor means \"sea change\" (\nhttp://druidogham.wordpress.com\n) and it is indicating a great shift in your life.  Being on the Path now would be a major shift... just saying.  Phagos is the influence of Hermes, the power of writing things down, mastery of some aspect of the mental plane.  Straif, which I do read as well-dignified as it is not a Forfedha, is necessary challenge: what doesn't kill you makes you stronger.  You are being proofed.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8402104", "title": "Similar Courts in 2 Charts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I cast 2 geomancy readings on Sunday, each for a different job I applied for. The second followed right after the first.\nThis is a hard time to be applying for jobs, and I was quite worried over the weekend -- I already went through a few interviews at other roles, and the recruiters told me they were putting hiring on hold for the time being, but would try to contact me again soon.\nAnyway, I ended up with two charts with very similar Courts.\n1) LW: Tristitia, RW: Rubeus, Judge: Acquisitio\n2) LW: Tristitia, RW: Albus, Judge: Fortuna Major\nThe Court for 2) seems a bit more positive.\nMy interpretation with Tristitia as LW for both charts indicates that the companies are \"stuck\" in some way, and experiencing delays. However, the judges are both positive.\nAs the Witnesses weren't very positive yet gave positive Judges, I also looked at the Reconcilers for both charts.\nThe Reconcilers are fairly positive for both charts:\n1) 1st Mother: Conjunctio, Judge: Acquisitio, Reconciler: Fortuna Major\n2) 1st Mother: Via, Judge: Fortuna Major, Reconciler: Fortuna Minor\nMy interpretation is that I have a good chance of getting both jobs. However, there might be delays, and while the jobs might be good for stability, but I might otherwise be disappointed in other ways. Overall, it looks like I will end up fine.\nIs this a reasonable interpretation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8426680", "title": "Re: Similar Courts in 2 Charts", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's how I would interpret both of them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8402616", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "There are supposedly cases where a person, that has attained Gwynfydd, chooses to incarnate again in a human body to help other people, like bodhisattvas. Can it happen that such a person creates negative karma, does somethong bad, or the like? What would be the consequences", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8430520", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, because the attainment of Gwynfydd doesn't mean you're perfect; you can still mess up. Such a soul would likely have to incarnate as a human repeatedly until it had worked out the karma and was ready again to move on.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8402872", "title": "Strange memory", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nA few years ago, I was talking with some friends and started spouting strange things about Robert E. Lee.  I am Canadian and have never studied your Civil War or much of your history at all.\nI did not understand why I was saying what I was saying but the words tumbled out of my mouth with a will of their own.  I said Lee was a great man, a superior general, a paladin and I wanted to say he was against slavery but that seemed too strange.  Later, I looked up a couple of biographies of General Lee and he was everything I had said about him and he was indeed against slavery.\nSome time later, while doing Kundalini yoga, the music in the studio changed to a sad violin solo and I had a vision of a pair of shaggy black horses in the winter hauling a wagon with an empty box.  Neither the horses nor the wagon had any insignia on them but I was pretty sure I was seeing a scene from the American Civil War and I was overcome with sadness, guilt and self-loathing.  I think the wagon had either unloaded bodies or coffins.  I wept and I can go for years without shedding tears.  Later, I recalled the vision was from my left eye only.\nI stopped doing Kundalini yoga as I think it was bringing things up before their time.  My question for you is, do you think this was someone showing me things from their past or was I remembering things from my past?  I have tried to do divinations on this but have received odd, inconclusive answers.    One witch friend said I was haunting myself, that I was the soldier and another incarnation at the same time.\nI believe this could be an ancestor as one of my Grandmothers came from the States as a child a very long time ago.  He, or another man in a cape, (I think people might have been seeing the cape-shouldered great coats favoured in that war) has been seen here by a couple of friends and he or some other male disembodied person greeted an empath friend while I was helping her on with her coat.  My daughter could smell a man, very strong, rank smell, in her room one night.  I apologized on his behalf, explaining he had a very rough war.\nThese things have all happened over a number of years.  Sometimes, ages go past here without a single oddball thing happening.\nPlease let me know what you think.\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8430776", "title": "Re: Strange memory", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It sounds to me like a past life memory surfacing.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8433848", "title": "Re: Strange memory", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for that.  If that was my last lifetime, I must have resisted reincarnation vigorously.  I am finally starting to really enjoy being alive and hope to achieve a good result in this life to be a more kind and cheerful person next time around.  My family and friends agree I had been a man and a very bad one.  I will try to do better this time.\nThanks so much for the magic in my life.  You have been a great help.\nMaxine", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8403128", "title": "Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "Salutations JMG! If the subject is sacred geometry, might I recommend the Constructing the Universe series for those who like workbooks? Here's some quick questions and then a larger question I'm wrestling with:\n1) I've heard some people say the Donald Tyson edition of Agrippa's Three Books of Occult Philosophy has been modified according to Tyson's own tastes. At the very least, a Youtube review channel shows that the printing is horrendous (some pictures - inserted for flavour and not part of the original text - are so degraded they consist mostly of flat black ink, as if they're the product of 20 photocopies of photocopies). Joseph Peterson is a very respected scholar, but I can't seem to find a printed version of his translation of the Three Books. What version of the Three Books is sitting on your shelf?\n2) In Geomancy, when trying to choose a new form of magical practice, is that an 8th or 9th house issue? The 9th is \"occult philosophy and divination\" but what if you're doing more than just studying out of books such as performing daily rituals? Wouldn't that classify it as \"magic performed by/for the Querent\" as part of the 8th house? This leads into the big question...\n3-Big Question) I'm feeling unsure as to what magical path to choose. I've been sporadically working Bruce Frantzis' Water Style Qi Gong in addition to Geomancy and trying to meditate consistently, but I'm starting to think that maybe I should first ground myself in a more complete tradition first before going on to experimental magic. I see a great deal of worth in Taoism, both in its philosophy and practices that seem way more powerful and unique than anything I've seen. But it's difficult to break into as a westerner, and there is no self regulating system with checks and balances like Golden Dawn based systems. My plan was to develop my energy body with Qi Gong (my energy body seems about as responsive as clay) and move from there to a system of Astral Projection and Energy Work that is also fairly Qi Gong inspired, then once mastered move to Franz Bardon's system. Note that I'm not jumping around from system to system, but I've previously thought that each system is a prerequisite to waking up my sluggish energy body and giving me the tools to work the next system even more effectively. Like I need to learn metalworking to forge a shovel, and I need a shovel to begin gardening, and I need to begin gardening to grow herbs, and I need to grow herbs to make a fine tea.\nI'd love to experiment with the way Taoist practices interact with Western Energy work, but should I try getting established in a more accessible tradition first (even if it doesn't inspire me)? Or is this a test that I should meet by knuckling down and continuing with my Qi Gong practices?\nMy goal with magic is to become psychic/clairvoyant enough that I can experiment and observe directly the energies of the human body and living things. So I guess I'm looking for a tradition that is fairly etheric focused like Qi Gong.\nSorry for the shotgun spread of text, I thought if you understood where I'm coming from you might know how best to point me. Here's some bullet point questions:\n3a) Is staying the course advisable, or would I benefit more efficiently from a tradition that is more complete than Taoism and designed to be learned by westerners in solitude from a book?\n3b) Does the Celtic Golden Dawn work with the etheric, etheric/astral projection and developing clairvoyance? It seems to me the Golden Dawn traditions are very Astral/Mental plane based.\n3c) Will working with the Qi Gong circuits lock me out from practicing western styles of magic (and vice versa)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8431032", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I used Tyson when that was what was available. These days, when I want to consult Agrippa, I check a PDF of the Latin text. I know that may not be too helpful to you!\n2) Magical practice is 8th, magical theory is 9th. If you're looking at taking up practice, that's 8th.\n3a) That's something only you can decide.\n3b) No, its techniques are standard Golden Dawn-derived, thus primarily astral and mental. There's a significant etheric component via alchemy, but not the sort of thing you're working with.\n3c) Very probably yes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8455352", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "1) Hmm. Dr. Peterson has a pdf up on his wonderful site, but I find I learn better from physical paper. Bookbinding is one of the traditional skills I've wanted to learn for a while, perhaps once the local leather vendor opens back up I'll have to pay them a visit.\n3b) Do you know of any traditions other than Taoism that are focused on the etheric (aside from maybe natural magic)? Mesmerism perhaps?\n3c) Well darn. I'd really like to help obscure Taoist concepts enrich western magic, I think there's a lot to offer, it's just obscured by the lack of translated texts and the dozens of different methods with the same name. For example, the \"spiralling dragon currents\" of the Feng Shui traditions that focus more on the earth than on human buildings sound like a match for the Telluric currents you describe in The Secret of the Temple. The \"Creation of the Golden Foetus\" (beginning of creating a sort of perfected immortal spirit body) also sounds similar in its goal to the perfection of your Mental Sheath, or the attainment of Gwynfdd, except it begins in the lowest Dan Tien rather than out there in the Astral/Mental somewhere. I just wish I had more guidance, I think I know how those first Golden Dawn adepts felt trying to piece together things from bad translations and limited sources, except I'm no adept.\n4) You've said in the past that your Druid Magic courses are similar to Taoism. Did you mean only philosophically, or do they share some mechanics? The downward sun current and the upward earth current in the DMH sound very much like the downward Water Qi and the Upward Fire Qi, except the downward chi is pulled in through the crown of the head (but NOT the brain) through the face, over the tongue, down the throat and into the body. The moon current also sounds similar to \"The Fusion of Fire and Water\" practice, which combines both Qi currents. The Taoist \"stillness meditation\" neccessary for Frantzis' Qi Gong work is also identical to the \"receptive meditation\" in the Druidry Handbook.\n5) Why are these systems necessarily incompatible? I know it's because they treat energy in the body differently, but what specific differences cause the mix up?\nIs it the Qi Gong exercises which concentrate energy in specific spots, whereas western magic doesn't?\n6) I know you've said mixing Qi Gong with your own practice messed up your kidneys for a while. What exact practices were you doing, and what sources were you learning from? I've read and reread the following thread, but some more data points might help:\nhttps://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/80698.html\nEdited (Added more details)\nDate:\n2020-04-28 01:51 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8458680", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3b) Central European occultism of the sort exemplified by Franz Bardon. There are many other authors in the same field, but next to none of them have been translated into English. If you're up for learning German, you might be able to to very well.\n3c) Understood. Keep in mind that you're playing with fire, though.\n4) The similarities are mostly philosophical, as far as I know.\n5) That's a good question that can only be settled via experimentation. I'm not even sure that they're necessarily incompatible -- just that I've heard from a number of people who've tried to mix them and who had health problems as a result.\n6) I studied one of the old Yang styles of taijiquan from Sifu Andrew Dale in Seattle and then from his student Sifu Gene Burnett in Ashland OR. That system included several qigong sets, including Emei Mountai qigong and Tian Shan qigong. That interacted with the magical work I was doing to give me a serious yang kidney qi depletion, which took years to cure.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8470712", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "3b) Could you list as many of those authors as you can think of? Learning German might be in the cards someday, it's one of the languages I'd like to learn (the first is Latin, which I've resolved to begin learning by June if not sooner).\nDo you happen to know if anybody has tried combining Bardon with Qi Gong exercises? That would be an interesting experiment. His \"accumulation of the elements\" seemed exactly like an etheric exercise when I read it. Is there anything in Bardon that comes to mind as being incompatible with Qi work?\n6) Alright, I'll look into those sets and how they work, although any style with Yang in the title automatically sets off warning bells in my head. Mantak Chia is one master with particularly Yang style methods and quite a few people report getting burned with his methods (no pun intended).\nIf you feel like reading about Qi Gong, the system I'm practicing is by Bruce Frantzis, and can be best explained in \"Opening the Energy Gates of Your Body\" and \"The Great Stillness.\" Bruce Frantzis was one of the first westerners who journeyed into China when they opened their borders, and he spent a lot of time in China and Japan seeking ever more advanced martial arts practices (he's a very adept martial artist in multiple styles). During his time in Japan he zeroed in on the fact that some sort of ki energy was at work behind some of the most powerful practices, and these practices traced their lineage to Taoists and Chan Buddhists from China. He then went seeking masters in China and happened upon a very old master who had studied as a boy at one of the last monasteries that taught what he calls \"Water Method.\" The Water style was apparently in the process of dissolving (heh) and dying out in favour of newer Yang and Buddist-hybrid forms of Qi Gong. The tradition officially passed on to Frantzis claimed to trace it's lineage directly back to Lao Tse, although I'm not sure if I believe that part. Either way, Frantzis has come across some very obscure, untranslated forms of Qi Gong. In one of his books he mentions a kind of White Crane style Qi Gong that involved \"vibrating\" his Qi at tremendous speeds, and said that it made him strong enough to shatter bones with a single strike during martial arts, but he abandoned it when he realized it was making him \"subtly psychotic\" and induced subtle levels of megalomania and indifference to the pain caused in others in its practitioners. Fascinating and terrifying stuff!\nFrantzis recommends Tai Chi but says Ba Gua and Hsing-I are much more powerful and complete, so for anybody experimenting with eastern movement practices, there's a couple more inquiries for your experimentation.\nEdited (Changed Title from \"The Tao of Letting Go\" to \"The Great Stillness\", added addendum on Ba Gua and Hsing-I)\nDate:\n2020-04-28 03:49 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8472760", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "3b) Georg Lomer, Anton Joseph Kirchweger, and Franz Anton Mesmer are the ones who come to mind.\n6) You do know that the Yang in the Yang style is not the same character as Yang in Yin-Yang, I trust...\nAs for Kumar Frantzis, yes, I'm familiar with his work. He had quite a colorful reputation back when I was plugged into the tai chi scene.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8475576", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "3b) Thanks!\n6) Yes indeed, apologies for any unclear word salad.\nYes, Frantzis is quite the character personally. I wonder if he rails against \"Fire Type\" Qi Gong so heavily because his master told him \"Stay away from fire, it's evil! (because you're too much of a hot head already)\"\nOn an unrelated note, I got to hear your voice on the Hermitix podcast recently and was surprised at how warm, jovial and kind your voice sounded, which parallels your personality excellently. You sound like somebody I'd sit down to play D&D with. Thanks for all the work you do and the time you make for all of your readers. I can't think of many authors who go to such lengths and do it all with a smile. Have a nice night, good sir.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8457656", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "open_space", "content": "What is it that locks you out from Western style magic by doing these, I assume ethericly dense based exercises? Is it a permanent lock, or more like excluding you from practicing both at the same time?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8458936", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good question. What I know is that a number of people who've tried doing both, including me, ended up with significant health problems as a result.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8455864", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Basically, Tyson just reprinted the 1651 printed English translation (the only one ever made) of Agrippa's Latin, modernizing the spelling and adding paragraph breaks for ease of reading.  (He also added a huge number of notes and appendices.)  The 1651 translation is a usable one, but not a really great one.  It would be possible to make a better one (\"had we but world enough and time\").  You can download a PDF of the 1651 edition here:\nhttps://onedrive.live.com/?authkey=%21AEsyXVTCFS9XIKk&cid=2709E41E745116A5&id=2709E41E745116A5%21238&parId=2709E41E745116A5%21231&o=OneUp\nThere is now a good critical edition of Agrippa's original Latin, edited by V. Perrone Compagni (Brill, 1992) but it costs multiple hundreds of dollars.  You can download Agrippa's original first edition in Latin (1553) from a number of German and Swiss rare book libraries.  A PDF of what seems to be C. G. Jung's own personal copy of the 1533 edition is available from the \"Swiss Electronic Library\"  (www.e-lib.ch).\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-28 01:48 am (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8476344", "title": "Re: Lost in the Woods, Trying to Find the Path Again", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I know I'm late for the party, but since someone can stumble upon your recommendation in the future, one always must check at the publisher first.\nIt is not uncommon to find second-hand books, specially on magic, at astronomical prices, You can buy Agrippa's book directly from Brill for  €125.00 / $155.00 (I think this price does not include shipping).\nLink: https://brill.com/view/title/1024", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8403896", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear John,\nI have been a long-time reader of your writings, sincere thanks.\nI have recently started working through the lessons in \"Learning Ritual Magic\". I would like to request your advice on two things:\n1. I am a more-or-less practising Hindu, would this conflict with the practice and the lessons?\n2. While doing the LBRP, I'm not exactly sure how to visualise the archangels, i.e., which images to use. Are there any canonical images for this?\nMany thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8431288", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) As long as you can also deal with the Judeo-Christian god, as Sri Ramakrishna did, there should be no trouble at all.\n2) This is one of those areas where Hinduism has a huge advantage -- your tradition is very good with imagery, much more so than most others. (The Egyptians were on the same level, but I can't think of another example outside the Indian subcontinent and cultures influenced by, say, Buddhism.) There aren't really canonical images for each of the archangels, outside of the basic elements (robed, winged figures with halos about their heads and the standard symbolic objects in their hands). Do your best.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8404152", "title": "Astrology in German", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "Hi JMG and comentariat,\nI'd like to get into astrology and JMG has been recommending the old edition of \"A-Z Horoscope Maker and Delineator\".\nA question for German-speaking readers: Does anyone know of a good German introduction on astrology in the spirit of the above-mentioned book? I don't mind reading in English but I'm a bit daunted by the specialized vocabulary.\nThank you in advance!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8404408", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "How would I replace the god invitation of the SOP with something meaningful if I don't have a relationship with any Pantheon?\nOr..what might be a good Buddhist substitute for them?\nThanks a bunch.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8431544", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "What school of Buddhism do you practice? If it's one of the mantrayana or vajrayana schools I may be able to help you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8433592", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Vajrayana.\nThanks so much!. :)\nI actually used to deeply practice Shingon", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8434616", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you can handle Shingon, that's easy as pie, as I worked out a Shingon SoP years ago and found it very effective in practice. The Godai Nyorai or five Tathagatas plus Sakyamuni Buddha are assigned to the points as follows:\nEast: Fukūjōju Nyorai (Amoghasiddhi Buddha)\nWest: Amida Nyorai (Amitabha Buddha)\nSouth: Hōshō Nyorai (Ratnasambhava Buddha)\nNorth: Ashuku Nyorai (Aksobhya Buddha)\nBelow: Shaka Nyorai (Sakyamuni Buddha)\nAbove: Dainichi Nyorai (Vairocana Buddha)\n(These are not their traditional directional attributions but they are the ones that match the elements.)\nYou'll have to judge whether this is compatible with your current Vajrayana practice, but iirc the five wisdom buddhas are pretty generally revered.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8404664", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Sir and Druid,\nWhat consequences are there of using goofing powder on someone’s head in a dream? I do not know this person, and they were trying to pick my pockets when I realized that I had a bag of goofing powder in my hands. I broke the bag open over their head and I forcibly woke up as the powder was landing on their head.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8431800", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it's a dream, it's symbolic, not real. Have you considered meditating or journaling about it and seeing what you can figure out?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8405432", "title": "DA SOP", "user": "tunesmyth", "content": "Hello JMG,\nI have some questions of procedure with the Sphere Of Protection as given in The Dolmen Arch.\nQ1. The movements to the four points of the Elemental Cross are performed with just one hand, is that correct? So one hand hangs down at the side while the other moves up, down, right, and left; and then finally move both hands when crossing the hands over the chest.\nQ2. When invoking the third and fourth powers (the horizontal axis), are the names spoken while touching one's appropriate shoulder? Or is the hand stretched out to the side? Or some place else? The description for the third power seems to suggest the former, but the description for the fourth power also includes a part where one visualizes a ray flowing from the solar plexus \"flowing through your left side and across the palm of your left hand in a straight line\", which doesn't make sense if the hand is one the shoulder, and doesn't jibe with my assumption back in Q1 that the Elemental Cross is performed with just one hand.\nWould you mind clarifying here just a little bit?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8432056", "title": "Re: DA SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Yes, that's correct.\n2) Hmm! That's an edit-o. Ignore it -- it'll be removed in the next edition. You simply touch each shoulder with the right hand.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8405688", "title": "LBRP & SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello!\nI have been learning and studying LRM for a number of years and I have completed the course. Only the initiation is left to be carried out.\nI regularly do the ritual magic exercises of LRM and all I get is a rather pleasant tingling sensation in the forehead.\nI also practice discursive meditation and divination.\nI am pleased with DM + DIV as I get good results.\nHowever the LRM ritual gives me pretty much muted results compared to what others have been reporting.\n(1) I was wondering whether I should give the SOP ritual a try and compare the effects?\n(2) If I give SOP a try I would like a version that does not involve invoking gods, I'd prefer one which does not refer to a particular religious tradition. A version that could be suited to persons of different faiths and coming from different religious backgrounds for instance. Is that possible?\n(3) I would be interested in introducing some form of ritual magic + DM & DIV to my wife and may be a few selected friends. If ever I do that I'd need a version that is acceptable to people of diverse backgrounds because my wife is of a different faith as me and  where I live there is a lot of religious diversity. It is impossible NOT to bump into polytheists one minute and strict monotheists the next.\nPS: Yes, I'd like to found a lodge one of these days where I live and such a lodge could attract people of very diverse faiths. Finally, given your perspicacity and intelligence you might very well be able to identify me. Please keep it confidential if ever for where I live magic is considered either as foolish, superstitious or outright demonic. And yes I intend to do some divination about the matter!!!!\nMany thanks - I really appreciate your comments and dedication to teaching sane occultism.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8433080", "title": "Re: LBRP & SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Once you've completed the initiation in LRM, yes, you might want to spend six months or a year practicing the SoP and comparing the two.\n2) Easily done. The version covered\nin this series of posts\ncan be done without specifying or invoking deities -- just leave out references to them.\n3) The SoP is very well suited to that sort of thing -- it was the standard ritual in the Universal Gnostic Church, which has as a basic tenet the rule that every member chooses what he or she worships.\nAnd I'll go out of my way not to notice, or mention, who you might be. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8405944", "title": "DMH progress", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "I've been progressing very slowly through the DMH (5 years so far I think) but as you say there's no such thing as too slow. I'm living in a house with young kids and another on the way, so unless I find somewhere else to do magic I'll be sticking to the grove from your druidry handbook and the SOP for a while.\n1) Should I hold back on the more advanced rituals than the SOP and Grove until I've got the symbolism of the wheel of life memorized.\n2) If I do an SOP and then the druidry handbook's grove would it be workable to do path working in that open grove?\n3) Do you have any thoughts on a divination deck with the Ogham few's and 8 stations of the wheel of the year for 33 cards in total?\nI'm in the process of making an oak staff from a branch which came off a living tree in a storm. It felt quite wild and powerful (which I've since noticed is how a living oak tree feels) as I was taking the bark off though now that it's sanded smooth it's much quieter. I'm planning to coat it in linseed oil to protect it and use it as a walking stick while going tramping where I will use it to help me connect to the energies of nature and do the SOP. I feel like it is for powerful rituals outdoors and that I need to grow to be able to work with it properly. Once the staff and I are ready I'm planning to use the ritual in the DMH to enchant it.\n4) Will there be any issue that you can see with exposing it to sunlight for long periods as in your ENM you said it can wear off other enchantments.\n5) Similarly would there be any issues with it having contact with other people who may not have any idea what it is. I've had the intention that it should be safe to be around for others, keeping it's power locked up until needed so to speak.\n5) Would Esus be the one to ask to learn the \"tree magic\" you say Oak is used for in the ENM or are there other sources. Would you be able to briefly describe it for me, is it for helping trees grow, working with trees to do other magic or something else?\nHopefully that's not too many questions. Many thanks for your books and guidance", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8433336", "title": "Re: DMH progress", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, you can go ahead with the ritual work before you finish memorizing the symbolism.\n2) Yes, very much so. That's always the way I did it.\n3) Yes. You might be interested to know that that's also the number of cards in the Sacred Geometry Oracle...\n4) Wood and stone are both good at holding onto enchantments -- the stones of many stone circles are still powerfully charged, and think about how much sunlight they've been exposed to! -- and oak is particularly good at holding energy. You should have no trouble.\n5) That should also be fine.\n6) Yes, you'd invoke Esus for that. Tree magic is the branch of natural magic that uses the leaves, bark, wood, seeds, etc. of trees the way a herbalist uses herbs, for magical purposes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8439224", "title": "Re: DMH progress", "user": "sea_spray", "content": "Thank you very much.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8406200", "title": "Self-hypnosis et al", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In a response on the other blog, you said you had used magic not to get the universe to send you goodies, but to make yourself into the kind of person who does the things you wanted to do.\nI wish to do something similar. I mean to use affirmations and self-hypnosis, which I have practiced hitherto at a modest level of attainment. I am familiar with basic HOGD ritual, using Hellenic divine names and imagery.\nCan you suggest anything more, or particular ways of employing these methods? Do sigils have a place in this? What kind of regimen should I try to establish? Are there pitfalls to avoid?\nMy available references include your \"Circles of Power\" and \"Celtic Golden Dawn,\" so anything that can be adapted from those I should be able to manage. Thanks for any suggestions you may feel inclined to offer.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8434360", "title": "Re: Self-hypnosis et al", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you want to use magical methods in addition to affirmations and self-hypnosis, the basic triad of practices -- a daily protective ritual, such as the Hellenic LBRP; a daily session of discursive meditation; and a daily divination -- provides the foundation for that work. Once you've established that basis and made it a routine part of your life, you can start using the more advanced methods of ritual magic to transform yourself to become the kind of person who gets the life you want. Always do divination in advance of any working to make sure it's a good idea! Other than that, if you study\nCircles of Power\nclosely you should have all the tools you need.\nAs for for sigils, I never found them particularly useful, but your mileage may vary; some people get very good results from them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8441528", "title": "Re: Self-hypnosis et al", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!\nP. S. - Having partaken of the vibrations of the Cosmic Oom, I can now sign myself as -\nTangerine Palpitating Moose", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8445112", "title": "Re: Self-hypnosis et al", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a good one. I just gazed into the phantasmagoric nothingness, and got Aquamarine Squamous Tulip!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8406712", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nSo I'm over a year into the DMH, just awakened the two currents for the first time a couple of weeks ago. I don't know if the situation described here is related to that, or  just psychological issues.\nI notice how very often the default state my mind goes into is either daydreaming or worrying. Any menial errand I'm doing, or if I go for a walk, my mind automatically goes into its normal ruts. Based on observation, these ruts include: wondering whether if I had X or lived in Y whether life would be better, how to prepare for worrying-scenario Z, or less counterproductively, engaging in more harmless daydreams, or better, going over material in things I've read or meditated on. These latter two happen less frequently than the former two, and especially the last seems like a positive thing.\nWhat's interesting is how often my mind goes into these ruts, it's very difficult to choose to either think of something different than usual, or just be in the present moment and observe reality around me.\nI got so frustrated about this last week and in the past that I felt like I wanted to rush with the DMH, that I wanted to go ahead to the Grail working to get 'fixed' and so I've clamped down on that desire in order to proceed at a natural pace.\nIf the tendency of the mind to fall into these sorts of ruts is something that magical practice is in part meant to help overcome, how can one avoid this habit? Just by being aware of it?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8421304", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "I have something of the same tendency--for me, it's likely part of an anxiety disorder (and possibly inattentive-version ADD)--and what I've found helpful is performing a version of the Fourfold Breath. The need to count and pay attention to my breathing on its own tends to disrupt whatever \"hamster wheel\" my thoughts have been on, and then it's easier to either find another subject or be present.\nOf course, that requires me to notice what I'm doing and have the willpower to stop and do the breathing, which is another kettle of fish, but it's a help.\nFor wondering about different lives...two things come to mind. First, if these are changes you can make, you might want to sit down and make a list of realistic pros and cons--\"If I move to Wisconsin, I'll be in some very pretty country, but I'll miss my friends here,\" for example--and then let that sit for a month or two before reading it. If the pros still outweigh the cons, hey, maybe start trying to do that thing!\nIf the things you're thinking about aren't possible, try and keep in mind that we almost always can imagine the good parts of those situations. We often don't think about how they might not turn out well, or not turn out much better than what we have now--and we can't really see all of the things coming up for us that we might miss if we *did* have X or Y.  Again, I struggle with keeping that in mind at times, but when I can, it's useful.\n(It makes it easier if you can think of a parallel case where you were really disappointed at the time but two or three years down the road saw that it was for the best: I was devastated when one of my HS boyfriends dumped me right before college, for example, but after sophomore year, I realized all the cool things I'd gotten to see and do that probably wouldn't have happened if he and I were still dating, for a number of reasons. And then I read over his letters to me *from* when we were dating and realized that, while the guy in question was perfectly nice, there was nothing there I wanted any more. When I can keep that in mind, it makes similar \"but IF ONLY\" situations easier to weather.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8450744", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I will try the fourfold breath when I start to get stuck in my ruts. Part of it is how to think constructively when I do find myself thinking rather than just worrying, and part of it is how to balance thinking with general awareness. I often miss things when I'm out for a walk simply because I am lost in thought, and the landscape passes me by.\nAs for decision-making: Yes, I often fall into 'grass is greener on the other side' type of thinking - thinking more about things I don't have rather than things I do. And often worrying about things outside my control. It's been getting better through the years, and the balancing aspect of the SOP and reading Epictetus has helped. But putting it into practice is difficult, because the ruts get deeper as I continue the habit. So techniques like trying the fourfold breathing when I notice I'm in a rut is helpful!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8459192", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is where the rubber meets the road in meditative practice. Most people have some degree of this problem -- the mind keeps chattering, worrying, remembering, distracting. It's very common for beginners in meditation to find that they literally can't keep their mind from wandering for ten seconds at a time. So you're facing a familiar challenge.\nThe solution? Slow, steady, patient practice. There is no short cut, and doing the Grail Working won't fix it; just keep on doing your best in your daily meditations, and bit by bit you'll build the capacities on the mental plane that enable you to govern your mind.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8406968", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What were the original Golden Dawn terms for Abred, Gwynfydd and Ceugant?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8434872", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There aren't any. The Celtic Golden Dawn system uses Hermetic GD technical methods but all its symbolism and philosophy come from the Druid Revival traditions, which have their own odd and Druidical way of looking at things. If you're familiar with the Cabala you can probably find things that more or less match, but \"more or less\" is the operative phrase -- you won't find a straightforward one-to-one match.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8407224", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With Christian rituals, would you want to do a Summoning Ritual of the Cross, or stick to the Banishing Ritual of the Cross until you were ready for the Christian Middle Pillar? I'm thinking the last one could do with a rebrand...maybe Column of Light? Pillar of Light?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8435128", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Stick with the banishing. Then add in the Pillar of Fire exercise -- yes, that's what I'd call the Christian Middle Pillar exercise, with reference to the pillar of fire that led the Israelites in the Book of Exodus.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8407480", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had an idea about getting around the 'conservation of karma'. If someone decided to to the karma clear ritual, would it make a difference if they retreated into the wilderness and became a 'karma hermit'? Then when they were devoured by voles, or whatever horrific thing, the karma would be discharged without landing on another person. The game of karma pass-the-parcel would be broken. Could that work?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8435384", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I suppose, but given the wry sense of humor that seems to govern this world, the isolated wilderness where you decided to retreat to will be just the place that three crazed murderers who've escaped from the nearest penitentiary happen to choose for their hideout...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8454584", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Plus I'd imagine anyone who tried that would need to get \"There is no such thing as a perfectly isolated place\" hammered home.....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8459448", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "And it would be, of course, in some absurd and annoying way!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8461496", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a reason to think it's just this world that has the wry sense of humour?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8466104", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not making any assumptions either way!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8407736", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there such things as evil gods? For example what's the deal with gods who want human sacrifice?\nIs the sacrificee's afterlife or next incarnation different because of how they died?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8435896", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, but there are occasionally very powerful demons. They don't tend to last long but they can do a lot of damage before they implode.\n2) Only to the extent that they succeeded in working off some bad karma.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8445624", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "1. But what about gods of war? They seem to like violence. There's that Wotan guy who incited World War 2.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8449720", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on your definition of evil, then, doesn't it? Is violence always evil?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8454840", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Implode?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8459960", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure. A being that orients itself toward pure selfishness cuts itself off from the core of its own existence. Imagine for a moment that we're all inflatable creatures, and the \"air\" that keeps us inflated is spirit. Now imagine what happens when such a creature pulls itself loose from the air hose and expels the spirit in a rush...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8460728", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Sounds like a mess!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8462776", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "How about \"crappy demigod\" beings like the Asuras from Hindu and Buddhist lore? They're not depicted as being totally evil, just rather quarrelsome, petty and bound to stir up trouble.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8466360", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, those are also out there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8473528", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Do you know if these kind of beings are attested to in any Western pantheons? Would these type of demigods be what the Greeks referred to as Kakodaimons? Or more like the Etins of Norse lore?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8474808", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ettins are a good example; so are Titans (I suspect these names are related).", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8408248", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In the concept of Ahrimanic and Luciferian evil, where do 'enablers' fit in, if at all? For example the people who knew what Jimmy Savile or the grooming gangs were doing and did nothing, or helped cover it up. Or those who enforced the blacklist of women who turned down Harvey Weinstein?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8436152", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's an interesting question. It would depend presumably on what their motivation was.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8408504", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nNovice here - I've finished doing the stages of the SoP with the Greek pantheon but that's all.\nI'm a lifelong insomniac, and I was wondering whether there are elementary, entry-level, things I can do to improve my sleep and/or make some kind of positive change to the energy in the bedroom. These days I have little difficulty actually falling asleep, but I frequently wake during the night and can't fall asleep properly again.\nFor practical reasons, I normally do the SoP ritual in the room where we sleep - I'm not sure if this is good or bad. Any wisdom will be gladly received and acted upon.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8436408", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you tried, while banishing the elements, banishing sleeplessness?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8448952", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I’m not the poster but I can’t sleep either.  I’ll try it, thanks!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8409016", "title": "Barbarous words", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are your thoughts on 'Barbarous words' used in some magical texts?  Are they words that have no connection to any language spoken in the past, or are they words that have simply been butchered in transcription over time?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8436664", "title": "Re: Barbarous words", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It really varies from case to case. In ancient times, there were intricate sets of sound symbolism that were used to construct magical words of power -- you can find traces of the results in the Graeco-Egyptian magical papyri and in some of the Gnostic gospels. You also have words that are revealed by spirits, in which case anything can be involved. Finally, words do get garbled in transcription, but that doesn't make them useless -- there's an almost Darwinian process by which words mutate into more and more effective magical vocal sounds. Plenty of medieval names of power are complete gibberish, but if you use them as given you can get excellent results.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8409528", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can the structures you build in your imagination survive after your death? For example could you build a tower or villa in a nice part of the astral plane now, then spend your afterlife there?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8436920", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Well, you can't do that because you shed your astral body in chunks after the first part of the after-death process is over. The structures you build very often do survive, but they're not in your imagination -- your imagination is your window onto the astral plane, and so other beings can go to those places too.\nThis is something that's useful in practical magic. A group of people can build a location on the inner planes through their collective imaginal/astral work, and meet there astrally for joint ritual work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8478392", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Like the Tower in Magical Battle of Britain?", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8410040", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nAre the following diagrams (taken from The Secret Doctrine of the Rosicrucians) related to Sacred Geometry?\nhttps://www.sacred-texts.com/sro/sdr/img/fig10.jpg\nhttps://www.sacred-texts.com/sro/sdr/img/fig11.jpg", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8437176", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "See if you can construct them exactly using only pen, straightedge, and compass -- that's the litmus test. (The answer in these cases is \"no.\") Not all symbolism that looks geometrical uses the methods of sacred geometry.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8410552", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few weeks ago someone asked when they could start creating talismans and gamahes from The Art and Practice of Geomancy. I was surprised when you said after meditating on the figures as I assumed one wasn't supposed to start with that until after all the meditation and scrying. When can a person start or when best to start trying to contact the guardian genius?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8437432", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It varies from person to person. Why not cast a geomantic chart to find out?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8410808", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What's the fastest you've seen or heard of karmic culmination happening?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8437688", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Later the same day.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8459704", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I started meditating about a week ago and 3 days in my sink clogged. It caused considerable frustration and I still wonder if it was karmic culmination or if I have that to look forward to.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8460472", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If it caused more frustration than an ordinary domestic hassle would have caused, it might be karmic culmination.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8463544", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, I am a germaphobe, and running low on sanitizer so...\nThing is I thought the karmic culmination was supposed to resolve a issue which stands in the way of one's practice but it didn't do that. At least I don't think it did.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8466616", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It may be pushing you to get better at handling frustration, or something like that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8468408", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That's what I was thinking but I didn't handle it especially well. I suppose I could've handled it much worse however.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8471992", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You don't have to handle it well to learn from it!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8411064", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there any occult aspect to having extremely thick body hair? I'm about as hairy as it's possible to be, I may have seen one or two Armenian weightlifters who were hairier, but that's it. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8437944", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not that I know of.  It may just be an indication of Bigfoot somewhere back there in your family tree.  ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8449976", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That one made me laugh because Sonkitten is not only hairy, he has big feet!\nNo Armenians on either side so far as I know, and no other big hairy guys.  It’s a mystery!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8411320", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nOnce you mentioned that using Arthurian legends for magical work is risky for an order, since these legends ended up in failure. Is there a similar risk in using Atlantean legends - like ending up with a lodge flooded with rain water :) ?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8438200", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. Work with the Atlantean contacts can be done -- Dion Fortune's magical order did a lot of it -- but it's very risky.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8411576", "title": "Astrological ages", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is an astrological age?  We have talked a lot about the change from the age of picses to the age of Aquarius.  It is a very interesting topic but I don’t really understand what these ages are and also why are the dates involved not know exactly?  Everything else in astrology seems pretty exact.\nThanks much", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8438712", "title": "Re: Astrological ages", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, let's start with the precession of the equinoxes. The points in the heavens where the sun is located at the moment of spring and fall equinoxes creep slowly backwards against the backdrop of the stars, at a rate of 1° every 72 years or so. That means that the stars that used to be behind the sun at the moment of spring equinox in 2000 BCE, let's say, are a long way from that position now.\nThe moment of the spring equinox is 0° Aries in terms of standard Western astrological practice, but the stars of Aries are nowhere near that place. That doesn't mean that the sign is wrong -- the signs of the zodiac are not the constellations that gave them their names back in Greek times, they're 30° wedges of the ecliptic counted from the positions of the equinoxes -- but the fact that the stars are shifting reveals long slow changes in the pattern of celestial energies on earth.\nThat's what makes astrological ages. When the position of the spring equinox slips into a portion of space associated with a different sign, everything changes. The great problem is that nobody knows where the boundaries are. The constellations are very rough markers at best, and there are no dotted lines in the sky showing where one ends and another begins. so various secondary methods have to be used. Eventually it'll all be worked out and we'll be able to tell exactly how long it is until the next age of the world begins, but that's still a long way off!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8412088", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello Archdruid,\nWhenever I read a book by William Walker Atkinson, it gives me a feeling of additional strength and motivation. Do you sense the same things when you read his books? If so, is it due to the suggestions/affirmations in those books, or a subtler form of magical working?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8438968", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes. It's partly the affirmations and suggestions in his books, and it's partly the fact that millions of people have read his books and gotten strength and motivation from them. That builds up an egregor -- an enduring pattern of subtle energies -- that each reader can tap into, and then add to.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8412344", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dreamwidth is giving me a carload of trouble. Among other things, it keeps posting catchas with obvious questions one can apparently not answer correctly. I have posted here before without any trouble.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8439480", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "How annoying! If you get a free account you won't have to use the captchas, for what it's worth.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8412600", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I find it sad that pop-culture have advertised the figures like Aleister Crowley for a long time, while the works of Dion Fortune haven't got the attention they deserve. Or maybe, she didn't intend to get too much attention from profane masses in the first place... I don't know.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8439736", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Pop culture figures are by and large a lot more similar to Crowley than they are to Fortune, so it makes sense...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8413112", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had a very strange experience last Tuesday night. After a successful day, I lay down to sleep in a serene mood and felt an awareness of my body that wasn't quite physical. My left side felt solid, real, and grounded; my right side felt weaker, more fuzzy, darker. Fabrics felt delightful under my hands. It felt like a glorious awareness. What was happening?\nMonday I had asked myself \"The moon is the planet of psychism. Do I want to be psychic, and why?\" The answer came, \"for the same reason I'd like my hearing back, please.\" Tuesday feels like cause and effect. Is it?\nI had to leave the glorious awareness because it included a toothache I couldn't track down. Wednesday night the awareness was back, muted, but included a painful case of right-jaw TMJ which I'm still processing.\nFrom yesterday's insight - The TMJ seems to tie in nervous habits of very long standing, which seem to revolve around \"hurry-hurry-hurry\" and \"you're wasting time reading...\" but have intensified during the period of social distancing. And for months I've had dreams, often not remembered clearly, of having tasks set for me that I can not do as specified or in the way I was told to. For some reason riversides feature prominently in these dreams and the persons is often male.\nDo you have any insight into what's happening here? I'm trying to address these in meditation but am not sure of the direction to go.\nThanks,\nPat", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8440248", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's really quite remarkable. No, I don't have any clear idea of what you experienced; it's not something that's happened to me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8454328", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "The bodily imbalance vision reminded me of what a bodyworker in Socorro, NM told me decades ago, that I didn't understand at the time: that in me, my feminine side and masculine side were swapped around from what was usual.\nI also remembered which side of the brain controls which side of the body, and that doing puzzles has always calmed me and short-circuited the \"hurry-up\" inner voice (head nanny? Badger?)and that I needed more analytical work. My new Wednesday practice will be something you suggested long ago: to look for at least one news item and go through it for the common fallacies.\nThe jaw problem as part of the awareness state - that was diagnostic, I'm sure, and a sign I was ready to deal with it and badly needed to. It's like what you said about hidden tensions in the body - I've been doing the \"sit perfectly still and don't move a muscle\" meditation for some time. With my back supported, because of a near-crippling back problem I'm in PT for, but baby steps are better than none.\nThat's what I've got so far. For what it's worth.\nPat", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8446904", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may:\nThis reminds me of results I've gotten from a couple years of close attention to the three-way relationship between emotions, physical sensations, and the structures of the physical and etheric bodies. Two key principles I've learned in that work are that suppressed emotions often manifest as physical tension, and that chronic physical tension feels like numbness or blankness. The corollary is that when you release the tension/suppression/energy blockage, you get a new level of access to sensation, whether positive or negative.\nSo my guess is that something on the right side of your body has gotten partially unblocked, connected to the emotions behind your nervous habits, and this partial unblocking is giving you access to new sensations that were previously suppressed.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8413368", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If someone dropped dead while taking a hoodoo bath and collapsed in the water, would that affect the death process?\nIt's not something I have to worry about as I stand in a washing up bowl. Nearly all of it goes in the watering can. If I tried giving watered-down product to the tree I suspect it would be...displeased. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8440504", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I have no idea. Please don't experiment! ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8413624", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When occult books have multiple layers of meaning, how much of that is writing technique and how much is magic?\nOccult books and images are meant to be unpacked through meditation, but have you ever had a lot of undersanding arrive quickly, at first look?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8440760", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It depends on the author, but both are usually involved.\n2) If you're ready for the insights that a book can pass on, that will happen. Go on and meditate on it afterward -- you'll get even more.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8413880", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "When natural magic was being developed they didn't have access to all the chemical elements, so you don't expect to find an alchemist's treatise on helium. :) But they did have charcoal burning, so had a fairly pure form of carbon. Are there records of its magic properties?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8441016", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of anything like that. Remember that they didn't have the idea that charcoal was a pure form of anything in particular -- to them it was just wood that had been burnt without letting enough air get to it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8414136", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "eremon", "content": "JMG,\nHoping this finds you and yours in good health.\n1) At some time in the past I remember seeing a reference to Abramelin that mentioned a name for a magician’s workroom. For the life of me I can't recall if it was laboratory, operatory, oratorium, scriptorium?\n2) Was reading through the Encyclopedia of Natural Magic today and noticed that there is a listing for salt, but not sulphur or mercury. I understand that there could be liabilities for you if you encouraged people to handle elemental mercury,  but the exclusion of mineral brimstone/sulphur seemed odd. Am I missing something else in these exclusions?\n3) Is there a fundamental difference between the natural virtues of salt, sulfur, mercury and the alchemical properties of same, or between the natural virtues and the changes of negredo, rubeo, and albus?\n4) Lastly, I  have the CGD on order. Letting the US postal service’s delivery schedule aside, what can I do to begin preparatory exercise now?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8441784", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I don't recall, but\nyou could look it up\n.\n2) Sulphur wasn't used much in European natural magic.\n3) What a fine topic for a week or two of meditation!\n4) Wait until you get it. The book's designed to imitate a set of knowledge lectures or lessons in an old-fashioned magical lodge; it starts from the beginning and takes you a lesson at a time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8442296", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "eremon", "content": "1) hmm. Haven't been to that website in a long time. 15 minutes on Google didn't pan out at first try.\n2) Duly noted.\n3) This is my surprised face.\n4) Will do.  It's waiting on the doorstep as we type.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8442808", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's among the reasons I don't use Google. On Duckduckgo it was the second item, right after the Wikipuffery entry.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8446648", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "eremon", "content": "1) and found the answer.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8414392", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there magic systems from the past that are almost completely gone from history, but there's a tantalising bit of detail left? Just a mention of the name of a system, or a hint of how it worked?\nWouldn't it be strange if a thousand years from now, the only documents they had from the magic of today was a complete printout of every Magic Monday?\nTo the future: hello. Sorry about all the microplastic.\nTo the far, far future: the microplastic you built your entire economy on won't last forever. Transition away from it now while you still can, before you reach peak plastic.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8442040", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Good heavens, yes. To name only one example, we know very little about classical Greek theurgy, and even less about what went on in mystery rites such as the Eleusinian Mysteries.\n2) Weirder things have happened!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8414648", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nWith respect to the inner and outer elements of the sixteen geomantic figures, there are instances of fire-fire (Cauda Draconis), water-water (Populus, Via), earth-earth (Carcer, Caput Draconis), but no air-air.  Why would that be?\nDavid BTL", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8421048", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "To expand on the question slightly--\nWith four elements, each potentially outer and inner, one has a 4x4 (16 cell) matrix.  As there are 16 figures, one might expect a natural symmetry to result in a 1-to-1 mapping from the the set of figures onto the cells this matrix (an invertible function, as it were).  Alas, this is not so.\nSpecifically, we find four \"double assignments,\" which result in four cells of the matrix going unfilled.  Using the convention (outer,inner), one has:\nBoth Carcer and Caput Draconis at (earth,earth)\nBoth Populus and Via at (water, water)\nBoth Puer and Acquisito at (fire,air)\nBoth Albus and Puella at (air,water)\nThe unfilled cells are:\n(water,earth)\n(earth,water)\n(air,air) as I mentioned originally, and\n(fire,water)\nThe first two of the \"missing\" pairings at least possess a symmetry and the third (laying on the diagonal of the matrix) is by definition symmetrical with itself.  However, the last \"missing\" pair is most definitely asymmetrical as Laetitia is assigned to its counterpart of (water,fire).\nSwitching from math-speak to layman's language, what gives?\n--David BTL", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8442552", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Here again, you're in territory that as far as I know nobody has yet explored. The inner elements I used came from one source, the outer elements from a different source. Their relationship in terms of the deeper structure of geomancy is to my knowledge unexplored ground.\nThe work you're doing is great, btw. Please keep at it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8415160", "title": "invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Greetings JMG et al.\nIn reading your mundane horoscopes and Magic Mondays my understansing of astrology has increased a great deal, from roughly miniscule to very little.\nI have wondered recently whether it is possible to understand a certain lifelong pattern in light of a natal chart, and not having studied astrology at all beyond reading variously on the Web I hope my question is worth the asking. Forgive this clumsy attempt to interpret a concept in a language I may never learn well. However, it would be very helpful to me to see even where you think my thinking may be wrong.\nThe background is that I am someone who has always been overlooked - left behind on school excursions; consistently not invited to parties and outings in social groups or work situations although not for having enemies; my suggestions neglected however valid (not an uncommon problem for females in any case); not taken seriously when by ordinary expectations I should have been a decent leader. By this I mean such things as being loyal to a group, being prepared to contribute effort to its operation and taking responsibility to the extent I understand what this means. It is as though I don't make any impression or remain in others' memories when not directly in their field of view. Like a wraith, not a fully real being.\nIt is true that my social skills are not so strong - I am not at ease with people generally - but neither are they in the abysmal category. There is a monotonous quality to the repetition of these patterns. Questions to medicos about Asperger's syndrome, which seems to share the affective qualities of my situation, keep getting dismissed as though, to them, I am obviously not that. It is not as though I need to learn one key thing: not getting any closer to feeling like an authentic person however much else I do learn has taught me that that hypothetical key thing probably is not attainable.\nThe psychological explanation, I have come to conclude, is disordered attachment. It is not necessary to go into detail about that here. What I am curious about is what in a natal chart would correspond to or elucidate these observable features of a life.\nMy speculations currently are that these aspects are most relevant: first, although my Sun is in Sagittarius, there are precious few other fire signs. No Leo at all. I am making a vague equation of fire-as-expression-of-will with personality of a kind that stands out. Maybe as a binary conception of personality: something you have or lack?\nSecondly: Only other fire sign is Saturn, retrograde, in the 9th house, in Aries. That placement is said to point to karmic debt and past life issues with (and abuse of?) authority; and the description of Saturn in Aries people being effective leaders - to which role it seems I feel such unfulfillable affinity - provides a nice irony via the twist of the retrograde movement.\nYour pardon if I have misunderstood and ignored your refrain to others that it isn't so simple... just wondering if I may have something useful to go with.\nAs always, thank you for your time, effort and generosity in providing this forum and maintaining this valuable community.\nkallianeira.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8443064", "title": "Re: invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, first of all, what's your rising sign, and are there any planets in your first house? That's where you look first for identity issues. Also, the planet ruling the sign on the cusp of the first house will tell you quite a bit through its condition and aspects.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8458168", "title": "Re: invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Cancer is rising, at 26 some degrees. Does this mean the sign on the cusp of the first house is Gemini? Giving Mercury as the one to watch.\nThis is in house 4, in Scorpio, hence dignified, and combust.\nIt is in conjunction with Neptune, sextile Pluto and trine the Ascendant.\nThere is nothing whatsoever in my first house....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8460984", "title": "Re: invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, if Cancer is rising then Cancer is the sign on the cusp of your first house. Where's your natal Moon?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8475832", "title": "Re: invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "In Aquarius.\nShould I continue this next week? - it's already Tuesday evening here.\nthanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8477112", "title": "Re: invisible self - ? astrological markers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, let's pick this up again next week.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8415416", "title": "Herb question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are there any herbs you recommend to take to make a person less sensitive to subtle forces or spirits, if they are overly sensitive to them?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8443320", "title": "Re: Herb question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not familiar with herbs for that purpose; the standard advice I know of is to eat a diet rich in red meat, which helps get you back in touch with physical reality.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8447928", "title": "Re: Herb question", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do white meat and fish help with that too even if they are not as grounding as red meat?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8450232", "title": "Re: Herb question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They're more or less neutral. A vegan or vegetarian diet increases your sensitivity, a diet with white meat and fish maintains it at its current level, a diet with plenty of red meat decreases your sensitivity. If you're doing practices that make you more sensitive, red meat in the diet can be very useful to keep you from becoming overwhelmed by psychic impressions.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8415928", "title": "Dion Fortune Society, Nameless God etc.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG\nSeveral questions for this week - thank you in advance!\n1. I saw someone post on the other blog about pastlife memories (or was it this blog?) anyway: it occurred to me: if you can clearly remember previous lives and what you did and how they ended - does that mean you can remember the languages you spoke then too? Presumably it’s possible to remember fragments quite easily but do people just remember the old language fluently and keep their fluency?\n2. I am just starting out in my occult studies. I’ve mostly just read your stuff and a little bit of other stuff (some of Dion Fortune’s books). I’ve started to do discursive meditation fairly regularly (although having trouble with symbolic topics - much better with “mundane” ones - at least I can sit comfortably in the right pose now) and will soon be starting the SOP, and (later), some divination.\nI know I could do all this alone, but it would be nice to be part of a community and learn from someone.\nI am in England, plus I really liked Dion Fortune’s books, so I was wondering what you thought about me joining her organization.\nThey have two correspondence courses - one “supervised” (only available to UK residents) and one “unsupervised” (available to anyone anywhere but does not include some of the mind training exercises which need to be supervised).\nSuccessfully passing the Supervised course entitles you to apply to join the actual Society and study further and participate in rituals etc. I believe this is a process that takes years - first to do the correspondence course and then join etc.\nI know you think highly of Dion Fortune so I am assuming her Society still do good work. I guess what I am really asking is if there are any red flags for me to consider, and what it will add for me to join the Society (starting with the correspondence course) vs going it alone.\nAlso, as a newbie, am I better off doing a year or so of discursive meditation and SOP and then joining, or better off just joining now (maybe read a few more Fortune books first) and letting the Society take care of all that training? I have a general interest in the occult and particularly training my mind and experiencing the unseen world. I think I’d like to go more towards the practical rituals side and less in terms of the “knowledge” side - but honestly I’m so new, I’m not sure those preferences have really been tested.\n(I am also into aikido quite seriously if that makes any difference - although no exposure to its esoteric side)\n3. I have been praying for many years (last thing before bed, every single night) on a daily basis to an “unknown god”. As in, I have a Hindu background and originally started off praying to various Hindu gods, then kind of naturally evolved without planning to the “ultimate godhead” or “cosmic unity” kind of force, and then that kind of slowly changed again over the years to an individual god with no name - more like a force.\nAfter reading some of your stuff I started concentrating more on trying to “listen” to what he is saying - this only in the last few months.\nThere are no words, but I get the “sense” that he is male. Every time I pray to him it’s slightly different - some times it feels like he’s very nearby. Sometimes like he’s busy, sometimes like he’s far away and I can barely “reach” him. I got an idea out of nowhere one day he wanted me to stand or sit with my heels together while praying to him. Sometimes I’ll get a sense of “amusement” or “busyness”. No real specifics or answers to questions.\nI guess what I am asking is how do I know what is “real” and what is my brain making stuff up - what is just random thoughts coming into my brain that I interpret as his messages? These things just feel like random thoughts popping into my brain.\nI know it is a question of practice and I will get better at it (after all I didn’t notice *anything* until a few months ago) but are there any rules of thumb to distinguish? Or characteristics of “real” communication? This is very far from “a voice in my head speaking clearly”.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8443576", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune Society, Nameless God etc.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) No, the language stays in the brain, but the deeper patterns stay with the soul -- you'll have an easier time learning that language in a future incarnation.\n2) I don't happen to know much about how the SIL is doing these days, but it has a fine course of study, and taking the supervised study course strikes me as a very good opportunity to get some solid training. In your place I'd start the course now. As far as red flags, mostly just keep your eyes out for personality cults or for any request that you do something you would consider unethical or inappropriate.\n3) This is a standard sort of experience. Keep going, and the communication will become clearer and you'll be able to get your questions answered. (If you've read my novel\nThe Weird of Hali: Kingsport\n, the interactions between the main character and the Great Old One Tsathoggua have some of the same characteristics.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8475320", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune Society, Nameless God etc.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you JMG\nI have indeed read Weird of Hali and remember the scene where Jenny lights incense etc - maybe I will re read it for inspiration\nAlso I assume no problem in joining SIL as a non Christian", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8477368", "title": "Re: Dion Fortune Society, Nameless God etc.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You'll have to ask the SIL about that -- I'm not sure what their current policy is. Under Fortune's leadership they were cool about non-Christians.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8416184", "title": "Cell salts", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I wanted to mention that I've joined the cell salts experiment as well, as of last Thursday. I'd never taken homeopathy seriously, but the idea of doing the protocol kept coming back, and I've learned the hard way to pay attention when that happens.\nRecently I'd been having increasing problems with acid reflux and other stomach issues (my family has a history of digestive problems), and I was beginning to think I'd need to see a doctor. Well, as of the very first evening, I realized I'd had no problems that day, and my stomach continues to be much improved, even though I haven't changed my diet. I'm sun sign Capricorn, so it'll be a few weeks before I get to the missing salts, but any other health benefit will be an omake compared to this single result. I would never have found cell salts on my own, so thanks for this!\n--Sister Crow", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8444088", "title": "Re: Cell salts", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it. You might find it useful to get a book or two on cell salts and see if you want to learn how to prescribe them for your own home health care -- my wife and I have been using them in that role for upwards of 30 years with generally very good results.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8416440", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've started blogging, and I'm taking all the mundane steps to try to reach an audience (posting it where appropriate, writing interesting material, etc). I'm also interested in extra magical steps I could take. I'm posting it during the hour of Mercury on Wednesdays, but are there other steps I can take? (I work with the AODA rituals, have started working through the 1st grade of the Dolmen Arch and looked at the Druid Magic Handbook but haven't worked with it yet)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8444344", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends to some extent on what you blog about and what motivates you to blog. In my experience, if you listen to the universe and get a sense of what it wants you to communicate, and then do that, people will show up. You can open a grove with the usual ritual, enter into meditation, and ask the gods and powers about that...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8456376", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you! I've tried doing that, but will freely confess my skills at listening to the universe needs some work. It's something I'm working on anyway, but I'll keep an ear out for what I need to communicate.\nI'm blogging about the situation we're in with regards to the dead end our society has backed into (similar to the old Archdruid Report). My motivation is three fold:\n1) I'm practising writing essays on a regular basis, by having a blog to maintain.\n2) I'm hoping to get some ideas into broader circulation, with the idea of alleviating the worse elements of our future by getting some of the necessary ideas out there.\n3) I'm planning a career as a writer, and I'm hoping I can use my blog as a way to jump start it (both by getting practice and by making a name for myself).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8461752", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In that case, I have a little practical advice: don't say what everyone else is saying. Most people who want to write parrot the clichés of collective consciousness, and so nobody reads them -- why bother? I long since lost track of the number of would-be bloggers and authors I've seen go nowhere because they were basically trotting along with the herd, mooing in unison with everyone else.\nYou will attract an audience if you say things that nobody else is saying, in a way that nobody else is saying it. It may take time -- it took six months before my first blog had any noticeable amount of commentators -- but that's the secret.\nIt's also not easy. You will face pushback from other people who try to insist that you should say the same thing as everyone else. You may well face pushback from yourself. Ignore it and go your own way, and you'll succeed.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8464824", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, my first post looked at the present with an idea of outlining where we are; my next one argued the collective reaction to Covid-19, and the peculiar mix of people having mental breakdowns and others refusing to take any precautions at all make sense as the result of a collective refusal to admit death is real; the next introduced the concept of the consumer economy as an economy based upon creating addictions with the idea of being a theme for the next few months or years; then it was off to discussing TV's role in sustaining those arrangements.\nI also have this week's post written, where I'll discuss the issue of the collapse of community institutions as a result of the rise of TV (the timing is remarkably suspicious, plus all the hours glued to it must have come from somewhere) and how a number of the ones that survive are unrecognizable compared to their 1950s form using one I'm part of as an example.\nSo I think it's safe to say I'm going in a different direction from the herd. As for your blog taking six months to get a following, I'm planning for a year or two to get any real attention, so if I can get a few commentators in six months I'll be quite happy!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8466872", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good. That should find readers.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8416952", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "rafiwinters", "content": "\"Lilac Oracular Chicken\"! ha ha ha ha ha ha ha!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8445368", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good one. I just got Scarlet Hibernating Platypus!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8476856", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "rafiwinters", "content": "For some reason, any phrase involving \"chicken\" is funny to me. As in \"cobra chicken\" in place of Canada geese. Or \"threshing the rubber chicken\" instead of the wren. Etc. etc.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8417208", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If the subconscious believes everything it sees, then what kind of effects would watching TV where people die, and then seeing the actors again have? Would that convince people's subconscious death doesn't happen or isn't permanent?\nA lot of our culture's oddities make sense if we assume a lot of people don't believe death is real (and then freak when exposed to it)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8445880", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ding! We have a winner. Exactly -- and that's another good reason to get up right now and throw your television out a third floor window into a dumpster.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8455608", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I can't, as I don't own one! ;)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8462008", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the one really good excuse I know.  ;-)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8474296", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "lincoln_lynx", "content": "I've seen the opposite as well. People dismissing ideas, phenomena,etc. because TV has given them a unreal quality.\n\"That only happens on TV / or in the movies!\"\nThe Trump-Russia story was doomed from the get-go. Too \"unbelievable\".", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8417464", "title": "C* virus mundane astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nThis is a question about astrology more than it is about the banned topic, if that ban is still in place, so I hope it is permitted.\nI was trying to find an astrological 'signature' for the virus, and not seeing anything that I thought really fitted, when I switched to looking at transits for a natal chart and had an 'ah-ha' moment.  Transiting Neptune, the planet of viruses challenging your bodily boundaries, is now opposite where the Pluto-Uranus conjunction was in the mid sixties, specifically late 1964 to 1968 (depending on orbs used).  That conjunction was in Virgo, the sign of health, medicine, and the world of the workplace (amongst other things of course).  Many people who were teenagers or young adults at the time, and part of that sixties atmosphere, had natal Uranus in Gemini (the sign of social interaction). Neptune is now square that natal Uranus. They are being hit hard and challenged to re-evaluate dearly-held values and attitudes regarding freedom and authority (Uranus). Those born at the time are similarly being challenged.\nAs you can see, I use outer planet transits for my dabblings in mundane astrology.  What are the astrological indicators of the virus in the methods that you use?\nThank you\nChristineS", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8447160", "title": "Re: C* virus mundane astrology", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "Not JMG, but:\nI looked back at the chart for the Saturn/Pluto conjunction and noticed that the dwarf planet Ceres was actually conjoining them at the same time, separate from the Saturn/Pluto by only hours.  So it was really a Saturn/Pluto/Ceres conjunction.\nI include Ceres as a minor benefic influence associated with things like health, nutrition, and food.  Being a dwarf planet, she doesn't rule anything, but I take her as exalted in Virgo and thus in triplicity in Capricorn.  So seeing that makes it look (admittedly in retrospect) like a Saturn/Pluto event associated with a public health or food-supply crisis.\nLooking at Ceres more closely, I notice she ingressed into Capricorn (disposited by Saturn already in Capricorn), and I am wondering if the virus starting to fade\nnow\n(assuming that's really happening; I hope it is and the data seems to bear that out) is because she egressed out from under Saturn's Cap/Aqr thumb and into Pisces this past Thursday.  If this is the case, there might be a second wave, milder than the first, running from late September into early November when Ceres retrogrades back into Aquarius and back under Saturn's thumb.\nAnd there's a degree of \"Pluto's parting gifts\" going on here.  It's nearing the Saturn/Saturn \"teenage rebellion\" opposition of his demotion (that goes exact Feb. 2022).\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-27 11:47 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8448440", "title": "Re: C* virus mundane astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting! That seems quite reasonable, and it involves methods I haven't studied much yet, so thank you.\nIn the Aries 2020 ingress chart for the US, the basis for the traditional mundane methods I use, the virus is indicated by Uranus, the planet of disruptive influences, in his fall in Taurus conjunct the cusp of the 6th house of health. He is afflicted by a square from Saturn, who is in the last few minutes of arc of his rulership in Capricorn and about to pass into Uranus' sign Aquarius, and who is also at the end of the 2nd house about to pass into the 3rd. That shows that the pandemic can in fact be restricted (Saturn) by controls on travel and neighborhood activities (3rd house). (I missed this detail in my original delineation -- live and learn!)\nThe economy is going to take a serious hit -- the 2nd house of economics has Sagittarius on the cusp and Jupiter, its ruler, is in his fall in Capricorn and afflicted by a very close conjunction with Mars and a more distant but still applying conjunction with Saturn -- ouch. Fortunately the pandemic will not last all that long. The 6th house of health has Taurus on its cusp and Venus, its ruler, is in Taurus and in the 6th. The implication I see here is that once the pandemic passes off the effects of social distancing on other diseases will result in much better public health for the rest of the year.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8417720", "title": "Age of Aquarius/Post-Ragnarok Heathenry?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week, in response to a comment, you gave 1888 as the begining of the Aquarian age.  I've seen you mention the late 19th century in this context before but what makes you give that specific date?  Why not 1878 or 1898 for instance?  Is it an astrological calculation of some sort or based on historical events or both?\nAlso in that series of comments you described Odin as a Piscean deity, giving that as the reason why Norse Heathenry put up more resistance to christianity than other Pagan traditions from the Arian age.  This makes a lot of sense to me.\nYou went on to list Viðarr, the son and avenger of Odin, as a classic Aquarian deity.  This also makes a lot of sense to me.\nThese points all hit home pretty strongly for me.  Heathenry is my spiritual path and I was practicing your Heathen LBRP and Middle Pillar for quite a few months before 'falling off the wagon' so to speak.  I am now beginning to take up the practice again.\nI remember though, before falling off, that the gods that called to me the most were represented in my mind as a strange sort of fusion: Odin, Thor, and elements of Heimdall.  Occasionally they felt more distinct like in the myths but most of the time, particularly when I felt it strongest, it was the fusion. I thought this was just a combination of the nature of polytheism along with me being a beginner; the other gods in these rituals felt more consistently distinct to me though(Balder, Freya, Idun, etc.)\nThe notion that the Piscean age has given way to the Aquarian, with Odin as a Piscean deity and Viðarr as the Aquarian, has me wondering if Ragnarok has already happened and the younger gods that survived are filling the roles of the older ones.  For example: Viðarr is Odin's son, is said to be the strongest god after Thor, and elsewhere is called the “silent god”.  That fusion I was experiencing fits the descriptions of Viðarr very well.  I'm wondering if I've been using the wrong names...\nAll of this has made me realize that Viðarr will likely be my Patron deity going forward and your LBRP for polytheists is probably a better fit for me.\nTo try and streamline the questions from this long comment of mine.  I'm wondering:\n1.) Why the exact date of 1888 for the begining of the Aquarian age?\n2.) Does my idea of the post-ragnarok Heathen pantheon make sense to you?\n3.) Have you heard of anyone in the Heathen scene following this post-agnarok/Aquarian perspective, and changing their practices accordingly?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8450488", "title": "Re: Age of Aquarius/Post-Ragnarok Heathenry?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That was announced, on the basis of some intricate calculations as well as the usual visionary experiences, by an assortment of occultists in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. I accepted it as a convenient date because a lot of Uranian/Aquarian influences seem to have shifted into high gear around then.\n2) Yes, it does.\n3) No, but I don't follow the Heathen scene at all closely.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8417976", "title": "Oil question and more", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If a hoodoo book says to dress oneself with an oil does this mean rub over the whole body? When it says anoint I would take it mean a specific part of the body or parts. Which part or parts? I typically assume the forehead, but I've seen other places mentioned as well I think.\nAre there any books you like for spiritual bath recipes or some of the standard hoodoo oils?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8451000", "title": "Re: Oil question and more", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Depends on what you're doing it for. If you're doing a sexual working, well, you can probably do the math as well as I can. On the same basis, if it's for something that relates to some other part of your body, use that. Otherwise, apply it as you would perfume -- a dab on each wrist, a dab under each ear -- and then another dab at the base of the nose, where the third eye is located.\n2) My main book for that is the textbook for Cat Yronwode's hoodoo course, which is only available to students. Her\nHoodoo Herb and Root Magic\nis also quite helpful.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8418232", "title": "DDH Active Earth working", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI have been contemplating my first \"active\" DMH working using a stone, and I was hoping I could get your input?\nSituation: Started a new job recently that involves a quite technical knowledge subject. I've shown my facility with it enough to move up a pay grade, but now need to go much further.\nI am on home working lockdown however. And I am finding it much harder to learn and focus in my bedroom than I would in the office with my colleagues right there to help.\nGoal: I want to be more focused, and my knowledge and confidence in the role to grow. Having contemplated it, I don't know if this falls foul of the \"ends not means\" principal i.e. I should instead be asking for \"success at the role\". But because I don't yet know what success quite looks/feels like, I preferred the specificity of focus, confidence and knowledge growth. Does this seem a reasonable approach?\nSecondly, I cast an Ogham reading on the above goal, and got:\n1st: Quert (reversed)\n2nd: Ngetal (reversed)\n3rd: Duir (reversed)\n3 reversals obviously made me rethink things :-/. From daily castings I associate Quert with my recent job success, so reversal could just indicate the recent issues I am having there, and Duir could be the \"borrowed\" energy from a working maybe only temporarily helping, with Ngetal counselling that I am not quite ready. I am unsure what I'm not ready for however: the nature of what I should ask for, or not ready to do even simple workings like this...?\nAny thoughts you could provide as ever much appreciated,\nMorfran (aka Cobalt Tangential Piglet)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8451256", "title": "Re: DDH Active Earth working", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The reading is a clear no. For now, that's not a useful thing for you to attempt, and you might want to do further readings to clarify where the blockage is.\n-- Indigo Orthogonal Stoat", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8418744", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I was actually wondering about this recently. How would you recommend doing a one card yes-no ogham reading? Meaning, how would you phrase the question and what would indicate yes or no?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8451512", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'd ask it in a straightforward yes-no manner -- \"Is this a good idea?\" or what have you -- and take an upright card as a yes and a reversed card as a no, with the meaning of the few telling me why it's yes or no.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8419512", "title": "meditation versus scrying", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In practicing discursive meditation and scrying, I find that one tends to morph into the other. Is it best to keep these practices separate, to maintain the differences between them? I’ve found scrying much easier and more enjoyable, but then, flights of fancy aren’t always productive either.\nThank you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8451768", "title": "Re: meditation versus scrying", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I find it best to keep them separate, but your mileage may vary.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8420536", "title": "Personal Integrity and Divination", "user": "laflamme", "content": "Dear ArchDruid,\nI first came across this idea in the work of medical intuitive Carolyn Myss, and the more I observe and think on it, the more right it seems to me.\nMainly, she says if you want the spirits to talk to you, you must strive for utmost integrity in your conduct: telling truth, honesty in business dealings, acting according to your conscience: all of that.\nIn that particular book she was getting information regarding intuitive healing, but it seems to me this same idea, if true, would relate to divination in general.\nYet I cannot recall reading anything similar in the books on Tarot I have read, which is my method of divination.\nI know from reading your work you place a high value on ethics, but what about in the specific case relating to the efficacy of divination, as described above.\nI would be very interested in your take.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8452024", "title": "Re: Personal Integrity and Divination", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't think it's safe to generalize from her experience to divination in general. Some diviners are scrupulously honest, others are trickster figures, and I've never noticed any lack of accuracy on the part of the latter!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8424376", "title": "occasional divination", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I don't do regular divination because I know it would provoke anxiety.\nHowever, occasionally things come up where I don't mind either way, and I would like to know what it said. (In this case, it's seeing if it's worth trying to patch things up with an acquaintance who has been shunning me for some time. It would make things a bit easier in my social circle if they weren't, but I don't really miss them as an individual.)\nIs it not worth doing things like this if you haven't built up the practise with regular divinations?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8452280", "title": "Re: occasional divination", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Many people do divination that way, and it works well. I recommend daily divination purely as part of a systematic course of magical training.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8424632", "title": "Herb astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So, I've noticed that in the Encyclopedia of natural magic and other references the planet and the zodiac sign are frequently correlated. For instance solar herbs usually have leo for the zodiac sign. Now of course to some degree this makes sense they have similar qualities.  What if you want to find an herb that has an unusual pairing? Are there any references for this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8452536", "title": "Re: Herb astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Quite a few herbs have unexpected pairings. Frankincense, for example, is Sun in Aquarius, and hemp is Saturn in Aries. I don't know of a specific rule for finding such things, though.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8425144", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is the experience of Daath akin to that of Nirvana?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8452792", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "When I've experienced both of them, I'll let you know. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8426424", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "When scrying the elements, as described in the Druid Magic Handbook, it sometimes happens that one scene suddenly gives way to another scene or thing. Is this astral static, or is it a normal occurrence?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8453048", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's astral static. The more stable and realistic a scrying is, the better.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8426936", "title": "Jung & others", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "Not a question but an observation. Recently I immersed myself in Carl Jung's books. And its such a delight to read. Jung says he's doing science, but then with a straight face he starts talking about soul and mystical experiences. What a sly fox! Since I started reading his books I've also started having very vivid dreams. I guess I've been influenced by his writing, but I'm not complaining, I like it.\nP.S. Also I am apparently I am a Scarlet Tangential Weasel which I find slightly offensive. I may be a weasel. Scarlet is debatable. But calling me Tangential is just plain rude! :)\nP.P.S. Also in other news magical #orcs is trending on twitter, because apparently somebody read the D&D description of orcs as an aggressive and brutish race and thought it reminded them of how white colonizers viewed non-white natives. So D&D is problematic now. To be honest I've been expecting this to happen for a while now. It's really scraping the bottom of the barrel.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8453304", "title": "Re: Jung & others", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Jung was a fascinating figure; I think of him as an occultist who managed to convince most people that he was a scientist. As for orcs, at this point they've gone through the bottom of the barrel and are scraping up samples of the floor...", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8458424", "title": "Re: Jung & others", "user": "brendhelm", "content": "Re: #orcs - FWIW, this controversy is nothing new to D&D.  It isn't even that new in relation to orcs and how they're depicted.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8427192", "title": "Astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nI have begun investigating astrology, inspired by your posts.  In looking at my natal chart, I have a particular planet that seems to have rather prominent positioning. I was born with Sun on the Ascendant, so Sun and Sun sign in first house.  In addition, the planet ruling my Sun sign was also in that sign and in the first house.  So, I am trying to figure out the particular message or understanding here.  I have been reading up on astrology (online and an astrology 101 book) and reading up on that particular God/Spirit, but it seems that I may not have found the most useful sources.  In being in such a prominent position, is the God/Spirit associated with that planet and sign providing a particular opportunity or message?  Not sure if that is even a proper way to frame it or what to think about this.  Maybe it is just one feature of the whole picture of my chart?\nThanks,\nWill1000", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8453560", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's just one feature of the whole picture of your chart. It does mean that the way you appear to others and the way you appear to yourself tend to be pretty closely in harmony, and that you had the same Sun sign in your previous life as you do this time around, but the rest has to be interpreted as a whole picture.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8427448", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Good afternoon, JMG\nMy question today is about imagination and visualization.\nI have noticed in my efforts to improve this faculty that I experience what feel like two different kinds of visualizations/imagined objects or places.\nOne kind is when I am in a state of actively focused concentration on forming a sign or a landscape. It is a lot of work, and feels like the mental equivalent of tense muscles. I can do it with an acceptably good amount of visual detail, but it gets to be a strain after a while. These imaginings have a dense feel to them. It is difficult to perceive information about these places or objects in a receptive mode as I seem to be expending a lot of mindspace in creating them and maintaining their presence. If I let up on my concentration they lose their fullness.\nThe other kind is much more gossamer and relaxed. An example- I lightly but clearly direct my mind to say SEASHORE, and a whole panoramic view of a seashore and every little thing in it glides into view, like I am focusing a camera lens. It is much more spacious and expansive than the previous kind of vision but it is also much harder to maintain. It's more remote, lighter. It's like when you are dreaming and catch yourself noticing that you are dreaming, and as a result the whole thing vanishes to vapor. In contrast to the previous kind of imagining, I must stay more receptive to maintain the vision. I can \"make\" things in it, but almost everything else does not feel made by me. Staying connected is often tricky and unstable.\nWhat's going on here? Do I have two different sets of \"visioning\" eyes? Should I be concerned that this faculty seems to be divided in me rather than unified?\nThanks so much!\nBonnie\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-27 08:27 pm (UTC)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8462264", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent. You're beginning to perceive the two functions of imagination. The first is the ability to act on the astral plane; the second is the ability to perceive on the astral plane. Give them both time and attention, and you'll develop both powers -- they're both necessary to magical practice.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8463288", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Thank you!\nI will keep at it.\nB", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8427960", "title": "DMH Grove Ritual", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nSo sorry if this is an annoying question. I have read the MM FAQ and just had one niggle to clarify: I have two kids aged 9 and 5, with another on the way. I currently practice SOP in a room where they and my pregnant partner spend very little time.\nI have become increasingly eager to try the DMH grove ritual (and possibly Scrying) and was crestfallen to see that you recommend nothing more complex than SOP around kids 0-3 years old. Does that mean even if I do it away outdoors? Am i bringing energies back with me that could harm?\nI have done the SOP outdoors, though this would admittedly be a real challenge. But I'd do it if I could.\nThank you, Morfran.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8462520", "title": "Re: DMH Grove Ritual", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Ahem.\n\"If your children are under the age of three, basic magical practices such as the Sphere of Protection, the Lesser Ritual of the Pentagram, or the Middle Pillar exercise are fine, but don’t do them in any place where your children spend much of their time. Any more complex magical working? Leave it until later. Your kids come first.\"\nPlease reread that until you see that I have in fact answered your question.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8428472", "title": "How to explain magic to a loved one", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good afternoon. I'm a long-time reader and commenter, lately posting anonymously. I will try to tell my story briefly and then keep my question succinct.\nI was raised in a fairly liberal Christian home, and in my early twenties had a series of difficult visionary and non-human entity encounters- difficult in part because the Christianity I was raised in had little to no interest in metaphysics, and no resources to help me emotionally with these particular phenomena.\nOver the nearly ten years since, your writings have been a big help to me in finding language and concepts for those experiences. Slowly I've been overcoming my initial fear of the non-visible and have recently gotten in touch with a mystery school which you recommended to me and and which I've spent some time researching and building confidence in. (They're currently closed to new students for restructuring, but I am looking forward to their re-opening).\nTwo months ago I began dating a woman with whom I'd like to build a long-term relationship. She was raised in a slightly less liberal Christian home (compared to me), left the church in her early twenties, and has recently begun to tentatively explore Christian faith again.\nLast week I summoned up the courage to tell her about my long-ago spiritual experiences and the quest I've been on since then to understand what happened to me and why. I told her that magic and Qabalah seem to be the best fit I've found for me to learn and develop further. She listened carefully and has responded gently, but it's all so far outside her experience that she's expressed surprise and some fear about the idea of invisible entities and magic.\nThis was a risk I knew I'd have to take when I initiated the relationship; now I'm looking for resources or advice for how to introduce the world of magic and spirit to someone thinking about it seriously for the first time.\nI've thought of sharing with her your Well of Galabes, Dion Fortune's 'Psychic Self-Defense', or Gareth Knight's 'Experience of the Inner Worlds'. (I'm especially grateful now for the preservation of the Well of Galabes, with the comment threads intact). Do you have any other resource suggestions, or advice for how to proceed? Encouragement or tips from other commenters is welcome as well.\nThank you again for all your work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8463032", "title": "Re: How to explain magic to a loved one", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The book I recommend to anybody who wants to see how magic and Christianity fit together is Gareth Knight's\nExperience of the Inner Worlds\n. Since he's a devout Anglican Christian and writes from that standpoint, his way of talking about magic is very well suited for Christians to understand. Another book to follow up with is Anthony Duncan's\nThe Christ, Psychotherapy and Magic\n-- the late Father Duncan was an Anglican priest. Certainly encourage her to read the Well of Galabes if she likes, but Knight's book is the first go-to resource.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8432568", "title": "The Midnight Gospel", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Are you familiar with a podcaster called Duncan Trussel? I wasn't, until last monday when his new Netflix show called The Midnight Gospel aired.\nIt's basically a podcast with a cartoon animated over it. The cartoon is about a guy with an interdimensional machine that he uses to interview people who live in dying worlds. The people he interviews are real people talking about themselves and what they do, all related in one way or another to the occult.\nWhy would you care about this? Well on the third episode, the interviewee is voiced by Damien Echols, and they talk about ceremonial magic in general. It felt super weird to hear talk of actual magic in such a mainstream show. Here he is talking about it, and how a purpose of the show is to demistify magic. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1wcdBUDnv4U\nWhat do you think of this? Would you be willing to appear on a potential second season? This is also a recommendation of the show for those into the jerky color patterns.\nJP", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8463800", "title": "Re: The Midnight Gospel", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I wasn't at all familiar with it, and I'm not sure if I'd want to be on it or not. Good to see Damien with a proper wizard's beard! ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8432824", "title": "My friend Ronson", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and Readers,\nMy friend Ronson was dying a few months ago and now seems to have a new lease on life!  I told him how he had helped me realize I needed to deal with my childhood of neglect and abandonment and that seems to have made him feel better for having touched my life in such a good way.\nI have been praying for him every day to the Great Spirit as he is Blackfoot.  I know some of you have also prayed for him and special thanks to Kimberly and everyone who did pray for him.  His recovery is nothing short of a miracle as is the healing I have received from him.\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8464056", "title": "Re: My friend Ronson", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Glad to hear it!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8434104", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIs it possible to map the Ten Sephiroth into 10 points in the pentagram symbol (5 outer points of pentagram + 5 points of the pentagon inside it)? Would it yield something meaningful?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8464312", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I think you've just found a fine theme for your next couple of weeks of meditations.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8435640", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nI’ve been musing on the spiritual concept - there are many paths to “god”  It’s often used to unite different religions and highlight common purpose over differences in order to reduce tension. Of course, it may also be true.\nI’d like your perspective on two aspects of this. First, is this true? How do we know? In the sense that it gives people a sense of home or being found, I’m sure it is. And I’d like to think that it was true, as in there is something beyond words that connects us all. Is that the same as AWEN? But maybe it’s not so?\nSecond, by the same token, this can be a story to support a belief that it doesn’t matter which path I take, so long as I take one. What do you think?\nBest\nEdward", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8464568", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My take is that this is false, because it assumes that all the paths go to the same goal. I don't think that's the case. I also think there are many, many valid goals that human beings can seek, not just one goal we are all supposed to end up at. Thus there are many paths to many gods, and the path that's right for you may not be right for me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8478136", "title": "religions the same?", "user": "ritaer", "content": "Stephen Prothero (Professor of Religion at Boston U)--God is not One: the Eight Rival Religions That Run the World and Why Their Differences Matter (2010) very good book on this subject. Interesting for his choice of religions to compare: Islam, Christianity, Confucianism, Hinduism, Buddhism, Yoruba religion, Judaism, Daoism, atheism--he asserts that they are not, in the popular metaphor, paths up same mountain. He has written a number of books on the role of religion in American life'\nRita", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8439992", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "tamanous2020", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI ran this geomancy today and was a little perplexed by the answer. For the background of this question, I've been engaging in daily planetary devotions alongside Christian prayers, the opening/closing of the SoP and doing an occasional rosary.\nQuestion- Is my current spiritual practice connecting me more towards God, Jesus, Mary, and the saints?\n1. Acquisito\n2. Fortuna Major\n3. Albus\n4. Cauda Draconis\n5. Tristitia\n6. Carcer\n7. Caput Draconis\n8. Fortuna Minor\n9. Conjunctio\n10. Fortuna Major\n11. Laetitia\n12. Luella\nLeft witness- Fortuna Major\nRight Witness- Amissio\nJudge- Carcer\nThe judgement would appear negative indicating restriction, lack of process or any real change. Amissio has similiar negative affiliations with loss or negative outcomes to reinforce the judge, but it's strange that Fortuna Major is also a witness given its positive nature. Is one interpretation that over the long term, my goal will be successful, but not without loss and stagnation in the present?\nThanks for your time JMG.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8443832", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "tamanous2020", "content": "Sorry JMG, number 12 should be Puella", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8465080", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This is definitely a no -- a negative judge with one negative witness is not positive by any measure. Looking at the time factor, it says that you have lost something and are in a \"stuck\" position right now; you'll be okay eventually, but it will be a while and you may need to make significant changes on the way to that happy ending.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8465592", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "tamanous2020", "content": "Thanks for the reply JMG. This will give ample room and opportunity for meditation on the issue.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8444856", "title": "Help with Affirmation Wording?", "user": "alacrates", "content": "I'm wondering if you could help with the wording of an affirmation that I'd like to put into use.\nI've always had a lot of trouble dealing with other people, individually, but even more so when group dynamics are involved.\nIn one-on-one interactions I tend to do better, but I have trouble making connections with people. In larger groups, maybe beyond 3-4, I tend to freeze up entirely, I'm not necessarily anxious to begin with, but I'm very uncomfortable, and once I've been silent & uncommunicative for awhile, the anxiety starts to build from there. Whatever methods I have for relating with people individually, they don't work well in larger groups.\nIt's causing a lot of problems, especially because I almost can't go to family gatherings anymore, I can't hide how upset I am, even though in my family these are pretty benign, pleasant gatherings. I feel ridiculous, but I also can't seem to stop these reactions. I've also dropped out of some interest groups that I tried to participate in, I just couldn't find a way to interact in any normal sort of way.\nI was thinking of something like: \"I am comfortable around other people, I speak my mind freely, and I connect with others in beneficial ways.\"\nI would like to find an affirmation that would combine the idea of relating with others (and maybe groups of people) more easily with the idea of making connections with others which would be beneficial & enjoyable for them and for me. I feel like I've isolated myself unnecessarily over my life, and would like to make steps to change that.\nThanks as always for your work, and these forums you offer for readers to pose you questions!\n~ Daniel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8465336", "title": "Re: Help with Affirmation Wording?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Okay, before you fling yourself into affirmations, I'm going to recommend that you do some serious journaling to get to the root of the emotions you're dealing with. You need to figure out where this reaction is coming from or it'll just keep on coming back. Once you know what combination of issues (most likely rooted in unresolved childhood experiences) are holding you back, you can craft an affirmation to address those issues directly, and go from there.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8468920", "title": "Re: Help with Affirmation Wording?", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Hmm, that's kind of depressing to hear - I'm definitely not opposed to engaging in journaling, but from where I stand now, I feel like I can remember all the major events that happened in my childhood, I feel like it was fairly routine & mundane (though perhaps I'm wrong in thinking that.)\nIt seems to me like the problem is more an aspect of my personality generally, I feel like I noticed this problem relating to others when I started into kindergarten... but maybe this problem is more than be cleared up in posts like these... I guess some therapy might be called for, I have done some of that though, I don't have much hopes for that helping the problem...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8469432", "title": "Re: Help with Affirmation Wording?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You still need to figure out what's at the root of the issue so you can address it directly.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8446136", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG, thanks for your time! I always miss Magic Monday so I write down my questions for when I can make it, so please forgive the list\n-what do you think of Peter Carroll's Liber Null & Psychonaut?\n-are there any magical traditions that have/or are dying out that you feel should be revived/protected?\n-what's the rarest esoteric book you own or have read?\n-How much does magic rely on the environment? IE, does English Druidic magic work better in England, etc?\n-Have you worked with gematria much in the past, and are there any books in particular you would recommend on the subject?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8465848", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's one of the best of the chaos magic books; I owned a copy for a while when it first came out. It's not relevant to the kind of magic I like to do, but if that's what you're drawn to, by all means.\n2) Yes. I'm extremely interested in preserving and passing on classic American occultism, the sort of thing that was readily available from lodges and correspondence schools in the early 20th century and is rarely even noticed today. I'd like to see that change.\n3) The Triangular Book of the Comte de St.-Germain. I own a copy. It's a little easier to find now than it used to be, but it's still far from common.\n4) The connections are subtle and unpredictable. I found English Druidry to work extremely well in Seattle, for example.\n5) I've dabbled in it, but never found it that useful. No doubt if I were an orthodox Jew I'd have a very different take.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8453816", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do our mental sheaths remain intact in our next incarnation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8467128", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The capacity to produce a mental sheath remains intact. Basically, you create a new one with each incarnation, but the work you put into developing the mental sheath, making it complex and functional, etc. leaves an enduring trace, so your next mental sheath starts out where this one ended.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8455096", "title": "Several themes per meditation", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG\nConcerning discursive meditations.\nIs it wise to finish a meditative theme and then begin  another in the same session?  I'm describing a session that would last in total half an hour.\nMany thanks for your time", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8467384", "title": "Re: Several themes per meditation", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't recommend it. If it's a good theme it should be worth at least half an hour.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8456120", "title": "Rough few months", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So… I had a TSW moment.  The story is no doubt not terribly interesting but suffice it to say that I saw, via divination, something that shouldn’t have been possible, at least from a materialistic point of view.\nProblem is… afterwards I dropped everything.  All ritual, divination, meditation.  All of it.  I feel like I touched a live wire and now I’m wary about getting back at it. Anyone who has done electrical work and gotten zinged knows the feeling.  You approach the electric panel with trepidation.\nOther things have also affected this as the real world has had its issues dragging down my mood and my will power.  I wouldn’t describe this as “freaked out” though I did have a moment around the same time that left me a bit shook.  I was driving past a venerable old oak and projected a grandfatherly benevolent sort of image on to it.  It in return cast back an image of eldritch horror that oozed hatred.  I’ve never had that happen before.  I feel bad for the tree as it sits at an intersection of two busy roads located in between two college towns.  I think the cumulative effect of these experiences has been that of me enjoying the view of the scenery only to become acutely aware that the scenery was enjoying the view of me. That’s probably enough metaphors for now.\nAnyway, no real question specifically.  I have gotten back to doing things but at a much reduced rate and I’m working on my will power to get back in the ring.  Any words of advice will be appreciated.\nThanks for making a place to allow folks to ponder on things like this.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8467640", "title": "Re: Rough few months", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you can arrange to get some massage, that would be helpful. Fear leaves patterns of tension in the body that can take a long time, or massage, to get rid of.\nOther than that, though, you've faced what one of the classics of my insufficiently misspent youth called \"the first enemy of a man of knowledge\": fear. You and you alone can decide whether you will back away from the Path, or return to it and push on.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8456632", "title": "Paying for it", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have some pdfs of out of print books from authors that have passed on, but are recent enough to still be in copyright.  Is there a recommended charity or practice to pay for their use?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8467896", "title": "Re: Paying for it", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you considered doing the honorable thing, deleting the PDFs, and buying ebook or print copies of the books?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8468152", "title": "Re: Paying for it", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP, but what do you make of the way copyright seems to trigger a mental equivalent of the blue screen of death in so many people?", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8456888", "title": "Hestia", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recently, out of the blue, felt like Hestia wanted to, for lack of a better word, get in touch?\nAside from prayer, which I am pursuing, is there an obvious gesture, ritual, color of candle or what have you that a reasonably competent GD practitioner with no experience working with any other entities might do for Hestia? (I am a former chef, still love to cook, especially directly over fire, so when I meditated on it, it didn't seem so strange really, but I have no clue what to do).", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8468664", "title": "Re: Hestia", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The classic approach is to get a statue or image of Hestia, place it on a shelf or other elevated place (the top of a dresser, etc.) with a nice cloth under it, and burn a little frankincense to her each day while reciting one of the traditional hymns (you can find some of them\nhere\n). By classic, I mean that people like Iamblichus and Proclus were teaching people to do this back when Rome still had an emperor! After you've offered incense and verse, sit in front of the image and listen inwardly; she'll speak when she's ready to.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8479416", "title": "Re: Hestia", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "The traditional offering to Hestia is barley.\nI have interpreted that as tossing some uncooked grains onto the altar, but afterward, I'm not sure what to do with them.\nThere are several groups practicing reconstructions of ancient Greek religion, in some cases under the title of Hellenismos. Generally they decline to do animal sacrifice and have various workarounds. Some of these groups have websites. You can find some advice and examples of ritual practices to do at home, and perhaps citation of sources. If you were doing a traditional rite in which several Olympians were invoked, you would start with Hestia and i think also end with Her.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8457144", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Has anyone here ever visited a previous life’s gravesite?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8469176", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "As far as I know, I haven't done so.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8457400", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!\nAs someone just starting to get into occultism, I've wanted to work on implementing a daily divination practice. The trouble I've been having is that I'm a very skeptical person by nature, and I have an enormous amount of difficulty actually trusting the results.\nIf I were to do a tarot spread, and then reshuffle the deck and ask the same questions, it would be extremely unlikely for me to then draw the same cards. In fact, I could ask the same question multiple times and get completely different answers, due to probability. Wouldn't this invalidate the legitimacy of the reading, or the oracle as a whole?\nSimilarily, if I were to use a binary yes/no oracle to determine (for example) whether my offerings were accepted, even if they were accepted 100% of the time, I still have a 50/50 chance of drawing \"no,\" and I'd have no way of determining whether I was receiving a genuine message from the gods, or whether it was just random chance.\nAny advice on how to overcome these concerns?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8469688", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you approach divination that way you will fail. How well do you think it would work for you to establish a relationship with another person if, at every moment, you were doubting if you could trust anything the other person said? My advice, therefore, is to leave divination alone until you can treat it with some degree of respect.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8457912", "title": "Problems With A God?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWriting to you with an unusual problem. A few years ago when I was highly mentally unstable and superstitious, a sort of animated mental image of what I assumed was Loki fell into my head and started chatting with me. I was working my customer service job at the time, lost my cool, and mentally \"attacked\" the Loki figure in an effort to gain myself some peace. It didn't work out. The entity (?) still intrudes in my head to this day, disparaging me at inopportune moments. I've tried apologizing to it, pleading with it, etc. but this hasn't changed the situation either. In the event that I've actually offended a Norse trickster god, what's the proper protocol? Would banishing rituals help? Odin also pops in to offer words of encouragement from time to time. Given that I was raised Reform Jewish, this has all left me quite puzzled as to how tooling around in my mind could have such profound consequences. I should mention that I'm much more stable nowadays apart from the intrusive thoughts of Loki. Any thoughts?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8470200", "title": "Re: Problems With A God?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may want to consider psychotherapy, and I would strongly encourage you to avoid occultism until you get that taken care of. Uncontrolled intrusive voices in your head are kind of a bad sign, you know.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8460216", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Speaking of geometry, a lot of old magical practices seem to rely on the sort of math you’d learn in the quadrivium. Since then we’ve developed calculus, abstract algebra, statistics, and sundry other disciplines, and I assume there’s a lot of room there for innovation and exploration. Do you know of investigations in these areas that have already been tried?\n2) As someone who is prone to depression and intrusive thoughts, are there any particular otherwise-safe practices that are best avoided?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8470968", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The few of us who are interested in such things are still trying to revive the basics of the quadrivium! Esoteric tensor calculus will have to wait until that task is finished.\n2) I don't recommend any form of occult training to anyone who has mental issues serious enough to need medication.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8461240", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A  few questions about astrology - when you are assessing if a planet is in its fall, triplicity, etc., do you evaluate each planet against the sign it appears in for a given chart, so for example the Sun might be in Taurus, Venus in Gemini, Mars in Aquarius, etc? If this is correct and a planet is in a sign other than the one it rules how significant is the influence on the sign ruled - for example if Mercury is in fall/detriment in Pisces for a given chart how does that impact Virgo and any planets in that sign? Thank you again as always.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8471224", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not sure I understand what you're asking, but I'll give it a try. When you say that Venus, let's say, is in her fall, you mean that she's in Virgo -- that and that alone is the sign of her fall. If you say she's in her detriment, she's in either Aries or Scorpio. Whose chart it is doesn't matter. If Venus is in Virgo, then any house that has a cusp in Taurus or Libra (and is thus ruled by Venus) will have that negative energy affecting it. Is that what you're trying to ask about?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8476600", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "That was it exactly, thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8469944", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "alacrates", "content": "Alright, thanks for this, I will try to do this.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8470456", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Hello, JMG, it's Aquamarine Apopleptic Pangolin reporting in right before MM closes down for the week.\nQuick question:\nI've switched to invoking the Druid gods for my SOP practice. I'm not entirely sure how to properly pronounce Sul and Hesus (I found the the rest to be no-brainers). You did mention the Welsh \"u\" has a \"w\" effect to it. I'm iffy on whether it's a long or short vowel though.\nSo is it \"Sweel\" and \"Eh-swees\"?\nOR\n\"Swill\" and \"Eh-swiss\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8471480", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, the Welsh \"u\" is sounded \"ee.\" The Welsh \"w\" is sounded \"oo.\" So Sul is \"Seel\" and Esus \"Eh-seese.\" Hu is \"hee,\" btw.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8473272", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Thanks a bunch! Looks like I've been saying their names semi-wrong. Hopefully these aren't especially nitpicky gods.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8474552", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In my experience they're very mellow. They're used to dealing with Druids, after all!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8477880", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "amritarosa", "content": "Hi laughingsage and JMG,\nFWIW, I was mispronouncing Their names a bit as well. Then I started learning Welsh on Duolingo and decided to try them out with the new pronunciations I'd just learned. The response, as far as I could sense it, was bemused approval. Because of that I decided to keep the new pronunciations (which are as JMG described).\nBonnie\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-04-28 05:55 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8471736", "title": "Magic Marriage?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG!\nSo two of my friends have asked me to marry them, (as the officiator of the ceremony, not a member of the marriage.) Legal stuff not yet started but there's plenty of time.\nI'm a sucker for symbolism and ceremony, so I'm very happy with the role, although I'm 21 and have no previous experience with anything like this, and in general I'm open for any advice (from you or the commentariate? commentariot?) for this particular event as well.\nBoth members of the couple are into Reiki, with one currently practicing, I say that just to establish that they're into the alternate spirituality world already, and open to the subtler areas of reality.\nOriginally they pitched it to me as having me dressed up as the grim reaper to marry them, with a theme of \"till death do us part.\" Although they're open  to changing the ceremony around, and happy to let me make plans and see what they like.\nSince the ceremony is being held in late autumn, and with their preferences, it seems somewhat appropriate to have a marriage ceremony with some kind of death and rebirth symbolism.....\nI'm assuming that unless I put some kind of serious magical intent to that, it's not really gonna be anything more than fun drama, but if they want me too, and it seems appropriate and checks out in divination and all that, I'd like to.\nAny reason you think a marriage ceremony with death rebirth symbolism with somewhat charged intent could go awry? Would you recommend avoiding such a combo, or keeping it more on the \"fun drama\" side?\nAny ritual or natural magic tips or suggestions for such an occasion?\nAnd in general, pointers to keep it fun, safe, and meaningful?\nThank you for all your help thus far,\n-Wind Man\nMagickal Background in very basic golden dawn, working knowledge of LBRP, GRP, LBRH, RC. Have not made tools or a consecrated altar or anything, recently got the go ahead through (partner's) divination to try experimenting more and being creative with my own rituals. I also own your encyclopedia of natural magic, have a developing passion for gardening, and am eager to start learning to combine those, though I haven't yet.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8473016", "title": "Re: Magic Marriage?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Oh dear gods, no.\nI let a couple talk me into doing a marriage ceremony with magical components and a mythological theme many years ago, when I was young and dumb. The marriage was a disaster, and it ended explosively in a way that carried out the mythological theme to the letter. If you do a wedding with a Grim Reaper theme there's a very good chance that one or both of them will die young.\nMarriage is much more magically powerful than most people realize. The traditional symbolism is there for very good reason and I strongly advise you to advise them to stick with it, and at most throw in some funny costumes.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8477624", "title": "Re: Magic Marriage?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Very good to know, Thank you.\nAs I've never actually had the opportunity to attend a marriage ceremony (most of my family members belong to particular christian sect where non-members are not allowed into the marriage building, so I've mostly just been to receptions)\nit seems I have some research to begin doing, and some exploration to due to the fact that both of them are pretty emotionally damaged by that particular christian tradition. More questions for next MM!\n-WM", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8479672", "title": "Re: Magic Marriage?", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "In a nutshell, your responsibilities are:\n1. To officiate a marriage ceremony that is legal in the place they are getting married. That includes making sure that they obtain a marriage license ahead of time and the proper form to fill out after the ceremony. Then you need to make sure to fill it out properly, get the two witnesses to sign it, sign it yourself, and mail it or hand deliver it to the proper office.\n2. Unless the wedding is not going to have any guests, the wedding ceremony needs to be designed in a way that allows the guests to be happy for the couple, and it also needs to be recognizable to the guests as being a wedding ceremony. Since you have never attended a wedding ceremony, you are flying blind (other than any depictions of weddings in the movies or on TV, which usually are based on the Anglican ceremony in The Book of Common Prayer).\nIt sounds as if the couple is focused on their own experience to the exclusion of the feelings of the guests. You can balance that. Do a little research online or get a book or two on how to do a modern marriage, and get a clue about what the guests are going to expect and how they hope to participate. You don't have to cater to all of the guests' expectations, but it would be rude not to put them at ease and make them welcome.\nHaving guests has several purposes. The couple get to share their joy with others. The guests get to wish the couple well. Everyone gets to enjoy a celebration. The rite of passage from two single people to one married couple is recognized by the community. If any of those things are omitted without a good reason such as necessity, the marriage starts off on on the wrong foot.\nPeople who are active in a religious tradition rather than alienated from one often get some preparatory counseling from their minister or rabbi. This of course assumes a prior relationship with a minister or rabbi and with the religion he or she practices.\nLast year I helped to compose a marriage ceremony loosely based on a standard Jewish wedding ceremony. I went to an excellent Judaica store in Berkeley called Afikomen. The store had many different books on how to plan a Jewish wedding. I bought two that the owner recommended, one written from an Orthodox viewpoint and one more liberal.  Both books had advice on things that the couple could do during the weeks ahead of the wedding to prepare themselves for the step they are going to take. This is a good idea, but if people don't know about it, they will just be caught up in all the mundane preparations rather than doing any inner work. You are not qualified to be their spiritual advisor, nor did you sign up for that, but if you come across something in a book that looks like it might  be helpful, you could share it with them.\nIf you can, try to find an advisory book about weddings that is mostly secular in its outlook, but which focuses at least a little bit on people's love and happiness, rather than entirely on hiring the caterer and planning the floral arrangements. Then offer the couple some gentle suggestions. They aren't going to do anything they don't want to do, but you might be able to suggest ideas that hadn't occurred to them.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8472248", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "Good evening JMG!\nA few questions about divination today.\nYou have mentioned that you should not make decisions on the result of a single divination but I also understand that asking the same question several times is a slippery slope. What I have come to realize is that one should think carefully about what is really being asked to the oracle, since it is not The Great CosmicOom to answer instantly, unquestionably and omnisciently. However, I still feel stuck into how tackle a question from different angles. Could you give me some advice into how to use an Oracle more wisely? I think I am in that threshold between the daily reading and using it more widely.\nRelated to the first one. How can one avoid falling into an echo chamber while using an oracle? I have fallen into one in the past, not related to divination but more of in a behavioral way and it is nasty. Would definitely want to avoid that in divination!\nWith zooming eagerness,\nHeliotrope Tangential Eel\nP.D I’ve discovered something in my thought patterns with our past Q&A interactions. Somehow, the way you reply in some instances leaves me puzzled, frustrated and then gloriously reflexive. I take it is not completely unintentional. Very grateful for inducing that in me! Or as a song I like says: “Oh the pain it is but the joy it brings!”", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8473784", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) A great deal depends on what kind of oracle you're using. With a relatively flexible one like the Tarot or Coelbren, think about the question until you can construct a spread where each card gives you the information you need about some part of the issue. With a more fixed oracle such as geomancy or horary astrology, think about the issue until you can frame a set of questions, each of them different, each giving you some of the information you need.\n2) Treat the oracle as a friend giving advice, not a source of infallible knowledge.\n(No, it's not unintentional. Just one of the services I offer.)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8472504", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello- a quick recipe question: last week you recommended splashing Florida water in the corners of my new basement workspace to \"brighten things up\". I did some scouring of recipes found on the internet and concocted the following from items that usually seemed to be included that I had on hand:\nSweet orange essential oil\nLavender Essential oil\nDried tangerine skin\nBay leaves\nCloves\nCinnamon sticks\nAn early grey teabag, to get some oil of bergamot,\nAll macerating in 100 proof vodka- assembled last Thursday, first day of the waxing moon, I believe, planetary hour of the sun.\nDoes this seem like a workable Homebrew Florida water to you? Any other must-add ingredients? Or would you recommended just springing for ordering the commercial stuff online?\nThanks much (and hope this posts on time- apologies if it does not)!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8474040", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm pretty sure that would make a very nice Florida water. See how it works in practice, and refine the recipe from there!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"title": "Magic Monday", "url": "https://ecosophia.dreamwidth.org/87551.html", "year": "2020", "month": "05", "day": "03", "time": "11-31PM", "comments": [{"id": "cmt8480767", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG and thank you for another Magic Monday, right on time as usual. I have a couple of questions about your personal magical practice and writing habits:\n1. What is your go-to divination method these days (other than astrology)?\n2. Do you prefer to jump headfirst into new writing projects or do you do lots of methodical research and preparation beforehand? How do you know when you've done enough research and it's time to start writing?\n3. Are you involved in the design of your book covers (specifically, I have in mind the Occult Book, the Conspiracy book, and the Dolmen Arch), or is it more of a publisher responsibility?\n4. Back when you were more involved with occult groups and Masonic lodges, what was the preferred means of communication between the members? How did you recruit new members? I assume you weren’t using social media back then either?\n5. How many hours in a given day would you estimate that you spend in front of a computer screen? If this is a high number, do you find this problematic at all? Nicholas Carr wrote a book called The Shallows in which he argues that the Internet exerts a negative effect on memory and cognition. Do you agree with this?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8481535", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Right now it's my Sacred Geometry Oracle, which will be out in a new edition soon, and which is also central to a new system of occult training I'm developing.\n2) However much research I do in advance, I end up having to do more as the writing process turns up new questions and ideas. Thus I usually start writing as soon as I have a good basic idea of how I want to begin the book, and research and write in parallel. (This is as true of novels as it is of nonfiction books, btw.)\n3) It's the publisher's job. I'm very pleased that a few publishers of mine actively solicit my input into the cover art.\n4) Masonic lodges are one thing and occult lodges are quite another. Most Masonic lodges use the internet all the time. Magical lodges work best in silence, and usually recruit by personal recommendation.\n5) There's a difference between sitting in front of a computer screen and using the internet. My writing computer is not connected to the internet; my wife and I have a dedicated internet computer on which we keep no files of value, to avoid certain obvious problems, and outside of Mondays I usually spend 1-2 hours online per day. Yes, it's a dumbing-down medium, but some parts of it are much stupider than others; I use it almost exclusively to answer email, manage my blog and this journal, and find and download old and otherwise unavailable occult texts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8502527", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "5) Do you think the dumbing down online is inherent to the internet? Do you think it could be turned into a more positive medium?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8507903", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Sure, but you'd be fighting the entire corporate establishment. Dumb people are more likely to buy shoddy products, after all...", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8481023", "title": "Evolution...", "user": "hungryghost108", "content": "You’ve said a couple things recently, though I can’t remember where, that suggested you believe beings are reincarnated “up the ladder” (my phrase) towards humanity and consciousness. Am I remembering wrong?\nIf true, this seems a weirdly chauvinistic belief in favor of consciousness by those who happen to have it. My dog doesn’t seem any less advanced/evolved than me, and trees don’t seem any less advanced/evolved than either of us. In fact, there’s a tree in a graveyard near my house I’m convinced is an ascended master! :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8482303", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're certainly free to disagree with this bit of classic occult philosophy if you like. It's not accurate, though, to equate humanity and consciousness. All things are conscious to one degree or another, and your dog is fully capable of a rich experiential and emotional life. What differentiates you from your dog is the first feeble stirrings of activity on what occultists call the mental plane, which is the plane of abstract meaning; you and I can sometimes, to a very limited extent, think in abstract terms, while dogs think wholly in concrete terms -- the way we do 90% or more of the time.\nAs any Greek pagan could have told you, btw, it's not the tree who's the ascended master, it's the guardian spirit of the tree -- the dryad, in Greek terms. You and your dog also have guardian spirits, but for complex reasons it's somewhat easier for human beings to experience the guardian spirits of plants and of \"inanimate\" things like rivers and mountains. The tree, like you, me, your dog, and the planet earth herself, are all in the process of evolution, although at different stages -- and there are beings as far beyond you and me, in terms of intelligence and complexity, as we are beyond pond scum. That's what occult philosophy teaches, at any rate.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8482559", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "hungryghost108", "content": "Thanks for your reply. Is a guardian spirit distinct from the “etheric body” which you mentioned in a reply to me a few weeks ago?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8483583", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. The levels of being go roughly like this:\nSpiritual Planes\nMental Plane\nAstral Plane\nEtheric Plane\nMaterial Plane\nSo you have a material body, which is meat; an etheric body, which is the body of life force (prana, qi, voor, etc.); you have an astral body, which is the body of concrete consciousness (the level on which you do most of your thinking and your dog does all of its thinking); and a mental sheath, the first very rough draft of the mental body you'll evolve over many lives. Above that are the spiritual planes. Guardian spirits, as the name suggests, belong to the spiritual planes, though they can act downward into the planes below.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8487679", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "So, what IS a guardian spirit? Is is distinct from the higher self? Is it analogous to the Holy Guardian Angel from Abramelin?\nIf so, why do we have guardians? It's just hard to accept because it smacks of the typical mentality of \"I'm so special that the universe has given me extra special helpers.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8488447", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) A guardian spirit is a being of a more advanced evolution, whose further development is benefited by helping one or more beings of a later evolution. Yes, it's distinct from your higher self; yes, your HGA is such a being.\n2) You're not special. You have a guardian spirit; so does your dog; so does the tree in the graveyard; so do the dust mites that live in your pubic hair. The universe is just like that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8499967", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "2) I suspect that the spirit who pulled pubic mite duty is possibly working off some karma. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8508159", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends. From a certain point of view it could be rather entertaining. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8500991", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do guardian spirits have guardian spirits of their own?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8508415", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yep. It's turtles all the way down!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8527359", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(from Myriam)\nWould you say that a different Guardian Spirit is assigned to each personality, or is the same Guardian Spirit watching over you as you go through various incarnations? If the latter, I imagine they would feel like proud parents/teachers/mentors when you finally make it all the way to their level, from having been with you for the long haul.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8533503", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Traditionally it's said to be the same guardian spirit all along, so yeah -- and of course the experience they get through helping you helps them reach new levels, too. There's a very strong element of mutual aid in all this.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8551935", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "Might you have any recommendations for those who wish to tune in to their guardian spirits in order to a better job being under their \"tutelage,\" or is this a one-way mirror kind if situation?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8552447", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Regular practice of the basic magical disciplines, and then appropriate workings aimed at that kind of spiritual development, are the usual recipe.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8556799", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "temporaryreality", "content": "OK, onward, then!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8557055", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "open_space", "content": "Almost a year ago a friend did a Tarot reading for me which quickly turned into a bit more than just a reading and said “they were screaming in frustration and were basically dragging me and questioning why wouldn’t I just move” out of a strong period of my life which is still lingering and close to its end, so it feels. Then two days ago I did a tarot reading regarding where should I take my spirituality to, since what I have been noticing has basically made it clear that there is much, much more to Life than what I could possibly imagine and I have spun into a frenzy of looking for something that I can pursue for at least a long period of time if not the rest of my life in order to give it the respect and dedication such things deserve. I didn’t even put so much thought and research to choosing what to study in College! The reading was very fuzzy and when I was about to pick up the cards I noticed a train of thought, something like a thread in my mind and when I grabbed it I just said out loud very quickly: “Take your mind to a different place than where it is right now and then come to me”. Said and done the next day, with a much more calm mind I came to the reading and started looking for the same mental threads and without much thought just writing the first things that came to my mind. It was awesome, creepy and certainly made sense with what my friend was telling me a year ago and even though it was basically the same message than what he told me back then I think I am much more prepared to make something out of it. What you said to me last Monday helped me a lot! I think I have been holding back in fear of being wrong, instead of just letting it come out because I am treating it like an infallible source of truth rather than advise that is still subject to my judgement. Where I am trying to get at is:\n1)How can I start making a distinction between what comes from, say, journaling with some emotions and divination? Both seem to be related to finding and tuning into a thread that you just follow similar to when inspiration comes. Or more technically how can I make a distinction between tuning with my psychological patterns and letting them speak and tuning with the Astral Light and what my guardian spirit has to say?\n2) I’ve been pondering a lot into the magical implications of everyday life and something that has got me into trouble is for example thinking about other people. I feel more cautious about what I think but have also become afraid of expressing for example anger in my mind. Is there a magical effect about having such feelings in ones mind while thinking about others?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8557311", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That sort of distinction is something you have to learn to do; it takes time and practice. Fortunately both sources give useful feedback.\n2) There can be. If you focus your anger on another person it can set magical processes in motion that can harm them, and generate blowback for you -- this is especially true if you fantasize about hurting them, or what have you. Acknowledge the anger, accept that this is where your mind is at right now, and then turn your attention to something else. Again, it takes practice!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8499199", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "thesseli", "content": "Are there any books or articles you would particularly recommend that go into these planes further?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8508671", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Arthur Powell's summaries of Theosophical literature --\nThe Etheric Double, The Astral Body\n, and so on -- are good sources. Khei's\nRosicrucian Fundamentals\nand Heindel's\nRosicrucian Cosmo-Conception\nare also good. I'll have a book out next year that will lay all this out in detail.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8516607", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "thesseli", "content": "Thanks!  Looking forward to the new book.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8520959", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Amazing. I'm looking forward to your book about the planes of being! From my observation here on MM, you get asked questions about it often enough that it's probably less work for you to just write a book!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8522495", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's going to be a general introduction to occult philosophy, so will cover a lot of basic questions that get asked here.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8529151", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have seen many different versions of the \"planes\" theory. Some traditions divide them into 4; some has 5 planes; some has 7 planes... Do different traditions divide these planes according to their emphasis on different practical aspects? Is there any objective way to determine the \"true number\" (if there is) of these planes?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8533759", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There isn't really a \"true number\" -- it's a spectrum, and different schools divide it differently depending on what kind of work they want to do.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8491263", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "open_space", "content": "When one does the exercise of talking to a tree who are we communicating with the tree or the dryad? In any case, I have attempted communicating with a huge maple tree close to my apartment and even though it was not very chatty some sort of communication happen I believe. It was a bit mystical just staring at its branches being swayed by the wind, they seem so wise! Definitely funny the look on the bystanders watching someone barefooted completely immersed on, to their eyes, nothing at all. It’s unfortunate to see such a beautiful tree cornered to a small triangle patch of grass, I’m probably going to go there more often. What can one do to enhance the sensitivity to talk to trees (or the dryad if that is what it’s answering)?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8508927", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's generally the dryad. As for enhancing your sensitivity, er, what do you think all these occult practices are for? ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8496895", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What do these philosophies have to say about people who seem somewhat evolved,  but who are interrupted on that journey by illnesses affecting the brain so they get negative mood or behavior changes? (such as stroke, dementia or brain tumor, to take common examples) Conversely, what if someone becomes more spiritual after a stroke or brain tumor or similar?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8509183", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That usually has to do with karma. The process of spiritual evolution requires you to clear away your karma, and sometimes that involves some very sharp detours.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8502783", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not OP\nComing back to dogs experiential life. I was startled awake one morning by my dog who had barked and was angrily gazing at what appeared to be a woman moving thru the doorway. I assumed it was my wife. After a few seconds it dawned on me we were alone, my wife had left earlier for work. I looked around only to find the house empty. We had not lived here for long and it's an old house. I assumed it was a previous inhabitant, not menacing in the least. Are animals in general sensitive to the plane that spirits/ghosts inhabit? What plane are \"ghosts\" on? Why do some see them? Have you?\nThank you for your immense effort every week!\nLes", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8509439", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Dogs are legendarily sensitive to ghosts and other spiritual beings; some other animals have similar levels of sensitivity, but it varies from species to species and, of course, from individual to individual. Yes, your dog saw a ghost and so did you. As for what plane they're on, it varies, but their lowest manifestation is usually somewhere on the etheric plane -- the shedding of the etheric body is called the Second Death in occult writings, and many ghosts are people who are stuck between the First and Second Deaths for a while. (My book\nMonsters\ngoes into all this in detail, if you're interested.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8514047", "title": "Monsters", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I got the original version of your book Monsters.  How much new material is there in the updated version?\nAlso you mentioned that you wanted to find an illustrator for the Gypsy witch tarot you wanted to create.  Have you heard of this guy, very good artist..\nhttp://www.yurileitch.co.uk/home", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8518399", "title": "Re: Monsters", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The new edition has chapters on zombies and chimeras; other than that it's the same. No, I hadn't heard of Mr. Leitch, and yes, he's quite good. Do you know him personally?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8521983", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Rupert Sheldrake did a bunch of psi research with dogs, and even wrote a book about it, called \"Dogs that know when their owners are coming home.\"\nP.S. I am pretty sure you are spot on with your guess that Sheldrake is an occultist - I just learned recently that he has a son named Merlin! Who is a mycologist of some note...", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8538623", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Breathes there an owner with soul so dead\nWho never to himself has said\n“Why does that stupid dog stand out in the yard and bark at nothing?”\nMaybe we finally have an answer.  Maybe the dog’ s barking at a ghost he can see, but you can’t.\nOr maybe they can smell the ghosts.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8541439", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Back in the day it was common knowledge that dogs can see spirits. I suspect half the reason that dogs are so irritable these days is that they've caught on to the fact that we've lost track of so obvious a point!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8511999", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Has anyone made estimates of what percentages of people are at these different levels of evolution? Highly evolved people don't seem to be running the show, they aren't most politicians, or closed-minded professional cadres.\nYou suggested a while ago, that there are currently a lot of souls taking their first turn at being human, and that this could explain the amount of angry, doctrinaire people influencing culture.\nHave there been particular times and places where there was a higher percentage of evolved people or where they had more power in society?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8512767", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It varies constantly from time to time, since souls who have completed their work on the human level are passing beyond it, while new souls are coming into the human level, and both of these happen irregularly, depending on the fine details of who's achieved what in which life. I suspect that under most circumstances it's kind of a bell-shaped curve, with most people somewhere in the middle and only a few on either end.\n2) The people I've met who I'd guess are brand new at the human level aren't particularly doctrinaire, though they do repeat a lot of sound bites, and they're angry only when they've been told to be angry. They absorb what they're told by the media and repeat it back word for word, but there's no real commitment or understanding, just the human equivalent of one sheep bleating to another.\n3) Yes. Look at the great ages of human culture, such as classical Greece or the European Renaissance, and notice how many well-known figures in those times had the kind of remarkable talents that you only get by lifetimes of work. Those periods are always brief, because the souls who make them what they are move on past the human level, but a great deal of our species' greatest creations come into being in such times.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8551423", "title": "Re: Evolution...", "user": "happypanda", "content": "This is true. Which is why it's only very advanced persons whom might choose to do all the practices that let them stay in the material realm when their Consciousness has gained enough \"velocity\" (in a manner of speaking) to ascend. According to Sadhguru for 99% of people the moment of enlightenment is the same moment of their death on the physical plane because the physical layer can't hold them anymore.\nThere's also one very interesting twist according to Yogic lore. If one can stay fully, objectively conscious during the final 40 seconds of the whole death process (first death, second death, etc) then That Which is Not - the Enlightened Stillness - finishes all of your karma completely. For that person who has stayed objectively conscious throughout the whole process - all 16 overarching aspects of Mind stay fully awake and functioning - there will be no more human rebirths. That person has ascended for good. That's why Tibetan Buddhists place so much emphasis on the Bardo and practice for it. Their goal is to take advantage of that 40 second window of opportunity for complete karma burn. As the saying goes, \"Samsara\nis\nNirvana, when rightly seen.\"\nEdited (fixed typos and slight additional info for added clarity)\nDate:\n2020-05-05 02:16 pm (UTC)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8481279", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\n1. You've mentioned in the past that natal astrology isn’t your specialty, but I would like to get your feedback on the following chart placements if you don't mind: Natal Sun conjunct Saturn & Mercury in Aquarius in the 8th house, Sun and Saturn trine Jupiter in Libra in the 4th house. Does this seem promising for an aspiring occultist? My intuition says yes, but I’d like to get a second opinion in case I'm grossly misreading things.\n2. What are the kinds of things that the Higher Self generally wants, based on the experience of people who have made contact with it? Knowledge? Power? Wisdom? Does the Higher Self try to direct the personality towards some external goal, one that the personality may even disagree with, or is it more like the Jungian process of individuation, where the Higher Self wants to bring the full potential of the personality into manifestation, whatever that potential might be?\n3. Are all the different occult systems, Eastern, Western and otherwise, manifestations of the same system of knowledge with a different coat of paint, or do they refer to fundamentally different realities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8482815", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Any given set of placements has to be understood in the context of the rest of the chart, and no, I'm not up to spending an hour or so delineating your chart to make sense of it! As for whether or not your stars favor occultism, remember the old Rosicrucian motto: the wise govern their stars, fools are governed by them. If it's your will to pursue occultism,\ndo it\n.\n2) Your higher self is your real self; it's who you actually are. Your personality is a temporary mask worn by the higher self as it descends into the world of experience. Thus the full potential of your personality\nis\nyour higher self, and it's not the same for any two beings in all the cosmos. Jung knew what he was talking about.\n3) Roughly halfway between those two extremes. All occult systems exist within the same universe and make use of some subset of the available options, so there are definite parallels between systems, but the differences aren't just skin deep, and the endpoints are not all the same by any means.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8502271", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Do you know of any books that outline some of the endpoints of the different systems? I've ordered Mouni Sadhu's \"Ways to Self-Realization.\" And have some other books. It seems like part of my path is to compare lots of other paths and try to see the commonalities. I think everybody creates their own path, and two people in the same system are not necessarily going to the same place, but that there are also underlying Truths that can be accessed by people from radically different systems, though they might express them in different words and concepts.\nThank you again for hosting these discussions. I don't comment as often as others but I keep up.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8513023", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't know of a really useful book on that subject. Maybe you can write one.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8517375", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "Seems like an undertaking that I am not yet up to, but maybe after many more years of study I will be. Thanks.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8539135", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isaac_hill", "content": "What is the difference between attaining Gwynfydd and gaining union between the lower and higher selves?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8541695", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A fine theme for meditation!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8481791", "title": "Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear Mr Greer,\nAn interesting thing happened yesterday. I have a small Cthulhu statue that sits on the mantle of a disused fireplace. The chimney sometimes leaks when it rains and water drips through the ceiling. After a heavy downpour yesterday I found that the water was dripping exactly on the top of the Cthulhu statue. It missed everything around it and even the picture on the wall was dry. Only the Cthulhu statue was wet and sitting in its own little puddle. Would there be any significance to this? How do you think I should interpret this and what should I do next, if anything?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8483839", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A traditional polytheist would take that as a signal that Great Cthulhu is interested in interacting with you. If you want to take up the offer, there are various ways to do it -- the simplest and safest would be the twice-daily meditative ritual I put into my novel\nThe Weird of Hali: Kingsport\n.\n(Normally I don't recommend trying to work with fictional deities, but people have been invoking the deities of the Cthulhu mythos and getting results since Kenneth Grant's time. For that matter, while I was working on my Mythos novels, it was very clear to me that I was interacting with something that was far from fictional.  Your mileage may vary...)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8485631", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I get that feeling from READING Lovecraftiana, as well as from some of Stephen King’s earlier work.  Also from others here and there.  When I finally got to read Joseph Payne Brennan’s “Nine Horrors and a Dream,”  all the stories were entertaining horror fiction, EXCEPT “Canavan’s Back Yard.”  That one had the hard cold ring of terrible truth.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8486143", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I get it from Lovecraft, not from most of the others. I don't know if you've looked at my very odd contributions to the genre, but they unfold from the simple fact that I don't find the Mythos deities frightening. The only Lovecraft story I find actually scary is \"The Color out of Space.\" The others?  To me they're fantasy, not horror; the idea that the universe doesn't notice or care about our existence strikes me not merely as common sense but as actually rather comforting. Of course I also think that octopi are cute. Thus in my Mythos novels, the Great Old Ones are the old gods of nature, those sinister and multiethnic cultists are\noc\ncultists who've been vilified in the usual way with the usual blood libels, and the bad guys are basically Delta Green on bad steroids with an extra dose of lust for power and a fanatic belief that human beings ought to run the cosmos. Yes, the main character's love interest in the first volume has tentacles in place of legs, and yes, I got that from the movie\nDagon\n. ;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8492799", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you, I will give this a try. Now to find potpourri during the lockdown...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8509695", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Rosemary leaves would be a good start -- they're widely used for sea magic. A blend of rosemary leaves and spices with a bitter element, such as cloves, might be a good option to start with; you can add new ingredients and explore essential oils when you have the chance.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8504575", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "causticus", "content": "Wouldn't these observations then point to the probability that Lovecraft himself might have been interacting with real entities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8510207", "title": "Re: Ph'nglui mglw'nafh Cthulhu R'lyeh wgah'nagl fhtagn", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We know he did in one sense. When he was a boy, he was crazy about Greek mythology, and took it to the extent of setting up an altar in his backyard and pouring libations to the gods and goddesses of Olympus. I don't think it's at all accidental that his fictive mythology resonates so closely with actual powers -- or that there are definite similarities between the way that the Greek gods in Homer relate to human beings, and the way that the Great Old Ones relate to their worshipers in Lovecraft's stories!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8482047", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) The archetype of the successful male in contemporary Western culture generally involves material wealth shown off through conspicuous consumption, high social status, handsome looks (extra points for a sculpted, muscular physique), and a string of lovers tumbling into his bed. Are such portrayals an image created by marketers and entertainment moguls to erode men’s self-esteem and promote products, or is it something that corresponds to a genuine reality? And do you have any advice for those of us who don’t conform to it, particularly in the sense that it's become almost an expectation in the dating market?\n2) In Japan, there is a sociological phenomenon called hikikomori, where upwards of a million people have withdrawn completely from society, never leaving their homes (and often, their bedrooms) for years on end. 75-90% of hikikomori are estimated to be men, but women may be underrepresented in the statistics for various reasons. They’re supported by their parents or relatives into their 40's and 50’s, although a minority make an independent living through remote work. The withdrawal of the hikikomori is usually caused by factors such as academic pressure, exam failure, bullying, workplace stress, or job loss. Do you have any thoughts on this condition, and what might be going on in the psyches of the hikikomori?\n3) Why do you think the divorce rates are so high in Western countries? Depending on how it’s measured and what country is being considered, estimates range from anywhere between 30-60%. Presumably, most people don’t get married with the expectation that they’ll get divorced someday, and yet it seems to happen with unfailing regularity, on average, 7 years after the vows are exchanged. Is this sort of breakdown an inevitable feature of human relationships? Clearly, making divorce impossible led to miseries of its own, but do we have to accept such a high rate of failure for the minority(?) of successful relationships out there, considering the fallout that often accompanies divorces?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8484095", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's not a genuine reality -- far from it. As Ioan Couliano pointed out many years ago in\nEros and Magic in the Renaissance\n, modern advertising is a corrupt and malevolent form of magic. The image you've described is pushed on you by the media to keep you feeling weak and inferior, just as a comparable image (I'm sure you can describe that just as clearly) is pushed on women with the same goal in mind. The result is that 90% of guys chase blindly after the 10% or so of women who more or less correspond to the image, and 90% of women chase just as blindly after the 10% or so of men who likewise more or less correspond to their image.\nAs for what to do about it, depends on whether you're willing to extract yourself from both sides of the equation. I was fortunate enough to catch on to this in my teen years, and learn to appreciate a wider range of feminine charms; as a result, I was only rarely and briefly without a girlfriend from the time I turned sixteen until I got married six years later. (Yes, we're still married; our 36th anniversary is coming up in July.)\n2) I've read about it but I don't claim to understand it. I have Aspergers syndrome, and asking an Aspie about what's going on in someone else's psyche is not necessarily going to get you far. ;-)\n3) No, that sort of breakdown isn't inevitable at all. (As my case demonstrates.) Our culture raises barriers in the way of successful long-term relationships, but they can be overcome so long as both people involved are willing to work at it. The key is being able to step outside a purely self-centered perspective and see what your actions and words look like from the other person's perspective, If both partners cultivate that, there's a very good chance the marriage will last. Of course here again, that's something the marketers and the media do their best to prevent, since miserable people buy more products!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8501247", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not the OP.\nThis really resonated with me: \" ...modern advertising is a corrupt and malevolent form of magic. The image you've described is pushed on you by the media to keep you feeling weak and inferior... \"\nI'm a woman who's struggled with self-image since puberty (so a couple decades). It's been a powerful and destructive demon in my life; one with which I (embarrassingly) still wrestle. How I wish my younger self had recognized the media and advertising I over consumed as the \"malevolent form of magic\" it is.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8510463", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Understood. Advertising directed at women is deliberately aimed at making them feel ugly, lonely, and helpless. I don't know if this will work for you, but I know women who've benefited a good deal by noticing those feelings and learning to say to themselves, \"that's the advertising talking, not me.\"", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8524543", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "If I may I think question 1and 3 are very much linked. If you have been programmed to be the typical advertised male (tm) or female (tm) everything is seen as temporary or disposable.  That relationship not working here is the shiny new 2002 model for you...\nAs an example how many romcoms do you see were the story stops at the alter.  No discussion about what happens after.  So when life’s bumps happen or your wife after 2.3 kids doesn’t look like a slim 20 something anymore...get a new one.\n“ The key is being able to step outside a purely self-centered perspective and see what your actions and words look like from the other person's perspective, If both partners cultivate that,”. This a 1000 times this.  I might add that some thought should be given to second or third order consequences to what ever it is you want to do.\nOther Dave", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8492543", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "My take on the high divorce rate in Western Countries complements our host's take on it.\nMost folk, so it seems to me, expect that all the work of\nmaking\na marriage is over and done with the moment both parties exchange their vows: after that comes the rather different,\nalien\nwork of making a married life (getting such things as a house and yard, children, social position, etc. ad nauseum).\nNo; exchanging your vows is when the real work of making a marriage finally begins, and that work never ever stops until the day you die.  And it's work that stands completely apart from the consumer economy, from the all-too-human quest for status and/or power, etc.  This work cannot be monetized; it cannot become a part of any consumer economy; there is no possible way to do that.  It's more like the very hard, unrelenting work of a life-long spiritual path.\nMy wife and I have\nboth\nbeen doing this marriage work for nigh on 53 years now, consciously and deliberately, and we plan to keep doing it for the rest of our lives.  It's really paid off for both of us.  We can honestly say that we're each other's best friend.  There are also other real benefits that come with long, long, long marriages, thoughtfully built and maintained.\nOne of the more surprising things we discovered is that a long-married eventually couple develop, in additon to their own individual Selves, a shared Self as well.  The syzygy--the \"yoke\"--you have voluntarily undertaken to share as you work together will develop a consciousness and awareness of its own, which turns out to be a different thing from each partner's own personal consciousness and awareness.  It's fun to have this, and it's also useful.\n[I should mention here that my own family's esoteric theories posit that each human being consists of many interdependent Selves, which naturally are created in the course of living one's life.  For us, the new-born baby has no Self at all, but must construct the various Selves that it will need to live its life as it grows and matures and ripens and dies.  (Jung, I think, got it quite backwards with his idea of an undivided, \"individuated,\" human being as a desirable goal.)  --  This theory of ours has its roots, so far as I can tell, in the sort of experiences and experiments that led people like Frederic W. H. Myers to talk about \"subliminal\" selves that people have quite apart from their \"liminal\" selves, through which they present themselves to the world.  (And before Myers, there were the experiments of Mesmer.  So it's a very old-fashioned theory, predating and--it seems to me--very much at odds with the sort of cosmology that Madame Blavatsky (and eventually, Dion Fortune)  talk about in their writings.]", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8498175", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "oligopsony", "content": "FWIW, at least in the US, the divorce rate for first marriages is not especially high - you get the \"half of all marriages\" statistics from a minority of people who divorce and remarry several times - and has been declining for some time. The highest divorce rates have been the from generations where marriage was highly normative and expected, and then no-fault divorce came in and gave them more options. Younger generations have divorced less in part because if they get married, they're more likely to really intend to, and also more likely to do it a little later in life, when decisions are less impulsive.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8515327", "title": "marriage", "user": "ritaer", "content": "We tend to forget that the median age for first marriage has been steadily rising. The lowest was in 1950--men 22.8 and women 20.3. My parents married at 19/16 in 1948. My sister married at 15, also to a 19 year old. I was the old maid of the family, waiting until 20 to marry after swearing to my family that I would finish college. (I did)\nAnother thing that seems to be forgotten, as I have noticed over on the same themed discussion on Ecosophia, is that not all couples choose to get the government's stamp of approval. A women may be a single-mother on paper while she is actually in a stable, long term relationship. I might note that the opposite is true too, a couple may be married on paper and live separately or be in the same house but seldom communicate on a level higher than 'pass the salt.\" And, of course, same sex couples were unable to marry until recently, yet history is full of partnerships that lasted a lifetime. Artist Don Bachardy produced a wonderfully moving series of portrait sketches of his dying partner, novelist Christopher Isherwood. And I will pivot this back to occult topics by recommending Isherwood's book about his experience in Vedanta, My Guru and His Disciple.\nRita", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8527615", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "3) Here is a tentative answer: seven years seems to align well with the age a child finishes the anchoring into the physical plane, and is, so to say, ready to be left to fend off by itself, because it is fully human then. So boom, the only thing that was keeping the marriage is out of the way. Perhaps more children would extend this time further; that should be easy to falsify (in the scientific sense of the word).", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8483071", "title": "CGD and astrology", "user": "deansmith", "content": "JMG,\nWhen you were writing and developing the CGD magical system, did you set out to keep astrological symbolism out or did it just end up that way initially.  If it was on purpose, what was your reason for doing so?\nIt certainly to my mind keeps it more earth centric and focused I suppose.\nThis popped into my head recently reading about iron age Druids being (according to Caesar) proficient in astrology, and also thinking on your growing astrological body of work.  Just kind of sparked my curiosity as to your architecture of the system.\nThanks!\n-Puce Anthropoid Raccoon", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8484607", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It was partly my idea, because there's a different system of magical timing that goes with the CGD system -- a solar/lunar system, of the sort that was clearly used by the people who built Stonehenge -- and partly a clear sense of what the inner powers behind the CGD system wanted. All my books of magical instruction are the product of a certain degree of cooperation with the Unseen.\n-- Lilac Amphibious Tulip", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8485887", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Maroon Exiguous Tulip butting in here\nI think perhaps we may be related?\nMaroon / Lilac - similar colour spectrum\nExiguous / Amphibious  - small things (generally)\nTulip / Tulip\nperhaps a lookup of the family tree is in order, or would that be the family Bulb?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8486399", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Nah, it just means we have related Pangalactic New Age Soul Signatures -- that's not heredity, it's a matter of the resonance between the Cosmic Oom and the phantasmagoric nothingness of being. ;-)\nEdited\nDate:\n2020-05-04 05:20 am (UTC)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8494079", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Speaking of Stonehenge, can you recommend an author on this place, and also on Avebury?  Thanks.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8506111", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Second this request, on the solar/lunar system used.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8510719", "title": "Re: CGD and astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I haven't read a lot of recent material on them, but Gerald Hawkins'\nStonehenge Decoded\nis a classic, and Mike Pitts'\nHengeworld\nis well worth reading. Hawkins explains the solar and lunar alignments of Stonehenge.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8483327", "title": "Holy Water", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good Evening,\nThank you again for hosting this.  I was gathering up  my materials to make my weekly holy water tonight and had a thought (yes it was quite painful).  Normally I make holy water exactly as per instructions given in Circles of Power using distilled water as a base.  However I live near the ocean and was wondering if using water from the ocean or any other local source would have an effect positive or negative.  Have you experimented with this at all or do I have another homework assignment?\nSpeaking of homework assignments on a MM awhile back I asked if the Tibetan Rites and the Essential exercises from Spirit and the Sword play well together.  I am happy to report that after about 3 months of work I have not noticed any major problems.  Two thing did crop up.  One a feeling of lethargy if they were skipped or delayed too late in the day.  It appears to be best to workout in the morning with this.  Also the Tibetan Rites recommends working up to 21 repetitions.  I found that to be too much in combination.  11 repetitions seems to be the sweet spot if you are following them with your essential exercises.\nHeliotrope Exiguous Toad...or Other Dave", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8484863", "title": "Re: Holy Water", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You have another homework assignment!\n2) Many thanks for this. I'm not at all surprised -- the Five Rites seem to play well with most Western esoteric practices -- but it's good to have that data point on the basis of experience.\n-- Cobalt Translucent Muffin", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8484351", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI vaguely remember in one of the early Magic Mondays you mentioned some New Thought books that focus on developing mental abilities and that learning those would not clash with studying ceremonial magic. I also vaguely remember that there was a name to this... Something like 'mentalism' only it wasn't this word, it was something else... And I can't find that message because of how vague my memory of all of this is. Does any of it ring a bell or am I dreaming something up? :)\nThe reason I suddenly remembered about it, is that I am looking for a way to deepen one little technique I'm using with a reasonable success for the last decade or so. It is similar to affirmations only it targets a very specific result in the immediate or near future. I could repeat intensively a phrase 3 or 4 times to trigger a memory, an event, or a state. For example, I could mentally repeat \"Next time I open the front door I remember to call my mother\" while visualising me opening the front door of my house and remembering about my mother. Another example, is to use these auto-suggestions as free coffee with no side effects (other than still needing to catch up on sleep later): I could say \"I am wide awake and focused for the next hour\" (or until something particular happens) and be reasonable awake even though I was nearly falling asleep just before. One more use is to wake up at a certain time and this sometimes works with an astonishing precision, particularly when visualisation and affirmation is done in a state of deep relaxation just before falling asleep.\nI picked up the basic technique back when I was dabbling in NLP. Since then I found that all talk of NLP people on how they've came up with these techniques from scratch is basically bragging. As a Russian saying goes -\"Anything new is a well forgotten old\". I am pretty sure NLP just rebranded something older and I'm looking for some sources on similar techniques (or, the best case scenario, a system of training) that predates NLP. Would you possibly have any pointers?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8485119", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm; \"mentalism\" is the word I'd have suggested. There was a huge amount of material on mind training in the late 19th and early 20th century; Theron Q. Dumont (another of W.W. Atkinson's pseudonyms) and Edmonde Shaftesbury (real name Webster Edgerly) are two of the more popular authors in the field, but there were hundreds.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8487423", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Oh, so it\nis\nmentalism after all! I tried googling it and ended up bumping into all sorts of articles on stage tricks and performances. Wikipedia article on mentalism doesn't even mention anything about New Thought. That's why I became sure that I must have misplaced the word with something else...\nMany thanks for the leads!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8488703", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Annoyingly, the word \"mentalism\" is also used for a kind of stage magic, just as \"magic\" means stage tricks as well as the art and science of causing change in consciousness in accordance with will.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8504831", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I remember you using the term 'mental magic' as well. Is that the same thing?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8510975", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, that's another term that was used.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8517887", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Atkinson's best and most complete book on the subject has the title \"Mind Power: The Secret of Mental Magic\" (1912).  It's available in many places online, including:\nhttp://iapsop.com/ssoc/1912__atkinson___mind-power.pdf", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8558335", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ganeshling", "content": "Huge thanks for this!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8485375", "title": "Formulating questions for divination and geomancy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In your experience, are you liable to get true answers that respond to your divinations, but aren't really what you wanted to ask, similarly to how poorly phrased intents work in magic?\nThis is just a hypothetical example but, if I cast a geomantic chart for the question \"Will I get in a relationship with X?\" And I get a positive Court -- what I want to know is whether I will be in a romantic relationship, but we end up as good friends. So the oracle answered my question, but I wasn't clear enough. Have you encountered situations like this?\nFor geomancy at least, the various traditional indicators like Rubeus or Populus as the First Mother usually guard against this, I would think?\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8486655", "title": "Re: Formulating questions for divination and geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, this happens, and I'm very careful to phrase my questions for divinations to try to prevent this. Rubeus will tell you if you're lying to yourself, and Populus will tell you that you haven't really thought about what you're asking; careful phrasing of questions will still spare you a lot of confusion.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8505599", "title": "Re: Formulating questions for divination and geomancy", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "An example from just this morning:\nI asked the question, since we treated them in Leo but our female was scratching and biting at herself (we think her brother butted in and ate most of her medicine before we caught him),\n\"Do I need to flea-treat Polly again?\"\nGot Rubeus in the 1st and immediately realized that the answer is \"of course you (will) need to flea-treat her again.  At some point.\nSo I re-asked the question this way,\n\"Does Polly have living fleas on her right now?\"\nCame up with an occupation between houses 1 & 5 with Tristitia.\nMuch clearer, they said...\nI suspect that a good deal of the magic of geomancy is in getting us to think more clearly, n'est pas?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8511231", "title": "Re: Formulating questions for divination and geomancy", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a great example. Yes, one of the points of divination generally is to teach the necessity of asking clear questions if you want clear answers!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8486911", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Good evening, JMG!\nI've recently started working through LRM, and am on lesson 3 right now. (The book is wonderful, by the way. Thank you for writing it!)\nI have a few questions about the LBRP.\n1) What do I do with the circle and archangels when I begin the Qabalistic Cross? Do they grow in size with me, or disappear, or what?\n2) I find that after the ritual, there's a strong sense that the circle/pentagrams/archangels are still there in the place I did the ritual. Should I be trying more to dismiss the images, or is this expected/desirable?\n3) I feel a bit odd invoking the archangels without any other relationship to them. Is it appropriate to pray to them? Are there traditional ways to approach them? Or am I thinking about this in the wrong way somehow?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8488959", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Don't pay attention to them any further. Focus all your intention on the Cabalistic Cross.\n2) Don't worry about it. The space where you do the ritual will be psychically clean for a good long while afterwards.\n3) You can certainly pray to them; many people do. If you do so, spend time listening as well as talking to them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8489983", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Excellent, thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8487167", "title": "Group work and Mysteries of Merlin", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG!\nJust got my hard copy of Mysteries of Merlin. I think my favorite bit so far has been the section on the roots of Christianity as a mystery cult and the possibility for it to reorganize from being doctrine-driven to being transformative group experience driven. Really turned my world upside down there. Also, as someone working with the CGD, the descriptions of the individual gods and goddesses along with pointers to how some of them appear in the Mabinogion are probably worth the price of admission alone.\nNow on to the question: chapter 8 got me wondering if there are any books that you would recommend that give concrete examples of solid group rituals and/or accommodating more people in solitary rituals? I'm looking to take apart a variety of examples to see how they tick and how they compare to the solitary work I've been doing. My background is CGD plus I've read through Inside a Magical Lounge, but I'm looking to expand my horizons so I'd be interested in any other system or pantheon.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8489215", "title": "Re: Group work and Mysteries of Merlin", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm going to assume that you meant\nInside a Magical Lodge\n, though a magical lounge might be interesting too!\nAs for books, the classic source is\nThe Golden Dawn\nby Israel Regardie, which gives the Hermetic GD grade rituals.\nThe Druid Grove Handbook\nby me also gives the rituals of the Ancient Order of Druids in America, which might be worth a look.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8487935", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "🎼Oh, she’s MYYYYY tentacle baby, For the rest of the night...🎼\n🎼Long Tall Sally she’s real sweet, she got all the tentacles 🦑 that Uncle George needs...🎼\n🎼It’s cost me my soul, but there’s one thing I never let go\nIt’s my man\nHe’s not much for looks, reads none but unmentionable books\nBut I love him\nTwo or three fell priestesses has he\nThat he likes as well as me\nBut I love him\nI don’t know why I do\nHe is untrue\nAte all my toes too\nWhat can I do?\nOh, my man I love him so\nHe’ll never know\nI’m imprisoned in his dark lair\nI don’t care\nWhen he smothers me in coils\nYuggoth is right, all night\nWhat’s the difference if I say\nI’ll go away\nWhen I know I’ll come back a faceless horror someday\nFor whatever critter my man is, I’m his, forevermore!”🎼", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8489471", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Funny. In the last of my tentacle novels,\nThe Seal of Yueh Lao\n, we find out that Wilbur Whateley had a girlfriend...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8491519", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I saw that gag in a short story, too!  Not one of yours.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8511487", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course! We know from Lovecraft that Wilbur had gone through puberty, and I don't know what your experience was, but when I was sprouting my first beard and dealing with a voice an octave lower than I was used to, I was very, very,\nvery\ninterested in the opposite sex. It stands to reason that Wilbur would have been just as interested, and Dunwich being Dunwich -- and young women being young women -- somebody would have found so strong and vulnerable a bad boy irresistible.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8517119", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would you be a lesser magician without the beard?  We are used to associating beards with wisdom, eg, Merlin, Jesus etc. Does it have a significance beyond the visual?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8519167", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "In my case, I used to have five o'clock shadow by two in the afternoon, and so shaving just wasn't worth it. ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8523007", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "At least you could make it to the afternoon! ;)", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8488191", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "Hello JMG,\non several occasions you've mentioned that there is a reason why we are living on the material plane. What is this reason? Besides it being a fine theme for meditations.\n- Scarlet Tangential Weasel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8489727", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "To waken into objective consciousness and begin the process of evolution, we need a world that resists us. Matter functions as a thrust-block, something that gives us that resistance to push off of.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8491775", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "That takes Newton’s third law into a whole new level...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8511743", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You can apply all of Newton's laws quite exactly to spiritual as well as material realities!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8530431", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "Interesting... I can kind of see that with the other two. So his laws of motion are actually Laws of Motion beyond materialism probably intentionally as he was an alchemist. Do you know if he talks about this on his writings?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8534015", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Not that I know of, but yes, he was an alchemist and a good one, and I suspect he knew perfectly well that his laws dealt with more than matter.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8503295", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophian", "content": "That makes a lot of sense to me and it is a fine theme for further meditations indeed. Thank you.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8492031", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "For tax purposes?\n(Sorry.  Obviously, I’m not JMG.  Let’s move on to his words of wisdom.  🤪", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8490239", "title": "Bardon", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "Salutations JMG!\n1) How does Bardon's system differ from Golden Dawn style systems, especially with regards to how energy is utilized in the body and the future progression of the practitioner after basic magic proficiency is attained?\n2) What flaws and strengths do you see in Bardon's system? For that matter, what's your opinion on the minutiae of Bardon's system?\n3) What's a general ballpark of when the Heathen Golden Dawn will be released? A handful of months? A handful of years? Also, why is it called the Heathen Golden Dawn and not the Asatru Golden Dawn? As I understand it, Heathen is a much broader term that's similar to \"Northern Pagan\" and Asatru refers specifically to the Norse Aesir, right?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8512255", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's a completely different system. Like most central European systems, it does a lot of work on the etheric plane, where the Golden Dawn works primarily with the astral. Both systems have the same long-term goal, the attainment of union between the higher and lower selves, but they get there by radically different means.\n2) I've never practiced Bardon's system -- I got to the Golden Dawn first, and stuck with it -- so you'd have to ask somebody experienced in his work.\n3) At this point I have no idea. Sven and I were about to pile back into serious work on it, when the coronavirus outbreak came up; he's an officer in the Norwegian Army and he's been busy with emergency duties ever since. As for \"Heathen,\" we include the Vanir in the system as well as the Aesir, so the broader term seemed more sensible.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8515071", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "1) Could you elaborate on how they \"get there by radically different means\"? I persist because I found a practitioner online that says:\n\"For the record, Golden Dawn practice divides the two categories, spheric and planetary, into two closely related, yet different, practices. Bardon does not.\n...\nFirst, the energies of the planets are harsh. Practically alien in comparison to the fundamental energies in the first book and Kabbalistic energies in the third. It almost feels like the planetary energies are something that humans can work with…we’re just not designed to work with.\nWorking with these involves exposing yourself to them and letting them burn their way into your mental, astral and physical bodies.  Then you take a break. Purge the energy completely and rest. Your bodies grow more resistant. Then you go back and do it all over again. If you wait too long and they burn through, you end up having a psychotic episode and this hurts a lot. Allow me to reiterate, it hurts A LOT.\nOn a practical basis the sensation is one of scarring yourself and I’m not sure this is a healthy behavior physically speaking.\nThe energies through the Sun/Solar sphere become increasingly harsh. Do not skip ahead. If you decide to do this, complete your work with one sphere before moving onto the next. And do them in order for a minimum of ten hours each and doing the full one hundred is probably not a bad idea.\"\nhttps://yogicengineering.com/2016/09/09/sphericplanetary-meditationyoga-what-you-get-and-the-dangers-involved/\nDoes this sound similar to rising up the paths of the Tree of Life in the Golden Dawn?\n1b) On another note, this past weekend I was innundated with a flood of new Bardon research. It was as if my google searches weren't connecting, but all of a sudden I found a whole bunch of Bardon practitioners' blogs. Am I just getting better at research, or is there something occult going on?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8519423", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Seems to me that the person you found confirmed what I was saying. Rising up the paths of the Tree is a means, not an end...\n2) Have you considered doing divination to find out?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8537855", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "1) Well what I'm trying to ask (and not very well, my apologies) is whether this \"astral scarring\" and rough process in the Bardon system is mirrored in the Golden Dawn, or if GD magic is more gentle and safe. Are the planetary energies supposed to be so harsh and dangerous on the human energy body? Or is this unheard of in Golden Dawn style magic?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8541951", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Fair enough. Golden Dawn magic isn't as rough on the etheric body, since it doesn't do much with that. It's rough on the astral body -- that's where you get the emotional imbalances that sometimes come with mishandled GD work.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8548351", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "boulderchum", "content": "Hmm, interesting. Thanks.\nA thought occurred to me just now: if there's Engineering for the Material Plane, Bardon/Qi Gong for the Etheric Plane, and Golden Dawn/Art of Memory for the Astral Plane, what would a Mental Plane tradition look like? I suppose a Spiritual Plane tradition would be a form of Theurgy and ritual offerings to gods, or attempting to \"become one with everything\" in the\nBuddhist sense. It sounds like a great theme for meditation, to be sure.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8550143", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "We don't have mental bodies yet -- all we have is a mental sheath, which is the matrix from which a mental body evolves -- so a mental plane tradition is outside our reach; meditation is about as close as we can get. Yes, it's a worthwhile subject for meditation!", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8556543", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey hey JMG,\nI know that you haven't done Bardon's IIH, but do you know people who have?  Is it advisable to do both the Golden Dawn system and Bardon's (one after the other) or are they not very complimentary?  I assume that since they are both in the hermetic tradition that they would go well together, but I'd prefer to have good evidence of that than test it myself.\nThanks,\nTim", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8557567", "title": "Re: Bardon", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I know people who've worked both of them, so it's certainly an option. Just take your time and follow instructions -- with Bardon's work, especially, you can mess yourself over if you decide you know better than he did.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8490495", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "I have a question about \"old souls\": You have described that old souls are human souls who took quite a few lifetimes  to dig out themselves from serious mistakes in a past life. But souls who are ready to enter Gwynfydd should have quite a few lifetimes behind them, becuase it takes time to master the human level. Aren't they, too, \"old souls\"? Is there a difference between the two kinds of \"old souls\"?\nTo dissolve a tainted egregor, traditionally, occult lodges would dissolve themselves, lie fallow for one to seven years and begin with new symbols and robes. That means that the closing down of so many social activities due to the current pandemic must have an influence on the egregor of the respective organizations. Is this right and is it known what kind of things will happen to the egregor of clubs and social activities?\nAbout cursing: Someday, maybe in the Archdruid Report, you wrote that cursing involves stating the way that someone trips himself or herself up, and in Magic Monday, you wrote that it involves setting up a pattern of self-defeating behavior against someone with the help of magic. Are the two things the same, or were you talking about different things?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8512511", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In theory, somebody could go through the necessary series of human lives without messing up and having a lot of bad karma to deal with. Maybe it's even happened a few times! In the vast majority of cases, though, by the time you're ready for Gwynfydd you've been through the wringer a few times, or more than a few.\n2) The suspension of activities isn't enough by itself; you have to start up again with new symbolism and gear. Otherwise the old egregor reasserts itself promptly.\n3) I was speaking of different things, in very different contexts.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8490751", "title": "Divination using tarot - who's answering?", "user": "shadow_rider", "content": "Hi JMG\nI've been wondering about divination using tarot.  My question concerns what entity it is that's answering.  I wondered whether it was my own higher self, the planetary spirit, the planetary archangel or a spirit guide.  I'm thinking at the moment that it's either my own higher self or spirit guide.  Can you offer any suggestions?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8513535", "title": "Re: Divination using tarot - who's answering?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's supposed to be a combination of your guardian spirit and the intelligences of the Tarot, who are spiritual beings that work with and through the cards. So both of your guesses are correct.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8491007", "title": "Telesmatic images and the LBRP.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey jmg\nI read the section in your book  “circles of power” on telematic imagery and I want to know if it is possible to use the rules for creating these images to make more detailed visualisations of the archangels in the LBRP in order to increase the ritual’s power?\nJ.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8513791", "title": "Re: Telesmatic images and the LBRP.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good. Not too many people notice that trail of bread crumbs.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8492287", "title": "Banishing.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What is the purpose of banishing?\nHow does it work? How does one know that what was gotten rid of was bad instead of unpleasantly helpful?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8514303", "title": "Re: Banishing.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A proper banishing ritual, such as the LBRP or the Sphere of Protection, is designed to balance the elemental forces in your aura and your surroundings under the direction and guidance of Spirit. Any entity or energy that can abide the presence of Spirit and a condition of elemental balance will be perfectly able to come and go in a banished space; the entities and energies that can't tolerate Spirit and can't maintain themselves in a balanced condition are driven off. Thus anything you actually need to have around you -- for example, unpleasant experiences that you need to balance your karma -- will stick around before, during, and after a banishing ritual; it's the stuff you don't need -- noxious spirits, nasty magic, other people's thoughts and feelings, etc. -- that gets swept away.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8514815", "title": "Re: Banishing.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Why would the presence of Spirit cause a problem for some entities?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8519679", "title": "Re: Banishing.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There are various theories. Quite reliably, though, when you invoke the fifth element demonic beings run like roaches.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8524287", "title": "Re: Banishing.", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "With the SoP in particular then, does that mean that when you reach the point of invoking with spirit below the effect will start showing up?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8525567", "title": "Re: Banishing.", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you're doing the Opening right, and invoking spiritual influences or deities at that point, you should begin getting some effect right away.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8493055", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are the ethics of behaviour in dreams? There are some matirialist ideas of lucid dreaming that say it's all a model created by your own mind, so you don't need to hold back. I've also heard acconts of people who felt guilt after going to town on a revenge fantasy. If characters in dreams can be independent entities, that seriously changes the situation.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8514559", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on how lucid you are in your dreaming. Ethics deals with your own choices. In the kind of dream where you're not lucid at all, where you make no deliberate choices and things just happen, you're no more ethically culpable than if you do something while delirious from fever, say. Lucid dreams are another matter; the more conscious you are, the more your actions have karmic consequences, and the mere fact that they take place on the astral plane (where dreams happen) rather than the material plane doesn't change that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8493311", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A few years ago I tried one of those Chinese astrology calculators. It told me my health was going to suck that year, and it wasn't kidding. :) From a cursorary look at how it works, it seems to be based on a more expanded planetary hours system. Have you looked into Chinese astrology much? Is it fundamentally different, and does it still end up in the same place? If you went for readings from a Western and a Chinese astrologer, would they end up telling you basically the same things?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8515583", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Chinese astrology is one of our species' four great mathematical astrological traditions; it's very thoroughly developed and very accurate. It probably originated from archaic traditions that also gave rise to Jyotish (Hindu astrology) and Western astrology, but it's a very different system. I don't know what results you'd get if you consulted a Western and a Chinese astrologer and compared the results -- it might be a very interesting experiment.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8493567", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "LAst week someone had been a Druid but then converted to Christianity. They then did the druid version of a ritual and proceeded to have a very bad day. Would that have been divine retribution, or more like spending time training for the shot put, then suddenly doing a marathon?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8520191", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Most Christian churches require you, at baptism, confirmation, or both, to formally renounce all other deities (lumped together as \"the Devil\"). Since that's done in a ritual context with full intent, it's the equivalent of an initiation oath, and those reliably bring blowback if you break them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8537599", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "kylec", "content": "I was baptised as a baby, and later went through the motions of confirmation unwillingly at about 13 or 14 because my parents made me, though I didn't really care for church at that point. (In a very mild-mannered Methodist church). What obligation should I expect to have? I've working with the CGD for five years with great results, so I figured I was ok, but all this talk this week has me wanting to be sure.\n--Kyle", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8542207", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You have a connection to the egregor, but since you went through the process unwillingly, you have no obligation to do anything with that. That is to say, you're fine.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8550399", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "This got me thinking...\nSay a person gets baptized, as a adult, into a Christian Church, later they become interested in Gnosticism, possibly considering themself a Christian Gnostic, but Gnosticism even of the Christian variety seems quite different than \"ordinary\" Christianity with reverence for the True Father and Sophia and so on. Would that person suffer karmic blowback for \"cheating\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8550911", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a very good question to which I don't happen to know the answer. It would probably depend on the exact nature of the baptismal vows they made.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8552703", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So a Episcopalian might not get blowback but a Methodist could? (I just picked two denominations randomly, I don't know the phrasing they use in their vows.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8552959", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Or vice versa, yes. The wording of a serious spiritual vow isn't a minor thing.", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8493823", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is anyone else starting to feel like when you're asking questions on Magic Monday, you might not just be asking for yourself? When I'm trying to think of questions I'm finding myself going more into a trance-like state and ideas coming to me. It's not unique as I do sometimes use altered states of consciousness for deep thinking. However given the context, is it possible other entities want me to ask things on their behalf?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8520447", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. Anyone else had that experience?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8555007", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Not that specifically.  But I can’t tell you how many times I wanted to ask a question or was thinking about it and someone beat me to the punch.\nOther Dave\nCrimson Oracular Weasel", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8530175", "title": "Regularly", "user": "kimberlysteele", "content": "Yes.  In fact, I am often reticent about commenting because I don't want to bother JMG with a topic that will usually pop up within one to three weeks!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8553215", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "open_space", "content": "I don’t know but to me it is on the reverse. I usually think my questions for the week instead of on Monday, spend some time with them and writing them coherently and I am almost always the last, or close to last commenter if that gives any clues. Two or three of my questions where asked by somebody else today almost exactly as I was going to ask them! I hope my mind is not leaky... Any ideas JMG?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8555775", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's not a matter of minds being leaky. Our minds have a transpersonal dimension -- they're not just isolated blobs of thought locked away in skulls. Every mind blends subtly into every other mind, and when a group of people are following particular patterns of thought -- for example, reading this weekly forum and thinking about what's been said -- their minds inevitably resonate. It's one of the parts of being human for which our culture does very little to prepare us!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8494335", "title": "Astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear John, what a coincidence! Guess what book was I perusing last night...\nI find this an extremely comprehensive text, but not the easiest to navigate, particularly from a novice point of view; I much prefer the writing style of certain Archdruid Emeritus, but he's never published an Astrology Primer...yet...;-)\nSeriously, would you consider, if not a book, at least a first steps mini-course on delineating your own natal chart? (maybe linked to your existing patreon account on Mundane Astrology?)\nAnd two more astro-questions if I might:\n1. Do you agree with George in the house placement of mother and father?\n2. Some astrologers seem to disagree also respect to whether it's the Sun sign or the Ascendant which marks the personality. In your opinion, Does the Sun sign tell you who you really are and the Ascendant the image you show to the world or the other way round?\nMany thanks again John.\nManuel", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8520703", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I'm still of two minds about that. My father corresponds very closely to my 10th -- his sun sign is on my MC -- and my mother to my 4th, but I know people for whom the opposite seems to be true.\n2) I tend to read it the other way around. The Sun is what you present to the world, the Ascendant is who you are.\nAs for an astrology primer, there are so many of those in print right now that most publishers would sooner tear their hair out and eat it than deal with another manuscript for another astrology primer. (It's right up there with one more Wicca 101 book.) I wouldn't feel comfortable trying to teach natal chart delineation, anyway, until I study it much more closely -- I do mostly mundane and electional astrology, you know.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8530687", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have Virgo sun but I’m not a neatnik.  I have Sagittarius ascendant and the house is sanitary but a bit cluttered.  It’s less cluttered than when I was working because Sonkitten ‘s a confirmed night person so now that I’m home from 0530 on I can throw things away when he isn’t looking.  He is also a confirmed packrat.  I used to be gone from 0530-1800, M-F, and then on weekends I mostly slept.  Now I’m on Packrat Patrol for an hour or so at dawn and then go back to sleep for a while.\nDo the stars impel or discourage packratitude?  I always figured he inherited it from my mom, also a packrat.  Or it could be his brain damage.  We’re working on him disposing of the ephemera because I don’t want him to end up on the news after I’m dead.  He’s doing quite well on newspapers.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8534271", "title": "Re: Astrology", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The influence of the natal chart on packratitude (lovely word, btw) is not something I think I've seen discussed in the books I've read!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8494591", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\n1. I've been doing the DMH, and I will start with the Dolmen Arch at some point, too. When I start the Dolmen Arch, do I continue to use the same SOP/Three Cauldrons/etc as I learned in the DMH? I noticed in the Dolmen Arch that the vocal component is a specific SOP working (to attain Gwynfydd in this lifetime) but the gestures are different between the two books.\n2. Can you do Ogham readings outside of the daily SOP, ie - later in the day? I thought it's best to do it in a banished space.\n3. If images on TV affect the subconscious, ie, the subconscious believes the images to be real, does this effect also apply to cartoons? What about video games? To paintings? Or does it apply to just films of real scenes and people?\n4. I was thinking about intentionality, and that you can choose how you see something in the outside world, and that for example you could see either certain activities one does as 'boring', or be able to see value in them, and this is a choice. To take the example of one's job, one could be bored doing it, and waste one's life doing it by choosing to see it in this way. By this logic, one's job, no matter what it is, could always be a source of meaning, even if you are, to take an example from the other blog, a bureaucrat in the university administration system, or perhaps an executive in the advertising industry. Yet  neither of these jobs are activities which I would like to spend my time doing. I wouldn't want to become a great advertising copywriter with all its potentially harmful effects on society, because I buckled down, saw some sort of meaning in the job, and did it very well. Plus, this argument could be used an excuse to remain in a situation which you truly don't want to be in, or to avoid making a change you need to make.\nThe only holes I can poke in the argument are that, first, if we co-create our reality in cooperation with the rest of the cosmos, then meaning in a particular activity will differ  depending on the lessons a particular individual needs to learn, and two, the cosmos being much smarter than we are, we can't really make the judgement of whether an activity or career is harmful to society or not, because there are much larger complexities at work.\nAm I missing some subtlety here?\n5. In the Dolmen Arch, there are little triangular images after each chapter and throughout the text (Celtic knots?), and they are different in each chapter. Is there significance to this, or are these purely decorative?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8521471", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) You can either continue doing the DMH version or try the Dolmen Arch version instead.\n2) You can divine in a space that hasn't been banished. Most people do.\n3) The more realistic, the stronger the effect, but it certainly works with paintings, for example. That's the point of religious art!\n4) It's not all one or all the other. Your intentionality matters, but so do the facts of the case. If you swallow rat poison, thinking that it's medicine, your intentionality will not keep it from poisoning you!\n5) If I were feeling unusually sly, I'd suggest that you meditate on that. (They're purely decorative.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8527103", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Data point re 3): growing up I played a lot of top-down 3rd person games like Age of Empires and League of Legends and I will not infrequently dream from the perspective of a disembodied sensor ball looking down on something in isometric view. This regardless of whether I've been playing video games recently.\nSo yes, screen images do interact with your subconscious in weird ways.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8559103", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thanks for that! You reminded me that, when I used to play video games, I had a similar thing happen. Good thing I stopped, then!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8494847", "title": "DMH stuff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nthank you for all your previous answers. I’ve got some more questions:\n1. In DMH you mention that the solar current evolved more recently than the telluric current. Does that mean that nwyfre evolves too? And if the telluric current was here first, didn’t it pose a state of imbalance until it was balanced by the solar current? Does the solar current affect animals, given that it has to do with the mind?\n2. You say in DMH that the lunar current does not exist naturally in the individual or the world. Yet its symbols are the egg and the child which are natural. Without the explanation that it has to be created, I would have thought it occured naturally in the act of conception, for example. Could you explain, please?\n3. Last MM you mentioned the two functions of imagination: the ability to perceive and the ability to act. I see a connection with two other statements of yours:\n- What makes good poetry also makes good magic.\n- Ritual is poetry in the realm of acts. (I hope I remember the latter correctly.)\nI see poetry more as the perceptive function of imagination and magic more as the active function of imagination. Could it be so?\nThank you,\nHana\naka Maroon Somnolent Filbert - my English wasn’t good enough for that, I had to look up the words to know whether I should worry ;-)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8522239", "title": "Re: DMH stuff", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Nwyfre evolves, and so does everything else, but it's not the solar current as such that evolved more recently -- it's the ability we have as human beings to tap into it. (The solar current has been here as long as the Sun has.) Animals and plants also relate to the solar current, just not as intensely, and their balance between the currents is appropriate for them, just as ours is appropriate for us.\n2) You've just asked me to explain the secret of the Grail -- and no, I don't mean that metaphorically, or as a joke. This is something you need to seek for yourself; systematic meditation on the symbols is a good place to start.\n3) Poetry and magic are twins; there's a reason why in English we've got the word en\nchant\nment! Poetry is perceptive in some sense, but it can also be profoundly active and creative.\nGlad to help with your English vocabulary!   ;-)\n-- Citrine Oracular Raccoon", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8530943", "title": "Re: DMH stuff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "You write better English than most native speakers I know.  👏👏\n—Lady Cutekitten", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8495103", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Since banishing rituals weren't used in the pre-Golden-Dawn era, the question occurred to me if they weren't needed in the time before because of different conditions in the lower astral plane? In the absence of a daily banishing ritual, how often did ceremonial magicians then practice magical rituals, on average? And what do you think, will be the future of banishing rituals after the end of Western civilization?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8522751", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) In premodern Western magic, the assumption was that you were a devout Christian or Jew and were using the ordinary protective prayers and spiritual disciplines of your faith. Banishing rituals have become necessary because (a) most mages since Eliphas Levi's time weren't members of a mainstream religion and (b) the mainstream religions discarded most or all of the protective practices they once had, under the influence of a misguided rationalism and modernism.\n2) Rarely. An active mage might do ritual work three or four times a year.\n3) Good question. It depends on the future of religion in the Western world, and that's anyone's guess right now.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8541183", "title": "Premodern stuff", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What sort of premodern prayers and rituals where the ones that did what banishing rituals do?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8542463", "title": "Re: Premodern stuff", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Look up pre-Reformation Roman Catholic sacramentals (which are not the same thing as sacraments) for a good set of examples.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8495359", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Is there a way to tell whether one is merely understanding intellectually the concepts in an occultist tradition, and actually embarking on the work of uncovering one's individuality?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8523263", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Does what you learn change the way you live? If not, it's just a head game.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8495615", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi John,\nHave you read Fortune's 'Magical Battle'? There's a quote in it that stuck with me ever since I read it:\n\"Before we give you the work, we test you. It is better that the empty\nvessel should fall to pieces than the full one. We strike the vessel before we proceed to fill it. There are certain tests which, having been taken, open out new planes.\"\nDo you have an idea what she's exactly referring to here? I mean the procedure of striking the vessel, could it be related to the Lords of Karma in particular? The closest thing I can think of is present in Hindu religion about the antahkarana, but I'm not sure and I've always preferred a Western source.\nAlso on Fortune...\nI'm guessing you read the theories on the cause of her death, do you think the effort she made in that magical battle resulted in that?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8523519", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's more specific than that.  The entities she was working with were testing her, and others, to see if they could handle the forces that needed to earth out in the rituals. That's something that happens quite routinely when you start work with the Inner Planes -- and yes, I've experienced it.\n2) My guess is otherwise. I think that it was the conflict between her Christian faith and the decidedly Pagan forces that flowed through her that brought about her early death.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8559871", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Yes, I'm really curious on the nuances of how that testing happens, 'cause I think I've experienced it as well. Crowley mentioned some stuff in his 'Magick Without Tears' letters about the Ophidian vibrations that the Secret Chiefs use, but I need to get back to it and see if it sheds any light on this.\n2) Hmm, I've always thought her system transcended both, but she indeed tended to lean more towards Christianity from what I've read of her work. Can't wait to read her biographies.\nAziz", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8561663", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "robertmathiesen", "content": "Dion Fortune came to her Christian faith only as an adult: she says herself that she was raised as a Christian Scientist.  So maybe the conflict between Christian and Pagan forces wasn't as strong in her as it would be in a baptized (and confirmed) Christian.\nChristian Science has nothing even remotely resembling the traditional Christian sacraments: no baptism, no confirmation, no funerals ... not even any such thing as church marriages.  (Sure, Christian Scientists marry all the time, but their only option is a civil marriage.  Mary Baker Eddy taught that parents could conceive their children without any such thing as physical sex, if only they had developed their Christian Science sufficiently.)  There is such a thing as Christian Science communion, which happens four times a year, but it makes no use of bread or wine or anything else that can be eaten or drunk, and it entails no vows or promises, explicit or implicit.  So she wouldn't have been either baptized or confirmed as a child.\nIf she ever did seek to enjoy Christian sacraments, it would have been as a grown woman.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8495871", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any information about the significance of Beltane/Hexennacht before they were sanitized for our safety? It sounds an awful lot like the spring version of Samhain, where the doors to other worlds are supposed to be open a little more than usual. It is odd that this happens when the sun is perfectly lined up with the equator, like it has something to do with they daylight/darkness ratio or gravitational pull away from the poles.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8523775", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Um, the Sun's not lined up with the equator on Belteinne or Samhuinn. The Sun and the equator line up perfectly at the spring and fall equinoxes, about six weeks earlier. As for the old significance of Belteinne et al., people have been bickering over that for a century or so; I don't know of an unbiased account.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8558847", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hmmm. I wonder if it is too late to get a refund on that mail order astrophysics degree.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8496127", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There's a form of agricultural magic I've never heard of but assume must have been done. Using divination for planning selective breeding of livestock. Presumably along with other practices to help the process along. Is there a record of that and how well it worked?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8524031", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I assume it must have been done, too, but I've never read an account of it. Sorry.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8532991", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Daughter of poodle breeder here.🐩. As far as I know she never used magic, but I think a magical breeder today might profitably use a spell to protect from the effects of rampant inbreeding.  It wasn’t a problem back in the ‘60’s but today nearly all lines of pedigree dogs are so closely related that you can’t avoid inbreeding.  Some breeds are descended from the same handful of dogs—an entire breed closely inbred!—and the breed clubs still refuse to re-open the stud books.  (To “re-open the stud books “ means to allow fresh blood into the line.). So a breeder’s only choice in those cases is how closely to inbreed.  You can see where the animal equivalent of an anti-Hapsburging spell might come in handy.  In fact I’ve always wondered whether the Victorians had such magic and lost it.  They liked to talk about “purebreds” and “mongrels” a lot, but as a society still largely dependent on animals, they’d have known all too well what the effects of inbreeding were.\nOr they could have been talking the talk in public and outcrossing like mad in private.  Unless the buyer observed the mating, as far as he knows the animal’s father is who the breeder says it is.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8496639", "title": "Routine", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "In your suggested magical routine guidelines, you've given ritual, meditation, and divination as the recommended method for practice. And while I do find that a helpful formula, I've wondered of its origins. Is this of your own making, or does it go back further?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8524799", "title": "Re: Routine", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's my creation. I found that including all three as daily practices had much better results than neglecting any of them. A banishing ritual, a session of discursive (rather than mind-emptying) meditation, and some kind of divinatory reading every day is what does the trick.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8497151", "title": "Update and question", "user": "bendithfawr", "content": "Hi JMG,\nan update to my question\na few weeks ago\n: last week a neighbor approached me and asked if we would be interested in a plot of land around the corner for a garden. We signed the lease yesterday and are now proud gardeners-to-be! So your interpretation of the divination was spot on: it just came to us.\nAnother question in that regard: we're thinking about buying a \"Tiny House\", a cozy little cabin on wheels, for the garden. Would that be movable property (2nd house) or a building (4th house)? I'm guessing the former but would like to be sure.\nAs always, thank you so much for sharing your knowledge and interpretations!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8525055", "title": "Re: Update and question", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it!\nAs for the cabin on wheels, if it isn't anchored permanently to the ground, it's not fourth house.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8497407", "title": "Index or list?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Another reader was indexing some of your online content or helping with an expanded FAQ, weren't they? Or something of that nature.\nA suggestion for another feature for that site if it doesn't already exist: lists of the occultists, and the texts, used to illustrate Magic Monday posts, so they are all on one page.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8525311", "title": "Re: Index or list?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you considered doing that?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8497663", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week, someone touched briefly on discernment, picking out real divine messages from the tangle of your own thoughts. I'd had a relationship with a particular god that I called a patronage but have recently come to realize was actually not. I've known it for a while in the back of my mind, but I've since had it confirmed by multiple outside divinations - either it's been over for a long time, or it never actually was outside of a couple very powerful experiences in the very beginning.\nMy background is in NeoPaganism though I'm no longer involved there. I've been realizing they don't do a good job with discernment, and may have done much to set up a mistake like this. I think it was on your other blog, a while ago you described NeoPaganism as focused more on emotional states than spiritual realities with a lot of pop culture notions getting in the way, I think you're absolutely right about that. A lot of what gets promoted as the way humans and gods interact is little more than bad fantasy fiction tropes, that get more extreme if you're out in the, uh, kookier end of things, which I was for a time, wading neck deep in Chosen Ones. I remember a culture that actively discouraged critical thought (which got a lot worse as the current political trends began creeping in more), blind acceptance of anything that came along, anything someone told you, whether they're a reincarnation of a ten year old anime character or worshipping demons, it's all good and who are you to question them even in the privacy of your own thoughts? If you can't question anything, how do you question your own experiences, or keep those other experiences from influencing your own? There was no understanding (I almost want to say it seems like a deliberate misunderstanding) of group minds, collective narratives and the affect they can have in shaping or outright creating your own thoughts (that latter was something I experienced for a time, thankfully brief but very confusing, nothing I'd learned from the NeoPagan corners I was in gave me any context for what had happened, I had to piece it together on my own).\nEven though I knew almost from the beginning (and I know that, because I was more active on the internet then and wrote about it a lot) that something was wrong, I was actively discouraged from considering this option, that it was a mistake, as being the root of the problem. No matter how long things didn't work, whatever time or effort I made, just keep going with it, forever if need be, even if it never works again, just do don't ask questions. The possibility of being wrong, that your interpretation of spiritual experiences was incorrect and a lot less glamorous than you may have first thought, doesn't seem to be something people want to grapple with. Can't blame them, it hasn't been much fun.\nI'm still struggling to figure out how this happened, how I lost control of this, how it got this bad. I have no doubt a lot of the mistakes made were all my own (in the very beginning, when I knew no better, it's no wonder), but I also think group dynamics, the particular culture in NeoPaganism (the parts I was involved in), the expectations they implant in you, instruction not given, questions never asked, played a big part in this, too.\nMy question for you:\n1. How do you develop good discernment, separating your thoughts from the gods (or someone else's)? How do you overcome a background like this, separating out the bad instruction and unrealistic expectations so you can move forward, and hopefully not into a second blunder of the same sort? I have no wish to give up, on the gods or the path of mysticism I had as my goal, but what can I do to try and prevent something like this from happening again?\n2. As I'm not the Chosen One, what could I do to find/attract a patron deity - for the more intense, devotional, mystical kind of connection? For when I am ready to go there again.\nI also just want to throw out a quick thanks to Violet. Her comments here about her relationship with Aphrodite in particular have been a help in this mess, in giving another perspective and sorting a few ideas out in my head. I've really appreciated reading them.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8526079", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's a long slow process. Regular practice of meditation and divination helps, but it's also important to cultivate the habit of ordinary reflective thinking, and trying your best to practice discernment in the rest of your life, so you'll have the habits in place when you approach the spiritual realm.\n2) You might wait for one to show up. That happens fairly often. Alternatively, read a lot of mythology and legends, and see what speaks to you.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8539391", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Re discernment:  judging from history, a good test is whether the god is telling you to do something you’d like to do anyway, e-g. Hitler thinking God told him to create a thousand-year Reich and eradicate world Jewry.  Didn’t work.\nIf God ‘s telling you to do something nobody in his right mind would want to do , e.g. go get yourself crucified, it’s probably legit.  Also, there’s at least one Biblical character who said, “Look, for all I know I’m going crazy.  If I’m going to do all this stuff you’re asking, please SHOW me beyond any doubt that you’re God.”  And God complied.\nRequests from Bacchus that you go out and get drunk remain a gray area.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8562687", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Ha!\nThough on that: there's the mitigating factor that, in a polytheist system, it seems like itd also be natural to be drawn to the gods whose service you'd find most pleasant and vice-versa. Aphrodite and Hermes have thrown some curveballs my way, granted, but nothing *near* the square-peg-round-hole unpleasantness I'd get from trying to take, say, Hera or Apollo as a patron.\nThough you're right that even there, what I think of as word from the gods is generally pretty \"huh, I wouldn't have thought of that!\" rather than what I was wanting/planning to do beforehand.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8560127", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "violetcabra", "content": "You're most welcome -- I'm so delighted that what I wrote has been helpful in your process!", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8574463", "title": "discernment", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "What JMG says in comment 1) is fundamental.\nI'd like to add my own two cents, writing from a perspective of about forty-five years of participation in coven-centered wiccanate witchcraft, from the more neopagan (feminist Dianic witchcraft) to the more systematic and rule-bound (Gardnerian Wicca), and including a regional mystery tradition that is\nsui generis\n.\nAt some point you might feel a need to dip your toes into group work again, or want to participate in a community in a less intensive way than by joining a group. You will probably be worried about making the same mistakes again, or getting into some other kind of trouble. If you have developed discernment (about people, groups, ideas, goals and entities), you will be much quicker at sizing up people and the opportunities that may be presented to you. You are no longer naive. You are developing your will, your self knowledge and your psychic abilities. You are probably getting better already at noticing when you are being led in a particular direction. You are getting the tools to figure out who or what is doing the leading.\nIf the time comes when you want to return to group work, you might get the best benefit from one of two types. One would be a formal hierarchical group with a set cirricultum and a visible boundary between what is part of the system and what is not. JMG has written books presenting several systems of that type. If you join a group that claims to be working a system, whether it's a form of Druidry or British Traditional Wica or some other thing, keep an eye out for whether their behavior matches their pretensions, and how people advance to positions of authority.\nAnother possibility is that you will find your passion in a specific kind of magical work and then will need to find companions to compare notes with, watch each other's backs, and fill in the gaps in each other's knowledge and skills. To assemble a group of this kind, you will probably need to do some magic or prayer, certainly some divination, and make agreements with the people who turn up to the call, in order to set boundaries on what you do and what connections you form with each other. In that instance, you likely will be doing experimental work, and experimental work requires keeping records of results and doing peer review.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8497919", "title": "reprise: astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Hello JMG, commentariot.\nContinuing my query from last week regarding whether my natal chart might explain my lifelong perplexing social experiences of unintentional invisibility...\nSun in Sagittarius.\nmy first house is empty.\nmy rising sign is Cancer.\nThe Moon is in Aquarius, in house 7, not dignified. Her aspects are:\nsextile Mercury, Neptune;\ntrine Jupiter, Uranus, Pluto;\nin opposition to the Ascendant.\nHaving read about these aspects on popular-astrology-type sites I am none the wiser as they seem to be indicators of charisma, leadership talent, etc: things which I might have in an inverted way but not manifestly.\nDoes this give enough to answer my question?\nThank you again, I read with great pleasure and am always enlightened by the discussions on this site.\nkallianeira.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8521727", "title": "Re: reprise: astrological markers", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Well, if your Moon is absent from home, so to speak; and is, in fact, way the heck over on the other side of the chart, as far as it can get from being seen by the outside world, plus in an air sign famous for being nondemonstrative emotionally, it is no wonder that people do not notice your presence in the room. It is like having an invisibility cloak or at least a talent for personal obscurity. Your moon is like a hermit crab, withdrawn into its seashell, on purpose, so nobody can see it. Nope, nothing to see here, just move along folks. Was it too vulnerable in its last life, one wonders; so now it is trying out the cool airy side of life?\nBTW, why is not the Opposition poised in Capricorn where it usually would be? Sitting right on the cusp or something like that? A loose orb? Because, a bit of cold, practical Earth would not come amiss in your situation! A place to ground out a lightning rod in the likely event of unusual shocks in your emotional arena. And steer clear of stormy scenes. If ya know what I mean...?\nAnyway, your Moon is in the Cloud of the Crowd that the Water Bearer is carrying across the sky.\nYour Moon Balloon is lightly tethered to your thoughts and dreams, drifting in and out of illusions of inner space. You are carrying a lightweight cargo basket with some fossil fuel to burn that gives you additional lift and easy maintenance of your expansive notions.You've been lucky so far, but I think you might want to latch onto old Saturn to learn proper launch and landing procedures in a strange land. Do this before you are carried out over the ocean with no compass.\nYour Sun wishes to travel and be freeeee (wheee!) most likely. But unless you are going undercover as an invisible spy, it would be safer to secure some Saturnian sandbag ballast, a detailed Virgoan map, and a little Arian drone to send out on scouting expeditions. Practice with it till you know how to gauge and cope with sudden shifts in air currents. Journal your moods; they may be your best barometer of social atmospheres and interpersonal weather forecasting.\nYou may be the woolly, curlyhaired Belgian sheepdog that leads the sheep by looking like one of the crowd but having a higher guide to direct your movements. Wolf-like sheepdogs nip at the heels of the sheep, behaving like predators; Bouviers gently lead by going out ahead and ambling along with seeming purposeslessness. Blending in will suit your secret agenda better than standing out.\nScarlet Eldritch Eel of Rio (the SEER)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8539903", "title": "Re: reprise: astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Thank you for your most kind, perceptive, poetic and thoughtful comments, Scarlet Eldritch Eel!\nWhy is the Moon not in Capricorn? - she inched over into Aquarius, at less than a minute of arc in fact, in the same way that I held on tightly for a week so as to make it over the cusp into Sagittarius.\nAs for Saturn, perhaps I have not been so lucky so far... he is retrograde and in fall in Aries. We have had a difficult relationship. Your words are encouragement towards keeping up the effort to improve it.\nkallianeira.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8551679", "title": "Re: reprise: astrological markers", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ah! Retrograde Saturn IS your ballast, and he is sitting on the head of oft impulsive Aries. Retrograde just means 'slow down' and 'think harder, delve deeper.' It drags you down and back a bit which is rather helpful under the circs. Saturn in your 9th-10th house? Education-Career something to do with the Army, perhaps? What's Mars up to? I suppose he's over in Leo trying to stir up some action? Urging the King to go to war and let him be the general in the field?  Do you feel you need to take charge and get urgent prompts to assert yourself? Or, if not, see what his relationship is to Saturn. Maybe he could use some discipline and steady effort in his House towards achieving an objective to satisfy his thirst for me-first and drive for power. Tricky, but doable and it will take a lot of T-I-M-E, that dirty four-letter word Aries hates. (Hope this off-the-cuff stuff is helpful?)", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8526335", "title": "Re: reprise: astrological markers", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The ruler of your first house is in opposition to your ascendant, and you have nothing else in that house. That right there would do it: your first house is your identity, so the ruler of your identity is in opposition to your identity! \"Self-erasure\" would be a good description of that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8538879", "title": "Re: reprise: astrological markers", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "Yes, that opposition. It looked significant.\nMany thanks for clarifying this.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8498431", "title": "Getting up early for magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do many people here get up early to do rituals at the first planetary hour of the day?\nI seem to remember reading one or two other posters talking about this here in the past.\nHow much does it matter? Last week, I was unhappy that I'd accidentally slept in, because the alarm had been set for the right time on a different day, and missed the first planetary hour. As the ritual was important to me, I wasn't sure about doing it in the afternoon, with the sun slightly past its zenith. So I left it until the following week, but I wondered and worried if I had missed out on something by missing the first week of the waxing moon? This is for one of those rituals of lighting a candle on a given day for several weeks.\nSometimes I am still tired at that time and I am not sure which matters more, for it to be first thing in the morning, or to be more alert.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8526591", "title": "Re: Getting up early for magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm not a morning person, so I pretty much always do things on the second or third repeat of the planetary hour corresponding to the day. It doesn't seem to hinder the effectiveness to do the work in the afternoon or evening.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8498687", "title": "Not sure what to make of this", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I came across this article last week and thought it might make an interesting addition to the Magic Monday conversation: \"Belief in Aliens Could Be America's Next Religion.\"\nhttps://getpocket.com/explore/item/belief-in-aliens-could-be-america-s-next-religion\nI wonder if this is a serious prospect or just another religious Flavor of the Month for people ever in search of the new and novel.\nBeekeeper in Vermont", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8526847", "title": "Re: Not sure what to make of this", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Somebody's ***way*** behind the times. Belief in the Space Brothers was a big deal in the 1950s, and while it's still around, it's been in the diminuendo phase for a long time.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8498943", "title": "Magic and addiction", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG!\nI'd like to ask if there's any way in which magic can help deal with/overcome addiction and other self-destructive habits. Any guidance would be much appreciated, thanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8527871", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, but it's not a quick fix. The magical structure of addiction is that it's a division of the will: you want the object of the addiction, but you don't want to want it, and so you end up locked into a self-perpetuating cycle of trying to resist the addiction, failing, hating yourself for failing, trying again, and around you go.\nTo get out of the cycle you have to rebuild unity of will. The first step is to stop fighting and start managing. Stop pretending that you're in control of it, and stop telling other people or yourself that you'll stop, when you won't.  Accept that you have the addiction and that you can't white-knuckle it into submission. See what you can do to manage it so that it does the least possible harm to other people. While you're doing that, spend some time journaling to see what emotional needs of yours the addiction meets -- very often there are all kinds of tangled emotional patterns tied up in it.\nOnce you've done this, look for other parts of your life -- completely unrelated to the addiction, and without any strong emotional loading at all -- where you can begin working on strengthening your will. Start deciding to do certain things for no reason at all, and then do them. For example, decide to notice every red thing you pass on the way to work. On your next day off -- assuming that the quarantine has been lifted! -- decide to go somewhere in town that you've never been, choose a time to be there, and be there on time. Choose a subject you know nothing about -- the history of Albania, say -- and learn about it. Make a game of it. Don't include anything about which you have strong feelings; keep it playful, calm, interesting.\nYour daily magical practices are important here, too. Schedule them so that your addiction doesn't interfere with them, and vice versa. Keep on doing them. That's excellent will training all by itself.\nAs you continue in this way, you'll notice first of all that it becomes a lot easier for you to do things you choose to do, even when they're difficult. It also becomes easier for you to manage your addiction, and to make it even less of a burden on other people. Don't assault it directly; just keep on managing, willing, practicing, getting the rest of your life in order. Over time you'll find that the addiction matters less and less to you. You may suddenly realize that it's been a week since you last did whatever it is, and you hadn't noticed! That's what real recovery looks like.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8540159", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "a) So of course any attempt to go cold turkey is extremely counterproductive. Do you think it's a deliberate effort on someone's part to keep the idea cold turkey is the only way to go so widespread?\nb) Here's an odd one: I've got an internet addiction. From what you've said, it would make sense for me to tackle it in an odd manner: ignoring the more destructive elements, and slowly whittling it down by targeting the stuff which I do so as to justify why I need it; I have a good sense of what I'm addicted to, and a lot of internet doesn't count. Does this make sense?\nc) Is this part of why so many people relapse later? As much as they wanted the recovery, they still want whatever it is they were addicted to?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8542719", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Exactly. Miserable people buy more products.\n2) Yes, you could do it that way. The goal is to manage the addiction, not to justify it.\n3) Exactly -- and they still have whatever emotional needs the addiction addressed.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8544255", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "1) Of course it's corporate influence.....", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8547071", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hmm. Is procrastination then the result of wanting to want something? You want to want it, but you don't actually, so the result is a self defeating pattern where you try to do something, then don't, because you don't actually want it, and then rinse and repeat and you have a procrastination problem....", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8549631", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's one very definite way you can get a procrastination problem. Another is that if you've spent your childhood being told that whatever you do isn't good enough and doesn't, ahem, \"live up to your potential\" -- gods, I hated those words -- you can simply learn not to try, because you get just as much grief either way and if you don't try you won't have invested anything emotionally in the effort. It took me years of hard work to get past that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8562431", "title": "Re: Magic and addiction", "user": "isabelcooper", "content": "Here (with margarita) to chime in on the hatred for \"work up to potential.\" Being a demon child, I always got super snarky about that: like, what exactly would that get *me* except more work? And what if I need that potential later?", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8499455", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nA triad today :)\n1) Original\nThe View over Atlantis\nversus\nThe New View over Atlantis\n?\n2) I've seen a name in association with W.E. Butler.  What is you opinion of Dolores Ashcroft-Nowicki and her writings?\n3) I'm presently reading\nThe Meaning of Masonry\nby W.L. Wilmshurst.  The journey of the soul from the East to the West and back again sounds suspiciously similar to the descending arc and ascending arcs we've been discussing in\nThe Cosmic Doctrine\n(and which I've also been reading about in Barborka's\nThe Divine Plan\n).  Since there are no coincidences, I'm assuming this is not one...\n--David BTL (Crimson Eldritch Raccoon)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8528639", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) They both have their virtues. I like the original, but that's for sentimental reasons.\n2) Dolores is an amazing person, and one of the most potent ceremonial magicians I've ever done ritual with. Most of her books aren't relevant to the specific kinds of magic I practice, but the few I've worked with have been very solid.\n3) That's even less of a coincidence than most...\n-- Taupe Squamous Stoat", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8499711", "title": "cell salt experiment", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG-\nI have a quick question on the cell salt experiment. I got a late start, haven't made it to the first cycle of extra salts, but have been doing the bioplasma daily. But, cell salts are my go-to for, well, pretty much everything that ails me, so is it going to throw off the experiment for me if, for example, take calc phos and calc sulph semi-daily to deal with seasonal allergies this week? Or whatever else I need in addition to the experiment?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8528895", "title": "Re: cell salt experiment", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I hope not -- I use cell salts as my go-to for home health care, and as far as I know, so did Dr. G.W. Carey!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8500223", "title": "Astrology and Egypt", "user": "sophronismos", "content": "Do you happen to know the name of a astrology publisher based in Indianapolis whose founder was well known in the twentieth century for his writings about Egypt? I encountered them once in the 1990s but cannot remember the name.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8529407", "title": "Re: Astrology and Egypt", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, I don't -- and it sounds like something I'd like to know about. Anyone?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8554239", "title": "Re: Astrology and Egypt", "user": "sophronismos", "content": "I applied for a job there once, and they were very interesting; but the building was a firetrap, with papers and magazines piled up all over the place and several employees chain-smoking during my interview. I decided not to work there at the time, but when I decided to look them up again I couldn't find any information about them.\nIn the interim I had also forgotten the names of their flagship publication and the founder. All I can recall now is that they told me he had started in Chicago and that he was an expert on Egyptian occult history.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8554495", "title": "Re: Astrology and Egypt", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Hmm! No, that doesn't bring anything to mind.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8561919", "title": "Re: Astrology and Egypt", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "you might try browsing old editions of Writer's Digest guide to publishers--sorry, can't recall exact title. They index publishers by genre for the guidance of freelance writers looking for a market.\nRita", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8500479", "title": "Sphere of protection", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've started the Dolmen Arch, and have been using the suggested names of the druid gods, but didn't you list a set on angelic names that could be used? I seem to recall that but flipping back through previous entries I don't find it...going off the cantrefs, would it be Metatron, Sandalphon, Gabriel, and Raphael? Assuming one was facing south...", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8529663", "title": "Re: Sphere of protection", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "The angelic names were listed in a discussion a while back. These are the ones I'd use:\nEast - Raphael\nWest - Gabriel\nSouth - Michael\nNorth- Uriel\nBelow - Sandalphon\nAbove - Metatron", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8500735", "title": "tsw", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "HI John\nI kind of had at TSW moment this weekend.\nI had been thinking about how this year really is shaping up to be big transition, just like astrology has predicted with the Grand Mutation.  When I recalled a series of posts you did about how The Changer is working his way up river to its source.  And the Trumps election was a sign of this god becoming more active in our lives.\nAnd if moving up river to its source is a metaphor, the river is related to how we live our lives, and moving to the source of the river means ever more basic changes to how we live our lives.   With this pandemic The Changer is greatly deepening  the change, and how we end up responding to the pandemic will further and deepen the changes.  (I am so glad we have The Changer rather than Odin loose upon the land.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8529919", "title": "Re: tsw", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "This stuff works indeed. Keep changing!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8501503", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nWho were the mysterious \"Sea Peoples\"?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8531199", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "They aren't mysterious at all. Toward the end of the bronze age, societies north of the eastern Mediterranean had a population boom driven by the spread of intensive farming methods from Mesopotamia. The problem was that those farming methods depended on fertilization by river silt, which you didn't get much of in Greece and points north. The result was a subsistence crisis -- severe soil erosion (so bad that it left recognizable layers in the sediments of the Aegean Sea), disastrous crop failures, the kind of conditions that lead warriors to take desperate risks. Furthermore, the northern peoples had good ships, and a lot of warriors from there had served as mercenaries in the eastern Mediterranean cultures, and understood the weaknesses of the high-tech (for the time) chariot armies of their former employers.\nRobert Drews' very solid book\nThe End of the Bronze Age\nchronicles what happened thereafter: tentative initial probings, followed by mass raids that sacked city after city along the eastern Mediterranean coast. The Hittite Empire ceased to exist, and so did dozens of other nations that had thrived for centuries. Finally the Sea Peoples launched a sreries of assaults on the biggest prize of all, Egypt -- but the Egyptians were ready for them. The Egyptian generals abandoned chariot warfare and raised a massive infantry army armed with spears and shields, met the Sea Peoples in a series of major battles, and crushed them. Surviving Sea Peoples fled to the far corners of the Mediterranean, and most of the Mediterranean world sank into a long and bitter dark age.\n(If you're wondering why I had all this at my fingertips, I studied the late Bronze Age collapse extensively in the process of researching my novel\nTwilight's Last Gleaming\n-- it's one of the best examples on record of what I call asymmetric tactical shock, a process by which a less technologically advanced army monkeywrenches the more advanced technology of the enemy and renders the enemy helpless. An essay I wrote on the subject, \"Asymmetric Tactical Shock; A First Reconnaissance\" is included in my book of essays\nBeyond the Narratives\n.)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8539647", "title": "COVID-19 as asymmetric tactical shock", "user": "slclaire", "content": "Considering what something that scientists aren't convinced is alive is doing to what we think of as technologically advanced societies in terms of understanding of human health, the analogy of COVID-19 to asymmetic tactical shock seems close.\n-- Sepia Hibernating Sheep", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8542975", "title": "Re: COVID-19 as asymmetric tactical shock", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "There's a definite equivalence.\n-- Fuchsia Apoplectic Weasel", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8501759", "title": "Couple geomantic questions", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG! Thanks for doing these every Monday!\nI have a couple questions.\n1. Sam Block over on his digitalambler blog has come up with a version of the Qabbalistic Cross. The discussion of it can be found in these two articles (he mentions this blog as a catalyst for his exploration):\nhttps://digitalambler.com/2020/04/07/the-geomancers-cross-the-framework-behind-the-ritual/\n(https://digitalambler.com/2020/04/07/the-geomancers-cross-the-framework-behind-the-ritual/) and\nhttps://digitalambler.com/2020/04/08/the-geomancers-cross-the-motions-and-the-prayer/\n(https://digitalambler.com/2020/04/08/the-geomancers-cross-the-motions-and-the-prayer/). In regards to this, I have been doing a semi-daily SOP and I find I do not have a strong connection to the Druid deities, but I do have a strong connection to Geomancy and its figures. I was thinking of adapting this approach to the Elemental Cross in my SOP practice. What are your thoughts on this?\n2. As I've gotten deeper into Geomancy I find that I can see multiple meanings in the placement of a figure in the houses, such as how a figure relates not only to the querent, but also to other people or things in a querent's life, represented by its relationship to other houses. For example, Acquisitio in the 8th could mean that the querent will have good success in magical rituals, but it could also mean that the querent's wife will come into money. Or Tristitia in the 11th could mean that the querent will have a negative interaction with one of his friends, but could also point to the querent's cat getting sick. As I think and meditate about these different scenarios, I get the feeling that there are certain energies in the world that always play out in similar ways and tie things together. So if the energies of the world are opening up doors for success in ritual magic, those same energies are opening up doors for material success for the querent's significant other. Is this a good way of thinking about it? What are your thoughts on how these different scenarios can be present in a reading? (this would seem to apply not only to Geomantic readings, but to many forms of astrology and other divinatory practices as well)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8531711", "title": "Re: Couple geomantic questions", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's a good solid ritual, and it's pleasant to see someone doing this sort of creative work based on a firm understanding of the traditional lore. If you want to try that as part of your SoP work, by all means give it a spin.\n2) Yes, that's a very helpful way of thinking about it. It's as though you have a specific energy -- Acquisitio, say -- which can flow along many different pathways. That opens up the possibility of magical work to redirect the flow this way or that, but it also stresses the importance of asking a precise question for the oracle to answer!", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8502015", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Pentagram rituals have Lesser, Greater and Supreme levels. What extra things do the higher levels do?\nDoes the Sphere of Protection have escalating levels like that?\nIn some rituals you imagine energy going down one side of your body and up the other. Are there any asymmetric effects from it always going in the same direction every time?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8531967", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The Lesser RP is for general use. The Greater RPs invoke and banish specific elemental forces; the Supreme RP invokes Spirit.\n2) No. Different systems work in different ways.\n3) No, because when you're not practicing the working the energy flows in your body can balance things out.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8503039", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nDo you know of any good book that relates the \"seven principles\" in the Kybalion to other concepts in Hermeticism, like Qabalah or tarot?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8532223", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No, that's one of the many good books on traditional occultism that nobody's gotten around to writing yet.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8503551", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Two rather disparate things. :)\nI’ve seen this a couple times recently: friends or family of an atheist want to do religious things to said atheist or atheist’s kid (pray for them or baptise the child are the examples coming to mind). The atheist is uncomfortable with this but also figures it doesn’t matter because, as they believe, the religious practice isn’t doing anything. That’s incorrect... right? My instinct is to answer “no, don’t allow the religious thing to be done insofar as you can say no, because it creates a tie and/or obligation to that god or religion.” What’s your take on religious obligations again, and the consequences of them if one follows or doesn’t follow through?\nAlso, I devoured all of the Weird of Hali series and the Shoggoth Concerto, and am currently rereading Innsmouth because I wanted to hang out with the characters and world again. So thank you for an excellent series, and I can confirm that it stands up well to rereading!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8532479", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) The atheist is wrong, but if you're an atheist you can't allow the possibility that there could actually be gods or spiritual forces, so I doubt you'll get far. Religious obligations matter if you take them willingly; an infant who's baptized has a permanent connection to the energies of the Christian egregor but no moral responsibility to that egregor, while an adult who accepts baptism will face blowback if he or she then walks away.\n2) You're welcome and thank you! I'm delighted to hear this.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8560383", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Don't do it!\nBest case: Atheist is right, it's all a bunch of poppycock. And he'd be participating in a humongous lie. Whether you believe in higher powers or not, It is self-evident that lying does nasty things to your character.\nOn the other hand, if he's wrong...   most churches won't baptize children (outside medical emergency situations) without the parents committing to raising that child in the church, and in the knowledge and service of Christ. There is no way that making that kind of commitment to God, when you have no intention of fulfilling it, could be a good, or even neutral thing. It's deliberate fraud, and extremely disrespectful.\nIn my church, there is a general feeling that getting baptised (which in Orthodoxy makes you a full communicant member of the church-- it's not a half-step like with Catholics), and then leaving the faith, is *worse* than if you had never been baptized at all. For this reason, at many churches, the general attitude toward would-be converts is \"Eh. Wait a while. Make sure you know what you're getting into, and that you're really ready.\" Many priests will not baptize grandchildren: if the parents aren't members in good standing and fully onboard, how can you honestly commit to raising this child in the church?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8503807", "title": "Interesting", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "https://www.strategic-culture.org/news/2020/04/30/big-pharma-beware-dr-montagnier-shines-new-light-on-covid-19-and-the-future-of-medicine/\nI thought you all might find this article interesting on several levels. My initial take, and subject for much meditation, is that water does indeed disolve etheric energy, and may be able to suspend and \"copy\" prana/DNA.\nIt may be one of the best cases of science confirming magic that I've come across.\nTangerine Orthogonal Opossum", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8532735", "title": "Re: Interesting", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting indeed. -- Scarlet Radiant Sheep.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8504063", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Have you ever taken a break from your magical practice to deal with health issues? I presume the most minimalist practice in general would be prayer and meditation and then each individual must judge for themselves what they are able to take on additionally.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8533247", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've never been sick enough that I couldn't at least do a banishing ritual, a session of discursive meditation, and a divination. If that's beyond your reach due to health issues, by all means figure out what you can do, and stay within your limits.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8504319", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "What are the effects on the process of individualization of a personality who tends to spend a lot of time daydreaming or being lost in thought while doing mundane activities? Is this person constantly stuck on the astral plane? Or is this tendency simply a sign of a lack of mental focus and wakefulness?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8534527", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It really varies from case to case. It may be an attempt to flee an unsatisfactory material life; it may be just a lack of focus; it may be a talent for astral vision developed in a previous life and not yet disciplined in this one.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8549887", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello,\nHow can a person start to develop their astral vision?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8550655", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "W.E. Butler's book\nHow to Read the Aura, Practice Psychometry, Telepathy, and Clairvoyance\ngives good basic exercises for that purpose.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8505087", "title": "Circulation of light SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nI open my SOP in the garden every morning and close it, usually in the garden, every evening before meditation.  Recently, I have been circulating the light after the invoking phase and then again at the banishing phase.  It seems to be working well.  Would you say this is a good practice or should I only circulate the lights at the end of the banishing phase?\nThanks,\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8534783", "title": "Re: Circulation of light SOP", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Interesting. I don't think I've heard of anyone else trying that, so I don't know if it's a good idea or not.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8540415", "title": "Re: Circulation of light SOP", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I will keep trying it as it seems to be working and let you know how it goes.\nMaxine", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8505343", "title": "Shared dreaming", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG,\nContinued thanks for hosting this space!\nA close colleague and I experienced a shared dream recently. It has happened in the past, as has an instance where I experienced my colleague's thoughts in my dream while the thinking happened during my colleague's simultaneous waking activity in a time zone 13 hours apart. Can you help me understand how this works and whether (and if so, how) to cultivate the phenomenon?\nThanks!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8535039", "title": "Re: Shared dreaming", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Dreams are one of the ways we interact with the astral plane, and shared dreams and dream telepathy are known phenomena -- the old psychical researchers used to document cases by the ream. The exact mechanism isn't known to me, but it'll involve resonance between the astral bodies of the two people in question. W.E. Butler's\nHow to Read the Aura, Practice Psychometry, Telepathy, and Clairvoyance\nmight be a good source of exercises to build on that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8505855", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG Thanks as always for MM !\n3 questions on the \"5 Tibetans\"\n1/ When doing the \"Rites \"  is it useful to concentrate on the appropriate Vortexes ?\nKelders text does indicate that some Rites affect  different Vortexes.\nNow I know you'll say \"Try and see !\"\nBut that leads me to the vortex positions\n2'/ A few weeks ago here on MM you said that Kelder's placement of the 4th Vortes is a mistake and that it should be on the left side (Spleen cake ) not on the right,  With my professional hat on this makes sense but please would you expand on that.\nwhich leads to\n3/   Evidently you have some idea of where the Vortex placement came from ?  Again please expand on that.too.\nLastly an OT comment.\nI finally realised you were right  a while.ago\nTalking to friends here and in the US I see that what drives TDS is largely acute embarrassment !\nA friend said \"I know he's killed less people than Obama, but at least Obama didn't talk like THAT!\"\nIndigo Eldrich Wolverine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8535295", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) I've never seen this point discussed. You'll want to experiment.\n2) The spleen center is discussed at quite some length in early 20th century occult literature. It's the center by which life energy from the sun is drawn into the subtle body.\n3) There's a specific set of American occult schools that focused on energy centers not aligned with the spine -- yes, those seven. Several Rosicrucian schools used them. I'm pretty sure that \"Peter Kelder\" (probably not his real name) got his teaching from some such source, and developed the Rites based on his experimentation with the centers.\nOT: embarrassment, or perhaps class prejudice...", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8506367", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Hello JMG, a quick question today from Citrine Hibernating Platypus.\nCould you give us an operative definition of what exactly you mean by \"Occult Philosophy.\" This can come off as rather vague can and mean many things to many different people.\nDoes Occult Philosophy imply a sort of unity of opinion on key occult topics? And if so, do you have a basic bibliography in mind that could illustrate such a consensus?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8535551", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent. Why am I using a deliberately vague term like that, and what is it meant to encourage you to do?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8538367", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "causticus", "content": "Haha, well the answer becomes painfully obvious when you put it like that =D\nAnd ... suddenly I had a quick 2 minute meditation session on what differentiates doctrinal religion from occultism.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8543231", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My work here is done. Bwahahaha!", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8506623", "title": "cocoa magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Dear JMG and Gang,\nI learned to make chocolate from scratch last week. Someone a few months ago wrote about cocoa magic when they meant something else.  Since then, the idea of cocoa magic has stuck with me.\nNow, I know how to make chocolates natural magic style.  I would just put in magic foods such as rose petals, honey and spices to achieve my ends.\nWould it also be possible to use the magic of making talismans to make chocolates?  Would it be a good idea to eat a talisman?\nHow about enchanting the finished chocolates in an open Grove and charge them with the quality desired?\nHas anyone tried this?  Did it work?  Got recipes to share?\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8535807", "title": "Re: cocoa magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's the basic logic behind communion rituals. I don't know of anybody who's done that with chocolate, though!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8540671", "title": "Re: cocoa magic", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Would that be the enchanting them in a grove or doing the talisman work to prepare chocolate for communion?\nMaxine", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8543487", "title": "Re: cocoa magic", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Try it both ways and see which gives you the best results. (How's that for an excuse to eat a lot of chocolate?)\n;-)", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8506879", "title": "experience of the inner worlds exercise", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hello JMG,\nGareth Knight introduces a series of exercises for the reader in his \"Experience of the inner worlds\",\nthe exercise for chapter three involves a flame that rises along the spine into the cranium. Knight warns: \"the practice of this exercise may well bring some emotional disturbance into the daily life in the beginning\", he likens it to Kundalini-Yoga in an earlier paragraph.\nWhat kind of emotional disturbance is to be expected? Is this some kind of karmic culmination?\nDoes it result from things that might happen in my life, e.g. being depressed because of losing one's job or the sudden loss of a pet? Or is a purely emotional response without an external cause, e.g. suddenly feeling sad while everything external in my life keeps humming along nicely?\nThank you!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8536063", "title": "Re: experience of the inner worlds exercise", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It depends on what kind of emotional business you have that you're not dealing with. The more of your emotional life you suppress or ignore, the rougher it's going to be. In my experience this sort of thing rarely involves drastic life events -- it's more like wild mood swings unconnected to what's happening in your life.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8507135", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "JMG,\nI've been reflecting lately on how futile all of the attempts at changing the course of human civilization have been in the last 50 years. Here we are, accelerating towards disaster, our cultural institutions discredited and in freefall, with the current pandemic as a slap on the wrist, a warning sign of what's to come, and yet the only thought on most people's minds is how to kickstart the economy again and resume business as usual. Clearly, political ideology and activism has failed, technology has failed, capitalism has failed, the media has failed. There seems to be no off-ramp on the road we've set ourselves on, at least none that we could realistically take.\nI think the fundamental problem is one of belief - our model of reality is flawed, and our behavior is derived from that. We believe in a closed and disempowering material universe, in a natural world that is blind and unintelligent, in reductionistic political ideologies, in the rationality of our economic system based on infinite growth on a finite planet, and in the sovereignty of the 'individual' to do as he pleases. We can't imagine acting otherwise, so we don't. So the problem is: how do you get people to change their minds? If only you could catalyze a change of perspective, and spread that throughout the population, everything else would flow from that, from the bottom up, because you can't bring about radical change through persuasion from the top down while maintaining the current set of assumptions; that's been tried and it doesn't work. A handful of exceptional individuals can go against the grain and change their behavior, but the mass of humanity will go along with the herd until the end, and if those few individuals become a threat they will be neutralized rather than be allowed to become examples. Some kind of global training course in magic would be desirable, but the political will is nonexistent, the ideological high priests would be opposed to it, and it would take far too long to have any effects.\nSo we need something else. Lecturing won't do it. PR campaigns aren't enough. Technology will be co-opted by special interests. Politics is irredeemably corrupt. The religions that have organizational clout are impotent. Institutional science has become a sock-puppet for corporatist technocratic interests. The only hope, as I see it, is a mass psychedelic experience. It's the only thing that will work quickly enough and on a large enough scale, and which isn't tied to mechanisms of central control. We need to organize something like a World LSD Day, a simultaneous 8-billion person trip that will bring us back to nature, that will dissolve the mass hallucination that we're trapped in. I'm aware of the echo of the 60's here, but I don't see any other viable options on the table. Under proper supervision, responsible use of psychedelics can have ego- and boundary-dissolving effects, which is what we most need. And I'm not talking about saving our current living arrangements, because that's clearly impossible, but about demobilizing in time to prevent us from slamming into a wall, and transitioning to something sustainable. But the change in perspective has to come first.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8518143", "title": "hmmm...", "user": "kallianeira", "content": "(with your permission, JMG,)\nAs for psychedelic solutions, it is possible you have come across (JMG's onetime recommendation of) a novel from those open-minded 1960s, \"Davy\"?\nGood story! -- which proposes not a chemically mediated change of perspective but a league of heretics who encourage one another's thinking and actions in the direction of alternatives to the oppressive status quo. Nothing like this forum, of course. No connection. Uh-uh.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8536575", "title": "Re: hmmm...", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Of course not. No connection at all.\n;-)", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8536319", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Has it occurred to you that history's going the way it is for good reason, and the reason that it's not changing course is that it's supposed to work out the way it is?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8507391", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Last week you wrote that marriage is much more magically powerful than most people realize. How?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8536831", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It's a very old and well-established ritual by which two people pledge to make a life together. The egregor of the standard marriage ceremony is very robust, by sheer repetition!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8559359", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just musing, but reading this reminded me about having read before about the origin of the white wedding dress in Queen Victoria's wedding.\nI just went to search for a bit more about Queen Victoria's wedding: https://www.historyextra.com/period/victorian/royal-wedding-queen-victoria-prince-albert-dress-cake-1840/\nVictoria's wedding seems to be the prototype for the typical Western wedding, and I think it was a success for her, her husband, and her reign. But it seems like moderns neglect some of the details that were factors in her success while over-emphasizing others like the outward appearance?\nFor example, rather than having bridesmaids born of mothers of \"spotless character\", they opt for spotless bridesmaids costumes.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8507647", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi, Thanks again for hosting this!  Also I have pre-ordered your UFO book, and cant' wait to see what you've added.  It really opened my eyes when I first read it, so thanks again for that too!\nBut as for my question:  Over on the other blog you mentioned that the bizarre, self-defeating behavior of the Democrats can be explained partially by the kek-worshipping chaos mages of the alt-right deciding not to rest on their laurels, and have arguably tightened up their operation since 2016.  Could you speculate on what exactly might be going on there?  As in, what sort of workings would they be doing, or what effects that might have in the long run?  Would this also have to do with the collapse of the credibility of the media, on the left and the right?  Also, what would the \"Kek\" entity(or whatever is using that symbol as a vehicle) want out of this, or have in mind?\nI completely understand if you don't care to engage in speculation, but I value your speculations highly!", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8537343", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't have any direct knowledge of what's going on in that end of Kekistan, because the alt-right mages understand -- as their opponents on the left do not -- that secrecy is the foundation of effective magic, and also of effective strategy of any kind. My guess, based on what's happening, is that after 2016 proved to them that TSW, some of the alt-right mages took up serious study of magical traditions more robust than chaos magic. Which traditions?  Good question.  I know I have alt-right readers -- some of them have outed themselves, and I've also seen my name pop up on alt-right websites where I lurk from time to time -- and so Golden Dawn magic, hoodoo, and the astrological magic of the Picatrix will have been options they'll have known about; of course there are plenty of other resources and traditions as well.\nHow that will play out and what the consequences will be depends on what they're trying to do:\na) If they're doing the smart and effective thing, and concentrating on sending positive forces to Trump and the American egregor rather than using any kind of negative magic, they'll likely win big, without significant blowback. I'm pretty sure that this is part of what's going on -- the way that Trump keeps on popping up right side up and smiling no matter what the Democrats throw at him is typical of that sort of working. Still, that's not all that's going on -- the bizarre behavior of the Democrats suggests something rather darker.\nb) They could be doing workings for justice. That's potent magic, and it would certainly explain why the Democrats are busy blowing up their own credibility by going back on all their purported ideals -- watching #BelieveAllWomen get dropped like a hot rock now that women are accusing Biden is poetic justice with a finely honed edge. It's dangerous, because if you do a justice working you can expect to have to pay the price for all your own injustices, too, but if you accept that in advance that's an option.\nc) The option that worries me most is that some of them are doing serious malign magic directed at the Democrats, or at specific Democrats. That would explain Nancy Pelosi's bizarre behavior over the last few years -- there's a hoodoo product called Inflammatory Confusion Oil that could account for that, for example -- and quite a bit of the more general weirdness at work. Of course in that case there's going to be serious blowback, and it's an interesting question how that will play out. Of course the mages in question may have deliberately accepted the blowback; that's a very effective way to do malign magic, so long as you don't try to weasel out of it when the bill comes due.\nAs for the Changer -- the archetypal pattern I think is using them -- he wants things to be different, and apparently has a clear idea of what kind of difference he has in mind.\nAs I suggested in a blog post\n, there's a new, post-imperial America in the process of being born, and as long as the alt-right is pushing toward that birth, they're going to be more successful than those who are trying to maintain the imperial status quo at all costs.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8560639", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Is there something that makes the current crop of Democrats uniquely vulnerably to this sort of action, or could it be done to anyone?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8560895", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes and yes. Consider asking this next week; it would make for interesting discussions.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8561407", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "methylethyl", "content": "Duly noted.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8562175", "title": "Re: Kek and politics", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you very much!  This was very informative and I do look forward to next week.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8509951", "title": "More banishing", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Can concentrating on banishing big problems sometimes mean that smaller ones get through again? I had concentrated on certain smaller ones last year, and there were a few TSW moments with them at the time.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8543743", "title": "Re: More banishing", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, if you've banished the small problems rather than resolving them.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8513279", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Ok then... Hermann Hesse - your comment on ecosophia stirred something and I had to look after all his books that are sitting unread on my shelves. I was a little bit stunned when I finally found them for then I recalled how I got them. It's a used complete edition of Hesses work printed in the 70s or 80s. I got it as a present from my parents. One day (not too long ago, maybe a year or two) when my parents came to visit us, they just gave it to me. I know they had bought it long ago, probably before I was born and it was standing on their shelf for all the years. It was an highly unusual gift, for there was no obvious reason to make presents at that moment and even less reason to gift a used complete edition of Hermann Hesse. They never before gave old used books as a present (despite they have many) and I have never talked about let alone shown any interest in Hesse or his books.\nSo there is this little weird coincidence coming up right now when I started my \"past life memory exploration\" regarding which I asked you some questions over the last weeks. I'm regularly writing a journal on this issue and anything else that comes to my mind while writing. If I feel the need and the issue seems appropriate, I add geomancy readings. So this time I asked \"Has the work of Hermann Hesse any significance regarding memories of a past life?\" and I got this reading:\n1 - puer, 2 - rubeus, 3- albus, 4 - via, 5 - carcer, 6 - puer, 7 - fortuna major, 8 - carcer, 9 - carcer, 10 - puer, 11 - rubeus, 12 - amissio, rw - rubeus, lw - cauda draconis, j - amissio\nSo there is carcer in the houses 5, 9 and 8 which I'd consider relevant for the issue and as puer passes to 6 and 10 the chart perfects for all three houses either through conjunction (5 and 9) or mutation (8). I'd be very happy to hear your opinion on this - my interpretation roughly amounts to \"Yes, Hesses work is very significant. However, what lies behind this will remain concealed at least for now, since you approach the issue with more energy than skill (your comment on puer \"with no receptive inner life\" comes to my mind). This will continue for a while, (puer in 1 and 10) but eventually turn out to the best (fortuna major in 7) and result in transformation (via in 4)\". Sometime I have problems on whether a figure in a reading is to be interpreted descriptive or advisory. For example I'd could interpret carcer as advice \"leave that alone\". Given the nature of the question and that the geomantic intelligences are said to be very straight in their answers (and are as such as far as my experience goes), I'd say it's more likely the former interpretation?\nSo possibly it's time to read Hesse. Since you mentioned \"Das Glasperlenspiel\" over at the other blog, maybe that's a good starting point?\nGreetings,\nNachtgurke", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8543999", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Das Glassperlenspiel\nis Hesse's last, most complex, and most richly ironic novel; starting with that would really be jumping in the deep end of the pool first! I'd recommend instead starting with\nDemian\n, and then either\nSiddhartha\nor\nSteppenwolf\ndepending on whether you'd rather read a mystical parable or a fictionalized version of a successful Jungian psychoanalysis.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8515839", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nI was doing a candle working yesterday, using a white candle to send out blessing energy. It was a windy day, and towards the end of the six minutes a gust blew the candle out.\nWhat's the recommendation in a case like this? Is it a bad sign?\nThanks,\nCliff", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8544511", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "My recommendation? On a windy day, have the candle in some kind of candle lantern or screen to keep the wind from blowing it out.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8516095", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "John--\nOkay, I thought I was getting something of the hang of the shield chart, but I require assistance.  I saw the discussion up-thread regarding the traditional meanings of Rubeus and Populus as the First Mother.  When I cast that chart re the interdisciplinary master's program, I indeed had Populus as the First Mother.  The court was all positive, which was why I reached out to them, but my question was precisely that: \"Should I query WNMU re its MAIS program?\"  Nothing about whether or not I should apply...\nSo, I cast another chart just now, asking that question: \"Should I apply to WNMU's MAIS program?\"  I'll give you the whole shield chart:\nMothers (1-4): Via, Carcer, Carcer, Puella\nDaughters (1-4): Via, Laetitia, Carcer, Via\nNieces (1-4): Conjunctio, Albus, Caput Draconis, Conjunctio\nResulting in an odd (to me) court:\nRW Rubeus, LW Tristitia, J Acquisitio\nSo, I gain what I want, but I'm driven by passions rather than reason?  And how does Tristitia fit in?\nAny help you could provide would be appreciated.\n--David BTL (still Crimson Eldritch Raccoon, but I haven't checked yet)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8538111", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "As I thought on it more, I realized that 1) Tristitia is favorable for things requiring patience (which would apply, as this would be a project of 5-6 years) and 2) the Rubeus also refers to pleasure in passion (which might also apply, as this would be a project purely for the pleasure of scholarship).  Perhaps I’m just being thrown by the “bad” witnesses (understanding, of course that they’re not really bad per se) with a “good” judge.\nDavid BTL", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8544767", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "A good judge with bad witnesses is not a good sign. This suggests that you're pursuing this thing more out of some kind of emotional reaction than out of clear thinking (Rubeus), you'll be able to get the degree (Acquisitio), but you'll end up disappointed (Tristitia).", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8516351", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "And yet another question: Do you know where I can find translations of English occult terms into other languages, for example, German?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8545023", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I'm sorry to say I have no idea.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8558591", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Unironically at Wikipedia. If an English article on the subject is available in German, there is yoir answer. I use this trick all the time for all kinds of subjects, which yields way better results than dictionaries.\nA way that requires more work is to buy an English reference book,for example Greer's \"The Element Encyclopedia of Secret Societies\" and its German translation, „Enzyklopädie der Geheimlehren“.Then you compile your own dictionary, comparing the original with the translation.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8516863", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've recently been critically assessing the ideas which prevent me from achieving greatness, and realized there's a very simple thing which keeps a lot of people from achieving much of anything: the emphasis on sudden breakthroughs which dominate a lot of our culture.\nThey do occur, but they're rare, usually preceded by a long period of gradual change which builds up to a tipping point, and focusing on them to the exclusion of the more common slow and steady change prevents a lot of important things from being done, because they'll be \"too slow\". What do you make of the prevalence of this dysfunctional idea?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8545279", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Excellent! Yes, that's one of the narratives that keep people passive and miserable, and I tend to think that this is at least partly deliberate.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8517631", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "From an occultist perspective, what was the purpose of mummification?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8545535", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "That's a long and rather bitter story.\nA very long time ago, a specific set of practices was known by which a person could leave the cycle of reincarnation for a time in order to act as a guardian spirit for the living. That set of practices was certainly known from one end of Eurasia to the other; you can tell where it was practiced because it involved burial mounds -- big structures of stone covered by earth, in which the person went at the end of his or her life. (The stone and earth sheltered the etheric body from the rays of the sun.) The preservation of the physical body was essential to this, but that could be done -- as it was done in a few parts of the world until early modern times -- by a special diet alternating with longer and longer periods of fasting, which resulted in slow starvation and a body with basically nothing left that could rot.\nTime passed, cultures changed, and the technique was abused. In some places the method was lost and the practice turned into a rite of human sacrifice. In others, it was taken over by chieftains and kings who wanted to use it to cheat death. That's the condition it had reached by the time of historic Egypt, and mummification was used in place of the old dietary method to preserve the body. Later on, the rites became mere formalities, and people got themselves mummified at death in the same spirit that corpses nowadays get pumped full of formaldehyde.\nIn a very few places, the old system survived more or less intact. In some others, a debased and predatory version of it survived, and gave rise to the legends of vampires. I discuss this last phase of the tradition in my book\nMonsters\n.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8518911", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I recall reading here some guidelines about alcohol use and ritual magic. Specifically, that you should not consume alcohol (or have sex, I think) within a few hours of doing ritual magic (in my case, daily practice of the LBRP and Middle Pillar). Could you specify what those guidelines are? Is it  a safety issue, or more a matter of effectiveness?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8545791", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Don't practice magic when you're drunk, or even slightly impaired. It leaves you open to noxious entities.  (That's a good reason, if you drink, to do your practice first thing in the morning.)\nAs for sex, the rule there is the same as for food -- wait at least 30 minutes, or better still an hour, to let your subtle bodies settle back down to their ordinary state. That's just a matter of getting better results.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8519935", "title": "properly magic marriage", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey JMG!\nJust wanted to let you know I'm in the process of figuring out how to perform that Marriage I discussed in the last MM, without destructive symbolism. May have more questions on it in the future, but I just wanted to thank you and Deborah_Bender for sharing your experiences and offering advice!\nIf I run into any other big questions I'll be back!\nThanks again,\n-WindMan", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8546047", "title": "Re: properly magic marriage", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Delighted to hear it.", "replies": []}, {"id": "cmt8573951", "title": "Re: properly magic marriage", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "You are welcome. Have fun.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8521215", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "booklover1973", "content": "Is karma still a thing when being in Gwynfydd? And how would someone avoid karmic entanglements when he or she is ready to move on to Gwynfydd? I can't imagine how one person would manage to totally avoid any entanglements with other humans, major or minor, because there presumably isn't anyone who doesn't make a mistake sometimes in his or her life.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8546303", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Yes, karma's still a factor in Gwynfydd, but you don't have to work it off the same way; you can use the mistake as a focus for contemplation, correct the imbalance in your character that led you to make the mistake, and send appropriate energy to anyone who was harmed to make up for what you did. When you're ready to pass on to Gwynfydd, you figure out how to do this, too -- it's one of the changes that shows that you're ready.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8525823", "title": "Candles", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have four questions (sorry for this, but they are quite important) regarding the CGD practice.\n1) Though sometimes I get some abstract symbols during meditation, the bulk of what I get from it comes when I start to write, not from what the thinking between start and end yields. Is this a problem?\n2) Regarding using candles to ask for help with the practice, I have two options: use planets with classic color assignments, or use the CGD stations and names with its own colors, at (I assume) page 233 of the Llewellyn edition. I don't have my birth date and time, and astrology is not an option for this incarnation. Should I use planets (to improve this understanding on later lives) or the CGD system?\n3) Does the candle work using CGD stations need to use the planetary hour? And, how does one address a sphere, and not a god?\n4) Which sphere or god could help me with the fear that woowoo is real? I had a meeting with Mr. Watcher that set me back a lot. Mars for courage?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8546815", "title": "Re: Candles", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) That's very common, and no, it's not a problem at all.\n2) If you're working the CGD system, use the CGD colors and names.\n3) No -- and why not address the god or goddess? That's what I would do.\n4) Ah, I see you've had your TSW moment. That's an inevitable stage in this work. Invoke the fifth Sphere, Modur, and its deity Taranis.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8528127", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "My wife and I recently found a house we'd like to make a home. We're pursuing the material realm stuff as you do, but I was wondering if you had any suggestions for some practical magic / hoodoo rituals we might be able to do to speed/smooth things along?\n[For context, I've worked my way through your LRM, some of Regardies smaller books, and am fascinated by and dabble a little in hoodoo workings (I used a yellow candle ritual to help get a new job last year)]", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8547327", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Have you considered a\nhoney jar spell\n?", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8528383", "title": "Isolation has been getting to my practice", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I have been having a very hard time keeping a consistent magical practice. I've been doing my rituals more sporadically, I've pretty much dropped meditation, stuff like that. My other activities in life worked as anchors for different parts of my schedule around which my magical practice could work on. Can magical practice be safely put in a sort of hybernation mode? Is there an alternative? I have ADHD and the loss of structure really gets to me.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8547583", "title": "Re: Isolation has been getting to my practice", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You're facing one of the classic tests of the path. If you stop practicing magic at this point, you may never get back to it, and even if you do, you'll have to face this challenge all over again. Only you can decide whether your desire to become a mage is strong enough to keep you going through this test.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8537087", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nOther than WW2, is there any historical instance where magical operations were used as a weapon on a massive scale?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8548095", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "Good heavens, yes. It used to be standard practice in ancient times. The ancient Egyptians, for example, never went to war without all-out magical workings to support their armies. More recently, it's less common, but the struggles between the Stuarts and the Hanoverians over the English crown in the early 18th century were riddled with magic on both sides. Marsh Keith Schuchard has written some excellent books on that.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8540927", "title": "Hafgan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG,\nIs the Welsh name Hafgan a traditional title, such as a title for the sun or moon? Also, I have seen Hafgan translated both as \"summer white\" and \"summer song\", which seems like an important distinction.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8548607", "title": "Re: Hafgan", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I've always seen it as \"summer white,\" with\ncan\na very old word for \"white\" descended from Latin, but\ncanu\nis \"to sing\" so the other makes sense. No, it's not a traditional title except in the Mabinogion.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8549119", "title": "Re: Hafgan", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Thank you!", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8546559", "title": "The rosy cross", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hey again jmg\nIn your book “the circles of power” you’d say the rosy cross is a symbol of tiphareth, would replacing the circle with a hexagon ‘hexagram be a better tiphareth symbol?\nJ.L.Mc12", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8548863", "title": "Re: The rosy cross", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No. The Rose Cross has its own very distinctive geometry and should be left unchanged.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8547839", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Do you have any idea why people get so freaky about the fact I don't feel the need to be constantly immersed in ridiculously bright artificial lights?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8549375", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "No -- in what way and context do they get freaky?\nI find too much artificial light uncomfortable -- I can, with typical Aspergers hypersensitivity, feel it on my bare skin -- and so I tend toward dimly lit spaces as well, but nobody hassles me about it.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8551167", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "A while ago I saw someone ask about a Valentinian Gnostic SoP. I can't find it now. What was it again?", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8552191", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you use the search function on the bottom of the left hand side, it comes up promptly. Here it is:\n\"A Valentinian SoP would be easy as pie. The words for the opening are, \"In the power of Christ (touching the head) and the wisdom of Sophia (touching the womb center) I establish the Stauros. (bringing the hands up and out to form the image of the Cross). Amen. (Crossing the arms over the chest.)\nThe Stauros or Cross is the manifestation of the Aeon Horos, the Limiter, who keeps the archons from assaulting the world of light, so he's the obvious being to invoke here.\nAs for the six directions, I'd use:\nEast/Air: Logos, the Word\nWest/Water: Zoe, Life\nSouth/Fire: Nous, Mind\nNorth/Earth: Aletheia, Truth\nSpirit Below: Bythos, Depth\nSpirit Above: Sige, Silence\nThen invoke Spirit within in the name of Jesus the Christ, contemplating your own nature as a reflection of the Aeon Anthropos, the Human, and your participation in a reflection of the Aeon Ekklesia, the Church.\"", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8553727", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I had a brain fart and didn't think to use the dream width search, instead trying it the hard way, of looking through at least a dozen MMs.\nThank you. :)", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8555263", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "It took me quite a while to find the search function when I first started on Dreamwidth! Fortunately it works quite well.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8559615", "title": "Search function?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "I've never been able to find a search function on Dreamwidth for one journal specifically. This is how my left side of the screen looks: https://i.imgur.com/wsy2dER.png\nThere is a search tool at the top, but I can only search across Dreamwidth as a whole for that.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8561151", "title": "Re: Search function?", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "You may need an account. Mine has a search box right above the \"Expand Cut Tags\" button.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8573695", "title": "Re: Search function?", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Just to be sure that you are not mentioning the search function that only works for content in your own paid Dreamwidth account, does this search you have access to allow to look for content available on for journals written by other people?\nFor example, at https://violetcabra.dreamwidth.org/ ?", "replies": []}]}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8553471", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Hi JMG -\nA couple of questions late in the day:\n1) Is there a version of the Bible that you would recommend?\n2) Are you familiar with the New Thought minister and author Joseph Murphy? Is he worth spending time with?\nThanks, as always for your generosity in hosting this forum.\nDave", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8555519", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) Depends on the purpose. For study, I appreciate the clarity of the Jerusalem Bible. For sheer poetry, even though it's inaccurate, nothing rivals the King James Version.\n2) No, I'm not familiar with him -- sorry.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8573439", "title": "recommended Bible versions", "user": "deborah_bender", "content": "If you are interested in a scholarly Jewish perspective on the New Testament, have a look at\nThe Jewish Annotated New Testament\n, edited by Amy-Jill Levine and Marc Zvi Brettler, Oxford University Press, 2011. Hardcover with bound signatures is $35.00 US; there might be a softcover version. HC ISBN is 978-0-19-529770-6.\nI'm not mentioning this for the translation--it's the New Revised Standard Version, which is ubiquitous. Look at it for the front and back matter and the footnotes. The volume contains two introductory essays by the editors, \"Bearing False Witness: Common Errors Made About Early Judaism\" and \"The New Testament between the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh) and Rabbinic Literature\". Then 16 essays by various authors on History and Society (the one on \"Jewish Miracle Workers in the Late Second Temple Period\" is by Geza Vermes. Other topics include The Synagogue, Jewish Movements of the NT Period, Afterlife and Resurrection), 7 essays on Literature (Philo, Josephus, Dead Sea Scrolls, Midrash and Parable in the New Testament, etc.), and 5 essays on Jewish responses to the NT.\nIn the back are ten tables, including a timeline, a chronological table of rulers all over the area from 539 BCE to Hadrian, Greek and Hebrew weights and measures, etc.\nEach book has an introduction of several pages, covering authorship, date of composition, style and content, structure and genre, and key themes. Some of the books also include historical maps. The notes to verses are extensive.\nI think any layperson studying the NT from other than a strictly doctrinal perspective would find this edition to be a valuable reference work.", "replies": []}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8553983", "title": "Spirit Harassing me", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "There's a spirit that has chosen me to torment/mess with me. I was wondering if you are able to get a read on what it is, and how to deal with it, and how to get rid of it ideally. I don't like how it treats me. It deceived me into speaking to it, and I like a foolish young guy bit hoot line and sinker and let it in deep. It's been here for years.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8554751", "title": "Re: Spirit Harassing me", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "I don't have the particular kind of psychism that allows me to read something like that at a distance. Have you considered taking up a daily banishing ritual as a protective practice?  I know people who've shaken noxious entities that way.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8556031", "title": "Re: Spirit Harassing me", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Gotcha, someone from another forum linked me your site, first time here and said it was worth a shot asking. No, haven't tried that. I've mostly tried traditional religious means after realizing this spirit is bad news, and not good, and they've failed. I'm now seeking help in other forms of spirituality. I'm more open to alternative means now to try to rid myself of it. What would you recommend I start with, I'm naive in spirituality.\nThe spirit seems to be fairly powerful to me, but its the only one i've met. it's made a knife cut through Pyrex glass, and metal, through me. As in, asked to possess me so it could do the magic trick, then cut through the materials like they were nothing. And it has clearly spoken to me through other people very bluntly. Is doing a banishing ritual after researching it dangerous? The fear it's given me before when it's attacked me (rare) was more painful than when i was tazed before. I'm fearful of any way that doesn't involve God getting rid of it, due to the pain it's given me when angry, but after years of trying he isn't willing to simply remove it.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8557823", "title": "Re: Spirit Harassing me", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "If you invited it to possess you, it's going to take a lot of work to break the link -- but it can be done. No, a banishing ritual isn't dangerous, but the spirit may try to persuade you that it is.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8562943", "title": "Re: Spirit Harassing me", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "So the salt and nail amulet wouldn't help here, nor the vinegar bowl, presumably? What about old-fashioned exorcism? Do some priests still do these? If not, who could safely perform one from the old rituals? Guessing it would need to be a very experienced mage.", "replies": []}]}, {"id": "cmt8563199", "title": "Re: Spirit Harassing me", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "(Tolkienguy)\nI know I’m a little late, but my suggestion would be to find a Catholic or Eastern Orthodox priest you’re comfortable working with. Traditional Christian exorcism rituals have a lot of power but they aren’t something you can do yourself.", "replies": []}]}]}]}, {"id": "cmt8556287", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "(Anonymous)", "content": "Evening, JMG! I'm going to try to slide a couple of questions in under the wire.\n1. In a geomantic reading asking about a purchase, is Amissio a favorable sign because it represents spending or unfavorable due to connotations of loss?\n2. I've recently purchased your book Monsters and I'm finding all kinds of questions cropping up while reading the bestiary. For now I'll limit myself to this one: to your knowledge,  is it possible for etheric revenants like vampires, or people undergoing etheric projection, to take possession of another person's unconscious body in a walk-in type scenario (as, for example, in one of the Dr. Taverner stories)?\n3. Not a question, but a response to the person who asked last week about Western magical systems that incorporate qigong energy circulation: you might look into the work of Jason Miller, who also writes under the name Inominandum. His Strategic Sorcery system incorporates extensive etheric work, with many of the foundational exercises based on Franz Bardon's writings but also many practices explicitly derived from qigong and from Vajrayana subtle body disciplines.\nThanks as always for your help!\n-Fred N.", "replies": [{"id": "cmt8558079", "title": "(no subject)", "user": "ecosophia", "content": "1) It's a loss, not a gain.\n2) I've never seen it happen, but it's at least theoretically possible.\n3) I'm somewhat familiar with Miller's work, but hadn't realized he'd gotten deeply into the etheric side of things. Thanks for  this.", "replies": []}]}]}];